<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT JR. CAPTURES FIRST WINSTON CUP VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ His swagger replaced by self-doubt, Dale Earnhardt
Jr. walked into Texas Motor Speedway last week looking for a pat on
the back.
</P>
<P>
   He got that from an unexpected source, NASCAR Winston Cup Series
director Gary Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Nelson sat me down this weekend and told me some things
that nobody else had said to me before,'' said Earnhardt Jr., who
limped into Texas Motor Speedway on the heels of consecutive
finishes of 29th, 40th and 38th. ``Gary Nelson sat down with me and
told me he knew I was going to be able to make it and be a good
race car driver, and that I just needed to calm down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   That impromptu pep talk served as a prelude to Little E's
breakthrough Cup victory. Earnhardt Jr. turned his 12th series
start into his first victory, pulling away from points leader Bobby
Labonte and former TMS winner Jeff Burton in the final 53 laps
around the 1.5-mile quadoval. With that, Earnhardt Jr. reached
Victory Lane four races faster than his famous father, a seven-time
NASCAR champion and the first man to greet him yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just told me he loved me,'' Earnhardt Jr. said, after his
father had pulled him out of the cockpit of his red race car. ``And
he wanted to make sure I took the time to enjoy this and relax a
little bit with what we accomplished today.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-time NASCAR Busch Grand National Series champion, Little E
came into Winston Cup armed with a blockbuster $10 million
sponsorship contract from Budweiser and cars provided by his old
man. The preseason favorite for Raybestos Rookie of the Year
honors, Earnhardt Jr. had posted a season's best 10th-place finish
at Las Vegas Motor Speedway before he and his former BGN team had
stumbled at Atlanta Motor Speedway, Darlington Raceway and Bristol
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really do know if you're going to win, ever,'' said
Earnhardt Jr., who qualified fourth in the No. 8 Budweiser
Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``Guys race and race for years and don't
ever know. I really didn't know what to expect \Rthis year\S. I
didn't know if we were going to be kicking butt right out of the
box or whether we were going to be crappy for a year or two. But I
felt like we could win a race. The odds were not really stacked
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially at TMS. Earnhardt Jr. scored the first victory of his
BGN career here in April 1998, the first of his two consecutive
championship seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a lot of tracks like this that we don't run the
same at,'' said Earnhardt Jr., who qualified fourth. ``\RCar
chief\S Tony Eury Jr. and the guys have a good setup here. We
didn't change nothing all day long. I could adjust my driving line
and style to each set of tires. I didn't have to do a whole lot.
I'd point-and-shoot and that thing ran. That's about all there was
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Earnhardt Jr. was one of 17 drivers involved in a
record 29 lead changes. A record 12 caution flags also played into
the mix, with Earnhardt Jr. and crew chief Tony Eury Sr. opting for
four-tire changes on every pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stuck with four tires because we didn't want to upset the
handling of the car,'' said Earnhardt Jr., who led eight times for
a race-high 106 laps. ``That was the smartest thing we did all day
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who scored his first Cup victory here in 1997, said any
designs he had on tracking down Little E were slowed by his attempt
to clear Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long time to get by Bobby,'' said Burton, driver
of the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus. ``If I could have
cleared Bobby a little bit quicker, then we could have given him a
run for his money. I had a fast enough car to run with Dale Jr.,
but once I got behind him there was no sense in running the car any
harder than I needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton finished 5.920 seconds behind Little E, and Labonte was
fading at a faster rate _ whether changing two or four tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty screwed up,'' said Labonte, driver of the No. 18
Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand Prix. ``Four was worse than two
was.'' But the native Texan retained his series points lead for the
fifth consecutive week, stretching his advantage to 84 points over
Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace, last week's winner at Bristol, finished fourth,
followed by No. 2 qualifier Kevin Lepage. Wallace, driver of the
No. 2 Miller Lite Ford, scored his second consecutive fourth-place
finish at TMS. Lepage posted his first top-five of 2000, and tied
his career-best Cup result set at Darlington in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Little E said that after the last three weeks, he enjoyed
running at the front again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to show these guys I could use my head and make
smart decisions,'' said Earnhardt Jr., 25. ``Even when I've got a
real fast car and I'm not up front, I can be patient and pick my
way through there. It was fun to prove that to them, and prove my
status as far as a driver goes.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
