<HEADLINE>
BIG-HOME BOOM RANKLES PARADISE VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY DIANA BALAZS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Upscale isn't the buzzword in Paradise Valley anymore.
Try large-scale.
</P>
<P>
   Home buyers with money to burn and developers attracted by the
town's reputation as a haven for the rich and famous are snapping
up developed lots and replacing modest homes with modern-day giants
that are two, three or more times as big, at a rate that could set
the tone for the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   That has some worried that the town is losing its coveted rural,
airy feel and becoming a Beverly Hills clone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers us is the big houses in the smaller, older
neighborhoods. It doesn't fit,'' says 18-year Paradise Valley
resident Nan Murley, who, with her neighbors, took on a developer
planning a 10,800-square-foot house on a teardown lot in their
Mummy Mountain neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Boucek, 65, has a few choice words about the
6,000-square-foot, two-story house going up next door to his
one-story, 2,600-square-foot hacienda on East Doubletree Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stinks,'' he said. ``It's out of proportion. It's out of
character.''
</P>
<P>
   There is less than a year's supply - 100 lots - of vacant
residential land in the town.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, an average of 100 new homes have gone up yearly in
the 5,000-home town, where the minimum lot is 1 acre but the
average size of new homes has risen from 2,000 to 4,000 square feet
40 years ago to 5,000 to 6,000 today. And some houses are being
built to the maximum size allowed on an acre, nearly 11,000 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   There are enough residents questioning the trend that this month
the Town Council is forming a special citizens committee to
consider tougher ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   John Donatov, a Paradise Valley resident who is a developer,
bought the teardown on Murley's street last July for $585,000. The
planned two-story, four-bedroom, four-bath house already is being
marketed for nearly $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a small hotel,'' Murley said of the design.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors went to the town's hillside building committee.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member group, which includes two Town Council members,
two planning commissioners and a resident, reviews whether plans
conform with the ordinance, which covers issues from lighting and
landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the complaints, the home's size was reduced to 9,000
square feet by eliminating a guest house, an exercise room and one
of four garages, architect John Sproule said.
</P>
<P>
   Sproule says residents will become even more involved as their
neighborhood changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think maybe the problem is sort of made a little bit
worse because of the speed of redevelopment.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucek, a semi-retired insurance consultant who has lived in his
house for 33 years, laments that the new home, with five bedrooms
and 5 1/2 baths, towers above his and blocks his backyard views of
the McDowell Mountains and sunrises.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be some sort of regulations protecting the
existing character of older neighborhoods,'' Boucek said.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Lincoln, a former mayor and Town Council member who has
been on the hillside committee for 20 years, hopes the
bigger-is-better trend will reverse in five or six years and thinks
it would help if the committee sat down with home builders before
plans are drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Town Councilman Bernie Barry says the new citizens committee
would focus first on hillside homes because what is built is highly
visible, but he says restrictions that are too tight could affect
land values.
</P>
<P>
   Resident Rick Johnson, 50, a financial planner, welcomes the
big-house building boom.
</P>
<P>
   His neighborhood near 52nd Street and East Doubletree Road is in
transition from tract to custom. Johnson is remodeling and doubling
the size of his 1970s-built home to about 5,300 square feet. At
least a half-dozen neighbors are adding on or building spacious
homes from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variety is nice. It adds character to the neighborhood,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the housing boom started in the early 1990s, housing
values and property taxes have skyrocketed. The median price of the
14 new homes sold in Paradise Valley last year was $951,000. The
median price of existing home sold last year was $660,000. In 1999,
the median property tax bill for a Paradise Valley resident was
$2,846.43.
</P>
<P>
   Murley and Boucek said some longtime residents who have paid off
their homes may find paying the higher taxes difficult. The town
does not levy a property tax, but residents still pay school and
county property taxes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at &QL; 
Diana.Balazs(at)ArizonaRepublic.com &QL; 
or (602) 444-7479. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
