<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, April 3. If you
have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOUSE (PARADISE VALLEY, Ariz.) _ Upscale isn't the buzzword in
Paradise Valley anymore. Try large-scale. Home buyers with money to
burn and developers attracted by the town's reputation as a haven
for the rich and famous are snapping up developed lots and
replacing modest homes with modern-day giants that are two, three
or more times as big, at a rate that could set the tone for the
Phoenix area. That has some worried that the town is losing its
coveted rural, airy &UR; feel and becoming a Beverly Hills clone. ``What
bothers us is the big houses in the smaller, older neighborhoods.
It doesn't fit,'' says 18-year Paradise Valley resident Nan Murley,
who, with her neighbors, took on a developer planning a
10,800-square-foot house on a teardown lot in their Mummy Mountain
neighborhood. By DIANA BALAZS. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   SMASH (MESA, Ariz.) _ Melissa Ruiz sat in bed and read the
newspaper with her parents Saturday night before kissing them good
night. She didn't know as she headed toward her bedroom that it
would be the last time she would see them alive. Three hours later,
11-year-old Melissa, an only child, awoke to the sound of a loud
crash in her parents' bedroom. A car smashed into her parents'
bedroom, killing them instantly. By BETH DEFALCO. Story will move
in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FINGER (PHOENIX) _ School staff background checks in Arizona can
take an unprecedented three months, forcing schools to leave
positions open or hire teachers without knowing whether they're
criminals. The backlog is the longest since checks began in 1990,
and it could get worse, just as Arizona faces a severe teacher
shortage. Lawmakers are close to requiring background checks on
educators every six years. Now, just new staff members have to be
cleared. ``We're trying to protect Arizona's schoolchildren,'' said
Rep. Steve May, R-east Phoenix, a sponsor of the bill that would
require fingerprint checks as certificates are renewed. By LORI
BAKER and KELLY PEARCE. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new
books. By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' and ``L''
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WEB&AMP;MAGS (undated) _ Bill Muller's reviews of a Website and some
current magazines. Story will move in the ``E'' and ``L''
categories.
</P>
<P>
   STARTREK (undated) _ To analyze U.S. foreign policy, it takes a
keen intellect, years of study, and a profound awareness of the
intricacies of international politics _ or, you can watch Star
Trek. Trek and its successors have served as a mirror in popular
culture of American world stance over the decades. By BILL MULLER.
Story will move in the ``E'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
