<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDFIGURESKATING-KWAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SPIN ON AN OLD TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ Michelle Kwan was leaving the Palais des
Expositions Friday after placing third in the short program when a
well-wisher approached her. ``I wish the Russians would fall
down,'' she told Kwan. ``For you.'' ``Oh, don't wish that,'' Kwan
told her. ``I don't want any skater to fall down. Wish for me to
skate well.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never about Maria Butyrskaya, who held the women's crown
Kwan had worn twice. It was never about Irina Slutskaya, who had
beaten Kwan in this year's Grand Prix final. It was always about
Kwan skating the way she used to skate, with passion and energy and
daring.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody had seen that Kwan since the US Championships two years
ago in Philadelphia, when she blew away Tara Lipinski. And many
skating observers were wondering whether they ever would see her
again.
</P>
<P>
   Did she still want it after seven years? Could she still do it?
Kwan hadn't put together two clean programs at a major event since
the 1998 Olympics, where she'd skated cautiously and watched
Lipinski beat her for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad always tells me I have to be up against the wall before
I fight back,'' Kwan said Saturday night, after she had risen to
beat the Russians and claim her third world title in five years.
``He says, `Why don't you fight back from the very beginning?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan's back was up against the Mediterranean seawall here. No
woman ever had regained the title twice and none since China's Chen
Lu (in 1995) had come out of third to win. And Kwan needed to do
more than win the long program. She also needed Butyrskaya to come
apart. ``That was reality,'' Kwan said. ``I told myself, `Michelle,
you've done this so many times.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe too many times, her critics said. Kwan has been coming to
the global championships since she was 13, since she stepped in for
Nancy Kerrigan after the 1994 Olympics in Lillehammer. ``This is my
seventh Worlds,'' she said. ``After a while, it all seems to blur
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan had won the title and lost it, won it back and lost it
again. She had beaten everybody here. But each year, she had to dig
deeper to find the motivation.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with Kwan juggling skating and her freshman studies
at UCLA, was the toughest of all. She was scrambling to find ice,
driving an hour each way from Westwood to practice for an hour.
After living in a mountain hideaway at Lake Arrowhead, she was
bunking in a noisy dorm on a huge campus. ``People don't care if
you're a figure skater,'' said Frank Carroll, Kwan's coach.
``They're going to stay up all night partying. It's their school,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kwan had to pull herself up from third place to beat
orthodontic pursuers Sasha Cohen and Sarah Hughes at the US
Championships, she realized she had to live in the rink if she
wanted to have any chance here. ``No excuses whatsoever,'' Carroll
decreed. ``She had to be there, and I had to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks, Kwan prodded herself, working on the
triple-triple jump combination she needed just to get into the
game. Then, with the world watching and the title on the line, she
pushed herself to the limit, landing not only the combo but five
more triples. ``I wanted to use up all of my energy,'' she said.
``I don't want to come off the ice thinking, `You know, I have a
little more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Drained and exultant, Kwan went backstage to decompress.
``Michelle, you just skated the best program of your life,'' she
told herself. ``No matter what happens, be happy, be happy, be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Butyrskaya and Slutskaya came undone, Kwan found herself on
the top step of the podium, as she always is in even-numbered
years. ``What happened in the odd years?'' she wondered.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tick-tock cycle, the 27-year-old Butyrskaya mused, after
she'd given back the crown. ``Things are repeating themselves,''
she said. ``This is sport. Michelle was first, then second, then
first again. It's just a normal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   No women's champion has repeated since Kristi Yamaguchi in 1992.
Some, like Lipinski, moved on after their Olympic gold. Others,
like Chen, never recaptured the magic. The next even-numbered year
is 2002, when the Olympics will be in Salt Lake City and Kwan will
have been coming to these planetary all-skates for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could bottle this motivation I had from Nationals to
here,'' the new _ and old _ world champ was saying. ``So I can open
it up for later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
