<HEADLINE>
JAPAN PREMIER SUFFERS STROKE; STAND-IN NAMED
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for earlier story. The story is an added starter on Page 1.) 
 (rk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The prime minister of Japan, Keizo Obuchi, has suffered
a stroke and was temporarily relieved of his duties Monday, the
government announced.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's condition was confirmed more than 24 hours after he was
hospitalized early Sunday, complaining of exhaustion. The prime
minister was temporarily replaced as the nation's top official by
Mikio Aoki, his chief Cabinet secretary, at a hastily convened news
conference early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 9:00 a.m. today, I accepted the job of acting prime
minister in accordance with the 9th article of cabinet law,'' Aoki
said. ``When I visited Mr. Obuchi yesterday, he said that pending
the results of his medical examination that I should take over the
job of acting prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Aoki said the move was especially justified by the emergency
operations surrounding the eruption four days ago of a volcano in
the country's northernmost province, Hokkaido. Aoki said he would
convene his first Cabinet meeting later in the day, and the meeting
was expected to be dominated by the government's response to the
eruption of the volcano.
</P>
<P>
   The stroke suffered by Obuchi on Sunday comes at a time of
mounting political activity in Japan in anticipation of national
elections, which must be held by October. His incapacitation, even
if it proves only short--lived, injects a major dose of drama and
uncertainty to the nation's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's medical emergency was initially diagnosed as
``overwork'' and came on a weekend when the prime minister was both
grappling with the emergency response in the north and struggling
to keep his ruling coalition together.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the leader of the smallest member of his three-party
coalition, the Liberal Party, announced its departure from the
government after an hourlong meeting with Obuchi. Less than an hour
later, Obuchi complained of extreme fatigue and asked shortly
afterward to be taken to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party leader, Ichiro Ozawa, expressed surprise and
regret Monday over Obuchi's condition. ``I was extremely surprised
at the information,'' he said. ``I would never have suspected that
he would be hospitalized after the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after such a long delay in announcing the medical
emergency, the government's initial statements about the prime
minister _ emphasizing that he had gone to the hospital in a
private vehicle and not an ambulance, and asserting that he had
never lost consciousness _ seemed mostly intended to minimize the
political impact of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has once previously experienced the temporary replacement
of a prime minister. Twenty years ago, Prime Minister Masayoshi
Ohira was also replaced by his chief Cabinet secretary. Ohira
eventually died in office, throwing the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party into turmoil on the eve of elections. He was ultimately
replaced by Masayoshi Ito.
</P>
<P>
   If Obuchi is incapacitated for any substantial length of time,
pressures will rise within his Liberal Democratic Party to chose a
new standard bearer before the October elections.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi has been under increasing political pressure in recent
months, as the mandatory October deadline for new national
elections approaches and many economic indicators, as well as his
government's poll ratings, deteriorate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japanese political analysts say that Obuchi had hoped to call
elections after a summit meeting of the world's leading economic
powers, the Group of Eight, to be held in the southern prefecture
of Okinawa in July.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has reportedly been working hard at ensuring
the success of the meeting, taking part in planning and other
preparations, and visiting the prefecture last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi has a history of cardiac trouble, and uses a pacemaker to
stabilize his heartbeat. According to several Japanese newspapers,
Obuchi's history of heart problems had been discussed within his
party prior to his selection as its prime ministerial candidate.
Obuchi is reported to have collapsed once, in 1997, as a result of
his heart trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his hospitalization, Obuchi had been through an
unusually active weekend, closely monitoring the emergency
evacuation of an area near the volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi and some predecessors have come under harsh criticism for
their tepid responses to past emergencies and natural disasters.
The government took several hours to respond to the country's worst
nuclear-related accident last September. And with elections due
soon, Obuchi's heavy involvement in the response to the volcanic
eruption seemed intended to avoid new criticism over the
government's ability to manage crises.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's government is by tradition extremely stingy with news
about the medical condition of officials and public figures. Other
than announcing the fact that Obuchi had suffered a stroke, the
government gave no information about its severity, or of Obuchi's
prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   The information vacuum sent the Japanese press into a
speculative frenzy, with many reporters seeking off-the-record
snippets of information from the medical staff at the hospital. On
that basis, the state broadcaster, NHK, announced shortly after
noon that Obuchi's condition was believed to be ``extremely
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why there had been such a lengthy delay before the
announcement of the prime minister's hospitalization, Aoki, who is
also the chief government spokesman, gave a somewhat
strained-sounding explanation. ``It was Sunday, and he was
undergoing examinations,'' he said. ``We were waiting to see how
things turned out. I had no other intention. I am speaking
honestly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
