<HEADLINE>
CLEAVES IS FLINT-TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It's a good thing names don't break bones like
sticks and stones. Michigan State guard Mateen Cleaves would be in
traction rather than waiting to lead the Spartans (31-7) in Monday
night's national championship game against Florida (29-7).
</P>
<P>
   The senior from Flint, Mich., is a magnet for opposing fans'
insults. He is a player with an exceptional game and a checkered
past, which means he is an obvious target. Yet, some of the taunts
can get rather personal, and range from senseless to mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that fans have been chanting ``Alcoholic'' since
Cleaves was cited by police for having a beer in his car in 1998
and was charged with teammate Antonio Smith for stealing a 40-ounce
bottle of beer from a convenience store (the charges later were
dropped against Cleaves, and Smith was acquitted).
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan State beat writers say that fans even utter the
chant to Smith's mother, Frances, and some often question her
parenting skills. Others taunt Cleaves for his involvement in a
fight during a party on campus (the incident remains under
investigation after two years and Cleaves never has been charged).
</P>
<P>
   Even members of the fourth estate have taken jabs at Cleaves,
who is known for repeatedly uttering credos about hard work,
respect for everyone, and honoring God.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, after Michigan State gained the No. 1 seed in the
Midwest Regional and Cleaves spent 10 minutes saying the Spartans
need to take one game at a time, one reporter asked, ``Hey Mateen,
who taught you all those cliches?''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves said it doesn't bother him, and that was evident during
the Spartans' national semifinal game against Wisconsin, in which
he sank 9 of 11 free throws as fans taunted him each time he went
to the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't get caught up in that. I laugh at that stuff,''
said Cleaves. ``My mom gets upset, she kind of gets mad. But I
don't take it personal. Those same fans who say those things are
the first people outside the locker room shaking your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely Cleaves wouldn't be the subject of such taunts if he
weren't the prime reason Michigan State is 40 minutes from its
second national championship. Arguably the best Spartans point
guard since Magic Johnson, he averages 11.9 points and seven
assists a game, and leads a team that has held opponents to 54
points per game and 36 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some say many of the taunts have come from Michigan
State's Big Ten rivals, most notably Michigan, whose Fab Five teams
of the 1990s endured similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I went through the Scott Skiles deal that took taunting
to a new level,'' said coach Tom Izzo, referring to the former
Michigan State player who also was mired in off-court woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother Mateen as much,'' Izzo added. ``He's pretty
tough-minded. You know what I love about Mateen? We talked about
it, and I told him that if you do something wrong you've got to pay
the consequences. And sometimes the consequences linger and last a
little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I feel more sorry for his parents and his sister. It
was tough on them at times. And yet I say that not as many people
taunted Mateen as you may think. I still think he has enough
blue-collar work ethic in him, he's egoless, and people appreciate
that about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo said he could recount only a couple of times when he
believed the opposing student section got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one game in particular when I just went down and
sat with him and kind of hung out for a while at the end of the
game,'' he said. ``But all in all, I think people have been pretty
good to Mateen.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Florida fans are likely to taunt Cleaves if he
buckles under the pressure of the Gators' full-court trapping
defense. But he said he welcomes that style to Wisconsin's
slow-paced attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wisconsin is going to take the air out of the basketball,
they're going to get back on defense, it's going to be a tough,
physical game,'' said Cleaves. ``I'm not saying it's not going to
be tough and physical against Florida, but we pretty much can get
more up and down and try to play our style of basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
