<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED CARPET FOR JUNIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ In the rest of America and the world, today is
Monday. But here, in baseball's homeland and heartland, this day is
known as it has been known for generations, known by Cincinnati's
two sweetest words.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   A semi-holiday, a day almost holy for the city with baseball's
oldest franchise, a day where truly all is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Especially this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. returns to his home city, 13 years after leaving
Moeller High School as a troubled teenager, 13 years after leaving
with three words in his name and returning home with sports'
highest accolade of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   One name.
</P>
<P>
   Just like ``Michael,'' and ``Larry,'' and ``Magic,'' and
``Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   One name explains all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Cincinnati-Northern Kentucky Airport across the Ohio
River in Kentucky, the huge sign welcoming Griffey home is merely
the precursor to an amazing phenomenon, this ``Juniorizing'' of
baseball's senior team in the senior circuit in one of America's
senior cities. Meanwhile, ``Senior'' himself looks on, father and
son reunited, a link from the first (and real) Big Red Machine of
the mid-1970s to this next (but only potential) Big Red Machine of
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   And today _ not Monday, but Opening Day _ is when reality begins
to test The Phenomenon of Junior Returning Home. Heavier loads
seldom have been placed on anyone's shoulders in baseball than what
is expected from Junior in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain fell on Cincinnati Sunday, buckets and buckets, and
more is possible for Sunday's game against the Brewers. A
suggestion, perhaps, that reality might include a few more clouds
than the endless blue skies in winter and through spring training
of The Phenomenon of Junior Returning Home.
</P>
<P>
   The Phenomenon. In Cincinnati, the deal that brought Junior from
Seattle already has been described as baseball's biggest since the
Red Sox sent Babe Ruth to the Yankees 80 years ago. Well, at the
time of the infamous Sox deal, Ruth was five years younger than
Junior was when he asked out of Seattle. Not to mention, Ruth
already had helped the Red Sox to World Series titles, while Junior
has yet to be ``Mr. October,'' having one very good series against
the Yankees in his first postseason action and being only average
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The Phenomenon. In an earlier _ but smaller _ phenomenon, when
Eric Davis came to the Reds, he was supposed to be the next Willie
Mays. He was not. It is open to debate if even Griffey is another
Willie Mays, but the media monster now is so huge, so many sound
bites, so many stories, so much hyperbole, that before a game is
even played _ a game in April, mind you _ the ultimate comparison
is placed on Griffey's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Another Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Reds general manager Jim Bowden has pulled off some good trades
(pitcher Dave Burba to the Indians for first baseman Sean Casey)
and a stinker or two (Paul O'Neill to the Yankees for Roberto
Kelly). But this deal bringing Junior home is Bowden's proudest
moment, as it should be; Bowden sees the deal on par with the
Yankees stealing Ruth from the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But what the deal unleashed is truly amazing. Virtually every
detail of Griffey's life has been recapitulated in Cincinnati, and
the life of his father, and even the life of his grandfather, who
some thought was on par with a player he used to play with on the
sandlots, the most famous ballplayer ever to come out of Donora,
Pa., Stan Musial. But Junior's grandfather and Senior's father had
no chance to prove it in the early 1940s, with blacks still being
kept out of baseball then.
</P>
<P>
   No Red Sox fan can forget the 1975 World Series or how
outstanding that Big Red Machine was, and how superlative a player
Senior was. Sometimes Senior would bring Junior to the park (the
Reds didn't allow players' children in the locker room after a
loss), but not too often. Still in all, by 1987, when Junior was
17, the Mariners had chosen him as the first player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a few months later, just after turning 18, Junior had
swallowed 277 aspirin in a suicide attempt. As the Cincinnati Post
has quoted Junior of the angst, ``It seemed everyone was yelling at
me in baseball, then I came home and everyone was yelling at me
there. I got depressed. I got angry. I didn't want to live.''
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, in 1990, Junior was in the big leagues with
Seattle and immediately named to the American League All-Star team.
Ever since, he has been a sports highlight show celebrity, climbing
fences to snag would-be homers, running the bases, and hitting
those laser shots into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   But Junior never could lead the Mariners to the ultimate. The
pitching-poor and bullpen-deprived team had its problems, but
Junior also was not Mr. October.
</P>
<P>
   But now The Phenomenon is promising all. Bowden also has
acquired Dante Bichette, and with Casey and Bichette sandwiching
him in the lineup, Junior will not be pitched around. But that was
also the case in Seattle, when the Mariners had Edgar Martinez, Jay
Buhner, and many other bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Phenomenon has been created by that media monster, hinting
that the Reds will be the Reds of the 1970s and Junior will be
Reggie Jackson, swatting homer after homer in countless World
Series. The Phenomenon notes that seldom, if ever, has one division
had such sluggers as the National League's Central. Yet, even with
Mark McGwire's homers, the Cardinals were forgettable last season
and so were the Cubs, even with Sammy Sosa's blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, athletes were judged after their careers.
Those who grew up in the 1940s and 1950s never heard anyone put in
the same breath as Babe Ruth; it was not until Hank Aaron
approached and then broke Ruth's sacred number of 714 homers that
even he was paired with Ruth. Yet The Phenomenon of Junior
Returning Home mates the two.
</P>
<P>
   The modern media creates so much expectation before a game,
before an event, before a season, before a career. It is so unfair.
</P>
<P>
   It is best to wait. And merely enjoy watching what a great
player can or cannot accomplish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
