<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
ASHCROFT TAKES A MORE MODERATE COURSE IN RE-ELECTION BID 
</HEADLINE>
 BC-  KC-ASH-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY and STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years ago, when John Ashcroft thought about
running for president, he declared that it was time to ``unfurl the
banner of unabashed conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Ashcroft is waving a different banner _ one that
signals a more moderate agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a battle for re-election against Democrat Mel
Carnahan, Ashcroft's focus has shifted to voters in the middle of
the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of touting the $4 trillion, 10-year tax cut that he
unveiled during his exploratory presidential run, Ashcroft now is
almost mum on the topic. Instead of saying he would use Social
Security surpluses to cut taxes, Ashcroft has changed course and
now wants to leave the surpluses alone.
</P>
<P>
   And he recently lost his two-year distinction as the most
conservative senator in a well-known annual ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft puts little stock in assertions he has drifted to the
center to have a better chance of defeating Carnahan in Missouri's
high-profile Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I think Missourians know the kind of conservative I've
been,'' Ashcroft said. ``These issues I'm focusing on for Missouri
are the same themes I was focusing on before.''
</P>
<P>
   A shift from conservative to moderate would hardly be unusual.
It comes straight out of political textbooks that advise candidates
to move right or left in the primaries, then back to the middle for
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's trend toward the center is difficult to miss based on
a review of his voting record, public statements and media
releases. Political scholars have noted the same shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would lose to Mel Carnahan if he continued to push a real
right-wing agenda,'' St. Louis University political scientist Ken
Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Virginia, political scientist Larry Sabato
noted that Carnahan and Ashcroft both are moving to the center,
though Ashcroft has further to travel.
</P>
<P>
   As a presidential candidate, Ashcroft was viewed as a ``hard
right'' conservative who was seeking to win over such right-wing
leaders as Pat Robertson, Sabato said. ``He was seen as one of the
two or three favorites of the Christian right.''
</P>
<P>
   A top Carnahan aide said Ashcroft's shift is transparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is running away from his record in a wholesale fashion,''
Marc Farinella said
</P>
<P>
   According to Farinella, the most notable example involves
Ashcroft's 1998 call for a tax cut of $1.7 trillion over five years
and $4 trillion over 10 years. Likely 2000 GOP presidential nominee
George W. Bush is proposing a smaller cut of $1.3 trillion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said he still supports major elements of his tax-cut
plan, although he no longer gives it a $4 trillion price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I favor very substantial tax relief for the American people,''
he said. ``I'm not sure the menu would be exactly the same. Some of
those things have already been undertaken.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Congress is working on Ashcroft's proposal to
eliminate the marriage tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   On the highly sensitive issue of Social Security, Ashcroft said
in December 1997 that surpluses should be used for tax relief.
Fifteen months later, after deciding to focus on his Senate race,
he sponsored a bill for a ``lockbox'' to keep the surplus intact.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft spokesman Steve Hilton said the only other choice in
1997 was to use the surplus for spending.
</P>
<P>
   But Farinella said that Ashcroft ``cannot both cut taxes by $4
trillion and at the same time promise people he's going to protect
Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton called that a ``political lie.... The proposal was fully
paid for with reductions and reforms in government with a minor
share from the non-Social Security surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton acknowledged that the senator's tax cut was financed, in
part, through savings on Medicare and other entitlements. Social
Security, however, would have been unaffected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some issues boil down to a difference over what constitutes a
shift to the middle.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on plans to help senior citizens pay for
prescription drugs, Ashcroft in 1999 voted twice against proposals
aimed at furthering that goal. In news releases and public
appearances, Ashcroft now expresses an interest in expanding drug
coverage for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   But Hilton said Republicans voted against the drug plans because
they were waiting for President Clinton to take the lead on saving
Medicare. Since that has not happened, ``It's time to proceed,''
Hilton said.
</P>
<P>
   On Medicare, Ashcroft voted in 1997 to increase the eligibility
age from 65 to 67 and has, over several years, voted for many
budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton said the eligibility adjustment amounted to a gradual
rise and makes Medicare conform to the Social Security age
schedule. The senator's votes to cut the rate of Medicare's growth
were aimed at saving the program from bankruptcy, and in some cases
preserving GOP tax cuts, Hilton said.
</P>
<P>
   In overall tone, there's little doubt that Ashcroft has adjusted
his public demeanor. As a presidential contender, Ashcroft focused
on such conservative issues as abortion, flag desecration and
prohibiting federal testing of schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ashcroft focuses on more centrist proposals, such as making
air bags safer and ending the earnings test for Social Security
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is considered one of the Senate's most conservative
members, a point he emphasized during his presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 radio interview, Ashcroft said, ``There are two things
you find in the middle of the road: a moderate and a dead skunk.
And I don't want to be either one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point that year, Ashcroft spoke of Republicans ``who
preach pragmatism, who champion conciliation, who counsel
compromise.'' Then he added, ``I stand here to reject those lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he stood by those remarks: ``I'm certainly not going
to support lies, I'm going to fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 rating by the National Journal that covered 50 votes
on a variety of policy issues, Ashcroft tied for first with six
senators for the most conservative ranking. In 1998, he rated 94
percent, tied for first with two others. But in 1999, he dropped to
a tie for 15th with 83.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relative to his colleagues, he's drifted,'' said Gideon
Berger, the Journal's associate editor.
</P>
<P>
   One example from the Journal: In 1999 Ashcroft voted to retain a
law requiring background checks to buy guns at pawnshops.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said dozens of groups do rankings, and ``I doubt you'll
find uniformity in rating systems.''
</P>
<P>
   While still exploring a presidential bid, Ashcroft displayed his
conservative stripes when he became one of the first senators to
call for Clinton's resignation after it became clear the president
had lied about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said I wouldn't want to forgive the president,''
Ashcroft said last week, although he still believes the president
was irresponsible. ``I don't have any intention to not work with
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Ashcroft co-sponsored a proposed constitutional
amendment in 1998 that would outlaw it, even in cases of rape or
incest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been my philosophy during my time in government,''
Ashcroft said. He's no longer pressing the amendment, but has
helped pass other anti-abortion measures.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Wittmann of the conservative Heritage Foundation said
Ashcroft hasn't changed his views since his presidential run, but
was now ``broadening his portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Wittmann said, ``You have different constituencies when
you run for president than when you represent a state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
