<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-KC-Net-KAN &LR;      04-03 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS CLAIMS A GROWING SHARE OF CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- KC-Net-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget what Dan Rather thinks you need to know about the 2000
campaign. No longer must you endure the know-it-all tone of
Newsweek or Time or U.S. News &AMP; World Report. Nor must you settle
for the editorial choices of your daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   You have the Internet to soothe your civic desires.
</P>
<P>
   It makes bankrolling a candidate as easy as ordering a
bestseller. It lets you lobby Capitol Hill from your den. In
Arizona, residents have cast votes online.
</P>
<P>
   Want to play politics? Just click your mouse. Assuming, of
course, you're interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people would rather be watching wrestling or going to a
wrestling Web site than using the Internet to see something about a
candidate,'' said Rachel Gorlin of the Washington-based Laguens
Hamburger Stone political consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some of the people who watch wrestling also vote. And some
of those people like to get their information about politics off
the Internet. And they will only go there more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Even political professionals who dismissed the importance of
cyberspace in past campaigns say that for both candidate and voter
it reaches a new significance in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In quantity, quality and ease of use, the Internet has evolved
into a tool that makes it far more convenient for anyone with a
modem to play politics.
</P>
<P>
   For the voter, there's a nearly endless array of Web sites that
compare candidate records on greenhouse gas emissions, foreign
trade or U.S. policy toward Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   It can tell you what candidates will appear on your ballot,
which agree most with you, who pays for their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   There is some evidence that voters want that information. Tens
of thousands of people have registered online to vote through
Project Vote Smart, a nonprofit group run largely with money from
foundations and volunteers on a Montana ranch.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, its www.vote-smart.org drew nearly 1 million hits on
Election Day. (For all this high technology, comparing the
popularity of Web sites is rather crude. Hits measure how many
times a Web page has been called up without revealing how many
different people looked at it or how many are repeat visitors.)
This year, well before the general election, the site records about
1.5 million hits almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those calling a companion hotline (1-888-VOTE-SMART, or
1-888-8683-76278) want to know where candidates stand on the
issues. Those calling and visiting the Web site are mostly young _
about 70 percent are 25 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hear about us through MTV or Rosie O'Donnell and they
come,'' said Richard Kimball, the director of Project Vote Smart.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Web also offers voters a chance to soak up a
candidate's message firsthand _ free of the editing of traditional
media or even the analysis of new Internet-based political referees
like Project Vote Smart.
</P>
<P>
   Since the television watcher differs from Internet wanderer _
politics is thrust at the couch potato, the person online must
search it out _ academics and political operatives alike say the
new technology could be a force for electoral good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because voters go to a political Web site with interest,
campaigns need to make sure what they put up is specific and
relevant,'' said Kathryn Coombs of Washington Web Works, a firm
that helps Republican candidates navigate the Internet. ``You can't
get by with vague images the way you might in a TV spot.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Internet remains a political novelty _ more a
roadside attraction on the campaign trail than a critical
crossroads. The people politicians hire to run their campaigns
still advise spending far more on television advertising than on
Web design.
</P>
<P>
   It's the nature of the medium. Television brings politics to the
normal voter, the sort who tunes into campaigns reluctantly in
30-second intervals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet can't do what television does, which is to reach
out to people when they're thinking about something else _
`Friends,' `The Simpsons,' `The Sopranos' _ and get them to think
about politics,'' said Bruce Bimber. He is director of the Center
for Information Technology and Society at the University of
California, Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet still is a preaching-to-the-choir medium,'' he
said. ``Research suggests that the Internet does not stimulate
people to vote who otherwise would not vote....It tends to be
people who are well-informed and already interested.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the exception to the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Americans tend to use the Internet for things other than
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., ranked the top 23
things Internet users do online. Most send e-mail. Roughly half go
shopping or researching their purchases or looking for weather
reports. A quarter to a fifth play games, play the stock market or
linger in chat rooms. One in seven wants pornography. Politics
didn't make the list.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to campaigns crafting a place where voters log on early and
often, the net can mean the difference at the margins of a tight
race.
</P>
<P>
   Politics Online flatly declares Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura
``the first candidate that would not have won without the
Internet.'' His surprise win in 1998 has been widely attributed to
the way his campaign mobilized voters through e-mail and a
relatively primitive Web site before he raised enough cash for
television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain used the Internet another way. He built his
presidential campaign by advertising and using his personality to
draw attention from journalists. Then, having won the New Hampshire
primary, he used his Web site to convert momentum to money.
</P>
<P>
   He raised $20,000 on the Web site in the hour after his New
Hampshire victory was announced, $1 million in the first 48 hours
and $2 million in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other candidates had done well in New Hampshire in past years
but could never capitalize on it to get the money in time to keep
their campaigns afloat,'' said Tracy Westen, chairman of
Grassroots.com and a government professor at the University of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was fast money.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Web sites are the new darlings of political
fund-raisers. Where ordinary methods of mailing out letters asking
for donations can mean spending $25 to raise $26, Web sites promise
bigger returns on smaller investments. They also tend to draw money
from first-time donors, the hardest contributors to find.
</P>
<P>
   People like Eric Johnson, chief executive officer of
Campaignoffice.com, offer customized Web sites for as little as
$250. For $1,500 his outfit supplies a campaign with a Web site
that will take credit-card donations, organize volunteers and post
campaign commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost political malpractice not to raise money and
recruit volunteers there,'' Johnson said. ``(But) the verdict is
still out on whether the Internet will transform politics in the
way TV transformed politics in the '60s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
