<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ABROSIMOVA-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABROSIMOVA PERSEVERED TO CLIMB TO THE TOP
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Being from St. Petersburg, Russia, home of the
Hermitage, Svetlana Abrosimova would not bother sending videotapes
home unless her games were of museum quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only send tapes when I play well,'' Abrosimova said. ``My
mom thinks I'm the greatest ever.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been little reason for her mother to change her
opinion this year as Abrosimova enjoyed another all-American season
and agreed to a sort of detente with Connecticut coach Geno
Auriemma.
</P>
<P>
   If they made a movie of Abrosimova's career at UConn, it might
be called, ``From Russia With Tough Love.'' Auriemma has generally
been the coaching equivalent of Nikita Khrushchev, banging his shoe
on the table (albeit a shoe he has a contract to endorse), claiming
that Abrosimova wasn't tough enough or enough of a team player,
especially in big games.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far has our relationship come?'' Auriemma said before
Sunday night's national championship game against Tennessee.
``Well, our relationship was the best when she was in Russia, and I
talked to her on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship is no different from the relationship he has
with all his star players, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like any of them, because they are never as good as I
think they can be,'' Auriemma said. ``So we're always arguing about
how to do things better. Then after they graduate, I tell everybody
that was the best player I ever coached.''
</P>
<P>
   In Abrosimova's case, it might be true. The 6-foot-2-inch
forward scored 25 points in the East Regional final and was named
the most valuable player. Then she chipped in 14 points, 10
rebounds, four assists and a steal in the national semifinals. She
has spent her career like a self-assured quarterback trying to
persuade her coach that she can throw into triple coverage. This
year, for the first time, she finished with more assists than
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Svet plays the way she can, I don't think there's many
people that can do as many things as well as she can _ shoot the
three, get to the basket and rebound,'' Auriemma said. ``She's
learning to play with other great players.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrosimova was born nearly 20 years ago, when St. Petersburg was
called Leningrad, and sport was a way to promote state propaganda
in the Soviet Union. Like thousands of other kids, she was selected
to play basketball at age 7 because she was tall. By 10, she said,
her mother, Lyudmila, had put a basket up in the family apartment.
The women's game is not particularly popular in Russia, though. Her
high school championship game drew 150 people, Abrosimova said, so
she decided that the future of her game and her education rested in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived three years ago in Storrs, Conn., confident about
her basketball but not her English. When she spoke, she put her
head down and avoided looking others in the eye. But few people
know more about persevering than natives of St. Petersburg. The
city survived despite being surrounded by the Germans for 900 days
during World War II. Her aunt and grandmother told her stories
about the siege, Abrosimova said, ``about how they got through a
lot of tough things.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to that, learning English did not seem so
insurmountable. She used tutors to help with her class work, and
her English skills blossomed with her basketball skills.
</P>
<P>
   She does put her foot down, though, at country music, a favorite
of teammate Shea Ralph's. ``If they make me listen to country
music, the next day they've got to listen to Russian music,''
Abrosimova said.
</P>
<P>
   She has a great Russian sense of humor, and once, when asked if
she was nervous, told Auriemma that she had calmed her nerves by
imagining everyone in the arena naked. ``But not you, coach,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she said, her parents worry about her safety, knowing
that Russian gangs have tried to extort some of the country's most
visible athletes. ``I'm just a poor college student,'' she said.
``I don't have millions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
