<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5205 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     04-03 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Astros are so happy in their new downtown home that even when
nobody could figure out a way to turn the Enron Field lights on for
practice Sunday, nary a grumble was heard. Craig Biggio kept right
on taking his extra BP in the gloomy gloaming, prompting trainer
Dave Labossiere to make an observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to simulate conditions in Pittsburgh,'' he
said. ``It's always like this there.''
</P>
<P>
   And as it happens, it figures to be again tonight, when the
Astros venture back into the cold, cruel world to begin their first
season of the new millennium. There will be no trendy retractable
roof to shelter the teams from the elements, meaning opening night
could well be delayed until Tuesday. Today's forecast for Western
Pennsylvania, where spring hasn't fully sprung yet, says rain is a
virtual certainty and a raw breeze a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the weather, however, the three games in Three Rivers
Stadium, another of the doomed cookie-cutter parks we in Houston
can now sniff derisively at, are fraught with peril. The low-budget
Pirates are the sleeper team in the National League Central because
their top three starting pitchers might be the most collectively
troublesome trio in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Schmidt throws consistently in the mid-90s, Kris Benson
was clocked as high as 98 during the spring, and Francisco Cordova,
the staff ace three years ago when Pittsburgh dogged the Astros'
heels into the final week of the season, has historically made life
difficult for Houston. Granted, bellwethers Jeff Bagwell and Biggio
have handled Schmidt, who opposes Shane Reynolds in the opener
whenever it takes place, with a measure of consistency. But they
are a combined 10-for-76 (.132) against the other two guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hits might be hard to come by,'' Bagwell conceded.
``That's a tough place for us to start the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly under these circumstances, with the Pirates series
stuck between the gloriously giddy unveiling of Enron and the first
for-keeps games there against the Phillies beginning Friday night.
There figures to be scant electricity in Pittsburgh, where baseball
will remain moribund at least until the Pirates' own new old park
is ready, and therefore the Astros have to be extremely vigilant
about keeping their emotional edge.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, speaking for the team, promised as much. But as manager
Larry Dierker would say later on Sunday, ``It's one thing to think
you're ready _ and we do _ but you have to go out and prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Dierker is of the opinion that the magic of the
previous three days should send the Astros into the regular season,
their dismal destination at the outset notwithstanding, on a crest
of euphoria. The atmosphere for the two Yankees games in particular
was playoff-like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night baseball in front of big crowds is a lot more
stimulating than day baseball in front of little crowds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dierker, entering his fourth season as manager, has
already claimed one more division title than all other Houston
skippers combined _ three vs. two _ we must give such
pronouncements of his a certain weight. And it's clear the Astros
need any edge they can finagle if they are to extend Dierker's
Central winning streak to 4-for-4, because the once-puny division
has evolved into a nasty brute.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros could finish third or fourth playing as well as they
did to finish first three seasons ago, when 84-78 was a good enough
record to outlast a Pirates team that, as a group, was paid
significantly less than the ``bargain'' $12.5 million Ken Griffey
Jr. will be making by his lonesome with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The Enron factor itself then looms large, with sellouts and near
sellouts to become regular occurrences. Assuming the Astros fit
nicely into the park, and so far there's no reason to believe they
won't, the pumped-up energy level alone could be worth a couple of
extra victories over 81 home dates. Having nosed past Cincinnati by
only 1{ games last season with Griffey still a Mariner, the Astros
couldn't have been transformed into the hottest ticket in town at a
more fortuitous juncture.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic the Astros aren't opening at home, given the Taj
Mahal that home for them has become. Since 1982, the Astros have
been sent on the road for their first game only once, although the
1995 season also kicked off in San Diego because of how the
strike-shortened schedule broke.
</P>
<P>
   But the feeling was that Enron Field's contractors badly needed
the four-day shakeout to problem-solve after the three-game trial
run. And they most definitely do. While the lights aren't a problem
_ it's just that nobody with the Astros who happened to be present
at the start of Sunday's practice knew the secret code necessary
for turning them on _ plenty of little bugs abound.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them the literal kind. Mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   As per Houston's reputation for an overabundance of same, they
have already proved to be a major nuisance at Enron. Richard
Hidalgo, for one, wouldn't take the field to shag flies until he
had ferreted out a can of repellent and sprayed his arms until they
glistened. Never mind the closed roof above him. He was already
covered with welts.
</P>
<P>
   At least there won't be any biting insects awaiting the Astros
in Pittsburgh. Too cold.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
