<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-LIGHTNING-     04-03 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE POOR TEAM WINDS UP AS FODDER FOR DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Devils have stayed on top of their division by
feasting on the weaker teams in the league and they did it again
Sunday night, overwhelming the Tampa Bay Lightning, 4-1, at the Ice
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The victory against the league's second-worst team extended the
Devils' lead in the Atlantic Division to four points over the
Flyers, who lost to the Carolina Hurricanes Sunday afternoon. It
also made the Devils the first team in the Eastern Conference to
surpass 100 points; they have 101.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they win their final three games, though, they cannot
hope to catch the St. Louis Blues in the race for the President's
Trophy, which is given to the team with the most points. The Blues
have 111 points after their victory Sunday afternoon over the
Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   By beating the Lightning, the Devils are 3-2-0 since Larry
Robinson replaced Robbie Ftorek as coach. The two losses have come
against Toronto and Pittsburgh, teams the Devils could meet down
the road in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The victory Sunday came just two days after they routed the
league's worst team, the Atlanta Thrashers. But it was the first
time in 15 games that they have won two in a row, and it was only
their sixth victory in those 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern for the Devils is that they have only one
victory in the last six weeks against a team with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils can boost their confidence, though, if they can win
in their visit to the Florida Panthers on Monday night, a game in
which some Devils expect to see retribution from the Panthers for
Scott Niedermayer's stick hit to Peter Worrell's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer will serve the seventh game in his 10-game
suspension against the Panthers on Monday and his ninth when the
Panthers visit New Jersey on Saturday for the last game of the
regular season for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had little difficulty against the Lightning, which
entered the game with three victories in its last 17 games but had
beat the Devils on March 17. Sunday night, the Devils scored two
power-play goals 70 seconds apart in the first six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Elias opened the scoring during a two-man advantage 4
minutes 6 seconds into the game with his 34th goal, leading the
team. Standing at Zac Bierk's right doorstep, Elias converted Petr
Sykora's pass from the right side, culminating a play that was
started by Brian Rafalski.
</P>
<P>
   With the Devils setting up camp in Tampa Bay's zone, Vladimir
Malakhov's first goal of the season gave the Devils a two-goal lead
thanks to hard work by Randy McKay in a crowd in front of Bierk,
the sixth goaltender used by Tampa Bay this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' domination in the first period was also translated
into Scott Stevens' eighth goal of the season, a blast from the
left circle in the 12th minute, after a good pass from behind the
goal by Sergei Brylin.
</P>
<P>
   So dominant were the Devils in the first period that the
Lightning had its first attempt at Martin Brodeur in the ninth
minute. The only difficult save Brodeur made in the first two
periods was on a one-timer from the right circle by Steve Martins.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur had a couple of crucial moments in the third period
during a penalty to Rafalski before Elias scored his second of the
night with 7:26 left in the game. Brodeur lost his bid for a second
consecutive shutout with about three minutes left when Fredrik
Modin beat him from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who tied Terry Sawchuk for the most victories over a
five-year span, with 195, improved to 18-4-2 against Tampa Bay. The
Devils lead the series between the teams, 25-6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
