<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5208 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-ADVANCE-HNS &LR;      04-03 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ The pundits claim guard play is the key to success
in the NCAA Tournament.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What they really mean is point-guard play.
</P>
<P>
   Whether quick like Isiah Thomas, heady like Bobby Hurley or
all-around dominant like Magic Johnson, if your point guard gets
the job done, you can win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   For Michigan State (31-7), which plays Florida (29-7) for the
national title tonight at the RCA Dome, the point guard is even
more important to the Spartans' cause. With Florida bent on
pressing, trapping and harassing its foes with its pressure
defense, protecting the ball is a necessity to beat the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   The ball _ and some say Michigan State's fortunes _ will be in
Mateen Cleaves' hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans' senior point guard wouldn't have it any other way.
He believes he was born to be a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can make a leader,'' Cleaves said. ``A
leader is born. You've got to have confidence in yourself because
all eyes are going to be on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates credit Cleaves' halftime outburst against Syracuse for
righting the team's ship and helping the Spartans to a
come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   How he handles the Gators' press will dictate how the rest of
the team handles it. Cleaves knows he sets the pace for the team _
on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the leader, you have to be the hardest worker also,''
Cleaves said. ``I can't go out there, not work hard and then get on
someone else for not working hard. I need myself as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I can say, `If I'm out here an hour before practice and an
hour after practice working out, then why aren't you? If I'm out
here diving on the floor for loose balls, then why can't you?'''
</P>
<P>
   It is that attitude that makes Cleaves so important to the
Spartans. Whether he plays well or not, Cleaves feels he controls
the show. Even when he does not play well, he seems to will the
Spartans to victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida is not the kind of team that succumbs to will.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators score points in bunches. A poor stretch from Cleaves
and the Spartans could result in a quick 10- to 15-point burst by
the Gators. Many times that could mean the game is all but over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida really concerns me,'' Cleaves said. ``They score fast
and have great athletes that get up and down the floor. We can't
play in spurts like we have in some of our previous games or it
will be a long night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans said they lean on Cleaves to keep that from
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the best guards in the country in the open
floor,'' forward Andre Hutson said. ``(Florida's style) gives him a
chance to make some of those open-floor plays. Their press is going
to make us try to do some things that we wouldn't normally do, like
take quick shots. So we have to really focus on taking what they
give us. We've had a lot of success against teams that press, but
we have to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to pick and choose situations in which to take
chances,'' Cleaves said. ``If you go up and down the floor three or
four times without a basket, then you have to slow it down. I've
matured a lot over the years and know when to slow it down and when
to push it. The key is to put other guys in position to make
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cleaves will be called on to handle most of the Spartans'
ball-handling, shooting guard Charlie Bell and small forward Morris
Peterson are capable ball-handlers as well.
</P>
<P>
   When Cleaves was out for the first 12 games of the season with a
stress fracture in his foot, Bell moved to the point and did a
solid job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to face pressing teams, and I feel confident in my
ball-handling,'' Bell said. ``I'm not worried about it. If we
maintain our composure, we can break it. We've beaten teams who
press. If we get it past guys and into the open court, we can get
shots in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mateen is going to need a lot of help. One guy can't beat a
press; it is going to take the whole team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves averages just under four turnovers per game, but he
offsets that with an average of seven assists a contest. The
Spartans turn the ball over 14.6 times a game; Florida forces
nearly 20 miscues a game.
</P>
<P>
   In Peterson, Michigan State has a wingman who can finish the
break. And in Hutson, the Spartans have a post man who runs the
floor well and can even dribble the ball up in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   That versatility will make it difficult for Florida to sustain
its pressure without giving up easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gators are not only trying to speed up the tempo and
create turnovers with their press. They play 10 players, and they
expect to wear their opponent down by game's end.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is what many believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the media helps in talking about the press; other
teams let it get to them mentally,'' Florida forward Brent Wright
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves touched on that point as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of scares you, but we're just going to have to fight
through (fatigue),'' he said. ``This is the last game, and it's for
all the marbles. A lot of wearing down is in your mind. You have to
have inner toughness to fight through it.''
</P>
<P>
   If at some point tonight the Spartans are in trouble and fatigue
is setting in, they will look to Cleaves to provide the spark for
them to fight through it. That's the point guard's job.
</P>
<P>
   If Cleaves wants his name listed among the great point guards in
NCAA Tournament history, this is when he will have to come through.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Monday night is about,'' Cleaves said. ``I'm not a
guy to get caught up in individual stats or individual honors, but
I want our team to be known as national champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to leave a legacy or anything of that sort, you go
out there and win. The name of the game is to win. If you win,
people will always respect you. That's in life or whatever. If
you're a successful person, people will always respect you.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
