<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ Even if you've never been to Gainesville, you
probably know about the image and fun-loving luster the place
emits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a well-earned reputation and as much a sense of pride as a
way of life. Fun and sun. Steve Superior. Blondes. Cocktail
parties. Tans.
</P>
<P>
   The place radiates with an uninhibited spirit that covers the
Gators empire like a morning mist on a Central Florida swamp.
That's why Billy Donovan seems to personify this burgeoning love
affair between Gators fans and their newfound basketball glory.
</P>
<P>
   But even with his starched shirts and slicked-back hair, with
his pressing and running, his bold ways and free-spirited game,
Donovan is only half of the image that should be remembered in this
momentous Gators basketball turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Donovan is the master recruiter and daring young
coach, the image that fulfilled his dream is not typical Florida
brass and dash.
</P>
<P>
   It is a toothy, fair-skinned kid from the land of snowbanks and
prong-horned antelope. It is a lanky kid nicknamed ``Skinny'' who
put the Gators on the fast track to perhaps their first basketball
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tall, goofy white boy from South Dakota,'' is how Gators
forward Mike Miller describes himself.
</P>
<P>
   But such talent. Now a sophomore so skilled that if he decides
to forgo his last two seasons of eligibility he should be an NBA
lottery pick, Miller is likely the most talented player ever to put
on a Gators uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan naturally deserves much credit for persuading Miller two
years ago to travel 2,000 miles across the country and spurn the
likes of proven basketball powers Kansas and Kentucky. Donovan
admits that wooing everyone's All-American out of Mitchell, S.D.,
and making him the cornerstone piece to the Florida plan probably
was his greatest recruiting victory.
</P>
<P>
   And Miller still laughs about the telephone call he received
from Donovan at 12:01 a.m. on the first day coaches could contact
recruits in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was half-mad because Florida wasn't even on my list,''
Miller said. ``Here it is midnight, and I'm getting this call from
coach Donovan. But after that first conversation everything
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Months of intense, high-spirited recruiting ensued, with Donovan
constantly urging and prodding. But it was Miller alone who made
the boldest step and changed Florida's basketball fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will ever truly understand the kind of pressure this
kid was under,'' Donovan said. ``We were second tier in a lot of
people's minds. But he wanted to put his own footprints on a
program.''
</P>
<P>
   By choosing the Gators, who were coming off seasons of 12-16,
13-17 and 14-15, Miller stomped all over conventional wisdom and
found himself in the middle of a bitter feud between Kansas coach
Roy Williams and Donovan. Williams _ amazed that a player of
Miller's ability would dare sign with a mediocre program without
something fishy going on _ reported Donovan to the NCAA, charging
Donovan with recruiting violations.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA investigated but found no wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell into what coach Donovan was preaching, but some people
thought it was more complicated than that,'' Miller said. ``I could
have gone to Kansas and won. I could have gone to Kentucky and won.
But there's a lot more gratitude and satisfaction coming to Florida
and knowing that you helped start something.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this program keeps developing the way it has, maybe
somewhere down the line someone's going to ask a high school kid,
`Gee, why'd you pick Kansas over Florida?'''
</P>
<P>
   Since making his controversial decision to join Donovan two
years ago, the Gators have risen quickly, reaching well outside of
their usual in-state recruiting territory. High school players
across the country noticed Miller's bold steps and followed in
them.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Bonner, from Concord, N.J., signed a year ago, as
did high school All-America forward Donnell Harvey of Shellman,
Ga., and superb high school All-America guard Brett Nelson, who has
been called the best player to hail from West Virginia since Jerry
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're successful here because we have players that buy into
coach Donovan's system and realize he gives us a freedom to just
play,'' Miller said. ``There are players here that could have gone
somewhere else and played 35, 40 minutes, but would they win and be
a part of something special?''
</P>
<P>
   If this amazing Florida rise should culminate with a victory
over Michigan State and a national championship tonight, their
fun-loving and free-wheeling style surely will fit the typical
Florida mold. But the key to it all was the decision the tall,
goofy white kid from South Dakota made two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was very, very rare,'' Donovan said. ``Most kids
would buckle and end up making the easy choice. But he did
something very tough. It seemed like he had to justify his choice
to everyone, but now he doesn't have to justify anything.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
