<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-03 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ This is why he came back. For nights like this when
the air is electric with anticipation and heavy with the burden of
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in St. Petersburg, Fla., when his Spartans lost in a
semifinal game to Duke, he gathered them inside a room at the team
hotel and told them it wasn't enough and that the only acceptable
response was to return to the Final Four and become the Final One.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago at the conclusion of the Big Ten tournament, he
stepped up to the TV cameras and said his Spartans were going to
win it all. Now it is down to only two.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Mateen Cleaves came back for his senior year at
Michigan State. To play Florida for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   And also this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all like to get together and just hang out at each other's
apartment or house, playing video games, watching TV, just making
each other laugh,'' Cleaves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just show up at one guy's house and spread out all over the
place. We might order out for something to eat; we might watch
games on TV or a movie. And when we leave, we're just up and gone.
If it's your house, well, you get to clean up the mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves is a point guard built like a fireplug, the words
spouting from him faster than water from the hydrant, and what is
pouring out now is how he sees that the past year could have been
different if he would have taken his game to the pay window of the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some guys in the NBA,'' Cleaves said. ``And I've heard
what it's like. You've got a locker room where there are 19- and
20-year-olds playing their video games alongside of guys who are 29
or older and have to leave practice right away to tend to the wives
and families. It's a strange mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around here, we all get to be, well, kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids hanging out. Kids cracking jokes. Kids who are still out
there on the court trying to make the shots and the steals and the
plays for the same reasons they always have. Just to prove they're
better than the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   Probably if Cleaves hadn't suffered more injuries than a
crash-test dummy in his career at Michigan State _ back, shoulder,
stress fracture in a foot _ that slowed his development, he'd have
moved on along by now. And then he'd have missed all these things
that are now becoming precious memories. Seeing this team that
settled for the bittersweet taste of playing in the NIT his
freshman year climb the ladder to this spot, just one rung away
from the national championship. Sharing it all with his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves is by no means a sure-shot future All-Star in the NBA.
Listed generously at 6-2, he doesn't run or jump or shoot the ball
particularly well. What he does is push the ball up the court, find
the holes, make the right passes, the right decisions, and lead. He
shot 1-for-7 with one assist in Saturday's victory over Wisconsin
and was invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   He will never draw comparisons with Steve Francis in terms of
athleticism. But if an Avery Johnson can be the starting point
guard on an NBA champion, then there likely is a place for Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Morris Peterson recognized that when they were both 8
years old, playing in a pee-wee tournament in their hometown of
Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this short, stocky guy and said, `Who's he?''' Peterson
recalled. ``But I could tell he had confidence and a game.''
</P>
<P>
   When Peterson's team won that first day and the stocky kid
flopped himself down on his belly and began to pound his fists onto
the court, he also could see how much winning meant to Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   So together with Antonio Smith and Charlie Bell, the four
``Flintstones'' took their act to Michigan State and put down the
bedrock upon which the Spartans' title hopes have been constructed
and relationships built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Morris, we know each other inside and out,'' Cleaves
said. ``All it takes is a look to know what the other is
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cleaves spent the first months of this season hobbling on
crutches with his stress fracture, Peterson said he cooked his
roomie's meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told you that?'' asked Cleaves. ``When Morris `cooked,'
that usually meant he drove out for some fast food or put popcorn
in the microwave.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week when his friend returned from attending his
grandmother's funeral in Mississippi, it was Cleaves who embraced
him and did all he could to pick him up, and Peterson produced 20
points to beat Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win this game, we go down in the books and we'll always
be remembered,'' Cleaves said. ``If we don't, I've had one more
year to hang out with Morris and the guys. To be a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why he came back. For tonight. For all those nights.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
