<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONGRESSMAN WEIGHS RESUMING N.Y. SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ariz.)  (jw) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, noting a recent decline in
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's standing in the polls, said on national
television Sunday that he was once again considering a bid for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ready to run,'' Lazio, a Long Island Republican, said on
``This Week,'' ABC's Sunday morning political interview program.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, 42, a four-term congressman and a former Suffolk County
legislator, defied party leaders in announcing a bid for the Senate
last summer, but then backed down at the urging of Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Sunday that the mayor's ``dramatically collapsing''
poll numbers against Hillary Rodham Clinton had led him to
reconsider his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the process of potentially blowing this race,''
Lazio said of the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's decline in the polls has been attributed to his
hard-line reaction to the March 16 fatal shooting of an unarmed man
by police officers. The mayor authorized the release of sealed
court records concerning the victim, Patrick Dorismond, and implied
that Dorismond had been partly responsible for his death.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he would run only if encouraged to do so by party
leaders. Spokesmen for Pataki and the New York Republican State
Committee made it clear Sunday afternoon that Lazio's entrance into
the race would not be welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership has not changed its mind,'' said Dan
Allen, a Republican State Committee spokesman. ``We are 100 percent
behind Mayor Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, a senior policy adviser to Pataki, added: ``The
governor very strongly supports the mayor's candidacy for the
Senate and feels he is the best man to beat Hillary Rodham Clinton.
It is important that the Republican Party unite behind one
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager, said that Lazio's
comments were no surprise. ``It seems to me that he said all this
before,'' he said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Long, chairman of the state Conservative Party, said
he hoped that Lazio would formally enter the Senate race, and that
he might win the endorsement of both the Conservative and
Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   More so than Giuliani, Lazio ``reflects the views of the average
Republican throughout the state of New York,'' said Long, who has
clashed with the mayor over his support of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spent the weekend in Arizona, where he attended two
fund-raising events. He plans to campaign on Tuesday in New York
with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had backed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas over McCain in
the New York Republican presidential primary last month. But the
mayor also frequently complimented McCain, an old friend, and the
senator's staff members said he wanted to repay the favor by
encouraging moderate Republicans who had supported his bid for
president to back the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
