<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS IN OWN FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So, there it is.
</P>
<P>
   With only four games remaining in the Bruins' season, the
1999-2000 edition all boils down to contests against Tampa Bay
Tuesday, the Florida Panthers Wednesday, the Philadelphia Flyers
Saturday, and the Pittsburgh Penguins (the only game at the
FleetCenter) Sunday. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no postseason for Boston _ that became official
after Saturday's 2-2 tie with the New York Rangers, which knocked
both clubs out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing deadlock was a microcosm of the season _ the
Bruins played well for a time, got a lead, and then blew it in the
third period. The tying goal _ by Rangers rookie Michael York with
1:20 remaining in regulation _ was an awful case of Murphy's Law
for Boston right wing Eric Nickulas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned the puck over down below, then I try to get back and
I don't get back; I try to get it out on the point and can't get it
out,'' said Nickulas, shaking his head. ``I just watched it on the
film. York fed it out to the slot, another guy tried to one-time
it, and I went out and tried to block it. It hit my stick and it
was sitting right on the doorstep for him and he just put it in the
back door. What are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the way of a team chock-full of youngsters with little
experience. They have yet to learn to play with a lead, among many
other lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all it is _ frustration,'' said goalie John Grahame,
who weathered 14 shots in the third period and stopped all but
York's. ``We're playing solid for 50 minutes or 55 or whatever, not
just quite 60. We're just going to have to learn from it and keep
moving on. There's nothing you can do. Experience is the only way
we're going to learn. Hopefully, if we keep learning from it,
things will be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Grahame said he could see the difference in that fateful third
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York was jumping a lot more,'' he said. ``You can just see
the talent level they have. They can control it when they want to
and they just kind of took it to us in that third period. We held
them off as long as we could. We have to go back at them just as
hard instead of being intimidated by all the skill and everything
they have. If we would've come hard at them, I think the outcome
might have been a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent call-ups from Providence provided the Boston offense,
with Jay Henderson picking up his first NHL goal (as well as an
assist) and Antti Laaksonen, just recalled Saturday morning for his
fourth stint in Boston, getting the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to see guys do well,'' said Grahame.
``They're getting an opportunity to show what they can do. For the
most part, everyone has tried to take advantage of it. I'm glad to
see it for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins started the season 0-5-4 but weren't playing as badly
as their record indicated. Lately, though, the team laden with AHL
players has been fine in spurts but has surrendered lead after
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, either, to be honest,'' said Grahame.
``I'm just going out there and trying to stop the puck. Sometimes,
we have the lead and we don't stick with what got us there. We kind
of hang back a little bit. We didn't do it as much (against the
Rangers) but that's the way it goes sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to work on our positioning and try to overcome that
bad luck or whatever. I think maybe if we try to be more
aggressive, the outcome might have been a little different. We have
a lot of guys here with not a lot of experience. Everyone is
learning. Let's hope they're quick learners.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Nick Boynton made his NHL debut, logging 20 minutes
25 seconds over 17 shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really, really nervous, but after the first couple of
shifts, I felt pretty good so I can't complain,'' said Boynton, the
Bruins' first pick (No. 21 overall) in last June's draft. If he has
an area that isn't up to par, it's his conditioning. Boynton is
coming off a knee injury and had only played a couple of games in
Providence before being called up to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all right. I'm not quite what I should be,'' he said,
``but it's almost there. My knees feel fine. I strained my MCL and
came back a bit too soon and I tried to push it and just twisted it
again. It set me back a couple of weeks but I feel 100 percent
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
