<SLUG> BC-TEN-ERICSSONOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS TAKES TOUGH VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Maybe it isn't an epitaph Pete Sampras
would approve for himself, but words uttered a few years ago by a
rival, Jim Courier, seem to fit: ``Every time Pete looks dead . . .
he rises up to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo ``Guga'' Kuerten understands.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten, a Brazilian built like a scarecrow, threw a scare into
the high-flying Sampras, clipped his wings, and sent him into a
seemingly groggy tailspin as the Ericsson Open title bout
approached a roaring climax in its fourth set. The man from coffee
country drove the 14,000 witnesses filling Crandon Park Sunday to
such a frenzy that they'd better order decaf for a while.
</P>
<P>
   As Sampras resurrected himself on the green slab below them, the
patrons enhanced the electrified atmosphere by waging a spirited
vocal battle. Kuerten's flag-shaking Brazilian compatriots in green
and yellow chanted and sang his name _ ``Gooo-gaaa! Gooo-gaaa!'' _
and the Pete-pushers countered with choruses of ``Let's go, Pete!
Let's go, Pete!''
</P>
<P>
   It had everything. A nerves-busting opus that wound up with
Sampras admittedly ``choking on match points'' (squandering six of
them in the third overtime) _ and yet soaring after all, as great
champions do, to win, 6-1, 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-5), 7-6 (10-8).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dogfight,'' said Sampras of the 3-hour-18-minute
bow-wowser that the underpup very nearly sent into a fifth set.
``It was my toughest match in months, more demanding than the
five-set semifinal I lost at the Australian to Andre Agassi. I
don't know if I could have recovered if it went to five. Sure, I
choked some; nerves got me at the end. I was probably lucky on the
last match point (the seventh) that his passing shot just missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I sucked it up. You do what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   You do if you are Sampras, holder of 12 majors, winning his 62d
pro singles title, now abreast of Bjorn Borg and Guillermo Vilas in
the all-time chase, though still behind Jimmy Connors (109), Ivan
Lendl (94), and John McEnroe (77).
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Sampras said with a laugh, ``I get a day off before
starting work for Davis Cup (a weekend series against the Czech
Republic in Los Angeles). It would have been very hard to get up
again if I'd lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten said with a shrug, ``When I play well, then he play
good, too. I think we were both tired, but I have more chance in
the fifth. But . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But the fifth will have to wait for another day because Sampras,
though wobbling and groping, dragging between every point in the
climactic 18-point tie-breaker, kept coming at Kuerten. Despite his
pale appearance, Sampras kept charging and reflexing vital volleys,
letting Kuerten know only the finest shots would beat him.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth set-that-wasn't could have commenced earlier if
Kuerten had seized one of the two set points for which he had
reached with Sampras serving at 5-6, 30-40, and then ad-out.
Sampras served and volleyed too determinedly to let it happen.
</P>
<P>
   With a reprieve, Sampras flapped to 3-0 in the decisive
tie-breaker, then 6-2, four successive match points, of which
Sampras would serve two. ``I was having it my way,'' he said, ``but
I got tight. Sure, it happens. Everybody in sports chokes
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And just like this,'' Sampras snapped his fingers, ``those
match points disappeared.'' His error; Kuerten's pair of low,
half-volley-disrupting returns; and another error. Suddenly it was
6-6. The stadium rocked with the two combatants.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras socked a backhand winner to set up a fifth match point
at 7-6. But he double-faulted, his second serve seeking the net
like a stupefied salmon. Back to form: a service winner to 8-7.
Oops, a backhand error, 8-8. Now Kuerten, with serve, was within
reach of another set point.
</P>
<P>
   But it was chip-and-charge time again, the serve-returning
tactic that much earlier had given Sampras a two-set lead.
</P>
<P>
   His return was a rare chip, a forehand, not very sharp, but it
got him to the service line for a nifty backhand volley. So the 9-8
lead belonged to him, not Kuerten, with a seventh match point.
</P>
<P>
   One last salute to Admiral Farragut: Damn Kuerten's torpedoes,
full steam ahead! One more serve, one more volley _ not forceful _
but Kuerten's forehand passer grazed the net cord on the way past
Sampras, enough of a disturbance to make it land an inch beyond the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing as well as I could for almost two sets,'' said
Sampras, who had launched killer hook serves for aces and winners,
volleyed acrobatically, and pressured Kuerten with the
chip-and-charge. ``But I let it slip, and Guga fought his way back
in. Not an accident, really. You think of him as a clay-court guy
(he's the French Open champ of 1997), but Guga can play on this or
anything. He'll be around, and good, for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The nimble, whippy scarecrow _ 6 feet 3 inches, 150 pounds _
almost frightened Sampras to death. But with Sampras, it's always
too soon for an epitaph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
