<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-McALLISTER-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Nev., Ore., Ariz.)  
 WAYNE McALLISTER, 92, ARCHITECT FOR A CAR CULTURE  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wayne McAllister, a West Coast architect who some critics say
elevated commercial structures like the drive-in restaurant and the
theme resort to art forms, died on March 22 in Arcadia, Calif. He
was 92.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister injured his head in a fall on March 3 near his home
in Pasadena, Calif., and never regained consciousness, said his son
Donald.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister created his designs for a world shaped by the
automobile and for people who seldom willingly left it, even to
eat. He let them drive through fantasy drive-ins and cruise by
palaces on the Las Vegas strip.
</P>
<P>
   Among McAllister's memorable creations were the Sands (the
hangout for Frank Sinatra and Dean Martin), El Rancho Hotel (the
first of many theme resorts on the Las Vegas Strip), the expansion
of the Los Feliz Brown Derby and restaurants for the Pig 'n Whistle
and Kentucky Fried Chicken chains.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rapid growth of cities like Los Angeles and Las
Vegas, where his works once dotted the cityscapes, and because
flamboyant commercial architecture was not highly regarded, only a
few of his buildings survive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, however, Chris Nichols, an architectural historian, led
a successful effort to have the Bob's Big Boy restaurant,
McAllister's low-slung, mustard-colored, drive-in on Riverside
Drive in Los Angeles, designated as a California State Point of
Historical Interest. The 1949 restaurant, the third Bob's built and
the oldest still in existence, is considered an outstanding example
of 1940s art moderne, with a whiff of 1950s coffee-shop modern.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in McAllister's work grew, and in 1998 an exhibition of
photographs and drawings of his designs was presented at the
Pacific Design Center in Los Angeles. ``Wayne McAllister didn't
invent the drive-in restaurant, but in the 1930s he took it a step
higher than the diner and made it reflect a way of life,'' said
Nichols, curator of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture critic Alan Hess has praised McAllister's work
in his books ``Googie: Fifties Coffee Shop Architecture'' (1986)
and ``Viva Las Vegas'' (1993). Calling McAllister ``one of the most
significant architects of the 20th century in terms of creativity
of form and influence,'' Hess said, ``He saw that the world was
becoming shaped by the automobile.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part McAllister was humble. In 1998 he told The Los
Angeles Times, ``I just ran a modest office and did modest work.''
</P>
<P>
   He often said that he simply tried to fill a need, and that his
futuristic dazzle was ``influenced by the automobile, not the
architect.''
</P>
<P>
   Born on Nov. 17, 1907, in San Diego, McAllister dropped out of
high school to work for an architect. At 20 he designed the Mexican
resort Agua Caliente, which was later frequented by Clark Gable,
Jean Harlow and Gloria Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son Donald, who lives in Corvallis, Ore.,
McAllister is survived by his wife, Corinne, of Pasadena; two other
children, David of Tucson, Ariz., and Paulette of Prescott, Ariz.;
four grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister gave up architecture in 1956 and moved to Washington
to become vice president of Marriott Corp. He returned to Los
Angeles in 1962 where he developed coin-operated copying machines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
