<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS WORK ON TURNAROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After Boston lost to Cleveland Saturday night, Antoine
Walker was the last player to the leave the locker room. He took
his time getting dressed. Then, he took his time talking about the
Celtics' latest setback. He did not rush to the team bus, but
answered every last question. He did not run from the bad luck and
bad play that has doomed Boston, but faced a future that does not
include the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' seventh straight defeat left Walker disappointed
but not despondent. Seven games behind Orlando in the Eastern
Conference, Boston's focus has shifted. The Celtics have nine games
left to show signs of progress and demonstrate they are better than
their 30-43 record. According to Walker, there's no better time
than the present to start reversing the Celtics' fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to keep playing,'' he said. ``We've got to get off
this losing streak first. We've got nine games that we're going to
try to win. We've got to come in with the mentality that we're
going to win the next nine and go from there. You can have no other
mindset or you'll never reach your potential, you'll never get 110
percent effort every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to keep working and make the next nine games
the most positive nine games we can make it. We've just got to
continue to work and not get discouraged. We're fighting through a
lot of adversity and we've got to continue to battle and fight and
it's going to show the character of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout March and into April, the Celtics' learning curve has
followed a tortuous path. They were tantalizingly close to a
postseason appearance before the season unraveled in dramatic
fashion. If Boston's emotions were actually charted, the line would
be marked with sharp peaks and valleys that kept getting lower.
</P>
<P>
   The ups and downs have been well-documented: three losses at the
buzzer in March; a Rick Pitino rant about the negativity in Boston;
an impressive 7-2 stretch that followed the tirade; the
double-overtime defeat in Philadelphia that effectively sucked the
playoff life out of Boston; an embarrassing loss at Orlando that
led to finger-pointing and the threat of suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   All that and Boston continues to find experiences to learn from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past frustration. You know what I mean. It's frustration
10 times over,'' said Eric Williams after the Celtics let a
10-point lead slip away against the Cavaliers. ``We've just got to
go out there and play these games and learn how to win games down
the stretch. It's not about the other team. It's us right now.
We're still trying to figure it all out. We can break down the tape
and go through everything. If we don't do it on the court, it's all
for naught.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the tough losses and the times they caught glimpses
of their unrealized potential, the Celtics are not planning to
stagger to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got is games to play so we can get better, have
pride in ourselves,'' said Kenny Anderson. ``We can come to work
every day until the last buzzer goes off. It's still our job. We're
not making the playoffs, but we've got to play and get better and
carry it into next season. We can't throw in the towel because of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Walker: ``We've got to keep plugging and try to somehow
salvage our season by playing good basketball and proving to
ourselves that we can play and continue to know that it's going to
turn around for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker hopes the next couple of days will give the Celtics a
chance to rest and ready themselves for the final two weeks of the
season. But Boston next faces back-to-back road games with
playoff-bound teams in Charlotte and Detroit. Not exactly the
situation a team trying to snap a losing streak wants to find
itself in. Still, Walker voices optimism. He sees the road games as
an opportunity for a late-season turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much what the team can take,'' said Walker of the
mounting losses. ``We've got to correct. Nobody from the outside
can help you. The only way to correct it is the one game that gets
us back on the positive side. We've got to do it on the road.
You've got to come in with the right frame of mind. I think we
will. One day, we're going to have our time in the sun and be the
team on top.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the young and wealthy should learn, it's never too soon
to start preparing for the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
