<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CUP-STEVE-PARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD LUCK KEEPS CURTAILING PARK'S SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's turning out to be a disturbing pattern
for Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six races, including yesterday's DirecTV 500 at
Texas Motor Speedway, Park has either had a top-10 finish or a
blown engine.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worse part of that cycle yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Park had climbed to fourth with fewer than 70 laps remaining,
when his car began to smoke. He had to pit on Lap 314, when Winston
Cup officials posted a black flag. Park said that he lost a
cylinder in his No. 1 Pennzoil Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Park finished 19th, one week after he won the pole at Bristol
and ended up seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a motor, that is all you can say,'' Park said. ``We
had another good top-five run going, and to have it spoiled with
another motor problem ... I am so disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Park admitted that he might not have had a car that could keep
up with his Dale Earnhardt Inc. teammate and race-winner Dale
Earnhardt Jr. But he was expecting a top-five finish.
</P>
<P>
   The way things have been going for Park this season, though,
yesterday was an unfortunate day in a cycle that started in
Rockingham, N.C., in February. He finished ninth in that race on
Feb. 27, but one week later he lost a motor at Las Vegas and was
43rd.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to form at Atlanta on March 12, picking up a
career-best, fourth-place finish. Then on March 19, he had another
motor problem and ended up 39th in Darlington, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistent finishes have kept Park from climbing the point
standings. He was 19th after yesterday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win races and finish races if your stuff don't stay
together,'' Park said. ``That is not the kind of streak you want to
be a part of. Junior was real fast all day long. The 18 \RBobby
Labonte\S and 99 \RJeff Burton\S seemed to be the class of the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's engine troubles are strange considering that Dale
Earnhardt Jr.'s engines come out of the same shop. Park has had
more top-10 finishes over the first seven races of the season, but
Earnhardt's engines have stayed together through most every race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our confidence is high,'' Park said. ``This wavers you and
takes the wind out of you a little bit. It could be worse. We could
be running like junk and blowing up. It seems like when you run
like that your stuff lasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Park still managed to smile because Earnhardt Jr. won
yesterday's race, but Park must now focus on next week's race at
Martinsville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   He will take a new car, that the team will test tomorrow in
Greenville, S.C., to Martinsville He just hopes that he will
finally break the cycle and match the accomplishment of his
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be a part of a two-car team because we both have
the availability to test and we share a lot of information,'' Park
said. ``We can get a win if we can stop breaking down. We got a
good race team there, and I am keeping a good perspective about
it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
