<HEADLINE>
RUSTY WALLACE SAYS FOURTH PLACE KEEPS HIS MOMENTUM GOING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RUSTY WALLACE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had a great car today. I led a lot of laps. I wound up in the
top five.
</P>
<P>
   I had good pit stops, but not great pit stops. I was losing
three and four positions, and one time I lost eight. And I said,
``Man, I just can't take those chances any more.'' So I started
putting on two tires so we could get track position. And the two
tires ran really, really good for me.
</P>
<P>
   We gained a lot of points (moving up to fifth in the Winston Cup
standings). It was a good strong run. I finished fourth here last
year, so it looks like I'm stuck on fourth. But I'm not going to
complain about it because that was a good run. And to come off a
win and come here and finish fourth and keep the momentum going and
gain a lot of points ... that's what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   I thought the track was excellent. All day long it was
consistent. I thought the tires were consistent.
</P>
<P>
   We had a seventh new winner this year today. The races have been
so damn exciting it's been unreal after the Daytona fiasco with the
cars not being real racey. Of course, it sure has changed a lot. It
was great all day long.
</P>
<P>
   Man, the race was just action-packed. It was super-exciting.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans got to see a new kid win, a young guy win who's
pretty much a fan favorite. I'm happy for him. We're competing on
the track for the beer brands, but we don't really compete. He's a
good kid.
</P>
<P>
   It establishes him as one of the forces. He did a great job.
They got that car dialed in and really flying. The thing that was
so good about it is that when they put new tires on, it would run
fast. When I put new tires on my car, it would dog my car down. A
lot of guys, I noticed, it would dog their cars down. But he would
put new tires on and make his fly.
</P>
<P>
   A little overanxious driving caused the wrecks. It sure wasn't
the racetrack. On some of those restarts, a lot of guys had rubber
built up on their tires. I could see that. And they'd get up on
that outside and get a little loose, and that was hurting.
</P>
<P>
   I just drove around the wrecks. I never was around any crashes.
I got lucky. I wasn't in that atmosphere.
nn
</P>
