<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALE JARRETT'S GOOD DEED CAN'T SAVE A BAD DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ No good deed goes unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, NASCAR's defending Winston Cup Series champion,
experienced the harsh reality of that adage yesterday during the
DirecTV 500 at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's No. 88 Quality Care Ford slammed into the wall in Turn
1 on Lap 247 after touching the No. 28 Texaco//Havoline Ford driven
by teammate Ricky Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett led the race on three occasions for a total of 18 laps,
but the accident doomed him to a 33rd-place finish after qualifying
fifth Friday. Jarrett returned to race after being examined and
released from Lone Star Health Infield Care Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be OK,'' said Jarrett, whose car also received attention
in the garage during his examination. ``I'm just a little bit sore.
I hit my right knee on the steering column.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett also appeared sore, perhaps at Rudd. Jarrett could not
identify the cause for his accident, although replays revealed that
their cars touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the replay,'' Jarrett said. ``I didn't. I don't know.
I'm not sure what happened. I just know I got into one. The car
started wiggling. If that was from a touch or if that was from the
tires, I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd's participation in the accident proved ironic. Jarrett
slowed before the start//finish line and allowed Rudd to pass him
and remain on the lead lap preceding the race's caution for laps
157-159.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief, went out of his way to shed
light on his team's good deed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 28 car got his one help for the day,'' Parrott told CBS'
national television audience. ``Now, they've got to get the car
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words came back to haunt Parrott.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the second consecutive disappointing weekend for
Jarrett, who finished 21st in the Food City 500 at Bristol Motor
Speedway on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are just things that you go through,'' Jarrett said.
``We'll have to come back next time.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
