<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JEFF-GORDON-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW-LOOK TEAM, SAME OLD PROBLEMS IN TEXAS FOR GORDON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF WILSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway remains a mystery to
Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beats the heck out of me,'' said Gordon, unable to pinpoint
his bad luck here. ``I just can't seem to stay out of trouble. I
don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   A four-car wreck in Turn 2 yesterday became the latest malady
for the three-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion at TMS. Gordon was
running in the top 20 of the DirecTV 500 and nose-to-tail with a
pack of cars that encountered slower, lapped cars. Gordon struck
Hendrick Racing teammate Jerry Nadeau, who started the incident
when he tapped Dave Blaney. The worst damage, though, was caused by
Bill Elliott, whose car briefly lifted onto Gordon's hood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't pass. I couldn't do anything,'' Gordon said.
``If you can't pass, you're going to have a lot of wrecks, and
that's what happened today.''
</P>
<P>
   The wreck was the fourth for Gordon in four Cup races at TMS. He
also crashed in the Coca-Cola 300 Busch Grand National race in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good out there until I got in the back of Jerry,''
Gordon said. ``Before that, everything was really good. We were
just biding our time, waiting for track position.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon managed to stay on the lead lap but eventually lost it
and went behind the wall for repairs on Lap 265. He returned five
laps later and finished the race down 14 laps and in 25th place.
Nadeau finished 43rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do?'' Nadeau said. ``It's just part of
NASCAR racing. The cars bunched up in front of me and I got back
into the No. 93 after someone tapped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's previous best at TMS was a 30th-place run in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a place that really is easy to maneuver,'' Gordon
said. ``This is the toughest place there is on the circuit to pass.
It's a one-groove racetrack. It doesn't offer what we are notorious
for.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Gordon has been notorious for his fall from Cup
contender to a driver struggling to adapt to a new team.
</P>
<P>
   A patchwork crew of ``Rainbow Warriors'' helps a new crew chief
service the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet. Late last
season, Ray Evernham left Gordon to help jump-start
Daimler-Chrysler's venture into Cup racing with Dodge in 2001.
Robbie Loomis was hired after last season to replace Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the off-season, reigning Cup champion Dale Jarrett
hired five Warriors to the No. 88 Quality Care Ford team, leaving
Gordon without six team members who helped him to three series
titles in four years.
</P>
<P>
   The new No. 24 team has yet jell to Gordon's standards. He has
gone 12 races without a top-five finish. Gordon stands 12th in
points after yesterday's race. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
