<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVERA-CONTRACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' RIVERA EXPECTS LONG-TERM CONTRACT SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (REMOVES reference to luxury tax in lede.) 
 (ms) 
 By   BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mariano Rivera, the New York Yankees' closer,
said Sunday that he was hopeful of reaching agreement on a
long-term contract shortly into the season. ``I think we could get
something done,'' he said. ``I'm not looking to get all the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are not negotiating with Rivera, who is the game's
best closer, but there was not a large divide in the proposals
passed between the two sides before the Feb. 17 arbitration
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Before the hearing, the Yankees had offered Rivera a four-year,
$36 million contract, according to people familiar with the
negotiations. Just as the case was about to be heard, Rivera's
agent offered four proposals with suggested packages of $37.5
million, $38 million, $38.5 million and $39 million. Under the
$37.5 million proposal, the reliever's base salary would have
increased by $750,000 if he had won the Rolaids award as the top
reliever, and there were similar bonuses attached to the other
packages as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera lost his case and will earn $7.25 million this year,
rather than the $9.25 million for which he asked. Rivera and
shortstop Derek Jeter will be eligible for free agency after the
2001 season. Jeter, whose agent negotiated a seven-year, $118.5
million deal that never got final approval from the principal
owner, George Steinbrenner, said he knew of no progress toward
completing any contract. ``It's not up to me,'' Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Johnson, the former Mets outfielder, was added to the
Yankees' major league roster Sunday as the team made its final
moves in preparation for Monday's season opener against the Angels.
Johnson, 36, agreed to a one-year deal worth $350,000, and he will
be used primarily as a pinch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance is very excited about the chance to be with the
Yankees,'' said Phil Tannenbaum, his agent. Johnson was expected to
arrive here this evening and perhaps participate in a workout at
the Angels' Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will open the season using Jim Leyritz as their
backup catcher, behind Jorge Posada; six outfielders, including
Johnson and Roberto Kelly as bench players; six infielders,
including Clay Bellinger and the newly acquired Wilson Delgado; and
11 pitchers _ the opening day starter, Orlando Hernandez, and Roger
Clemens, David Cone, Andy Pettitte, Ramiro Mendoza, Mariano Rivera,
Mike Stanton, Jeff Nelson, Allen Watson, Jason Grimsley and Todd
Erdos.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees designated pitcher Mike Buddie for assignment and
have 10 days to trade him or pass him through waivers. They also
optioned pitcher Darrell Einertson to Triple-A Columbus and
reassigned infielder Jon Zuber, outfielder Felix Jose, pitcher
Domingo Jean and catcher Chris Turner to Triple-A. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
