<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SCHOUREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOUREK SIGNING THROWS WAKEFIELD A CURVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a move that inevitably will raise almost as many
questions about the state of the Red Sox pitching staff as it will
answer, the Sox brought back lefthander Pete Schourek and put him
in the starting rotation, bumping Tim Wakefield back to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, best known for his valiant performance as manager Jimy
Williams's much-debated choice to pitch the deciding game of the
1998 American League Division Series against the Cleveland Indians,
was released last week by Pittsburgh just two days before training
camp ended in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates elected to eat Schourek's $2 million salary and go
with rookie Jimmy Anderson rather than have the 30-year-old as
their fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, by offering Schourek a
club option for the 2001 season for essentially the same money he
is to be paid this season, outbid the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and
Atlanta Braves for Schourek's services. The Sox will be obliged to
pay only the minimum $200,000 this season for Schourek, with the
Pirates picking up the rest of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real tempting,'' Schourek said of the offer from the
Braves, the defending National League champions who instead signed
veteran John Burkett to help fill the void created by the
season-ending elbow surgery to John Smoltz. ``But they didn't want
to make much of a commitment to me. They just wanted to use me for
the time being until one of their younger pitchers was ready, just
filling the gap, and then I would have been back in the same
situation again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox signaled a greater commitment, he said, with their
offer of an added year on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is guaranteed in baseball,'' he said. ``But the Red
Sox made a little more of a financial commitment than Atlanta was
willing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An agreement was reached Friday, a day when Schourek worked out
with the high school team in West Springfield, Va., for which his
brother, Danny, is an assistant coach. But Duquette did not
announce the move until Sunday here, where the Sox open the 2000
season Tuesday night at 8 against the Seattle Mariners. Schourek
will pitch the in Anaheim on Friday, the opening game of a
three-game set against the Angels. That was the start Wakefield was
on track to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know _ destiny, I guess,'' Schourek said with a
chuckle as he reeled off the chain of events that brought him back
to the Red Sox, who first bought him from the Houston Astros in an
August 1998 waiver deal.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek made eight starts for the Sox down the stretch, going
1-3 with a 4.30 ERA. With Pedro Martinez in no shape to pitch on
short rest in the playoffs, according to pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan, Schourek was selected to start Game 4 of the '98 Division
Series, and responded with 5 1/3 scoreless innings in a game the
Sox ultimately lost, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek thought he'd found a home in Boston after that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of excited going into the offseason, thinking I'd
get a halfway-decent deal for the way I'd pitched,'' Schourek said.
``But as I recall, Boston offered me a minor league deal. I was
kind of surprised, but I got over it in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, worried about Schourek's history of elbow trouble, were
reluctant to commit beyond a minor league deal and went into last
season without a lefthander in the rotation. Schourek, meanwhile,
did not live up to Pittsburgh's expectations, going 4-7 with a 5.34
ERA in 30 appearances last season, and failed to finish the sixth
inning in 12 of his 17 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox took Sunday off but plan to work out at Safeco Field
this afternoon. Williams said Schourek will throw three innings in
a simulated game. Schourek acknowledged that Pirates doctors found
some small bone chips in his left elbow but said that after taking
anti-inflammatory medication he was OK.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield stepped in as closer last year when Tom Gordon tore
the ligament in his right elbow but he thought his days as a
reliever were over entering camp this season.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield pitched two innings in a minor league game in Fort
Myers Sunday, allowing one run. He arrived at the team's hotel at
about 9 p.m. local time. Asked for his reaction to being sent to
the pen, Wakefield said, ``I'll let you know tomorrow. I'm meeting
with Jimy and Joe (Kerrigan, pitching coach).
</P>
<P>
   All spring, Wakefield had been adamant about not pitching again
in relief. But the Sox, who left Wakefield off the roster for the
ALCS against the New York Yankees in October, once again dealt a
blow to his ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's disappointed,'' said Williams. ``I don't blame
him. But we don't have a lot of pitchers in the minor leagues to
put in Juan Pena's spot or Rod Beck's spot. I feel it's a good
move, putting a veteran pitcher in that slot who has pitched there
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have a number of marginal big leaguers who have pitched
in relief before _ Dan Smith, Julio Santana, Willie Adams _ who
could have been pressed into service for the short term until Beck
recovers from the irritated nerve in his neck. Schourek's signing
suggests the Sox want him for the rotation not only to take
Wakefield's spot but perhaps to replace lefthander Jeff Fassero,
who was 5-14 last season and did not have a good spring.
</P>
<P>
   Williams insisted the move was born of necessity, not as a
commentary on Wakefield's performance this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told Wakefield before spring training he was going to
start, but things happened to our pitchers,'' Williams said. ``He's
pitched out of the bullpen before. We need him. Does this mean he
won't start again? No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
