<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     04-03 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING EXPECTATIONS COULD LEAD TO NASTY FALL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The 100th American League Boston baseball season
begins Tuesday night in this town without Griffey. The Red Sox will
be more than 3,000 miles from home when Pedro Martinez toes the
rubber at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   To find a season in which more was expected of the Red Sox, one
probably would have to go back to the spring of 1978 when 20-game
winner Dennis Eckersley joined a team that a year earlier had seven
All-Stars, hit a franchise record 213 homers, and won 97 games.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it feels this spring. The 2000 Sox haven't played
a game yet, but they are kings of New England, expected to light up
the summer sky and compete with the hated Yankees come harvest
time.
</P>
<P>
   The boundless expectation has, at times, seemed silly. The Sox
have two of the game's top five players in Martinez and Nomar
Garciaparra. They're coming off seasons of 92 and 94 wins and
they've added five-tool center fielder Carl Everett. They're
capable of scoring a ton of runs without hitting a ton of homers,
and Derek Lowe could be a dominant closer. Best of all, they should
be held up by an AL that has only a couple of really good teams _
the Yankees and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But is it fair to put them on the cover of Sports Illustrated
with a headline predicting that this is the year they finally win
the World Series? Is there some form of mass delusion at work when
thousands of citizens of Red Sox Nation walk around saying, ``This
is the year''?
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are hot. No doubt about it. Never mind their sorry
spring record of 11-19. Never mind the fact that their No. 2 and 3
starters _ Ramon Martinez and Jeff Fassero _ kept getting lit up
this spring. Never mind that Ramon has pitched 20 2/3
regular-season big league innings since June of '98 and that
Fassero was 5-14 last year. Never mind that Juan Pena, a contender
for the No. 5 job a week ago, might never pitch in the big leagues
again now that he's slated for Tommy John surgery.
</P>
<P>
   All teams have holes and it's early to suggest that the wheels
could fall off this Sox machine. But unlike other years, they're
not going to sneak up on anyone in 2000. The Sox have targets on
their backs. Bettering predictions of low finishes is easier than
playing up to great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Sox general manager Dan Duquette admits, ``It's easier to
operate the ball club when expectations are low . . . but it's nice
to come into the season with a good foundation of fan support.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Sox players have no idea how much New England expects from
them. They dispersed after losing the playoffs to the Yankees and
they weren't around to see the Patriots, Bruins, and Celtics get
flushed down the hopper. They haven't endured Pete Carroll, Jeremy
Jacobs, Ray Bourque getting traded, and Rick Pitino's diatribes
about the ``negativity'' in the New Garden. They can't possibly
know of the winter wasteland that was New England sports in
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell what it's like in Boston, because I haven't been
there yet,'' says Pedro. ``But I'm glad they expect good things.
What they expect we can do is one thing and what we can do is
another thing. I hope we can please them. I hope we can do whatever
we can do to win it all and give it to Boston. Boston deserves
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When this opening trip to Seattle and Anaheim is over, the Sox
will come home to a town hungry for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, who was a junior at Amherst when the fever last peaked
in '78, says, ``There's been a lot of enthusiasm for the Red Sox
over the wintertime. People really enjoyed themselves last year
during the Division Series and the ALCS. They're enthusiastic that
the core of the team is returning. We had enthusiasm from the fans
on the winter tour and it was also reflected in fans buying
tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that the fans are excited about this
team,'' says veteran John Valentin. ``Expectations are always gonna
be there and it's good they're high.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley, another veteran, admitted he hasn't been in Boston
since the day after Orlando Hernandez beat Kent Mercker in Game 5.
``I can only just imagine what it's like,'' he says. ``But the way
they reacted to what we did last year when they weren't optimistic
and we provided, now I think they are anxious to get us back. But I
don't think it will change our approach. We can use the extra buzz
at Fenway. When we've got a quality team on the field, it puts that
much more pressure on the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans like these players,'' adds Duquette. ``They like
Pedro, they like Nomar. They like (Jason) Varitek and Troy O'Leary
and they were enthusiastic about the addition of Carl Everett.
Ninety-nine was a great year for Boston baseball and they're all
coming back for this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox uniform through the years has proved too heavy for some.
Calvin Schiraldi couldn't play here. Neither could Matt Young, nor
Mike Marshall. Wade Boggs and Roger Clemens were among those who
had to go elsewhere to win championships. Fred Lynn and Bruce Hurst
played their best ball here, but didn't like the climate. Both
later regretted leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's there,'' acknowledges young reliever Lowe.
``When you come to Boston you're expected to win and that's the way
it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to win in 2000. Historically, the Sox have not
been at their best under these conditions. But it's a new century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
