r a BC-TEACHERS-UNION_LADN     04-03 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-UNION_LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS SEEK `CLASSROOM BILL OF RIGHTS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE AND DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Angrily rejecting the school district's plan to
tie teacher pay to performance, Los Angeles' powerful teachers
union on Sunday unveiled its own contract proposal, demanding a
cumulative 21 percent raise.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal from United Teachers Los Angeles also goes far
beyond mere issues of pay, calling for a ``Classroom Bill of
Rights'' that would cap class sizes in all grades and make unclean
classrooms or a lack of textbooks grounds for a grievance against
the school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole lot of very angry people,'' said union
President Day Higuchi, addressing the union's membership at
Hamilton High School, just north of Culver City.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which represents the union's opening offer in
contract talks, makes no mention of the district's performance-pay
plan. Enraged teachers have threatened to strike if the district
doesn't drop the idea, which would give teachers extra pay if their
school's test scores improve.
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi said that as a practical matter because of legal
barriers to public teachers' striking, a strike is not imminent,
but he predicted that strike sentiments will continue to grow among
the rank and file if the district dismisses their demands.
</P>
<P>
   Higuchi said the 21 percent raise would equate to about $400
million. He said the amount demanded by the union could change as
the amount of available money for salaries is revealed.
</P>
<P>
   He justified the raise demands, saying the district is
hemorrhaging good teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a certificated teacher and it (the raise) makes you
not leave, that's good for the institution,'' Higuchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Unified School District leaders called the union's
offer unrealistic. Desperately behind in its effort to build more
schools to handle swelling enrollment, the district has no room to
cap class sizes in every grade or end the sharing of classrooms,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Ramon Cortines said he agrees that smaller class
sizes are a worthy goal but wouldn't comment about the salary
increase demand until he sees the UTLA proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one pot of money,'' he said. ``You can have it in
salaries, in incentives, or for class size.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines also said that the district has not spent the tens of
millions of dollars it has available for textbooks, making the
teachers' demands regarding them unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The union proposal aims to improve both the pay and working
conditions of the district's 43,000 teachers by taking steps the
plan's executive summary calls ``extensive and drastic.'' The union
wants:
</P>
<P>
   _ A 6 percent raise retroactive to July 1 and a 15 percent raise
for the 2000-2001 school year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clean, safe schools with adequate supplies of textbooks and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   _ A program through which teachers review the performance of
their peers and help those struggling in the job.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal leaves the union and the district far apart as they
head into contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   District officials have proposed a 6 percent raise, 1.8 percent
of which would go to health and benefits and 2 percent of which
would make permanent a one-time increase granted last year. In
addition, teachers at low-performing schools that steadily improve
their test scores could earn up to $5,000 extra.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to tie pay to student achievement has angered many
teachers, who feel they may be penalized for factors such as
poverty that affect students' grades but are outside teachers'
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't use that as an excuse for our children not
learning,'' said board member Caprice Young. ``I'd love to be able
to have higher pay raises. It's a matter of finding the money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
