<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5235 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EMOVIES-PIRATED-SFCHR     04-03 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMOVIES-PIRATED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM INDUSTRY ALARMED BY NET PROGRAMS THAT COPY MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The   San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even if record companies manage to unplug the
popular and controversial online music search program Napster,
Derek-PLA won't care.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania high school student and countless other
programmers around the world have already come up with alternatives
to Napster that not only find free top music hits on the Net, but
also free full-length feature movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they can do about it,'' said the
16-year-old, known online as Derek-PLA, who wrote and posted a
program called VBGNUtella.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd have to shut down the whole Internet if they wanted to
stop someone from downloading illegal songs,'' he said. ``Nobody
wants to pay for music when they can get it for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Internet denizens aren't waiting for lawyers from
Napster Inc. of San Mateo and the Recording Industry Association of
America to define copyright infringement laws in court.
</P>
<P>
   In just three weeks, dozens of programs like VBGNUtella have
appeared on the Internet, permutations of a file-swapping program
called Gnutella that was released as a demo by the Nullsoft
division of America Online for just one day in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   They have joined other Napsterlike programs and services like
Wrapster, iMesh and Spinfrenzy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is a new, rising threat to the film and DVD
industry _ DivX, a program that can be used to copy and compress a
full-length feature film on a DVD into a file that can fit onto one
standard 650 MB CD-ROM. Some observers believe DivX may eventually
do to movies what the MP3 format has done to the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment establishment may be headed for a free-for-all
on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Napster goes away, what Napster has created doesn't go
away,'' said Malcolm Maclachlan, an analyst with International Data
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Napster founder Shawn Fanning invented more than just a computer
program that allows easy sharing of best-selling hit songs without
having to buy a CD. Napster has introduced an idea that will be
hard to stifle: the idea of using a decentralized network of
individual computers on the Internet to share and swap files.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of creative programmers out there on the Net
who can constantly develop and refine new Napster-type programs.
And they can easily remain ahead of the law and the entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   With such a distributed network of people creating and using
those programs, trying to haul each one into court would be like
trying to capture the ocean with a bucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is always going to be five or 10 steps behind where
the technology is,'' said Neil Rosini, a copyright law attorney
with Franklin, Weinrib, Rudell &AMP; Vassallo of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the Napster case, the Recording Industry Association of
America, which represents major record labels, filed a copyright
infringement suit against Napster in December, about four months
after the first demo version became available on the Napster Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the earliest the RIAA can obtain a court order halting
Napster will be June.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Napster has become a popular tool among college
students with high-speed Internet access who fill up their hard
drives with free music. Napster users make their personal library
of MP3 files on their computer's hard drive available for download
by other Napster members.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to capitalize on Napster's notoriety, San Francisco's
WiredPlanet, an online music site, last week launched a service
called MyStation, which in the company's words combines
``Napsterlike music-locating features with legal, streaming MP3
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the similar file-swapping Gnutella is also gaining
steam. Gnutella was developed by Nullsoft, the same company that
produced WinAmp, the most popular software program for playing MP3
files on a personal computer. Gnutella looks for swapable MP3
files, but also finds swapable movies.
</P>
<P>
   Programmers at Nullsoft, now owned by AOL, released a Gnutella
beta on March 15 for people to try, but suddenly yanked the program
off the Web and shut down the project.
</P>
<P>
   Programmers were still able to reverse-engineer what they had
already seen of Gnutella and come up with their own versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cat is more of less out of the bag,'' Maclachlan said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Napster, there is no company behind Gnutella, and there
are no centralized servers or Internet service providers that the
record industry could go after.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these distributed operations, who do you sue over
Gnutella?'' Maclachlan said.
</P>
<P>
   But information about Gnutella is abundant, with sites like
www.cdfreaks.com and gnutella.nerdherd.net providing instructions
and links.
</P>
<P>
   Derek-PLA wrote his version in the Visual Basic programming
language. He said he regularly chats and collaborates online with
other Gnutella programmers to help create better versions.
</P>
<P>
   Gnutella's popularity is rising, although it's hard to quantify
because there isn't a single source of information.
</P>
<P>
   Derek-PLA said a week after Nullsoft shut down the official
Gnutella project, he found about 300 computers online using a
Gnutella clone. One day last week, he went online and found more
than 1,600 computers logged in offering about one terabyte worth of
songs.
</P>
<P>
   And he also was able to find two downloadable, pirated copies of
the movie ``Mission to Mars,'' which is still playing in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   While movie files still take several hours to download, DivX
surfaced on the Internet in March with the ability to copy and
shrink DVD files down to a size that is easier to transmit and
store on a computer hard drive or writable CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   DivX, which has no connection to the defunct Divx DVD format
promoted by the Circuit City, Calif., retail chain, is the work of
authors who go by the names ``MaxMorice'' and ``Gej.'' The program
is posted at http://divx.ctw.cc.
</P>
<P>
   According to the information file on the program, the authors
``hacked'' Microsoft MPEG4 video technology, and used the MP3
format to reduce a film's audio soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The process of copying, or ``ripping,'' a movie from a DVD is
still complicated and highly technical, and there is so far no
consumer-friendly program like a WinAmp for DivX.
</P>
<P>
   But Maclachlan noted that playing MP3 files was just as
complicated in 1997, until easy-to-use players and copiers like
WinAmp started to appear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For people who are technically inclined, Web sites like
Global-DivX, at &UR;  &LR; http://divx.vcdguide.com, have sprung up to
provide step-by-step instructions along with other news and
information.
</P>
<P>
   The site lists movies such as ``The Nutty Professor,'' ``Last of
the Mohicans'' and ``Universal Soldier: The Return'' as the latest
releases available in DivX form.
</P>
<P>
   ``DivX won't do for DVD quite what MP3 did for music, but I
think it will leave a mark,'' said Global-DivX Webmaster Michael
Saunders of Australia in an e-mail. ``It has potential, if pushed
in the right directions.''
</P>
<P>
   One DivX fan named RogueOne wrote in an Internet post that he
has shown friends his illegal copy of the movie ``American Pie,''
but doesn't believe the format will ignite rampant movie piracy
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, RogueOne wrote, ``It's the digital age, boys and girls.
Anything that can be protected can be cracked. Stop whining and
figure out some other way to feel good about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Litvack, vice president of legal affairs for the Motion
Picture Association of America, said his group is concerned about
DivX.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking into it and need to determine from our various
options what method of attack we will use,'' Litvack said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he still believes that most Americans are
law-abiding citizens and will not want to make illegal copies of
videos, he conceded that the motion picture industry is also going
to have to gear up its defenses for the new spate of technological
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's now clear to all of our members that they need to
be prepared to move at Internet speed, and I think you will see
they will,'' Litvack said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Hoffman, president of online music site EMusic.com Inc. of
Redwood City, Calif., believes the entertainment industry's best
chance of stopping piracy is to start selling downloadable video
and music, making it as easy and almost as cheap as getting illegal
copies.
</P>
<P>
   EMusic will announce today that it has sold 1 million legal MP3
songs since 1998, which Hoffman says shows there is a huge
potential market for legal downloadable entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to make gin in bathtubs during Prohibition,''
Hoffman said. ``Once they made it legal, nobody made bathtub gin.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
