<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Dressing Like the Fab Four
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dougie &LR;  and  &UR; Gordon Millings &LR; , British tailors to the Beatles,
have authorized an Italian company to create a new ready-to-wear
line of suits based on ones made for John, Paul, George and Ringo.
Gordon Millings told GQ that the time seemed right for the suits
``because at the moment the Beatles films are being rereleased and
there is a huge interest in everything to do with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Millingses' clothing for the Beatles ran from costumes
``from `A Hard Day's Night' and `Help!' to tour outfits, tuxedos
for royal command performances and getups for going to Buckingham
Palace to collect their MBEs in,'' he said. ``We were also doing
people like the Kinks, the Rolling Stones, the Who. Keith Moon died
in one of my suits. In fact, he hadn't paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Ken Maley &LR;  forwards a page from the Voyager's Collection
catalog featuring ``a Pewter Tribute to  &UR; Ringo Starr &LR; ,'' a $125,
9-inch-tall ``museum quality'' figurine of Ringo giving the
two-fingered peace sign. The catalog notes: ``In keeping with the
former Beatle's stance against handguns, each pewter figuring
contains metal from recycled firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. An essay written in 1967 by Stanford historian  &UR; Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Stansky &LR;  _ newly published in Stansky's ``From William Morris to
Sergeant Pepper'' (Sposs; $22.50) _ calls ``Sergeant Pepper's
Lonely Hearts Club Band'' a social document of England. The
Beatles, writes Stansky, in prose that seems wistful now, ``can
tell us about the great strengths of English character, the English
vitality and imaginativeness, their ability to lead better and
better lives over the course of this century, both in a material
way, but also in the ways of the imagination.'' Furthermore (listen
up, ye Beatles' haberdashers), they appear, on the album cover,
``dressed in a triumph of gear.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ At a fund-raising auction Saturday night for the Russian Arts
Foundation and the Headlands Foundation, a hat owned by  &UR; Marilyn &LR; 
 &UR; Monroe &LR;  fetched $11,500, and a dress worn by  &UR; Sophia Loren &LR;  fetched
$7,500. The event raised close to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ How can the census-takers announce that 42 percent of the
population has sent back census forms, asks  &UR; Gary Hanauer &LR; , when
they need the census to determine the overall size of the
population?
</P>
<P>
   - Novelists  &UR; Alice Walker &LR;  and  &UR; Amy Tan &LR; , restaurateur  &UR; Alice &LR; 
 &UR; Waters &LR;  and  &UR; Elizabeth Farnsworth &LR;  of ``NewsHour With  &UR; Jim &LR; 
 &UR; Lehrer &LR; '' are pitching in to support a $3.7 million restoration and
expansion campaign for the Central Library in downtown Berkeley.
The Berkeley library is No. 1 in California in circulation per
capita in cities of comparable size; the average circulation is 15
items per citizen a year.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Carolyn Kizer &LR;  forwards a clip from American Airlines' highly
literate in-flight magazine, which mentions that  &UR; Angela &LR; 
 &UR; Bassett &LR;  was on the New York stage in 1998 playing ``Lady Macbeth
in Shakespeare's `Hamlet.'''
</P>
<P>
   In further high-flying news,  &UR; Paul Spiegel &LR;  was pleased, when he
signed on to United Airlines' Web site, to have the menu option of
identifying himself as the standard Mr., Mrs. or Dr., or Baron,
Prince, Lt. Commander, Swami or President.
</P>
<P>
   - More on the 4CUE license plate sighting:  &UR; Bob Wieder &LR;  says the
Oakland Tribune includes an entertainment page identified as 4-CUE
every day.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Craig Harrison &LR;  and  &UR; Lisa Wills &LR; , both in their 30s, were
having lunch at the Bistro in Lafayette last week, among many
fellow diners who seemed to live at nearby Rossmoor, a community of
older people. When a cell phone rang, he reports, ``Suddenly, all
eyes were on US. You know the look: the sneers and disdain for ones
loathe enough to bring a cell phone to lunch.'' Harrison hereby
proclaims his innocence. The perps, he says, were ``the oldest
couple'' there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TO STREEP'S RESCUE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mary McFadden &LR;  told  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  at the premiere party for
``Me, Myself, I'' that she designed two different very elegant
dresses that  &UR; Meryl Streep &LR;  wore for both the Golden Globes and for
the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators who said Streep didn't care about clothes and
keeping in shape were wrong. ``Meryl Streep cared incredibly how
she looked at the awards,'' said her supportive designer. ``I told
her that I could disguise the mountains and valleys of her body.''
</P>
