<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; IMMIGRANTS:  &LR; San Jose attorney Bruce W. Burns used to have a small
practice helping immigrants get visas, green cards and other
documents from the Immigration and Naturalization Service. He
worked mostly with people already living in the Bay Area. Then he
put up a Web page,  &LR; www.burnslaw.com &LR; , a simple site that explains
the basic kinds of visas available and prominently displays his
e-mail address. In the five years since he brought his practice
online, his client base has tripled and diversified.
 &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EMOVIES:  &LR; Even if record companies manage to unplug the popular and
controversial online music search program Napster, Derek-PLA won't
care. The Pennsylvania high school student and countless other
programmers around the world have already come up with alternatives
to Napster that not only find free top music hits on the Net, but
also free full-length feature movies.  &UR; BY BENNY &LR; 
 &UR; EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN):  &LR; One of the scions of the Coca-Cola Co. fortune
has added his voice to the chorus of protesters who want U.S. firms
to quit using genetically engineered ingredients, or to at least
label their products if they do. William C. Wardlaw III, grandson
of one of the first investors in Coke stock, has co-sponsored a
shareholder resolution asking the company to stop using genetic
foods so long as questions remain about the environmental and
health effects of the new technology.  &UR; COLUMN BY &LR; 
 &UR; TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; INVESTING (COLUMN):  &LR; The accounting fiasco at MicroStrategy
underscores the importance of investment research. The software
company is in the red hot Internet business-to-business sector.
Unlike many Internet wonders, MicroStrategy has been in business
for some time and reported positive earnings during each of the
last three years. That was before the company said recently that it
is restating both sales and earnings for 1998 and 1999 to conform
to new regulatory guidelines.  &UR; COLUMN BY HARRY DOMASH &LR;
</P>
