r s BC-CAR-JEFF-BURTON-TEX     04-03 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JEFF-BURTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFF BURTON'S DAY A DUPLICATION OF HIS SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jeff Burton's systematic pursuit of NASCAR
Winston Cup points leader Bobby Labonte and victorious rookie Dale
Earnhardt Jr. emulated his own methodic ascent in the points
standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a nice and steady charge up to the front,'' Burton
said of his second-place finish in yesterday's DirecTV 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's improbable charge from 37th to second place cemented
his fourth top-five finish and fifth-top 10 finish in seven Winston
Cup races this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't worry too much about where we qualify,'' Burton said.
``We knew we had a decent car. Right off the bat we were good.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three races, Burton has climbed from 13th to sixth
in the point standings, and is second-leading money winner with
earnings of $2.7 million this season. Yesterday also marked his
third top-10 finish in four events at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   None of that comes as earth-shattering news to the No. 99 Exide
Ford team. Burton has been on the lip of Winston Cup greatness the
past three seasons, finishing fourth in the points standings in
1997 and fifth the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously an outstanding race-car driver and he continues
to show it on a weekly basis,'' Frank Stoddard, Burton's crew
chief, said. ``We got some points out of here, we gained on
everybody we needed to except for one \RLabonte\S. So based on that
we did what we needed to do for the points and that's what we're
here to do, to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's run to the front of the pack resulted from a steady
diet of conservative driving and a little luck. Stoddard said he
allowed Burton to become aggressive only when racing turned into a
single-file line where he could bob and weave his way through
traffic. His luck ran as strong as his car as he dodged much of the
trouble that drew a TMS record 12 yellow flags.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Burton to make his charge. By Lap 68, he
had jockeyed his way up 28 spots to ninth. By Lap 100, he was in
sixth and by Lap 200 he managed a brief lead.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed in the top five the rest of the way and was a
contender to win the race until Earnhardt Jr., made it clear no one
would catch him as he duplicated Burton's 1997 feat by making TMS
his first career trip to Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte battled long and hard to keep Burton in his rear-view
mirrow, but Burton took advantage when Labonte got pinched by a lap
car, enabling him to assume second place with 16 laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a chance to win, definitely, but I just
couldn't get by Bobby,'' Burton said. ```If I could have cleared
Bobby a little bit quicker then we could have given him \REarnhardt
Jr.\S a run for his money.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into next week's race at Martinsville, Va., Burton is 90
points behind his brother Ward, who sits in third. Jeff Burton
gained five points on Labonte to move within 180 points of the
points lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen overnight to contend for a
championship,'' Burton said. ``It' going to be a slow process.
Today was in the right direction.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
