<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-TIRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS SAY IMPROVED TIRES MAKE DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway has not been kind to
Goodyear tires.
</P>
<P>
   During both Indy Racing League races last year, Goodyear tires
had blistering problems. And in last year's Winston Cup race at the
1.5-mile quadoval, several top teams suffered blowouts resulting in
wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   But in Sunday's DirecTV 500 Cup race at TMS, there was nothing
but praise for Goodyear and the tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great ... awesome,'' said second-place finisher Jeff
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear brought two different tires for the tough TMS layout.
</P>
<P>
   The left-side tires on the Winston Cup cars were the same ones
used at Atlanta Motor Speedway. The right-side tires were specially
designed to withstand the speeds that TMS can produce and the
pressure the track exerts on the right-front tire, where there was
a big problem last year. Mike Skinner and Jeff Gordon both had
trouble with right fronts last year and ended up in the wall. Some
teams were running the tires under Goodyear's recommended tire
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   When drivers wrecked Sunday, it was not because of the tires.
The race concluded a weekend in which teams were not worrying about
tires or tire wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to salute Goodyear,'' said Larry McReynolds, Mike
Skinner's crew chief. ``We've got a tire. We had no problems, and
to my knowledge nobody had no problems and nobody had any problems
in the Busch race.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, teams had so much confidence in the tires, there were
several two-tire stops during the race.
</P>
<P>
   Winner Dale Earnhardt Jr. took on four tires at almost every pit
stop, but his teammate, Steve Park, had two two-tire stops. Park
said the car ran better on new right sides, instead of four new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept putting right sides on, and they just kept getting
better and better and better and it gave me track position,'' Rusty
Wallace said of the two-tire stops. ``We kept the right sides on
and led for a while, then started falling back. The left side tires
had about 80 laps on it, but she was still running good.''
</P>
<P>
   The new generation Goodyear Eagle, which was introduced at
Daytona, has been the subject of both praise and controversy this
season. Some people equate the boring races to the tires adhering
to the track better than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   TMS is one of those tracks where the asphalt is newer and still
has good grip, even though some consider it a one-groove track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to leave this tire alone,'' McReynolds said. ``I think
it's called averaging 180-something mph around a mile-and-a-half
racetrack. Dale Jr. ran some laps that would have qualified him
probably in the top 15 or so there the last part of the race.
That's awful fast, and that means your margin of error is small.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
