A5241 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-RODRIGUE     04-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-RODRIGUEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ NOW THE MAN IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He made his major league debut at Fenway Park July 8,
1994, as an 18-year-old. Right away, one could tell Alex Rodriguez
was something special. But now, away from the shadow of Ken Griffey
Jr., traded from the Seattle Mariners, that will really show.
</P>
<P>
   With Griffey traded to Cincinnati, a new leader must be found,
and the clear choice of Mariners fans is Rodriguez. The amazing
shortstop who is a three-time All-Star and has a .308 career
average, with power, can hang around for a decade or so, say the
fans, even if he becomes baseball's first $200 million player.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have had a contract offer on the table since last
November. Rodriguez has elected to wait until the end of the 2000
season, become a free agent, and see what's available on the open
market. It's possible he could write his own ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``What direction the Mariners are going in the next four to five
years is something I am trying to assess,'' said Rodriguez. ``So
often it's the player who is evaluated. Only once or twice in your
career do you get to evaluate the (teams). I need to feel we have
an opportunity to win, and enough players in the right positions to
make a run the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's my contract year or not, I'm going to try and
give it my very best. I think my performance over the years has
said that. There might be some obligations on my end. I welcome
them. I love baseball and I love to play and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's contract status has been a big story in recent
months. But with the Mariners set to start their first full year in
47,000-seat Safeco Field, what happens on the field becomes
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners host the Red Sox in their opener Tuesday night at
8.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will become his ball club now,'' said Mariners manager
Lou Piniella, who also has reached the final year of his contract.
``Alex has good leadership qualities. You know he will play hard
and he plays every day. You know he wants to win. But it's not
something we're going to force. We're going to let things take
their natural course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already know he can do everything as far as the skills are
concerned. There aren't too many players in baseball that have his
abilities. He's got power. He can hit for average. He can steal a
base and plays shortstop with good range, good hands, and an
excellent arm. There isn't much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``The Kid'' after his precocious debut in '94, he came
to the forefront two seasons later when he finished second in the
MVP race to Juan Gonzalez of Texas (a Seattle writer left him off
the ballot).
</P>
<P>
   He's batted .300 or better three times, including a league best
.358 in 1996. Twice he's hit 42 home runs, a record for AL
shortstops. Rodriguez might be the best of the outstanding current
shortstop class, which includes Nomar Garciaparra of Boston and
Derek Jeter of New York. Rodriguez's power is the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The exit of Griffey might not be the worst thing to happen to
the Mariners. Now that the team is out of the recently demolished
Kingdome, it can play a style more to Rodriguez's liking. Fans
might like that more than the nightly home run derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a better team,'' said Rodriguez. ``There is
more offense, more confidence, more security around here. We don't
just count on one or two people. The only pressure should be the
pressure to win. The fans deserve a winner. We want to give them
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be a more contact-oriented team. We'll hit-and-run.
We'll bunt a little more. We have to produce runs and not depend on
the long ball. To me, it was kind of a boring game just waiting for
the home run. We'll play more of a National League-style baseball
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez understands he isn't Superman, as Griffey often was
called, although sometimes it seems that way. Last year, he
suffered a torn meniscus in his left knee and underwent surgery and
was on the disabled list from April 7-May 13. But in his first
at-bat after his return, Rodriguez hit a home run. Without him,
Griffey might have struggled all year. But as the No. 2 hitter,
Rodriguez hit .295, and batting fourth he hit .282. He scored 110
runs and drove in 111. Despite missing 33 games, Rodriguez hit a
solid .285.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's definitely a great player,'' said John Olerud, a
free agent who played last year for the New York Mets. ``Alex has
put up great numbers every year. He's had consistency year in and
year out. I don't think he was overlooked just because Griffey was
here. I think everybody recognizes him as a great player. Maybe
he'll get more attention because Griffey is not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez says he's been around long enough to know not to pay
attention to predictions about his future, particularly when it
comes to a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, there will be another free agent out there,'' he
said. ``And he will be the most powerful or whatever. I can't worry
about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
