<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHUKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREGORY SHUKER, 67, DOCUMENTARY FILMMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., W.Va., Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregory B. Shuker, a documentary filmmaker and pioneer in the
techniques of cinema verite, died on Wednesday at Calvary Hospital
in New York. He was 67 and lived in Bronxville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said Nancy Shuker, his former wife.
</P>
<P>
   Shuker was among the first American filmmakers to use cinema
verite, a technique in which the camera discovers life without
predetermining it: Scripts are not used, subjects are not
rehearsed, and drama develops from daily experience.
</P>
<P>
   Shuker, who was born in Charleston, W.Va., began a career in
journalism at Northwestern University, where he worked on the daily
newspaper, becoming the editor in chief by the time he graduated in
1954.
</P>
<P>
   During college he went to the Soviet Union and provided
photographs and text to Life magazine. After serving in the Navy,
he began work in 1959 as a correspondent for Life, where he wrote
about Ernest Hemingway and bullfighting, the Project Mercury
program at NASA, and a presidential hopeful, Sen. John F. Kennedy
of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   While writing about the Indianapolis 500, he discovered the
magazine's experimental film unit and began making style-oriented
television programs. The unit, called Drew Associates, was founded
by the former Life photo editor Robert L. Drew. It was different
from other film crews because its members acted as their own
producers, sound recordists, film loaders and, later, editors.
</P>
<P>
   Shuker helped create some of the unit's most memorable films, in
particular ``The Chair,'' the tale of a condemned man, Paul Crump,
and the successful struggle of his novice lawyer to prevent his
execution. The work won the Grand Prix Award at the Cannes Film
Festival in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Crisis: Behind a Presidential Commitment'' cameras were
admitted to the offices of President Kennedy, Attorney General
Robert F. Kennedy and Gov. George Wallace of Alabama during the
confrontation over desegregation of the University of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   At President Kennedy's funeral Shuker, along with other
filmmakers from Drew Associates, turned their cameras not on the
funeral but on the mourners, creating the film ``Faces in
November,'' which won the Grand Prize at the Venice Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   He also produced ``Letters From Vietnam,'' a 1965 documentary
shot in combat and on board helicopters, and the ABC special
``Twiggy: Why?'' which theorized on the model's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Time-Life, Shuker worked at the Public Broadcast
Laboratory, the forerunner of PBS. There he produced ``Free at
Last,'' which chronicled the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s
organization of the 1968 march on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The project took on a new form when King was assassinated, and
the 90-minute film became a document of his last days. The film was
hastily edited and shown three days after King's death, with Shuker
writing and providing the narration. The production won an Emmy
award as well as first prize at the Venice Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972 Shuker helped found Playback Associates, which produced
industrial training videos and instructional tapes.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a son, John, of Peekskill, N.Y.; two
daughters, Allison Devlin of Bronxville and Frances Shuker-Haines
of Williamstown, Mass.; and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5245 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVESTING-MICROSTRATE     04-03 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-MICROSTRATEGY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING: DIG DEEPER FOR MORE MEANINGFUL NUMBERS  &HT;     BY HARRY DOMASH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The accounting fiasco at MicroStrategy underscores the
importance of investment research.
</P>
<P>
   The software company is in the red hot Internet
business-to-business sector. Unlike many Internet wonders,
MicroStrategy has been in business for some time and reported
positive earnings during each of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the company said recently that it is restating
both sales and earnings for 1998 and 1999 to conform to new
regulatory guidelines. As a result, its reported sales for 1999
will be cut by 25 percent, and the reported earnings may turn into
a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The bombshell sent MicroStrategy shares plunging to $72.31 on
March 21, down about 77 percent from its high of $313 less than two
weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   How could investors have seen this coming? Not by looking at
analysts' recommendations. According to information compiled by
Zacks Research, 9 of 10 analysts covering MicroStrategy had ``buy''
or ``strong buy'' recommendations on the stock when the bad news
broke.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK AT THE CASH: A good way to gain insight into a company's
health is by looking beyond reported earnings to cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   A company's reported earnings is subject to a myriad of
regulations and arbitrary accounting decisions that have a major
bearing on how it recognizes revenues, how fast it can depreciate
an asset, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Cash flow measures real money flowing into, or out of, a
company's bank account. Unlike reported earnings, there is little a
company can do to overstate its bank balance. Every company filing
reports with the Securities and Exchange Commission is required to
include a cash-flow statement within their quarterly and annual
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC files the reports on its Edgar database as soon as they
are received. You can access them there (www.sec.gov) or on a
variety of other sites. My favorite place to view SEC reports is
Free Edgar (www.freeedgar.com).
</P>
<P>
   I like Free Edgar for two reasons: 1. access is free, and 2. it
provides a table of contents for each report. The company reports,
which can be lengthy, have a table of contents that is handy for
locating and printing sections of interest, such as the cash flow
statement. Companies file quarterly (10Q) and annual (10K) reports.
Always look for the most recent report filed.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET GUIDE: While the reports filed with the SEC include more
detail, Market Guide (www.marketguide.com) compiles the financial
information into a format that is easier to access and easier to
read.
</P>
<P>
   I will show you how to find cash flow information on Market
Guide using MicroStrategy as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Enter MicroStrategy's ticker symbol (MSTR) into the box labeled
``search for'' near the top-left of Market Guide's home page to
display the Snapshot page for MicroStrategy.
</P>
<P>
   Market Guide's Snapshot shows you useful information to help
evaluate a company, but we will save that for another column. Click
on Financials on the menu on the left to display Market Guide's
financial statement summaries for MicroStrategy.
</P>
<P>
   Scroll down past the Income Statement and the Balance Sheet to
the Statement of Cash Flows. When I looked last week, Market Guide
displayed columns for the fiscal years ending December 31 of 1996,
1997 and 1998, and for the 9-month periods ending September 30 of
1998 and 1999. The latest information is the most valuable, so the
9-month figures commanded the most interest.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the September 30, 1999, column. The top line is the
reported income, which shows in this case $8.864 million (the
figures are shown in thousands). That's the net income
MicroStrategy reported for the 9-month period.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DOMASH03 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Look down four lines to ``Total Operating CF.'' That is the
amount of actual cash that flowed into, or out of, MicroStrategy's
bank account from operations during the period. In this case,
$2.459 million went out.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reporting a profit, MicroStrategy's basic business,
selling software and services, used about $2.5 million more in cash
than it took in during the period.
</P>
<P>
   Now look down one line to Capital Expenditures, the cash used to
buy new plants and equipment. Some analysts say these outlays must
be taken into account, especially for technology companies, since
they must be continuously investing in new plants and equipment to
stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   These analysts subtract the capital expenditures from the
operating cash flow, to get ``free cash flow,'' the amount of
spendable excess cash generated by the company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   MicroStrategy's free cash flow for the 9 months ending September
'99 is a minus $28 million, meaning the company spent $28 million
more than it took in.
</P>
<P>
   MicroStrategy's recent problems are reportedly due to recording
sales prematurely, and that may account for the contrast between
reported earnings and actual cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, while still on the Financials page, enter Cisco
Systems' ticker symbol (CSCO) into the ``Search For'' box at the
top-left and then scroll down to Cisco's cash flow statements. You
will see that Cisco had a positive operating cash flow of $2.715
billion and free cash flow of $2.3 billion for the 6-month period
ending January 29.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-growing companies may burn cash for justifiable reasons.
The SEC reports' management discussions often contain additional
information helpful in understanding why the cash is flowing out
instead of in.
</P>
<P>
   You can see that Cisco Systems is generating billions in excess
cash that can be used to develop new products, acquire
complementary companies, buy back stock, etc.
</P>
<P>
   MicroStrategy, on the other hand, is burning cash, and
eventually will have to get a refill, either by borrowing, or by
selling more stock. Neither option is good for stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe a stock price-to-cash flow ratio (stock
price/cash flow per share) is a better measure of value than the
traditional price/earnings ratio. I will show you how to search for
stocks based on price/cash flow in a future column.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Domash lives in Aptos, Calif., and publishes the Winning
Investing newsletter. You can read his columns at
www.winninginvesting.com or contact him at
hdomash(AT)winninginvesting.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
