<HEADER>
A5262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-UCONN-TENNESSEE-H     04-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-TENNESSEE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PHILADELPHIA _ Top-ranked Connecticut has a way of making a
mediocre opponent look even worse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday night, UConn made six-time NCAA champion Tennessee look
like an also-ran.
</P>
<P>
   Using a pressure-packed defense to disrupt the Lady Vols, the
Huskies breezed to a 71-52 victory before a sellout crowd of 20,060
at First Union Center to capture their second national championship
in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Geno Auriemma made all the right moves to cap a season in
which the Huskies were ranked No. 1 at the beginning and still
standing head and shoulders above everyone else at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is an indescribable feeling when you win something
like this,'' Auriemma said. ``Tonight when they had to do what
we've practiced all year long, they did it better than at any time
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we did it against a team that's as good and has as
much tradition as Tennessee makes it even better. This team was
intent on proving tonight they were the best in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn finishes 36-1, with the lone loss a 72-71 defeat by
Tennessee at midseason. Then, the Lady Vols played sluggishly
through the first half, rallied in the second and won on a
last-second shot.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the Huskies, who set a school record for wins in a
season, rendered Player of the Year Tamika Catchings _ and the rest
of her teammates _ virtually powerless. The loss was the
second-worst in a championship game in the 19-year history of the
women's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols (33-4) were seeking their fourth NCAA title in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   What they got were shots smacked back in their faces on a
routine basis by Kelly Schumacher and shots that could not be
launched without obstruction. Schumacher set a championship record
with nine blocks as UConn finished with a team-record 11 blocks for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was fantastic,'' said Auriemma after the Huskies
limited the Lady Vols to 31-percent shooting and forced 26
turnovers that led to 30 UConn points.
</P>
<P>
   All-America guard Shea Ralph played with three fouls, all picked
up in the first half, and finished with a team-leading 15 points
and seven assists. All-American Svetlana Abrosimova scored 14
points, and reserve Asjha Jones had 12 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Catchings, after scoring only five points for Tennessee in the
first half, led all scorers with 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   The victory provided Auriemma with his second national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was very special to me,'' said Auriemma, who grew up
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee was forced to play without Kristen Clement, who
sprained an ankle during the morning practice, but coach Pat
Summitt said Clement's absence was not the reason the Lady Vols
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it have changed the outcome of this game? I can't say
that would happen,'' Summitt said. ``But she's a player who's
influenced the intensity and the attitude of our team. When we
started tonight, I thought it affected the way we handled the
press. When you look at it, we had 26 turnovers and most of them
came from our juniors and seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also didn't knock down shots. (The Huskies) were just too
deep tonight. They rotated a lot of bodies on Catchings and had a
lot of fouls to use up on her.''
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, Ralph gave Catchings fits. Catchings went
without scoring until she hit a layup and a 3-pointer on
back-to-back possessions as the Lady Vols went on a brief spurt and
trimmed a 25-10 deficit to 28-19.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph picked up her third personal with 1:33 left in the first
half, hacking Kyra Elzy as she rebounded a missed 3-point try by
Sue Bird, who started in place of Clement. Elzy's two free throws
got Tennessee to within nine. But that only served to jolt the
Huskies back awake. Two baskets in the closing 40 seconds yielded a
32-19 lead for UConn at the break.
</P>
<P>
   At least four Connecticut players spent time chasing Catchings.
With she and Semeka Randall feeling the effects of the Huskies'
smothering defense, Tennessee's already ragged play got even worse
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   After leading by 13 at halftime, the Huskies opened the second
half with an 8-0 run and increased their lead to 42-22 after four
minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first five minutes, we could sense they were getting
tired,'' Abrosimova said. ``And we just kept on pressuring them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Summitt: ``Our guards were not strong enough to handle the
pressure defense they applied. Offensively, they just schooled us _
even some of our veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, this was a very disappointing performance by our
basketball team and a painful loss. This team has been very
competitive all year. Tonight, we just got into a situation that no
one expected.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
