<HEADLINE>
CRASH COSTS NASCAR ROOKIE HIS CHANCE AT TOP 10 FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ All the ingredients appeared to be in place
for Scott Pruett's first top-10 finish in a NASCAR Winston Cup
Series event.
</P>
<P>
   Fast car? The No. 32 Tide Ford qualified third Friday for
Sunday's DirecTV 500.
</P>
<P>
   Suitable track? Texas Motor Speedway's 1.5-mile quadoval
appealed to the former CART veteran.
</P>
<P>
   No foolhardy charge by a driver in his rearview mirror? Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much, Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unfortunate set of circumstances where we just got
caught up with a guy not using his head,'' said Pruett, who led
laps 4-16 before being nudged from behind by Park's No. 1 Pennzoil
Chevrolet on Lap 18. Pruett's car spun and slammed into Turn 4,
which resulted in significant damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1 car took us out,'' Doug Richert, Pruett's crew chief,
said. ``The 1 car is underneath us, and it's way too early in the
race to be running us that hard. We're just up here. We're making
laps. We made the race. We just wanted to run good, and
unfortunately the guy was a little too impatient ``way'' too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett went to Park's hauler in search of an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was underneath Scott, and his spotter did not let him know I
was there,'' Park said. ``He looked like he was real loose and
trying to gather his car, and when he got loose, he came down and
got into me and I got into him. It was a racing deal. It was
unfortunate that it happened. We talked and straightened things out
so we can continue to race next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Pruett deemed the nudge unacceptable for that
stage of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five hundred miles is a long way,'' said Pruett, who finished
27th. ``In all the forms of racing I've been in, when you're four
to five laps into it, there's a lot of give and take. There are a
lot of miles left to go, and you just give each other a little
break. That didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett's crew salvaged 87 Winston Cup points with their efforts
during an estimated 15 pit stops throughout the afternoon,
including five during the five-lap caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``An unfortunate set of circumstances cost us a top-10 finish,
but the guys worked 110 percent all day long,'' said Pruett, a
NASCAR rookie whose career achievements include SCCA Trans AM, IMSA
GTO, IMSA GT Endurance and Professional Karting Association
championships. ``Even after it crashed, we were running fast. We
were running within two- or three-tenths (of a second) of the
leader with a crashed race car. We had a good car.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
