r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-KNICKS-LAD     04-03 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KNICKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT GETS IN FIGHT DURING LAKERS ROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The knockout punch was delivered long before the
fists started to fly Sunday, but a 30-second exhibition bout staged
in the middle of the Los Angeles Lakers' game against the New York
Knicks left the more lasting impression, and left both teams
bloodied.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won the game, a 106-82 rout, but lost their dazzling
21-year-old star when Kobe Bryant was ejected for a third-quarter
scuffle with Knicks guard Chris Childs. And with an NBA-imposed
suspension all but certain, the Lakers probably will lose Bryant
for at least one game, probably Tuesday at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided victory at Staples Center was no surprise. Seeing
the 21-year-old, ever-composed and good-natured Bryant come unglued
on the court qualified as the biggest shock of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But after Bryant absorbed a head-butt to the chin and two fists
to the face from Childs, no Laker blamed him for swinging back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows Kobe's a clean-cut kid,'' teammate Shaquille
O'Neal said. ``The guy hit him first and then you expect to let
somebody punch you in the face on national TV and expect him not to
do anything about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant did, or tried anyway. His return punch never connected,
and a scrum led by officials Ted Bernhardt and Ron Garretson
corralled the furious Bryant before he could get close to Childs
again. Lakers assistant coach Jim Cleamons stepped in as well, and
teammate Ron Harper tried cooling Bryant off as they headed back
toward the bench, but cameras showed Bryant still yelling and
pushing away O'Neal's bodyguard, Jerome Crawford, on the way to the
locker room afterward.
</P>
<P>
   It was an image of Bryant never seen to this point in his
four-year pro career, and his first ejection. Bryant didn't stick
around to explain his emotions to reporters afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's supposed to react,'' coach Phil Jackson said, ``Probably
not with a fist. You get into it, grab a guy, push him away,
whatever you want to do.... It's pretty much a natural reaction for
a player that takes a punch that doesn't see it coming, that he's
going to react to it. But it's probably human instinct for players
at least at this level to react aggressively to something like
that, so I'm not surprised that any player would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   All the mayhem diverted attention from the main event - the
Lakers thoroughly dominating the Knicks for a season sweep of their
potential sparring partner in the NBA Finals. In doing so, the
Lakers (62-12) got their ninth consecutive victory, 14th straight
at home, and reduced their magic number for clinching the league's
best record to two.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's 34 points and 12 rebounds led the thrashing, which saw
the Lakers up by 14 late in the third. They were up by 71-60, with
43.4 seconds to go in the quarter, when things got ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Lakers' Glen Rice and Harper had mixed it up with
the Knicks' Patrick Ewing in the first quarter, resulting in
technical fouls for Ewing and Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the Knicks play, they always play that way,''
Harper said. ``Hard-nosed basketball. I'm not mad at them, that's
just how they play.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rice: ``Teams are going to do whatever they can to try to
provoke us and try to get us off-balance in some kind of way. It
just didn't work today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were working on offense when Childs and Bryant
exchanged shoves near the baseline in the vicinity of the Knicks'
bench. As they went chest-to-chest, Childs threw the head-butt to
Bryant's chin, Bryant responded with a left elbow to Childs' mouth,
and Childs threw a right-left combo, landing at least the first
one. Childs ducked Bryant's return swing, and the fight was broken
up from there, while O'Neal gave a hard shove to Ewing on the
outskirts of the melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me with an elbow in the mouth, and I just reacted,''
Childs said. ``He does it a lot and never gets called for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said officials were partly responsible for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the referees didn't do the kind of job they should
do in the third quarter, for whatever reason, and it got out of
hand,'' he said. ``There were some fouls that probably should have
been called but were ignored, and I don't know if they were trying
to make the (game end in time for the) 6 o'clock news time or what,
but those are the things that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's response left an impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood up for himself,'' teammate Rick Fox said. ``He was a
little frustrated there that he couldn't get a piece of Chris
Childs. Kobe being such a nice guy, a nice kid, I suspect it had to
be something pretty serious that happened for him to respond that
way.... I've seen Kobe upset, at refs, in the competitive heat of
the battle. But he's always had a composed way about him in a game
situation.... That's not his caliber of response.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
