<SLUG> BC-CAR-LABONTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WIN, BUT LABONTES LEAVE TMS WITH PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Terry and Bobby Labonte had hoped to make a
statement. But while neither driver won the DirecTV 500, they also
didn't leave Texas Motor Speedway empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby, who finished third, left retaining his points lead.
Terry, who was eighth, left with his first pole in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was definitely an important race for us,'' Bobby said.
``... But I can't really complain about it. It was a good day _ a
really good day. We just want to do like everybody else and win
here or win there and win everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad day but a good weekend for the Labontes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was father-son day at the racetrack. Dale Earnhardt Jr.,
driving for his father, won the DirecTV 500.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Labonte had nothing for Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Terry didn't have the engine. Bobby didn't have the
aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were off,'' said Terry, whose last victory came here last
year. ``Our car was just not fast. ... Earlier in the race I ran
some with Dale Jr., but I couldn't ever get close enough to him at
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry did have his No. 5 Kellogg's Chevrolet up front for the
start.
</P>
<P>
   He set a Cup qualifying record at TMS, with a 192.137 mph lap
Friday. It was his first pole since 1996, when he was the fastest
qualifier at Sonoma, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   He had lobbied for the engine the team used in the race, but it
developed a problem during the DirecTV 500. He would have figured
that out Saturday afternoon had Winston Cup's Happy Hour practice
not been canceled by rain. Instead, the No. 5 team realized they
were horsepower-out-of-luck early during Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew right off that we were in a little bit of trouble,''
crew chief Gary DeHart said. ``We just weren't as good as we
thought we were going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the eighth-place finish was his worst in four starts at
TMS, Terry wasn't looking his gift horsepower in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're going to run for the points, on a bad day, if you
can get a top 10, that's good,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby's No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac was as good as he
expected. It just wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came time to go, no, we didn't have anything,'' crew
chief Jimmy Makar said. ``It was pretty obvious there at the end
that he (Earnhardt Jr.) had a lot left and a lot more than what we
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our car wasn't perfect at the end. We were a little too tight.
But I think even with our car perfect, we probably would have
finished second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Joe Gibbs Racing team argues that the Pontiacs are
handcuffed by an aerodynamic disadvantage, and they are campaigning
for some concessions from NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran decent but just not quite fast enough,'' Bobby said.
``We just kind of didn't have it all there (Sunday). We had about
50 cards out of a 52-card deck, and I think NASCAR is holding the
other two cards from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to play with what we've got. We had the best
car in class. I just wish we had a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   He had enough to hold onto the points lead. Bobby's third-place
finish was his sixth top-10 finish in seven races, and gave him an
84-point advantage over Mark Martin in the season standings.
</P>
<P>
   And next weekend at Martinsville, Va., everyone will be trying
to catch him. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
