<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT MIGHT KEEP JACKSON'S PLAN OUT OF ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Coach Phil Jackson proclaimed his team
playoff-ready. Their ability to survive Kobe Bryant's third-quarter
ejection solidified that assertion, but Bryant's punishment
probably will throw a crimp in the Los Angeles Lakers' postseason
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been looking for the right time to rest veteran
guard Ron Harper before the playoffs, and he had resolved to place
him on the injured list before Tuesday's game at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant's fight with the Knicks' Chris Childs will probably
net at least a one-game suspension, and without Harper, the Lakers
would be down to Derek Fisher, Brian Shaw and rookies John
Celestand and Devean George.
</P>
<P>
   ``(We) probably won't be able to put Harper on the IR like we
planned to, or at least scoped it out to be, because Kobe probably
will be suspended a game,'' Jackson conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Said Harper, ``I guess I ain't getting any time off, huh?... I'm
fine. I'm fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant left without speaking to reporters, but asked how Bryant
felt, Jackson said, ``He's feeling like he's probably going to miss
out on a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The positive side for the Lakers was they survived without
Bryant, who had 17 points, eight assists and six rebounds. The
Lakers had an 11-point lead when he was ejected - two Glen Rice
jumpers extended the lead to 75-60 heading into the fourth, and
they finished strong, with an eight-point quarter from Harper and
seven points from Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We responded very well at the end of the third quarter. Glen
got on a roll and Harper did a great job,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   East is least: Sunday's game was the Lakers' last against an
Eastern Conference opponent, and they finished with a 27-3 record
and a .900 winning percentage that stands as the best in NBA
history for a West team against the East.
</P>
<P>
   They also went 5-1 against the East's three top teams
</P>
<P>
   the Knicks, Miami Heat and Indiana Pacers, the latter dealing
the only loss. What does that say about the Lakers, who could face
one of the above in the Finals?
</P>
<P>
   ``That at whatever point we played them during the course of the
season, we were a better ballclub than they were,'' Jackson said
wryly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
