<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION WILL LACK FOOT SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Revolution are acting less and less like one of
Major League Soccer's worst teams. They not only held the Los
Angeles Galaxy to a 2-2 tie after threatening to turn the match
into a rout Saturday night in Pasadena, Calif., they returned to
Boston feeling like underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is disappointed,'' coach Fernando Clavijo said
Sunday. ``Before the game, if you said we would get out of there
with a tie I would have said, `Great.' But we played well enough to
really put them away and I look at it like we lost 2 points.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a major change in attitude for a team that had not
defeated Los Angeles since July 4, 1996. Since then, the Revolution
have been outscored, 22-7, and have earned only 2 of a possible 27
points against the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution's confidence will be tested when they visit
Dallas Saturday without defender Ivan McKinley and midfielder
Mauricio Ramos (both suspended), and striker Fabio Zuniga (sprained
right knee).
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution imposed their game on the Galaxy, and Leonel
Alvarez stifled Salvadoran midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos for much
of the first half. Alvarez scored his first MLS goal since 1996,
volleying in a rebound of a Ramos free kick. And Wolde Harris
finished a Ramos through ball for a 2-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The goals were the result of a cohesive Revolution attack. And
their advantage could have been greater _ Imad Baba hit the post
off a corner kick in the first half, and Ted Chronopoulos beat
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman with a looping shot off the crossbar early
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chronopoulos's shot could have put the game away at 3-0, but
it didn't happen,'' Clavijo said. ``Then, we lost our composure and
didn't play as well in the second half as we did in the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Zuniga departed in the 33d minute, but substitute Johnny Torres
sparked the team by drawing a free kick four minutes later that
resulted in the first goal. But Clavijo had few options, especially
after McKinley was ejected by referee Brian Hall after a clash with
Costa Rican midfielder Roy Myers in the 78th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Eduardo Hurtado missed the game because his family was
experiencing visa problems in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was luck or experience, but I made sure we
traveled with enough players, because I thought something might
happen,'' said Clavijo, who brought 16 players on the trip as a
precaution against the availability of Hurtado and William Sunsing.
``We played good soccer in these last two games and we didn't go to
Tampa or Los Angeles hanging back and playing defense. This team
has character and we have some fighters. This was only our third
game together for 90-plus minutes and I'm pleased. When you go on
the road for four games and you have a chance to win one, lose one,
and tie two, that's pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaker Asad likely will audition for Ramos's playmaking role
when the Revolution play a scrimmage against the Connecticut Wolves
Tuesday. The Revolution are 0-1-2, third in the Eastern Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to look for excuses,'' Clavijo said. ``We have 23
players on the roster who can contribute at any given time. I have
no problem with McKinley and Ramos because of the situation they
were in _ you look at what LA did and they get away with murder,
and we touch somebody and get a red card. Somebody (Hall) in the
middle of the field is making those decisions, and sometimes we are
going to get the call our way and sometimes we are not. But we lost
our composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKinley should have kept away from a confrontation because he
already had a yellow card, and Ramos knew he could not get another
yellow. They are mature guys and should know better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado, who was with Ecuador's national team Wednesday,
returned to New York Sunday &UR;  &LR; night and is expected to move into a
Boston-area apartment Monday, his agent, Eric Manasse said. ``They
would not let his family get on the plane in Ecuador,'' Manasse
said. ``His wife had to go to the American Embassy and, since she
does not speak English well, she called Eduardo to go with her. The
problem was that the (MLS) office screwed up on the visas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado informed Revolution public relations director Jurgen
Mainka of his family's visa problems Friday. But Clavijo had not
heard from Hurtado since then. ``I want to get all sides of the
story before making a decision,'' Clavijo said. ``I need to get all
the facts from the league, about who is responsible for the
paperwork for his family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
