<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAFINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-FOR-ONE SPECIAL IN FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ One game. Two styles. Endless possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Monday night's final game of the college basketball
season, starring a Michigan State team in the role of favorite
simply because none of the other high seeds in the NCAA tournament
survived, most of them not even reaching the regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Co-starring is a University of Florida team that has shined even
as its school still carries more of a football heritage.
</P>
<P>
   There's more, of course, to come from the festivities in the RCA
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Florida. Surely you know most of the story of
Billy and his Kids, 10 of them freshmen or sophomores who have been
so precocious in five tournament victories, including a systematic
demolition of Duke and North Carolina, two of the more storied
programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The misconception is that Florida's recent success under
34-year-old coach Billy Donovan makes the Gators a rising
basketball power.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. Look at how the Gators have reached the first national
championship game in school history _ using a 10-player rotation,
platoon basketball, even alternating point guards the way Gators
football coach and Florida basketball fan Steve Spurrier alternates
his quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Duke learned that a week ago when the Gators' Run 'N Fun offense
overwhelmed it in the final minutes. North Carolina learned it
Saturday night when the Tar Heels, who use a six-player rotation,
didn't have enough bodies or stamina to avoid becoming the latest
Gator bait.
</P>
<P>
   Now Florida (29-7) is 40 minutes from adding another national
championship trophy to the display case back in Gainesville.
Donovan says he doesn't want to talk about how much fun the ride
has been. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I don't want to enjoy it,'' said Donovan, who 13
years ago was a player on a Providence team that also was chasing a
championship dream. ``I want to exhaust every possible avenue I
have as a coach to try and put these guys in the best possible
position to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't focused on the fact that we're 40 minutes away from
a national championship. It's probably more we're playing Michigan
State and what we have to do to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take a lot. Michigan State (31-7) has won 10 straight
games, the last six by double-digits, including Saturday night's
53-41 grinder over Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans come after you early. And while they are more
plodding than the Gators and certainly don't go 10 deep in their
rotation, they have shown a tendency to put teams away with a late
rush that overwhelms them the way the Gators have the past few
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin game, perhaps because it was the fourth meeting of
the teams, perhaps because the defensive style of the Badgers was
conducive to hand-to-hand combat, was more a game of attrition than
one of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Even Michigan State coach Tom Izzo knew the victory over the
Badgers would not win many style points.
</P>
<P>
   When he came out of the locker room at halftime of a game in
which Michigan State held a 19-17 lead, Izzo spotted Northwestern
coach Kevin O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you like the Rose Bowl?'' joked Izzo.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's game might be like the Citrus Bowl, in which
Michigan State won a wild and often contentious 37-34 victory over
the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Expect more of the same with the basketball teams. Michigan
State, dominated by senior point guard Mateen Cleaves and forwards
Morris Peterson and A.J. Granger, realizes this is the last hurrah
for a group that has won 103 games in college.
</P>
<P>
   Not getting win No. 104 is not an option. ``We were disappointed
with the loss to Duke last year (in the Final Four semifinals),''
said Granger, ``and we used it as a motivation in preseason. It
finally hit just how long we had left when we played our last home
game against Michigan. Hopefully we can dull the pain of leaving by
trying to go out on a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be remembered as champions. No one remembers who
came in second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators also want a championship. They reached the regional
semifinals a year ago, which gave them a taste of what they might
win Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, a master motivator, has used all sorts of tools to
prepare his team. A week ago, he showed the Gators a film of the
Ali-Foreman fight. On Friday, he got into the football mode and
showed them ``Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Teddy Dupay offered a suggestion for a pregame movie
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll see `Home Alone,' '' he said. ``Some young kid
defending his house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
