<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAATOURNAMENT-WALSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALSH HAS TITLE IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   University of Maine cocaptain and forward Brendan Walsh of
Dorchester has a lot on his mind while awaiting the Black Bears'
NCAA Frozen Four semifinal-round game against North Dakota
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about cocaptain Corey Larose, who has to sit out
because of a butt-ending penalty he took March 26 during a 5-2 win
over Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about last year's semifinals against Boston College in
Anaheim, Calif., when his Eagles friend Andy Powers put him out of
the finals with a check that buckled his patched-up knee. Maine
went on to defeat New Hampshire, 3-2, in overtime, to win the
title.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks back to his days playing for Catholic Memorial, his 1
1/2 years at Boston University, his sitting out a year after
transferring to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about his grandfather, Joe Walsh of 6th Street in
South Boston, who ``gave me the urge to be competitive,'' Walsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll miss Corey big time,'' Walsh added. ``It's frustrating.
He's a catalyst for us. He's been there and he's a silent
motivator. We'll miss him and his locker room presence. Corey is
special. He's always been a spark, and he does everything well _
passing, shooting, checking. He's a great leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what Coach (Shawn) Walsh does is he carries a larger team
traditionally. We've been working with different guys lately, and
hopefully everything will fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a well-coached team, and we can adapt to adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened last year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke my kneecap in November of 1998 against New Hampshire
in the Governor's Cup,'' said Walsh, ``and I took four weeks off
and had a screw put in. And I was playing with it broken the rest
of the year, and the screw was holding the bone together. In that
semifinal game, I cut across the blue line, and Andy got the better
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was at the final but was in the stands. He wanted to be on
the bench with his teammates, but he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult,'' he said. ``It was one of those bittersweet
deals. It was tough, but the way we play and the system we have,
it's not so much what you have on the back of your jersey, (it's
what's on) the front of your jersey. It may sound corny these days,
but that's basically the system we play. We're a complete team, and
you never know who is going to make that big play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't place any individual stats on the walls in the
locker room. There's nothing there that points out any individual
categories. It's been like that since I've been at Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh butted heads with coach Jack Parker at BU over what the
player termed ``minor rules violations. It was basically
philosophical differences.''
</P>
<P>
   He's done well at Maine, and he is excited to be facing North
Dakota Thursday at the Providence Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the way the team is playing right now,'' he
said. ``Back in January we had that tough skid, and Coach Walsh
just told us we control our own destiny. We've done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back in that Hockey East tournament final and we're
scoring big goals. And we're getting scoring from different guys
every night.''
</P>
<P>
   When Maine ousted Michigan in the regionals, it had scorers on
every line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been a characteristic of our team,'' said Walsh.
``We're not relying on any given guy on any given night.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine trailed Michigan, 2-0, after two periods in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not all that worried, really,'' said Walsh. ``That was
the most comfortable I've ever been being down two goals going into
the third period. I'm not cocky, but we knew that conditioning
would come into play. Michigan played late the day before. We
outlasted them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Walsh has lots on his mind these days. It's the final
weekend of his collegiate hockey career. He'll miss not having
Larose on the ice Thursday. He hopes to play in a final for his
last hurrah. And he hopes his grandfather will see Maine win
another national title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
