<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS VARGAS EXPERIENCED ENOUGH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One question arising from the rubble of Felix
Trinidad's demolition of David Reid is this: How much experience is
necessary to cope with boxing's elite champions?
</P>
<P>
   Reid had only 14 fights behind him when he stepped into the ring
last month and it showed. He was unable to cope with his powerful,
savvy opponent in the second half of the fight and lost decisively.
</P>
<P>
   Is Fernando Vargas of Oxnard, who faces Ike Quartey on April 15
in Las Vegas, in for a similar fate?
</P>
<P>
   Vargas has fought only 18 times (18-0, with 17 knockouts) over
three-plus years. Quartey, while no Trinidad in the eyes of most,
has fought 36 times (34-1-1, 29 KOs) over 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   And Vargas certainly hasn't faced the likes of Quartey. He's
beaten tough, but limited Yory Boy Campas and Raul Marquez and
narrowly outpointed wily Winky Wright in his last fight.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey has been in the ring with Oscar De La Hoya - a fight
some believe he won - and talented Jose Luis Lopez, with whom he
drew.
</P>
<P>
   These are facts to which Quartey couldn't resist pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who has he fought? He doesn't have the experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wright fight, in December, certainly raised eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas claims he was unable to focus because of family problems.
And, to be fair to Wright and Vargas, the left-hander is more
skilled and tougher than many imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some wonder whether the fact Vargas had to pull out the
fight in the final rounds against a relatively unknown challenger
is an indication he needs more work.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made (that fight) tougher than it had to be,'' he said. ``I
was mentally drained for that fight. I'm not taking anything away
from Wright. He's the slickest southpaw in the game with the
exception of Pernell Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't there that night. I was only 50 percent. And,
still, I showed that I'm a champion when the championship rounds
came.
</P>
<P>
   ``...I showed the world I can win even on a bad night.''
</P>
<P>
   That experience should help Vargas: He knows what it's like to
be in a tough fight and what it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
   And, in comparison to Reid, there are other reasons to believe
he won't fall apart as his 1996 Olympic teammate did against
Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas will have had four more fights going into his big moment.
It's not much but it is a full year of boxing at the championship
level, at which the top names fight about four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Campas, Marquez and Wright aren't frightful
opponents, they are collectively better than that which Reid had
seen. Reid's toughest opponent going into the Trinidad fight was a
fading Keith Mullings.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Ghanan is a fine all-around fighter. He has a
terrific jab, he can punch and he can box. If there was doubt, he
proved against De La Hoya that he could compete with anyone. His
performance was better than Trinidad's against De La Hoya, who
frustrated the Puerto Rican with his boxing skills until he gave
the fight away in the final rounds.
</P>
<P>
   However, he probably won't be Trinidad's equal when he steps
into the ring with Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad's inability to cope with a quick, exceptional boxer was
exposed by De La Hoya. Meanwhile, Quartey, who tends to fade late
in fights, was almost knocked out by De La Hoya in the 12th round
and had big problems against Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   If Lopez can get to Quartey, one must suspect Vargas could do
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Quartey has had another long layoff. He will not have
fought since the De La Hoya bout in February of last year - 14
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey and Vargas both said the layoff should be no factor.
After all, he did almost beat De La Hoya after another long layoff,
that one 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   However, logic says one fight in 2 years makes for a rusty
fighter. Quartey couldn't possibly be at his best on April 15,
which could leave a door open for Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit the nail on the head,'' said Vargas, when asked
whether he had anything to prove in this fight. ``Every time I
fight an experienced guy, people say I need more experience and
then I beat these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``By beating Ike Quartey, I will move up in the pound-for-pound
(best fighter) class, I'll show I don't need to have 20, 30, 40
fight to beat these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe then I'll get respect, maybe people will say I'm a good
fight, a great fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   More Vargas: Vargas and Co. don't want to look past Quartey,
which is typical.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they're already negotiating to fight Trinidad
if Vargas wins.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over Quartey would give Vargas' career a meaningful
boost. A victory over Trinidad would catapult him to the top of the
sport, at least close to the level De La Hoya and Roy Jones have
reached.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Vargas-Trinidad is as fascinating as any
possible matchup.
</P>
<P>
   One more Vargas: ``KO'' magazine asks four former or current
fighters to predict the winner of the Vargas-Quartey fight in its
May issue.
</P>
<P>
   Genaro Hernandez, Bernard Hopkins and James Page pick Vargas
while, interestingly, Wright picks Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   More Quartey: AthletesDirect is auctioning on eBay an
opportunity to be part of Quartey's entourage for the April 15
fight.
</P>
<P>
   The winner gets: air fare, hotel, tickets, clearance to hang out
with Quartey before and after the fight and more.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the bidding has surpassed $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what that figure would be if it were De La Hoya....
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Vitali Klitschko, the previously undefeated
heavyweight, quit against substitute Chris Byrd to lose his WBO
title Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   No great surprise there. How many top European heavyweights have
turned out to be more hype than substance?...
</P>
<P>
   Fabrice Tiozzo defends his WBA cruiserweight title against
Valery Vikhor on Saturday in Paris on Showtime....
</P>
<P>
   Jose Navarro of Los Angeles beat a familiar foe at the Americas'
Qualifying Tournament in Tampa to earn a berth in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   He outpointed reigning U.S. champ Roberto Benitez, who failed to
make the U.S. team in the trials and was subsequently invited to
box for the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez's parents are Dominican....
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight Andrew Golota is scheduled to face Marcus Rhode on
April 22 in Guangzhou, China.
</P>
<P>
   Iran Barkely and Montell Griffin are among others scheduled to
fight on the card....
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Richard Hall has little chance to beat light
heavyweight champ Roy Jones on May 13 in Indianapolis. Hall hasn't
fought since June of last year and has yet to beat a big-name
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has a nice record: 24-1, with 23 knockouts. At least
there's !ital!some!off! intrigue....
</P>
<P>
   Pat Coleman faces Pedro Ortega in a 10-round welterweight bout
on April 13 at the Pond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
