<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUN-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE SOFTBALL TEAM FINDS WINNING FORMULA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No worries.
</P>
<P>
   That was the mantra for Cal State Northridge softball players as
they went through a brutal February and March schedule. The
Matadors played nine teams in the USA Today/NFCA Coaches Top 25,
and were 3-11-1 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are one of the hottest teams on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN improved to 8-1 in the Big West Conference with a
three-game sweep of Sacramento State this weekend in Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played all those tough teams, and we worked through all
those growing pains,'' said CSUN coach Janet Sherman. ``It's just
taken time (for the team) to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge entered the Sac State series last in the Big West in
team batting average (.183) but it outscored the Hornets 23-4 over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors had 11 hits in Sunday's 9-0 win, which was stopped
after 4 innings because of the mercy rule. It's the first time CSUN
has won by a mercy rule this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem relaxed,we're having fun,'' said junior pitcher Sarah
Farnworth, who beat the Hornets twice this weekend, in addition to
having a save on Saturday. ``We had the talent, we just needed to
come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said she and assistants Barbara Jordan and Randy Roeder
worked on keeping the players from getting low after a a 2-6
stretch two weeks ago. Farnworth said there haven't been any
``clear-the-air'' players-only meetings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to make each other press,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has three nationally ranked teams left on the schedule: No.
2 Arizona, No. 17 Long Beach State and No. 12 Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors play host to Long Beach State (April 15-16) but
have to go to Fullerton the next weekend. LBSU and Fullerton are
both ahead of CSUN in the Big West standings.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman has taken the Matadors to the NCAA playoffs in each of
her first five seasons. CSUN was ranked 10th in the Pacific Region
in the latest regional rankings and it will move past No. 9 Sac
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every series is a big series for us right now,'' said Sherman,
who got her 200th coaching victory on March 18 against Fresno
State.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the faith: Even as CSUN's youthful baseball team
struggles - the Matadors dropped to 12-21 with two losses this
weekend at Oklahoma State - coach Mike Batesole said last week he
was encouraged by the team's good morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed,'' he said. ``Usually this is the time of the
season where fingers are being pointed and guys are going their
separate ways and forming groups. I'm not seeing any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge has only six homes games left, including UCLA on
April 15 and Cal State Fullerton in the finale on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Motley's marks: Triple-jumper Clinte Motley broke the broke the
school record Saturday in a nonconference quadrangular meet at
UCLA. Motley, a junior from Alta Loma High, went 52 feet, 7 inches,
breaking the mark of 52-6 set by John Haynes in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Motley, who set CSUN indoor records in February in the triple
jump (52-9) and high jump (7-3), also finished second Saturday in
the long jump with a mark of 22-9.
</P>
<P>
   Motley helped the men finish second to UCLA, 203-133, in
quadrangular scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN women, who also finished second to the host Bruins,
162-103, had four individual event winners: Annetta Wells in the
200 (24.11 seconds), Nancy James in the 800 (2:09.16), Nancy Dollar
in the 3,000 (9:55.9) and Dee Scott in the long jump (19-5).
</P>
<P>
   Foreign flavor: The Northridge women's tennis team has won 10 of
its last 13 matches, including an 8-1 win over Idaho State Saturday
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Northridge's eight women's tennis players are
international, including Isabella Peintner of Germany at No.1
singles and Tereza Simonyan of Armenia at No.2. Peintner is the
Matadors' only senior.
</P>
<P>
   Coming together: It's been 30 years since Northridge won the
first of the baseball program's two Division II national
championships, and players from the 1970 team are being honored
prior to the Matadors' home game against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for a pregame luncheon for the team are available for
$15. The price includes admission to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (818) 677-3215.
</P>
<P>
   Improved radio: Good news for Northridge football and basketball
fans who couldn't clearly receive campus-based KCSN's radio
broadcasts last season.
</P>
<P>
   KCSN (88.5) has a new 320-watt transmitter and should be heard
throughout the San Fernando and Santa Clarita valleys. The old
signal was powered by only 52 watts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
