<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, April 3.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-IMMIG (London) _ In the latest effort by a west European
government to stem the tide of immigrants flowing into the region,
many of them from impoverished, post-Communist eastern Europe, a
sweeping law takes effect in Britain on Monday that aims to make
the country less attractive to asylum seekers. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-GYPSIES (Rudnany, Slovakia) _ Worsening conditions for
the Roma, or Gypsies, throughout Eastern Europe have caused
thousands to try to emigrate, quickly wearing out any welcome from
Western Europe. In fact, their flight has created new pressure,
most recently in Britain, to tighten visa, immigration and asylum
rules to keep the Roma out. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ A military analysis of the fighting
that is still going on in southern Chechnya. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-SURVIVOR (Beirut, Lebanon) _ At the height of Lebanon's
civil war in the 1980s, when every other American working at the
American University of Beirut had been driven out of the country by
hostage-taking, assassinations and threats, a lone American woman
remained, earning a reputation among her colleagues at the
university's medical center, and among victims of the fighting, as
a ministering angel. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IDENTITY-THEFT (Undated) _ Law enforcement authorities are
becoming increasingly worried about a sudden, sharp rise in the
incidence of identity theft, the outright pilfering of people's
personal information for use in obtaining credit cards, loans and
other goods. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HABITAT (Los Alamos, Calif.) _ The U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service's decision to give the California tiger salamander an
emergency listing as an endangered species has thrown the whole
northern end of Santa Barbara County, a spectacular stretch of
valleys and oak-dotted ranches, into an uproar. For residents, the
emergency listing of the obscure salamander represents just the
latest pitched battle over development as this bucolic landscape
comes under pressure from creeping urbanization and changes in the
agricultural economy. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 7-9 and map are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WESLEYAN-ADMISSIONS-II (Middletown, Conn.) _ In the last round
of the admissions process at Wesleyan, the university's gatekeepers
convened to consider the 368 applications still unresolved for next
year's freshman class. Of all the applications submitted to
Wesleyan, these 368 were the hardest calls for reasons as varied as
a single failing grade, an extended absence, a borderline test
score, or a rating of ``arrogant'' from an alumnus interviewer.
Part 2 in an occasional series. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EX-CONVICTS-JOBS (Detroit) _ Most job applicants have
butterflies. People who have just finished serving time in prison
have more than usual. By Robyn Meredith.
