</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-STATES-U.S. (Washington) _ As the settlement talks
between Microsoft and the government foundered last weekend, so it
appeared did the relationship between the Department of Justice and
the 19 state attorneys general, who together filed antitrust suits
against the software giant almost two years ago. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   OPRAH-MAG-MEDIA (Undated) _ When Oprah Winfrey announced last
year that her company, Harpo Inc., and Hearst Magazines would start
a magazine using her name and image, it made sense. Winfrey gets a
new audience _ one that is both younger and more affluent than the
one that watches her talk show, said the magazine's publisher. And
Hearst gets to use the Oprah Winfrey brand to sell magazines. By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   COFFEY-CNN-MEDIA (New York) _ Four months after he took over as
president of CNNfn, C. Shelby Coffey III is in the early rounds of
a truly tough brawl, an attempt to reverse one of Ted Turner's rare
failures: a financial news network that is being pummeled by the
sassy, fast-moving CNBC, and that is so weak that many of its
corporate cousins, Time Warner's cable systems, refuse to carry it.
By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-BOOKS-MEDIA (Undated) _ In the weeks since Stephen
King's e-novella made its debut with the unexpected fury of Carrie
at the high school prom, traditional publishers are quickening
their entrance into the emerging market for digital books with a
mix of anxiety about security issues and optimism about nurturing
new forms of literature. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   SIRICA-ADLER-MEDIA (Undated) _ A writer attacking other writers
is not, strictly speaking, news. Still, the offhanded evisceration
