<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5292 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-TENNE     04-03 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-TENNESSEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES ONE-UP VOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Delirious. That's probably an understatement for
describing how the University of Connecticut women's basketball
team felt Sunday &UR;  &LR; night as it led the entire way in routing the
Tennessee Lady Vols, 71-52, to win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The players on the bench ran onto the court, assistant coaches
broke down in tears, and head coach Geno Auriemma hugged his kids
and mother as the 20,060 fans at the First Union Center roared.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second title for the Huskies (36-1) _ their first
since 1995 _ as they defended the No. 1 spot they've held all
season. And it was a defiant defense that led the way. The teams
had split two games during the season and were 5-5 all-time.
</P>
<P>
   But the rivalry that had been touted all week _ all year, really
_ never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we came out and played, I'm not surprised,'' Auriemma
said. ``We wanted to prove that we're the best team in the country.
And when you do it against a team that's as good as and with as
much tradition as Tennessee, that makes it even more worthwhile.'
</P>
<P>
   With three minutes to go, Auriemma put in seniors Paige Sauer
and Stacy Hansmeyer, and then the rest of the reserves to finish
the job. The trophy was theirs.
</P>
<P>
   And even with his team ahead by 20 points, Auriemma didn't stop
yelling at his players or at the officials. This was, after all,
the final game of the season, so every possession mattered, every
foul counted, and every field goal made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   So what if guard Shea Ralph had three fouls before halftime? She
finished with a team-high 15 points, with six steals. Forward
Svetlana Abrosimova had 14 points, and Ashja Jones added 12. Center
Kelly Schumacher scored 6 points and had a career- and NCAA
tournament-high nine blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Pat Summitt was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an extremely disappointing game, and a very painful
loss, but in no way do I want this to take away from the way we
competed all year,'' she said. ``When you go up against a team as
aggressive and physical as Connecticut, you have to have great
guard play. But their defense, from beginning to end, pressured our
guards, and at times we played in a panic.'' The Lady Vols (33-4)
had 26 turnovers and made just 16 of 51 field goal attempts (31.4
percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this 26 years, and I never experienced what I
did today,'' Summitt said. ``We were shelled.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamika Catchings scored a team-high 16 points for the Lady Vols,
but her teammates were held to 8 points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee had a letdown even before the tip. Starting guard
Kristen ``Ace'' Clement was knocked out of the lineup when she
suffered a right ankle sprain during the morning warmup.
</P>
<P>
   Clement, a junior from the Philadelphia area, had started in all
of Tennessee's games, averaging 5.6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma had said earlier in the NCAA tournament that he had a
theory _ players should look at the game in four- or five-minute
increments, and take it one quarter at a time.
</P>
<P>
   So it couldn't have looked better for him when the Huskies led,
9-4, at the 15:55 mark, and then went on a 10-2 run in the next
five minutes to lead, 19-6. The Lady Vols were limited to two field
goals by Michelle Snow and two free throws by Semeka Randall.
</P>
<P>
   Randall tried to rev up the Vols' crowd, but it didn't do any
good. Tennessee shot just 11 percent in the first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee faced a double-digit deficit for most of the first
half, but came within 9, 28-19, with 1:33 to go on two free throws
by guard Kyra Elzy.
</P>
<P>
   But Swin Cash hit a running jump shot a minute later, and when
Sue Bird pulled up to hit a jump shot with five seconds left in the
half, the Huskies high-fived each other as they took a 32-19 lead
into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we played that good all year, and we got the
ultimate prize,'' said Ralph. She looked delirious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
