<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-UCONN-ANALYSIS-BO     04-03 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHING UCONN WAS POWERFUL EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The only thing missing is the title transfer.
Maybe the NCAA can work on that this morning. The organization can
draft a blue-and-white document, stamp a Husky logo on it, add some
contractual words such as ``herewith'' and ``whereas,'' and make
official what everyone should know by now:
</P>
<P>
   The new college basketball queendom is based in Storrs, Conn. It
will be that way for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Connecticut Huskies defeated Tennessee in the
national championship game Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, 71-52. Well, that's not
entirely true. They didn't just defeat the Lady Volunteers. They
faced them at the First Union Center for 40 minutes and then took
over their dynastic rights at the end of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Like most takeovers, this one was abrupt. UConn and Tennessee
entered the game as the two best programs in America. Most of the
20,060 fans in the arena expected a gradual war. Instead, they
watched as Tennessee went on a 2-for-18 shooting odyssey to begin
the game. It was over in the first half. You could sense it. You
looked into the mass of orange-and-white on the Volunteer bench and
saw about 15 faces of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   These programs have met twice for the national title since 1995.
Twice, UConn has emerged as the champion. Tennessee may have six
titles under Pat Summitt, but you would be naive to think that
UConn 2, Tennessee 0 (head-to-head) won't come up again.
</P>
<P>
   UConn not only won a championship Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. The school
probably won a few more recruits, too. And that has to be
frightening to anyone who watched the game; why, you wondered,
would this team need anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   There were times when the game unfolded far too easily for the
skilled Huskies. Center Kelly Schumacher played 20 minutes and had
nine blocked shots. She blocked Tamika Catchings's shot, Semeka
Randall's shot, and Kara Lawson's shot. When she was on the court,
she made the Vols look for her. That was a problem for them since
they already were having problems looking at the rim (31-percent
shooting).
</P>
<P>
   When the young woman, who is nicknamed ``Schu,'' wasn't blocking
shots, guard Shea Ralph was, well, doing everything. She was
dominant with 15 points, 7 assists, and 6 steals. Because of her
work and the work of her teammates, there is now a new flag waving
above the College Hoops Capitol Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're young, we're not going away,'' Summitt said shortly
after her Rome-in-Knoxville had fallen. ``I'm not as old as Geno
thinks I am. We'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Summitt is right on many counts. She is 47 and UConn coach Geno
Auriemma is 46. The women from Tennessee will be back. But they
will be back as renters in the queendom they used to own. UConn won
the game by 19 points and, Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, they were at least 19
points better than the Vols. There was nothing anyone on the
Tennessee sideline could do to change that.
</P>
<P>
   It definitely wasn't the best day, karmawise, for the team from
Knoxville. Starting shooting guard Kristen ``Ace'' Clement sprained
her right ankle during a light morning practice and did not play.
Clement, a native of the Philadelphia area, was restricted to
cheering at the end of the bench. The cheers went from vigorous to
sporadic to nonexistent. Three minutes into the second half, the
score was already 40-19. Nineteen points for a Tennessee team? That
just doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   After the coup, Auriemma said he didn't want to share his
pregame thoughts. He explained that if he did, he would be
perceived as something that he doesn't want to be perceived as.
Said another way: People would think him arrogant if he said, ``I
knew we'd win,'' even if that was what he was truly thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The curator of the new New England dynasty, Auriemma is a
complex man who grew up in this city. He came to this country from
rural Italy when he was 7. He did not speak English when he
arrived. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, he didn't need Italian or English when the
game ended. He was surrounded by his three children and all of them
stood together, crying. They tried to say a few words, but only
tears came. And then their grandmother, Auriemma's mother, headed
toward the court. Her son met her halfway and they embraced. More
tears.
</P>
<P>
   If you had watched those scenes, you might have shed a tear,
too. There was a feeling that something significant had happened.
Something had changed.
</P>
<P>
   This was a power swap. You can say New England is an area
obsessed with pro sports if you want. But you should know there is
now a dynasty in your back yard. It is tucked away in Connecticut,
in the queendom of Storrs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
