<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-CORRECTION     04-03 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SHOWING NEW OPTIMISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Fixing byline) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With the Anaheim Angels, nothing is
predictable. Otherwise, how could their recent success against the
New York Yankees be explained?
</P>
<P>
   The Angels open the 2000 season against the defending champions
at 7:35 tonight at Edison Field with renewed optimism. But it has
nothing to do with the fact the Angels have won the season series
vs. the Yankees the past two seasons and four of the past five.
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Stoneman improved the club with a
couple of trades with only a week remaining in spring training. The
popular and talented Jim Edmonds is gone, but the Angels have a
starting second baseman in Adam Kennedy and a starting pitcher in
Kent Bottenfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes patience has its rewards,'' Stoneman said. ``I think
it has paid to be patient because now we have two players our
people really like at positions (where) we had a need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally when I arrived in November we targeted starting
pitching. The road between then and now, you realize you just don't
get starting pitching. Everybody's looking for it. It's so
difficult to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman also made the move to acquire the young and talented
Edgard Clemente, who will DH and play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason the Angels, whom many have picked to finish last
in the competitive A.L. West, are excited about the season is the
attitude new manager Mike Scioscia and his coaching staff have
instilled in the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's experienced, he's won, he's played with some great
players,'' Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn said. ``He played a lot
of years. He puts the club together with expectations to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill will start for the Angels tonight against Orlando
Hernandez. Hill, called by Scioscia the ``ace'' of the staff, was
named the opening-night starter early in camp. Scioscia never
wavered in his praise of Hill during spring training, despite
Hill's inconsistent numbers (1-2, 7.94 ERA in six starts).
</P>
<P>
   And going up against the Yankees to start the season has no
added meaning, Scioscia says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had the philosophy of worrying about your own
house and not who you're playing, especially at the beginning of
the year,'' Scioscia said. ``Playing the Yankees won't have any
bearing on how we're going to attack it. Obviously the Yankees
bring to the table some things other teams don't, but you have to
attack it as if you're playing anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one final reason for optimism in Anaheim - health. At
this point last season, the Angels had already lost shortstop Gary
DiSarcina and Edmonds to injuries and were about to lose Vaughn in
the first inning of opening night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're starting the season on a roll,'' Scioscia said.
``We've played well, particularly the last 10 days or so. Another
thing I'm happy about is the club has practiced hard all spring and
is in great shape. I think we'll carry that over into the season.
I'm happy with the makeup of the club, the focus this club has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SMITH&AMP;WESSON-NYT     04-03 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SMITH&AMP;WESSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RETALIATING AGAINST SMITH &AMP; WESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, April 3:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and gun dealers are foolishly
trying to punish Smith &AMP; Wesson, the nation's largest gunmaker, for
striking a deal with the Clinton administration to embrace new
safety restrictions in exchange for ending threatened lawsuits
against the company. They are angry because Smith &AMP; Wesson, by
breaking ranks, has demolished the claim of gun-control opponents
that built-in trigger locks, better policing of gun dealers and
other safety measures would impose an impossible burden on the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has denounced Smith &AMP; Wesson for running up ``the white
flag of surrender,'' one of the nation's largest wholesalers said
it will stop distributing Smith &AMP; Wesson handguns, and many retail
dealers have said they will not sell Smith &AMP; Wesson products. The
gun industry denies any collusion to harm a competitor in violation
of antitrust laws, a matter that Eliot Spitzer, the attorney
general of New York, and Richard Blumenthal, Connecticut's attorney
general, are investigating.
</P>
<P>
   These retaliatory efforts add fresh urgency to the campaign to
get state and local governments to purchase their guns from Smith &AMP;
Wesson and other firms that adhere to the deal's principles. The
campaign is being led by Spitzer and Housing Secretary Andrew
Cuomo, two gun-control advocates who have been rivals for the
spotlight on this issue. This week, Sen. Charles Schumer, the New
York Democrat, will try to insert language in the federal budget
for federal law enforcement agencies to do the same. Spokesmen for
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki say their bosses are
generally supportive but need to study how they would implement the
preference. If the two men are serious, it should not be that hard
to find ways the city and state can use their purchasing power to
achieve stronger gun controls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
