<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-GRIFFEY-SPI &LR;      04-03 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GRIFFEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNIOR SET TO TAKE PLACE IN REDS' HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Joe Morgan remembers what it was like, when
Cincinnati was home to the Big Red Machine, the best team in
baseball and the greatest father-son game in history.
</P>
<P>
   When sharing a clubhouse with Pete Rose, Tony Perez and Ken
Griffey meant also sharing it with their kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all loved playing baseball,'' Morgan said. ``They used to
play it in the locker room. They were here early. When we came out
for batting practice they would come out to the cages, they would
go on the field. They were always around.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as much as ballplayers are on the road, it was good for
the fathers to have them around. Not many fathers are lucky enough
to be able to have their kids come to work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for most kids, visiting the old man's workplace
involves sitting bored in a cubicle, keeping quiet and watching the
clock. It doesn't involve hanging around with future Hall of
Famers. Morgan said the Reds kids would imitate his batting stance,
flapping their left elbows just as he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the kids around here did that, though,'' Morgan said with
a smile. ``All the Little Leaguers did that in Cincinnati. And
within a month, I think you'll see them all imitating Junior's
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Junior. After 11 summers in Seattle, after the biggest
trade of the winter, Ken Griffey Jr. opens his first season with
the team he dreamed about playing for when he was a kid in the
Cincinnati clubhouse. Game time for Monday's Reds-Brewers opener at
Cinergy Field is 10 a.m. PDT, barring rain (there were showers
throughout Sunday and more forecast for Monday).
</P>
<P>
   While the other Reds were more than willing to discuss the
opener, the season and their new teammate, Griffey declined to
speak much more than a sentence or two to reporters, refusing to
take part in an interview session until after Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   He did tell a handful of reporters that he enjoyed opening day
as a child in Cincinnati because he could skip school to go to the
game. ``My son is skipping school on opening day. It's a
tradition,'' he said. ``Cincinnati expects that a lot of kids
aren't going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Griffey went about his business quietly Sunday. He
unpacked an enormous container filled with uniform pants, running
shorts, batting gloves, shoes and T-shirts. He tried on his Reds
uniform and pronounced it properly tailored. He tossed aside two
pairs of running pants with the Mariners' colors _ ``Won't be
needing those.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a passing of the torch of sorts, Johnny Bench brought his
son into the clubhouse to meet Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to every age group,'' Bench said, ``from first
graders on up to 90-year-old men in nursing homes and it's all the
same. Do they have enough pitching? And, how many home runs will
Griffey hit?''
</P>
<P>
   This is a city that takes its baseball and its team seriously
enough that it still gets a little miffed when another team dares
to open the season before the Reds. A city that has a street named
for Rose, even though he did time for cheating on taxes and is
banned from baseball for betting on the game.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Griffey Avenue yet, though a downtown store is
selling Griffey Jr. street signs along with the Pete Rose Way
signs.
</P>
<P>
   How excited is the city? Said Reds chief operating officer John
Allen, ``I've gotten three standing ovations when I've gone out to
Rotary luncheons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the fans I've talked to, there must have been 10,000
kids where Junior went to high school. They all say, `I went to
high school with him.' It sounds like everyone in Cincinnati went
to high school with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati first baseman Sean Casey learned his thumb was broken
and he would miss the season's first two weeks but he was genuinely
excited about the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``The craze will be awesome,'' he said. ``It will be exciting
just to hear him introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will it be like when he's introduced?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the Messiah,'' Bench said. ``You know how Cincinnati
feels about their hometown boys, from Pete to Barry Larkin to
Junior _ and they'll think this is absolutely the best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be electric,'' Allen said. ``I think
there will be two instances. First, when the players run on the
field for their introductions and then when they say, ``Playing
center field, number 24 ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Whoops. Make that No. 30. Griffey has switched from his familiar
24 to his father's old Reds number (Senior is wearing 33).
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's going to take some getting used to, seeing Griffey in
a uniform other than one of Seattle's three dozen day-alternate
business person's holiday jerseys. But there's time. An entire
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the fantastic plays and the dramatic home runs,'' Larkin
said, ``all start tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
