<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KHMER-JUSTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTICE FOR THE KHMER ROUGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, April 3:
</P>
<P>
   More than two decades after the mass slaughter in Cambodia, a
critical moment is at hand in a long-overdue attempt to bring the
killers to justice. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will soon
decide whether the U.N. should participate in a criminal court that
will try surviving leaders of the Khmer Rouge, whose members killed
more than a million Cambodians between 1975 and 1979. The court
will be in Cambodia and needs the approval of Cambodia's strongman,
Hun Sen, who is doing all he can to impose conditions that would
enable him to manipulate the trials. Annan must make clear that the
U.N. will not abide by those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A team of U.N. negotiators left Cambodia last month after
failing to reach agreement with the government on ground rules for
the tribunal. But progress was made and the negotiations are not
over. Annan is expected to take up the matter directly with Hun Sen
at a meeting of developing nations in Cuba later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Some form of international participation will be essential to
real justice. The Cambodian judicial system has neither the
competence nor the political independence to conduct credible
trials on its own. The best approach would be an international
tribunal like those the U.N. established for Rwanda and the former
Yugoslavia, but Hun Sen rejected the idea. Until last month
discussions on U.N. support for Cambodian trials had made little
progress since the surrender in 1999 of the last fugitive Khmer
Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point involves a legitimate demand by the U.N.
that the tribunal include a foreign prosecutor with independent
authority to issue indictments. The Cambodians have insisted on
having co-prosecutors, one foreign and one Cambodian, in a
collaborative arrangement that would effectively give Hun Sen veto
power over any indictment. This would be unacceptable. The U.N.
must not participate in a process that fails to grant an
independent prosecutor sufficient authority to issue indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot died in 1998, but many of his top
lieutenants are alive and free in Cambodia. Hun Sen cut deals that
effectively gave some of the top surviving Khmer Rouge leaders _
Ieng Sary, Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan _ immunity from prosecution
in exchange for their loyalty. But their immunity should not apply
to an internationally backed tribunal, and the U.N. must insist
that these men be tried. Without them the process will be a
mockery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HOMELOANS-NYT &LR;      04-03 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOMELOANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DECEPTIVE HOME LOAN PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, April 3:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys general and consumer advocates increasingly have
expressed alarm over abusive practices in the ``subprime'' home
equity market, which caters to people with blemished credit records
and charges them higher interest rates and fees. Practices like
tacking exorbitant fees onto loans without adequate disclosure can
cause unsuspecting consumers to borrow more than they can repay,
driving them into default and resulting in the loss of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a New York-based home loan company, Delta Financial,
settled a lawsuit filed by three federal agencies accusing it of
predatory lending to minority homeowners. Earlier, Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, gave added prominence to the
issue by voicing his concern about such practices.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan indicated that the Federal Reserve is working with
several federal agencies, including the Federal Trade Commission,
the justice department and the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, to examine deceptive behavior in this market. Other
agencies, individual states and some in Congress are also pressing
for a crackdown. The subprime lenders are largely regulated by the
states, whose laws can vary substantially.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the chief pressure on lenders has come from
private consumer lawsuits. Last month, the First Alliance Corp., a
prominent subprime lender that is facing lawsuits by several
homeowners and the AARP for deceptive practices, filed for
bankruptcy protection. First Alliance, the subject of a report by
The Times' Diana Henriques and ABC News, denies the accusations.
The bankruptcy proceeding will freeze the legal actions and force
the plaintiffs to pursue their claims in bankruptcy court. First
Alliance is also facing suits by regulators in Illinois and
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy filing will give no relief to customers of First
Alliance who face high repayments. But the troubled lender says it
will stop making new loans. Meanwhile, federal regulators need to
examine the adequacy of state regulations and intensify federal
oversight in this market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
