<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NUCLEAR-AGENDA-N     04-03 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUCLEAR-AGENDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE UNFINISHED NUCLEAR AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, April 3:
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Putin has made clear that he intends to maintain
Russia's nuclear defenses. But he also faces sharp reductions in
the number of long-range nuclear weapons capable of reaching the
United States. His election as president should revive stalled arms
negotiations between Washington and Moscow. Completing a treaty
that would lock in deep new weapons cuts by the time President
Clinton leaves office is a realistic target. A new agreement should
also incorporate changes in the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty
that would allow both countries to deploy limited defensive systems
to protect against threats from rogue states like North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still has a little more than nine months left to work
with Putin toward this mutually beneficial goal. History shows that
American presidents can deal effectively with arms control issues
until their final weeks in office. The last major nuclear arms
reduction treaty with Russia was signed by President Bush on Jan.
3, 1993, less than three weeks before he turned over the White
House to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ratification of that treaty got caught up in the
parliamentary gridlock in Moscow. Getting it approved by the newly
elected parliament should be one of Putin's earliest goals.
Carrying out the 1993 treaty would cut the number of long-range
nuclear warheads on both sides almost in half from the current
levels of about 6,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that pending treaty is ratified, intensive
negotiations should begin on a new treaty that would bring those
numbers down to around 2,000 or even lower. Without these further
cuts, Russia would have to build thousands of new single-warhead
missiles to replace the multiwarhead missiles it must destroy under
the 1993 treaty. Building expensive new missiles that both sides
already agree should be negotiated away would be a wasteful use of
Russia's pinched budgetary resources.
</P>
<P>
   The 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty is an integral part of
the arms-control architecture Washington has developed with Moscow.
Defense planners on both sides have felt comfortable with lower
levels of offensive missiles knowing that they would not have to
penetrate a defensive missile shield. But the ABM treaty was
negotiated at a time when this kind of missile calculus was
premised on a clash between the two superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   The likely emergence of smaller, less-predictable nuclear-armed
nations over the next few years creates a different equation.
Neither America nor Russia wants to be blackmailed by countries
like North Korea threatening to unleash a handful of poorly aimed
but highly destructive nuclear missiles. The technology of limited
defensive missile shields has not yet been reliably perfected. But
when it is, both countries should be free, within carefully
negotiated limits, to protect their people from this kind of
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who has not yet made his mark on the world stage, and
Clinton, whose two terms in office have not brought a major arms
control success, have before them a clear opportunity. They can
eliminate thousands of unneeded nuclear weapons and help free their
countries from one of the Cold War's most dangerous legacies.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
