<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-03 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAD DISCOURSE OF MESA HAS FAMILIAR RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Wearing a scowl that at least made him look like a
closer, Jose Mesa walked out of Lou Piniella's office Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This was about an hour before game time at Safeco Field, where
the M's played their final exhibition of spring.
</P>
<P>
   Since Piniella already announced that Mesa is not the Mariners'
closer _ remember, last week, Mesa gave up six runs on six hits to
six unknown Padres minor leaguers, ouch _ it's tough to know what
was left to say to Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Piniella wanted to warn Mesa not to be jealous. In a city
where dog owners have been known to name their pets after Mariner
stars like Griffey and Buhner, a new crop of canines might carry
the tag: ``Kazuhiro.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Mariners' opener tomorrow, and after the bitter taste
of Mesa's blown save in last July's Safeco opener, the stage is set
for the very self-possessed all-time save leader from Japan,
Kazuhiro Sasaki, to restore order to the Mariners bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   On a Mariners team built on pitching, Sasaki _ known as
``Diamajin,'' Japanese for ``malevolent deity'' _ is the only
pitcher who exceeded expectations during spring training, earning
him respect and the closer role.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mesa, perhaps this is a generous way of pardoning his
declining skills, but it is not his fault the Mariners signed him
to a two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it his fault that the Mariners, desperate, set up
expectations that in the wake of Bobby Ayala and a rapidly
declining Norm Charlton, Mesa would be the man.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, signing Mesa last season was a high-risk proposition _
one that has set Mesa up to be the whipping boy not only of
Piniella but of Mariners baseball fans who can't fathom why Mesa is
so unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball parlance, Mesa has lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland knew it was time to cut Mesa loose. He was never the
same after he blew the save in the 1997 World Series that cost
Cleveland the championship to the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Mariners ignored the fact that Mesa was toast in
Cleveland and later again in San Francisco, where he walked in runs
and was seen to be beyond restoration.
</P>
<P>
   But for the M's, desperation led to a desperate move, even
though the speed gun does not lie.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's fastball never gets much above 93 or 94 mph. He's got
nothing else in his arsenal to make the hitters bite. His 33 saves
last season were really, at best, 10 saves and here he was in
Arizona last week, enduring more jeers and boos as his career
further unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you could say Mesa is used to his status as one of
baseball's unloved performers. But you can not envy his station in
life. Some of us would not trade the $3 million he'll make this
season to have to suffer the merciless public failures.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, Seattle sports fans this past week have been
taking a hard look at Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, time has come to trash-talk Baker's
soft-as-a-down-pillow game.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the Sonics so-called power forward reached a
crescendo last Thursday when, after a five-game home losing streak,
Baker's tendency to float from the paint to the perimeter and avoid
the nasty stuff was deemed a major reason why the Sonics were
losing.
</P>
<P>
   To magnify matters, word is that Baker resorted to pouting last
Friday after Sonics coach Paul Westphal, along with Gary Payton and
Horace Grant, challenged Baker to do the dirty work required of his
position.
</P>
<P>
   As in the case of Mesa, however, you have to ask:
</P>
<P>
   Is it Baker's fault the Sonics signed him to a seven-year deal
for $87 million, which is the NBA maximum salary?
</P>
<P>
   It's like that song, ``Looking for love in all the wrong
places.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's went with Mesa because there wasn't anyone else out
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, meanwhile, re-signed Baker not because they were
convinced he could get the job done, but because they did not want
to take the risk of losing the free agent and finding themselves
handcuffed by salary cap restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sonics, who watched Baker's alarming display of poor
conditioning and depression-like response to poor play, making
Baker one of their high-paid centerpiece players was as much a wing
and a prayer and a guarantee for wins.
</P>
<P>
   He's still young. He appears to have the basketball tools. He
has been an All-Star. All these things roll up into a risky hope
that Baker will turn himself into the star the Sonics need _ and we
repeat, need _ him to be.
</P>
<P>
   But basketball fans in Seattle can't quite wrap their minds
around a team, a league and sports phenomenon that prompts a
franchise to reward a guy like Baker for such serious
underachievement.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, it is hard to know exactly what Baker thinks about
himself, his game, his role on the Sonics and in the NBA. Yes, he
might have the physical tools. But Baker gives every appearance of
being a very nice guy. He is soft spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Baker might think that if the Sonics brought Grant in to do the
heavy lifting, how come he doesn't have the right to float out and
look for his jumper, the way Payton looks to create his own shots
instead of passing first, especially late in the game?
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, he might believe he is playing as hard as he can. He
might think that running and sweating and wanting his minutes
proves his desire.
</P>
<P>
   It is Baker's misfortune, though, that his desire will
ultimately be judged by everyone else. Same with Mesa, whose arm
doesn't deliver the kind of stuff fans want to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the big time.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
