<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-TITLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS, GATORS GEARED FOR UP-AND-DOWN TITLE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Get out your running shoes and prepare for one
final sprint to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   But keep a cooler by the couch: There won't be any time for
dashes to the fridge Monday night, not with Michigan State and
Florida dueling in a track meet that figures to be a nonstop battle
for the college basketball championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans show up at the RCA Dome as survivors of a Saturday
slugfest with Wisconsin, eager to flow in the open court and win
the national title, just like point guard Mateen Cleaves said they
would.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators appear as the polished challenger, whipping North
Carolina in the other semifinal, preparing to unleash another
baseline-to-baseline attack with a talented, deep rotation.
</P>
<P>
   All of the keys were discussed Sunday, many dealing with
Florida's ability to create opportunities and fatigue with its
relentless full-court defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a controlled chaos,'' said Gators guard Brett Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Spartans were pressed by reporters who wondered if
Tom Izzo's team can cope with those athletic and frenetic
Floridians for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally the answer was yes; Cleaves is a superb ball-handler
and his teammates are equally experienced, not apt to be flustered.
In fact, Michigan State doesn't want to settle for simply breaking
the press, preferring to capitalize by pushing the ball and getting
2-on-1 situations.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, though, believes it messes with people's heads. The
Gators see the mental distraction and physical exhaustion in their
victims' body language.
</P>
<P>
   In Gainesville, it's called Billy Ball, a system devised by
Billy Donovan, a 34-year-old who looks like he would be
emasculating someone in the corporate world if he wasn't coaching a
successful basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's Gators are as slick as he is. Even if it appears that
Florida consists of a bunch of free-wheelers, the concepts are
sound, debunking perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our style of play is completely misunderstood,'' Donovan said.
``All we're doing is trying to get easy baskets in transition. We
do things that are maybe a little bit unconventional, but we've
still got to rebound, play unselfishly and screen and execute.
We're doing all of the fundamental aspects, we're just doing them
at a faster rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's strength is its depth. Ten players contribute. None
played more than 29 minutes against the Tar Heels. In addition to
the freshness factor that reveals itself in the second half,
Florida's reserves routinely batter the opposition, the Gators'
bullpen outscoring North Carolina's 37-2.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has quite the collection of standouts, which enables the
Gators to overcome off-shooting nights like the ones Mike Miller
and Teddy Dupay had against North Carolina, going a combined
4-for-21.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the freshman who is supposed to be the best player from
West Virginia since Jerry West, compensated with 13 points. And
Florida, more frequently viewed as a perimeter outfit, also has
players like Udonis Haslem, Donnell Harvey, Brent Wright and Matt
Bonner who inflict considerable damage inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Udonis is as good as any frontcourt player in America,''
Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's journey to the title game nearly ended at its first
stop in Winston-Salem, where it defeated Butler 69-68 in overtime
on Miller's last-second shot from the lane. Since then, the Gators
have flattened their NCAA Tournament opponents by an average of
12.5 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering what inspired Florida, you could say that
Butler did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game gave our guys a tremendous sense of energy and
emotion of understanding how fragile this whole thing is and how
you can be sitting home at the blink of an eye,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Kenyan Weaks, Florida's only senior: ``That game brought
us together. The season could have been over, but we realized we
had each other's backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some come from the inner city, some from the suburbs, others
from the sticks, like Miller, a native of Mitchell, S.D. Their
universal will to win overrides any cultural differences.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Donovan molds and motivates. He showed them the
movie ``Rudy'' and tapes of the Muhammad Ali-George Foreman
rope-a-dope fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put those situations in front of our guys so they can see
what a hunger, what a passion, what a desire does for a human being
when they want something,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach wasn't sure what he planned to show to last night, but
Dupay had an idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll see `Home Alone,' '' he said. ``Some young kid
defending his house.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning for its second consecutive Final Four, Michigan State
lost to Duke in the semifinals last year, after which Cleaves vowed
to win the national title this season. The scenario for a sequel
with a better ending is set.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans are confident and concerned. They're aware of the
Gators' firepower and understand that their own bench will have to
be more productive. They know they can't go 12 minutes without a
field goal like they did against Wisconsin. But Michigan State,
with three seniors and two juniors in the starting lineup, believes
it has the veterans to withstand the assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the fortitude. Morris Peterson, the Spartans'
leading scorer, and Cleaves could have left a year early to sample
life in the NBA but chose to stay in East Lansing for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, particularly, epitomizes Izzo's motto of ``players
play, and tough players win.'' Cleaves may be erratic with his
shooting, but the body and mind are solid. He leads in different
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys you have to yell at, others you have to help them
laugh to ease their tensions,'' Cleaves said. ``And then there are
others you just have to stare at to get their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night in the RCA Dome, he will focus on a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's ever a guy who had a true dream, it's Mateen,''
Izzo said. ``He's dreamed it since he was old enough to touch a
basketball, and he has the opportunity. We're going to find out if
it can become reality.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
