<HEADLINE>
MARINERS DEMOTE TOMKO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There are aproximately zero major league teams for
whom the final cutdown day is not without pain and angst, and so it
was for Seattle Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Tomko, a hard thrower who came to the club from Cincinnati
in the Ken Griffey Jr. trade of Feb. 10, was judged to be too
limited by lack of innings thrown and was one of four players sent
to the minor leagues as the Mariners got down to the 25-player
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tomko declined to talk about the move with the media,
it was clear he was furious.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he was the Opening Day starting pitcher for the Reds
in a season that would wind up one game short of the post-season.
Today, he's just another veteran minor leaguer struggling to get
back to the bigs.
</P>
<P>
   Sent via option to Triple-A Tacoma in addition to Tomko were
right-handed pitcher Kevin Hodges and infielder Carlos Hernandez.
Right-handed pitcher Todd Williams was outrighted to the Rainiers.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the Seattle roster is major. Gil Meche claims the
final spot in the rotation. And outfielder/infielder Charles Gipson
and outfielder/catcher Raul Ibanez, both of whom could have been
bumped from the roster had Tomko stuck as a 12th pitcher, will
start the season with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision, but he and we are better served,''
Piniella said, referring to Tomko. ``He can start the season
pitching in a rotation, building up his arm strength and his
velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be difficult to have Meche and Tomko in the
rotation, and to have one in the rotation and one in the bullpen
would have set the one in the bullpen back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomko was judged by the Mariners not to be ready after a left
Achilles tendon problem he brought to spring training slowed him
down. He only threw four innings in his final spring appearance on
Friday in Las Vegas, two innings less than the Mariners wanted from
him.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Meche, who lost a week of spring training due
to a sore lat muscle behind his right shoulder, pitched only 82/3
innings in Cactus League games, five innings less than Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Saturday night, the option of carrying 12 pitchers on
a roster that would have included both Meche, who did pitch in
minor league spring games, and Tomko was alive, even likely.
</P>
<P>
   But that would have meant the Mariners would have had to start
the season without Gipson, leaving them short on middle infield
help.
</P>
<P>
   Or they would have had to risk losing Ibanez on waivers, because
the outfielder is out of options. Moving Tomko then became the
simplest, least disruptive way to balance out the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Tomko will join Tacoma's rotation and could be back in Seattle
soon. Or come back not at all.
</P>
<P>
   If he thrives at Tacoma and stretches out to pitch six or seven
innings effectively, he could be brought back to Seattle if one of
the five starters _ Meche, Jamie Moyer, Freddy Garcia, Aaron Sele
and John Halama _ falters or is hurt.
</P>
<P>
   If none of those five is hurt or stumbling, however, the
likelihood is that Tomko would be traded, if he's pitching well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he's a major league pitcher,'' Piniella said. ``He
wasn't very happy when he was told, and I concur with that. But
what he has to do is take it as a positive that he is liked here
but is being sent down as a consequence of needing more innings to
get in shape to throw six or seven innings (per start).
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel he's very important to our pitching staff. Just not
right at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
