<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS CAN'T SOLVE BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ It would stand to reason that the Portland
Trail Blazers might be more manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Their starting center was unavailable because of an injury, and
his replacement became disqualified, barely lasting two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sonics were the ones a bit off kilter Sunday night
in a 95-82 loss in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   What they missed most were shots. Even the freebies wouldn't
fall, an untimely deficiency that led to the Sonics losing for the
fourth time in as many meetings with the Blazers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard. We just didn't play well,'' said Sonics coach
Paul Westphal, who watched his team shoot 40 percent and miss 12 of
26 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics remained in eighth place in the Western Conference
standings. They fell 1{ games behind the seventh-seeded Sacramento
Kings, who beat Philadelphia yesterday at home.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second straight game when those `e' words _ effort
and energy _ weren't called into question for the Sonics. It seemed
evident that the momentum from an emotional win against Sacramento
last Friday carried over into the first half of this game.
</P>
<P>
   Exploitation, though, became a troubling term for the Sonics in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Portland used its deep lineup to overcome poor shooting (41
percent), the absence of center Arvydas Sabonis (sprained right
foot) and Rasheed Wallace (ejected early in the second quarter).
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 67-63 with 10:47 left in the game, Portland found
favorable matchups with its reserves on the floor to extend the
lead. The Blazers got Stacey Augmon, Detlef Schrempf, Jermaine
O'Neal and, sometimes, Scottie Pippen in post-up situations over
the Sonics smaller guards.
</P>
<P>
   With each of those players standing 6-foot-8 or taller, the
Blazers literally became a big challenge down the stretch. On
several occasions, Sonics guard Vernon Maxwell found himself giving
up four inches in the post.
</P>
<P>
   Portland went on a 12-4 run and led 79-67 after Schrempf's
putback basket.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the Sonics got within eight points in the final period.
But Portland closed the door on both comebacks by converting free
throws. The Blazers made all eight foul shots in the fourth and
finished the game 24-for-30 at the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portland always found the extra guy to exploit us,'' Westphal
said. ``They have size and quickness advantages and did a great job
of taking it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics battled until the Blazers countered with their size.
Seattle trailed just 45-43 at halftime and was in the game mainly
because of rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Patterson's eight rebounds in the first half helped the
Sonics forge a 29-21 edge on the boards. The Sonics collected 13
offensive rebounds at that point. Scoring easy baskets in
transition and cleaning up their misses is what kept the Sonics
close. But the Sonics did not rebound any of their shots in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played hard and we played well defensively,''
forward Vin Baker said. ``But the essence of the game is to make
shots. We didn't do that. Give Portland credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace started at center for Portland because Sabonis is on the
injured list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time we have been in that position,''
Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``But I was pleased the way we
responded. The key was ball movement.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the Blazers had been cut down to size even more when
Wallace was ejected with 10:37 left in the second period. Wallace
argued with referee Joe Crawford after a foul had been whistled on
teammate Brian Grant's putback attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace thought he had been hacked on his shot in the sequence.
He complained for about five seconds. Then, Crawford tagged Wallace
with two technical fouls and sent him to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   The game reached a feverish pitch at that point. On the Sonics
next trip up court, Jermaine O'Neal received a flagrant foul for a
hard hit on Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Baker split two free throws and then sank a short jumper in the
lane after the Sonics were awarded possession. That basket got the
Sonics within 23-22 with 10:04 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of opportunities in the first half to build a
lead, but we shot only 37 percent and had too many turnovers,''
Westphal said. ``When Portland found ways to make plays, our bad
shooting continued. ... Our missing 12 free throws was
catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
