<SLUG> BC-NEXTEL-WORLDPHONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXTEL TO OFFER WIRELESS `WORLD PHONE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Targeting a market now served largely by Omnipoint and expensive
satellite phones, Nextel Communications is offering a new wireless
phone that can be used around most of the world with one phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   It's not cheap: The phone costs $350, or $250 under a launch
promotion. And calling prices range from $1 a minute in Western
Europe up to $5 in some African, Southeast Asian, and Eastern
European countries.
</P>
<P>
   But compared with the cost and hassle of using a calling card or
hotel room phone internationally, and considering the convenience
for US-based globetrotters to be able to take their phone around
the world and get calls wherever they are, ``It's a good move for
Nextel,'' said Adam Zawel, a wireless analyst with The Yankee Group
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   To use the service, subscribers must buy a Motorola i2000 phone.
It is a ``dual mode'' phone that works on Nextel's iDEN network
system in the United States and Latin America, and on the GSM
standard that dominates in Europe, Asia, and much of the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Omnipoint, one of the six carriers that serves Greater Boston,
uses the GSM standard and heavily promotes that you can take your
Omnipoint phone to Europe and get phone calls there as if you were
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   However, GSM service still has some big holes domestically.
Omnipoint phones cannot pick up service in some big cities,
including Chicago, Dallas, and New Orleans, although GSM networks
are being built out now.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel covers all but four of the 100 largest US metropolitan
markets and large cities in Argentina, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, and
Peru with iDEN service.
</P>
<P>
   While so-called third generation phones are in development that
would work on the multiple conflicting network systems in use
around the world, it could be two to three years before they hit
the market. That gives Nextel a window of opportunity for
international roaming.
</P>
<P>
   The Reston, Va.-based company is known for an operating system
that allows use of the phone as a walkie-talkie. The phones are
especially popular with tradespeople, fleet drivers, and service
technicians for big companies because their offices can make
``direct connect'' radio calls to them.
</P>
<P>
   To get international calling access, Nextel customers will have
to pay a $5 monthly fee in addition to their domestic calling plan.
But the charge will be permanently waived for people who sign up
before June 30, said Nextel executive vice president Tom Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Zawel said he thinks the price would make the average consumer
think twice. ``But with most Nextel customers, their company foots
the bill,'' so steep foreign roaming charges may not deter business
users, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   A Nextel-commissioned survey by pollsters Wirthlin Worldwide
found that the majority of US business travelers don't use cell
phones when they travel abroad. Nearly three-quarters use a hotel
phone, and 53 percent use a calling card at a payphone.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third said they repeatedly experience problems such
as not being able to find a phone or get a good connection.
</P>
<P>
   To make calls when abroad, subscribers to the Nextel service
would press and hold the 0 key to get international access, then
dial the number they are calling. In a country where the service
works, their phone would ring whenever someone called their
10-digit US phone number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0093 </DOCNO>
