<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADCLIFFE-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAUST APPOINTED DEAN OF NEW RADCLIFFE INSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Six months after Harvard University merged
with Radcliffe College, Harvard president Neil L. Rudenstine Sunday
named the first dean of the Radcliffe Institute of Advanced Study,
the pared-down legacy of the elite 106-year-old women's college.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine selected Drew Gilpin Faust, a history professor and
director of the women's studies program at the University of
Pennsylvania. The selection capped an eight-month search in which a
committee reviewed more than 80 applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faust has the clarity of mind, the commitment, and the
leadership qualities essential to the successful launching of this
new venture, particularly within an institution as complex as
Harvard,'' Rudenstine said.
</P>
<P>
   Faust, who turned down an offer to teach at Harvard in 1989,
will take over Radcliffe in January. With the decision still taking
root in her mind, she said at a news conference Sunday she has not
yet made specific plans for revamping Radcliffe. But, she said,
``It's not as if this is a blank slate. There are hints where to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   When she takes over the reins next year from acting dean Mary
Maples Dunn, she said, her focus would be to build on Radcliffe's
work in the field of women, gender, and society and deepen the
roots of the new fellowship program, which brings in distinguished
scholars, artists, and other professionals (both women and men) to
study any subject of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the mid-1970s that an agreement between the
schools allowed women to be jointly admitted to Harvard and
Radcliffe, which retained its independence. With the merger
agreement announced last April, however, Radcliffe ended its
undergraduate role, dissolved its board of trustees, and received a
$150 million investment from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Radcliffe Institute is considered on par with Harvard's
nine other institutions such as Harvard Law School and the John F.
Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine said the appointment of Faust, a prolific author who
has written five books and specializes in Civil War studies,
grounds the new institution and will shape its uncharted future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deans at Harvard have enormous power,'' Faust said. ``As far
as I understand, that's how Harvard works: The dean decides and
sets the tone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 0931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
