<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-GUNS-BOS &LR;      04-03 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AG TO ENFORCE STRICTER GUN SAFETY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the gun industry finally admitting defeat,
Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly says he will begin to enforce the
state's tough weapon safety standards, which had been tied up in a
lengthy court battle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Massachusetts became the first state in the nation to
try to utilize consumer protection regulations to enforce handgun
safety. The rules were issued, but never implemented, by former
attorney general Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations effectively ban cheap ``Saturday night
specials'' and require all handguns sold in Massachusetts to
include childproof locks, tamperproof serial numbers, and safety
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The rules also set strict safety standards for gun
manufacturers, and permit the attorney general's office to conduct
independent tests to ensure compliance.
</P>
<P>
   According to state law enforcement sources, Reilly's actions
affect not only Massachusetts gun dealers, but also gun
manufacturers across the country that must comply with the new
safety standard in order to sell weapons in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very bad news for the gun industry that's already
staggering from lawsuits and the recent Smith &AMP; Wesson agreement,''
said one state law enforcement official who declined to be
identified. ``It shows states can effectively adopt and enforce gun
safety standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The court battle over the regulations ended on March 20, when
the gun industry failed to meet the deadline for appealing a
Suffolk Superior Court decision upholding the attorney general's
authority to issue gun safety regulations. Reilly had been waiting
to ensure the gun industry had given up its legal battle before
embarking on the full-scale enforcement effort, slated to begin
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge victory,'' said John Rosenthal of Stop Handgun
Violence, a leading proponent of gun-control measures in the state.
``And since the attorneys general in 34 other states have similar
powers, we hope that in the absence of a national safety standard
for guns, this will become a blueprint for how states can regulate
the manufacture and sale of handguns.'
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., the nation's largest gun
manufacturer, voluntarily signed a code of conduct accepting
responsibility for how its guns are distributed and sold. The
Springfield, Mass. company was facing the threat of a costly
federal lawsuit when it agreed to sweeping safety measures intended
to control both the sale and use of its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   However, gun-control advocates say the new Massachusetts gun
safety regulations, and Reilly's promised tough enforcement of
them, goes further than the Smith &AMP; Wesson agreement because the
state regulations are mandatory, and affect all gun manufacturers,
not just one company.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the Gun Owners Action League and the National Rifle
Association seeking comment on Reilly's expected enforcement effort
were not returned Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Massachusetts regulations, it is now a violation of
state consumer protection laws to sell, lease, or rent:
</P>
<P>
   --Handguns without specific child-safety features.
</P>
<P>
   --Handguns without state-approved trigger locks and other safety
devices.
</P>
<P>
   --Handguns without tamperproof serial numbers.
</P>
<P>
   --``Junk'' handguns made from inferior materials that are prone
to explosion or accidental discharge.
</P>
<P>
   --Semi-automatic handguns without a load indicator or magazine
safety disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   Features of the Masssachusetts gun regulations were incorporated
into the Smith &AMP; Wesson agreement, in which the company agreed to
put safety locks on its guns, add ``smart gun'' technology to new
guns to prevent unauthorized usage, and not to peddle weapons at
gun shows where background checks of buyers are not carried out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
