</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-POPE-REPORTERS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD IS MY CO-PILOT: PACKING A BIBLE AND LOLLING WITH THE
VATICANISTI 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The true nuttiness of papal coverage hit me in the Old
City of Jerusalem, when members of the Vatican press corps
following the pope's historic pilgrimage to the Holy Land were
standing tensely outside a mosque behind a wall of Israeli police
officers, waiting for John Paul II to end his meeting with the
mufti of Jerusalem and pray at the Western Wall, Judaism's most
sacred place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a Lutheran! I finally found a Lutheran!'' my German
colleague, the correspondent for the Axel-Springer newspaper chain,
shouted exultantly. A first-rate reporter who closely monitors the
pope's moods and fading health with binoculars, a handheld
television set and a tape recorder equipped with a tiny video
camera, Andreas Englisch explained that his editors in Berlin were
constantly pressing him to find a local German angle to even the
most extraordinary moments of John Paul II's pontificate.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, traveling with the pope is a little like
covering the White House or a presidential campaign: long bus
rides, early wake-up calls, bunker camaraderie, cell phones,
laptops and an obsessive thirst for advance copies of his speeches
(homilies, in church parlance).
</P>
<P>
   But Vatican reporters, unlike their political colleagues, spend
a lot of time in church _ and are gently encouraged to spend even
more. On Sunday nights during a trip, a priest says Mass at a hotel
room for reporters who had to work through the pope's Mass earlier
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Political reporters hit the road carrying their bible, the
Almanac of American Politics. Vatican reporters carry the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps to the envy of colleagues who spent the last five
months listening to Sen. John McCain, the pope isn't running for
anything and we never interview him.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, 79 and now very frail, rarely comes to the back of his
chartered plane to chat with reporters anymore. The only time he
has done it in the last two years was on the way to Mexico City and
St. Louis, Mo. Weak, his speech slurred, the pope grimly noted the
global triumph of unfettered American-style capitalism. ``For
better or worse, there is only one superpower left,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican, like the Kremlin, has little sense of public
accountability. That means sparse disclosure of even basic
information about the pope's health, Vatican finances or shifts in
Curia policy. Spinning, an art form perfected by American political
advisers to shape reporters' coverage, is also limited. For
example, on trips, the Vatican spokesman, Dr. Joaquin
Navarro-Valls, will occasionally pop up after a Mass to brief the
press pack in three languages. (``The Holy Father was deeply moved,
but I did not see him weep, no.'')
</P>
<P>
   We rarely see the pope up close, relying on binoculars and
television to track his declining health. He travels with two
doctors. His chief physician, the tall, elegant Dr. Renato
Buzzonetti, answers all questions about the pontiff's health by
smiling silkily and saying, ``Bene, grazie.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, whose left hand trembles uncontrollably from
Parkinson's disease and who walks with a cane in a stiff, painful
shuffle, held up amazingly well throughout the six-day pilgrimage
to the Holy Land. But in Georgia last November, he was shaking so
badly in a cold, damp Orthodox church that Italian reporters,
receiving cell phone reports from their editors in Rome watching
him on television, wrote alarmist stories about his endangered
health. I was in the church, 10 feet away from him, but hemmed in
by hundreds of jostling Eastern Orthodox and Roman Catholic
believers, saw nothing. Just as well, since by the next morning, he
looked and sounded fine.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro-Valls tells reporters that when aides implore their boss
to take it easy, the pope retorts, ``I'll have all eternity to
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of the pope is respectful, a tribute to his position,
and also to his extraordinary personality and will power. But those
of us who work for mainstream, secular news organizations generally
focus on the broad political and social ramifications of this
pope's words and actions (as well as Vatican intrigue) more closely
than on his purely religious message. Many of the reporters in the
press corps, however, work for Catholic newspapers and magazines,
with inevitably different notions of what their readers need to
know and what they are likely to find interesting.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope was scolded in Poland last summer by the grand
rabbi of Warsaw, who called him ``pope'' and demanded that the
Catholic Church remove the last cross from Auschwitz, the
unscripted moment became a front page story for mainstream news
publications. But French and Italian religion reporters shrugged it
off as a ``provincial issue,'' and focused instead on the spiritual
significance of the Black Madonna of Czestochowa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-POPE-REPORTERS-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
(Repeating) &QL; 
 &UR; ROME: of Czestochowa. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bus chatter often varies along the same lines. Just as political
reporters give odds on primaries and polls, the papal pack
handicaps cardinals.  &UR;  &LR;  After a Mass in Austria attended by many
European cardinals, I recall sitting with Victor Simpson of the
Associated Press, weighing the papal chances of Cardinal Jean Marie
Lustiger, archbishop of Paris (too old, too brainy, too French but
a favorite long shot of the press corps because he is a convert.
The headlines would read, ``Conclave Selects First Jewish Pope.'')
 &UR;  &LR;  Behind us, Guillaume Goubert, the correspondent for the French
Catholic newspaper, La Croix, was deep in a theological debate with
Caroline Bouan, the correspondent for I. Media, another Catholic
publication.
</P>
<P>
   They, too, sometimes display a sense of worldliness. Asked by
ELCI, a French version of CNN, for commentary on the pope's sermon
on the Mount of Beatitudes, Goubert shrugged. ``OK, but it's a
little spi, '' he replied, using French slang for ``spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their publication, different nationalities have
different working styles. The Americans and Germans, true to type A
stereotype, attend every event, record every utterance, and
conscientiously deliver pool reports to their colleagues. The
Italian vaticanisti, who are close in spirit to British royal
watchers, rely more on their own richly intuitive insights and
unnamed sources in the Curia. They skip the Masses and reserve
their energy for uncovering the one good restaurant with decent
local wines.
</P>
<P>
   Most cardinals and bishops have limited experience talking to
reporters and, in chance encounters, sometimes speak quite freely.
During the pope's visit, Israeli officials were nervous about his
trip on Friday to the Sea of Galilee, which would force his
entourage _ and hundreds of Israeli security officers _ to work on
the Sabbath, offending Orthodox rabbis. The pope flew by helicopter
to Jerusalem that night. To spare Orthodox sensitivities, the
bishops, with the rest of the entourage, flew to Tel Aviv and then
traveled by car to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   As evening fell on Capernaum, where the pope was praying at the
ruins of the house that tradition says belonged to St. Peter, I
sidled up to two bishops and, remarking on the late hour, asked
them if they were worried about breaking the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, a local bishop, gave me a long look and replied,
``Funny, you don't look observant.'' They both laughed heartily.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
