<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stealing Each Other's Thunder &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One major-party presidential candidate proposed a
multibillion-dollar package of education reforms last week. The
other asserted that a 6-year-old Cuban boy, rescued offshore
Florida, should be made a permanent resident of the United States
and his father should be lured to the United States with a similar
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Which candidate was the Democrat, and which the Republican?
</P>
<P>
   At this early juncture of the general election campaign, Gov.
George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
nominees, are staking claims to positions that belie political
stereotypes. It was the Republican, Bush, who sought to make a
traditional Democratic issue, education, his own, by unveiling an
education plan that included a $5-billion proposal to fight
childhood illiteracy and a five-year, $2.9 billion initiative to
improve teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the Democrat, Gore, who, backing away from the
Clinton administration on one of the most politically sensitive
issues of the year, announced his belief that Elian Gonzalez should
be granted permanent residency status in the United States and that
his father should be offered the same, rather than leaving a return
to Cuba as the only way to reunite them.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's move so startled Democratic allies _ ``Oh my God, it's
unbelievable!'' declared one official _ that some, like Rep. Maxine
Waters of California, said that they might have to reconsider their
support for Gore. While some liberal Democrats said he was making
an irresponsible vote grab that played politics with a little boy's
emotional state, there was no denying how important those votes, in
the pivotal state of Florida, might be to him in November.
</P>
<P>
   In embracing these positions, Bush and Gore appeared to be
inching closer to each other ideologically: Gore, after all, has
also offered an education program, amounting to $115 billion in aid
over 10 years. And Bush has long been arguing that Elian's father
should leave Cuba and be with his son in the United States, rather
than having the boy sent back to Havana.
</P>
<P>
   And both found ways to demonstrate how in sync they are with the
popular Sen. John McCain. Included in Bush's education proposals,
for instance, was money for one of McCain's favored projects,
enlisting military retirees as teachers. Gore, meanwhile, announced
his desire to raise $7.1 billion as an endowment fund for the
underwriting of House and Senate races beginning in 2008, even if
he did acknowledge that he was ``an imperfect messenger'' for
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Art War Guns Fall Silent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it began last fall, it was the political equivalent of holy
war. New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani denounced the Brooklyn
Museum of Art's ``Sensation'' exhibit as sacrilege. The museum's
defenders denounced the mayor as an enemy of freedom. The mayor cut
off the museum's funding. The museum took the city to federal
court. For a while it looked as if neither would ever bend.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. This is New York, where politics (almost) always bends to
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Giuliani agreed to abandon his campaign against the
museum, which had provoked his notorious ire with its exhibition of
young British artists that featured a portrait of the Virgin Mary
adorned with elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   Under a settlement agreement, Giuliani dismissed his state
lawsuit seeking to remove the museum's board of directors and to
evict the museum from its city-owned building. The museum, in turn,
dropped its federal lawsuit, which accused Giuliani of violating
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, of course, Giuliani retained his right to call
the exhibition offensive and anti-Catholic, an ``abominable use of
public funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials took the settlement more quietly. ``We're
stronger,'' said Robert S. Rubin, the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN FEUER
</P>
<P>
   OPEC Votes to Raise Oil Production
</P>
<P>
   After one of its most raucous meetings in years, the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed to pump a
modest additional amount of oil, a move that should at least slow
the recent surge in oil and gasoline prices. Iran tried to rebel,
arguing that OPEC was caving in to political pressure from the
United States. But Saudi Arabia, the world's biggest producer by
far, ultimately forced it and all the other countries to raise
their official quotas by 1.7 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   That probably will not lead to a big reduction in prices; Saudi
Arabia is determined to keep prices at about $25 a barrel and will
cut production if prices slip much below that.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDMUND L. ANDREWS
</P>
<P>
   A Blow to Tobacco
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers had long relied on package warning labels as a
defense from lawsuits by smokers who claimed they were not told
about tobacco hazards. But a San Francisco jury ordered two
manufacturers to pay a total of $20 million in punitive damages to
a California woman who began smoking after strong warning labels
appeared in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   No New Syria-Israel Talks
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sat down with President Hafez Assad of Syria
in an effort to restart the Syrian-Israeli peace talks that broke
off in January. The effort failed, leaving it an open question when
the talks might resume.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was carrying proposals from Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel, but none of his own, when he and the Syrian leader met for
three hours in Geneva as Clinton was returning from a six-day tour
of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
