<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-ALEX-COMFORT-REVIEW     04-03 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ALEX-COMFORT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOY, THE CHAGRIN: SEX BECAME HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Alex Comfort, who died on March 26, personified the sort of
tweedy English intellectual who could gracefully range from subject
to subject. He was a physician, poet, novelist, anarchist, pacifist
and a leading researcher on how people age.
</P>
<P>
   But to millions of people around the world, Comfort, who was 80,
will be remembered only for his book, ``The Joy of Sex: A Gourmet
Guide to Lovemaking'' (Crown, 1972). To his considerable chagrin,
his 50 other books, ranging from medical textbooks to metaphysical
poetry, were totally eclipsed by the graphically illustrated sex
book he knocked out in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Burgess may have compared his intellect with Machiavelli
and Voltaire, but Comfort rued that he would never escape the
``albatross'' of his $3 million best seller. He feared he would
forever be Dr. Sex.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at his oeuvre, however, reveals a multifaceted mind. In
his 1945 novel, ``The Power House'' (Viking Press), he argues for
life over abstract ideas:
</P>
<P>
   ``The lunatics either desire you or fear you, and I do not know
which kills you more rapidly. Banners are waved in your face, guns
are thrust in your ribs, grinning flat-footed gangs of citizens,
all mouthing the same bilge, push you and threaten to educate you
by cutting your throat. People ask, what is the use of life to a
slave? That's bilge _ what's the use of freedom to a corpse?''
</P>
<P>
   His 1948 essay, ``The Novel and Our Time'' (Alan Swallow),
advanced the theory that writers use their art as a means of
liberation. The writer, he said, ``does not learn to write so that
he can `write,' but because without the necessary tools he cannot
dig his way out of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   His 1949 novel, ``On This Side of Nothing'' (Viking), addressed
the meaning of being a Jew: ``There was something unnatural in his
assumption that the ghetto would shelter him _ he was taking a good
deal too much for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had reached some conclusions of my own before that in
the earliest weeks of the siege, that Jews are not born, but made;
that everyone who runs, who disobeys, who prefers living to
obeying, is a Jew. Doesn't he carry his ghetto around with him, in
every country, at every time?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Comfort wrote ``Darwin and the Naked Lady'' (George
Braziller). He considered the relationship between Darwin and
Freud. ``Freud has had the greater effect on our understanding of
behavior, aesthetic behavior in particular, but Darwin provides the
groundwork for the understanding of Freud. We had better,
therefore, take them together.''
</P>
<P>
   As shown in his 1966 book, ``The Nature of Human Nature''
(Harper &AMP; Row), he did not believe in sugarcoating hard truths. ``
`Hell,' said a Sartre character, `is other people.' It can also be
ourselves. Man is the only animal which is inherently able,
corporately and individually, to be his own worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally dark was his view of old age, as presented in ``A Good
Age'' (Crown, 1976). At retirement age, he commented that people
are ``rendered unemployed, useless and, in some cases,
impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that transition, and in proportion to their
chronological age, they are prescribed to be unintelligent,
unemployable, crazy and asexual.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Sex? ``In the days of formal dancing one used to wish
that the girl had her breasts on her back where one could reach
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dr. Alex Comfort was more than that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
