<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-SCHOOL-INTEGRATION-     04-03 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCHOOL-INTEGRATION-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOST PROMISE OF SCHOOL INTEGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By JEFFREY ROSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, nearly half a century after the Supreme Court ruled that
school segregation was unconstitutional, are efforts to achieve
racially integrated public schools legally and politically doomed?
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Supreme Court let stand a decision by a
federal appeals court, which held that school authorities in
Montgomery County, Md., violated the Constitution when they tried
to prevent a white student from transferring to a magnet school
from his neighborhood elementary school, which is predominantly
black.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County case is only the latest in a series of
decisions, going back several years, that are making it hard for
public schools to maintain even a semblance of racial diversity in
a judicial and political climate that exalts choice above all other
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't reconcile choice with diversity, and that's the
tragedy,'' says Samuel Issacharoff of Columbia Law School, a
leading scholar of desegregation. ``Fifty years after Brown vs.
Board of Education, there is still no non-coercive mechanism for
racial integration that has evolved in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   That unanimous 1954 Supreme Court decision became famous for the
phrase, ``Separate educational facilities are inherently unequal.''
Less well-remembered is the opinion's insistence that education
itself is ``the very foundation of good citizenship ... the
principal instrument in awakening the child to cultural values.''
</P>
<P>
   In the court's view, educating children of different races
together was key to the crucial project of creating a society less
divided by race. But the era when courts were willing to force
integration through mandatory busing ended in the mid-1990s. Now,
judges and parents are questioning the constitutionality and value
of programs that try to create racially balanced schools without
busing, by restricting who can go to school where. Indeed, based on
a pattern of rulings in recent years, the Supreme Court may be on
the verge of holding this as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in judicial and public opinion may mean that the
central premise of the Brown decision _ that integrated public
schools are the most important institution in a pluralistic society
_ will not survive the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Montgomery County case. White enrollment at the
Glen Haven elementary school in Montgomery County dropped from 40
percent in 1995 to 24 percent in 1998, although the county as a
whole is 53 percent white. In an effort to stop the rapid decline,
the county adopted a policy that no student could transfer out of a
school if the transfer would adversely affect racial diversity,
unless he or she could prove some kind of ``unique personal
hardship.'' In striking down this policy, the 4th Circuit U.S.
Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va., concluded that the Constitution
prohibits ``racial balancing'' from being used as the decisive
factor in school assignments.
</P>
<P>
   This is a straightforward application of years of Supreme Court
decisions restricting the use of race to distribute government
benefits. But those decisions have left surprisingly few
alternatives open to school districts that value integration. In
the early 1980s, many districts began to abandon futile efforts to
integrate neighborhood schools and instead set up magnet schools in
the hope of attracting a diverse group of applicants from the
entire school district. But using random lotteries to determine
admission to oversubscribed magnet schools often fails to produce
racial balance. For this reason, a magnet school in Arlington
County, Virginia, recently adopted a weighted lottery system,
giving preferences to minority students. Last year, the Court of
Appeals struck down the weighted lottery on the same grounds it had
invoked in the Montgomery County case: in school admissions, racial
balancing is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Academically competitive exam schools have had no more luck in
adopting explicit racial and ethnic admissions goals. In recent
cases, the Boston Latin School in Massachusetts and Lowell High
School in San Francisco, were forced to abandon their racial
admissions targets. In response, Lowell set aside 20 percent of its
class for applicants who met the minimum test score cut-off but had
suffered from socioeconomic disadvantage. This system allowed the
school to admit disadvantaged white and Asian students, but
produced few African-Americans and Hispanics. The handful of
successful efforts to achieve integration in school districts as a
whole are now in legal jeopardy. Cambridge, Mass., has designed a
program called ``controlled choice,'' in which all schools are open
to everyone regardless of where they live, and parents rank the
schools in order of preference. But each school must have a
balanced racial mix. If the Supreme Court ultimately decides that
racial integration for its own sake can't justify race-based
admissions policies, then ``controlled choice'' programs like the
one in Cambridge may be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any school district that is doing anything around these issues
of promoting diversity is feeling vulnerable right now,'' says Amy
Stuart Wells, a professor of education at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-SCHOOL-INTEGRATION-     04-03 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCHOOL-INTEGRATION-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOST PROMISE OF SCHOOL INTEGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By JEFFREY ROSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, nearly half a century after the Supreme Court ruled that
school segregation was unconstitutional, are efforts to achieve
racially integrated public schools legally and politically doomed?
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Supreme Court let stand a decision by a
federal appeals court, which held that school authorities in
Montgomery County, Md., violated the Constitution when they tried
to prevent a white student from transferring to a magnet school
from his neighborhood elementary school, which is predominantly
black.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County case is only the latest in a series of
decisions, going back several years, that are making it hard for
public schools to maintain even a semblance of racial diversity in
a judicial and political climate that exalts choice above all other
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't reconcile choice with diversity, and that's the
tragedy,'' says Samuel Issacharoff of Columbia Law School, a
leading scholar of desegregation. ``Fifty years after Brown vs.
Board of Education, there is still no non-coercive mechanism for
racial integration that has evolved in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   That unanimous 1954 Supreme Court decision became famous for the
phrase, ``Separate educational facilities are inherently unequal.''
Less well-remembered is the opinion's insistence that education
itself is ``the very foundation of good citizenship ... the
principal instrument in awakening the child to cultural values.''
</P>
<P>
   In the court's view, educating children of different races
together was key to the crucial project of creating a society less
divided by race. But the era when courts were willing to force
integration through mandatory busing ended in the mid-1990s. Now,
judges and parents are questioning the constitutionality and value
of programs that try to create racially balanced schools without
busing, by restricting who can go to school where. Indeed, based on
a pattern of rulings in recent years, the Supreme Court may be on
the verge of holding this as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in judicial and public opinion may mean that the
central premise of the Brown decision _ that integrated public
schools are the most important institution in a pluralistic society
_ will not survive the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Montgomery County case. White enrollment at the
Glen Haven elementary school in Montgomery County dropped from 40
percent in 1995 to 24 percent in 1998, although the county as a
whole is 53 percent white. In an effort to stop the rapid decline,
the county adopted a policy that no student could transfer out of a
school if the transfer would adversely affect racial diversity,
unless he or she could prove some kind of ``unique personal
hardship.'' In striking down this policy, the 4th Circuit U.S.
Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va., concluded that the Constitution
prohibits ``racial balancing'' from being used as the decisive
factor in school assignments.
</P>
<P>
   This is a straightforward application of years of Supreme Court
decisions restricting the use of race to distribute government
benefits. But those decisions have left surprisingly few
alternatives open to school districts that value integration. In
the early 1980s, many districts began to abandon futile efforts to
integrate neighborhood schools and instead set up magnet schools in
the hope of attracting a diverse group of applicants from the
entire school district. But using random lotteries to determine
admission to oversubscribed magnet schools often fails to produce
racial balance. For this reason, a magnet school in Arlington
County, Virginia, recently adopted a weighted lottery system,
giving preferences to minority students. Last year, the Court of
Appeals struck down the weighted lottery on the same grounds it had
invoked in the Montgomery County case: in school admissions, racial
balancing is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Academically competitive exam schools have had no more luck in
adopting explicit racial and ethnic admissions goals. In recent
cases, the Boston Latin School in Massachusetts and Lowell High
School in San Francisco, were forced to abandon their racial
admissions targets. In response, Lowell set aside 20 percent of its
class for applicants who met the minimum test score cut-off but had
suffered from socioeconomic disadvantage. This system allowed the
school to admit disadvantaged white and Asian students, but
produced few African-Americans and Hispanics. The handful of
successful efforts to achieve integration in school districts as a
whole are now in legal jeopardy. Cambridge, Mass., has designed a
program called ``controlled choice,'' in which all schools are open
to everyone regardless of where they live, and parents rank the
schools in order of preference. But each school must have a
balanced racial mix. If the Supreme Court ultimately decides that
racial integration for its own sake can't justify race-based
admissions policies, then ``controlled choice'' programs like the
one in Cambridge may be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any school district that is doing anything around these issues
of promoting diversity is feeling vulnerable right now,'' says Amy
Stuart Wells, a professor of education at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the new era, only strategies that entice parental choice,
rather than control it, can clearly pass constitutional muster. But
in an age when political support for integration is declining,
these strategies face an uphill battle. Some districts, for
example, have increased financing for inner-city schools on a
field-of-dreams theory: If you improve the schools, white students
will come. But the most visible example of this approach, in Kansas
City, was a notable failure. Under court order, the city spent
nearly $200 million to build a state-of-the-art magnet school. The
white students failed to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Choice plans that allow black parents to send their children to
white suburban schools have had similarly mixed success. Twenty
states have open enrollment laws that allow children to transfer
from district to district. But because few of these states provide
for subsidized transportation to the suburbs, many black parents
are unable to avail themselves of the opportunity. St. Louis, by
contrast, was forced by court order to provide subsidized
transportation for children from the inner city to attend 16
suburban school districts. Thirteen thousand children have accepted
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents make their decisions on the basis not of ideology but
on whatever they think will advance the education of their
children, and they will choose desegregation whenever it's a viable
option,'' says William Taylor, a veteran desegregation attorney who
represented the plaintiffs in the St. Louis case.
</P>
<P>
   The experience in St. Louis shows that money is necessary to
allow poor parents the same opportunities to escape failing inner
city schools as richer parents enjoy. This, perhaps, accounts for
the growing support among minorities for school vouchers. Professor
Jay Greene of the University of Texas at Austin contends that in
cities that have adopted voucher programs, the voucher schools tend
to be more racially integrated than the public schools. Nearly a
fifth of voucher recipients in Cleveland attend private schools
that reflect the racial composition of the city as a whole, Greene
notes, while only 5.2 percent of Cleveland public school students
are in comparably integrated schools.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas, a strong supporter of vouchers, has
become the leading national advocate for the view that racial
diversity is ultimately less important than ensuring a genuinely
equal education for African-American children. ``It never ceases to
amaze me that the courts are so willing to assume that anything
that is predominantly black must be inferior,'' Thomas wrote in a
1995 decision criticizing the district court's decision to convert
Kansas City into a magnet district.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to choose between racial diversity and educational
quality, most African-American parents seem to agree with Thomas.
In a 1998 survey of 800 white parents and 800 black parents
conducted by Public Agenda, 82 percent of the black parents said
that raising academic standards was more important than achieving
more diversity and integration.
</P>
<P>
   These overwhelming numbers do not, however, capture the full
complexity and ambivalence of the views of white and black parents
about the value of integration. In the same poll, 80 percent of
black parents and 66 percent of white parents said it was ``very
important'' or ``somewhat important'' to them that their own
children attend an integrated school. Only those without the means
to choose an education that is both integrated and adequate are
willing to settle for quality.
</P>
<P>
   With idealism that, in retrospect, seems poignant, the Brown
decision assumed that the removal of state-enforced segregation
would be enough to integrate schools around the country. In the
North and the South, that view proved to be naive and untenable.
But now that legal and political tolerance for even mildly coercive
forms of integration appears to be evaporating, the hope of
integrated public schools may soon be a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the final frontier,'' says David Goldberg of the NAACP
Legal Defense and Education Fund. ``If the Supreme Court decides
that there's no compelling interest in educational diversity, then
the basic premise of Brown will have been repudiated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0120 </DOCNO>
