<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ABBY-COHEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GURU CONQUERS WALL STREET. NEXT, THE WORLD? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never underestimate the power of Abby Joseph Cohen.
Last week, a warning about stock prices from Cohen, the formidable
chief investment strategist for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.,
singlehandedly caused a broad sell-off in markets worldwide. It
left even the most seasoned traders quivering. ``When she speaks,
markets move,'' one marveled to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   And not just markets. While Cohen has been ubiquitous on Wall
Street, the rest of the world is badly in need of her guidance. But
all that just might change in the months to come if Cohen expands
her spheres of influence. Here's a scenario as played out in a
series of news items:
</P>
<P>
   April 20, 2000 _ Steven Spielberg surprised Hollywood today when
he announced he was dropping plans to develop ``Minority Report,''
a science-fiction thriller set to star Tom Cruise, after the
Goldman, Sachs stock market seer Abby Joseph Cohen told Spielberg
that she believed the highly anticipated film would be a flop. ``I
thought we had a solid script, and Tom is usually bankable,'' he
said, ``but I couldn't take a chance after Abby gave the project a
thumbs down.'' An obviously disappointed Spielberg said, ``I'm
hoping she likes the sequel to `Saving Private Ryan' better.''
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 2000 _ Teen pregnancy rates dropped by nearly one-third
in 1999, to the lowest level in four decades, federal health
officials said yesterday. The National Center for Health Statistics
attributed the encouraging trend, which spanned all racial and
ethnic groups, to the ``Abby Says No'' teen abstinence campaign
featuring the stock market strategist Abby Joseph Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody touches kids like Abby,'' said Donna E. Shalala,
secretary of health and human services. ``Not Britney Spears, not
the Backstreet Boys, no one. She's been so right on the market for
so long that she has what the kids call `cred,' and you can't fake
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey, director of the Office
of National Drug Control Policy, has asked Cohen for the chance to
expand ``Abby Says No'' to its anti-drug campaigns. ``Let's be
honest, those ads with the heroin addicts are getting old,'' said
General McCaffrey. ``We're looking for something a little more
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   July 20, 2000 _ Abby Joseph Cohen took home the top prize at the
World Series of Poker yesterday, winning $1.1 million after
defeating a field of more than 400 of the world's best poker
players. Cohen vanquished her final opponent, poker veteran Huck
Seed, with an ace-high flush, topping Seed's straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no chance,'' he said. ``It was like she could read my
mind!'' The always-modest Cohen attributed her victory mainly to
luck and said she had never played poker before entering the
tournament. ``I signed up mainly because I always wanted to see Las
Vegas,'' Cohen said. ``It's pretty neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5, 2000 _ ``China and Taiwan will announce today that they
have ended more than a half-century of hostility and agreed in
principle to reunify as one nation by the end of the year, sources
close to the talks said late last night. The shocking deal comes
only days after Goldman, Sachs strategist Abby Joseph Cohen quietly
offered top Chinese and Taiwanese officials a white paper that
predicted stock markets in both countries could fall as much as 90
percent in the event of a Chinese attempt to take Taiwan by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abby found the issue that resonates with the leaders of both
sides when she showed them just how much money a war would cost
them,'' said one American diplomat about the talks, which are being
held at Goldman, Sachs headquarters in New York City. ``She
deserves the Nobel Prize for this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 8, 2000 _ New York voters soundly rejected both New York
City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton yesterday, instead choosing Abby Joseph Cohen as New York's
newest senator. With 98 percent of precincts reporting late
Tuesday, Cohen, whose name was not listed on the ballot and who did
not campaign, had more than 63 percent of the vote, while Giuliani
and Clinton were locked in a virtual dead heat for second place
with 18 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   After word of Cohen's unexpected triumph was announced
yesterday, New Yorkers statewide rushed into the streets to
rejoice, creating an impromptu block party that stretched from
Buffalo to Montauk. ``I'm so glad it's Abby,'' said Gov. George E.
Pataki of Albany. ``Hillary and Rudy, Rudy and Hillary _ you've
gotta be kidding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
