<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reading about the Light Party makes you want to drink a beer
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ When I first looked at the brouchure for the
Light Party, I wasn't sure if I was reading about a political
movement or a place I could go to get drunk on low-calorie beer.
</P>
<P>
   I've decided that it was, in a sense, about both things, a
political party that is less filling and tastes great.
</P>
<P>
   The brochure says the party is a synthesis of the Republican,
Democratic, Libertarian and Green Parties ``a proactive, wholistic,
education, empowerment party.''
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   So I can see right away where the Democrats, Libertarians and
Greens come in (goofy, wacky and weird), but I had to read a little
further to figure out the Republican connection.
</P>
<P>
   Aha! You have to pay $33 to join.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for that money, you get the party's comprehensive
networking and resource guide, the human ecology program and an
Artainment music video. Wow. Not only are these guys part
Republicans, they are part televangelists, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Light Party was founded by a fellow who calls himself Da
Vid, M.D. If you're like me, you did a quick check to make sure he
wasn't on the list of doctors affiliated with your HMO.
</P>
<P>
   You can actually find a long (he calls it brief, but trust me,
it is long) biography of Da Vid on the Internet. The operative
sentence in all of it is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer of 1972 a transformative event of the first
magnitude took place for me _ an event that forever changed my life
... I took my my first LSD trip _ and what a trip it was!''
</P>
<P>
   At least with Da Vid, who is a candidate for president, we don't
have to worry about whether he inhaled or not. The question is: Did
he ever exhale?
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps you wonder what the Lights want other than free love
beads for everyone. For one thing, they believe in an amendment for
national initiative and referendum, which is a Libertarian idea.
They also believe in global peace and health, though when I went to
see how Da Vid wants to bring about this health, there is no real
idea, just about 2,000 Internet links.
</P>
<P>
   A clearer clue to what the Lights are all about comes in their
19 political action alerts.
</P>
<P>
   It probably will come as no surprise to you that Da Vid and the
gang are keenly interested in stopping the war on drugs. When it
does end, they are gonna have a heck of a victory party.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more interesting ideas, they promoted Jan. 1,
2000, as a day without any violence in any prison on Earth _ no
fights, no stabbings, no incidents of any kind. Hmmm, I wonder if
it worked?
</P>
<P>
   When you get to the part where it says how you could help
achieve this, the first item is ``SEND MONEY.'' (There goes that
Republican/televangelist connection again). I suppose maybe we
could have bribed all the criminals on Earth to play nice for one
day.
</P>
<P>
   The party's other hot points include gun control, opposition to
the death penalty, saving the rain forest, banning all nuclear
weapons and freeing Leonard Peltier.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite plank in the Light platform _ oops, better not call
them planks, they don't believe in cutting down trees _ is the Save
the Whales program.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't just saving the whales as in keeping them from
being harpooned by fishermen, this is Save the Whales from Low
Frequency Active Sonar. We want to make sure the whales don't get a
headache.
</P>
<P>
   At the Light Party Web site, they have a long section on
prophecy which I'm assuming Da Vid came about during one of his
wonderful experiences with LSD. Again, one sentence will be enough:
</P>
<P>
   ``In another grand astronomical event, our whole solar system is
intersecting a photon belt (zone of light and higher consciousness)
in its grand cycle around the Pleiades. In fulfillment of prophecy,
cycles within cycles are culminating together as we rapidly evolve
into The Eternal Here and Now (the Fifth Dimension).''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes you long for Ross Perot, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
