<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ban on flag burning would dissolve rights for which founders
fought
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Given a choice, few Americans would live in a
country where people were arrested for expressing opinions banned
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   This nation's guaranteed individual liberties have limited the
number of citizens who support the police-state practices of
governments operated by dictators, communists or fascists.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, one of America's greatest strengths has been
the freedom of its citizens to express their opinions on any
subject, no matter how odious those opinions may be to government
officials or other citizens.
</P>
<P>
   This freedom was granted to Americans by the nation's founders
who waged a long and bitter war to overthrow a government that
arrested citizens who dared express banned opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The Founding Fathers knew exactly what they were doing when they
prominently included certain individual freedoms in the Bill of
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress shall make no law,'' wrote James Madison, that
abridges the freedom of speech, the freedom of the press, the
freedom of citizens to practice their chosen religions or other
listed and implied freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   These hard-won individual freedoms, often taken for granted by
citizens today, were upfront and personal to the men and women who
suffered under a government that criminalized unapproved speech,
religion or publications.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, these individual freedoms have been
responsible for launching and maintaining the world's
longest-running and freest democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens cannot be truly free unless they can express opinions
in opposition to the government and its symbols without fear of
arrest or punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, for the fourth time in 11 years, Congress members
have attempted to ban a form of speech they don't like. That's a
shame.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how ugly the speech, it's far worse for Congress to
make a law that abridges the public's free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Constitution forbids Congress from making laws that
abridge constitutional rights, Congress members are trying to
change the U.S. Constitution with an amendment that allows them to
ban burning the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that burning the national flag is an
expression of speech. It is a repulsive form of speech for
Americans who believe in the freedoms and principles of this
nation. Nevertheless, it's still speech.
</P>
<P>
   If flag burning were not speech, there would be no need to pass
a constitutional amendment that gives Congress the right to pass a
law that abridges speech.
</P>
<P>
   Flag burning is rare. When it is done, the perpetrators are
making a statement that expresses their opinion about this nation.
The U.S. Supreme Court has twice held flag burning as protected
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, burning the flag is not what outrages so many
Americans, even though there were only 45 documented cases of
malicious flag burning between 1777 and 1989. Burning is the
accepted method for disposing of the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress and the American public ever passed a constitutional
amendment that outlawed desecration of the American flag, the
government would have to determine what the flag-burner was
thinking and what message he intended to communicate when he put
the match to the flag.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of having government thought-police arresting citizens
for expressing unacceptable opinions would be a grievous erosion of
this nation's freedoms. It would make America's founders heartsick.
</P>
<P>
   The flag is a symbol of this nation's freedoms. Abridging those
freedoms to protect the symbol weakens the symbol. In other words,
it desecrates the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
