<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looks as good as it sounds
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You want to look good while listening to your
tunes. That's why you need to pick up Sony's Street Style Discman
($160, www.sony.
</P>
<P>
   com). The industrial-looking Discman is a must-have for the
trendy, on-the-go set. The device is finished in chrome and red
translucent plastic and has a carrying strap, making it the
ultimate accoutrement to a rollerblading escapade. The Street Style
Discman also comes with Street Style headphones, which wrap around
the back of the head and provide awesome sound. If you think this
portable CD player just looks good, think again. This Discman is
equipped with Sony's patented ESP2, which is some of the best skip
protection on the market. With ESP2 and the Street Style Discman,
you'll never miss a beat _ and look good in the process.
</P>
<P>
   THIS'LL HELP YOU GET A GRIP
</P>
<P>
   Touted as the PlayStation's ``first Mini Wheel that rumbles as
you drive,'' Madcatz's Hand Held Racing Wheel ($35;
www.madcatz.com) combines smooth analog steering and lots of
digital action buttons in an innovative compact design and is
endorsed, of course, by Madcatz spokesman and racing legend Mario
Andretti. While the unit is terribly comfortable with its ergonomic
pistol-grip shape and side-mounted, firm and responsive little
wheel conveying healthful resistance, button configuration leaves a
little to be desired, especially for games that require/demand
simultaneous application of throttle and brake and a gear change or
three. Still, a great vibrating RC style wheel/controller for
straightforward, pedal-to-the-medal racing games such as NASCAR,
FI, Motocross or Superbike _ and it's just a peach with GT
Interactive's Driver _ but rally games just aren't attuned to this
particular design.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
