<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All dressed up with nowhere to go
 &HT;    By Joe Stafford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The first test of a CD-ROM for children is
really about ease of use: Can you install it, set your child in
front of it and walk away, confident that the software will do the
rest? Unfortunately, that standard is beyond The American Girls
Dress Designer ($30 for Windows, www.mattelmedia.com) _ one of
woefully few programs aimed at pre-teen girls _ which is limited in
scope, yet difficult to use. On the positive side, the program lets
girls pick and create fabric patterns, colors and other trim for
finishing touches on clothes that can be printed out and used on
paper dolls of girls throughout American history. The artwork is of
a high standard, but our 8-year-old tester quickly got frustrated
with the program's limitations on her imagination: With too few
options toward the stated purpose of actually designing clothes,
she quickly lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
