A5444 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-GAMER0404-COX     04-03 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zombie Revenge a raw shooting spree lacking depth
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Raw and unassuming gameplay makes Sega's Zombie Revenge ($40;
www.dreamcast.com) a near-brainless third-person romp through
innumerable levels plagued by the undead. A thin, post
apocalyptic/secret-experiment-gone-awry story stands as the premise
behind nonstop shooting of rampaging rotting corpses. Terrific
graphics and intuitive control makes for a fast-paced, auto-aiming
killing spree replete with health grabs, power-ups and various
high- and low-tech weapons of mass-dismemberment pick-ups.
Surprisingly addictive in spite of its lack of depth, Zombie
Revenge works as a tremendous stress reliever without all the
inherent guilt of amoral behavior. After all, these aren't
simulated people splooshing and splattering, glorping and gooing
all over the TV screen; they're zombies, and zombies aren't real.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Flight sim fans want tons of the eye candy but they also want
the tiny details done right. On both counts, Jane's F/A-18A
Simulator ($40 for the PC, www.ea.com) further builds the sim
maker's reputation as the real deal with what might be the best
military flight sim yet. From the instructive, fun tutorials to the
massive campaign options, from the fabulously detailed cockpit to
the lush terrain below, Jane's has focused on a single aircraft and
gotten everything right. A white-knuckle landing in bad weather on
a carrier deck is unforgettable, and with great multiplayer
options, there's very little here to criticize. The game runs great
even on a modestly powerful machine, and many options are available
to customize the difficulty settings, so that this game, crafted
with hard-core simmers in mind, is not beyond the reach of the
casual desktop pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
