<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball was never this easy
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're a baseball fan, you've been there. It's late
in the game and the coach can't seem to pull the starting pitcher,
who's getting shelled. Or maybe it's August, the left fielder is
starting to wilt and the coach won't bench him for a few games to
get his strength back.
</P>
<P>
   The cure for all this, other than starting an Internet company,
selling it in 18 months and then buying your own team, is fantasy
baseball. The Internet version.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Web, fantasy baseball required effort. Here's how it
works: A group of people form a league, pick teams and hold a draft
to divide the best major league players. Eight to 12 teams per
league are recommended. Any less packs teams with all-stars. More
makes each team the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Teams earn points based on how well their players perform. The
everyday players are ranked using their offensive statistics: team
batting average, home runs, runs batted in and stolen bases.
Pitchers earn points by team earned run average, wins, saves and
team WHIP ratio (walks plus hits, divided by the number of innings
pitched).
</P>
<P>
   In the pencil and paper days, that meant a lot of record
keeping, tons of stat-checking and some serious math. Hardly tasks
fit for a sports mogul.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Web sites offer free fantasy baseball leagues; most
do the math for you.
</P>
<P>
   Owners can check their team performances each day, and the
previous day's performance already will have been factored in. It
reduces fantasy baseball to the relative joy of dialing up
Yahoo.com to check your stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   That frees you to do the real work of the owner _ making trades,
firing coaches and angling for taxpayer-subsidized stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is loaded with fantasy sports sites. A quick search
last week on Google.com, one of the Web's best search engines,
found 17,900 fantasy baseball entries in less than two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasybaseballcentral.com is as thorough a place as any to
start. It divides links to fantasy baseball-related sites by
category.
</P>
<P>
   DRAFT ADVICE:
</P>
