<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    End Task with care
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   When I hit Ctrl-Alt-Del, the screen shows a list of running
programs, many of which I don't recognize. For example: Explorer,
NsDee32, Realplay, Osa, Tsystray, Rundll, Systray, Aim, Imgicon.
Are these necessary? Should I End Task on each of them or just
ignore? Can, or should, they be deleted? Do they affect the speed
of my computer?
</P>
<P>
   _Larry Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   Sue: On Windows 95/98 machines, any time you do a
Ctrl-Alt-Delete to reboot your computer, the Task Manager will come
up. It's a list of all running applications, some system-critical.
It manages the applications that are activated and working and
those no longer responding. If you don't know what an item is
(because it may be a system app), do not End Task.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Be careful. System apps make your computer go.
``End-Tasking'' them won't speed it up.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I made the mistake of letting my kids play games on my Macintosh
Powerbook G3. They changed my password, and neither of them can
remember what they used. Can I access the computer to restore or
change my password without losing data? I called a couple of
dealers, and they want to charge me too much.
</P>
<P>
   _Keith W. Allen Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Ah, it seems you are now the proud owner of an expensive
paperweight.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: No, Sue's making a funny. All is not lost. We checked
with Apple Tech Support and found that, unless you want to
initialize your hard drive, you must take your Powerbook and
receipt to an Apple dealer to have the password reset without
losing data. If your computer is under warranty, you may not have
to shell out anything.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: If you really want to do this yourself, initializing is the
only way. Apparently, the password is written to the driver level.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I lost the basic toolbar in Microsoft Word. I can't see the
File, Edit, Tool, maximum, minimum or the ``X'' to close the
window. They are off the screen. This happens only in Word. I have
Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   _Anthony Kuchta
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Let's start simple. Did you accidentally move the Menu
Toolbar to the side, or is it now a floating menu? Is it minimized
into the menu bar at the bottom of your screen? This is easy to do
and can cause some confusion. I've been there. You also should go
to Toolbars under the View Menu and select Customize. Is Menu Bar
selected? If not, put a check in the box.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Also, it could be a deeper issue. Have you installed
software lately? We've seen software conflicts that cause menus to
get wiggy. Try reinstalling Microsoft Word. Nine times out of 10,
it'll do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
