<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring is in the air, and it's time for a little low-tech
cleaning
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's spring and the automated birds outside of
TechnoBuddy Ranch are singing, the trees are fringed with green and
the pollen has me and Buddy the Maine Coon Cat both sneezing. And,
me being a traditional sort of a guy, it's spring cleaning time at
my house.
</P>
<P>
   That means that I'll have to set off a small nuclear device to
clean out the basement and also identify some of the objects that
the cat has placed under the beds and couches. But, for my
computers, it's also spring cleaning time. The truth is that it's a
really low-tech way to make sure that the computer has a chance of
lasting through spring into next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Dust and dirt builds up inside a computer. And unlike the
dustballs under your bed, this dust can literally kill your
computer. The good thing about this problem is that it's one you
can fix, even if most technical things leave you flustered.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have to warn you. This does involve taking the top off
your computer.
</P>
<P>
   But we'll go in easy stages, so that you can do the chores that
feel comfortable to you and just ignore those that make you feel
quivery inside.
</P>
<P>
   So let's leave the screwdriver alone for a moment and clean your
mouse. It's easy and my guess is that you'll notice the difference
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Just remove the retaining ring that holds in the little rubber
ball and take a look at the rollers inside the mouse. Use a cotton
swab, moistened with alcohol, to remove the dirt. Hold the mouse
upright, while you do this, so that any trash inside falls out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's do another easy chore. Clean the monitor's screen
(you're going to be surprised at the amount of dirt you find) using
either special screen cleaning pads available at the computer
store, or just a small amount of glass cleaner sprayed on a paper
towel.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is a little steeper, but I promise that you can do
it. We need to open up the computer for this one. Since not all
computer cases work the same way, you'll either need to figure it
out by looking, or dig out the manual.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid doing any harm, make sure that you don't touch anything
inside before you discharge any static electricity you may have
accumulated. You can do that by either buying a ``grounding strap''
which is a weird little gizmo that you wear on your hand, or you
can just make sure and touch the chassis before touching anything
inside the computer.
</P>
<P>
   You'll want to unplug the computer, of course (although
professionals usually work inside with the computer plugged in, but
for mere mortals it's important to unplug the PC). Now find the
cooling fan toward the rear of your computer. Check to make sure
that it is free of dust and dirt. The fan keeps your computer cool
(a processor chip, while the computer is running, generates enough
heat to make popcorn). Since heat can age or even destroy
components, you need to make sure the fan is running correctly. And
anything that blocks the exhaust fan contributes to heat buildup.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to inspect the rest of the inside of the
computer, especially the main circuitboard called the motherboard.
Dust and dirt on the board can literally conduct enough electricity
to cause a short circuit. I once recommended that people use
compressed air to blow away the dust, or even a small hand vacuum
to clean it away (without letting the vacuum touch the components).
But since this is for beginners and since a mistake can do more
harm than the dust, I think I'll just recommend that you check for
excessive dirt and _ if you find it _ to get a professional to
clean the inside of the case for you.
</P>
<P>
   That's it for today. Spring cleaning is over. Now you can
perform the last ceremonial spring task. And that's to have some
spring tonic. I favor ice tea on the deck where I can watch the
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
