<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAIN WRECK
</P>
<P>
   Clues to school bus tragedy
</P>
<P>
   What caused a school bus to collide with a train last week?
</P>
<P>
   Officials are investigating the crash that killed three
elementary school students and injured four. It occurred near the
Georgia-Tennessee line. It was the worst train-bus crash involving
Georgians since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   A 33-car freight train slammed into the Murray County school bus
and dragged part of it down the track.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the school bus driver did not stop at the unguarded
rural railroad crossing, federal officials say. The AM/FM radio was
on, too, and people were talking, they say. Investigators aren't
sure if the noise could have prevented the bus driver from hearing
the train's whistle. Trees along the track may have prevented the
driver from seeing the train, they say.The investigation was
continuing .
</P>
<P>
   CUSTODY
</P>
<P>
   Will Elian's father arrive?
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez's father last week asked to visit the United
States and stay until a U.S. appeals court decides whether the
6-year-old should remain with relatives in Miami or return to Cuba
with his father. The father has been fighting for the boy's return
for months.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear when the father would arrive in America.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Elian was found clinging to a raft off the coast of
Florida. His mother had drowned bringing him to the United States
from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials meeting with Elian's Miami relatives want them to
agree to turn the boy over to his father if the appeals court
decides Elian should leave. So far, the family hasn't agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Vice President Al Gore urged Congress to pass
legislation allowing all of Elian's relatives in Cuba to come to
the United States and live here permanently.
</P>
<P>
   _ From news service
</P>
<P>
   MORE OIL
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices may drop
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) agreed
last week to raise oil production.
</P>
<P>
   That should cause the price of oil to drop. Because gasoline is
made from oil, its price also should drop.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 11 nations that are OPEC members have agreed to
increase production by 1.45 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton expects the price of gas to drop
</P>
<P>
   11 to 18 cents a gallon by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Volcano blows its top
</P>
<P>
   KOJI SASAHARA / Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   After threatening mountainside villages for four days, Mount Usu
erupted last week in Japan. It spewed a mixture of rock, gas and
ash over the snowy countryside. Experts had predicted the eruption
because of increased shaking of the earth. More than 11,000 people
had to leave their homes. As of Friday, there were no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Experts had predicted the eruption because of increased seismic
activity that began earlier this week. The evacuation of more than
11,000 people began Wednesday. Kikuya said that there were no
injuries reported in Date.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most eruption-prone countries, with
86 active volcanoes.
</P>
