<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get wired without a PC
 &HT;    By Mary Jo DiLonardo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Want to check your e-mail but don't have time to fire
up the computer? Check it on your cell phone or from the dashboard
of your car.
</P>
<P>
   Need some sports scores but left your laptop in your trunk?
Punch a few buttons on your Web wristwatch and you're online in
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   With the escalating consumer clamor for easy e-mail and
user-friendly online access, technology companies have been racing
to develop more and more methods for connecting to the Web without
a clunky computer. These new gadgets are appealing to two markets:
Techno-savvy users who want on-the-go Internet and people
uncomfortable with PCs who just want a taste of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``As computers become easier to use, there's still some level of
technology that's beyond most people,'' says Scott Testa with
Mindbridge.com, a company that creates Web-based software.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want simple devices that don't do everything but do two
or three simple tasks very easily,'' says Testa. ``You're going to
see the computer, the TV, the telephone morph into these devices. A
typical house may have one computer, one of these appliances and a
TV with Net access.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Consumer Electronics Association's International Show in
Las Vegas in early January, the products that generated the most
oohs and aahs were these so-called Internet appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an explosion in these kinds of devices,'' says
CEA's Jeff Joseph. ``More and more people want Web access without
having to be tied to a desktop computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``best of show'' honors went to InfoGear's iPhone, a $399
gadget complete with a touch screen, keyboard and software that
lets users communicate by phone and e-mail, and access the Internet
_ including both banking and shopping online.
</P>
<P>
   The iPhone has been around since 1998 but has gone through a
half-dozen upgrades since then, based on customer feedback.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these new Net appliances are geared toward the
techno-shy. Products like MailStation ($99.95 and up) and MailBug
($129.95) are countertop devices that let you have e-mail without
the price and complexity of a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that there are so many folks who are so intimidated
by PCs. They want e-mail but have no need or interest in learning
how to operate a PC,'' says MailBug's Bryan McCormick. He quotes
statistics: 50 percent of American households don't have a PC, but
93 percent have a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think e-mail should be as ubiquitous as the telephone, and
it will never happen if it's dependent on something as complicated
as a computer,'' says McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   Another device generating a lot of buzz is the i-opener from
Netpliance. Resembling a slimmed-down computer, the device offers
easy e-mail and Internet access with a flat-panel screen and
keyboard. Retailing at $199, the i-opener promises to be up and
working within five minutes after it arrives at your door.
</P>
<P>
   For James Bond types, Casio even offers a wristwatch that lets
you exchange data with your PC.
</P>
<P>
   Though much of this technology is fairly new, many people have
been surfing without a computer for some time on WebTV. For more
than three years, WebTV has offered subscribers the ability to surf
the Net and send e-mail from the comfort of their recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Now in 1 million homes, WebTV ($99-$199) offers a range of
possibilities _ like creating Web pages and playing along with
Interactive TV programs. According to WebTV customer demographics
information, nearly three-quarters of all WebTV subscribers don't
own a computer; more than half have no prior Internet experience.
</P>
<P>
   The technology that allows e-mail and Net surfing isn't limited
to stand-alone appliances like TV sets and phones, however. A
company called Planetweb makes Internet software that goes into
non-computer consumer electronics. Currently, that technology is
available in the home video game, Sega Dreamcast ($199), letting
game players go online, using their TV set as a computer screen,
their remote control as a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Planetweb Internet browser will start appearing
on some new DVD players _ called iDVDs. It will allow viewers to go
online and check movie reviews, program guides and more before
watching a show. The price of the iDVD will depend on the company
that uses the technology, says Planetweb spokesman Jim Wallace. So
far, Aiwa is on board.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their out-of-the-box cost, all of these new
Internet appliances require an Internet connection. If you already
have an Internet service provider, there's no additional cost for
most. If you're not already plugged in, you can either choose your
own ISP or take advantage of special deals that most of the
manufacturers provide. The monthly access fee is often $10 or so _
usually half of what the major ISPs charge per month.
</P>
<P>
   While many of these products are already available, some are
still on the drawing board. Some auto manufacturers, for example,
are working on built-in hands-free e-mail retrieval from the
comfort of your car. While you're driving, you can check e-mail
messages and even answer them using voice-recognition capabilities.
(Sounds an awful lot like voice mail!)
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works are boom boxes that would have wireless
connections to the Internet. You could download MP3 files right
into your boom box and play them instantly on the go.
</P>
<P>
   These products apparently aren't so far-fetched. Industry
analysts agree that Net appliances are the hot techo-gadgets du
jour.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say I need a computer to surf the Web is like saying I need
a computer to talk on the phone,'' says Internet expert and author
Mark Minasi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We geeks thought the way the world would get wired was that
everybody would grow smart and techy. We were wrong. The products
just got simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   Minasi likens these Net appliances to the traditional telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid we had one phone. Now we have them all over
the house,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years from now _ maybe less _ every room in the house
will have Internet access. This is coming so fast you can't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Agrees the CEA's Joseph, ``We have met the Jetsons and they are
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy e-mail access from tiny device.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.netpliance.net
</P>
<P>
   _ 1-888-467-3637
</P>
<P>
   _ Price: $199
</P>
<P>
   iphone
</P>
<P>
   _ Touch screen, keyboard and software that lets users
communicate by phone and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.infogear.com
</P>
<P>
   _ 1-877-746-7727
</P>
<P>
   _ Price: $399
</P>
<P>
   MailBug
</P>
<P>
   _ Countertop devices that offer e-mail without a PC.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.mailbug.com
</P>
<P>
   _ 1-800-831-2169
</P>
<P>
   _ Price: $129.95
</P>
<P>
   WebTV
</P>
<P>
   _ Browse the Web using your TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.webtv.com
</P>
<P>
   _ 1-800-469-3288
</P>
<P>
   _ Price: $99-$199
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
