<HEADER>
A5460 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-CAPTAIN-UNDERPANT     04-03 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-CAPTAIN-UNDERPANTS0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Captain Pilkey Reveals All
 &HT;    By Julie Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dav Pilkey, author of the wacky and best-selling
``Captain Underpants'' books, only does interviews by e-mail. But
News for Kids figured that was better than nothing, and we were
right. Pilkey, who is 34, lives in Seattle with his dog named
Little Dog (what else?). Pilkey sent responses to our questions in
a flash.
</P>
<P>
   After we invited readers to call in with questions for Pilkey,
we got more than 140 calls in just two days. We sent Pilkey the
most common questions, plus a few others.
</P>
<P>
   NFK: Is your real name Dav?
</P>
<P>
   DP: My real name is David. I shortened it to Dav many years ago
when I worked at Pizza Hut. They were making a name tag for me, but
the letter ``e'' on the label-maker was broken. Instead of printing
``Dave,'' it printed ``Dav.'' The name stuck!
</P>
<P>
   NFK: How did you get the idea for Captain Underpants?
</P>
<P>
   DP: I invented Captain Underpants back when I was in the second
grade. I was the ``class clown'' and got in trouble constantly for
making my friends laugh. To punish me, my teacher would send me out
into the hallway. I had a lot of spare time out there in the hall,
so I began making my own comic books about a superhero named
Captain Underpants.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, my second-grade teacher gave me the inspiration.
She happened to use the word ``underpants'' in class one day, and
everybody laughed. She got mad and said, ``Underwear is NOT
funny!''
</P>
<P>
   This only made us laugh harder. At that moment, I discovered
that underwear was a powerful thing _ not only could it make my
friends laugh, but it could also make my teacher very angry. What
fun!
</P>
<P>
   NFK: Why do you like talking about toilets and other nasty
stuff?
</P>
<P>
   DP: I always liked mild ``potty humor'' when I was a kid. I
still think it's funny.
</P>
<P>
   NFK: Where did you get the name ``Professor Poopypants''? And
did you base that character on one of your own teachers?
</P>
<P>
   DP: The name ``Professor Poopypants'' just came to me one day
when I was walking my dog. I giggled the whole way home. He's not
based on any of my former teachers, though. Any resemblance to any
actual person, living or dead, is entirely unintentional (and
unfortunate).
</P>
<P>
   NFK: Are any of the characters in your ``Captain Underpants''
books based on real people you've known?
</P>
<P>
   DP: The principal, Mr. Krupp, is based on two really mean
principals I had growing up. George and Harold's gym teacher, Mr.
Meaner, was based on EVERY gym teacher I ever had when I was a kid
(they were all pure evil). That's why the gym teacher always gets
attacked (but nobody seems to care) in all of George and Harold's
comic books.
</P>
<P>
   NFK: What's your fifth ``Captain Underpants'' book? When will it
come out?
</P>
<P>
   DP: ``Captain Underpants and the Wrath of the Wicked Wedgie
Woman'' will probably come out in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   NFK: So WHO is the Wicked Wedgie Woman?
</P>
<P>
   DP: It's a secret ... but it's somebody we already know!
</P>
<P>
   NFK: Do you personally wear briefs or boxers, and why?
</P>
<P>
   DP: Actually, I wear boxer briefs. They're the best of both
worlds.
</P>
<P>
   These extra questions will be placed in the lesson plan online:
</P>
<P>
   NFK: What does your mom think about Captain Underpants?
</P>
<P>
   DP: My mom (and dad) weren't too crazy about Captain Underpants.
They liked the fact that I was being creative and drawing comic
books, but they didn't like the ``potty humor.'' So they encouraged
me to make comics about another super hero I had invented called
``Water Man.'' But Water Man wasn't as silly as Captain Underpants,
but I still had fun making up stories about him.
</P>
<P>
   NFK: How many ``Captain Underpants'' books do you plan to write
in your entire career?
</P>
<P>
   DP: Right now I think there will be eight books. But I might
write others if I come up with more good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   NFK: Are there any plans or contracts for a ``Captain
Underpants'' movie or TV series?
</P>
<P>
   DP: No. I get offers all the time, but I want ``Captain
Underpants'' to just be books for right now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
