<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-MEDIA0404-COX     04-03 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movies may come to a computer screen near you
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Academy Awards last week focused America's
attention on the movies. But there may come a day when movies
aren't confined to the theater, VCR or DVD.
</P>
<P>
   There's a real move toward the Internet. As high-speed access
becomes more common, some experts think that movies will be
available for viewing in real time on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The April edition of Yahoo magazine takes a look at that trend
and predicts that ``when bandwidth and signal quality get better _
and they're getting better fast _ more users will be willing to
watch a movie on their computer screens.''
</P>
<P>
   Many problems, quality and broadband aside, remain.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, will people want to watch a big movie on such a
small screen?
</P>
<P>
   While computer monitor sizes have grown, the best of them don't
approach the size of the average TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting twist that may help studios market these
movies-over-the-Internet is the fact that some studios may use the
marketing ploy of either releasing the movies first on the Net, or
making the Net version available as soon as the movie is released _
beating VCR and DVD versions to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   'WHO GIVES A GIGABYTE?'
</P>
<P>
   The book is called a ``survival guide for the technologically
perplexed'' but it's really an entertaining and well-researched
guide to the new technologies that seem to be popping up faster
than normal people can cope.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you've learned what one set of initials stands for,
the next appears.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``Who Gives a Gigbyte?,'' isn't confined to computer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes a look at alternative energy sources and their
importance in a world that runs on oil and gas, and the
implications of altering genes in an effort to build the perfect
tomato.
</P>
<P>
   The book sells for $16.95 and is published by John Wiley &AMP; Sons.
It should be available now in most large bookstores as well as from
online sources.
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S GOING TO BE A REVOLUTION
</P>
<P>
   Music is a driving force on the Internet and there's a new
magazine called Revolution that will soon be hitting newsstands
with its premier spring edition.
</P>
<P>
   It's slick and upscale and will emphasize the high-tech aspects
of music. For instance, the first edition of the magazine will look
at the best MP3 music on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution will be a gadget-lovers' dream, including coverage of
the latest players and also the best of the conventional amplifiers
and other stereo equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Playing off that high-tech nature, each edition of the magazine
will contain a CD of some of the best of the new music.
</P>
<P>
   The first CD will include tunes from Kenlou such as ``Voodoo
Princess'' and ``Axus' My Planet Rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
