<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My father-in-law has recently been diagnosed with terminal
lung cancer. His medical expenses have become astronomical. The
main cause of his cancer is his 25 years of smoking, and I wonder
if he would be eligible to receive any of the Texas tobacco lawsuit
money for medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ R.J.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``No,'' says Andrea Horton, spokeswoman for the attorney
general. The state will receive more than $15 billion over 25
years. An additional $2.2 billion will be set aside for political
subdivisions within the state. According to Megan Haley, with the
Texas Department of Health, lawmakers so far have appointed some of
the money for endowments whose interest earnings will pay for
medical research, anti-smoking campaigns and smoking cessation
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was recently in the Middle East and bought some saffron
stamens for much less than they cost here. I was told I could
freeze them, so I bought enough to last for years, but I'm not sure
how to package them for freezing. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharon McCathern
</P>
<P>
   A: Is it completely dry? Nancy Levy, a local apothecary, says
you do not have to freeze the saffron. Freezers are humid places
and moisture is an herb's enemy. (A three-day stint will kill any
bugs however.) Only the saffron's stigmas are used. Place them in
an air-tight glass container away from direct sunlight. The saffron
should last at least seven years, adds Levy. Be very careful with
your stash. Saffron is an expensive spice _ it sells for $7 a gram
(more than $3,000 a pound).
</P>
<P>
   Q: The 2000 census forms say we cannot put our college student
on the form. How, then, are students counted? Ours goes to school
out of state, and if the census is used to get more representation
in Congress we lose out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pam D. A: Census 2000 will count people at their usual
residence (college), the place where they live and sleep most of
the time. This place is not necessarily the same as a voting
residence, legal residence or permanent residence (your house).
Leslie Lawson of the census says that if your children don't live
in the house but live in institutionalized college housing, such as
a dorm, the census works with the administrators to prepare a
special student form. If they live in a apartment or a house, they
will fill out their own census form.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I don't think we were counted in the 1990 census. Can we find
out? We never received a census form, but we got several postcards
asking us to return one. _ T.R. Rogers A: You can find out for a
fee if you were counted. The Census Bureau Age Search Service has
information from 1910 to 1990 that can be obtained by downloading a
BC-600 form through www.census.gov/genealogy/www or by calling
(812) 218-3046. The process takes three to four weeks and costs a
minimum of $40. You may request information about yourself or your
dependents. Often census information is requested by individuals
for Social Security or other retirement plans, for passports, to
prove relationship for estate purposes or in genealogical research.
The Census is confidential for 72 years _ individual 1990
information won't be available to the public until 2062. If you
don't receive a form this year, look for ``be counted'' sites.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The floor in my tiled shower is soooo slippery. I had the
stick-on daisies _ they got yucky, so I removed them. I tried a
rubber mat, but it kept slipping.
</P>
<P>
   _ C. White
</P>
<P>
   A: Give Skid-Tex by Bondex ($10.40) a try.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Years ago we found a company that would cut ``punt'' wine
bottles and make glasses. The drinking edge of the glass was
smoothed to eliminate the sharp edges. We have tried to find
someone who would be interested in doing this for us, but have been
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Malcolm Sanders
</P>
<P>
   A: Malcolm, you can do this yourself. Pick up a glass cutter.
Smooth the rim of the new glass with emery sandpaper from a
hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the best way to store money in the back yard? Would
it be in Tupperware or maybe a Mason jar?
</P>
<P>
   _B.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Neither is good. The Mason jar could break or crack, and the
Tupperware is meant for short-term food storage, not paper money.
It is not acid-free. If you must bury the greenbacks, use a
container that will protect the money from the elements, like time
capsules. These clear polymer cases will protect your investment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been trying to locate an original Munchkin from ``The
Wizard of Oz'' who apparently lives in Round Rock, Texas. His name
is Clarence Swenson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heather Eaton
</P>
<P>
   A: Close. Swenson lives in Pflugerville, Texas. Mail him a
missive at 1701 Azores, Pflugerville, Texas 78660. Autographs are
available for a small fee. Each of the Munchkin actors was paid
less than Toto, Dorothy Gale's dog.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My fiancee and I have been searching for the boxing gloves
that Ally uses (occasionally) on ``Ally McBeal.'' They're the huge
gloves, obviously intended for stress relief, and not real boxing.
Could you help me find them, please?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark C.
</P>
<P>
   A: What price love? $250? These oversized boxing gloves are
available through Inflatable 2000 Amusement Products for $250 per
pair (plus shipping and handling). The foam gloves are obviously
for amusement purposes. To order call (888) INFL8-IT or visit
www.inflatable2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm kind of a ``Price is Right'' fan (don't tell my mom _ she
thinks I go to work every day) and am curious about the prizes the
contestants win. Do they pay taxes on their winnings, how is their
merchandise shipped and does the show ever follow up with the
winners who win trips?
</P>
<P>
   _ N.G.L.
</P>
<P>
   A: The longest-running game show in television history arranges
for a delivery service to transport the prizes. Cars, however, are
picked up at the local dealership. The taxman (IRS and sales)
cometh to all winners, of course. Trips are handled through a
travel agency, and the show does not followup with the contestant.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR: Do you have catagelophobia, or
katagelophobia, a fear of being ridiculed, or perhaps
erythrophobia, erytophobia or ereuthophobia, fear of blushing or
the color red? Then April Fools Day is not for you. Stay in, lest
you develop ophthalmophobia, a fear of being stared at, or
geliophobia a fear of laughter. Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670,
Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or
fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
