   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SLAVE-RECORDS _ Driving to work in 1998, Eric Walther turned on
Allen Parkway in Houston and collided head-on with the past.
Construction workers at the Allen Parkway Village, a public housing
complex Walther passed every day, uncovered a cemetery where former
slaves were buried. For Walther, an associate professor of history
at the University of Houston, the find was poignant. ``I started
thinking there are hardly any physical remains of slavery in
Texas,'' he said. ``We find something and build right over it.''
Walther's desire to put a face on those who were denied their
humanity has blossomed into a project some consider impossible. He
wants to document every black slave who ever lived in Texas _ a
population he estimates at 250,000. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POMPEII-TOURISM _ In 62 A.D. it was devastated by an earthquake.
In 79 A.D., it was buried in an avalanche of hot ash from Mount
Vesuvius. Now, 2,000 years later, Pompeii is being destroyed again
_ a victim of its own popularity, creeping neglect and generations
of archaeologists more interested in digging up the past than
preserving it. (Toner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED
</P>
