<HEADER>
A5472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      04-03 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATHLEEN TURNER BRINGS OUT NAKED TRUTH ABOUT LONDONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Wanna sell theater tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Get yer kit off!
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the lesson here in London's West End, the
Broadway of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the hottest play in the West End was ``The Blue
Room,'' David Hare's drama about sexual obsession, which received
enormous publicity, mostly for the fact that Nicole Kidman appeared
on stage naked. One critic famously described the Australian
actress's performance as ``theatrical Viagra.'' The play went on to
become a hit on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Now the hottest ticket in town is for a stage adaptation of
``The Graduate,'' in which veteran Hollywood actress Kathleen
Turner plays the seductress Mrs. Robinson and, well, gets her kit
off, as the Brits say, playing the seduction scene in the nude.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales had been fair to middling when the show, which
opens Wednesday, went into previews last week. But once word got
around that Turner was taking to the floorboards at the Gielgud
Theatre wearing nothing but her talent, the show sold out its
three-month run in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   This despite the fact that, at 45, Kathleen Turner ain't no
Nicole Kidman. In the film ``Body Heat,'' Turner turned in one of
the most erotic performances of 1980s mainstream Hollywood, using
her sex appeal to get William Hurt's character to kill her husband.
But Turner is no longer the slinky temptress she played in ``Body
Heat.''
</P>
<P>
   She is, however, an accomplished actress, and perhaps more
importantly, a shrewd judge of what puts bums in seats, as the
Brits say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people learned that Kathleen appears nude, people went
mad, and the tickets just disappeared,'' said Hayley Burke, a
spokeswoman for the theater, who said the show has set the record
for advance sales by a dramatic play in the West End.
</P>
<P>
   Burke dismissed suggestions that the nude scene had been
included for commercial reasons. She said it is artful and in
keeping with writer-director Terry Johnson's adaptation of Charles
Webb's original novel, in which the protagonist Benjamin Braddock
gets seduced by the wife of his father's boss. Dustin Hoffman and
Anne Bancroft played the odd couple in the Oscar-winning film.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said the decision to do the nude scene ``was very much a
mutual one'' between Turner and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   When he recently snatched up a string of West End theaters,
Andrew Lloyd Webber, the composer-impresario behind ``Phantom of
the Opera'' and other enormously successful shows, said one of his
motives was to save London's stages from the bottom line, mostly
American owners who would be so profit-driven that they would put
on only safe, commercially successful, ``dumbed down'' fare.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plays on display in the West End these days are far
from conservative, but whether they are dumb is a matter of
opinion. At the Young Vic, for example, you can take in a
performance of ``The Man With The Absurdly Large Penis.'' At the
Gate, the show ``Cuckoos'' centers on a couple who become stuck
together while having anal sex. A serious play that took its name
from a profane reference to Franz Kafka's penis just wrapped up a
long run.
</P>
<P>
   There is a temptation to exaggerate here, to suggest that the
stiff-upper-lip Brits go a little nutty whenever they see a body
part that is normally clothed, that titillation is being used to
sell theater tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But as Fiachra Gibbons, the arts correspondent for The Guardian,
put it, the real revelation in ``The Blue Room'' for most audiences
was that Kidman, previously known for her film work and marriage to
Tom Cruise, could carry her own on stage. Gibbons said audiences
didn't leave the theater praising her body, but her acting. Preview
audiences have given Turner standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons also said that the only real extended commercial and
critical sensation in the West End in recent years was ``The
Weir,'' by the Irish playwright Conor McPherson, in which three
wistful bachelors tell ghost stories in a pub in the west of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons is right. The London theater crowd remains a discerning
bunch, more likely to see something by Shaw, Wilde, Stoppard,
Beckett and Pinter than they are to sit next to tourists at ``The
Lion King'' or ``Mamma Mia,'' the wildly successful show about Abba
songs. Contemporary British playwrights, such as Michael Frayn and
Alan Bennett, produce consistently provocative plays that are both
critical and commercial successes.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is this: Put a naked woman on display, on
page three of a sensational tabloid or even the stage of a
venerable theater, and many Brits will line up with cash in hand.
</P>
<P>
   It seems only a matter of time before there's a West End revival
of ``Oh, Calcutta.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of the Boston Globe London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
