<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     04-03 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV23-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., APR. 23, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I plan to use a paint and varnish remover to strip the paint
and varnish off some old furniture that I have in my vacation home.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the strong odor and the potential mess, I will do
this work outside. But when I tried a job like this before, I had
trouble with the liquid remover drying too fast.
</P>
<P>
   What suggestions can you offer to make the job easier and faster
this time?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you use remover while working outside, make sure you do
not work in the sun as this makes the remover dry too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Use a thick, semi-paste type, not a liquid, and apply this in
heavy layers, brushing in one direction only _ not by brushing back
and forth. The idea is not to disturb the layer of remover any more
than necessary and thus keep it from drying out too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the remover to soak long enough to soften the paint or
varnish all the way through (usually about 20-30 minutes), then
scrape the softened residue off with a dull putty knife.
</P>
<P>
   On carved or grooved surfaces use a wire brush with brass
bristle or a stiff scrub brush.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The ceiling in our master bathroom frequently develops dark,
rust colored spots after the shower has been used.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling is dry wall and has been painted several times with
a latex base satin enamel. The spots wash off with water, but they
come back after a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   We have a vent fan that exhausts into the attic and always have
this running when using the shower.
</P>
<P>
   Any idea as to what causes this, and what we can do about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is usually due to something in the paint or under the
paint that is activated by the moisture that seeps through when the
shower creates steam. This ``something'' is apparently leaching out
through the latex paint.
</P>
<P>
   It could be some type of size or other primer that was used in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   There is also another potential problem caused by your exhaust
fan blowing all that moisture up into the attic _ it should be
vented directly to the outside, not into the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Your problem can be solved by installing the duct work needed to
vent the exhaust fan to the outdoors and also scrubbing the ceiling
with a detergent to get all the stains out.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse with plain water and allow to dry for at least 24 hours,
then prime with an alkyd base primer or with a stain-killing sealer
such as BIN or Kilz.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A repair man recently spilled some asphalt roofing cement on
the concrete driveway in front of our house.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know how we can remove this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Asphalt roofing cement can usually be softened and dissolved
by soaking with gasoline or paint thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape off as much as you can, then pour a little of this
solvent over the stain and immediately cover with a heavy layer of
dry powdered Portland cement.
</P>
<P>
   Pour more solvent over the powder to saturate it and create a
thick paste, then cover the whole thing with a sheet of plastic (to
slow down evaporation).
</P>
<P>
   Let this soak in for several hours, and then sweep up the
powder. Repeat if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   If a slight discoloration remains it is possible you can remove
this with a liquid driveway cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My toilet does not flush properly so I used a stiff wire to
clean out all the little holes around the underside of the rim at
the top of the porcelain bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This helped but not enough to make it flush properly.
</P>
<P>
   How can I clean out the channel inside this porcelain rim so
that the full effect of the flush water will run down into the
bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A: When a toilet does not flush properly this is seldom the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is most likely with the flush tank's water level _
it does not fill up as high as it should so there is not enough
water and pressure for a thorough flush.
</P>
<P>
   This can be corrected by adjusting the ballcock or inlet valve
that controls the water level.
</P>
<P>
   If the porcelain channel you are talking about is really
blocked, then the bowl will have to be removed, turned upside down,
and then the channel flushed out with acid (not a do-it-yourself
job in my opinion).
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING PAINT REMOVER'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: After using paint remover, softened residue is scraped
away with dull putty knife or bristle brush.
</P>
