<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-EDWARD-NORTON-IN-KEEP     04-03 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARD-NORTON-IN-KEEPING-THE-FAITH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC MINISTRATIONS: EDWARD NORTON IS `KEEPING THE FAITH' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Edward Norton with Ben Stiller in a
scene from ``Keeping the Faith.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Edward Norton freely admits that he identifies with the bad guy.
 &HT;    ``Good guys are just not where it's at for me,'' he says. ``I
marvel at the characters played by actors like De Niro and Pacino.
They played men so bad that they didn't just remain on the screen _
they were burned into your subconscious.''
 &HT;    Norton has played a few equally searing roles, including the
schizophrenic altar boy who murders the archbishop of Chicago in
``Primal Fear'' (1996) and his Oscar-nominated role as a
shaven-headed, swastika-tattooed white supremacist in ``American
History X'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``Don't forget that I beat Brad Pitt into pulp in `Fight
Club,''' Norton adds with a laugh. ``Quite a few people are still
harboring a few resentments for that one, although I just saw Brad
and he's fine.''
 &HT;    His current role won't add to that list, however. In ``Keeping
the Faith,'' opening nationwide on April 14, he plays a Catholic
priest without any discernible antisocial tendencies whatever.
 &HT;    ``I guess there comes a time when everyone needs to stretch a
little bit,'' Norton says with a laugh, draped over a chair at New
York's Regency Hotel.
 &HT;    That's for sure. ``Keeping the Faith'' _ which he describes as
``a $30 million priest-and-rabbi joke'' _ also marks Norton's
debuts as a director and as a producer.
 &HT;    He plays Father Brian Finn, best buddies since childhood with
Orthodox Rabbi Jacob Schram (Ben Stiller). A unique romantic
triangle forms when Anna Reilly (Jenna Elfman), the woman both men
were fascinated with as teen-agers, reappears in their lives.
 &HT;    ``Of course, the priest cannot act on these feeling because of
his vows of celibacy,'' Norton says. ``The rabbi can't form a
relationship with her because she's not Jewish.''
 &HT;    Norton may describe the film as ``a romantic comedy in the
`Philadelphia Story' tradition,'' but he also sees a deeper
message.
 &HT;    ``It's a story about maintaining your traditions,'' he says
thoughtfully. ``To me it's also a movie about the stress people my
age feel, when they've been brought up by parents who exert this
religious pressure on their grown children.''
 &HT;    Sooner or later, Norton says, he was bound to move into
directing and producing.
 &HT;    ``I wanted the freedom to make the big choices,'' he says. ``The
worst thing about acting is the lack of authority over the final
product.
 &HT;    ``I also liked the idea of creating a project from start to
finish,'' he adds. ``Another tough part of being an actor is that
you sit around waiting for other people to say `yes' or `no' to
you. You get to this point where you long to be the catalyst.''
 &HT;    Thus, four years ago Norton teamed with screenwriter Stuart
Blumberg, an old college buddy from Yale with whom he also had
roomed during his early acting days in New York. Blumberg banged
out the script, but it took years before a studio _ Disney's
Touchstone Pictures _ finally gambled on the potentially
controversial story.
 &HT;    ``It was a scary process,'' Norton says, ``because the movie
literally consumes every waking moment of your life. There was also
an immense satisfaction when it was finished.''
 &HT;    His passion for the film has caused the normally press-shy
Norton to give more than his usual number of interviews, which he
freely admits isn't his idea of a good time.
 &HT;    ``The media has a way of reducing a complex human life and
boiling it into convenient copy,'' he says. ``I am the most private
person I know. I demand personal space, but I am an actor _ I work
for an audience. I do this for the people, and the people want to
know about me. That is the conflict.''
 &HT;    His last film, ``Fight Club'' (1999), was a box-office dud,
despite the presence of co-star Brad Pitt. But Norton doesn't see
any omen there for ``Keeping the Faith.''
 &HT;    ``You can't predict the box office,'' he says. ``You can't
predict what the public is in the mood to see on a Friday night.
But that's part of the risk of acting. It's all a big gamble _ in
fact, acting is the only thing in my life where I said, `I'm going
to let an enormous amount ride and just let fate decide what
happens.'''
 &HT;    Norton shrugs.
 &HT;    ``Any decision to pursue a creative life is a risk,'' he says.
``Any decision to pursue anything you care about is also
frightening, because you're so vulnerable. But there is no way to
go after something you care about without being scared. With my
fear is also an excitement.''
 &HT;    Born in 1969, Norton grew up in Columbia, Md., son of a lawyer
and a teacher. He began acting at age 5, and attended a school for
the theatrical arts in Baltimore. At 8, he recalls, he was known to
ask his teachers, ``What is my objective in this scene?''
 &HT;    Even then a serious young man, his biggest problem growing up
was his name, with its resonances of ``The Honeymooners.''
 &HT;    ``Actually, my father had it worse,'' Norton says. ``He would
get, `Hey, I love ``The Honeymooners!''' I would occasionally get
someone who would hear my name and scream, `To the moon, Alice!'''
 &HT;    After graduating from Yale, Norton spent a year in Japan and
then returned home. Settling in New York, he toyed with the idea of
going to law school, but supported himself as a proofreader while
trying to secure acting gigs. In 1994 he was cast in ``Fragments''
at New York's Signature Theatre Company.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, I don't know what I would have done if I hadn't
gotten serious about acting,'' he says. ``I don't know what else I
could do. I guess I would have been just another one of those guys
getting through life, trying to be financially stable. But my heart
wasn't in that sort of life.''
 &HT;    He had minor roles in ``With Honors'' (1994) and ``Hackers''
(1995), and then got the chance to audition for the role of the
baby-faced psycho in ``Primal Fear'' after Leonardo DiCaprio
dropped out.
 &HT;    Knowing that the character was an Appalachian farm boy, and
taking advantage of his longtime facility with accents, Norton told
the casting agent that he came from eastern Kentucky and had grown
up poor. It was an out-and-out lie, but it worked _ he got the
part, and an Oscar nomination to go with it.
 &HT;    That critically acclaimed performance led to roles as a singing
preppie in Woody Allen's musical ``Everyone Says I Love You''
(1996) and as the lawyer for the publisher of Hustler magazine in
Milos Forman's ``The People vs. Larry Flynt'' (1996).
 &HT;    As his star began to rise, however, Norton became a bit of a
hermit. He is extremely private about his personal life, and won't
discuss new girlfriend Salma Hayek or previous girlfriends Courtney
Love and Drew Barrymore.
 &HT;    ``I guess I need to lighten up about these matters of my private
life and take the interest in it as part of the silliness that goes
on,'' Norton says.
 &HT;    He shifts uncomfortably in his chair.
 &HT;    ``I find fame really bizarre,'' he says. ``Once in an interview,
someone asked me, `What is your blood type?' Does the public really
need to know all these details about an actor?''
 &HT;    No, he insists.
 &HT;    ``If the public knows too much about me,'' the actor says,
``they can't lose themselves in my characters. If I can't take
people on a journey away from who Edward Norton is, then what is
the point?''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Keeping the Faith,'' consult
the official Web site at www.studio.go.com/movies/keepingthefaith.
And don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
