<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-CHRISTIAN-BALE-IN-AME     04-03 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-BALE-IN-AMERICAN-PSYCHO-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PSYCHO'-SOMATIC: CHRISTIAN BALE'S AMERICAN NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Christian Bale in a scene from
``American Psycho.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    A solitary figure, clad in jeans and wearing a pair of running
shoes, sits in the deserted garden of a less-then-trendy hotel in a
beach community near Los Angeles.
 &HT;    The handsome profile is what gives Christian Bale away.
Otherwise you wouldn't recognize him as Patrick Bateman, the
perfectly coiffed and manicured yuppie with a fondness for
expensive suits and serial killing whom he plays in ``American
Psycho.'' It's a startling counterpoint to his recent television
appearance as Jesus in ``Mary, Mother of Jesus.''
 &HT;    Offering a quiet greeting in a British-tinged accent, Bale is
pleasant enough but a bit shy, even wary. He'd rather talk about
his controversial role as a homicidal Wall Street executive than
discuss his life offscreen, especially his recent marriage.
 &HT;    ``It's not beneficial for an actor to talk about his personal
life,'' he says with a shrug. ``It becomes a lot more difficult to
make the audience believe in the character you're creating if they
know all about you.''
 &HT;    Bale is nothing if not believable as he immerses himself in
``American Psycho's'' wave of bloody killings and brutal sex.
Directed by Mary Harron and co-starring Jared Leto, Chloe Sevigny
and Willem Dafoe, the dark drama _ which will open nationwide on
April 14 _ is based on Bret Easton Ellis' controversial novel, and
seems likely to kick up just as much fuss.
 &HT;    ``I expect people will have a knee-jerk reaction to Bateman
because he's so repulsive,'' Bale admits, ``but I found him sort of
fascinatingly entertaining.
 &HT;    ``I had this complete misconception about `American Psycho,'
before I read the script, as this deep, dark analysis of a serial
killer,'' the actor says. ``It's actually a biting, satirical look
at young, rich men on Wall Street at their worst. I didn't do any
research into serial killing, because the mayhem Bateman creates is
so over-the-top it's not realistic. It's very black humor.
 &HT;    ``Bateman is a total exaggeration of the emotional bankruptcy of
yuppie men in the '80s,'' he concludes. ``They were like media
stars behaving badly, driven by this `Masters of the Universe'
attitude.
 &HT;    ``Bateman couldn't really exist, and that's how I played him.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Bale made a concerted effort to capture the look
of the narcissistic Bateman, who admires his own physical
appearance as much as the carnage he creates.
 &HT;    ``I did manic amounts of training,'' the actor says. ``I was as
obsessive as he was, running six miles a day, boxing and lifting
weights. I gave it up at the end of film, although I still run a
bit.
 &HT;    ``Then there was the diet,'' he adds with a sigh. ``It was so
boring. Pretty much all I ate the whole time we were filming was
grilled chicken, cottage cheese, egg whites and a lot of water.''
 &HT;    Mastering Bateman's well-heeled American accent was another
challenge.
 &HT;    ``I worked with a dialect coach for about four weeks,'' Bale
says, ``and I got it. I started sounding like an arrogant prick.
After that, I talked like Bateman 24 hours a day, whether I was on
or off the set.''
 &HT;    He spent less time preparing for the film's scenes of bloody
brutality, which range from an axe murder and stabbings to a
sadomasochistic orgy.
 &HT;    ``You can't get carried away with the violence,'' he says,
``otherwise I would have been doing things like really putting an
axe through Jared Leto's head. What helped me was that, even when I
was losing control as Bateman, I had to be in control to stay in
the right position for the camera and lighting.
 &HT;    ``The abundance of fake blood helped,'' he says with a wry
smile. ``There were times when you felt like you were jumping in a
fountain of it with all your clothes on. It's very liberating and
almost bestial _ I felt very primal and sort of in touch with
Bateman's insanity.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, he adds, ``It's not much fun sitting around
in fake blood for like six hours. It stains incredibly, and it sort
of works its way into your skin.''
 &HT;    As for the film's already-notorious orgy scene, which got it in
trouble with the ratings board, Bale reports that the orgy wasn't
very sexy at the time.
 &HT;    ``It's actually a very unerotic scene,'' he says, ``incredibly
cold and narcissistic, as if Bateman is playing out his fantasies
of being a porn star. I actually think it's more uncomfortable for
the director and the crew, having to focus on your naked butt while
you're doing all that stuff.''
 &HT;    It took a while for Bale to even get to that scene. After Harron
had prevailed on Lions Gate Films to cast Bale instead of an
American star, the studio suddenly fired her and offered the role
to Leonardo DiCaprio, at a reported $20 million. After wavering,
DiCaprio declined, and Harron and Bale returned to the project.
 &HT;    ``I think I was a little tough to be around while all that was
happening,'' Bale says. ``I waited around for a year and a half. If
I had known it was going to be that long, I would have taken other
work.''
 &HT;    And he didn't end up with DiCaprio's $20 million, either.
 &HT;    ``After all that,'' Bale says, ``I got paid less than the makeup
woman for doing the movie. It had a low budget and I got scale,
which is the minimum. The fact is that I went into debt _ thank
God, my agents paid my mortgage for me. If I did too many `American
Psychos,' I'd be living out of my car.''
 &HT;    Bale is collecting a bigger paycheck for his next film, John
Singleton's remake of ``Shaft,'' in which he plays the villain to
Samuel L. Jackson's cool detective. It's an unusually commercial
outing for the art-film-oriented Bale, but he retains his
longstanding skepticism toward the entire Hollywood machine.
 &HT;    ``My first major movie was `Empire of the Sun' (1987), when I
was 13,'' he says. ``I rather enjoyed all the attention I was
getting _ and then suddenly it seemed very wrong and I just wanted
to disappear from the scene. For a while, I thought I might give up
acting.''
 &HT;    He gazes across the garden, remembering his arrival in Hollywood
with a slight smile.
 &HT;    ``I was 17,'' he recalls, ``and suddenly, oh wow, all these
people were taking me out to clubs and bars and things. Famous
faces were everywhere, and I found it fascinating but also a bit
hilarious.
 &HT;    ``I never really lost myself in it,'' Bale says, ``although I'd
be the first to say I've been as much of a brat as anybody. But I
could see that I could suffer from the supreme overconfidence of
stardom like anybody else. It can kill your joy in the craft of
acting. When you get too serious about being seen at the right
places, it's not fun anymore.''
 &HT;    Sounds a little bit like Patrick Bateman's world.
 &HT;    Bale stares across the garden again, toward the pool where the
sunlight is creating a glittering pattern of stars on the water.
 &HT;    ``I guess there are correlations,'' he says finally. ``Extreme
vanity and megalomania, self-obsession, incredibly fierce
competition. That's what you have to be careful of.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
