w e BC-BETTY-THOMAS-DIRECTS-     04-03 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-THOMAS-DIRECTS-28-DAYS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLED UP: BETTY THOMAS DIRECTS `28 DAYS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Betty Thomas directing Sandra Bullock in
a scene from ``28 Days.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Betty Thomas didn't grow up thinking, ``Oh, if only I could be
an actress'' or ``I'm just dying to direct.''
 &HT;    In fact, she says during an interview at the Four Seasons hotel
in Los Angeles, it wasn't until she landed a job as a waitress at
Chicago's famous Second City comedy club that the idea crossed her
mind.
 &HT;    ``I went to a workshop,'' she recalls. ``Somebody got sick and
they said, `Well, Betty knows ... ' It was always me saying, `I'm
just standing in for ... ' Then I realized, `This is my entire
life. Am I just standing in for my life? What am I doing?'
 &HT;    ``So I grew to like acting,'' Thomas says. ``But because I was
an artist and a painter, I thought I'd make art films _ that was my
five-year plan.
 &HT;    ``It didn't work out that way.''
 &HT;    Indeed it didn't. Performing comedy with Second City led to a
role as Officer Lucy Bates on the landmark television drama ``Hill
Street Blues.'' Eventually she made the leap to directing, first
with episodes of such series as ``Dream On'' and then with the hit
feature, ``The Brady Bunch Movie'' (1995). Her subsequent directing
credits include ``The Late Shift'' (1996), the Howard Stern
biography ``Private Parts'' (1997) and ``Doctor Dolittle'' (1998).
 &HT;    ```Hill Street' and all the acting I did with Second City, I
feel, was just preparation for being a director,'' Thomas says.
``If you're supposed to do something, you wind up doing it, I
guess.''
 &HT;    The director's latest film is ``28 Days,'' a drama with large
dollops of humor. Sandra Bullock stars as Gwen Cummings, a New York
writer who lives hard and drinks harder. After ruining the wedding
of her sister (Elizabeth Perkins) by crashing a limo into a house,
Gwen is sentenced to 28 days in a rehab facility.
 &HT;    The action centers on Gwen's effort to reclaim her life and on
her interaction with a group of fellow screw-ups (Viggo Mortensen,
Azura Skye, Alan Tudyk, Michael O'Malley and Marianne
Jean-Baptiste).
 &HT;    While prepping the film, Thomas spent several days at a
real-life rehab facility. She heard every conceivable story and
soaked up the methods of therapy, which ranged from the touching of
horses to the wearing of message-bearing signs.
 &HT;    She also heard a variety of sappy exit songs and listened to sex
addicts tell of doing it in the elevator.
 &HT;    ``It's all true, it's all true,'' says the high-energy Thomas,
who's decked out head to toe in black, with two pairs of glasses
dangling from strings around her neck. ``Interesting, isn't it? The
horse thing? True. I went to rehab, came back and said, `We're
putting this in the movie!'''
 &HT;    And, no, it doesn't bother her if, in this fairly substantial
drama, ``the horse thing'' and other offbeat elements nonetheless
draw some big laughs.
 &HT;    ``I want the audience to laugh,'' Thomas insists. ``I want them
to think about the laugh or not think about the laugh. Whatever
their reaction is, I think it's the right thing.
 &HT;    ``I went to rehab,'' she adds, ``and my experience was that
people were laughing and making jokes because they have to. You
have to _ just like cops make jokes, rehab people make jokes and
A.A. people make jokes. They make jokes about the horribleness, the
hardships and the melodrama of their own lives.
 &HT;    ``When I saw that, I knew we had to strive for more comedy in
the film.''
 &HT;    The film is Thomas' most serious effort to date, but it's also a
challenge for Bullock, who is best known for lighter fare.
 &HT;    ``Who knew?'' Thomas says. ``Who knew Sandy could be so complex
and fabulous? I only hoped.
 &HT;    ``I wanted her because she's the girl next door, she's the
accessible star,'' the director says. ``It's amazing to walk around
with her, because people come up to her and go, `Oh, hi, Sandy, how
are you?' It's like they're friends for 50 years.
 &HT;    ``I'm like, `Dude, this is a major star,''' she says. ``But she
approaches people like that, too, which is the right attitude for
the movie.''
 &HT;    Bullock, on the other hand, has said that she chose ``28 Days''
in part to shed that girl-next-door image _ which isn't the
contradiction it seems, Thomas believes.
 &HT;    ``I wanted that image of her,'' she says. ``I didn't want that
in the movie, and that's not what I got. I hired who she was,
because that's the image _ not the person _ in this movie.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, she isn't that,'' Thomas adds. ``I chose that as
the thing I wanted, to allow the audience to get into it, and then
I hoped I got _ and I got it _ this complex human being with plenty
of places to go.
 &HT;    ``I assume Sandy took the movie because she knew she could go
those places, that she said, `I haven't had a chance to go these
places and now I get to go.'''
 &HT;    For her own part, Thomas welcomed the opportunity to work with
darker, more emotionally powerful subject matter than she had
previously. It let her employ a wider range of directorial
techniques, including, in one crucial scene between Bullock and
Perkins, a single-take sequence that runs for one minute and 45
seconds _ an eternity by Hollywood standards.
 &HT;    ``I was so afraid,'' Thomas says. ``I'd never even approached a
scene like that before. I was like, `Aaaaah! Somebody's gonna
notice!' But you are so into Sandy and her face and the way she's
falling apart.
 &HT;    ``There was no other way to do it,'' she says. ``If I'd done
anything else, it would have been schmutzy and horrible _ as soon
as you cut, you ruin everything.''
 &HT;    The more she works, Thomas says, and the more she makes
different types of movies, the more comfortable she feels behind
the camera.
 &HT;    ``Well, I'm just learning s--t and getting better,'' she says.
 &HT;    ``I think I'm getting better. Hopefully, I have some kind of
depth.
 &HT;    ``Love and laugh,'' she says cheerfully. ``I agree with Preston
Sturges. A laugh is an important thing _ all of us in a room
together, laughing, that's important for humanity.
 &HT;    ``If that's all I do, that's fine. That'll be good.''
 &HT;    Next up for Thomas is ``The Dreyfus Affair,'' a comedy/drama
about two pro baseball players who come out of the closet. Ben
Affleck was supposed to star, but scheduling conflicts now have
left that in question.
 &HT;    When she isn't behind the camera, Thomas moonlights as a
producer. She and her partner, Jenno Topping, formed the production
company Tall Trees two years ago, and since then have produced
``Can't Hardly Wait'' (1998) and ``28 Days.'' They're currently
filming the big-screen version of the 1970s jiggle-television
classic ``Charlie's Angels.''
 &HT;    About the only thing she isn't doing these days, in fact, is
acting.
 &HT;    ``I'm done until I retire from directing,'' the 52-year-old
Thomas says. ``And then I'll be the next-door neighbor on a sitcom,
where I don't have to show my face.
 &HT;    ``That way I don't have to have any work done or anything stupid
like that.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
