w a BC-SARAH-MICHELLE-GELLAR     04-03 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAH-MICHELLE-GELLAR-IN-BUFFY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAMPIRE SLAYER-PLAYER: SARAH MICHELLE GELLAR IS MORE THAN JUST
BUFFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Sarah Michelle Gellar in a scene from
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'') 
 By MICHAEL LOGAN  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not for release in Canada until 16 April. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sarah Michelle Gellar is the queen of contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   The star of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' who will turn 23 on
April 14, is one of Hollywood's most opinionated and outspoken
actresses _ yet also one of its most private.
</P>
<P>
   She is supremely focused and clearheaded _ yet speaks at warp
speed, rarely concluding one topic before hurling herself headlong
into the next.
</P>
<P>
   She is sweet yet sassy, insecure yet audaciously self-confident,
childlike yet wise beyond her years.
</P>
<P>
   A role model for millions of young people, Gellar is avidly
antidrug and almost puritanical in her morals, yet she's been known
to toss her convictions aside for movie roles _ she played a
coke-snorting villainess in ``Cruel Intentions'' (1999) _ and the
occasional fashion spread, such as the Rolling Stone cover for
which she posed in kinky red leather and brandished a whip.
</P>
<P>
   Gellar is, quite simply, one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a decision _ a rule, really _ when I was very young
that I would always stay true to myself,'' Gellar says over lunch
in her trailer near the ``Buffy'' set. ``It's important to me that
I go to bed every night happy with who I am and with the choices
I've made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of people's lives go off track in this
business,'' she adds. ``I've seen them really lose sight of
themselves, and I don't ever want to do that. All the time I ask my
friends, `I haven't changed, have I? I'm still the same person,
right?'''
</P>
<P>
   If she weren't, it would be understandable, given Gellar's
skyrocketing popularity as the stake-wielding, butt-kicking Buffy.
And there have been some well-reported episodes: A few months ago,
for example, the actress was being photographed for the cover of a
major entertainment magazine when she abruptly halted the
proceedings and packed up her belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted it sexier and sexier, and I just couldn't do it,''
Gellar says, still bothered by the incident. ``I said, `You know
what, guys? What you want is not for me.' And I left the shoot. I
just walked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do what's sexy only to the degree I feel comfortable,'' she
says. ``I have a problem with so many actors these days going nude
for magazines. I thought we were promoting our talent, not our
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   She is quick to point out that ``Cruel Intentions,'' a
prep-school version of the classic ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' was
``very sexy and my character did a lot of risque things, including
kiss another woman, but she never actually had sex and I never
showed a thing. The only thing naked in the movie was Ryan
Phillippe's butt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'd never appear nude in a film if I thought it
was important,'' the actress adds, ``but that script has yet to
come along.''
</P>
<P>
   A working actress since age 4, Gellar spent her teen years
playing in the suds, first in the syndicated serial ``Swan's
Crossing,'' which featured fellow rising star Mira Sorvino, and
then on ABC's ``All My Children,'' where she won an Emmy as
backstabbing brat Kendall Hart.
</P>
<P>
   It was on ``All My Children'' that the precocious Gellar played
her first love scene _ she was 15, while her partner, Michael
Nader, was pushing 50.
</P>
<P>
   It was also there that she realized that she had bigger dreams
than most of her co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone told me not to leave `AMC,''' Gellar recalls, ``and I
mean everybody. They petrified me! They reminded me of every soap
star who left daytime and couldn't get arrested. They said, `You'll
never work. You'll come crawling back.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, for a while, it looked like they were right. After quitting
the New York-based soap, Gellar headed west and found herself
barely able to land an audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Emmy was meaningless,'' she recalls with a laugh. ``I could
not get in the door for any project, much less the good ones. I
mean, I figured I'd at least get a little episodic work, maybe a
small role in a movie, maybe a lousy pilot _ but I got nothing!''
</P>
<P>
   A half-year later, things changed virtually overnight. The young
actress was cast in the television movie ``Beverly Hills Family
Robinson'' (1997), a modern-day shipwreck comedy starring Martin
Mull and Dyan Cannon. While filming that in Australia, she was
paged to audition for ``Buffy'' _ ironically, not for the title
character, but for the rich, snobby Cordelia.
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to another, however, and Gellar hasn't looked back
since.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she remains one of the least-known stars in
Hollywood, in large part because of her fierce efforts to keep her
private life to herself.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York, Gellar was raised primarily by her mother, a
schoolteacher. The actress is estranged from her salesman father,
and has very little to say about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a person who exists in my life,'' she says. ``Just
because you donate sperm does not make you a father. I don't have a
father _ I would never give him the credit to acknowledge him as my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Gellar is equally tight-lipped about her love life. Though she
has been seen with actors Freddie Prinze Jr., Matthew Perry and
Jerry O'Connell at premieres and award shows, as well as with
``Buffy'' creator Joss Whedon and her former leading man David
Boreanaz, now the star of ``Angel,'' Gellar steadfastly insists
that anyone the paparazzi have caught her with is ``just a good
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds are, you will not see me at one of those industry
events with someone I am interested in,'' she says, ``which is why
I go with Freddie or Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gellar has never publicly confirmed being in a romantic
relationship during her recent years in the spotlight, but she says
she has indeed had them and has suffered her share of emotional
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I go out of my way to keep that private,'' she says. ``I
don't want to pick up some supermarket tabloid and find people
making judgments about me or read reports about how my guy is
cheating. It would put doubt in my mind. I'd be miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   She does confess that, these days, she's flying solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no fun not having someone to snuggle up with on a rainy
day,'' she admits. ``I'd love to have the perfect boyfriend right
now _ but, as a society, we have to learn that it's OK not to be in
a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her show-biz peers are less discreet: Keri Russell of
``Felicity'' told Jane magazine how she lost her virginity in a
closet. Jessica Biel of ``Seventh Heaven'' tried to get herself
fired by posing nude in Gear.
</P>
<P>
   But Gellar is unswayable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My true fans appreciate and respect that I won't discuss
certain things,'' she says emphatically. ``The ones who have a
problem with it, the ones who want to dig into my life and make me
uncomfortable, are not my true fans.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Logan is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
consult the WB Web site at www.thewb.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-EDWARD-NORTON-IN-KEEP     04-03 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARD-NORTON-IN-KEEPING-THE-FAITH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC MINISTRATIONS: EDWARD NORTON IS `KEEPING THE FAITH' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Edward Norton with Ben Stiller in a
scene from ``Keeping the Faith.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Edward Norton freely admits that he identifies with the bad guy.
 &HT;    ``Good guys are just not where it's at for me,'' he says. ``I
marvel at the characters played by actors like De Niro and Pacino.
They played men so bad that they didn't just remain on the screen _
they were burned into your subconscious.''
 &HT;    Norton has played a few equally searing roles, including the
schizophrenic altar boy who murders the archbishop of Chicago in
``Primal Fear'' (1996) and his Oscar-nominated role as a
shaven-headed, swastika-tattooed white supremacist in ``American
History X'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``Don't forget that I beat Brad Pitt into pulp in `Fight
Club,''' Norton adds with a laugh. ``Quite a few people are still
harboring a few resentments for that one, although I just saw Brad
and he's fine.''
 &HT;    His current role won't add to that list, however. In ``Keeping
the Faith,'' opening nationwide on April 14, he plays a Catholic
priest without any discernible antisocial tendencies whatever.
 &HT;    ``I guess there comes a time when everyone needs to stretch a
little bit,'' Norton says with a laugh, draped over a chair at New
York's Regency Hotel.
 &HT;    That's for sure. ``Keeping the Faith'' _ which he describes as
``a $30 million priest-and-rabbi joke'' _ also marks Norton's
debuts as a director and as a producer.
 &HT;    He plays Father Brian Finn, best buddies since childhood with
Orthodox Rabbi Jacob Schram (Ben Stiller). A unique romantic
triangle forms when Anna Reilly (Jenna Elfman), the woman both men
were fascinated with as teen-agers, reappears in their lives.
 &HT;    ``Of course, the priest cannot act on these feeling because of
his vows of celibacy,'' Norton says. ``The rabbi can't form a
relationship with her because she's not Jewish.''
 &HT;    Norton may describe the film as ``a romantic comedy in the
`Philadelphia Story' tradition,'' but he also sees a deeper
message.
 &HT;    ``It's a story about maintaining your traditions,'' he says
thoughtfully. ``To me it's also a movie about the stress people my
age feel, when they've been brought up by parents who exert this
religious pressure on their grown children.''
 &HT;    Sooner or later, Norton says, he was bound to move into
directing and producing.
 &HT;    ``I wanted the freedom to make the big choices,'' he says. ``The
worst thing about acting is the lack of authority over the final
product.
 &HT;    ``I also liked the idea of creating a project from start to
finish,'' he adds. ``Another tough part of being an actor is that
you sit around waiting for other people to say `yes' or `no' to
you. You get to this point where you long to be the catalyst.''
 &HT;    Thus, four years ago Norton teamed with screenwriter Stuart
Blumberg, an old college buddy from Yale with whom he also had
roomed during his early acting days in New York. Blumberg banged
out the script, but it took years before a studio _ Disney's
Touchstone Pictures _ finally gambled on the potentially
controversial story.
 &HT;    ``It was a scary process,'' Norton says, ``because the movie
literally consumes every waking moment of your life. There was also
an immense satisfaction when it was finished.''
 &HT;    His passion for the film has caused the normally press-shy
Norton to give more than his usual number of interviews, which he
freely admits isn't his idea of a good time.
 &HT;    ``The media has a way of reducing a complex human life and
boiling it into convenient copy,'' he says. ``I am the most private
person I know. I demand personal space, but I am an actor _ I work
for an audience. I do this for the people, and the people want to
know about me. That is the conflict.''
 &HT;    His last film, ``Fight Club'' (1999), was a box-office dud,
despite the presence of co-star Brad Pitt. But Norton doesn't see
any omen there for ``Keeping the Faith.''
 &HT;    ``You can't predict the box office,'' he says. ``You can't
predict what the public is in the mood to see on a Friday night.
But that's part of the risk of acting. It's all a big gamble _ in
fact, acting is the only thing in my life where I said, `I'm going
to let an enormous amount ride and just let fate decide what
happens.'''
 &HT;    Norton shrugs.
 &HT;    ``Any decision to pursue a creative life is a risk,'' he says.
``Any decision to pursue anything you care about is also
frightening, because you're so vulnerable. But there is no way to
go after something you care about without being scared. With my
fear is also an excitement.''
 &HT;    Born in 1969, Norton grew up in Columbia, Md., son of a lawyer
and a teacher. He began acting at age 5, and attended a school for
the theatrical arts in Baltimore. At 8, he recalls, he was known to
ask his teachers, ``What is my objective in this scene?''
 &HT;    Even then a serious young man, his biggest problem growing up
was his name, with its resonances of ``The Honeymooners.''
 &HT;    ``Actually, my father had it worse,'' Norton says. ``He would
get, `Hey, I love ``The Honeymooners!''' I would occasionally get
someone who would hear my name and scream, `To the moon, Alice!'''
 &HT;    After graduating from Yale, Norton spent a year in Japan and
then returned home. Settling in New York, he toyed with the idea of
going to law school, but supported himself as a proofreader while
trying to secure acting gigs. In 1994 he was cast in ``Fragments''
at New York's Signature Theatre Company.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, I don't know what I would have done if I hadn't
gotten serious about acting,'' he says. ``I don't know what else I
could do. I guess I would have been just another one of those guys
getting through life, trying to be financially stable. But my heart
wasn't in that sort of life.''
 &HT;    He had minor roles in ``With Honors'' (1994) and ``Hackers''
(1995), and then got the chance to audition for the role of the
baby-faced psycho in ``Primal Fear'' after Leonardo DiCaprio
dropped out.
 &HT;    Knowing that the character was an Appalachian farm boy, and
taking advantage of his longtime facility with accents, Norton told
the casting agent that he came from eastern Kentucky and had grown
up poor. It was an out-and-out lie, but it worked _ he got the
part, and an Oscar nomination to go with it.
 &HT;    That critically acclaimed performance led to roles as a singing
preppie in Woody Allen's musical ``Everyone Says I Love You''
(1996) and as the lawyer for the publisher of Hustler magazine in
Milos Forman's ``The People vs. Larry Flynt'' (1996).
 &HT;    As his star began to rise, however, Norton became a bit of a
hermit. He is extremely private about his personal life, and won't
discuss new girlfriend Salma Hayek or previous girlfriends Courtney
Love and Drew Barrymore.
 &HT;    ``I guess I need to lighten up about these matters of my private
life and take the interest in it as part of the silliness that goes
on,'' Norton says.
 &HT;    He shifts uncomfortably in his chair.
 &HT;    ``I find fame really bizarre,'' he says. ``Once in an interview,
someone asked me, `What is your blood type?' Does the public really
need to know all these details about an actor?''
 &HT;    No, he insists.
 &HT;    ``If the public knows too much about me,'' the actor says,
``they can't lose themselves in my characters. If I can't take
people on a journey away from who Edward Norton is, then what is
the point?''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
