<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-TRAUMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S NEEDS UNMET, SPECIALISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Usually, they are the children of divorce, whipsawed
between mothers and fathers competing for their affection and
loyalty. Or they are wards of the state, living with foster
families while social workers decide whether to return them to
their biological parents. Or they are adoptees from other
countries, old enough to remember their first homes as they adjust
to a different culture, a new language, and unfamiliar people
raising them.
</P>
<P>
   The legal-political storm swirling around Elian Gonzalez is
unusual, perhaps even unique. But the psychological and
developmental issues involved when a 6-year-old boy is thrust into
a custody battle, or suffers the loss of a parent, or is
transplanted from his home and must adjust to a radically new one _
or all of the above _ are commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Mental-health professionals, social workers, adoption
counselors, and divorce lawyers see the effects of such
life-altering events every day. And while they say many children in
comparable circumstances go on to become healthy adults, they also
agree few children who experience trauma as profound and complex as
Elian's escape without serious psychological scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible situation in which he's being exploited by all
sides, and it's clearly to his long-term detriment,'' says Michael
Brody, a nationally prominent specialist in childhood development
and an officer of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent
Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says they want to do what's best for the child, but
they've done nothing from the start to help him deal with the
terrible loss and dramatic change he's gone through,'' adds Brody,
who, like everyone interviewed, stressed that he was speaking in
general terms since he had never examined Elian himself. ``Will he
get over this, as they like to say he will? No. As a child
psychiatrist, the one thing I can safely say . . . based on
experience and research in the field is that he will never get over
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say that he'll become dysfunctional or
emotionally debilitated. Ironically, citing studies that show a
child's treatment during his earliest years has the most lasting
effect on his development, experts say it is Elian's upbringing in
Cuba that will generally determine his capacity to deal with having
watched his mother drown, with his own harrowing journey to the
shores of Florida on an inner tube, his enforced separation from
his father, and the extraordinary attention he has received from
his relatives, others in the Cuban-American community, and the
media.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it seems unimaginable that anyone _ much less
a 6-year-old _ could emerge unscathed from such a jarring series of
events.
</P>
<P>
   Even boys and girls who endure far less distress commonly suffer
at least short-term clinical depression, according to the
specialists interviewed. And the adults around them often don't
detect it, because the main way in which children cope is to go
into denial, smiling and playing as if nothing untoward had
happened at all.
</P>
<P>
   Children wrenched from an existence they know into unfamiliar
circumstances, particularly when they understand or sense they may
be moved yet again, often grapple for the rest of their lives with
deep insecurities, questions of self-worth, and feelings of
powerlessness born of an immature comprehension of what has
happened around them. They may viscerally believe they must somehow
be responsible for causing a mother's death or a father's
estrangement, for instance, even if the situation is repeatedly
explained to them and they are explicitly told they were not at
fault in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, children in these situations frequently develop
difficulties in making or sustaining emotional bonds because their
experience is that even the people to whom they feel closest may
suddenly disappear, or at least can't be counted upon to remain an
essential, ongoing part of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The post-traumatic effects will manifest themselves in many
ways,'' says Joyce Maguire Pavao, the author of ``The Family of
Adoption'' and a specialist in separation and loss during
childhood. Pavao, agreeing with other therapists, says that in
addition to the obvious trauma of loss, political and familial
wrangling over his fate seems certain to take a toll on him.
</P>
<P>
   Pavao and others interviewed suggest the best solution for
helping Elian is one that doesn't seem at all likely given the
virtual state of war between Fidel Castro and the Cuban-American
community in South Florida: therapy involving all of the adults who
have been the boy's guardians during his young life and, regardless
of how the battle over his residency plays out, an upbringing akin
to an open adoption so he can stay in touch with the relatives he
loves and the experiences that have shaped him in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   That Elian appears to have received no professional counseling,
at least to determine his state of mind and assess what help he may
later need, is one indication to many observers that political
considerations and not the child's best interests have been at the
core of the maneuvering over his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe because he seems fine on the surface, no one's
apparently dealing seriously with his longer-term needs or doing
much, if anything, to address the emotional harm and the grief he
has suffered,'' says Bernard Perlmutter, director of the Children
and Youth Law Clinic at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed agree there are two even starker illustrations
of how little thought people have given to Elian's needs and to the
consequences of their behavior on the boy's psychological
development.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the ever-present horde of Cuban-American
supporters, television camera crews, journalists from around the
world, and sightseers outside the Little Havana home in which the
boy has been living with his great-uncle's family since being
rescued last Thanksgiving. All of this has occurred with the
family's apparent willingness to regularly expose the boy to the
crowds and even to bask in the attention it gives him when he comes
outside to play or wave.
</P>
<P>
   As in a custody battle during a divorce, but to a far greater
degree in this case, specialists say that highly focused attention
on children can give them a heightened sense of the power they hold
and of their importance as individuals. The situation eventually
settles, but the higher the children have elevated their sense of
themselves, the farther and harder they fall.
</P>
<P>
   The second way in which nearly all the adults around Elian have
shown a lack of understanding of his needs, according to the
specialists, is by not recognizing that children don't start
thinking abstractly until they are about 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not only highly unlikely that Elian grasps the
permanence of his mother's death _ he has alternately said on
television that he knows she died and that she's still alive
somewhere, suffering from amnesia _ but it's irresponsible nearly
to the point of abuse, in the estimation of Brody and others, for
anyone to ask Elian questions as leading and consequential as where
or with whom he wants to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absurd,'' says Pavao, who says there probably isn't a
parent anywhere whose children haven't expressed a desire to live
with other relatives, friends, or at an amusement park if they were
enjoying themselves or seeking refuge from a problem. ``But this is
a very young child . . . still in shock and in grief, and of course
he would likely say that he wants things to stay as they are. Who
wouldn't?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
