<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Who's not fit to raise Elian?
 &HT;    (For immediate release.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There seemingly is no end to the hideous soap opera
surrounding the 6-year-old Cuban political pawn Elian Gonzalez.
There will be an end, of course, and the sooner the better. But for
the time being, it gets more ugly by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the crowd of lawyers who surround Elian and his Miami
family fanned out to play the network TV talk shows. From their
prattle emerged a picture that Elian's father is unfit to care for
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   About the worst we know regarding the father is that he is a
communist _ and we're not even certain about that. Nevertheless,
being a communist, while deplorable to most of us, isn't even
illegal in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The charge that the father is unfit is a pre-emptive act that
cloaks a question as to whether the Miami family is fit to care for
the child _ and that is a legitimate question!
</P>
<P>
   While there is no available record for Juan Miguel Gonzalez _
the father _ there are several for the Miami Gonzalezes; and
``record'' is the functional term.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 9, The New York Times revealed that 49-year-old Lazaro
Gonzalez, the auto mechanic great-uncle who has possession of
Elian, has a nasty record of drunk driving and driver's license
revocation.
</P>
<P>
   While communism isn't illegal in this country, and certainly not
in Cuba, drunk driving is _ in both places.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles
records, The New York Times revealed that Lazaro Gonzalez, who did
not arrive in the U.S. until 1985, has four convictions for drunk
driving in Florida and that his driver's license was revoked or
suspended for a total of three years. The paper also said the
great-uncle completed an alcohol treatment course in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the paper cited his brother Delfin who, while living in
the Florida Keys, also has spent considerable time at the Miami
house with Elian. Delfin Gonzalez has four Florida convictions for
drunk driving, two involving property damage or personal injury.
The Times says Delfin Gonzalez's license also had been revoked for
a period of two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Herald reported those same findings two days later but
not on its front page as did The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks prior to the New York Times article, the Miami New
Times, an alternative newspaper with a deserved reputation for
muckraking investigative reporting, reported that two of Elian's
cousins, Jose and Luis Cid of Miami _ twin sons of Lazaro's sister
_ have had brushes with the law. Both also frequent the Gonzalez
house.
</P>
<P>
   According to that paper, which cited police and court records,
Luis Cid was arrested last September and charged with strong-arm
robbery of a tourist. In 1994, Luis Cid also was charged with
carrying a concealed weapon and resisting arrest with violence. His
ex-wife charged him with domestic violence and he was arrested
another time for what the newspaper termed ``felony firearms and
prowling charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Cid's twin brother, Jose, was arrested five times between
1986 and 1990 on charges varying from burglary to grand theft and
robbery with force.
</P>
<P>
   When this news was published in the Miami New Times, with an
admission that the paper was not able to unearth whether there were
convictions, Lazaro Gonzalez, through a spokesman, said he had
never before had any knowledge of the eight combined arrests of his
sister's sons.
</P>
<P>
   With that collective baggage to tote, isn't it surprising that
the Miami Gonzalez family lawyers would want to promote an argument
on who is fit to care for Elian?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
