<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PERCEPTIONS-B     04-03 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PERCEPTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFLICT LEAVES HEARTS HARDENED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a land where both sides see themselves as
victims, Palestinians and Israelis often fail to recognize the
suffering of the other.
</P>
<P>
   This tragic axiom of the half-century of conflict here was
captured in a disturbing light last month as Palestinians reacted
to Pope John Paul II's emotional visit to Israel's Holocaust
memorial during his pilgrimage to the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, on a muddy hillside overlooking the Sea of Galilee
while the pontiff presided over an outdoor Mass, James Kajjo, 26, a
Palestinian from Jerusalem, was coldly unmoved by John Paul's call
for Roman Catholic reconciliation with Jews, and for recognition of
Jews' suffering in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler was a good man. Look at what they (Nazi Germany) did to
raise up their country under him,'' said Kajjo, a Roman Catholic
who is college educated and who runs a family printing business.
``If he had killed more we would be much better off. I am not the
only Palestinian who believes this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kajjo's sentiments are commonplace among Palestinians. This kind
of dismissal of the Holocaust, or claim that it is an exaggeration
crop up in many corners of the Palestinian community _ on its
university campuses, in taxi cabs, in its newspapers, and in its
Parliament. The fate of Jews in the Holocaust is virtually absent
from Palestinian high school and college history books.
</P>
<P>
   This not only offends Israelis but serves to undermine the
confidence both sides need to share for the peace process to
succeed. In Israel, where some 300,000 Holocaust survivors live, to
deny or minimize the Nazi genocide is to contradict decades of
research validated by the world's most respected historians, and in
effect to deny the modern history of the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the 6 million Jews killed in Nazi death camps, Kajjo
called the figure ``Zionist propaganda.'' He said he was aware that
``Jews and other people'' were killed, but ``not that many.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want me to do? Cry? Because I can't,'' said Kajjo,
even as the pope's voice carried in the background. ``What did
Palestinians have to do with the Holocaust?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if, as a Catholic, his statements flouted the pope's
message, he replied bitterly, ``The pope lives in Rome, and I live
under occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   These raw views of history came up repeatedly in lengthy
interviews with a random sampling of 12 young Palestinians
encountered along the path of the pope's pilgrimage last month.
Eleven of the students _ a mix of Muslims and Christians from
Israel and the West Bank _ saw the Holocaust as an exaggeration
used as propaganda by Zionists. Nearly half the students said they
saw Hitler in some positive ways. Three said they agreed with
killing Jews in the Nazis' ``final solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Lena Qassem, 22, a Muslim from Nazareth, is in her third year of
medical school at Hebrew University and was trying to catch a
glimpse of the pope as his motorcade passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jews were victims of the Shoah. And we have been the
victims of the Jews,'' Qassem said. ``We think the Jews exaggerate.
It was an ugly part of history, but it was not as bad as they show
it all the time on television and in books. They control the media.
So they can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Palestinians, it is another holocaust. Their homes
were taken, their lives. What the Jews lived through was bad, but
it is over. The Palestinian holocaust is now. People cry every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians are preoccupied with their own suffering, the
plight of 3.5 million refugees, their lives under Israeli
occupation in the West Bank, a peace process that has done little
to change difficult lives, and the uprooting of their culture by
creation of the Jewish state. They only rarely, and reluctantly,
look at how Jews suffered in the Holocaust. Many say they have
suffered in Israel because the West, guilt-laden by its failure to
prevent the Holocaust, has been hesitant to criticize Israeli
violations of international law.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiments are jarring, and seemed particularly so when
uttered by the Palestinian Liberation Organization's chief Muslim
cleric on the eve of his meeting with the pope in Jerusalem's Dome
of the Rock, one of the holiest sites in Islam, during the pope's
interfaith journey through the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six million? It was a lot less,'' said grand mufti Ikrima
Sabri, who is appointed by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, in an
interview published by the Italian newspaper La Repubblica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my fault Hitler hated the Jews. Anyway, they hate
them just about everywhere,'' he added, sentiments he repeated in
interviews with the Associated Press and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli analysts pointed out that such attitudes are woven
into Palestinians' history. During World War II, Sabri's
predecessor as grand mufti of Jerusalem, Mohammed al-Husseini,
supported the Nazi war effort.
</P>
<P>
   Afif Safieh, a Palestinian Catholic and the PLO's general
delegate to the Vatican, said Sabri's comments were taken out of
context, and he reacted furiously to a reporter's question about
them, saying that even to ask was ``guerrilla work'' by the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the immensity and horror of the Holocaust. Whatever the
number, it was horrible. But I also have lived the horror of the
Palestinian holocaust. . . . How do we measure pain? How do we
measure suffering?'' Safieh asked.
</P>
<P>
   That the Palestinian leadership was unwilling to criticize Sabri
for his comments disappointed many Israelis and members of the
Roman Catholic hierarchy accompanying the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Such comments from Palestinians supposed to be among the
enlightened leaders of their people enrage Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Segev, a controversial historian who wrote the explosive
1993 book, ``The Seventh Million: the Israelis and the Holocaust,''
has criticized his homeland for using and sometimes abusing the
memory of the Holocaust for political gain. He dismisses Holocaust
denial in Europe and America as ``a kind of pornography'' that
should be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Arab Holocaust denial is more troubling,'' said Segev,
``because you cannot understand Israel unless you understand the
Holocaust. And you cannot make peace with your enemy unless you
understand him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arabs, by recognizing that Jews are victims, feel it takes
away from their victimhood. And this competition for who has the
market on victimization has been going on for many years. Too
many.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There cannot be real peace until Israelis understand the
Palestinian tragedy, and Palestinians understand the Israeli
tragedy,'' Segev added. ``That is not to say that these two
sufferings are comparable. They are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hisham Ahmed, a Palestinian professor of political science at
Ber Zeit University and a community activist in the Dheishe Refugee
Camp that the pope visited, said he has heard such vicious views
among many students in the classroom. But he said they had to be
seen in light of a traumatized people who feel the world has never
recognized their plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a common mistake of Westerners who come here, to hear
comments like this and exaggerate their importance,'' Ahmed said.
``You have to understand the sentiment, not the words. This
expresses anger, it is a rough way of saying, `Look at what has
happened to us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed and other Palestinian academics agree that the views
expressed by young Palestinians grow out of ignorance of history.
Virtually no history classes in Palestinian schools in the West
Bank and Gaza (which follow a Jordanian curriculum), teach about
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Itimar Marcus, an Israeli member of the anti-incitement
committee of Israelis, Palestinians, and Americans established as a
result of the peace process, has extensively researched the
Palestinian school system and its textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we find is outrageous,'' Marcus said. ``They refer to
World War II, to Nazis, to the rise of Hitler and its racism. But
there is no mention of 6 million Jews being killed. There are,
however, repeated comparisons to Israel and fascism, and often in
vulgar fashion. So there is no outright denial, there is just
complete avoidance, as if it did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian and even some Israeli academics say Israel has, in
turn, denied Palestinian suffering in teaching history, avoiding
confronting the ways in which Palestinians were victimized. Only in
the last year have Israeli high school textbooks taken on the other
side of history in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. And only in
the last few years have the views of so-called ``revisionist
historians'' begun to expose Israel's forced expulsions of
Palestinians in the 1948 Arab-Israeli War and challenged some of
Israel's founding myths, such as the slogan ``A land without people
for a people without land.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Palestinians living within the 1948 boundaries of
Israel, who grew up in the Israeli school system, had a much more
informed and balanced view of history.
</P>
<P>
   Ehab Saaba, 27, a Palestinian from a village near Haifa,
attended Israeli schools with Jews, Muslims, and Christians, and he
said he was sickened to hear some of the comments by young
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler was a killer. Period. Anyone who says anything else is
ignorant,'' Saaba said.
</P>
<P>
   On the same hillside where Kajjo made his comments, a group of
German Catholic pilgrims clustered, seemingly depressed and
saddened by the views some Palestinians were voicing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe there are people out there capable of thinking
that way,'' said Manfard Bastel, 35, of Munich. ``Even today, even
after the pope's message here, even after all we have seen in our
own history.''
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Sennott covers the Middle East for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
