<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-KOREAN-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGING THE DIGITAL AND CULTURAL GAP  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By Stanley T. Lee  
 &HT;    They said it couldn't be done.
 &HT;    A small technology startup dared to challenge the giants of the
telecommunications industry. Two years later, Bitro Communications
pronounced ``bee-tro,'' has proved that it can compete with the
likes of AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint.
 &HT;    The founders of the company chose the name Bitro, which in
Korean means ``toward the light,'' to symbolize the team's mission
to elevate the company to the upper echelons of the telecom field.
But this is an industry dominated by corporate household names and
other Fortune 500 companies. The key to Bitro's success was the
relentless pursuit made by seven young entrepreneurs for a direct
connection contract with Korean Telecom, the dominant telecom
carrier in South Korea _ the equivalent to AT&AMP;T. Several emerging
telecom companies, such as Frontier, Global Crossing and Qwest,
failed in their attempts to establish a relationship with Korea
Telecom, as the company decided to partner only with the Big Three.
 &HT;    But because of their tenacity, Bitro joined AT&AMP;T, MCI and Sprint
in providing long-distance phone service to Korea through Korea
Telecom.
 &HT;    Bitro soon emerged as a leading carrier of voice and data to and
from Korea, surpassing MCI and Sprint. During December 1999, Bitro
handled nearly as much AT&AMP;T, according to Korea Telecom sources.
Now, Bitro is earning over $1 million a month in revenue, with
prospects for future growth. Bitro will expand by merging and
acquiring other companies with direct connections throughout Asia.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, this is a far different picture from when the
company first started in April 1998.
 &HT;    Bitro's founders, composed primarily of 1.5- and
second-generation Korean Americans, struggled in the early months
of operation. Several of them gave up their salaries in order to
preserve every penny of scarce capital. There were numerous
occasions when consecutive nights were spent in the office with
little regard to personal hygiene.
 &HT;    They familiarized themselves with the telecommunications
technology, spending countless hours reading manuals and complex
technical guides. When they called Lucent Technologies for
technical assistance on a switch that they just bought, the Bitro
engineers were the ones that figured out how to make it function
properly, not the Lucent technicians.
 &HT;    Designing and implementing advanced telecommunications systems
presented an enormous challenge, but with sweat and a lot of luck,
their resilience paid off.
 &HT;    When the first call to Korea was made over their system to the
mother of Chris Lee, Bitro's chief financial officer and founder,
tears fell from the eyes of all the founders. Lee commented that
his mother's voice never sounded sweeter.
 &HT;    Bitro will now promote the use of advanced technology to offer
traditional voice and data products at competitive prices. Bitro
CEO and President Tae Joon Kim envisions integrating the Internet
with traditional phone products and new value-added services. One
thing the Bitro pioneers never wanted was to position the company
as a traditional telecom company, let alone a typical Korean
company. But one of the keys to Bitro's success is that it operates
as an American corporation with a strong understanding and
appreciation for Korean culture.
 &HT;    ``We are Koreans, and we are an American company,'' says Patrick
Kim, vice president.
 &HT;    By capitalizing on its dual cultural and philosophical
identities, Bitro hopes to innovate the ways people communicate
globally in the new millennium.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Stanley T. Lee is a contributor editor of Koream magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Stanley T. Lee 
