<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-DRUG-WAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING A FUTILE BATTLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES GARCIA 
 &HT;    Colombia is not another Vietnam. But didn't the United States
learn anything from that war?
 &HT;    The policy toward Vietnam was fueled by fear and ignorance. The
U.S. government was afraid that communists were about to take over
the world. In our ignorance _ and arrogance _ we thought that
carpet bombing the North Vietnamese would convince communists
everywhere that American-style democracy was a better alternative.
 &HT;    Today, the Clinton administration and Congress worry that drug
traffickers in Colombia are trying to take over certain parts of
the world. In their ignorance, Clinton and his supporters suggest
that new legislation to send the Colombian government about $1.7
billion to battle drug traffickers _ and the Marxist rebels that
protect them _ will discourage drug lords from smuggling dangerous
narcotics into the United States.
 &HT;    As with the United States' ill-conceived plans to thwart
Communism in Vietnam, the U.S. drug policy in Colombia will fail.
 &HT;    Colombia's civil war has dragged on for 40 years. To date, about
35,000 people _ mostly civilians _ have been killed in the
conflict, and the death toll continues to mount. Meanwhile, the
U.S. government's involvement in Colombia continues to deepen.
 &HT;    U.S. military advisors routinely provide special training to
Colombia's armed forces. The Drug Enforcement Administration is
involved in extensive investigations there.
 &HT;    American lives have even been lost. In fact, more American
soldiers have died in Colombia than in the war in Kosovo.
 &HT;    Last July, five U.S. soldiers were killed in Colombia when their
airplane slammed into the Andes Mountains during an anti-drug spy
mission. Their deaths, however, attracted little attention by the
U.S. media.
 &HT;    On March 20, Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, explained the U.S. military's mission in Colombia.
 &HT;    ``One of the threats to America's interest is the large amount
of drugs that come in from that region,'' Shelton said during a
press conference at Fort Bliss in El Paso, Texas, where the
soldiers who died were once stationed. ``It is in America's
interest, I think, to do whatever we can to slow the amount of
drugs coming in.''
 &HT;    Colombia produces about 80 percent of the cocaine consumed in
the United States. It is also a major producer of heroin and
marijuana. Last year, Colombian traffickers earned an estimated
$3.5 billion dealing drugs. During that same period, according the
National Association of Financial Institutions, Colombia earned
$3.7 billion producing oil, its leading export.
 &HT;    Shelton did not mention Colombia's rebel armies, which control
about 50 percent of the countryside. We're not officially at war
with them. But no one believes that Colombia's military _ slated to
receive about 75 percent of the $1.7 billion in U.S. aid _ will not
hesitate to use the U.S.-made Blackhawk helicopters it plans to
purchase against rebels if given half a chance.
 &HT;    And since the guerrillas are led by the 17,000-strong
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), which is known to
protect the drug traffickers, there should be plenty of
opportunities.
 &HT;    FARC officials who are involved in peace negotiations with the
Colombian government say the U.S. aid package will only fuel the
war. If the Colombian military uses the added resources to mount a
major military offensive, the rebels vow to strike back hard.
 &HT;    We should also ask ourselves if the Colombian government even
deserves to receive any U.S. aid, especially in light of its record
of military abuses against civilians.
 &HT;    In late February, the U.S. State Department issued a stinging
report charging that in 1999 ``government forces continued to
commit numerous, serious abuses'' that included murders and
torture. The report also documented formal links between the army
and right-wing paramilitary death squads, which, like the rebels,
have profited from the international drug trade. ``Paramilitary
forces find a ready support base within the military and police,''
the State Department concluded.
 &HT;    For his part, Colombian President Andres Pastrana, like his
predecessors, pledged to crack down on human-rights abuses
committed by the government's armed forces. Like his predecessors,
hehas failed to live up to that promise.
 &HT;    In December, Pastrana vetoed a bill that would have created a
government agency to search for thousands of missing leftists and
made genocide an official crime. The United Nations has been urging
Colombia to approve the legislation for the past 12 years. Critics
say Pastrana bowed to pressure from the military, which claimed the
proposed legislation would hamper its efforts against the rebels.
 &HT;    In the end, any money and equipment given to the Colombian
military will be used to fight the rebels and the drug traffickers.
As a result, the war will widen and many more Colombians will die.
 &HT;    As for the drug traffickers, they will simply wait to ship their
goods another day.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James Garcia is editor and publisher of Politico, a national
weekly newsletter focusing on U.S. Latino politics. E-mail
Politico1(AT)aol.com.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James Garcia 
