<SLUG> BC-MONEY-CHILDREN-LIFEBEAT-986&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING MONEY-WISE CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (tlk) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Nancy Lloyd is the author of ``Simple Money Solutions: 10 Ways
You Can Stop Feeling Overwhelmed by Money and Start Making It Work
For You.'' (Random House, 2000).
 &HT;    
 By NANCY LLOYD 
 c.2000 Nancy Lloyd 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   ``After playing at classmates' homes, my 5-year-old son, Bobby,
greets me with questions like, 'Why can't I have as many cool toys
as my friends?' says Kay Johnson. ``I made a choice to stay home
with my kids while they're little but I'm feeling a lot of pressure
to keep up with families where both parents work.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says that she and her husband want Bobby ``to realize
that he just can't get everything he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say you can't afford something if you can because your
kids will look back later and realize it wasn't true,'' cautions
psychologist Sylvia Rimm. ``Say, 'It costs too much and is not
within our value system.' Be firm, but don't deny them
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions such as, ``Why can't I have as many toys as my
friends?'' can be a good springboard for discussing financial
trade-offs. Whether you earn $40,000 or $400,000 a year (or get a
$4 weekly allowance), you have only a finite amount of money and
each person or family must decide what are the best things to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Children as young as 3 develop an interest in money, so talking
about it should begin before your child is unduly influenced by
product advertisements. Don't wait until your child starts school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching kids about money is part of the required curriculum
in only a small percentage of schools,'' says Don Blandin,
president of the American Savings Education Council, a nonprofit
association. Even if your child's school does have saving and
spending lessons, they need to be reinforced at home to have
lasting effect.
</P>
<P>
   A weekly allowance is a practical way to start teaching a child
as young as 5 or 6 how to manage money. The sums are small and
mistakes aren't fatal. By teaching these lessons before your
children head off to college and start getting credit cards, you
may be able to spare them an increasingly common college-student
problem: not having enough money to pay credit card bills and to
buy food.
</P>
<P>
   While a recent allowance survey showed that some teens are
getting $50 or more per week, many parents still give their kids
between 50 cents and a dollar per week per year of age. So an
8-year old would get $4 to $8 weekly. If, however, you expect your
children to pay for school clothes and athletic equipment they will
need more than if you're just providing a little spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Baskin recalls starting her two daughters on allowances
``only after they begged, saying all their friends were getting
them. Chelsea, 11, gets $5 a week and Vanessa, 8, gets $3. I chose
those amounts after talking to other parents about going rates and
what they expected their kids to pay for. My kids' allowances are
not tied to chores.''
</P>
<P>
   Tying allowances to chores often backfires. Sooner or later many
kids will say, ``For that amount of money, I'm not doing those
chores.'' A good compromise for many families is a base allowance,
plus extra pay for additional chores (such as painting the lawn
furniture or cleaning the garage).
</P>
<P>
   Be realistic about the quality of your child's work. An
8-year-old won't paint the furniture as deftly as a professional,
but you're probably paying your child much less than you would a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea is lobbying for a raise to $7 a week. But this larger
sum will come with strings, including saving some of the money,
giving some to charity and even chipping in money to help pay for
friends' birthday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of kids, Chelsea admits, ``I don't have a good idea
of what things cost.'' Before settling on a new amount, she and her
mom have agreed to write a budget and go to a store to check
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who learn the most about money typically have some
restrictions on when and how they can use their allowance. A
portion can be spent immediately, another portion must be saved and
a third portion is to be used to help others via charities or
individuals your family knows who need assistance. Piggy banks can
be inexpensive and as simple as labeling three plastic jars:
``spending money,'' ``saving money'' and ``charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Agree up front about other restrictions on the use of the money.
For instance:
</P>
<P>
   _ Can your child buy anything or are certain toys or other items
not permitted in the house?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is there a maximum amount (or percentage) of saved money that
your child can spend at one time?
</P>
<P>
   _ Can your child use the allowance to upgrade gifts you pay for
(a pricier catcher's mitt or trendier workout clothes)?
</P>
<P>
   Paying an allowance on time is a vital part of teaching a child
how to budget. ``I'm supposed to get paid on Saturdays, but
sometimes they forget and I forget to ask,'' says Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   To stay on schedule, at the beginning of the year, consider
giving each child a notebook or calendar containing 52 IOUs, one
for each week. Then pick a day to give each child their allowance
in exchange for one IOU.
</P>
<P>
   Saving was part of my kindergarten curriculum. As a 5-year-old,
I remember carrying two quarters to school twice a month. My public
school had arranged with a local bank to set up small, free savings
accounts for its students. A bank representative would drop by the
school to collect the money and give each of us a handwritten
deposit slip. Every few months, my mom would drive me to the bank
and we would get the deposits and interest posted to my passbook.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from making saving almost automatic, it was a shrewd
marketing move on the bank's part since consumers develop loyalty
to their first bank. Sadly, with large minimum deposit requirements
and hefty monthly fees, few banks offer free accounts to young
children anymore, but it doesn't hurt to ask.
</P>
<P>
   You can encourage saving with a Family 401(k), by matching money
your child doesn't spend. Whether you match dollar for dollar or 50
cents for every dollar, it's a simple way to show your child how
savings grow and it's easier to understand than compound interest.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS GET THE MONEY MESSAGE YOUNG
</P>
<P>
   Whether children learn to spend and save responsibly will
depend, in part, on the values conveyed to them by their parents.
And kids can begin to get that message when they're quite young.
</P>
<P>
   ``When parents don't have time to spend with their children,
they try to compensate with gifts,'' says psychologist Sylvia Rimm.
``Kids can get so much that they don't value anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a working mom, I always felt guilty. My hours were long, so
to try to make up for the time I wasn't spending with my then
3-year-old daughter, Catlin, I would bring her a gift _ a book or
toy _ every day,'' recalls J.C. Patrick. ``When she'd hear me at
the door, she'd run to meet me. But before saying hello, she would
ask, 'What did you bring me?'''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Catlin turned 4, Patrick knew these ``guilt gifts''
were getting out of hand. She discussed her dilemma with friends
and discovered that they, too, were having guilt pangs about
working long hours and were also overindulging their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a friend said, 'Your daughter would much rather have time
with you than a toy.' So I made a conscious effort to carve out
more time with her. It's amazing what you can learn when you sit
quietly and let your child talk about her day and what's important
to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, breaking the gift-giving ritual was tough. Patrick
recalls a trip to a store when Catlin wanted to buy a toy not on
their list. ``I said 'No,' a word she hadn't heard often, so she
followed me around the store saying loudly, 'I hope you know I'm
bringing this home.' I picked her up and we walked out the door
empty-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   The parent-child tug of war over toys and other must-have
possessions is not limited to homes where parents have demanding
jobs. Stay-at-home parents are also fighting a tougher battle than
June or Ward Cleaver ever did, and it's starting at a younger age.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Patrick knows first-hand that saving money doesn't always
come naturally: ``When I was young, I racked up credit card debt
that took me years to pay off and I don't want Catlin to fall into
the same trap. I'm trying to teach her that we can have as much fun
window-shopping as we can buying things.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
