<HEADLINE>
VERSATILE SHORTBREAD MAKES HOLIDAY BAKING FUN AND EASY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photos of decorative chicken and bunny cookies available
in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Larry Hayden is a contributing editor of ``Country Living''
magazine. &HT;    
 By LARRY HAYDEN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Shortbread is one of the simplest and most versatile of cookie
doughs. Like its precursor, short cakes, which appeared in the
British Isles in the 16th century, it's made from butter, flour and
sugar. These simple ingredients produce a rich, crumbly cookie open
to endless variations. The dough rolls out easily and holds its
shape well, making it a prime candidate for little hands using
cookie cutters. Shortbread's buttery flavor makes it an adaptable
foil for other ingredients _ chopped nuts, chocolate chunks, citrus
rind, candied ginger, even peanut butter. This dough also does well
when used for jelly-filled sandwich cookies, crisp little jam
turnovers, lemon bars and pecan squares. And you can always
``chocolatize'' shortbread by adding cocoa powder.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever extra ingredients you use, the predominant flavor of
shortbread comes from the butter, so it's worth buying the best
butter available. Using unsalted butter permits the sweetness of
the butter to come through while allowing you to control the amount
of salt in the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on oven temperature, cookies can take on a golden glow
or the classic ivory hue. Since all cookies, including shortbread,
will continue to bake as they cool, remove them from the oven a
minute or two before they appear completely done. Cookies that you
want to be crisp yet tender, for example, should be removed from
the oven when they feel firm but still give a little to the touch.
Once cooled, they will be light, crisp and crumbly. On the other
hand, if permitted to completely set while baking, the cookies will
turn out too hard. And always place baking sheets on wire racks so
air circulates around the cookies as they cool.
</P>
<P>
   Making shortbread dough takes only a few minutes and, with the
help of a standing mixer, is effortless. The fun comes when you
realize that every batch of this simple dough can be different _
just add a favorite flavoring, shape with a whimsical cookie
cutter, or decorate with a colorful icing. So indulge yourself and
your family by baking a batch of cookies _ whether to celebrate
spring or to while away a pleasant afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE SHORTBREAD COOKIES (The Basic Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   This basic cookie dough lends itself to nearly endless
variations and possibilities. Vanilla and salt are optional, but
heighten the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups unsalted butter, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract (optional)
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 350 degrees. In a large bowl with mixer on
medium speed, beat butter and sugar until light and fluffy. If
desired, add vanilla and beat until combined. Reduce mixer speed to
low; gradually beat in flour and salt, if using, until a dough
forms.
</P>
<P>
   2. Between two sheets of floured parchment paper, roll out half
of dough to a 1/8th inch thickness. Remove the top sheet of paper
and cut out as many shapes as possible, leaving 1/4 inch space in
between. Press together trimmings. Roll out dough again and cut
more shapes. Repeat with remaining half of dough.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bake until cookies are golden and feel slightly firm to the
touch _ 7 to 9 minutes. Transfer cookies to wire racks to cool
completely. Store in an airtight container for up to four days or
freeze for up to two weeks. Makes 4 dozen 3 1/2 inch cookies.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE DELICIOUS TAKES ON OUR SIMPLE SHORTBREAD RECIPE
</P>
<P>
   Our recipe for ``Simple Shortbread Cookies'' yields cookies that
are rich, buttery and crisp. Enjoy them just as they are or try
these tasty variations on the basic dough.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLASSIC SHORTBREAD COOKIES: Divide the dough in half. Roll out
each half to a 12-inch round. Using a fluted pastry wheel, trim
perimeter and then cut each round into 16 pie-shaped slices.
Transfer the slices to a parchment-lined baking sheet and bake at
250oF until just firm to the touch _ 45 to 60 minutes. Makes around
32 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ GOLDEN SHORTBREAD COOKIES: Make dough as directed. Form 1-inch
balls and place on baking sheet, spaced 1 inch apart. Bake at 350oF
until golden brown _ 10 to 12 minutes. Makes around 5 dozen
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ CHOCOLATE SHORTBREAD COOKIES: When making dough, replace 1 cup
all-purpose flour with 1 cup unsweetened cocoa powder. Form 1-inch
balls; place on baking sheet, spaced 1 inch apart. Bake at 350oF
until just firm to the touch _ 10 to 12 minutes. Makes around 5
dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ RASPBERRY THUMBPRINT COOKIES: Divide the dough into 3/4-inch
balls and place on parchment-lined baking sheets, spaced 1 inch
apart. Flatten each ball slightly with your thumb, making an
indentation in the center of each ball. Spoon a scant 1/4 teaspoon
of seedless raspberry jam into center of each cookie. Bake at 350oF
until cookies are set but not hard and the jam bubbles _ 12 to 15
minutes. Makes around 7 dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ EXTRAS: Add 1 1/2 to 2 cups chocolate chips, chopped nuts,
minced candied ginger, peanut-butter chips, shredded coconut, or
any combination of these to the dough for additional flavor and
texture.
</P>
<P>
   EASTER BUNNY SHORTBREAD SANDWICHES
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients for these decorative cookies are the basic
shortbread dough, 1 1/2 cups of seedless raspberry jam and 2/3 cup
of confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   First, heat the oven to 350oF. Between two sheets of floured
parchment paper, roll out half of the dough to a 1/8th inch
thickness. Place on a baking sheet and refrigerate for one hour.
Next, remove the top sheet of paper and cut out as many bunny
shapes as possible, leaving 1/4 inch space in between. Press
together the trimmings and roll out the dough again. Cut more
shapes. (If the dough becomes difficult to handle, chill in the
refrigerator for 10 to 15 minutes.) Then, using a drinking straw,
make holes for the eyes in half of the shapes. Bake until the
cookies are golden and feel lightly firm to the touch _ 7 to 9
minutes. Transfer to wire racks to cool completely. Finally, cover
the cookies without eyes with an even layer of jam, stopping just
short of the edges. Place the remaining shapes on paper towels;
sift an even layer of confectioners' sugar over tops. Place sugared
cookies on top of jam-covered ones. Add small dollops of jam, if
needed, to fill in the eyes. Store the sandwiches in an airtight
container for up to two days.
</P>
<P>
   BABY CHICK SHORTBREAD COOKIES:
</P>
<P>
   If you wish to use these cookies for decorative purposes only,
substitute 6 large egg whites combined with 6 cups confectioners'
sugar for the meringue powder and water. You'll need two plastic
squeeze bottles and a small pastry bag to decorate the cookies.
Meringue powder and Lemon-Yellow Liqua-Gel No. 11186, which we used
to decorate the cookies, are available from the New York Cake and
Baking Distributor, 56 West 22nd St., New York, NY 10010; Phone:
800-942-2539.
</P>
<P>
   Make the Simple Shortbread Cookie dough, refrigerate it, roll it
out, cut it and bake it as you would for the Easter Bunny
Shortbread Sandwiches. To make the icing, use:
</P>
<P>
   2 1 pound boxes plus 1/2 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons meringue power
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   yellow liquid food coloring
</P>
<P>
   4 dozen mini chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   First, in a large bowl with mixer on low speed, beat two boxes
of confectioners' sugar, meringue powder and cream of tartar until
well mixed. Add water and increase speed to medium. Beat until
consistency is just smooth and pourable _ around two minutes. Cover
tightly with plastic wrap until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Next, divide the icing among three bowls. Add 4 to 6 drops of
yellow food coloring to each of two bowls, stirring until well
mixed. Spoon the white icing into one squeeze bottle and one bowl
of yellow icing into another.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the remaining 1/2 cup confectioners' sugar, 1 tablespoon
at a time, to the second bowl of yellow icing until consistency is
stiff enough to be used for piping; spoon this icing into a small
pastry bag fitted with a No. 6 tip. Using the pastry bag, pipe
yellow icing around a cookie and along the ``cracked'' edge. Repeat
with the remaining cookies. Using the squeeze bottle with the
yellow icing, fill in the ``chick'' parts. Fill in the ``egg''
parts with the white icing. Place a mini chocolate chip on each
cookie for an eye. Allow the icing to dry completely. Store in an
airtight container for up to four days. Makes 4 dozen chicks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
