<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HUMORQUIZ-APRIL-LIFEB     04-03 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMORQUIZ-APRIL-LIFEBEAT-1350-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APRIL FOOL? SOME QUIPS AND JOKES FROM THE FAMOUS AND INFAMOUS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (tlk) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Norman Zierold is a historian and author. &HT;    
 By NORMAN ZIEROLD 
 c.2000 Norman Zierold 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Ever wonder why April 1 is called ``April Fool's Day?'' It's
because the annual calendar used in Europe used to begin with the
month of April. But in 1562, Pope Gregory introduced a new calendar
that ran from January 1 through December 31. News traveled slowly
in those days, however, and many people couldn't read. They refused
to believe that the calendar had changed; they continued to
celebrate April 1 as New Year's Day. Some of those who knew better
mocked them as ``April Fools.''
</P>
<P>
   As time went by and the new calendar became widely accepted, the
reason for April 1 being known as April Fool's Day was largely
forgotten, but the custom continued of playing practical jokes on
others. More benignly, this became a day for telling jokes.
</P>
<P>
   April Fool's Day has come and gone for another year, but it's
still the month of April and humor is always welcome. As American
humorist, Mark Twain, once remarked: ``The first of April is the
day we remember what we are the other 364 days of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quiz that may amuse you.
</P>
<P>
   1. ``I have a 'call' to literature, of a low order _ i.e.
humorous. It is nothing to be proud of, but it is my strongest suit
... seriously scribbling to excite the laughter of God's
creatures.'' So said:
</P>
<P>
   a) Oliver Wendell Holmes
</P>
<P>
   b) H.L. Mencken
</P>
<P>
   c) Mark Twain
</P>
<P>
   2. This fabled encounter between two witty ladies took place
when they arrived simultaneously at the entrance to a New York
restaurant. ``Age before beauty,'' Clare Booth Luce is reputed to
have said as she deferred to her rival. The rival swept through the
open door declaring, ``Pearls before swine.'' Who was the second
lady?
</P>
<P>
   a) Tallulah Bankhead
</P>
<P>
   b) Lillian Hellman
</P>
<P>
   c) Dorothy Parker
</P>
<P>
   3. This noted American could make people laugh in many ways,
including the theater. When he was told that a play of his was an
even bigger success in Paris in a French version than it had been
on Broadway, he showed little surprise, quipping: ``My work seems
to lose something in the original.'' Who was the quipper?
</P>
<P>
   a) Phillip Barry
</P>
<P>
   b) Marc Connelly
</P>
<P>
   c) James Thurber
</P>
<P>
   4. He was a versatile musician, a clever writer and a good
character actor _ indeed he was a ``character.'' One of his popular
songs is ``Blame It On My Youth.'' One of his volumes of
autobiography is called ``Memoirs of an Amnesiac.'' Among his most
oft-quoted quips is this one: ``I knew Doris Day before she became
a virgin.'' His name?
</P>
<P>
   a) Steve Allen
</P>
<P>
   b) Oscar Levant
</P>
<P>
   c) Harpo Marx
</P>
<P>
   5. An enduring comic classic is the ``Lives and times of archy
and mehitabel,'' the work of Don Marquis. Mehitabel is a
sophisticated alley cat and archy is a literary:
</P>
<P>
   a) cockroach
</P>
<P>
   b) bulldog
</P>
<P>
   c) spider
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Pardon me for not getting up.'' Which famous writer chose
this as his own epitaph?
</P>
<P>
   a) William Faulkner
</P>
<P>
   b) F. Scott Fitzgerald
</P>
<P>
   c) Ernest Hemingway
</P>
<P>
   7. ``A classic is something that everybody wants to have read
and nobody wants to read.'' So said:
</P>
<P>
   a) Oliver Wendell Holmes
</P>
<P>
   b) H.L. Mencken
</P>
<P>
   c) Mark Twain
</P>
<P>
   8. ``With 60 staring me in the face, I have developed
inflammation of the sentence structure and definite hardening of
the paragraphs.'' So said:
</P>
<P>
   a) Russell Baker
</P>
<P>
   b) Art Buchwald
</P>
<P>
   c) James Thurber
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Give a man a free hand and he'll run it all over you.'' So
said:
</P>
<P>
   a) Anita Loos
</P>
<P>
   b) Dorothy Parker
</P>
<P>
   c) Mae West
</P>
<P>
   10. He said ``Be good and you will be lonesome.'' He also said
``Few things are harder to put up with than the annoyance of a good
example.'' And he gave this sound advice: ``When in doubt, tell the
truth.'' His name was:
</P>
<P>
   a) Abraham Lincoln
</P>
<P>
   b) Mark Twain
</P>
<P>
   c) Artemus Ward
</P>
<P>
   11. This genial humorist had enjoyed a good dinner well
lubricated by spirits but on leaving the restaurant he met a
drenching downpour. Happily, he saw a heavily braided uniform that
signaled a doorman and asked the man to hail a cab. ``Sir, I'm a
four-star admiral!'' said the outraged officer. ``Well then,'' said
our diner, ``hail me a battleship!'' The diner's name was:
</P>
<P>
   a) Robert Benchley
</P>
<P>
   b) Oscar Levant
</P>
<P>
   c) Ring Lardner
</P>
<P>
   12. President Abraham Lincoln often irritated this Civil War
general by asking for more detailed accounts of his army, leading
the general on one occasion to wire his commander-in-chief: ``We
have just captured six cows. What shall we do with them?''
Unperturbed, Lincoln wired back: ``Milk them.'' Who was the
general?
</P>
<P>
   a) Ulysses Grant
</P>
<P>
   b) George McClellan
</P>
<P>
   c) Daniel Tyler
</P>
<P>
   13. Here's an easy one, the legendary wire sent by a famous
comedian to the Friar's Club of Hollywood: ``Please accept my
resignation. I don't want to belong to any club that will accept me
as a member.'' Who sent the wire?
</P>
<P>
   a) Groucho Marx
</P>
<P>
   b) Harpo Marx
</P>
<P>
   c) Zeppo Marx
</P>
<P>
   14. Perhaps the most famous saying of this noted wit was
embroidered on a pillow in her sitting room: ``If you can't say
anything good about someone, sit right here by me.'' Her name was:
</P>
<P>
   a) Clare Booth Luce
</P>
<P>
   b) Alice Roosevelt Longworth
</P>
<P>
   c) Dorothy Parker
</P>
<P>
   15. This witty lady also famously said: ``I do wish ---- ----
did not look as if he had been weaned on a pickle.'' (She herself
attributed the remark to a fellow patient of her doctor's.) She was
referring to:
</P>
<P>
   a) Warren Harding
</P>
<P>
   b) Calvin Coolidge
</P>
<P>
   c) Herbert Hoover
</P>
<P>
   16. New Englander Calvin Coolidge was well known for his laconic
nature. When a lady seated next to him at dinner said she had made
a bet that she could get more than two words out of him, he
replied, ``You lose.'' On being asked what a reverend preaching on
sin had said, he summed up, ``He said he was against it.'' Perhaps
best known of all his remarks is his pithy political statement: ``I
do not choose to run for president in:
</P>
<P>
   a) 1924
</P>
<P>
   b) 1928
</P>
<P>
   c) 1932
</P>
<P>
   17. When poker-faced Calvin Coolidge died in 1933, this noted
American wit quipped: ``How can they tell?'' So said:
</P>
<P>
   a) H.L. Mencken
</P>
<P>
   b) Dorothy Parker
</P>
<P>
   c) Frank Sullivan
</P>
<P>
   18. ``An egotist is a person of low taste, more interested in
himself than in me.'' So said:
</P>
<P>
   a) Ambrose Bierce
</P>
<P>
   b) Bret Harte
</P>
<P>
   c) Artemus Ward
</P>
<P>
   19. Fanny Dixwell Holmes, the wife of Supreme Court Justice
Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr., often remained at home when her husband
went to social gatherings, but on this occasion she did make an
appearance and was engaged in conversation by none other than the
president of the United States, greatly amusing him with this
remark: ``Washington is full of famous men and the women they
married when they were young.'' Who was the chief executive who
roared at her sally?
</P>
<P>
   a) Theodore Roosevelt
</P>
<P>
   b) William Howard Taft
</P>
<P>
   c) Woodrow Wilson
</P>
<P>
   20. Another U.S. president made this wry observation about the
nation's capital: ``Washington is a city of southern efficiency and
northern charm.'' So said:
</P>
<P>
   a) John Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   b) Lyndon Johnson
</P>
<P>
   c) Ronald Reagan
</P>
<P>
   21. Which clever comic said: ``I never forget a face, but in
your case I'll make an exception?''
</P>
<P>
   a) Milton Berle
</P>
<P>
   b) Groucho Marx
</P>
<P>
   c) Henny Youngman
</P>
<P>
   22. ``Ninety-nine percent of the people in the world are fools
and the rest of us are in great danger of contagion.'' So wrote:
</P>
<P>
   a) Ring Lardner
</P>
<P>
   b) Damon Runyon
</P>
<P>
   c) Thornton Wilder
</P>
<P>
   23. A writer chose this epitaph for his tombstone: ``This is all
over my head.'' His name?
</P>
<P>
   a) Robert Benchley
</P>
<P>
   b) S.J. Perelman
</P>
<P>
   c) E.B. White
</P>
<P>
   24. And finally, this well-known television personality asked
for only one word on his memorial stone: ``Smile.'' His name was:
</P>
<P>
   a) Dick Clark
</P>
<P>
   b) Allen Funt
</P>
<P>
   c) Art Linkletter
</P>
<P>
   SMILE!
</P>
<P>
   Answers 1. c 2. c 3. c 4. b 5. a 6. c 7. c 8. c 9. c 10. b 11. a
12. b 13. a 14. b 15. b 16. b 17. b 18. a 19. a 20. a 21. b 22. a
23. a 24. b
</P>
