<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors for publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; TUESDAY, April 4  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-WARCRIMES (The Hague, Netherlands) _ NATO troops in the
French sector of Bosnia arrest the highest-level Bosnian-Serb to
date, Momcilo Krajisnik, on genocide charges. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Japanese politics were thrown into
disarray Monday by the news that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was in
a coma after suffering a stroke early Sunday and was being kept
alive on a respirator. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move by 1 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY (Beijing) _ In a rare reversal, Beijing's High Court
has overturned the conviction of a Chinese researcher for Stanford
University sentenced to 15 years imprisonment for leaking Chinese
state secrets. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GERMAN-DEATHS (Shanghai, China) _ A German family of four
was stabbed to death in the central Chinese city of Nanjing early
Sunday, a rare incident of violence against foreign residents here
that nonetheless highlights a creeping acceleration of crime across
the country. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Washington) _ Clinton speaks at 1:25 p.m. Eastern
time on China-trade. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Fatma Passage) _ Israel says that after it
withdraws from Lebanon it will take in the Lebanese who now live in
the ``security zone.'' By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE (Jerusalem) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen and Israeli's prime minister, Ehud Barak, wrangle over
AWACS-type planes Israel is selling to China. By William A. Orme
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-FUTURE (United Nations) _ Kofi Annan lays out his vision of
the future of the United Nations. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-KILLING (Undated) _ Jean Dominique, the director of Radio
Haiti and the country's best-known political commentator, died here
from gunshot wounds after being attacked by unknown assailants,
relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developments in the case of Elian Gonzalez
and his Miami relatives' battle to keep him in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   EMBRYOS-DIVORCE (Boston) _ Issuing an opinion in a case it had
already decided, the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court says a
divorced woman cannot use the frozen embryos she created with her
husband because public policy dictates that no one should be forced
to procreate against their wish. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   MAMBO-SALON (New York) _ During the week, many come to the Ene
Hair Salon for trims, highlights, conditioning treatments, maybe an
upper body massage. But come Sunday afternoon, they are infected by
mambo madness when the basement-level salon on East Ninth Street
turns into a dance palace. By Lynda Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _ Washington
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   GAS-ALTERNATIVES (Washington) _ The government once had a plan
to fix the oil problem so that the United States would not have to
pay attention to OPEC any more. Congress passed the plan in 1992,
right after the Persian Gulf War, and by the far-off year of 2000,
10 percent of the gasoline and diesel fuel used for cars, pick-ups,
vans and sport utility vehicles was supposed to be displaced with
other fuels. But thus far, it has been a fairy tale. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
