<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE TAKES THE PRIZE AS THE APRIL FOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What an April Fools' Day. I got taken in by
everything. I thought these things were all Harvard Lampoon jokes.
</P>
<P>
   How about this one? Al Gore interrupted his calls for campaign
finance reform (as opposed to his phone calls for campaign
financing) to repudiate President Clinton's position on 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to give permanent resident status to the Cuban boy
and his father _ in exchange for the worn-out ball of silly putty
that passes as Gore's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   That shyster just lost my vote, if he ever had it. He's worse
than the other shyster.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is playing footsie with the worst right-wing child-stealers
in the world, a bunch of nuts who don't care about the kid but just
want to pull Castro's beard _ even if they have to fight the
federal government in the streets of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been captured by Elian Nation.
</P>
<P>
   There's another bad joke. The biggest family values and foreign
policy issue of the election year is a tug-of-war over a lost kid.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore has come down four-square on the side of two-timing his
boss and talking out of both sides of his mouth. The least he can
do is keep his mouth shut. But Gore has remained true to his
pandering instincts and his inability to be true to anything.
</P>
<P>
   What an April Fools' weekend it was for Democrats. George W.
Bush is the candidate with integrity.
</P>
<P>
   And how about this one: California Gov. Gray Davis has been
suggested as a possible vice presidential running mate for Gore,
which sounds plausible. It's hard to think of any better way to
make Gore seem charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being made of the same wood, Gore and Davis are
philosophically in synch. Raising money is their main concern, and
opportunism their operative word.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has been appointing right-wingers to the state's parole
boards to protect his right flank. To protect his left flank, he
points to his junk gun bill.
</P>
<P>
   Go in a gun store, and you'll see how effective it's been.
You'll see the same wares, junk and non-junk.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed, except that when you buy a gun you're asked
if you've bought a gun in the last month. That's how the
one-gun-a-month bill is enforced _ by taking purchasers' word.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' vaunted gun-control measures are a joke _ almost as big a
joke as his running for vice president on the snooze ticket with
Gore. Unless Gore picks Elian as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
