<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EUROPEAN-CARS-HNS &LR;      04-03 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-CARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ON EUROPEAN ROADWAYS, SMALL IS STILL BEAUTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (EDS: Note optional trim; Web address is CQ)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ For a Texan, one thing stood out quite prominently at
the recent Geneva Motor Show, one of the world's premier annual
automotive events: Pickups were few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on the highways of Switzerland _ and the rest of
Europe, for that matter _ pickups are rare. Perhaps it's all the
foggy, rainy days, as anything in the pickup's bed would be
subjected to the elements.
</P>
<P>
   But this European disdain for the pickup is due to more than
just the weather. A look through the seven exhibit halls at
Palexpo, the Geneva convention center that is home to the motor
show, gave the visitor a keen sense of the practicality of European
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Cars, very little cars, ruled the showroom floor. Cars that get
upwards of 40 mpg, something vital to consumers on a continent
where gasoline sells for an average of $5 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Highways and city streets are quite narrow throughout much of
Europe, too, which makes driving a large vehicle quite a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Europeans do buy the occasional big sport-utility, such as
a Range Rover, Toyota Land Cruiser or Jeep Grand Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who drive those vehicles are among the
continent's most affluent, and they can afford to fill those huge
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Most Europeans drive tiny little cars that we'll probably never
see in the United States, and particularly in Texas, where we
always think BIG in everything, especially cars and hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the cutest or ugliest cars (that depends on the
individual's point of view, and there seems to be no in-between) at
this year's Geneva show, held last month, were the Fiat Ecobasic
and the Mercedes-Benz Smart.
</P>
<P>
   These are the tiniest of econoboxes, smaller even than the
British Mini Cooper, designed for city driving and the most minimum
use of precious fuel. They come with just two seats, small engines
and fuel-economy ratings that have them barely sipping gasoline or
diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Most automakers who sell vehicles in Europe have developed cars
in this segment _ even Mercedes-Benz, whose A-class minicar sells
for under $20,000 and is a big hit among Continental consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes has no plans to sell the A-class in the United States,
however, and it's not just because Americans generally eschew such
small vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   No, the main reason we won't see an A-class sold at U.S.
Mercedes-Benz dealerships is because it's not expensive enough.
Mercedes officials don't believe that a cheap, mass-market vehicle
such as the A-class would be a good mix with its line of luxury
cars.
</P>
<P>
   BMW does plan to introduce a minicar to the U.S. market next
year in the form of the next-generation Mini, developed while BMW
owned Britain's Rover Group, which builds the Mini Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   What sales channel BMW will use for the Mini is not clear, but
one thing is: It won't be sold at traditional BMW dealerships,
whose line of cars is similar to that of Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   Small sport-utility vehicles were a big hit at Geneva this year,
because while Europeans generally can't afford or don't want the
hassle of driving huge SUVs, they still like the concept of the
sport-utility.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota showed off its second-generation RAV4 mini-SUV, Ford
introduced its Escape, and Tata, India's No. 1 automaker, displayed
its Safari, a 90-horsepower model about the size of the Escape
(which goes on sale later this year at U.S. Ford dealerships).
</P>
<P>
   Small vans and panel trucks are huge sellers in Europe, and
almost every mass-market automaker has two or three in its lineup.
Those vehicles were prominent throughout the Palexpo halls.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were the Renault Kangoo and the Toyota Yaris.
</P>
<P>
   To Americans, these are quite odd-looking little vans, but their
body styles are popular with Europeans. This type of car is the
European's idea of a utility vehicle, because it can be used to
haul people or cargo, and the cargo is inside, protected from the
elements.
</P>
<P>
   The closest we've seen to these tiny vans in the United States
have been vehicles such as the 1980s Toyota Tercel four-wheel-drive
wagon, the Mitsubishi Expo and the Dodge Colt Vista wagon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One tiny, very practical vehicle at the Geneva show could become
a niche-market star in the United States: the Twike.ME.
</P>
<P>
   This essentially is a fully-enclosed, three-wheel, two-seat
electric motorcycle that also can be pedaled.
</P>
<P>
   Built by SwissLEM Ltd., the Twike.ME carries two people and
their luggage, goes up to 52.7 mph, and can negotiate slopes up to
22 degrees. Known as a ``light electric vehicle with complementary
pedal drive,'' the Twike is quite popular with Swiss motorists.
</P>
<P>
   With aluminum space-frame construction and a plastic body, the
lightweight Twike can go up to 50 miles on a charge, and the
batteries can be recharged in under two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The driver and passenger have pedals, so the range can be
extended by pedaling instead of using the motor. For steering, the
consumer can choose between a conventional steering wheel or a
joystick.
</P>
<P>
   Electric Vehicles Northwest Inc. in Seattle is working toward
getting the Twike approved for use on U.S. highways. Check out the
Twike Web site at http://www.twike.ch/english/international.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular European minicar that eventually might find its
way to U.S. shores is the three-door, hatchback Ford Ka, powered by
a 1.3-liter, 60-horsepower gasoline engine that gets nearly 43 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   It has a top speed of 96 mph, which makes it suitable for U.S.
freeway driving, and it goes from zero to 60 mph in 14.3 seconds _
no hot rod, but adequate for most people's needs. In Britain, the
Ka sells for about $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of the cute, inexpensive cars that crowd the streets
and highways of Europe will never be seen in the United States, the
automakers say _ unless gasoline prices go a lot higher than they
are now.
</P>
<P>
   To Europeans, our gasoline prices are a bargain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
