<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-FALCONE-HNS &LR;      04-03 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAN CBS SCORE A HIT WITH NEW MOB SHOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you're going to like CBS's very ambitious new series,
``Falcone,'' basically comes down to this: Do you have HBO or not?
</P>
<P>
   If you do, then you probably watch ``The Sopranos.'' In fact,
that show may be the reason you subscribed in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have HBO, well, hey, you're 12 bucks richer every
month, and ``Falcone'' is a decent enough mob show that's made for
television. Commercial television. And maybe you'll enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   That is: If you haven't already seen ``Donnie Brasco,'' the
feature film based _ like this show _ on the undercover exploits of
FBI agent Joe Pistone. Or ``The Godfather'' series. Or
``GoodFellas.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can tell, there are a lot of asterisks attached to this
show. It's probably not fair, but you can't throw a mob show on TV
without getting a ton of comparisons _ fair or not.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is launching ``Falcone'' (Tuesday at 9 p.m. Eastern) in a
two-hour premiere, followed by nightly viewings at 10 p.m. all the
way through April 12 (except Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   Does this show really need an explanation? If we must:
``Falcone'' essentially has two stars. There's Jason Gedrick as Joe
Falcone, an undercover FBI agent, who's in deep, tracking the mob
and simultaneously losing touch with his own family, particularly
his wife (Amy Carlson). And there's Titus Welliver as Santino
``Sonny Boy'' Napoli, burgeoning mob power player. Falcone hooks up
with Napoli and down the drain of underworld carnage and chaos they
go.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a wild ride, really. Made more intriguing by the fact
that CBS is pulling out the stops and launching this show like it
was some massive May sweeps miniseries. If people aren't hooked by
the first two hours on Tuesday, it's going to be a long, long ride
to nowhere for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   However, a substantial number of people ought to tune in for a
peek, given that CBS is pushing the show during the NCAA basketball
tournament and there's a natural curiosity in this country for mob
stories.
</P>
<P>
   But, wait. ... Is there? Taking nothing away from Gedrick and
Welliver, who make for some solid TV viewing as dark-haired tough
guys, why would anyone watch this show if a) they've seen the
movie, b) they don't have eight days of free time already blocked
out and, most importantly, c) they could watch ``The Sopranos''
instead.
</P>
<P>
   This much we know: By the time ``The Sopranos'' came on the air,
Hollywood had pretty much played out that genre. Like cop shows
before it, getting all mobbed up didn't hold the same kind of
emotional payout it once did for viewers. Been there, done that.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the brilliance of ``The Sopranos,'' which flat-out
embarrassed any other competitor, there was no longer a need to try
to do mob shows. What was the point? Unless Francis Ford Coppola or
Martin Scorsese were going to take another swing at it, the
definitive modern version of the mob was being played out every
Sunday on HBO to frighteningly great critical acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Who would be dumb enough to launch a mob show on commercial
television where you couldn't swear, you'd have to tone down the
violence and no one could get naked? Uh, CBS, apparently. This show
was going to debut in the fall, but bending to congressional
pressure about violence on TV, the network wanted to retool the
violence and bring it back when things cooled down. Unfortunately,
things had heated up at HBO. But, not content to cede Mafia stories
to pay-TV, ``Falcone'' was put on the schedule for the rest of the
mob-hungry country that doesn't get HBO (which means most of it).
</P>
<P>
   The question remains, however: Why? Are there really millions of
people who want a watered-down, commercially interrupted,
half-challenging competitor when they can get the best show on
television on HBO?
</P>
<P>
   CBS is banking on it. That's why we have this crazy, nonstop
``Falcone'' marathon. It will be interesting to see how it all
unfolds. The show is good but not great. It feels redundant because
it is _ two times over, if you count the movie. There's no denying
that's a huge drawback, no matter how brooding Gedrick and Welliver
get. And, from a pure entertainment standpoint, it's less
satisfying to see Falcone's wife and family implode than it is to
see what's happening with Tony Soprano's home life. Sorry, but it's
true.
</P>
<P>
   CBS can't get away from its own ghosts. Several years ago it had
a tremendous mob show called ``EZ Streets.'' CBS gave up on it
quickly and that amazing little gem of a show withered and died
without much trace.
</P>
<P>
   Has CBS's audience changed that much? No, it hasn't. Should we
expect the same seldom-seen exit for this show? At least
``Falcone'' has the advantage of having the network interested in
its success. If ``EZ Streets'' had this kind of support, maybe
``The Sopranos'' would never have been made in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but that's history. The question now is, will ``Falcone''
be?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
