<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULPTOR-HEADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG HEADACHE: SCULPTURES FROM TEXAS SPARK DEBATE IN VIRGINIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG, Va. _ When Thomas Jefferson came back to Virginia
two weeks ago, he didn't get a hero's welcome. There were no red
carpets, no praise-filled speeches. Many folks just wished he would
go away _ far away. Like maybe to the middle of the Mojave Desert.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's travel mates, former Presidents Martin Van Buren,
Woodrow Wilson, Herbert Hoover, John F. Kennedy and Ronald Reagan,
didn't fare any better. That might seem odd, given the Williamsburg
area's obsession with history.
</P>
<P>
   But these heads of state are just that. Heads. Big concrete
heads, some standing 18 feet tall. And for some who take their
history _ and community image _ seriously, they are just too
``tacky, tawdry and tasteless.''
</P>
<P>
   The statues are the work of Houston sculptor David Adickes, the
artist who created the towering concrete statue of Sam Houston
erected near Huntsville, Texas, and the disembodied cellist on the
plaza of downtown Houston's Lyric Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Before year's end, Adickes and his Virginia backers hope to
install the six presidential heads _ along with 35 others now
stored in Adickes' Houston warehouse-studio _ in a forested
educational park in York County, just outside Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Adickes, 73, believes the statues will perfectly complement
Colonial Williamsburg _ the meticulously restored/re-created
British capital of colonial America _ and nearby Yorktown, site of
the last major battle of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The first six heads, which arrived March 17, were to have been
temporarily displayed on their pedestals at a Days Inn owned by
Adickes' partner, Williamsburg real estate developer Everette H.
Newman III. The planned, but later aborted, display was designed as
a ``show and tell'' to ease the project's way through the
permitting process.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it launched a withering fusillade of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surely not in danger of overgentrification as long as
these Barnumlike entrepreneurs are able to push such things off on
us,'' one resident raged in an unsigned letter to a local
newspaper. ``My wife and I considered and rejected a suicide pact,
but we are thinking seriously of moving on if this abomination is
approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivor Noel Hume, who for 18 years was chief archaeologist for the
Colonial Williamsburg Foundation, agreed. ``The proposed Presidents
Park has to be the tackiest project to exploit and pollute
America's heritage since composer-lyricist Kermit Goel turned
Pocahontas into a musical, and that was nigh on 40 years ago,'' he
fumed.
</P>
<P>
   W.C. O'Donovan, editor and publisher of the feisty twice-weekly
Virginia Gazette _ which boasts of its 1736 founding as the first
paper in the South _ insisted that the statue park would be better
situated in the wide-open spaces of the Mojave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Williamsburg would have been much better served if
Adickes had taken up painting miniatures,'' he huffed.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of Gazette readers responding to the
paper's ``Heads or Tails'' poll opposed the project. Overall,
critics felt the heads insufficiently ``authentic'' to join the
Peninsula's historic milieu, defined by Colonial Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Adickes, who has invested four years and $1 million in the
project, seemed nonplussed by the uproar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone is missing the point,'' Adickes said last
week. ``This is not a slapdash thing thrown together. It is as
authentic as any contemporary sculpture can be. It is a very
high-level thing for people to go to. It's one more thing that can
be listed among attractions of the Williamsburg area.''
</P>
<P>
   Adickes said his presidential head project was inspired by Mount
Rushmore in Keystone, S.D. _ and by the fact that the presidential
visages there were hard to appreciate without binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with the first six heads to Virginia, Adickes noted
that passing motorists frequently snapped photos of the
presidential caravan, even at night. At fueling stops, Adickes
frequently was beseeched for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   The project's target audiences, he suggested, are schoolchildren
and a mythical couple he named ``R.V. Harvey and his wife, Lou.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's R.V. like `Recreational Vehicle,''' Adickes said.
``Retired people. R.V. Harvey and his wife, Lou. They eat at
Shoney's and stay there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He likened the project's critics to painter Grant Wood's
portrayal of Daughters of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're there with their teacups and snarled-up faces,''
Adickes said. ``Williamsburg is full of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, there are people who are trying to balance
the books. Williamsburg is slipping. The cultural tide is turning
against the purity of beautiful little places. (Nearby) Busch
Gardens and other places are running away with their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the prime nonhistorical attractions in the Williamsburg
area is Water Country USA, a water park developed by Adickes'
partner, Newman. It now is owned by Busch Gardens, which attracts
about 2.5 million visitors each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're having to do something within taste to improve their
overall economic picture. Those who understand that are in favor of
doing things to bring tourists,'' Adickes continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Williamsburg. I'm thrilled every time I go there. They
have re-created that century very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Andrews, spokesman for Colonial Williamsburg, which includes
88 original buildings and hundreds of re-created and restored homes
and shops on its 173-acre compound, said park attendance has been
growing. As many as 3 million people visited the village in the
most recent year for which figures are available. Not all of them,
however, purchased tickets to tour houses and other historic
structures.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said the heads will be installed on 12 landscaped acres
adjacent to his Days Inn East, just outside Williamsburg. The park
will be screened from view of passing motorists by a buffer of
natural forest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a tourist attraction in the sense of having a lot of
bells and whistles,'' Newman said. ``These presidents don't dance,
and they don't sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has developed about $25 million of projects in the
Williamsburg area, and even critics like O'Donovan credit him as
``a good guy'' for the tasteful development of Water Country USA.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said the proposed park's primary mission is educational,
and each statue will be flanked by signs explaining the president's
historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Chestnut, sales manager for Newman's FCR Group, said she is
working with educational agencies in each state to ensure that
schoolchildren visiting the site will be eligible for class credit.
She said that as many as 250,000 students might visit the park
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said much of the opposition to the presidential park
grows out of anger over other developments _ realized or only
attempted _ in the Williamsburg area. One of the most controversial
projects is a miniature golf course under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a proposal for a Ripley's Believe It Or Not
``odditorium'' was rejected, in part because of a Colonial
Williamsburg director who held a seat on the planning commission.
</P>
<P>
   The first skirmish in the battle of the heads came when York
County officials disallowed temporary display of the heads mounted
on their pedestals at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   All sides agreed that the county originally gave an informal
green light to such an exhibit. But while the heads were en route,
county officials revisited the issue and determined such display
would be prohibited by county ordinance, said Assistant County
Administrator J. Mark Carter. He said Newman will have until the
end of the week to find another temporary location for the heads,
which remain chained on flat-bed trailers in the hotel parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there was some misunderstanding,'' Carter said.
``All I can say is we regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut had her own theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truckers started seeing the heads as we were driving them over
and calling the radio stations about them,'' she said. ``The radio
guys, without bothering to find out, put out the word that they
were destined for an amusement park to be built in Williamsburg.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to develop the sculpture park, Carter said, Adickes and
his backers will need to petition York County for a special-use
permit. That process, which requires review by the county planning
commission and action by the board of supervisors, usually takes at
least three months.
</P>
<P>
   Newman at first said such an application might be made this
week, but later said park proponents instead might argue that the
park qualifies as a museum, which would not require a special
permit. A county spokesman said that argument already has been
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, Adickes and Carter all agreed that plans to erect a
92-foot statue of George Washington _ a component of the park that
had drawn intense criticism _ have been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the controversy, the Colonial Williamsburg
Foundation, founded in 1926 with money donated by John D.
Rockefeller Jr., has remained neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The project certainly has raised eyebrows in the
neighborhood,'' said foundation spokesman Andrews. But the
organization will not consider taking a stand in the debate until
it has had opportunity to review the formal park proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Much-published archaeologist Hume, who still works as a
consultant for the foundation, had no such qualms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my feeling,'' he said, ``that the heads are simply one
manifestation of the dumbing down of history and the exploitation
of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums of punishment, matchbox museums, these sorts of things
grow up around historic places. People exploit the past as a
business, and I don't see anything wrong with that as long as it
doesn't lower the public's impressions or expectations of the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   As the controversy rages, Adickes said he actively is looking
for property for two other presidential head parks. One, he said,
might be near Mount Rushmore, where the concrete statues could warm
up visitors for Gutzon Borglum's better-known visages of
Washington, Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt. He
said he also is investigating sites in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   A second set of statues already has been poured into rubber
molds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Virginia, the first six heads have become de facto
shrines.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the oversized head of President Reagan, cracking at the
neck from rigors of the road, lies a wilted bouquet of supermarket
flowers. A silk red rose adorns the ear of Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath Wilson _ like Jefferson, a Virginia native _ a silk rose
rests next to a lizard-green Mountain Dew bottle in a fragrant pile
of fallen dogwood blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
