</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FRAUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHDOG GROUPS WARN OF LIKELY ELECTION FRAUD IN PERU 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Election is Sunday, April 9) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ With the presidential race tightening, election
observers are warning that the Peruvian government may tamper with
the results of Sunday's vote to guarantee victory for President
Alberto Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of fraud ``is very real,'' said one foreign
election monitor who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Fujimori campaign, he added, ``Everything up to
now points to a desire to win at all costs. You don't spend
millions of dollars putting together this type of machinery only to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Fujimori dismissed such concerns and
pledged that the Peruvian vote will be free and democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for months, the U.S. State Department, the Organization of
American States and independent observers have described Peru's
electoral process as being grossly unfair to opposition candidates
while stacking the deck in favor of Fujimori, who is running for an
unprecedented third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Little has been done to address these concerns, the observers
say, and confidence in the government's National Electoral Office,
known by its Spanish initials ONPE, to carry out a clean election
is evaporating.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, two ONPE members have been accused of taking part in a
scandal in which more than 1 million signatures may have been
forged in order to get Fujimori's name on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possible involvement of ONPE officials in the alleged
falsification scheme has damaged the credibility of the very
organization whose mandate it is to guarantee the integrity of the
electoral process,'' said a report issued March 24 by the
Atlanta-based Carter Center, which has been monitoring Peru's
electoral process since last year.
</P>
<P>
   With nine candidates in the presidential race, it may be
difficult for Fujimori to score an outright victory in Sunday's
first-round vote. If no one gets more than 50 percent of the
ballots, the two top finishers will meet in a runoff in June.
</P>
<P>
   The latest survey by the Lima polling firm Apoyo showed
Fujimori's support at 37 percent and that of second-place candidate
Alejandro Toledo at 27 percent. In a runoff, many analysts believe
that the divided opposition could unite behind Toledo and sweep him
to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Toledo is moving up in the polls and it looks like
Fujimori could lose in a second round, it's obvious that there are
dangers of fraud in the first round,'' said one Peruvian election
monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts claim that many officials in the Fujimori government
are desperate to remain in power, because they fear a slew of
lawsuits over alleged human rights violations, corruption and other
abuses should Toledo win.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for the government to steal the election are vast,
according to Transparency, an independent Peruvian electoral
watchdog body.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, due to the lack of volunteers in outlying areas,
monitors from opposition parties will be present at just one-third
of the 87,000 voting precincts. The rest will be staffed only by
government electoral workers and the military. Problems could occur
during the initial, manual counting of ballots or the
transportation of electoral materials, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Transparency points out that the vote count and the settling of
any disputes will be done by electoral workers and untenured
judges, many of whom owe their jobs to the Fujimori regime.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the results are tallied, the ballots will be
destroyed. In many mountain and remote jungle villages, the
military _ which has been fiercely loyal to Fujimori over the past
10 years _ will transport census sheets with the results to larger
cities, where they will be fed into computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For fraud to take place, the army has to cooperate precisely
because of this role they have in transporting the vote tallies,''
said Coletta Youngers, an expert on Peru at the Washington Office
on Latin America, a think tank known as WOLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an area that will be very difficult for international
monitors to watch. It is the weakest link in the chain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there have been increasing calls by opposition
candidates and some Peruvian newspapers for the military to stay
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent interview at the government palace in Lima,
Fujimori dismissed such scenarios as sour grapes by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidates with the least support are always the ones who
cry fraud,'' Fujimori said. ``In spite of the imperfections that
must be corrected and are being corrected, this is simply one more
Peruvian election, like the one we had in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet according to a WOLA report, the 1995 election was no model
of electoral hygiene. For example, even though Peruvian security
forces are banned by the Constitution from voting, about 50,000
police and army soldiers cast ballots in the 1995 elections. the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no doubt that Fujimori won the presidential
race, the 1995 congressional election was rife with irregularities,
WOLA said. Nearly 7 percent of the ballots disappeared, and 41
percent were nullified by electoral authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls in 1995 predicted that Fujimori's coalition
would get 25 percent to 35 percent of the seats in Congress. But
official results gave the president's coalition an all-important
majority.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS, which declared elections in Panama in 1989 and the
Dominican Republic in 1994 to be rigged, could come to the same
conclusion in Peru, according to Eduardo Stein, who heads the OAS
team monitoring the process.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Fujimori wins in a clean election Sunday, Peruvians may
have little faith in the results due to all the shenanigans leading
up to the vote, according to Santiago Pedraglio, a columnist for
the Lima newspaper Gestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will believe it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
