<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5621 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-UNDERCOVER-HAZARDS-2N     04-03 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERCOVER-HAZARDS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... and back.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the precautions, Evans said recently, he constantly
worries that a mistake will happen. Stressing that police from 27
departments _ from federal, state and city agencies, as well as
colleges and universities _ are involved in law enforcement in
Boston, Evans said: ``It's awfully easy for something to go wrong.
. . . A tragedy like that can mar a department and a city for an
awfully long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, the former Boston commissioner, says racial
stereotyping adds extra peril for black police officers working
undercover. ``If you talk to them, you'll hear how black police
officers know it's a problem and it worries them,'' Bratton said.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is serious enough that one major organization that
represents black police officers now routinely recommends that they
think twice before taking on undercover assignments. New York City
Police Lieutenant Eric Adams, head of 100 Blacks in Law
Enforcement, said, ``Until it is as safe for an African-American to
work undercover as it is for a white man, I would urge my
colleagues not to take those assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Association of Minority Law Enforcement
Officers has not taken a position on the issue, according to its
head, Boston Patrolman Larry Brown. Because of the precautions
Evans put in place, black officers can decide themselves if
undercover work is too dangerous, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, as elsewhere, the percentage of blacks assigned to
undercover work is usually greater than their overall numbers on
the police force. For example, 42 percent of the rank-and-file
officers assigned to the Strike Force, which concentrates on gang
violence in Boston, are black, while the department itself is 26
percent black.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of black officers retreating from undercover
work concerns most police commanders. Blacks working in such
undercover assignments are ``essential to our crime-fighting
capacity,'' said Sergeant Detective Margot Hill, spokeswoman for
the Boston Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the problem of racial stereotyping has some black
officers rethinking how they ought to respond when witnessing a
crime in progress while they are off duty. In many cities,
including Boston, off-duty officers are required to respond to
crimes they witness, whether in uniform or not. But that does not
mean they have to pull their guns, some officers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my colleagues to be a good witness to the events that
are going on; the crisis will resolve itself in due time, and
they'll be safe and be able to testify as to what happened,'' said
R. Muhammed Bessard, a 26-year veteran of the Berkeley, Calif.,
department.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald E. Hampton, executive director of the National Black
Police Association, said he believes Young's death in Providence
might have been prevented if the federal government had previously
identified this problem in undercover police work and coordinated a
program to make departments aware of the danger. He also said that
black officers should have considered the problem more serious than
they have.
</P>
<P>
   Having been a policeman for 23 years, and as head of the
organization that represents about 15,000 black law enforcement
officers, Hampton said the problem is significantly worse than
shown by the 12 shooting casualties in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of us knows of near misses or of people being
roughed up without being badly hurt that just never make the news
because the (black) police officer just doesn't want to buck the
system,'' said Hampton. ``The number of officers shot is bad
enough, but it's lucky that it's not a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton and leaders from other black police organizations have
met with Justice Department officials on several occasions since
1995, asking that more attention be paid to whether racial
profiling contributes to these shootings. While the federal agency
has investigated two recent shootings for possible civil rights
violations, it has not filed any charges, said a Justice Department
official who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   As for an investigation of the overall problem of racial
stereotyping faced by minority officers while undercover or off
duty, the official said that the Justice Department has lacked
statutory authority to conduct such a probe until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno
announced that the Justice Department would establish a committee
to take an in-depth look at policing in the United States. It is
likely that the problem of racial profiling would be taken up by
the committee, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A top White House official on race issues said the federal
government and individual police departments should be doing far
more to prevent minority officers from being shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would urge departments to provide better training and come
up with better ways of identifying police officers who are
undercover or in plainclothes,'' said Robert Ben Johnson, executive
director of the President's Initiative for One America. ``We're
seeing the awful consequences of these things: It is agonizingly
painful for a family to go through and it divides communities along
racial lines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
