<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT-LOOPHOLES-B     04-03 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-LOOPHOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESCRIPTIONS ELUSIVE FOR CURBING MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Microsoft Corp. and prosecutors tried to
negotiate an antitrust settlement, they bogged down over how to
craft a loophole-free agreement that gave the famously aggressive
software maker no room to wriggle out of its promised changes in
behavior, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the same problem will likely face Federal District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is presiding over the case.
</P>
<P>
   With settlement talks collapsing on Saturday, Jackson is
expected to issue his verdict this week on whether Microsoft broke
the nation's antitrust laws. All indications are that he will rule
that Microsoft did violate the law, and that the trial should next
consider what penalty is in order.
</P>
<P>
   But as the judge tries to fashion a penalty, some analysts say
he will run into the same problems that hampered the settlement
talks: How to put limits on a diverse and aggressive company that
maintains complex relationships with both allies and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard enough for the government and Microsoft, working
directly with each other, to fashion a workable set of conduct
remedies,'' or limits on Microsoft's business behavior, said Rich
Gray, a Menlo Park, Calif., antitrust lawyer who has followed the
case closely. ``It's going to be even harder for a federal judge to
impose a workable set of remedies based on arguments and briefs and
a formal hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Justice and 19 states charge that Microsoft
illegally used its Windows software monopoly to bully other
companies into taking actions that hurt consumers, and to try to
crush two companies, Netscape Communications Corp. and Sun
Microsystems Inc., which produced potential rivals to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing 76 days of testimony, Jackson issued ``findings of
fact'' last November that sided overwhelmingly with prosecutors and
portrayed Microsoft as a ruthless monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of settlement talks, which had been mediated by a
federal judge in Chicago, show how complex Jackson's task could be
if, as expected, he rules that Microsoft's conduct merits a
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   His challenge could be glimpsed in the Justice Department's last
settlement offer, which, according to sources, held that Microsoft
would be required to set a uniform pricing schedule for Windows.
Microsoft would not be able, for example, to raise the price of
Windows for a computer-maker who wanted to load Netscape's Internet
browser, and not Microsoft's browser, on the computers it sold.
</P>
<P>
   But critics among the 19 states, as well as Microsoft's rivals
in the computer industry, complained that price was just one
mechanism that Microsoft uses to manipulate other companies, one
source said. Microsoft could still bully companies by backing out
of joint marketing deals or by withholding the right to display the
Windows logo on their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the software industry is that companies have
ongoing, deeply integrated business relationships,'' said one
person familiar with the prosecutors' thinking. ``With Windows,
it's not like you sell someone a car and they drive off the lot
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, this source said, the final Justice Department
proposal required Microsoft to reveal, for a fee, the most basic
computer code of Windows so that computer-makers could make
modifications. A computer-maker might include Netscape's browser
with Windows and make sure that the two products worked well
together. Or the computer-maker could change the screen that users
see when the first turn the computer on.
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft reserved the right to withhold technical
support from parts of the software that had been altered. Critics
said that made the concession meaningless, because no
computer-maker would accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Ford saying that if you buy a new hood ornament,
your engine warranty is violated,'' said Ed Black, president of the
Computer and Communications Industry Association, which favors
tough sanctions against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also proposed, according to one source,
that Microsoft could integrate new features into Windows, but that
it could not write sales contracts that forced anyone to buy a
second Microsoft product along with Windows. Black said that
provision was weak, because Microsoft had many ways to bully
computer-makers into adopting Microsoft products and rejecting
products from Microsoft rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Justice Department proposal were requirements that
Microsoft reveal software code that allows other software-makers to
link their own products to Windows, and that technical information
be shared equally with all of Microsoft's partners without
discrimination. Justice Department lawyers also wanted to bar
Microsoft from raising the price of old versions of Windows when a
new one is released, a tactic Microsoft uses to encourage buyers to
adopt the newest edition of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Black said that the issue of how to enforce any agreement with
Microsoft was paramount, because the company had been so aggressive
in the past. In fact, it signed a consent decree to settle an
earlier case with the government, only to be accused by prosecutors
a year later of violating the terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Gray said it is difficult to enforce any company's promise
to change its practices. Even when company rules bar it, an
aggressive sales force or business-development team may want to cut
special deals on pricing or advertising to move a company's
products into new markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is a big organization, and for them to fully police
something with full internal cooperation is a non-trivial
exercise,'' Gray said. ``For an outside government agency to police
it . . . is just damn hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to go to the question of `Can the government
trust Microsoft?' before I get pessimistic about the value of
conduct remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   An alternative would be to impose a structural change on
Microsoft, such as breaking the company into pieces, possibly one
that produces Windows and one that makes other types of software.
</P>
<P>
   That penalty is considered by far the most extreme, but those
most critical of Microsoft say it is the only way to strip
Microsoft of one of its major advantages: the fact that it makes
both the Windows operating system and the word processors, Internet
browsers, graphics programs and other ``applications'' products
that works in conjunction with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and several of its allies sought to blame several of
the 19 state attorneys general in the case for the breakdown of
settlement talks. ``It's unfortunate that an outspoken minority of
AGs is holding the industry hostage by derailing settlement talks
at a time when resolution seemed possible,'' said Jonathan Zuck,
president of the Association for Competitive Technology, a trade
group that includes Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The National Taxpayers Union faulted ``overzealous state
attorneys general'' who ``would rather make headlines that make
headway toward ending this case.''
</P>
<P>
   But one person familiar with proceedings said that the feeling
was fairly uniform among states about what the settlement should
include, though states most involved in the talks may have
developed the strongest feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he doubted the deal fell apart just because of the
states. ``It's clear that Microsoft did not meet Justice's
standards for an agreement, regardless of meeting the standards set
by the states,'' Gray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
