<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAYING OF A MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The woman at the megaphone, Sacha Sanchez, is a familiar
character in the street theater surrounding Elian Gonzalez. Each
day she launches into a monologue attacking anyone who dares
suggest that the little boy should some day return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez talks and talks and talks. She routinely screeches into
her bullhorn for well over an hour the following screed: Clinton
has no guts; no morals, either. Every time she sees him she thinks
of Monica Lewinsky. Hillary Clinton traveled to Cuba in the
mid-1970s (understand that this registers as a major offense to
this audience, true or not) and is a secret sympathizer with the
Castro regime. Janet Reno practically has blood on her hands.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez is a middle-aged woman who has lived in Miami for far
longer than she lived in Cuba. She is at the vanguard of a graying
movement, the hardcore anti-Fidels. These are people whose politics
have been shaped by betrayal and nostalgia. The sad saga playing
out here taps into their longstanding grievances against Castro and
their equally enduring dream of an end to exile.
</P>
<P>
   It is they, not the Cuban-Americans who were born here, who
provide the most vocal support for Elian. There are individual
exceptions, of course. One spots the occasional twenty-something
carrying a Cuban flag, or a picture of the boy. In the city beyond
the barricades, there is broad belief that Fidel is a maggot, and
that anything that makes him uncomfortable merits support. If the
exile community could vote on a country for Elian, America would
win hands down.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, particularly in the 1970s, the Cuban question
routinely whipped people here into a frenzy. One Spanish-language
talk show host lost his legs in a car bombing that was believed to
be the work of those who found him insufficiently hardline in his
opposition to Castro's policies. Musicians and actors who had
appeared in Cuba could not perform in Miami; paintings that had
been displayed there were not welcome in galleries here _ unless a
curator didn't mind the risk of having his or her place blown up.
Any talk of the US trade embargo was unacceptable, save for praise
for the government's commitment to ``freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent years have brought neither retreat nor surrender, but at
least a bit of calm. It has become possible to publicly question
the embargo and live to tell. Nothing has been bombed in a while.
The Fidel death watch continues, of course, but at a slightly lower
level of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   To many younger Cuban-Americans _ the two generations raised
here in the last 40 years, most of whom have never set foot on
Cuban soil _ Elian's fate is mildly interesting, but not the stuff
of life and death. As one old friend said to me this weekend, ``I
hope the kid stays. But, hey, I've got a mortgage. And that's how
most younger Cubans I know feel.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend probably doesn't know Josephine Betancourt, or
Mercedes Rodriguez. Both in their 60s, they insisted Sunday they
would give up anything, even life itself, before they would see
Castro win. They've lived under Castro and know what a horror it
would be for Elian to go back, they said. They both said they are
inspired by the belief that Elian's mother died for his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to die for him,'' said Rodriguez. ``Other people
are going to die for him. He represents motherhood and freedom and
life and all the children under the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   For some people here, Castro will always be a life-and-death
matter. His regime ended capitalism, oppressed and impoverished
untold numbers of people, and created a generation of political
prisoners. Most poignantly to them, he destroyed the notion of
home, of safety. Decades later, they thunder from exile, from new
homes the reality of which cannot dislodge their memories of
paradise lost. Through an unlikely sequence of events, they are
holding fiercely onto something they believe Castro holds dear,
and, as their foe Bill Clinton might say, they intend to fight
until the last dog dies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
