u i BC-PERU-TOLEDO-HNS &LR;      04-03 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-TOLEDO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-EDUCATED TOLEDO APPEARS HEADED TO PRESIDENTIAL RUNOFF IN PERU 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Election is Sunday, April 9) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ When he was 7, Alejandro Toledo prowled the
cantinas of his hometown in the wee hours of the morning, wiping
the boots of drunken fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would shine their shoes. Then they would spill beer on them,
and I would have to clean them again,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Harvard-trained economist, Toledo is aiming for Peru's
most illustrious job.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's presidential election, he is staging an unexpectedly
stiff challenge to President Alberto Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Fujimori appeared invincible in his
controversial push for a third five-year term. But during the last
few weeks, Toledo has rapidly moved up in the polls. And, on the
streets of Lima, there is now talk of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Although Toledo is not expected to triumph in the current
nine-candidate race, he could garner enough votes to force a runoff
with Fujimori _ a contest that, analysts say, Toledo could win.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in many years, there is a feeling that
Fujimori might lose,'' said Guillermo Loli of Apoyo, a private Lima
polling firm.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori must get more than 50 percent of the vote in order to
win in the first round and avoid a June runoff.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Apoyo poll, the president had the backing of 37
percent of the respondents, followed by Toledo with 27 percent. In
a one-on-one race, another Apoyo survey showed that the men were in
a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Some predict, however, that Toledo will falter.
</P>
<P>
   International monitors have accused the government of waging a
dirty-tricks campaign against opposition candidates and blocking
their access to the media, charges that Fujimori has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also have warned that the government could attempt
election-day fraud in an attempt to ensure a first-round Fujimori
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under these conditions, it will be almost impossible for
Toledo to defeat the president, something which would no doubt
happen if there was a fair election,'' wrote columnist Fernando
Rospigliosi in the Lima magazine Caretas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, Fujimori, 61, has been called Latin
America's most successful president _ and one of its most
authoritarian.
</P>
<P>
   First elected in 1990, he has been credited with defeating the
Shining Path guerrilla movement and engineering an economic
turnaround. Re-elected by a landslide in 1995, he has spent much of
his second term concentrating powers in his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts now describe Peru's Congress as a pro-Fujimori,
rubber-stamp body, and many say meddling by the executive branch
has severely compromised the independence of the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   With the approval of both the Congress and the courts, Fujimori
managed to skirt a constitutional ban on sitting presidents running
for three consecutive terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken together, these actions suggest a systematic plan to
pave the way for an April 2000 victory for President Fujimori,''
according to a recent report by the Washington Office on Latin
America, a think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Toledo, 54, has overcome worse odds. He was born into a
family of subsistence farmers in the mountains of western Ancash
state. Seven of his 16 brothers and sisters died as infants.
</P>
<P>
   His family moved to the Pacific port of Chimbote, where he
worked as a shoeshine boy and sold newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo was a talented student; he won scholarships to a
prestigious high school in Peru, then to San Francisco State
University in California.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his campaign office last week in Lima, Toledo
admitted that ``there was some culture shock'' when he arrived in
California in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   He said he mistook many of the long-haired men for women and was
shocked to see a couple making love in a campus fountain.
</P>
<P>
   When Toledo heard Black Panther Eldridge Cleaver speak in
Berkeley, a friend had to brief him about the civil rights movement
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo adapted and went on to earn master's and doctorate
degrees at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   He studied and taught economics at Harvard and worked for the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Peru in the 1980s and ran for president in 1995.
At the time, President Fujimori was riding high after defeating the
Shining Path guerrillas and taming hyperinflation. Fujimori cruised
to a landslide re-election, and Toledo finished a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Peru's economy is stagnating.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate is at 9 percent, but 43 percent of the
work force is in the ``informal'' sector, earning money through
such pursuits as selling trinkets on street corners.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Toledo says he plans to continue the free-market
reforms initiated by Fujimori. But he also promises to pay more
attention to impoverished rural areas and create thousands of new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He blames Fujimori for an autocratic streak that, he says, has
undermined the country's democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have strong institutions, you don't have a good
climate to attract investment,'' Toledo says. ``Fujimori's
authoritarianism is insulting. He treats Peru like it's his own
cornfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Toledo's appeal, observers say, is because of his
rags-to-riches background and his Indian features, which allow him
to connect with the poor and other mixed-race Peruvians.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, most of the other opposition candidates in the
presidential race are upper-class white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see themselves in Toledo,'' said Loli of the Apoyo
polling firm.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Toledo's late emergence in this year's campaign
echoes the 11th-hour ``Fujimori phenomenon'' of the 1990 election.
Just weeks before election day, Fujimori was a little-known
university rector who registered single digits in the polls. But as
the son of Japanese immigrants and an obvious political outsider,
he appealed to many Peruvians, who were fed up with corruption by
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round of the 1990 election, Fujimori came in a
close second to novelist Mario Vargas Llosa, who had been the
favorite. In the second-round runoff, Fujimori won the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For Toledo, a key factor has been his charisma on the campaign
trail. Until recently, opposition candidates have had trouble
getting air time on Peruvian TV, which is dominated by
pro-government stations, leaving them little choice but to
barnstorm for votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the TV channels closed off, it forced the candidates to
take to the streets,'' said Juan de la Puente, an editor at the
opposition daily newspaper La Republica. ``Toledo was good at
reorganizing his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though much of Fujimori's own popularity among the poor
stems from state support of soup kitchens and other welfare
programs, the president labels Toledo an unrealistic ``populist''
who, he says, will destroy Peru's economic stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snake-oil salesmen are coming around and promising to resolve
the country's problems overnight,'' Fujimori said at a recent
campaign rally. ``But we will not permit a return to the chaos and
populism of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, critics say, Fujimori's campaign has relied
on a scorched-earth strategy designed to smear his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The effort has already undercut some of the president's
challengers, including Lima Mayor Alberto Andrade. The
pro-government media vilified Andrade for months, and he is fading
in polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toledo has benefited from the demise of his colleagues, but
now it's his turn,'' Rospigliosi wrote in Caretas.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Fujimori camp has trumpeted allegations
that Toledo fathered an illegitimate child.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case was thrown out by a judge for lack of evidence
five years ago, Fujimori's campaign is preparing TV spots to hammer
Toledo on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Crespo, a Lima resident, said he was a member of one focus
group, organized by Fujimori's campaign, that was shown a 25-minute
video featuring Toledo's purported daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the video, everyone (in the focus group) was
saying: `He's a disgrace. How can he deny his daughter? I wouldn't
vote for him,''' Crespo said. ``They are going to ruin Toledo's
image.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pro-government tabloids are full of scandalous
headlines. They claim that Toledo's wife, a Belgium-born economist
and anthropologist, is obsessed with Peruvian men and seduces them
behind her husband's back. One story said Toledo is so vain that he
believes he is singing idol Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo laughs off the onslaught and predicts that it will
backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harder they attack me, the higher I go in the polls,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
