<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EROTICA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEX SHOW (HO-HUM) HEADS TO SAN FRANCISCO  
 &HT;     (ATTN: N.Y.) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In New York, it got the mayor hot under the
collar and thousands of customers, well, hot _ or at least curious.
</P>
<P>
   Now Erotica USA 2000 is bound for San Francisco, home of the
Folsom Street Fair and the Exotic Erotic Ball. And promoters of
what purports to be the nation's first sex trade and consumer show
are, frankly, worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in San Francisco is, we consider the town so blase
about these types of things that this may not be enough to
titillate the press or create controversy. We want our name in the
paper so people know about it,'' said Fred Bari, New York insurance
dealer, sex entrepreneur and one-third partner in Erotica USA.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to oblige, Fred.
</P>
<P>
   After three sellout shows in London, the concept hit the United
States last year. For four days, New Yorkers lined up outside the
Javits Center, usually home to pharmaceutical conventions or auto
shows, to spend $30 to $150 to cruise booths full of latex wear,
sexual devices, XXX-rated videos, tattoos, and erotic art from
people like ``Chainsaw Chuck.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican candidate for
Senate in New York, called it a big mistake for a public venue _
the state-owned Javits Center _ to open its arms to
``Erotica-whatever-it-is.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the press stirred things up, ``the people at Javits called
us in and said, `What would it cost to make you go away?''' Bari
said. ``We said we're not doing anything bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in San Francisco, the fact that the show will occupy the
city-owned Bill Graham Civic Auditorium for four days, April 13-16,
is seen as rather vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for comment, Mayor Willie Brown's press secretary
Kandace Bender said: ``One of the truly spectacular things about
San Francisco is that there's always something unusual going on.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco public health workers see the show as a golden
opportunity to educate people about safe sexual practices. They
will staff a booth offering information about avoiding and treating
sexually transmitted diseases, according to Larry Meredith,
director of community health promotion and prevention for the
Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an everyday thing,'' Meredith said. ``We're at bars,
street fairs, every venue where we can get our message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Erotica USA calls itself the world's largest erotic trade and
consumer show, with 100 booths, plus lectures from some of the
usual suspects of the sex scene _ Candida Royale, a '70s porn star
who produces what she calls feminist porno; fetish diva Midori; San
Francisco sexologist Carol Queen. And porn icon Annie Sprinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Its arrival on the scene is part of the increasing mainstreaming
of the porn industry. Among exhibitors at Erotica USA in New York
were Barnes and Noble, Tower Records (which will be at the San
Francisco show, too) and a distributor for AT&AMP;T Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Internet sex sites are generating huge revenues,
unlike most other e-commerce, put porn.com on the cover of U.S.
News &AMP; World Report in March. And Playboy.com is about to become
the first X-rated Internet business that Wall Street will allow to
be traded on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how spicy Erotica USA's fare is depends on who's doing
the looking. The promoters are walking a fine line, making it sound
racy enough to pique people's interest, but not so lewd as to
discourage exhibitors or bring down official heat of any kind.
Everyone has to be 21 to get in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be girls dancing. It will be as erotic as they can
make it without being porn,'' said Erotica USA 2000 publicist Ken
Maley. ``No one will actually be having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naina Ayya, spokeswoman for SMG, the company that manages Bill
Graham Auditorium for the city of San Francisco, said nudity is
out. The company checked before renting to Erotica USA for $3,500
per day or 20 percent of the gross take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legitimate show,'' Ayya said. ``I know they're going to
have erotic videos and publishing, but here in San Francisco it's
kind of passe. I mean it's like, what of videos?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Joe Boxer, the San Francisco underwear mogul, passed on
being a sponsor or exhibitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a pretty G-rated company. It's worked for us
for years,'' said company spokeswoman Leigh Oshirak.
</P>
<P>
   The Tom of Finland clothing maker also chose to stay away,
according to Maley.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based company, which takes its name and design
inspiration from the explicit, homoerotic drawings of an artist
known as Tom of Finland and whose Los Angeles store features an
erotic art exhibit, told Maley it was trying to become more
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Playboy had no interest in exhibiting because
the show was too tame, Maley said, but Playboy Channel will send a
reporter to cover the show.
</P>
<P>
   Bari said that although the New York show generated long lines,
the show just about broke even. Like everything these days, it's
all about the Internet _ in this case, promoting Bari and company's
Web site, which hawks sexual products.
</P>
</TEXT>
