<HEADLINE>
A GROWING LIST OF OFFICERS KILLED BY OTHER OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
The following police officers were killed by other officers during
the past decade while working undercover or off-duty. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1) Jan. 28, 2000 _ Cornel Young Jr. A sergeant with the
Providence Police Department. Age 28. Young was shot by two white
patrol officers who mistook him for an armed suspect while he tried
to break up a fracas at a restaurant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2) July 18, 1998 _ Thomas F. Hamlette Jr. A District of Columbia
patrolman. Age 24. Breaking up a fight at his family-owned club,
Hamlette pulled his gun and was shot by a white, on-duty police
officer who had been called to the scene. &QL; 
 &QL; 
3) Feb. 16, 1998 _ Randy Analdo Stephens. A marshall in US
Territorial Court in Virgin Islands. Age 35. Trying to execute an
arrest warrant while he was working in an undercover operation,
Stephens was mistaken by an off-duty, black officer as an armed
suspect and shot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4) Feb. 7, 1995 _ James M. McGee Jr. District of Columbia
patrolman. Age 26. McGee, who was off duty, was shot by a white
patrol officer at night after he drew his gun while trying to break
up the robbery of a cabdriver. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5) Feb. 10, 1995 _ Mark White. Patrolman with the Roseville,
Calif., Police Department. Age 30. White was shot when, in
plainclothes, he drew his gun to confront an armed man who had
burst into the Roseville police station. Another white officer
acknowledged that he fired at White after mistaking him for a
second gunman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
6) Nov. 7, 1994 _ Rufus Gates. A major with the Memphis Police
Department. Age 39. Gates was shot while off-duty and in
plainclothes after drawing his gun in a confrontation with the
passengers of another vehicle at the scene of an accident. Another
Mempis police officer, also black, mistook Gates as an armed
felon. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following police officers were wounded during the past
decade by other officers while working undercover or off-duty. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Feb. 27, 1998 _ Dexter Brown, sergeant in the New York City Police
Department. Age 35. Brown was shot twice in the lower back by a New
York City police detective, a Hispanic, who mistook him for an
armed suspect after an undercover drug buy that Brown was working
went awry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dec. 19, 1995 _ Lani Jackson-Pinckney, detective in Washington D.C.
Age 33. In civilian clothes, she and a partner were in the process
of trying to stop a car-jacking when a patrol officer, who was
white, arrived on scene and ordered her to drop her gun.
Jackson-Pinckney, who was pregnant at the time, was shot in the
back as she turned towards the officer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Aug. 22, 1994 _ Desmond Robinson, patrolman with New York City
Transit Authority. Age 32. Pursuing an armed robber in a Manhattan
subway station while working undercover, Robinson was mistaken as
an armed felon by an off-duty, white police officer and shot four
times. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sept. 22, 1994 _ Graham Sylvester, patrolman with Baltimore Police
Department. Age 39. While working on an undercover drug raid,
Sylvester, who is white, was shot in the arm by another member of
the raiding party who mistook him for an armed suspect. The race of
the officer who fired the shot was not determined. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nov. 3, 1993 _ Scott Collier, patrolman for St. Louis Police
Department. Age 32. While working an undercover operation, Collier
was critically wounded by six bullets when other officers in the
raiding party become confused in the darkness and begin firing at
Collier and his partner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nov. 17, 1992 _ Derwin Pannell, patrolman for the New York City
Transit Authority. Age 26. While arresting a fare-beater on a
dimly-lit Brooklyn subway platform, Pannell was mistaken as a
mugger by three white, anti-crime officers. They fired 21 shots,
hitting Pannell once in the neck and twice in his protective vest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
