<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-PAVAROTTI-BOS &LR;      04-03 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PAVAROTTI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT TENOR   RETURNS, FIT AND OPTIMISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, 1975, Luciano Pavarotti made his Boston debut in a
Symphony Hall recital sponsored by BankBoston Celebrity Series. At
that time, the tenor was still establishing himself in the
affections of the public. Walter Pierce, then executive director of
the Celebrity Series, recalls that the hall was only two-thirds
full.
</P>
<P>
   This week Pavarotti, for decades the most popular classical
singer in the world, returns to Symphony Hall for his first local
concert since 1993. In a recent telephone interview from his home
in Italy, Pavarotti was reassured to hear the unsurprising news
that his Boston concert, scheduled for January but postponed
because of legal obligations in Italy, had sold out immediately;
there would be no empty seats this time. ``That, I hope,'' he said,
with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The concert marks Pavarotti's 11th appearance for the Celebrity
Series. He also sang Cavaradossi in ``Tosca'' opposite Magda
Olivero, Nemorino in ``L'Elisird'Amore,'' and Riccardo in ``Un
Ballo in Maschera'' in the Hynes Auditorium on the Metropolitan
Opera tour. He appeared in a memorable Boston Pops concert, under
John Williams, that provided the climax of his one Hollywood film,
``Yes, Giorgio.'' A Three Tenors concert announced for Foxboro
Stadium was canceled after disappointing ticket sales, but
Pavarotti will join Placido Domingo and Jose Carreras again in
Albany, N.Y. in August.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago Pavarotti made the formal announcement that he
would retire next season, 40 years after his debut in ``La Boheme''
on April 29, 1961. The 64-year-old singer has since exercised the
tenorial prerogative of changing his mind. ``I don't think I've
quite reached that point,'' he said. ``I don't think the voice is
spoiling, and I feel good. I enjoy singing so much and people seem
to enjoy listening to me, so I want to keep on doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenor has reason to feel good these days. For years, he had
been in great pain and stage movement had become almost impossible
for him; he sang Cavaradossi sitting down. People sometimes made
fun of his weight or confidently declared that he was losing his
voice because they didn't know what the problem really was.
Finally, in August 1998, he underwent knee and hip replacement
surgery. ``I am absolutely sorry that I did not do this before. Now
the pain is over; I suffered so much.'' Pavarotti, an expert
horseman, hasn't been on horseback since his surgery. ``I have to
take these things gradually. But this year I would like very much
to play tennis again. I will have to see.'' Right now, Pavarotti
prefers to concentrate on vocalizing. ``It is important for me to
vocalize every day.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his Met debut in 1968, Pavarotti was sure he
would never return. ``I had Hong Kong flu when I sang my first
performance at the Met _ a singer is very vulnerable to things like
this, and I had Hong Kong flu for a month. I had to cancel my
second performance of Rodolfo in `La Boheme' during the
performance, and I was thinking, `I will never be in this theater
again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Guess again
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as everyone knows, he became one of the Met's greatest
stars. Pavarotti is back in the Lincoln Center this season, where
he will participate in a gala performance with Domingo and
Carreras, each singing an act of an opera. ``I will sing an act of
`Turandot,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me guess which one,'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed and said ``That's good.'' The whole world knows that
he would have to sing Act 3, which opens with the aria that has
become his signature, ``Nessun dorma.'' Paradoxically, although
Pavarotti has sung the aria often, he has seldom performed the
entire role of Calaf. ``I sang it three years ago at the Met; at
that time it had been 20 years since I had sung it. But the Met has
asked me to do it again, so they must have been happy. Not bad,
eh?'' Pavarotti said he would be singing ``Tosca'' and ``Aida'' at
the Met next season; he likes singing ``Aida,'' but like every
other tenor, he says, ``It would be marvelous if `Celese Aida' came
later in the opera. To walk onstage and sing that is awful because
everybody knows that aria and knows how difficult it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavarotti, who has sung just about everything he could in the
Italian repertory, says he has no new roles in mind. ``I am not
looking, but one could still come along. There are so many roles
that I still enjoy singing.'' He continues to record. ``I would
like to make an album of songs, even some being written today.''
And he has been working on a CD of some of the literature he is
scheduled to sing in Symphony Hall _ nearly all of his operatic
roles are on disc, but his recital repertory has not been as
thoroughly documented.
</P>
<P>
   He will sing three ``early-music'' pieces by Bononcini,
Beethoven, and Scarlatti; a group of six Bellini songs; the two
arias from ``Tosca,'' eight songs by Paolo Tosti, and ``Una furtiva
lagrima'' from Donizetti's ``L'Elisir d'Amore.''
</P>
<P>
   At the piano will be his friend Leone Magiera, who was once the
husband of Mirella Freni. ``I love very much the recital singing,''
Pavarotti says. ``In the recital you are alone, in front of your
audience, with the composer and the piano; it is beautiful. Leone
Magiera is from Modena, too, and I have known him since I was 12. I
was an alto then, singing in church; my voice changed when I was
about 15. At the beginning it was a very high tenor, and when I
changed the voice, I began to imitate the movies of Mario Lanza _
not just `The Great Caruso,' but all of them. He had a fantastic
voice, not just a wonderful voice, a fantastic voice. I am a
fanatico for Mario Lanza.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce looks back
</P>
<P>
   Pierce recalls that Pavarotti's first Boston recital was
accompanied by Metropolitan Opera assistant conductor Eugene Kohn;
later his collaborative pianist was John Wustman. Several times he
appeared with orchestra; his choice of conductor was usually
Emerson Buckley, who had conducted his American debut in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Pavarotti came the second time, a year later, he
had appeared on magazine covers,'' Pierce remembers. ``He was also
doing those ads for American Express, spouting water out of his
mouth. The second concert sold out, and so did all the others. We
did one of his concerts at the Opera House. There was some kind of
problem at the Met, a strike or the potential for a strike, so his
management called and asked if we could put on a concert fast. `How
fast?' I asked. `About a week,' they said, and we did it. We sold
it without even having to run an ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Pavarotti concert Pierce remembers in particular detail.
``We were presenting a concert on a Tuesday night in the
Metropolitan Center, which is now the Wang Center. On Friday, I got
a call asking me to come over. An engineer had declared the roof
faulty and they had to close the building immediately. We had to
look all over town, and wound up at the Hynes Auditorium, where
there was no time to put the risers in; we did it with a flat
floor. People came early with their tickets and we tried to put
them in comparable locations. Everything was going smoothly until
10 minutes to 8 _ when there was no Pavarotti. He had been looking
at horses up in Beverly all day, and had neglected to tell the
driver when to pick him up. So I jumped to my car and went to the
Ritz to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce recalls another occasion when he went to pick up
Pavarotti at the airport. ``He had lost about 80 pounds, and John
Wustman came out first. `He whispered, `You'll make a lot of points
if you tell him how much weight he lost' so I lost no time in
telling him how much better he looked. We always did well with
Pavarotti, and his presence helped the Series out a lot. And he
never canceled in Boston _ he saved that for Chicago!''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Pavarotti was here, in 1993, he sang in the Boston
Garden; the audience sat on a special floor built over the Bruins'
ice, and the tenor emerged from a kind of sultan's tent at the back
of the stage. Pierce was at the airport that time too, but his
services weren't needed. ``When he landed at the airport, the plane
opened its hatch and the cars drove out and took him straight to
the Boston Garden _ they drove up the ramp the circus used to take
the elephants in. He never once hit the ground until he walked out
to sing!''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Pavarotti's career has been thoroughly documented on CD
and video; if he didn't want to, he'd never have to subject himself
to the strain and tension of live performance again. ``But live
performance is what I love,'' Pavarotti says. ``It is always
different; you never know what is going to happen, and when it is
good, it's fantastic _ a great, great feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
