<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-(TRIMS)-     04-03 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S PRIME MINISTER IN COMA   AFTER STROKE; AIDE TAKES OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese politics were thrown into disarray Monday by
the news that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was in a coma after
suffering a stroke early Sunday, and was being kept alive on a
respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese learned of the gravity of Obuchi's condition early
Monday, nearly 36 hours after he was hospitalized early Sunday with
complaints of extreme fatigue. The news was delivered at a hastily
convened press conference by the prime minister's chief Cabinet
secretary, Mikio Aoki, who used the occasion to announce that he
was temporarily assuming control of the government on the prime
minister's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In a marked change from the halting and long-delayed
announcement of the prime minister's hospitalization, Monday's
events only seemed to accelerate. By late afternoon, televised
reports specified that Obuchi was breathing only with the
assistance of a respirator, that he had been given drugs to reverse
a catastrophic drop in his blood pressure and that he might not
recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently he is in a coma,'' Aoki said. In a formula usually
reserved in Japan for people near death, the acting prime minister
added that Obuchi's condition was ``beyond prediction.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as other politicians issued statements of sympathy and
concern, Obuchi's uncertain prospects for recovery set Tokyo's
political class into high gear. Faction leaders within the
long-ruling Liberal Democratic Party and opposition leaders alike
moved to prepare campaigns either to succeed the prime minister
within his own party or to unseat the Liberal Democrats in upcoming
general elections.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the elections that must be called by October,
Japanese politicians had already begun intense behind-the-scenes
jockeying prior to Obuchi's stroke. For several months now, the
government has suffered dwindling popularity because of a series of
scandals involving public officials, high unemployment and a
faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   With Obuchi's resignation or removal for incapacitation now
highly likely, Japanese political analysts said Monday that the
country would almost certainly hold elections before Japan hosts a
summit meeting of the world's leading economic powers, the Group of
Eight, in July.
</P>
<P>
   Early speculation over Liberal Democratic Party candidates to
succeed Obuchi centered on Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the
party, and foreign minister Yohei Kono. Two former prime ministers
have also been prominently mentioned: Kiichi Miyazawa, Obuchi's
finance minister, and Ryutaro Hashimoto, Obuchi's immediate
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Few people Monday mentioned the possibility that Aoki would
serve as anything other than a strictly interim leader. Already, in
his 24 hours at the helm, Aoki has faced mounting criticism of his
exercise of authority, particularly of the way the public was
spoon-fed information about the crisis, beginning 21 hours after
Obuchi's hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For many, the crisis seemed to highlight the creaky nature of
Japan's rules of succession and underscore the deeply ingrained
attitude among those in power that in times of crisis the public's
right to know counts for little.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most cited examples of these weaknesses Monday was
how the prime minister's office deceived the press corps early
Sunday by announcing that Obuchi had risen at 6 a.m. and was
spending the day at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
   It was learned later that the prime minister had checked into
Juntendo University Hospital at 1 a.m. Sunday, hours before the
press briefing was given.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like the war-time government announcements, deceiving
the people,'' said Atsuo Nakamura, an independent member of
parliament. ``Even 50 years later, the administration is following
the same pattern, hiding problems and putting off announcements.
All the while they are having discussions on how to advance their
own interests arising from the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   One Japanese journalist in the press corps that covers the prime
minister, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: ``It is no good
telling lies to the Japanese people. In this incident, their
falsehood has been revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Aoki, who has announced most of the publicly known information
about Obuchi's condition, first told the nation of a problem with
the prime minister's health only shortly after 11 p.m. Sunday. Even
then, Aoki strove to minimize the problem, telling the nation in
his four-minute-long comment that the prime minister had remained
conscious and had been driven to the hospital in a private car
rather than by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, however, Aoki was telling a dramatically
different story of Obuchi's stroke. Looking grim-faced as he spoke
to the press, Aoki said that Obuchi had been placed on a respirator
by 9:50 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by somewhat antagonistic reporters, Aoki acknowledged
that this meant that the prime minister had already lost
consciousness well before the acting prime minister's first vague
statements to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper editorial writers have speculated that Aoki extended
the information vacuum as long as possible to favor the kind of
back-room consultation process over a new leader that defines
Japanese politics. Other critics have focused on the barely
scripted mechanism by which Aoki assumed authority, simply claiming
to have been asked to do so in an unspecified conversation with
Obuchi that apparently had no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Japan's constitution is unusually vague about what should happen
when a leader suddenly vacates power. In this instance, Aoki relied
on the so-called Cabinet law, which allows a prime minister to
personally designate his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the earlier times, when the Cabinet was formed, the prime
minister would designate an acting prime minister just in case
something happened to him,'' said Isao Sato, an emeritus professor
of law from Sophia University. ``This is not a legal name, but they
were informally called deputy prime ministers, making it clear who
was to take over.'' He added that this practice had ``become less
and less common.''
</P>
<P>
   Sato said the practice had fallen into disuse because faction
leaders in the Liberal Democratic Party resented the naming of an
official who would henceforth have an early start in the succession
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, faced with the prospect of Japan's first emergency
succession in 20 years, many politicians criticized the law's
vagueness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not based on the constitution, and it is a big problem
that two people can decide the supreme authority of the state all
by themselves, at their own discretion'' said Naoto Kan, the policy
director of the Democratic Party, Japan's leading opposition group.
``This has all occurred without witnesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
