<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MCCARTHY-BOS &LR;      04-03 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MCCARTHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOLD WOMAN OF LETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SEEING MARY PLAIN 
A Life of Mary McCarthy 
By Frances Kiernan. W.W. Norton. 
768 pp. Illustrated. $35. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't easy to see Mary McCarthy plain, although she directed
her leveling gaze in many directions, including her own.
</P>
<P>
   She was known for her beauty, her intelligence, her versatility,
her accomplishments, her candor, her ferocious wit, and, because
she was a woman and people love to gossip, the company she kept.
She was married four times, once to the eminent critic Edmund
Wilson, and she had several prominent lovers.
</P>
<P>
   She kissed _ and she also told, so men took her on at their own
risk, and some lived to regret that. A career contrarian and a
writer most of her life, McCarthy was an all-around woman of
letters, producing short stories, essays, theater criticism, travel
books, journalism, polemics, novels, and autobiography, genres that
frequently overlapped in her work. ``Novelistic'' detail enlivened
her journalism, polemics fueled her novels; her travel books are as
much about people as about places. And just about every word she
ever wrote was autobiographical; the one quality of a great writer
that she lacked was invention.
</P>
<P>
   In the essay, McCarthy was witty and polished with a deadly aim;
only Gore Vidal, wider-ranging, was any kind of rival at this. One
of her novels, ``The Group,'' became an international bestseller
and a movie. And William Maxwell, a great novelist who was once
McCarthy's editor at The New Yorker, believes that her short
stories and her first volume of autobiography, ``Memories of a
Catholic Girlhood'' are her finest achievement and what posterity
will value. ``The anguish beneath the highly polished surface is so
real. Nobody could fail to respond to that. If people still have
hearts, a hundred years from now they'll respond to it,'' according
to Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was notorious for her tongue as well as for her pen.
Paradoxically, this literary figure came closest to pop celebrity
not because of ``The Group'' but because of something she said
about writer Lillian Hellman on television in 1979. ``Every word
she writes is a lie, including `and' and `the.' '' Hellman slapped
a libel suit against McCarthy that ended five years later only when
Hellman died.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the end of McCarthy's own life _ she was 77 when she
died in 1989 _ her considerable achievement had been overshadowed
by what she had come to represent. She did not consider herself a
feminist and bridled at attempts to characterize her as a woman
writer. But her example meant a great deal, particularly to her
female contemporaries and their successors. She couldn't exactly be
a role model _ she started with better raw material than most
people _ but she did demonstrate to a lot of people that it was
possible for a woman to have it all, talent, a career, a child, and
at least one happy marriage, and she proved that a woman could be
as forthright and unapologetic about sexuality as men are generally
assumed to be.
</P>
<P>
   A short story involving a pessary sent this young reader to the
dictionary 40 years ago. It is gratifying to learn from Frances
Kiernan's new biography of McCarthy that the august connoisseur of
the arts Bernard Berenson was just as fascinated by the subject as
the rest of us were. When he met McCarthy in Venice, his first
question was, ``Have you brought your pessary with you?''
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan's is the fourth, largest, and best biography of
McCarthy. Kiernan saw her subject only once, in the ladies' room at
The New Yorker, where Kiernan was working as a fiction editor.
McCarthy was smoking a cigarette. ``You did not smoke in (editor)
William Shawn's office, even if you were Mary McCarthy.'' Kiernan
felt too intimidated to approach the woman she admired so much _ a
fact she later came to regret when others told her how approachable
McCarthy could be. She found much to admire in the previous
biographies of the writer, but not the human substance she was
looking for, so she set forth on her own.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's story will be familiar both in outline and detail to
those who have read her books or read around in the memoirs of the
period of nearly 60 years in which she was one of the most colorful
figures on the literary scene. Kiernan makes no attempt to match
McCarthy as a stylist, but she writes clearly and well, and she has
assembled a wealth of fresh detail, presenting the story
novelistically. Her intention is to appeal to the reader who may
not have read McCarthy's book, may even never have heard of her.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy does not escape the tragedies of life, but avoids the
kind that the great novelists, mostly men, have meted out to the
charistmatic female creatures McCarthy rivals in charisma. McCarthy
presented her own story retrospectively; Kiernan builds from the
other direction, letting the character surprise us as much as she
must sometimes have surprised herself. She gives us the appalling
childhood of the McCarthy children, orphaned and brought up by
relatives who didn't know the first thing about children. There is
the young student at Vassar, the brilliant young woman making her
way in New York. She gives detailed attention to McCarthy's
marriages, to actor Harold Johnsrud, to Wilson (McCarthy called him
``the minotaur''), to the elegant dilettante Bowden Broadwater, to
the the longest and happiest relationship, with the diplomat and
public affairs officer James West. And McCarthy's affairs and
might-have-beens are also duly documented.
</P>
<P>
   But Kiernan never forgets that the most important part of
McCarthy's day was the three hours she invariably sealed herself
off and worked. Kiernan discusses the books in an informed and
sensitive way, and she doesn't hesitate to cite McCarthy's failures
_ most notably, perhaps, the second of her Vietnam books,
``Hanoi.'' McCarthy, who headed for North Vietnam with eight
suitcases full of Chanel suits and other inappropriate attire, was
easily hoodwinked by her urbane hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Because McCarthy's best work crossed genres, Kiernan does too.
Nearly every page of her careful, chronological narrative is
interrupted and supplemented by oral history, comments from
interviews, letters, reviews, memoirs, and other sources arranged
into conversations about McCarthy. People loved to talk about
McCarthy and they still do; they also held and still hold the most
contradictory views about her. In talking about her, they are also
inevitably talking about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, one basic point. The men she knew were usually
thunderstruck by her beauty and glamor. Lionel Abel: ``Mary was
beautiful. You have no idea. A real beauty. You don't expect that
in someone so bright. That's what was so unusual about her.'' Not
everyone was equally impressed, however. The first time he saw
McCarthy, philosopher Isaiah Berlin thought ``she looked exactly
like a prostitute. Her clothes. Her shoes. Her way of dressing. Her
gait. She had these sort of open shoes with her feet showing
through and she had a particular way of walking. The skirt she
wore. It seemed to me that was exactly what those people wore. But
nobody was further from it.'' Berlin was equally opinionated about
her intellectual abilities. ``She was no good on abstract ideas.
She was fine on life in general. People. Society. People's
reactions. Character. She responded very sensitively and sharply.
Mary was a good writer, but ideas were not her thing at all. She
was a great wit, but she was not a great thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   The women she knew tended either to envy or deplore her
increasingly expensive wardrobe, to admire her appearance, or to
wonder exactly what men could possibly see in her. Susan Sontag
said, ``Mary came into the room like an aircraft carrier. She
wasn't folks. I mean, she behaved like a society matron. There was
Mary and there was a space that was cleared around her. . . . I
didn't think she was beautiful, but she was attention grabbing.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes right down to it, nobody can really agree about
anything here _ whether or not McCarthy was a good cook, for
example (she thought she was). Some of the hottest debates center
around the biggest issues, personalities and achievements in her
life. Her most important friendship was with the German refugee
writer Hannah Arendt, for example. Particularly after the
publication of her book ``Eichmann in Jerusalem,'' Arendt became a
controversial and indeed a polarizing figure. ``With Hannah Arendt
only litterateurs were taken in. Thinkers were not,'' said Berlin.
And while many of McCarthy's friends were touched by her devotion
to Arendt, others found the influence of the older woman far from
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is lively debate about her books, fueled
particularly by people who recognized themselves in her novels,
which nevertheless found strong admirers, some of them surprising.
Vladimir Nabokov, for example, wrote to Edmund Wilson about
McCarthy's novel ``The Company She Keeps'': ``It is a splendid
thing, clever, poetic and new. In fact I am quite flabbergasted. .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   The conversations about McCarthy present the kind of material
that another biographer would have evaluated, ordered, and
assimilated. At first, they can seem irritating _ isn't Kiernan
evading the biographer's responsibility to arrive at some kind of
reasoned and reasonable final assessment? But long before the end,
these artfully arranged conversations have become one of the most
engaging aspects of the book. And because a reader must make
personal judgments, the reader becomes a participant in the debate,
too. And in order to make a judgment, the reader has to turn back
to the source, McCarthy's books. There's no way to see Mary
McCarthy plain _ or anyone; and that's the point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
