<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-RACE-BOS &LR;      04-03 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM REFLECTS WHITE YOUTHS' FACINATION WITH BLACKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a concept as old as the young Elvis, as timeless as Little
Richard's ``Long Tall Sally,'' as fashionable as the FUBU shirts
and impossibly baggy jeans on the narrow hips of suburban teens,
and as scary as square white guys bellowing ``Whaassssssup!'' like
the brothers on a Budweiser commercial.
</P>
<P>
   White folks want to be as cool as black folks.
</P>
<P>
   Deny it, denounce it, but its power can't be diminished. Asked
last year to explain the rise of rock-rap hybrids such as Limp
Bizkit and Kid Rock, MTV's Chris Connelly made perhaps the most
perceptive statement ever uttered on the cable station: ``When they
write the history of popular culture in the 20th century, they can
sum it up in one sentence which is, `White kids wanting to be as
cool as black kids.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Never has this been more apparent than in the two decades of rap
music and hip-hop culture, which have permeated everything from
language to fashion. It's almost as if the essence of urban
blackness become a salve to be bought and sold like an Enyce shirt
or a pair of Esco jeans _ white kids can't get enough of it. So
call them wiggas and wannabes, or diss them in song as the
Offspring did in their hit, ``Pretty Fly (for a White Guy),'' but
white kids losing and finding themselves in all things black, is
now _ and always will be _ the way of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what makes ``Black and White,'' James Toback's latest
drama, such a timely film. Its geographic setting is New York, but
the film really unfolds at the explosive intersection of black
hip-hop and upper-class white kids who've immersed themselves in
the culture. As with any Toback film, there are many stories here,
including a college basketball star duped into throwing a game, a
bitter undercover cop bent on revenge, a gay man bristling against
the reins of his marriage, interracial relationships, and Mike
Tyson being, well, just Mike Tyson. But at its core, the movie is
about the ramifications of nice white kids playing ghetto games,
who try to ``keep it real'' by being something other than who they
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a sense that black was authentic, and that
white was imitative,'' said Toback, the film's writer and director,
during a recent stop in Cambridge, his stomping ground during his
years at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a reaching out _ sometimes to rip off, but
sometimes it's been sincere, imitation being the sincerest form of
flattery, where you say, `They're on to something, I have a version
of it I want to do.' In this movie,'' he said, ``I depict white
kids who are doing it with language, clothes, and a whole way of
thinking about the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The eclectic cast includes Robert Downey Jr., Brooke Shields,
New York Knicks star Allan Houston, Bijou Phillips, Claudia
Schiffer, Ben Stiller, Jared Leto, Elijah Wood, and Raekwon, Power,
and Method Man from the rap group the Wu-Tang Clan. The film opens
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural tourists
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Power plays Rich Bower, who is trying to go legit
in the music business after a life of crime. His big playa
lifestyle, with its hints of danger and nonconformity, are a
natural magnet for bored rich white kids. They're cultural tourists
walking the walk, talking the talk, even flashing the occasional
fake gold tooth. But they are way over their pretty little heads,
and Rich knows it. At one point, he asks, ``What do these people
want from us?''
</P>
<P>
   Power, whose given name is Oli Grant, has seen it all before. As
producer for the Wu-Tang Clan and founder of their Wu Wear clothing
line, he knows that many of their fans are just like the kids in
``Black and White,'' who find something they connect with,
regardless of how foreign that world may seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't against them,'' he said. ``To each his own, it's a
free country,'' he said. ``But I get mad when I see people frontin'
like they're part of it when in actuality, they're making a mockery
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The definition of ``frontin' '' could well be the scene where
the white teens, who become subjects in a documentary by
husband-and-wife filmmakers (Downey and Shields), refer to each
other as ``my nigga.'' Even though the N-word has been embraced by
some young African-Americans as a term of endearment, for others
it's simply too freighted with a history of hatred to be anything
other than a fighting word.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it's used lightheartedly, the unofficial rule is it
can be uttered only by black folk. (For example, Eminem, the
blonde-haired, blue-eyed rap phenom, may have used every
objectionable word imaginable on his ``Slim Shady LP'' last year,
but he never came close to dropping an N-bomb.)
</P>
<P>
   But in this brave new world where hip-hop culture is youth
culture, Power said the word, depending on context, can be
acceptable coming from a white person who has their mind right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pretty much know a skinhead saying `nigger' means you're a
nigger,'' Power said. ``But there's `niggers,' then there's
`niggas,' and there's white niggas. There's `Yo, that's my nigga
right there, I love him. Like Jim (Toback) is my nigga.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Modern usage
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Toback declined to refer to Power as same. But
he did offer how that word's modern usage is similar to the way in
which football great Jim Brown, whom Toback lived with for two
years in the 1970s, used a certain 12-letter word that once got
comedian George Carlin in a heap of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a substitute for guy,'' Toback said. ``It's just a casual
thing. Besides, if you overuse a word and make it common to the
point where it's a substitute for guy, you defuse its nastiness,
defuse its power to hurt and wound you, you defuse it as a
weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   This exchange, which has enough profanity to make Lil' Kim
blush, could be a scene from Toback's movies, which have included
``Two Guys and a Girl,'' with Downey and Heather Graham, and
``Fingers'' with Harvey Keitel. He was also nominated for an
Academy Award for his screenplay for ``Bugsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Toback himself, his films are freewheeling, provocative,
and uncensored, as much beloved as they are despised. So this
strange moment in a hotel restaurant overlooking the Charles is
downright Tobackian, with the bearded 55-year-old Toback and
20-somethings Power and Bankie, of the American Cream Team, which
contributed to the film's hip-hop-heavy soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   (And speaking of albums, Power says Wu-Tang Clan, which hasn't
had an album out since 1997's ``Wu-Tang Forever,'' expects to have
its next CD out ``maybe toward the end of the summer, but before
2001. You can quote me on that.'')
</P>
<P>
   Of course for Toback, who recalls donning dashikis and wearing
an Afro when he was the only white guy hanging with Brown's posse,
there's nothing strange about it. ``Black and White'' may be
fiction, but for him it reflects pungent realities about race, sex,
and American culture in this still-new century. He wants his film,
which is sure to get tongues wagging, to create a dialogue across
racial lines, much the way hip-hop has bridged various communities
as, he said, ``a way to speak, to think, and to be.''
</P>
<P>
   While bridges and dialogues are fine, Bankie, who like many of
his rap brethren keeps an ear to the street and an eye on the
bottom line, has more practical ideas about white kids who sample
hip-hop culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever embraces hip-hop to me doesn't matter,'' he said.
``Wherever I'm performing, if I look out and see 4,000 to 5,000
white kids, I don't care. The way I see it, whoever embraces
hip-hop, hey, that's just more paychecks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
