<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERCOVER-HAZARDS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREATER RISK TO BLACK OFFICERS WORKING UNDERCOVER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (With sidebar, Police-Shootings)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past decade, 12 off-duty or undercover police officers
have been shot to death or wounded by other policemen after being
mistaken as felons, according to a Boston Globe survey of the
largest cities in the nation. All but two of the officers were
black.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings, which have killed five black and one white
officers and wounded one white and five blacks since 1992, are
prompting representatives of several minority police organizations
to urge their members to consider refusing undercover assignments
until adequate safety measures are in place.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings, the latest of which was the killing in January of
an off-duty Providence (R.I.) Police Department sergeant, Cornel
Young Jr., do not include possible woundings in smaller
communities, physical beatings, or events in which errant shots
were fired. But the known casualties have some police commanders
weighing whether the dangers faced by minority undercover officers,
who make up much of the first line of defense against urban crime,
are too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nightmare of policing,'' said William J. Bratton, the
former commissioner of the New York City and the Boston police
departments. ``We rely greatly on minority officers to combat crime
this way, but in doing so we face exposing them to unintended
dangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the problem remains unexamined on a national level. While
several police departments have taken steps to reduce the peril,
neither the Justice Department nor the Federal Bureau of
Investigation has looked into the number of such matters, or how to
prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that this hasn't gotten more national attention
because it is a problem only waiting to reoccur and reoccur,'' said
Michael O'Connor, retired head of the New York City Transit Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent federal lack of attention means no one knows how
frequently such mistakes have occurred or why. A Globe inquiry
tracked the shootings by contacting police departments and minority
police organizations in the 20 largest cities. The FBI keeps
records on the number of police officers who die on duty, but
categorizes deaths from ``mistaken identity'' with those from
``crossfires'' and ``firearm mishaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau does not keep records on the number of times police
officers are wounded or assaulted because of mistaken identity, or
how often such confrontations result in shots fired errantly.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the nation's largest black police organization
contends that close calls and assaults happen far more frequently
than reflected by the 10 blacks killed or wounded since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   While the specific circumstances differ, several factors seemed
to recur in most of the shootings: The victim was a black police
officer out of uniform, and the person shooting was a white police
officer who had mistaken the black officer for a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In every case, the black officers had come upon a crime and were
trying to maintain order or make an arrest. But they were not
recognized as officers by the uniformed police who were responding
to the emergency, in confrontations tht usually lasted only
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, according to several law enforcement officials,
black and white, the reason for the mistake was racial
stereotyping: A black man with a gun, not in a police uniform, was
seen as a threat to public safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think for yourself; what does it look like when all hell is
breaking loose and there in front of you is a black man with a gun
in his hand?'' said Roger Abel, a retired New York City police
detective, who is black. ``People tend to see a criminal when they
see a black man with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Abel has written an unpublished book on the experiences of black
officers in New York. From department records, Abel has documented
28 cases since 1941 in which black police officers, while dressed
in civilian clothes, have been shot at by white officers. In four
instances, in 1941, 1969, 1972, and 1973, the black officer was
killed, Abel said.
</P>
<P>
   More black officers have been shot mistakenly in Washington D.C.
in recent years than in any other major city. Since 1995, two
District of Columbia officers have been killed and one has been
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   In the fatal case, on Feb. 7, 1995, James M. McGee Jr., 26, was
walking into a takeout restaurant with his wife and two daughters
when he saw a cabdriver being robbed. Although off duty and in
civilian clothes, McGee, a five-year veteran of the Washington
police force, pulled his gun and confronted the robbers at the same
time a patrol car came upon the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolman Michael Baker, one of the two officers in the car,
drew his gun, identified himself, and hollered for McGee to drop
his weapon, according to police reports. It was nearly midnight,
and in the darkness and confusion, Baker did not recognize that
McGee, whose back was to him, was a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   When McGee turned to him, Baker, fearing for his life, fired two
shots, killing McGee. An investigation cleared Baker of wrongdoing,
but the shooting sparked racial tension within the city and the
police department. McGee's father, who headed the National Alliance
of Postal and Federal Employees, asked for calm, saying he believed
that the shooting was an accident ``pure and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, James M. McGee Sr. remains convinced that his
son's death was an accident, but he now believes that more should
have been done to prevent such tragedies. While Washington police
have been trained to be more cautious before firing their weapons,
McGee says they should also be equipped, when off duty, with radio
equipment they could use to communicate their presence at the scene
of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that officer knew that my son was already on the scene,
something different might have happened,'' McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   District Police Chief Charles Ramsey said the city is spending
$5 million to buy radios for off-duty officers. ``If we want to get
at this problem, we've got to improve on communications and
training,'' Ramsey said. ``There's no other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Transit Authority also has seen more than one
of its black undercover officers shot in the past decade. The
shootings of Derwin Pannell in 1992 and Desmond Robinson in 1994
persuaded O'Connor, the transit chief, to undertake a thorough
review. He found that there were no procedures to inform patrol
officers on how to avoid making such deadly mistakes, and no
training for undercover officers on how to respond when confronted
by a patrol officer.
</P>
<P>
   Transit officers, now part of the city's police department, are
trained to avoid face-to-face confrontations, which can easily
spiral into a deadly shootout. Instead, on arriving at the scene of
a crime in progress, they are to take cover, announce themselves as
police officers, and demand that the suspect ``freeze.'' Undercover
officers, meanwhile, must follow the orders of responding patrolmen
to the letter, even if it results in their being handcuffed and
transported to a police station for identification.
</P>
<P>
   Steps to avoid dreadful mistakes have also been taken in Boston.
In 1995, Michael A. Cox, a black officer in plainclothes, was badly
beaten by several of his white and black colleagues after he
apparently was mistaken for a fleeing suspect. Police Commissioner
Paul F. Evans later issued a set of instructions to try to prevent
such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   All patrol cars are to be informed whenever an undercover
operation is taking place in their district, and later-arriving
officers in plainclothes are always to wear special jackets with
Boston Police emblazoned front and back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
