<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON SENSE BY KERRY ON CHINA-TAIWAN TENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before American politicians have their shouting
match over a genuine 21st century issue _ trade with China _ it's
starting to look as if there may be a preliminary shouting match
over a genuine mid-20th century issue _ military help for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense this isn't so bad, for the two shouting matches are
part of a much larger issue _ the US relationship with China, which
could use mature, as opposed to partisan and ideological,
discussion. Approval of normal economic relations should follow
because fair access to China's rapidly evolving new economy is
vital to American interests, but we should probably get a few
things straight first.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, what is going on between the Republican
congressional leaders and the Clinton administration is mostly
lousy.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of one of the adult players on Capitol Hill: ``The
debate on China today offers a false choice between a Cold
War-style containment of China and the current form of engagement
at all costs. In fact, containment of China along the lines of the
policy we pursued with the Soviet Union is neither necessary nor
prudent. Engagement is the right approach, but it must be
hard-headed and driven by our own interests.''
</P>
<P>
   As a senior Senate Foreign Relations Committee Democrat and the
minority's leading Asia policy hand, John Kerry of Massachusetts is
an experienced, constructive critic. He and his like-minded
colleagues will control the center of the political action. It may
be more fun in the media to fantasize that the politics of China is
a fight between Jesse Helms on one side and commie-coddlers on the
other, but sophisticated players like Kerry are the people who
deserve our attention.
</P>
<P>
   Take Taiwan. Kerry does not see this month's exciting
presidential election as the simple selection of a
``pro-independance'' figure, Chen Shui-bian (George W. Bush, please
note), that will lead to a crisis or worse with a truculent
mainland. Instead, he notes that the three-way race didn't come
close to providing a ``clear mandate'' and that President-elect
Chen's subsequent actions indicate he understands this. He has
already offered to visit the mainland; his political party is
likely to get rid of its platform plank favoring the establishment
of an independent republic; and the Legislature has already ended a
long prohibition against economic ties between Taiwan's offshore
islands and the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   China has also pulled back from most of its preelection
bellicosity, in particular, by suggesting that negotiations on
eventual reunification could proceed on a basis that resembles
equality. Kerry says China can do more, above all by recognizing
that this is no longer the late Chiang Kai-shek's one-party
``Nationalist China'' and that because of its democratic and
economic development, concepts like those applied to Hong Kong and
Macau (one China, two systems) are no longer adequate.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress, whose conservative leaders are behaving as if the
preelection posturing were still the reality, also has to behave
itself. But it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Its leaders continue, for example, to push ridiculous
legislation that would create a formal military tie to Taiwan.
Already through the House and pending in the Senate, it is,
according to Kerry, an open invitation to the conflict it seeks to
deter.
</P>
<P>
   A touchier topic is Taiwan's effort to purchase the Aegis, a
super-fancy class of antimissile and anti-aircraft destroyer, as a
response to China's military buildup and threats. Kerry's analysis,
but not yet his formal position, suggests that this is a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed narrowly, Taiwan's military needs all kinds of basic
improvements, as reports about a still-unpublished Pentagon study
make clear. That's where it needs to concentrate, not on fueling
another arms race.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, as Kerry noted, ``In the final analysis, balance
in the (Taiwan) strait is provided by us, by our willingness to
come to Taiwan's defense if China attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   That willingness was demonstrated during the crisis four years
ago, which Kerry calls one of the high points of administration
policy. But he's also correct that the immediate cause of the
crisis was administration indecision before granting a visa for a
visit here by outgoing Taiwan president Lee Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's argument is that US policy must be based on more
clarity, consistency, pragmatism, and accountability. It is also
fair comment that it should not be inflated with the helium of
overblown phraseology (Clinton's short-lived ``strategic
partnership'') or endangered by silly synonyms for Cold War-style
containment (George W. Bush's ``competition'').
</P>
<P>
   In time, Kerry will be there for the administration if Congress
schedules a timely vote on trade relations. In the meantime, the
administration and the rest of us need to learn from constructive
Republican and Democratic critics like Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Left-right polemics is something else that needs to be consigned
to the last century.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
