<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-03 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL PURSUING THE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of President Clinton should have ended in
February of last year, when the U.S. Senate acquitted him on
impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Or it should have ended last summer, when Congress let lapse the
Office of Independent Counsel from which Kenneth W. Starr launched
his investigation of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal and Whitewater.
It definitely should have ended by October, when Starr stepped
down.
</P>
<P>
   But Congressional Republicans, who lost the impeachment battle,
and the new special prosecutor, Robert Ray, who succeeded Starr a
couple of weeks ago, apparently are determined to pursue Clinton
even after he leaves office. They expect to pursue Hillary Clinton,
too, during her senatorial campaign against New York Mayor Rudolph
W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   With no apparent legal need to pursue Clinton, as even Starr
noted in a recent Wall Street Journal article, these pursuits
amount to nothing more than a political vendetta against a man the
Republicans hate with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's final report on Whitewater and other investigations of the
Clintons is expected soon. It will mark the completion of a long
probe of the president. It may also become a political weapon to be
used against the Clintons, even if the reports do not call for
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ray will not make his reports public, they could be
made public by the special panel of three judges that oversees the
OIC. It is more likely to be leaks that will reach the news media
when the judges first distribute the reports to individuals named
in them for comment or rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are these reports likely to be used by Republicans in
Congress to further their vendetta against the Clintons, but they
may also be used against the man trying to succeed him, Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the new GOP-driven investigation of missing White
House e-mails that apparently weren't archived because of a
technical glitch. Republicans are using this latest issue as more
fodder against the Clintons and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Based on news reports, Ray is looking into whether his office
could charge Clinton with crimes after he leaves office.
Ironically, if Ray decides to pursue Clinton, he would be taking
that pursuit further than even Starr would.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, according to a news report, noted that the proper forum
for the charges against Clinton was the impeachment process. With
that process concluded, he said, there was no need for separate
criminal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But the proceedings go on, both inside and outside the special
prosecutor's office. Last week, a federal judge ruled that Clinton
violated the Privacy Act by releasing letters written to him by
Kathleen Willey, which he said he did in order to rebut her charges
of sexual misconduct. The ruling was the result of a case brought
by a conservative watchdog group, Judicial Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton released the letters, he said, to defend himself against
Willey's charges, which later began to wilt under the heat of
further public scrutiny. If Clinton had written letters to Willey,
and Willey released them to the public, it is doubtful that she
would be convicted of violating the Privacy Act, since she would
not be a target of the right-wing conservatives who are pursuing
the Clintons and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Democrats are engaged in their own scrutiny of
Republican candidate George W. Bush's fund-raising records. But
because of Clinton's impeachment history, his involvement in
Whitewater, Starr's past zeal, and the fact that the Republicans
still control Congress and its investigations, the GOP has a lot
more fodder to use against the Clintons and Gore than the Democrats
have to use against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to conduct negative campaigning against Gore and
Hillary Rodham Clinton. It is entirely another when a special
prosecutor and a judge continue to go after the president long
after a case has been settled, just to provide Republicans
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the opinion of one justice on the three-judge panel that
oversees the Independent Counsel's office should have prevailed.
Judge Richard D. Cudahy wrote in August that he thought the time
had come to end the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw no need for the office to stay in operation once
the impeachment battle was over. But he was overruled by his two
colleagues, Judges David B. Sentelle and Peter T. Fay.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress decided to let the independent counsel law expire
last June, Ray's office is supposed to be wrapping up the
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it appears that Ray is intent on keeping the
investigation ongoing until he succeeds in getting an indictment
against Clinton. When Ray says, ``Nobody is above the law,'' he
apparently wants to prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it would be proper justice for Ray and federal
judges who continue to pursue Clinton to one day discover that
they, too, are not above the law.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
