<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGY AFTER A JOB LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am one of many people being ``de-selected'' as a result of
the merger of BankBoston and Fleet. I will work until September;
the severance package provides full salary until February 2002. I
will turn 62 and be eligible for Social Security in May 2002. My
job expertise involves mainframe computers and is not in great
demand. My goal is not to go back to work when this job is over.
I'm guessing I can retire on $60,000 a year. Can I achieve this
goal, given my financials? Should my portfolio be rebalanced if I
retire?
</P>
<P>
   M.C., Cohasset, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You should be in pretty good shape, but be careful. Counting
both your anticipated Social Security and your rental income, you
will need to take $36,000 a year from savings. The way I would do
that is to move toward a fixed-income portfolio of about $550,000,
completing the process by the time your current income stream ends
in early 2002.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to retire now, that would leave you with only
$135,545 that you could leave invested in stocks _ an account that
you want to leave in growth securities to protect yourself against
inflation late in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a great deal of money for that chore, but there are a
couple of factors in your favor: You can continue saving for 22
months, and your retirement accounts should continue growing. You
don't specify how much you have been contributing to your various
accounts, but whatever it is, I suggest you pick up the pace. But
even if you were not to contribute more, internal growth would add
a further $93,606 to the accumulation, if you earned a portfolio
average of 7 percent total returns during the next 22 months.
</P>
<P>
   I use that relatively low 7 percent figure for a couple of
reasons. One is my chronic caution about the current stock market,
and the second is that I suggest you immediately begin transferring
money to fixed-income assets. Since you already have that $100,000
in the cash balance account, you would need to move only about
$19,250 a month to the fixed-income side to build the fixed-income
account by February 2002.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't try anything fancy, looking to a three-legged
fixed-income portfolio with about half in intermediate-term
government guaranteed securities, such as US Treasury securities, a
GNMA fund, or a general government bond fund. I'd then have about a
quarter in CDs, money markets, or short-term bond accounts, and the
final quarter in a high-yield bond fund, such as Fidelity Capital
and Income or Vanguard High-Yield Corporate.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that's likely to improve the odds that this plan will
work is adjusting yourself to that $60,000-a-year budget as soon as
you retire. Then, treat the extra $24,500 in annual income for the
next 22 months as money that can be added, in toto, to your
retirement savings. The trick will be to see how much you can build
the stock end of the portfolio during that period, so it will serve
the eventual purpose of protecting you from inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I need information about rolling over pension and 401(k)
accounts after a job change and maximizing the value of my
retirement savings. I believe it is best to roll over the pension
account, but the 401(k) account is different. I could leave it
where it is, and they invest the money for me. I am not sure of the
fees associated with having an individual account compared to a
group account such as the 401(k). I believe my ability to
reallocate my money among the funds available in the 401(k) is no
longer an option since leaving the company. But when moving my
accounts I want to be able to do minimal maintenance. Considering
that I have 30 years to go, I can't let my funds stay in this ratio
forever _ or can I? My gut feeling is I should roll over to an IRA
so I can do an annual review and let the fund manager do the rest.
</P>
<P>
   I have just purchased a house, which is quickly absorbing my
extra cash. I thought it was time to stop living like a college
student and start buying things like furniture. I'll wait until
January to resume retirement savings, at which point I will be
eligible for my new employer's 401(k) plan and company match.
</P>
<P>
   B.V., Plymouth, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The question of whether to roll over the pension is simple.
If you take the lump sum as a rollover IRA and invest it for 30
years and achieve 10 percent average annual returns, you will build
a pool of $424,153 _ probably sufficient to produce an income
stream of $2,297 a month without invading the principal.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 401(k), I agree with your gut feeling. If rolling the
401(k) money over into an IRA is the only way to change the
investment allocations, I'd take that course _ if only to get rid
of that 19 percent of the account that is loafing in an interest
account _ even though you are young enough so that projecting
growth out for 35 years provides some pretty spectacular numbers.
For example, with no additions the 401(k) would hit $1,903,991
after 30 years with 10 percent average growth.
</P>
<P>
   But once you factor in inflation, you'll understand how
dangerous it is to let money loaf. If we combine the rolled-over
pension and the 401(k) after 30 years, the impressive sum would be
$2,328,144. But then you have to work the other side of the
equation _ inflation again _ and when you do, you come out with the
buying power of about $830,000 in today's dollars. That presumes an
average 3.5 percent inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   Given your strong start on retirement savings, I see no problem
with taking a year off while you wait for 401(k) eligibility. But I
will caution you not to get too comfortable living on your full
income.
</P>
<P>
   As for the costs of a rollover into an IRA, either with Fidelity
or Vanguard, both offer an impressive array of no-load funds, and
no charge for the rollover; the odds are that total management
costs would be lower after the rollover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The Independent Advisor for Vanguard Funds is one of my
favorite newsletters. It appears monthly, usually in a 12-page
format. In addition to a general overview of market activities and
particularly their effect on Vanguard offerings, among other
features, the newsletter provides statistical reports on all of
Vanguard's retail funds, four model portfolios, notices of likely
upcoming distributions from the various funds, and interviews with
various Vanguard managers.
</P>
<P>
   The model portfolios have excellent track records. Examples,
with results from the inception of the models at the start of 1991,
are the growth portfolio, beginning at $50,000 and standing at
$242,902 at the end of January; the conservative growth portfolio,
moving from the same starting point to $185,000; and the income
portfolio, which grew from the same base to $164,912. In the final
case, the accumulation is probably academic, since the models
presume that all distributions are reinvested, which is not what
income investors typically do.
</P>
<P>
   Write to Phillips Publishing Inc., 7811 Montrose Rd., Potomac,
Md. 20859-0042, or call 800-211-7641.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
