<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH AND CARRY: CLUES TO PERSONALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the wallet, or lack of one. How people carry their cash
is a psychological profile of sorts, and the amateur shrinks are
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Is the wallet fat, bulging with coupons, receipts, photos,
insurance and club membership cards, not to mention an entire
checkbook? Then it probably belongs to a married woman with a tight
grip on the family finances, says Jim Leiwakabessy, assistant
manager for The Sharper Image in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a control issue,'' he says. ``She wants the balance with
her at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   His store's slim, small wallets, with slots for no more than a
couple of credit cards, sell mostly to men, or to young single
women who want to travel unencumbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinner the better,'' says Leiwakabessy, describing not
only the leather, but the fashion-conscious customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone in the family is going to carry the health cards
for the kids, it will be the woman,'' says Rick Gebhardt, assistant
manager for Bally. ``Men carry nothing for the children, and they
don't like adding up numbers. Women are the money managers.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder civilization's first wallets, invented during the
Middle Ages, were strictly a female item _ cloth bags called
``pockets'' that hung from a cord tied around the waist under the
skirt. A trade group, Luggage and Leather Goods Manufacturers of
America, reports that the ``pocket'' evolved into a flat,
rectangular unisex ``pocketbook,'' made of linen in the 1700s and
later done in leather.
</P>
<P>
   Today's money-gear emporiums can offer as many as 40 wallet
styles that sell for anywhere from $35 to nearly $400, depending on
the type of leather, clasps, zippers, and compartments.
</P>
<P>
   For the status-seeker, choosing one can assume the importance of
buying a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me, `I make $100,000 a year, so I don't buy Coach
anymore,' '' whispers a clerk in a Coach store that would seem to
be the definition of class, with its elegant display cases and
smartly dressed staff. ``They want Gucci because it's got that G on
the front. Coach is subtle and puts the name inside.''
</P>
<P>
   A Brookstone clerk, noting that money clips are hot, adds that
his store's tasteful silver model was not quite flashy enough for
him _ he carries a big gold one purchased at Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of cash out there in a lot of money clips,''
says Bruno Marini, general manager of the restaurant Ambrosia on
Huntington. ``People take out the money clip and tip the coat
person and the valet. It's a show of prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the color of money _ or, more accurately, the color of the
wallet carrying the money _ which is moving way beyond basic black
and brown to blast old-Boston sensibilities with coral, pumpkin,
red, canary yellow, jungle animal fabric prints, and polka dots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can afford to buy a $310 wallet in lime green, you're
telling people you have disposable income,'' says Nunzio
Bellofatto, of the leather mecca Bottega Veneta.
</P>
<P>
   But Bellofatto also sees people who simply stuff their money
into their pockets in a wad. One customer wraps it in a thick
rubber band. ``A police officer once told him that he'd feel a
pickpocket taking his money if he carried it like that,'' he says.
``He comes in to buy wallets for his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The rubber band's casual chic also appeals to Lydia Shire, owner
and chef of Biba and Pignoli restaurants. ``I had a wallet once,''
she says. ``It didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Shire slaps the rubber band around her bills and tosses the
bundle into her purse, where ``it floats'' and she can grab it
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate developer Ron Druker is another rubber band man and
finds everything else ``too cumbersome.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this quest for streamlining in the age of overpriced
accessories is what inspires some Filene's customers to carry cash
in the tops of their knee-high stockings or to keep credit cards in
a zip-lock plastic bag. At Shreve Crump &AMP; Low Co., clerks have seen
the occasional customer walk in with money in a paper bag.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's basic, and a refreshing break in the opulence that
has become the currency of Boston. Could it be a trend? Maybe, as
long as nobody shops in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be
reached by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
