<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENTLY REVIEWED FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
 
!! 1/2 ``Onegin'' This snowy adaptation of Alexander Pushkin's
verse novel ``Eugene Onegin'' is gorgeously filmed, hypnotically
told, and seriously flawed by the miscasting of Liv Tyler. She
doesn't mix convincingly with Ralph Fiennes, who is perfect as the
conceited aristocrat who rejects her, then falls in love with her.
The period piece is the confident directorial debut of
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fiennes's sister, Martha Fiennes. (Unrated) (Matthew Gilbert) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``Price of Glory'' Seeming more rigged than any fixed fight,
this boxing movie is KO'd by predictability and a too-simplistic
take on a Latino family. Jimmy Smits plays the father who doesn't
know best as he pushes his sons into the boxing career he never
had. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Road to El Dorado'' Animated Spanish rascals go for
New World gold. It's OK, but no more than OK. More efficient than
inspired, its nouveau-Disney house style seems standard-issue.
Except for a Mayan scamster voiced by Rosie Perez, it plays like
``Ishtar'' with computer graphics. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``The Skulls'' This would-be expose of the sinister
power-mongering of a secret society at Yale declines into a
ludicrous exercise in frat-house gothic, populated by paper-thin
characters. Instead of a conspiracy thriller, it's ``Animal House''
with better clothes and pricier real estate. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``The Terrorist'' One of the few looks at a political assassin
that isn't about explosions or sensory jolts. Thoughtfully and
originally, Indian filmmaker Santosh Sivan focuses on what's going
on behind the huge eyes of Ayesha Dharkar's 19-year-old ``human
bomb'' awaiting her target in Sri Lanka. (Unrated)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
