<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-LIONS-BOS &LR;      04-03 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BETWEEN THE LIONS' AIMS TO LURE KIDS INTO THE LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With TV-Lions-Review)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the two years Judith Stoia spent developing a PBS
children's program titled ``Between the Lions,'' one of her
collaborators, Christopher Cerf, periodically opined that ``every
good idea begins with a bad pun.''
</P>
<P>
   The pun may be a groaner, all right, but it accurately reflects
the spirit _ and the atypical ambitions _ of the sprightly new
show, which debuts this week.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a library where books come alive, ``Between the Lions''
draws its title from the fact that libraries are often bracketed by
stone lions, which you have to walk between to enter. Getting kids
to walk ``between the lions'' and into their local libraries is the
program's long-term goal. Its short-term goal is to equip children
ages 4 to 7 with reading skills by blending puppetry, animation,
and live action in a series of songs and sketches that teach
vocabulary and sentence structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we want it to be entertaining,'' said Stoia, the
program's executive producer. ``But the real purpose of this is to
help kids learn to read.''
</P>
<P>
   But with television so often blamed for the national decline of
literacy, isn't it paradoxical, even presumptuous, for a TV program
to aspire to teach reading? Stoia doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television is actually very well-suited for teaching
reading,'' she said. ``We can do certain things it's hard for a
teacher to do. We can show a page of a book and make all the A's on
the page animate and wiggle. Or we can change all of the A's to
E's.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Sesame Street'' famously introduces children to letters
and numbers, and programs like ``Reading Rainbow'' and ``Wishbone''
try to open up the world of books to children, ``Between the
Lions'' goes further in focusing on the creation of a ``literacy
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the Lions,'' coproduced by WGBH and Sirius Thinking
Ltd., is built around a curriculum devised by reading experts.
``They explained what the challenges were for kids in decoding the
English language, with short vowel sounds, for instance, and word
blending,'' said Stoia. ``They explained the concept to us and we
came up with different ways to achieve it. Our advisers look at
every script; this is very pointed in terms of teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoia says you'd have to go back to ``The Electric Company''
(1971-76) to find a children's TV program tied so inextricably to a
literacy curriculum. The overall thrust of ``Lions,'' in her view,
``very much matches what kindergarten and first- and second-grade
teachers are trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   No less an authority than Peggy Charren agrees. Charren, who ran
children's book fairs before founding Action for Children's
Television, said she believes the show's creators have struck the
right balance between entertainment and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting kids to be wild about reading is the most important
education you can do,'' said Charren. ``But you have to get the
kids to watch the program. They did that without sacrificing
education.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stoia, ``Between the Lions'' is a new chapter in a varied
and Emmy-winning television career. She worked as a reporter and
managing editor of nightly newscasts at WGBH, Channel 2 in Boston,
from 1974 to 1979 before joining WCVB-TV, Channel 5, where she
cofounded ``Chronicle'' and served as the program's executive
producer. By 1990, she had returned to Channel 2, where she
produced documentaries and was head of local programming.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Stoia left that post to develop ``Between the
Lions,'' commuting between her home in Boston and New York City.
New challenges, such as working with puppets for the first time,
were ameliorated by her production team, which included heavy
hitters like ``Sesame Street'' veterans Cerf (who also cofounded
the National Lampoon), Michael K. Frith, and Norman Stiles.
</P>
<P>
   PBS seems to have high hopes for ``Between the Lions.'' On
Channel 2, which has an obvious interest in its success, it will
air twice a day, at 8:30 a.m. and 4:30 p.m., pushing ``Barney &AMP;
Friends'' to 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an ``educational outreach'' effort, involving such
groups as the American Library Association and the National
Coalition for Literacy, and a Web site featuring ``reading
activities'' at www.pbskids.org/lions.
</P>
<P>
   Stoia said she hopes the young viewers of ``Between the Lions''
will take the logical next step: getting a library card. ``Besides
teaching reading skills, the program honors books and reading,''
she said. ``It really celebrates reading.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
