<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HOLIDAY-BOS &LR;      04-03 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HOLIDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORY OF A SONG THAT CHANGED THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
STRANGE FRUIT 
Billie Holiday, Cafe Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights 
By David Margolick 
Running Press, 160 pp., $16.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the history of popular music, there is nothing comparable to
``Strange Fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither jazz nor blues, its music is stark and funereal. Its
three verses, comprising 12 lines, are unaccompanied by a chorus.
Raw, mournful, and accusing, it is a lament that bears witness to
horror. And, sung with a world-weary ache by the great Billie
Holiday, it amplified the anguished cry of all those whose lives
ended at the wrong end of a rope:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern trees bear strange fruit,
</P>
<P>
   Blood on the leaves and blood at the root,
</P>
<P>
   Black body swinging in the Southern breeze,
</P>
<P>
   Strange fruit hanging from the poplar trees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one years since Holiday first sang those words, they still
disturb the soul. It became Holiday's signature song, yet because
of its subject matter, it has long been regarded as too disturbing
for audiences, black or white.
</P>
<P>
   David Margolick's exceptional book, ``Strange Fruit,'' is a
biography of an extraordinary work, the singer who made it famous,
and its sustaining impact as one of the great protest songs of the
20th century. A contributing editor at Vanity Fair, Margolick
parses fact from fiction, unearthing the song's history from its
beginnings as a poem to its recent recognition by a British
magazine as one of the ``10 songs that actually changed the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolick debunks the most common myths about the song _
chiefly, that Holiday co-wrote it, or had it written for her, a
claim Holiday herself perpetuated. In truth, ``Strange Fruit'' was
written by Abel Meeropol, a Jewish schoolteacher in New York, who
was also a political activist and composer. (If his name sounds
familiar, it's probably because in later years he adopted the sons
of Ethel and Julius Rosenberg after the parents were executed.)
Under the name Lewis Allen, Meeropol wrote the song in the 1930s,
at a time when lynchings were common. By one conservative estimate,
there were 3,833 reported lynchings between 1889 and 1940; most
occured in the South, and the vast majority of victims were
African-American men, women, even children.
</P>
<P>
   The song was performed regularly in leftist circles, where it
was discovered by Robert Gordon, director of the floor show at Cafe
Society, an ultra-liberal, fully integrated New York nightspot
where Holiday, then 24, was the featured artist.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon brought the song to the club's owner, Barney Josephson,
who introduced the tune to Holiday. Although some remembered
Holiday as initially indifferent to the song, Margolick maintains
she did not overlook its searing message, and soon ``laid claim to
the song, telling audiences it has been written especially for her,
and resenting anyone who dared sing it.'' One who dared was
folk-bluesman Josh White, who performed the song even after Holiday
threatened to cut his throat.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday was so particular about the song, she wasn't beyond
evicting or attacking patrons who responded inappropriately
interrupted her rendition. It was that kind of song, Margolick
asserts, and he perfectly re-creates Josephson's elaborate staging
for the song, which would usually close Holiday's set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before she began, all service stopped. Waiters, cashiers,
busboys were all immobilized. The room went completely dark, save
for a pin spot on Holiday's face. When she was finished, the lights
went out, and she was to walk off the stage, and no matter how
thunderous the ovation, she was never to return for a a bow.'' It
would usually take audiences a few moments to gather themselves
emotionally before they could applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the song's blatant politics were as reviled as
revered. Some radio stations wouldn't play it; Holiday's own label,
Columbia, refused to record it (Holiday found another company to
make the first recording). The song was even rejected as too
depressing by civil rights protesters, who preferred more uplifting
fare like ``We Shall Overcome'' or ``This Little Light of Mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of a life addled by drink, drugs, and too many
bad men, Holiday sang ``Strange Fruit'' less and less. It simply
took too much out of her. She cried every time she sang the song,
and as Margolick writes, ``she was too busy holding herself
together to wage crusades for anybody else.'' Years later, others
would perform the song, including Nina Simone, Cassandra Wilson,
Sting, and Tori Amos, but Holiday's version remains the standard.
And she so embodied the song, one can understand how, with all due
respect to Meeropol, she claimed its authorship.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Time designated ``Strange Fruit'' the ``Best Song of
the Century.'' With reportorial finesse, Margolick also restores
``Strange Fruit'' to its deserved stature in the public
consciousness as a piece of shocking reportage _ a dispatch from
battlefields where the price of racism and ignorance was tallied in
blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans of the song do not say they like it _ how can one
actually like a song on such a subject? _ but they acknowledge its
lasting impact,'' Margolick writes. ``They credit it with helping
awaken them to the realities of racial prejudice and the
ameliorative power of art. Whether they protested in Selma or took
part in the March on Washington or spent their lives as social
activists, many say it was hearing `Strange Fruit' that triggered
the process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
