<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-TV-BOS &LR;      04-03 1667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-TV-BOS </SLUG>
  
 BRINGING THE STAGE TO THE SMALL SCREEN
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Television and the performing arts have never been a great fit
in America. From television's inception to the coming of cable,
prophets promised a window on the arts that would transform the
masses. Instead, the masses transformed television: The golden age
of drama lasted little more than 10 years as more channels meant an
even greater competition for ratings. On cable, the Arts &AMP;
Entertainment network became strictly Entertainment, and Bravo has
turned to mostly movies. Even PBS gives short shrift to the
performing arts these days, except for opera.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the bleak scenario for the arts on television _
particularly for theater, which has been relegated to a handful of
programs on ``Great Performances'' and ``Live From Lincoln Center''
each year _ is beginning to improve. Whether we're on the verge of
a new golden age of the arts on television or merely waiting for
the next unfulfilled promise remains to be seen, but the prospects
look promising.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the incredibly successful marriage of television and
sports. The adage in football, for example, was that television put
you on the 50-yard line _ but that's actually misleading.
Television was always able to seat the viewer in the fifth row
center, say, for arts programming, but it was rarely able to
simulate the experience of attending the live event the way that
sports programming has always been able to do, even in black and
white. Sports programming was able to take you to the key vantage
point on every play, while also capturing something of the feel of
being at the park.
</P>
<P>
   Now TVs are getting big enough, the sound is getting strong
enough, and the picture is getting sharp enough that the same thing
is starting to happen on television, particularly with the advent
of digital picture and sound. Two broadcasts earlier this year,
``Death of a Salesman'' on Showtime and Anne-Sophie Mutter's
appearance with the New York Philharmonic on PBS, showed that
television may have come alive as a partner for the arts. Both were
riveting broadcasts, ``Salesman'' as tension-filled in its way as
this year's Super Bowl was for sports fans. For those who like
20th-century music, and even for some who don't, Mutter's
performances were as dramatic as an episode of ``The Sopranos'' _
and we're not just talking about her strapless gown.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs, not so coincidentally, were directed by Kirk
Browning, who is hardly a young maverick when it comes to directing
arts programming for television _ next year will mark his seventh
decade in the business. He started at NBC in 1948 with three
cameras per performance. The technology at his end of the
transmission has improved just as it has at the viewer's. He had 9
cameras at his disposal for ``Death of a Salesman'' and 11 for
Mutter and the Philharmonic on ``Live From Lincoln Center.''
Additionally, according to Browning, the equipment is not as
intrusive as it used to be _ the audience hardly knows the cameras
are there.
</P>
<P>
   What television offers
</P>
<P>
   It may be heresy to say that these broadcasts were as good or _
shudder _ better than being there, but consider some of the
advantages. Brian Dennehy's performance as Willy Loman seemed less
fussy on television, and the camera didn't dilute the strength of
his delivery or that of any of the other actors, notably Elizabeth
Franz's as his wife, Linda. At a classical performance your vision
of a performer is fixed _ one angle is all you get. With the
Philharmonic concert, Browning was all over the stage, presenting
Mutter, conductor Kurt Masur, and the other artists from a variety
of angles. And the sound on both, with the TV hooked up to stereo
components, was terrific.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the broadcasts were far less static than similar
programs 10 or even 5 years ago. ``You never used to be able to
light in a way that would allow you to penetrate with as many
close-ups,'' said Browning in a telephone interview. ``The lenses _
by the time you punched in to a close-up, the picture was so dark
you couldn't take it. Now you can get a great amount of detail. A
lot of people think I do too much detail. I'm a little busier than
some people in this business, but something that I've decided over
the years is that the viewer is looking for is specifics. The
medium calls for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Salesman'' wasn't exactly a live broadcast: It was taped
before an audience just after the play had ended its Broadway run.
``It was a tough show because the production didn't lend itself to
the camera. The turntable was a theatrical artifice we couln't
handle on camera. I think that the most problematic thing is to put
live theater on television. Somehow it works better in dance and
opera because of the larger-than-life aspect that the audience
understands, but in theater you lose the sense of audience and you
say, `Why are they screaming at each other?' I hope you had the
sense with `Salesman' that it was in front of an audience so you
didn't lose that chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Living-room drama
</P>
<P>
   William Cosel, executive producer for WGBH's ``Evening at
Pops,'' says that both he and Browning use lipstick cameras (so
named because they are about the size of a lipstick holder), and
can go where cameras could never go before. Cosel shot the
reopening of Severance Hall in Cleveland recently, and the
Cleveland Orchestra's artistic director, Christoph von Dohnanyi,
challenged him to go even further and use the technology of sports
events to add text and split screens. Both Cosel and Browning are
increasingly able to make the pace and the image correspond to the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Television is about to take on theater again in a major way.
Broadway Television Network is poised to offer a dozen live
telecasts on a pay-per-view basis in the next five years, beginning
with ``Smokey Joe's Cafe.'' Its closing performance was taped
before a live audience. Subsequent shows will be aired live for a
fee of about $35 and then make their way to cable and home video.
In another venture, former HBO chairman Michael Fuchs has joined
with some theater people to restore such television classics as the
Lee J. Cobb ``Death of a Salesman'' and the Jason Robards-Colleen
Dewhurst ``Moon for the Misbegotten'' for broadcast and/or home
video.
</P>
<P>
   PBS will be getting back into theater with ``Stage on Screen,''
producing for television recent plays such as A. R. Gurney's ``Far
East'' and Anna Deavere Smith's ``Twilight: Los Angeles'';
broadcasting films made from plays, including Jon Robin Baitz's
``Substance of Fire''; and digging back into the archives of WNET,
New York's major public television station. WNET, however, will be
reshooting these new productions for television. ``Far East,'' for
example, will go from its one set and seven actors onstage to 16
sets and 50 actors on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Bill O'Donnell, manager of program develepment for culture and
arts programming at WNET, says that even though there have been
significant strides made in shooting before an audience, there is
still a feeling that the actors are under glass. ``We want to keep
the theatrical flavor in terms of lighting and camera movement, but
television and film are so literal that we'll take each on a
case-by-case basis and decide what best suits each project in
trying to re-create what comes across best in the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to gauge how successful WNET will be from Wednesday's
``Joseph and the Amazing Tchnicolor Dreamcoat'' (8 to 10 p.m.,
Channel 2) on ``Great Performances.'' Like the ``Cats'' video, this
is a more European approach, with heavily stylized camerawork and
Donny Osmond, Joan Collins, and the rest of the cast mugging
directly into the camera while lip-synching the lyrics, a la the
late Jean-Pierre Ponnelle's opera telecasts. As with Ponnelle's
operas, there's something to be said for this approach, which works
with Andrew Lloyd Webber, but who knows what the results would be
with less trivial material?
</P>
<P>
   Webber or not
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph,'' which was produced by Lloyd Webber's company, not
PBS, is more or less an infomercial for the recently released home
video of the musical. ``Great Performances'' seems infatuated with
Lloyd Webber, this being the fourth presentation of his ouevre _
``Jesus Christ Superstar'' will be number five. Leaving aside for
the moment whether hitching one's star to Lloyd Webber's wagon
represents a massive dumbing down for PBS, pursuing a radical
remaking of the arts for television may be the wrong approach in
light of Browning's recent successes with live or live-on-tape
broadcasts. (Last week's ``Tosca'' was another production by
Browning, who says that last year's ``Twelfth Night'' with Helen
Hunt was the best of all his theatrical broadcasts.)
</P>
<P>
   The production of an artistic event is hardly cheap _ about
$700,000 and reshooting something for television can be twice as
expensive. But with the recent improvements in both hardware and
software, PBS could be primed to chart the artistic life of the
country the way that ABC's Roone Arledge and the networks have been
able to chart the athletic life of the country for the past 50
years. PBS could now be that window on the artistic world observers
always hoped television would be. Given the complaint that public
broadcasting has grown redundant in the current television
landscape, to waste its time on piffle like ``Joseph'' would be
nothing less than a tragedy for PBS and the country.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, instead, going from the reopening of Severance Hall one
week to ``James Joyce's The Dead'' on Broadway to the American
Ballet Theatre's production of ``Le Corsaire'' to Pierre Boulez's
residency at Carnegie Hall to a new Don DeLillo play at the
American Repertory Theatre or Steppenwolf from week to week. That
would truly be a new golden age _ for PBS, television, and the arts
in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
