<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HORSE-BOS &LR;      04-03 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HORSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE SENSE AND SENSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HORSE HEAVEN 
By Jane Smiley. Knopf. 
561 pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the sweetest smells in my olfactory archives belongs to a
horse stable that, about a decade ago, overlooked the Pamet River
on the Lower Cape. Staying in the house next door, I would wake at
dawn to the sounds of nickering horses, and to the equine smells _
meadow, then hay, then recycled hay _ that are as inextricable from
a stable as sweat or leather. Granted, not everybody would find
this an intoxicating memory. But to certain fanatics of varying
pedigrees _ little girls, track hounds, horse trainers,
large-animal veterinarians, romantics, jockeys, grooms, mare
managers, and, of course, the horses themselves _ there is scarcely
a finer scent on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Smiley gets a place on that list, for ``Horse Heaven'' is
so redolent with the essence of horse that you will probably have
alfalfa in your hair when you're done with it. This is a big,
burly, full-of-itself story that swaggers out of the gate, opens
easy on the track, breaks into a canter and stays there, in steady
state, until twilight. It's a novel of passion in every sense, from
the drive of the Thoroughbreds who run and fail and sometimes fly
into greatness, to the people who work with them, up at 3 a.m. and
sacrificing the rest of life _ if there is a rest of life _ in
order to hang out in a barn 18 hours a day or save a mare in labor.
And if Smiley's voice is as thrilled-but-controlled as a race
announcer's, she has also managed this far-flung story with a demon
narrative intelligence. It's one thing to get right the look of a
newborn foal (sweet, wet) or the frenzy of a winner's circle at the
Breeder's Cup (bedlam, letdown). It's another entirely to manage
emergency colic surgery, solitary stable lurkers, and the way a
race feels from the horse's back _ and do it all with aplomb,
muscle, and not a little grace. ``Well, he knows who he is,''
trainers say about one uppity Thoroughbred. So does ``Horse
Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley's only predictable trait as a writer is her versatility.
Having wowed her way into acclaim with the careful literary feats
of ``The Age of Grief'' and ``Ordinary Love and Good Will,'' she
went on to produce high-serious (``A Thousand Acres'') and
high-funny (``Moo''), followed by an interminable faux-19th-century
novel (``The All-True Travels and Adventures of Lidie Newton'')
that was saved only by its fierce authenticity. If ``Horse Heaven''
has a predecessor, it is ``Moo,'' mostly because of its unstoppable
energy; in the same way that Smiley infiltrated the hilarious gulag
of academe, she has gone native here. ``Horse Heaven'' is easily
too long by a third, and while that's a not inconsiderable problem,
it also may be the only substantial one the novel possesses.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing its perspective wisely, ``Horse Heaven'' opens in 1997
with the lineage of four Thoroughbred yearlings, two colts and two
fillies, who are on their way to all kinds of chaos and maybe
splendor. These are the stars that will light the way for the
intersecting paths of the novel, for the two things you can count
on in the horse business are that no animal stays put for long and
that eventually everything connects. Thus an 11-year-old girl in
Texas who tries to save an old neglected gelding by writing someone
in California will wind up, years later, blessed for her kindness
at a stable in Maryland. And the bay colt who starts off as ``Wow''
will resurface as ``Limitless,'' 3 years old and transcontinental,
as seemingly infinite in wins and attitude as he has been in
owners. Serendipity is the main thematic link of ``Horse Heaven,''
and if the first third of the story feels maddeningly overpopulated
(imagine a John le Carre novel with horses), the major players here
_ human and equine _ soon settle into a rhythm that ensures none
will get too misplaced or ill-remembered.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, of course, ``Horse Heaven'' had to follow its people
outside the corral; a whole dramatis personae consequently emerge
with stand-alone sagas, marked by the usual private fears and
secret dreams. There's trainer Farley Jones, who looks more like a
bearded professor than a horseman, who has a rule sheet titled
``The Tibetan Book of Thoroughbred Training'' pinned to his office
door _ who, his assistant reflects, is ``deep as a well and twice
as dark.'' There's the blustery industrialist Al Maybrick, richer
than sin and vigilantly sober for two years, who rises each day and
calls his AA sponsor, his horse trainer, and his broker. There's
the unforgettable Deirdre Donohue, a 40-year-old Irish horsewoman
who broke her back on a jumper; now she spends her days training
racehorses and trying not to fall too hard when she falls for one
of them, again. Oh, and there are myriad small-time winners and
losers, kindly veterinarians or mean ones, born-again crooked
trainers, a father-and-son betting team, a horse masseur with the
wisdom of Yoda, a Jack Russell terrier named Eileen, and _ Smiley's
link to the other side _ an animal communicator, formerly known as
a horse psychic, who gives a whole new meaning to omniscient point
of view.
</P>
<P>
   This conceptual leap needs some defense, lest it sound smarmy or
ill-conceived; indeed, a lesser writer couldn't possibly have
pulled it off. But by foisting the ``channeling'' onto a
big-hearted innocent named Elizabeth, Smiley has found a way in; as
a narrator, she's given herself entrance into the world of animal
consciousness. The maneuver is a neat trick for several reasons.
It's never heavy-handed, no more anthropomorphic than necessary,
and informed with scientific and behavioral savvy as well as humor.
Anyone ever moved by a cross-species attachment will not be
surprised by what Smiley has imagined; the corridors between most
species, as Jane Goodall will tell you, are lined with patience and
respect. All Smiley has done is to illuminate the hallway _ and
thus remind one of the sheer delights of literary invention.
Viewing the track through a 2-year-old filly's eyes seems no longer
a stretch than, say, comprehending what the Breeder's Cup means to
Al Maybrick. The first rule of omniscient license is one that
Smiley accomplishes from the moment Elizabeth opens her mouth: that
you simply be able to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's a bit of mystical drizzle all over ``Horse
Heaven,'' whether it's Al's wife, Rosalind, on an inner pilgrimage
in Ireland, or the bountiful love for their own kind that a few
lucky humans ultimately unearth. There's also a plentiful supply of
realism, horseracing being a business driven, on the worst days, by
greed, steroids, and unthinkable cruelty. Linking these disparate
realms of the sacred and profane is Smiley's wit, not to mention
her eye for near-perfect detail (including horses' names). Having
figured out a way to implant a sensory device in her pregnant
mares, a mare manager finds out that her horses have broken water
when the receiver dials her at home. ``It was 1:37. She picked up
the cellular phone. She heard her own voice say, `This is Donut. I
am foaling. Get up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   True to its ethos, the finest heroes in ``Horse Heaven'' are not
the horses in the winner's circles or the men and women who put
them there, but the wider cast _ the pony proletariat _ who hang
out, eat carrots, perform daily minor miracles, head-butt their
grooms, and spoil young girls for any lesser love their future
lives may bring them. If the story sometimes seems alarmingly
desultory, so, come to think of it, is the life of a racehorse. For
a novel that dares to roll in both the agony and the glory of the
human-equine contract, that's probably a predictable lament.
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Caldwell is chief book critic for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
