   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRADING SCHOOLMASTER GEORGE DUBYA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEXAS-SCHOOLS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the state of Texas, public schools have developed
tougher academic standards and improved their performance in
assessment tests, an achievement that George W. Bush mentions
constantly in stump speeches on the presidential campaign trail. It
is the cornerstone of his claim to be a ``reformer with results.''
That boast requires two questions: Have Texan schools truly
improved? And if so, how much of it has been Bush's doing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
