   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 325 words; 1,250 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COURTS GO WHERE CONGRESS FEARS TO TREAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUDGES-RULE-CONGRESS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the political process is snarled up, go to the courts. There,
judges are willing to regulate by litigation what Congress will not
influence by legislation. Congressional ambiguity is breeding
judicial activism, but in the long run, the recent increase in such
legal activism may produce more controversy than the congressional
foot-dragging that encourages it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
