</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLAND-PUTIN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russo-Polish relations these days are pretty chilly. Publicly,
the Poles are hopeful that Vladimir Putin, Russia's new president,
will help to improve matters. Privately, though, several leading
Poles in the government say they fear that Putin is a ``Chekist
(old secret-service) neo-imperialist,'' strong on state control and
weak on democracy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAURENT FABIUS: FRANCE'S MAN OF DELAYED DESTINY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `LAZARUS'-FABIUS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Fabius's natural expression is a self-satisfied smirk.
Perhaps it's misleading. Or perhaps not, given that the elegant
Fabius has long had a lot to smirk about. And now that beleaguered
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has appointed him to be his
third finance minister in less than five months, Fabius has even
more reason to smirk: the political rehabitation of Fabius. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 totaling 125 words; 1,050 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTAINING INCORRIGIBLE MICROSOFT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MICROSOFT-KERBEROS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft trial is at last coming to an end _ at least for
the moment. At such a time you might expect Microsoft to be on its
best behavior. Not so, say computer-security experts. They complain
that the company is as reluctant as ever to abandon its
much-criticized business tactic to ``embrace, extend _ and
extinguish.'' Witness its encryption technology called Kerberos... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EARTHY APPEAL OF NEBRASKA'S SOD HOUSES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOD-HOUSES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 87, Curtis Dowse is a living link to Nebraska's
past. In 1900, Dowse's father, grandfather and some of his
neighbors teamed up to build a house on the windswept Nebraska
plains _ made mostly from sod, the hardy top layer of soil that
pioneers found in abundance as they made their way west. While
Nebraska was once dotted with sod houses, it now has only about 100
of them in even minimally decent repair. Even so, they continue to
loom large _ and not only in the prairie mythology of Nebraska,
Kansas and the Dakotas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: NEBRASKA, Great-Plains Editors) &QL;
</P>
