 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONTENEGRO CAN BE SAVED FROM MILOSEVIC, IF... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT-BALKAN-WAR-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of NATO's war over Kosovo last June, the West's
adversary, Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, has tightened his
grip on power, at least in his native Serbia, and raised the
rhetorical temperature. Several ominous signs suggest that his next
land grab could be Montenegro, the last remaining republic with
which Serbia is linked in the shrunken Yugoslav federation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRADING SCHOOLMASTER GEORGE DUBYA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEXAS-SCHOOLS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the state of Texas, public schools have developed
tougher academic standards and improved their performance in
assessment tests, an achievement that George W. Bush mentions
constantly in stump speeches on the presidential campaign trail. It
is the cornerstone of his claim to be a ``reformer with results.''
That boast requires two questions: Have Texan schools truly
improved? And if so, how much of it has been Bush's doing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 325 words; 1,250 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COURTS GO WHERE CONGRESS FEARS TO TREAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUDGES-RULE-CONGRESS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the political process is snarled up, go to the courts. There,
judges are willing to regulate by litigation what Congress will not
influence by legislation. Congressional ambiguity is breeding
judicial activism, but in the long run, the recent increase in such
legal activism may produce more controversy than the congressional
foot-dragging that encourages it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ((NOTE: Story can stand in 900 words; 1,050 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPROVED MILWAUKEE SCHOOLS VOUCH FOR FREE CHOICE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VOUCHERS-MILWAUKEE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee, Wis., is an unlikely laboratory for the country's
most radical experiment in ``conservative'' reform of education.
The city gave birth to the Progressive movement and elected a
succession of socialist mayors. Yet there can be no doubt about the
boldness of the city's experiment with school vouchers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Milwaukee) &QL;
