<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-EAST-INDIAN-HNS &LR;      04-03 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-INDIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOSE RING HELPS AWAKEN CULTURAL IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KINNARI SHAH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``But you're even more American than I am!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you've never seemed Indian to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's my favorite, usually offered
enthusiastically, beamingly, by these non-Indian friends _ as
though conferring the greatest accolade of all: ``You're so
Americanized that I never think of you as different at all!''
</P>
<P>
   So I went to India and got my nose pierced.
</P>
<P>
   Not directly, not like that. And not just because they'd said
those things. But after having lived my entire life in this
country, I think friends were startled to realize that I still felt
a connection with my cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, I think people feel threatened by what seems
``different.'' Not threatened-scared in any xenophobic way, but
threatened-discombobulated.
</P>
<P>
   It bothers me when friends, complacent in their degree of
emotional connection with me, exclaim in shock and discomfort when
they realize that there are still many ways in which I do not feel,
cannot feel, they share my particular window on the world.
</P>
<P>
   Or they grow offended when they hear me call myself Indian
despite their protestations, thinking that I seek deliberately to
distance myself, that I fancy my viewpoint superior or imagine them
incapable of empathy.
</P>
<P>
   Or they laugh at me _ wanting to believe that because I don't
dress in ways that would clearly mark me as ``other,'' because my
speech is unaccented, my line of work conventional and my interests
along ``Westernized'' lines, that I am therefore ``just like
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The current brand of political correctness demands that its
adherents be so proudly tolerant of differences that they start
believing that there are no differences.
</P>
<P>
   But different needn't be better and is definitely not worse.
It's only ... different.
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to my nose ring _ that tiny sliver of diamond you
almost might not see _ were therefore telling. I could tell at a
glance or from the first stammered compliment who was sincere in
approbation and who wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   So it takes some getting used to. That's fine. It took me a
while as well. Amazing how such a little thing as this double-take
sparkle can alter the contours of one's face. And, of course, the
assumptions associated with body piercings in general made friends
throw askance glances: ``I never figured you for a radical.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there were those people who were happier to
think that I had done it for fashion reasons than for reasons of
ethnic identity.
</P>
<P>
   When I told one friend how, when I went to India last January
and saw that every one of my female cousins had her nose pierced, I
decided to do it as well, as a kind of connection to them and my
vouchsafed heritage in general, he retorted, ``But you're back here
now. You're back in America now.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked at him in surprise and said, ``But I'm still Indian. I
always was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I don't think wearing my nose ring makes me more
Indian. Rather, it allows me to insist I'm Indian at all. And so,
some months after I returned from our long-delayed family trip to
India, I think I've finally realized why I got my nose pierced: To
lay a more solid claim to who I am.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kinnari Shah, 30, is a lawyer who lives and works in San
Francisco. She is the first generation of her family born in the
United States. Shah received an undergraduate degree from the
University of California at Berkeley and a law degree from the
University of Michigan.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
