<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 325-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; U-TURN OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admitting that he was an ``imperfect messenger,'' Al Gore
proposed a sweeping plan for reforming campaign finance that would
ban soft money and direct contributions to particular candidates.
George W. Bush immediately responded by dubbing Gore an ``obstacle
to reform.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FORCE IS WITH HIM: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Luke Skywalker was loosely based on me.'' (Al Gore, in
self-deprecatory mood, at the annual Gridiron dinner, which he also
claimed to have invented 115 years ago.) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes gave his endorsement to Bush, deciding that he is
on the right side on tax cuts, Social-Security reform and national
defense. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANDIDATE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gebhardt filed for the Democratic nomination for the
third congressional district in Missouri against Richard Gephardt.
One is the minority leader of the House of Representatives, the
other is a 65-year-old Republican activist who doesn't live in the
district. At the last minute, the incumbent changed his name on the
ballot to ``Richard A. (Dick) Gephardt.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEGAL RULING OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled that Pat Choate, Ross Perot's running mate
in the 1996 election, is the legitimate chairman of the Reform
Party. Choate was elected last month to replace Jack Gargan, an
ally of Jesse Ventura, at a meeting that Gargan contended was held
illegally. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NON-RECONCILIATION OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since he suspended his presidential campaign,
John McCain spoke by telephone with Bush. The five-minute talk
between the Texan governor and the Arizonan senator was described
by McCain as cordial and a ``good initial conversation.'' There are
no plans for further conversations. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STRATEGIC ADVICE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't work to link Gore to Clinton. It didn't even work to
link Clinton to Clinton.'' (Gore adviser, New York Times March
29). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
