<HEADLINE>
IF WHINING WEST DISLIKES OPEC, STOP BURNING LESS OIL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial...RESENDING from March 31)   (This pithy 450-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a revived West End musical of 30 years ago, the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) has been
brought back to the center stage in Vienna. The plot's the same.
Indeed half the cast of oil ministers remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   As the demand for oil rises, will the Middle East producers hold
back production and keep prices up? Or will America, in the name of
the consumer, force its Arab allies to open up the taps again to
appease voters' anger in gas-guzzling America?
</P>
<P>
   Or will the radicals, led by Iran, keep the valves turned down?
</P>
<P>
   And the denouement this time? Well, roughly the same as the ones
we got used to on the last run: a messy compromise of partially
increased production, renewed threats of a squeeze should prices
fall too fast, and Iran sulking in the corner declaring the whole
thing a neo-imperialist plot by America.
</P>
<P>
   Having driven the price up nearly 300 percent by cutting
production by 1.7 million barrels a day six months ago, OPEC is now
saying that it will bring it down again by restoring those cuts _
but not so much as to let it fall below $20 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   As a performance it doesn't match the full sound and fury of the
original performance in the 1973/4 oil crisis. Times are different.
</P>
<P>
   The world _ outside of America _ has learned to curb its use of
oil for transport and move from oil to gas for heating and
electricity generation.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC can tighten a tightening market but it can't reverse it or
change long-term trends. The harder it squeezes now, the faster the
move to alternatives, as the big exporters such as Saudi Arabia
well know.
</P>
<P>
   Cartels have a poor history of survival. No group can fine-tune
as volatile a market as oil. And OPEC is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   But OPEC, while hardly high-minded and certainly not estimable,
is saying something of importance to western economies at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   For all the remorseless logic of free markets, oil remains a
peculiar and highly political commodity so long as the world's
demand for oil imports has to be met by a small number of exporters
(including non-OPEC countries such as Mexico and Norway) whose
interest may not lie in promoting unlimited production.
</P>
<P>
   To grow, the world needs cheap energy. But when it grows as fast
as America has, then it hits the buffers of OPEC dependence.
</P>
<P>
   If the world wants rid of dependence on OPEC, and if American
politicians want to avoid rising gas prices in the run-up to
elections, the answer is in their hands: Cut consumption and
promote alternatives to the car culture. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
