<HEADER>
A5711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-SPY-660&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPY-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RARE MOVE, CHINESE NULLIFY STANFORD SCIENTIST'S CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a highly unusual judicial reversal, the Beijing
High People's Court has nullified the conviction of a Chinese-born
Stanford University scientist who has been in prison for more than
two years for ``revealing state secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Hua Di, a Chinese citizen who is a permanent resident of the
United States, was arrested on a visit to China in January 1998,
his first in nearly a decade. Hua, a former Chinese missile
scientist, was sentenced to 15 years in prison by the Beijing
Number One Intermediate Court late last year for making public in
his writing in the United States disclosures about China's military
program.
</P>
<P>
   But the High Court last month found that the evidence presented
to the Intermediate Court did not warrant the conviction and
ordered the lower court to retry the case, family members who
recently received notice of the reversal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notice we got from the Beijing High Court said that `some
of the facts were unclear,''' said Wu Sanbao, Hua's sister. ``I
don't think that means the whole verdict has been overturned _
maybe that's going too far. But the court said it must go back to
the Intermediate Court for retrial.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and legal experts said the reversal was unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in recent memory we could recall the
High Court overruling a lower court in a politically sensitive
case,'' said a western diplomat in Beijing, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But while some of the experts saw the judicial review as a sign
of China's developing legal system, others suggested that it was a
political calculation designed to improve China's image at a time
when it is seeking to join the World Trade Organization and to
avoid censure at an upcoming human rights meeting in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has repeatedly brought up Hua's case, until
now to no effect. Hua's colleagues at Stanford University have
contended that all of the information that Hua discussed in his
articles was already publicly available.
</P>
<P>
   On retrial, Hua could be convicted again, convicted of a lesser
crime that required little or no further jail time or fully
exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this review is a good sign, and it looks like the
judicial process is operating,'' said Jerome Cohen, a New York
lawyer who recently represented Song Yongyi, another U.S.-based
scholar imprisoned in China earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he noted that decisions are ``very opaque in such
security cases'' and that it was impossible to say how much the
decision was influenced by political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of great political sensitivity, and I'm sure
that political factors played some role,'' he said. ``There would
have had to be consultation with city, party and central legal
committees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese judiciary is not independent, and defendants are
often convicted in trials where in practice they have few rights _
particularly if their crimes are political in nature. They are
sometimes not allowed to have access to lawyers or to speak in
their own defense, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But China has also taken great efforts to reform its legal
system in recent years, writing new laws and training thousands of
lawyers. As this new legal consciousness has taken hold, legal
experts say, the system is slowly becoming more concerned with
justice and less with political expediency.
</P>
<P>
   The case was sent back to the Intermediate Court according to a
clause in China's Criminal Procedure Code, which took effect in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The legal turn of events seemed to take Hua's supporters by
surprise. Some had anticipated that Hua, who suffers from a rare
form of male breast cancer, might be released on medical grounds.
Chinese authorities have frequently released jailed dissidents to
the United States on medical parole as a political gesture of good
will or once their cases became politically embarrassing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wu, Hua's sister, said she had not seen her brother for more
than two years, since his arrest, and did not know ``whether he's
suffered any relapses or not.'' But she said that ``he hasn't been
getting the radiation therapy he was getting before.''
</P>
<P>
   Hua is being held in a Beijing State Security Detention Center,
his relatives said, the same one that earlier this year held the
other American academic, Song Yongyi.
</P>
<P>
   Song, a Chinese-born researcher at Dickinson College in
Pennsylvania, was jailed for purchasing original materials from
China's Cultural Revolution period _ materials that are widely
available in bookstores and street markets.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities granted his release only after saying that
he had ``confessed to his crimes'' and informed on others involved
in similar misdeeds. He has steadfastly denied all charges. He was
returned to the United States after a campaign by academics and
congressmen to secure his release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
