<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVAR-WINERY-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPES OF WRATH: KOSOVAR ALBANIANS RETURN TO THEIR VINEYARDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from March 31)   (This 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW BUNCOMBE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAHOVEC, SOUTHWEST KOSOVO _ The wine was red and, though it was
chilled, as Qamil Cena poured from the clear, unlabelled bottle,
its fragrance leapt from the glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is from 1992. It is made from the Merlot grape,'' said
Cena. ``It is one of our best wines.'' The year 1992 may have been
an excellent vintage for the wine-makers of southern Kosovo, but it
was also the year in which Cena, a trained agriculturist, was
forced from his job.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of Kosovar Albanians, 36-year-old Cena _ a
manager with the state-owned Orvin wine company _ lost out as the
authorities filled key positions across Kosovo with Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years scrabbling to make a living, he returned to
work last summer in the aftermath of the war. Now, nine months on,
Cena and thousands of other Kosovar Albanians are back in their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In such circumstances the renamed winery is now preparing to
make what may be its most memorable vintage yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speak for myself. After I finished my studies I
started working here. Of course (this year) is important,'' said
Cena. ``We don't plan to have any special name for the wine but
that could come later. First we have to produce the grapes and then
we can think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry of southern Kosovo, where often the vineyards
appear to run to the horizon, has always been important and the
wines of Orvin were traditionally considered the best.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, up to 80 percent of the wine the company
produced _ including Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot, Pinot Noir,
Chardonnay and Riesling _ was exported. It was a huge foreign
currency earner for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then. Although the Albanian workers have taken
control of the winery, calling it by the less than rounded mouthful
of the Agricultural and Industrial Enterprise of Rahovec (NBI
Rahoveci), the future is beset by problems.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the situation last year, in which the entire crop was
lost, people were not able to work the vines. As a result they
expect only 30-40 percent of their 3,500 hectares (8,650 acres) of
vineyards to produce grapes for this year's pressing.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the shortage of materials. The 600 workers are
short of fertilizer and herbicide. With the exception of the wine
labels, which they produce themselves, everything else _ the
bottles, the corks, the barrels of Croatian oak in which the wine
is aged for a minimum of two years _ have to be imported.
</P>
<P>
   To add to their difficulties, last winter was one of the coldest
in living memory and many of the vines were killed. A small area of
the vineyards still cannot be entered because land mines remain,
left by the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the enterprise _ its wage bill now being paid by the United
Nations, which has formally assumed ownership of all former
state-owned companies _ cannot afford to fail.
</P>
<P>
   While 600 people are employed directly by the plant, up to
30,000 people are involved in the region's wine industry. Many of
these are employed on an ad hoc basis _ helping with the harvest in
September and October _ but others own the privately-held vineyards
which make up two-thirds of the total acreage providing grapes for
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Among these owners are Bahtiar and Gazmend Tara, two brothers
who were cutting back the dead wood on their three hectares (7 1/2
acres) of vines. Their family of 11 depends on the grapes and other
produce they can grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really hope for much of a harvest,'' said Bahtiar,
his fingers furiously working a pair of secateurs as a snow storm
blew down the valley. ``Everything was frozen this winter so we
don't expect great results. We will have to wait until next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers at Rahovec believe their future could lie in
restoring the export agreements that Orvin had with a number of
European countries, particularly Germany. The plant's director,
Aqim Hasku, spends much of his time trying to achieve this.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, for the workers at the plant, spring is a busy
time of the year and they intend to go on doing what they have done
for many years: growing grapes, making wine. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
