<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-JUDGE04-COX     04-03 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUDGE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT JUDGE REGARDED AS TOUGH BUT FAIR
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At an early stage of federal antitrust action
against Microsoft Corp., when the company insisted that the Windows
95 operating system wouldn't work without its Internet browser,
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson decided to find out for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   With help from a courtroom technician, the judge was able to
``uninstall'' his own Explorer Internet browser in about 90
seconds. With that, Jackson ordered the software giant to begin
selling Windows 95 separately from its browser.
</P>
<P>
   While that order was overturned on appeal _ leading eventually
to the Justice Department suit against Microsoft that yielded a
ruling Monday _ Jackson's dive into the technical aspects of the
case is indicative of his approach to law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom calls it like he sees it,'' says James Schaller, his
former law partner at Jackson &AMP; Campbell in Washington. ``That's
his signature. Most people respect him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before issuing his verdict in the high-profile Microsoft case,
Jackson broke precedent by asking a federal appeals court judge,
Richard Posner of Chicago, to try to settle the case as a private
mediator. When Posner's efforts failed, he praised Jackson for his
bold initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 63, is is no newcomer to the national spotlight. The
burly white-haired judge was appointed to the bench in 1982 by
President Reagan. In 1991, he sent former Washington, D.C., Mayor
Marion Barry to jail for cocaine possession. Three years later, he
ordered former Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., to turn over sex-filled
diary entries to a Senate Ethics Committee. And in 1997, he fined
Reagan's former aide Michael Deaver $100,000 for lying about
lobbying activities.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's Washington roots run deep. He grew up in the city's
affluent suburbs, attending the exclusive St. Albans School. He
sang for the Washington Cathedral Choir.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to Dartmouth College. Upon graduation, he joined the
U.S. Navy as a line officer, spending three years aboard a
destroyer in the Atlantic and Mediterranean. He returned to Harvard
University Law School, graduating in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Washington, Jackson worked with his father, Thomas
Searing Jackson, a well-known Washington lawyer, at a predecessor
firm to Jackson &AMP; Campbell. The father of two grown daughters, he
loves sailing and spends weekends in St. Mary's County, Md.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallways of the U.S. District Court, prosecutors and
defense attorneys say Jackson is an affable, able judge who runs a
tight ship. A former litigator, he's considerate of the time
pressures on overworked lawyers. Also, he's been known to show
compassion for those sentenced. One defense attorney recalls
Jackson using flexibility in sentencing a former military medic who
served in Panama. The reason: The man had served his country during
war without a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jackson is not without critics. The gossipy
Washingtonian magazine lambasted him in 1996, calling him one of
Washington's worst judges. In 1995, the trade publication Legal
Times took him to task for moving slowly and calling long lunch
breaks. A 1993 Legal Times analysis showed that his reversal rate
was about 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Former clerks describe the judge as a warm, mentoring boss who
takes a personal interest in their lives. But no one denies he has
a tough side. Jackson repeatedly has gone head-to-head with
Microsoft. Following the browser incident, he threatened the
company's lawyers with contempt sanctions because he said they
defamed a court- appointed expert, Lawrence Lessig. Following a
Microsoft appeal, Lessig stepped down as the court's special master
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
