<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-JOHN-SCULLEY-2TAKES-H     04-03 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-SCULLEY-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORMER MOVER AT APPLE NOW PUMPS MONEY INTO TECH START-UPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SRACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Seven years after he left Apple Computer Inc.,
John Sculley is still chasing the technology dream, jet-setting
around the globe looking for that next killer app.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley, the former chief executive of Apple, is now a venture
capitalist, trading the political intrigue of the boardroom for the
thrill of the hunt. He has replaced one Apple with another in the
process, founding Sculley Brothers LLC, a low-profile venture
capital company based in his hometown of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside his brothers, Arthur and David, Sculley has helped
launch 25 companies to date, all of them in the technology
business. The companies run the gamut of e-commerce, including
business-to-consumer Web sites like Buy.com and More.com, and
business-to-business exchanges like BigMachines.com and TechEx.
</P>
<P>
   He is splitting his time between the two coasts these days,
visiting the San Francisco area about once a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this as three brothers, working with people we
like, focusing on a few themes which tie back into our marketing
and operating backgrounds,'' said Sculley, reclining in a Fairmont
Hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brothers and I have all held general management positions
in large companies. We try to always partner with first-tier
investors. Our role is largely business development, opening doors,
putting together partnerships, bringing in money, recruiting
management. It's not an awful lot different than the big venture
companies, but just on a smaller scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Sculley, 61, is high on business-to-business enterprises,
shunning any mention of the business-to-consumer space he and most
other financiers were falling over each other to fund just a few
short months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focused on several themes, like B2B exchanges,'' Sculley
said, referring to business-to-business companies. ``We're also
focused on B2B services and customer relationship management. We're
trying to be one of the enablers to transform the old economy into
the new economy, but we're doing it in a very low-profile way. We
don't want a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a big change for a man who has made a career out of
getting the attention of consumers. In his salad days in the 1980s,
Sculley was considered by many to be the best marketing chief
executive in the world. First at Pepsi, then at Apple, Sculley
earned his reputation with hard work and impressive results.
</P>
<P>
   During his 16 years in a number of marketing and management
positions at Pepsi, Sculley helped lead the company past archrival
Coke by the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   At Apple, where he served as chief executive from 1983 to 1993,
he is largely given credit for the rise in the corporation's
revenues from $600 million per year to more than $8 billion per
year by the time he left. Perhaps most importantly, he brought
big-brand marketing to the computer business.
</P>
<P>
   The transition between the two jobs took place in 1982, when
Sculley was first bitten by the Silicon Valley bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I ever came to Silicon Valley was in 1982.
Steve Jobs and Andy Hertzfeld, one of the original programmers of
the Mac, showed me this bench-top prototype product, which was the
Mac before the Mac,'' said Sculley. ``They had dancing Pepsi cans
on the screens. That's when I first began to realize what was
possible with visualization on a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   We all know what happened then. Jobs convinced Sculley, then the
chief of Pepsi, to stop selling colored sugar water and join Apple
in changing the world. A few years later, Jobs left Apple in a
boardroom coup for which he blamed Sculley. As Jobs put it,
famously, ``I hired the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sculley had given the Apple board of directors an ultimatum at
the time, essentially asking them to choose between him and Jobs.
With his fiery temper and manic management style working against
him, Jobs was out, and Sculley was alone at the top.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming years, the company grew under Sculley. On the
downside, he chose note to license the Mac operating system to
clone makers and gradually lost market share to Microsoft. By 1993,
with product shortages and planning snafus clouding the company's
performance, the board gave Sculley his own set of walking papers,
replacing him with Michael Spindler.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Sculley made one more pass at the executive suite,
taking over the wireless company Spectrum Information Technologies.
It was an ill-fated move that ended with Sculley's suing the
Purchase, N.Y.-based company for withholding information while
recruiting him.
</P>
<P>
   It was after that debacle that he slowly started getting into
the funding game, using his own money to back technology ventures
he liked. Sculley Brothers LLC was born in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   With it grew Sculley's thirst for a repeat performance of his
Apple experience _ another chance to change the world. Visiting San
Francisco with one of his world-changing candidates, it is evident
that Sculley has lost none of the evangelical spark needed to pitch
emerging technology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His latest protege is a young Israeli named Eyal Gever. Sculley
thinks Gever has hatched another ``insanely great'' idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Eyal is doing in my humble opinion _ and remember, I'm
not a techie, but just a plain old marketing guy _ makes me feel
like I'm witnessing again one of those extraordinary, special
moments where there is the beginning of a platform that
fundamentally changes the way the Internet can be commercialized,
from a publishing model, which I spent 10 years at Apple helping to
promote, to a broadcasting model.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO: xxx a broadcasting model. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eyal heads Gizmoz Inc. His company, formerly known as Zapa
Digital Arts, has created Internet infrastructure technology for
broadcasting over the Internet, with an eye on the marketing
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a broadcasting solution for broadcasters,'' Gever said.
``If you look in the dictionary, a gizmo is a surprising,
functional object. I wanted to name it as an object because I
wanted people to collect it and share it.''
</P>
<P>
   The end product is referred to as a gizmo, a 13K Java applet
that can be used to transmit, or broadcast, any number of media
over the Net to a user's computer, where they can be saved, moved,
copied, sent, posted or trashed. Gizmoz is hoping people keep them,
giving marketers a new pipeline into the consumers' home turf.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley declined to reveal his stake in the company. Regardless
of how much, Sculley is sharing that stake with some pretty big
hitters. Stateside, the company's investors include Chase Equity
Associates and AOL Investments. In Israel, two of the country's
biggest tech investment houses, Giza GE Venture Fund and Polaris
Venture Capital, are in.
</P>
<P>
   All these investors are betting that gizmos can revolutionize
the way advertising is done on the Internet. As any Net surfer
knows, banner ads are played out, and few if any Net companies have
been able to turn a profit on that business model. Enter Eyal and
his value-added gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now we've been dependent on banner technology, which
for the first few years was pretty important because it created all
the eyeballs out there,'' Sculley said. ``As we move into
e-commerce being the sweet spot of the Internet today, you've got
to have, as marketers, the ability to send messages that have a lot
more emotion to them. You've got to have the ability to interact
with people much more than banners.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether more emotion equates to more
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich media advertising has been problematic,'' said Jim Nail,
a senior analyst specializing in Internet commerce at Oat Forrester
Research, an Internet research company. ``You've got companies like
Unicast, Enliven and Blue Streak working in this space, but there's
a number of barriers to the adoption of these kinds of
technologies. One is the technology barriers of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second and bigger barrier is the rut that advertisers and
ad agencies are in. They don't understand the capabilities of these
technologies. It takes a different thought process to use these
things effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies Nail refers to _ Unicast, Enliven and Blue Streak
_ basically produce souped-up banner ads that still work on the
principle that users will see the ad, then click-through to a
company's site.
</P>
<P>
   Gizmos, on the other hand, represent a way for companies to take
permanent residence on a consumer's computer, allowing them repeat
visits with different marketing messages. While that sounds great
to marketers, it could defeat the whole business model.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can grab these gizmos and hold onto them on their
personal Web sites or wherever, and the advertisers can still
update and change those messages,'' Nail said. ``Effectively, the
advertisers wouldn't have to pay the media companies and Web sites
for repeat advertising. That could be bad news for both.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those hurdles, Nail feels Sculley's involvement with
Gizmos is nothing but good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he brings to this is enormous connections to the
traditional advertising world and the top brand marketers and
leading advertising spenders,'' Nail said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can open an awful lot of doors for this company. It's a new
idea, and it'll be hard for traditional marketers to wrap their
heads around it. With Sculley, at least they'll listen to the
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sculley, meanwhile, remains very fond of Apple, openly praising
Jobs for his triumphant return to the company's helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what Steve Jobs has done with Apple is one of the
great business success stories of all time,'' Sculley said. ``From
my perspective, I see Steve picking up exactly where he left off in
1995. Only this time, he's a far more experienced, savvy executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is really interesting, having been there when Steve was
there originally, was that he didn't waver from his original
strategy. He took the company right back to the same principles
that he believed in then and obviously believes in now.''
</P>
<P>
   Those same principles, namely finding technology you're
passionate about and driving it to greatness, have stuck with
Sculley. Just the same, he is not itching to get back in the
executive saddle, to the extent he did with Jobs and company back
in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had more fun in my life,'' said Sculley, looking
remarkably calm and rested for a man who is on the go all day.
``There are so many young, talented founders and CEOs that the best
role I could play is to coach and advise a lot of these young
entrepreneurs. Having had the chance to make all the mistakes I
have, they can learn from them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
