<P>
   &UR; MICROSOFT ANTITRUST &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the decision in the Microsoft antitrust case. This does
not include any text.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ A ledeall: Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson is expected to issue his ruling in the Microsoft
antitrust case at 5 p.m. EDT. As his findings of fact in November
largely agreed with the governments' case against Microsoft, the
judge's conclusions of law are almost certain to find that the
company violated federal antitrust laws. It is uncertain, however,
how sweeping his ruling will be. The judge will then consider
remedies, which could range from forcing Microsoft to change
certain business practices to a breakup of the company. Shares of
Microsoft fall nearly 14 percent in early trading. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TALKS (Undated) _ A look at the settlement
negotiations and how far the Justice Department was prepared to go.
By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LEGAL (Washington) _ A legal analysis of Judge
Jackson's decision, looking at any vulnerabilities on appeal. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACT (San Francisco) _ Industry reaction to the
judge's ruling. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REDMOND (Redmond) _ Reaction from Microsoft's home. By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   Other sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Plus this related story:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq stocks were down sharply in early
trading as the breakdown in the talks between Microsoft and the
government drag down technology stocks. At 11:15 a.m., the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 1.33 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 up 0.17
percent but the Nasdaq composite was down 4.27 percent. By Kenneth
N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors, Ford Motor and
DaimlerChrysler report March sales. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-MORNING (New York) _ CBS's big move to challenge the NBC and
ABC morning shows isn't working. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   MATTEL-LEARNING () _ Mattel puts the Learning Company, which it
had acquired earlier, up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TELECOMS (Mexico City) _ A look at the success of
Telefonos de Mexico, the country's dominant telephone company.
Critics contend that Telmex remains an effective monopoly, abetted
by the Mexico government, and other potential rivals, including
AT&AMP;T and MCI, are threatening to file a formal complaint with the
World Trade Organization. By Julia Preston.
