   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-WARCRIMES (The Hague, Netherlands) _ NATO troops in the
French sector of Bosnia arrest the highest-level Bosnian Serb
leader to date, Momcilo Krajisnik, on genocide charges. He was the
right-hand man of Radovan Karadzic and seen as someone who could
implicate Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Prime Minister Obuchi remains in a coma
after suffering a stroke early Sunday, and is being kept alive on a
respirator. The Cabinet secretary, Mikio Aoki, is acting as prime
minister. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY (Beijing) _ In a rare reversal, Beijing's high court
has overturned the conviction of a Chinese researcher for Stanford
University sentenced to 15 years imprisonment for leaking state
secrets. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GERMAN-DEATHS (Shanghai) _ A German family of four was
stabbed to death in Nanjing early Sunday, a rare incident of
violence against foreign residents here that highlights a creeping
acceleration of crime across the country. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (San Jose) _ Clinton speaks on China-trade. By
Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Fatma Passage) _ Israel says that after it
withdraws from Lebanon it will take in every Lebanese who now lives
in the ``security zone,'' about 70,000 people. The leader of
Israel's allies, the South Lebanon Army, says they will stay and
fight. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE (Jerusalem) _ William Cohen, the U.S.
secretary of defense, and Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak,
wrangle over AWACS-type planes Israel is selling to China. By
William A. Orme Jr
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-FUTURE (United Nations) _ Secretary General Kofi Annan lays
out his vision of the future of U.N.. He also holds a press
conference and calls for more high-tech/Internet work by the U.N.
in the developing world. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-KILLING (Undated) _ Jean Dominique, the director of Radio
Haiti and the country's best-known political commentator, died here
from gunshot wounds after being attacked by unknown assailants,
relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WELFARE (Washington) _ A roundup: In 1996 Congress said
that legal services lawyers, when representing welfare clients, may
not challenge the constitutionality of any welfare law. The 2nd
Circuit has declared that law unconstitutional, and on Monday the
Supreme Court agreed to hear the issue. Plus other cases also
accepted by the court. By Linda Greenhouse. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   GAS-ALTERNATIVES (Washington) _ Once upon a time, the government
had a plan to fix the oil problem so that the United States would
not have to pay attention to OPEC any more. Congress passed the
plan in 1992, right after the Persian Gulf War, and by the far-off
year of 2000, 10 percent of the gasoline and diesel fuel used for
cars, pick-ups, vans and sport utility vehicles was supposed to be
displaced with other fuels. But thus far, it has been a fairy tale;
alternative fuels like compressed natural gas, ethanol, methanol
and propane, then 0.23 percent of supplies, have risen to just 0.35
percent, about an eye-dropper full of progress for each gallon. By
Matthew L. Wald. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLLUTION (Pittsburgh) _ Gov. George W. Bush on Monday
unveils a plan for cleaning and redeveloping polluted industrial
sites. By Frank Bruni. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DIGITAL-DIVIDE (Atlanta) _ Vice President Al Gore speaks on
the digital divide. By Kevin Sack. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Campaign news and notes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   STANFORD-HENNESSEY (Palo Alto, Caif.) _ Stanford University to
name John Hennessey as its president. He is the university's
provost and had founded a Silicon Valley firm. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Redwood City, Calif.) _ A Silicon Valley
tycoon has spent $2 million to draft a school voucher initiative in
California and qualify it for the November ballot. If passed, it
would give $4,000 to parents of each pupil to spend on private
schools, including parochial ones, a broader subsidy than any
voucher program in the country now provides. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   EMBRYOS-DIVORCE (Boston) _ Ruling in a case in which a woman
wanted to implant and bring to term some frozen embryos she had
made with her husband before their divorce, the Supreme Judicial
Court of Massachusetts has ruled that as a matter of public policy,
no one should be forced by a court to become a parent against his
will. The court had already ruled that the woman could not use the
embryos, the opinion explains their reasoning. Other state courts
have ruled that the contract made between a husband and wife should
prevail. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez case. By
Rick Bragg. (800 words)
</P>
