<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-FALCONE-SPI &LR;      04-03 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB MINISERIES CLAIMS PHONE AS THE PROP OF CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C+  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Pistone, FBI mob infiltrator known to his underworld
colleagues as Joe Falcone, is on the phone. Let's listen in.
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Mags, you know I can't come home tonight.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE (his long-suffering wife): But honey, you haven't been
home since the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: I know. But I got a thing.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: What thing?
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: I can't tell you. It's a thing!
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: But the girls miss you.
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Are you saying I'm a bad father?
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: Well ....
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Hold on. I got another call. (Pause.) Hello?
</P>
<P>
   SONNY NAPOLI (Joe's mob boss): Joe, it's Sonny. Pick me up
tomorrow, 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Sure. What's up?
</P>
<P>
   SONNY: I got a thing.
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: OK. (Pause.) Honey, you still there?
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: Who was that?
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: Do I know this nobody?
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: It was nobody! Now, where were we?
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: You asked me if you were a bad father?
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: And?
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE (sobbing): Well, for someone who works for the feds and
is gone for weeks at a time and had to move us to the suburbs and
make us change our names and put the kids in new schools, and who
comes home occasionally with a black eye and cuts on his face, I
guess you're not so bad.
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: That's better.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: When will we get to see you?
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Soon. At that thing.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: What thing?
</P>
<P>
   PISTONE/FALCONE: Gotta go.
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE: But ...
</P>
<P>
   The preceding isn't from an actual script of the new series,
``Falcone,'' just a fair summation of where it's going. And maybe
it's no coincidence that ``Falcone'' rhymes with phone. It is the
prop of choice in this stylish mob drama that CBS wants us to watch
nearly every night for the next week, miniseries style. Problem is,
some performances in ``Falcone'' seem to have been phoned in. Some
of the writing, too.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the guy who inspired the film ``Donnie Brasco,''
``Falcone'' takes viewers inside the New York Mafia with undercover
agent Joe Pistone. Jason Gedrick plays Pistone/Falcone with little
emotion, apparently because FBI agents aren't supposed to show all
their cards. The guy he has endeared himself to in the mob, Sonny
Napoli, is played with little emotion by Titus Welliver, because
mobsters don't like to show their cards, either. Even Joe's wife,
Maggie (Amy Carlson), tries to keep her cards to herself in this
back-and-forth gin game. Unfortunately, when she does give in to
her pent-up emotions, well, it's as unsatisfying as a low-fat
cannolli.
</P>
<P>
   After two episodes appear back to back Tuesday, the remaining
seven installments in the series' first order will run tomorrow
through April 12, skipping only Sunday night. It's an unusual
tactic, especially for a dramatic series, but not a bad idea. CBS
sent six episodes to TV critics and, while ``Falcone'' has
limitations, including stomach-turning violence and pervasive
woodenness, it tends to grow on a person, kind of like nostril
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone. One-hour drama series about an FBI agent who
infiltrates a mob operation. Starring Jason Gedrick, Titus
Welliver, Robert John Burke, Amy Carlson, Sonny Marinelli and Lillo
Brancato Jr. Two-hour series premiere Tuesday night on CBS;
one-hour episodes continue through April 12, except Sunday. m.
Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
