<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAKE-CHARGE-HEALTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON TAKING CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Sidebar to story slugged `CANCER FIGHT') 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are a few jumping-off points in the growing sea of medical
information:
</P>
<P>
   Books: ``Don't Let Your HMO Kill You'' (Routledge; $14.95); and
``Surviving Modern Medicine'' (Rutgers University Press; $18) are
two titles in a growing cadre of books that spell out ways to take
charge of medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Television: HBO is taking the unusual step of making its signal
available for free as it rebroadcasts ``Cancer: Evolution to
Revolution'' at 4:30 p.m. Wednesday, 10 a.m. Thursday, 8 a.m. April
11, and 2:30 p.m. April 17. The network is also offering the tape
free of charge to cancer organizations. PBS' ``Frontline'' tackles
the managed-care issue at 10 p.m. Tuesday with ``Dr. Solomon's
Dilemma,'' a detailed look at how physicians are battling HMO for
control of patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Internet: Most illnesses are featured on individual Web sites or
have advocacy groups that are easily found via Internet search
engines. General information is available at Web sites such as
www.peoplesmed.org, a nonprofit medical consumer advocacy group.
For the next six months, HBO is offering extensive cancer contact
information at www.hbo.com. PBS goes into more depth on the
HMO-doctor struggle at www.pbs.org/frontline. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
