<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE-4     04-03 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CRITICIZES ISRAEL'S SALE OF MILITARY RADAR SYSTEMS TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With Prime Minister Ehud Barak standing by his side,
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen on Monday strongly criticized
Israel's decision to supply advanced airborne radar systems to
China.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government considers it ``counter-productive'' to
provide China with AWACS-type surveillance aircraft, Cohen said at
a news conference Monday morning after meeting with Barak, who
declined to halt the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Aircraft Industries, a state-owned defense contractor,
has already equipped one Chinese-owned Ilyushin cargo plane with
early-warning radar systems for a reported $230 million. It is
expected to present the aircraft for delivery to China's president,
Jiang Zemin, during his visit here later this week. Israel has
offered China systems for three more such planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have indicated before that the United States does not
support the sale of this type of technology to China because of the
potential of changing the strategic balance in that region, with
the tensions running as high as they are between China and
Taiwan,'' Cohen said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak responded that Israel would ``take into account'' U.S.
concerns. But he indicated that Israel expects to proceed with the
promised sale of at least the first radar-equipped aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware of the sensitivity in the United States with
regard to China,'' he said. Then he quickly added, ``We are, of
course, aware of our commitments in the contracts that we signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's arrival here Thursday will be the first official visit
to Israel by a Chinese leader, making this a singularly awkward
week to renege on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. congressional leaders have warned Israel that
proceeding with the sales could jeopardize support for the $17
billion military aid package Israel is seeking in connection with
an eventual peace treaty with Syria. Among the items Israel is
requesting are U.S. Boeing AWACS, considered far more sophisticated
than the Israeli version.
</P>
<P>
   According to Israeli military officials, Israel notified the
United States four years ago of its intent to offer airborne radar
surveillance systems to China. Pentagon officials reviewing the
proposed contract determined then that Israel would not be
providing China with proprietary U.S. military technology, the
Israelis said.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. objections to the sale now are based not on narrow
interpretations of technology transfer agreements but on the
broader principle that Israel as a U.S. ally should defer to U.S.
strategic judgments in regions beyond the Middle East _ especially
in areas where the United States has bases and warships. The United
States has not supplied arms to China since 1992.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cohen voiced concerns against the sale privately before but had
never spoken out publicly here.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Barak said, ``We are aware of the need to be in close
coordination and contact with the United States on every issue that
might pose a risk to American interests.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Barak has also placed great emphasis on the self-sufficiency
of Israel's military industry, which Pentagon officials readily
acknowledge can survive only through an aggressive sales program.
Israel Aircraft Industries is the country's largest export earner,
selling weapons systems and refurbished fighter jets to dozens of
countries, as well as civilian commuter aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and his predecessors have also put great stock in a
strengthened relationship with China, seen as both a critical
market for Israel and a bulwark against diplomatic isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Israel did not establish full diplomatic relations with
China until 1997, it has provided arms to Beijing since the 1980s.
Israel aided the ongoing development of China's F-10 fighter jet,
which is expected to carry a version of Israel's Pitun missile. But
the potentially billion-dollar order for four AWACS-type planes
would, if realized, be its largest sale to China yet.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials also consider the project important. Li Peng,
the chairman of China's National People's Congress, and Che Ho
Tien, China's defense minister, have personally inspected the
converted Ilyushin surveillance planes on visits to Israel in the
past six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
