u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     04-03 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, April 4:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ROBOT-SURGERY (Undated) _ A robot with three tiny metal
arms, operated by a surgeon at a computer console, now is
performing operations on patients, invading the body through
pencil-sized holes. This sort of operation, heart surgeons say, is
the start of what may be the biggest change in their profession
since it began nearly 40 years ago. Eventually, surgeons believe,
most heart surgery will be done by robots whose arms are inserted
through pencil-sized holes punched in the patient's chest. By Gina
Kolata. (1970 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICS-STRINGS (Undated) _ In the last few months, new
ideas emerging from theoretical workshops offer some hope of
connecting the airy speculations of superstring theory to reality.
Physicists are proposing a revised view in which at least one of
the six extra dimensions expounded in the theory is vastly larger,
large enough perhaps to be indirectly probed with existing
accelerators. Some experts say it is conceivable that experimenters
have already found subtle hints of other dimensions. They've just
had no way of appreciating what they were seeing. By George
Johnson. (2050 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MUSSELS-HUDSON (Undated) _ The zebra mussel has transformed
the chemistry of the freshwater portion of the Hudson. The mussels
consume microscopic plants, called phytoplankton, that are the
basis of the aquatic food chain. One result has been that numbers
of tiny aquatic animals that feed on the phytoplankton were cut
about in half, sharply reducing food for bigger creatures. Now
experts have discovered that mussels suck up so much oxygen from
the water that in summer that much of the ecosystem is approaching
a danger point at which other aquatic creatures begin to flee or
die, a new study reports. By William K. Stevens. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOGS-EVOLVE (Undated) _ After splitting genetically from
wolves around 135,000 years ago, dogs have followed humans through
every step in their cultural and social development, from hunting
and gathering to agricultural societies, from the farm to the city
and suburb. The dog has helped domesticate sheep and cattle, served
selflessly as a guard, beast of burden, guide, and erstwhile
companion capable of easing the pain of loneliness. So closely
entwined are their lives that a number of evolutionary biologists
argue that dogs and humans have co-evolved. By Mark Derr. (1450
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FLATOW-NPR (Undated) _ A conversation with Ira Flatow, one
of the most influential communicators of science. He is the host of
National Public Radio talkfest, ``Science Friday,'' a weekly
dialogue with scientists and members of Flatow's audience of two
and a half million listeners who phone in their questions, ideas
and opinions. By Claudia Dreifus. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEA-FLOOR-MAP (Undated) _ Oceans are hardly perfectly level
from one place to another. The height of an undisturbed sea's
surface can differ from a few inches to several feet from place to
place depending upon what lies far beneath the water. Scientists
have learned to exploit this from above to map mountains, valleys,
trenches and other features on the ocean floor that have gone
virtually unvisited by humans and their devices. This information,
coupled with data from submarine exploration, sonar scans and
instruments lowered to the depths, has now produced the most
comprehensive, detailed maps of sea-floor topography released to
the public. By Warren E. Leary. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on
principles of color found in male Indonesian butterfly and released
California condors. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOPSY-ACCURACY (Undated) _ Biopsies are sometimes wrong,
and second opinions are often proper when cancer is diagnosed. And
determining if cancer is present in sample of tissue the size of a
pinhead is not always clear cut. The experience and specialty of
the pathologist is often crucial an accurate finding. By Laurie
Tarkan. (1475 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTORS-CONSULT (Undated) _ Despite doctors' best
intentions, a chill wind still can blow through the exam room when
patients say they want second opionions. But often, without
patients' knowledge, doctors are already consulting colleagues
about treatment options and treatment plans. And when doctors are
perplexed, they often directly refer the patients to specialists.
By Abigail Zuger, M.D. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROPHYLACTIC-MASTECTOMY (Undated) _ A desperate measure for
reducing the risk of breast cancer, removing both breasts while
they are still healthy, has been proved effective even for women
who carry genetic defects that put them at the very highest level
of risk for the disease. By Denise Grady. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: New warnings are
issued on the dangers of piercings, including spurring allergies,
causing infections, leaving unsightly scars and causing injuries.
And, some teenagers, live to regret their excesses. By Jane E.
Brody. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Boys who are shorter are more likely to be held back in
school, a study from Australia suggests. (150 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Half of the surgical patients surveyed in a University of
Colorado study used herbal or alternative medicines or vitamins in
the days before their operation, although many of these substances
can interfere with anesthetics, prolong bleeding or affect blood
pressure. (250 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Thinking while driving can be dangerous, but mental tasks that
involve spatial calculations seem to distract drivers more than
verbal problems, a new study from Spain concludes. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Massage may make tired athletes feel better, but doesn't
appear to help muscles recover from exertion any faster, a study
published last week in the British Journal of Sports Medicine
concludes. (180 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study has found that one important class of high blood
pressure medications, thiazide diuretics, does not increase the
risk of diabetes, as had previously been suspected. In fact,
patients taking drugs in the class developed fewer cases of
diabetes than people not taking the drugs. One other kind of
hypertension medications, beta blockers, was found to increase
diabetes risk by 28 percent. But authors say it doesn't mean people
should give up their beta blockers. (225 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Why does
drinking alcohol give the illusion of warmth without keeping you
warm in cold weather? By C. Claiborne Ray. (280 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
</TEXT>
