<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5782 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SLAVE-RECORDS0404-COX     04-03 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-RECORDS0404-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Project aims to track slaves' past in Texas
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Driving to work in 1998, Eric Walther turned on
Allen Parkway in Houston and collided head-on with the past.
</P>
<P>
   Construction workers at the Allen Parkway Village, a public
housing complex Walther passed every day, uncovered a cemetery
where former slaves were buried. For Walther, an associate
professor of history at the University of Houston, the find was
poignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking there are hardly any physical remains of
slavery in Texas,'' he said. ``We find something and build right
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther's desire to put a face on those who were denied their
humanity has blossomed into a project some consider impossible. He
wants to document every black slave who ever lived in Texas _ a
population he estimates at 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most people laugh initially when they hear of the scope of
Walther's ambition. He admits the task won't be easy. Most slaves
were given only first names. Their births and deaths were not
recorded. Slaves could not legally marry, so marriage records don't
exist. The records that do exist are spotty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck to the gentleman,'' said David A. Williams,
executive director of the Texas African American Heritage
Organization based at Huston-Tillotson College. ``That's a terrible
load to undertake as a researcher. I wouldn't touch it with a
10-foot pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther, whose students are working with him on the project, has
heard it all before. To his surprise, many more records exist than
he ever imagined. Slaves and former slaves are listed in census
documents, tax records and, after the Civil War, voter registration
records, among other public documents. Newspapers published ads
seeking runaway slaves.
</P>
<P>
   One of Walther's students, Clayton Lust, compiled more than 300
descriptions of slaves, using the manifests from slave ships on
microfilm at the genealogy library in Houston. The manifests list
the slave's first name, age, height, scars and coloring _ from
black to copper. Some had scars on their cheeks; one was missing a
finger, signs of how slaves were treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really personalizes the whole thing,'' Lust said. ``There
was one slave named Amanda. Amanda is my sister's name. You can see
relatives' names all over, and when you see them in this sort of
context, you think, 'God, how would I feel?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lust, who grew up in the North and ``never thought of slavery,''
said working on Walther's Texas Slavery Project has ``put the face
on it ... that makes (slavery) a more compelling lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther, who is Jewish and a native of Los Angeles, was
fascinated by the Civil War as a child. He is emotional about
slavery partly because of his own family's history. A much older
cousin survived the Holocaust because he was young and able to do
slave labor for the Nazis, said Walther, who is 39.
</P>
<P>
   Slave labor also helped build Texas, he said. Slaves worked on
railroads, made bricks and did construction, in addition to working
in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who came here without any choice and were told what
to do and helped create the modern state of Texas deserve some
credit,'' Walther said.
</P>
<P>
   He also hopes his project will lead some African Americans to
their ancestry. ``That would be the most satisfying thing to me,''
said Walther, who has a Web site dedicated to the research at
http://www.texassla- veryproject.uh.edu. Donaly Brice, a reference
archivist at the state Library and Archives Commission, said he was
not aware of any similar project in Texas. Many people don't know
Texas' slave population was large and grew during the Civil War as
slave owners migrated from states ravaged by fighting, Brice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be impossible to find every slave, but he could
get a large number of them,'' Brice said.
</P>
<P>
   State archivist Chris LaPlante said the agency is prioritizing
research that documents ``the undocumented community,'' primarily
African Americans and Hispanics in Texas. Grants are available to
further such work, LaPlante said.
</P>
<P>
   Walther expects to have several thousand names by early May, but
because the project could take years, he's looking for any help he
can get. He realizes he probably won't get every name, but he
expects to produce a name and, at the very least, a biographical
sentence on 80 percent to 90 percent of the slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been studying history at the college level since
1978,'' Walther said. ``This is breathing new life into me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Swick, another student in Walther's class, said Walther's
passion is obvious and contagious. Swick has been researching the
Houston Telegraph, a 19th century newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found ads where they were selling slaves. I saw ads about
slaves running away and the reward for them,'' Swick said. ``You
see it (slavery) in the movies, but it was right here in Houston.
My family is from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never think of slavery as hitting so close to home,'' he
said. ``This will hopefully bring it home for a few other people,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
