<SLUG> BC-CHINA-GERMAN-DEATHS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER EXECUTIVE AND FAMILY SLAIN IN HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ A German family of four was stabbed to death
in the central Chinese city of Nanjing early Sunday, a rare
incident of violence against foreigners that underscores a creeping
rise in crime across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy general manager of a DaimlerChrysler luxury bus
manufacturing joint venture, Juergen Pfrang, discovered four
intruders in his house shortly after midnight Saturday, Chinese and
German officials said. Pfrang, 51, was stabbed during a struggle
with the men, who then killed his wife, 14-year old daughter and
12-year old son.
</P>
<P>
   Guards at the housing compound caught the men, four unemployed
farmers from nearby Anhui Province, according to the Nanjing
Foreign Affairs Bureau and the German consulate in Shanghai.
Robbery was the apparent motive.
</P>
<P>
   China has long been remarkably safe for foreigners. During the
1970s and 1980s, many travelers were amazed when lost wallets or
even plastic combs were returned to them by Chinese eager to
demonstrate the strength of their country's moral fiber. Most
foreign residents still don't think twice about wandering the
streets alone at any hour of the night in China.
</P>
<P>
   But a breakdown in central government control, growing income
disparities and rising unemployment have gradually led to more
crime. Several foreign businessmen were killed in the late 1990s.
Moreover, many Americans have felt less safe since NATO bombed the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last year during the Kosovo conflict.
The bombing, which few Chinese believe was accidental, sparked
violent demonstrations in several Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
   Most incidents of violence against foreigners have occurred in
smaller cities, where the foreign presence is small. But several
incidents in the past year have occurred in larger cities. Last
July, a Canadian man was hacked by a machete-wielding intruder to
his rented luxury villa in Shanghai. The man survived, but lost
partial use of one hand. And in January, a Chinese-American was
found slain in a Beijing bar.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the crime has been attributed to the droves of migrant
workers, many of them unemployed farmers, who have congregated in
China's cities looking for work. Beijing has tried various
strategies to control the tide, like leveling migrant shanty towns
and sending vagrants home. But as China's economy continues its
painful restructuring, the number of such workers grows.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In February, as many as 20,000 laid-off miners rioted in the
northeastern city of Yangjiazhanzi. And last month, train service
between Shanghai and Nanjing was interrupted for most of a day as
protesters who had lost money in a fraudulent financial scheme
blocked the rail tracks. Such flare-ups rarely touch the lives of
foreigners in China, and there is a debate among Western academics
about whether the increasing number of reported incidents indicates
growing social unrest or simply greater access to information about
events that previously might not have been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Two things are certain, however: unemployment is rising and _
infrequent as they still are _ reports of violence against
foreigners are more common than there were a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pfrang was deputy general manager of Yaxing-Benz Ltd., a joint
venture between DaimlerChrysler and Yangzhou Motor Coach
Manufacturing Co. Colleagues said Monday that although the company
is in Yangzhou, Pfrang lived with his family more than an hour away
in Nanjing so that his children could attend an international
school.
</P>
<P>
   The family had been in Nanjing since 1997, residing for most of
that time in a hotel until they moved last year to the Jingling
Royal Garden housing compound to give the children more room. Like
many compounds favored by foreign families in China, the Jingling
Royal Garden is a partly walled neighborhood of stand-alone houses.
</P>
<P>
   Such compounds are protected by security guards but are often
poorly patrolled.
</P>
<P>
   A German consular official from Shanghai traveled to Nanjing
Monday to arrange for repatriation of the bodies. The Pfrangs, from
the German city of Baden-Wurtemberg, have no other family members
in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
