r k BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     04-03 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHING THE COMEBACK AFTER THE STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HARRAL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My first real memories of tornadoes are of being dragged from
bed in the middle of the night by a mother insisting that we head
to the storm cellar to ride out the bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   We had the only cellar in the neighborhood, so it was a sort of
social gathering place during the terrible storms that sometimes
swept over the Texas Panhandle. It was a constant in my life from
my earliest memories until I moved away to college.
</P>
<P>
   My daddy was a cement contractor _ small time, small town.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways he made a living was building concrete storm
shelters. They cost about $500 at that time _ this would have been
in the late '50s.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't have one, of course. Just as the painter's house was
in need of painting and the carpenter's house was in need of
repair. The crafts people were so busy doing it for others that
they never got around to doing it for themselves. Our cellar was a
dugout covered by a wooden roof and a couple of feet of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Mom was a weather freak. Still is, mostly confined to her home
as she is at her advanced age. She watches the Weather Channel
faithfully and is prone to call to find out if we've been involved
in whatever weather is being reported.
</P>
<P>
   We beat her to the punch Tuesday night, calling to say that we
were OK before she even knew that we might have been in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The first tornado-damaged site I visited was just outside my
hometown _ Shamrock in the Texas Panhandle. My most striking memory
is seeing a water pipe neatly coiled around a small tree that stood
near the now-missing house.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, of course, because of my chosen profession, there
have been many more encounters with tornadoes. But they always
happened somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the things I always wondered was how people snap back
so fast and recover so quickly from natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   That question was answered in part last week.
</P>
<P>
   The main office of the Star-Telegram is located in downtown Fort
Worth. We also have major offices in Arlington and northeast
Tarrant County, so the downtown building is not as crucial to the
newspaper's production as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are functions that are most easily performed in
that office.
</P>
<P>
   Since downtown was cordoned off last week, most of us had great
difficulty getting to work. Police and fire personnel were taking
their roles seriously, and the Star-Telegram wasn't high on their
radar screens.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative staff members recognized the problems we were
going to have getting people into a secure area, and they arranged
a shuttle bus service from the newspaper's Printing and
Distribution Center on the southern boundary of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   It was while waiting for one of the buses the first day after
the storm that a realization dawned about how recovery operations
happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Star-Telegram is a big company, with about 1,300 full-time
employees with a lot of smaller operations within the major
divisions. We aren't thrown together all that much. Many different
divisions were represented at the shuttle stop.
</P>
<P>
   Some who worked in classified advertising were anxious to get to
work because they were afraid that the telephones they normally
staff would be going unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Some who worked in advertising special sections were alarmed
that their sections wouldn't be ready for the weekend unless they
could get into the office as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Some responsible for the mail operations were determined to make
sure that the mail moved as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Those who worked in the editorial operation were desperate
because they knew the workload ahead, and they knew that those
already in the office needed all they help they could get.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to imply that the Star-Telegram is especially
unique. We do have a role during crises to see that we provide the
best information we can, and we are sensitive to that mission.
</P>
<P>
   But we didn't face any more than thousands of others who work in
downtown Fort Worth faced. And we were better off than many. At
least our building was intact.
</P>
<P>
   What was demonstrated in the crowd waiting for the shuttle,
however, is the stuff of which recovery is made. Each person was
focused on a mission and was determined to perform that mission in
the best way possible during the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   People doing what they are supposed to do are the people who
pull together things after a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   That's true of firefighters and police. And it is true of the
men and women of the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure it was replicated many thousands of times by many
thousands of people who work in and around downtown Fort Worth and
in the other areas hit by Tuesday's storms.
</P>
<P>
   There is resilience in human nature.
</P>
<P>
   And determination conquers much.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is vice president and editorial director for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
harral(at)star-telegram.com; (817) 390-7836; or P.O. Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
