 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Microsoft faces an uncertain future as the wrath of the
U.S. government and its competitors finally starts to hit home. The
world's largest and most powerful software company is not going to
disappear, nor have we heard the last of Bill Gates, its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the pace of technology and the marketplace that the
antitrust case brought by the U.S. government may come to symbolize
the moment when the company's fortunes turned.
</P>
<P>
   The legal case is also coming to a climax at a critical time for
the new economy, the fusion of computers, software and the Internet
which Microsoft has helped to shape and create for the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is moving on; and Gates, one of the key architects of
the personal-computer revolution, was fighting to keep his company
on the cutting edge even without the legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   It is increasingly clear that the world of technology is just
beginning a vast process of reevaluation, and the stock declines
Monday _ which went beyond Microsoft _ are part of that.
</P>
<P>
   Much harder questions are starting to be asked about the ways
that business has been done; a critical eye is being cast on what
had been seen as innovation, but now looks in some cases like pure
hubris.
</P>
<P>
   The New Economy is entering what may be a troubled period.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is more associated with the New Economy than Gates. He
did not create the personal-computer revolution, but it was his
genius which helped to make the machines accessible to everyone.
His successes were in sales, marketing and promotion as much as (or
more than) in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's operating system, the company's first project, was
simple to use; so were the word processors, accounting software and
databases which followed. But the key was the operating system,
first MS-DOS, then Windows.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Gates owned the patent for the combustion engine in
the first industrial revolution. Everyone who wanted to make
software for the new machines needed to make it operate with
Microsoft products; so did everyone who sold computers. That gave
the company a hegemony which is only now being challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Microsoft scored its greatest successes, a second
technological revolution was brewing, the Internet, which
represented a quite different vision of computing.
</P>
<P>
   And the first, and initially the most successful, product to
explore this new world was made not by Microsoft, but by Netscape
Communications, an upstart company led by pioneer Jim Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government and Microsoft's competitors contend that the
company abused its dominant position in the market for operating
systems to gain a lockhold on the burgeoning market for browsers,
squeezing out Netscape and leaning on computer companies to co-opt
them in the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to read the testimony _ even of Microsoft officials
_ and disagree, and in the end the judge concurred.
</P>
<P>
   This was a war, and one which Microsoft knew it had to win.
Browsers were the key to the new world of computing, one which
Microsoft had been late to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   The case was about Microsoft's strength; but it was also about
how it dealt with a competitive weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The company won the browser war: in one sense, Monday's judgment
was about the past, not the future.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape's market share has dwindled away; Internet Explorer,
the MS product, now reigns supreme. But the hubris which the
company displayed _ as it sought to eliminate or marginalize
rivals, and as it defended itself in court _ has cost it dearly.
</P>
<P>
   Companies the size of Microsoft don't die. Even if it were
broken up, it would still be vast and powerful; in any case, it
seems more likely to be shackled than dismembered, forced to
operate under external controls.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case its dominant position is coming to a close, as
much because of future technologies as past misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of new devices _ everything from set-top boxes
to handheld organizers and mobile phones _ opens up a market where
Gates' imperium does not hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the Net itself, the big boxes that control the data
flows, and the much smaller ones which manage them, use other
software, and Microsoft has been slow to gain an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have been talking for a year about the post-PC
age; and that may come to mean post-Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   New competitors are already emerging to challenge Microsoft's
hegemony, using the open operating system Linux, for example; old
rivals, like Sun Microsystems, will try to capitalize on its
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no new Microsoft to replace the company: the
market is simply too variegated now. If Microsoft loses its grip,
in some areas there will be many competing products, and in the
short term it may be harder for consumers to work out which one
will survive.
</P>
<P>
   When empires fade, strange and sometimes destructive energies
are freed. &QL; 
