<SLUG> BC-OBUCHI-COMA-JAPAN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMATOSE OBUCHI GIVES JAPAN A NEAR-DEATH EXPERIENCE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This timely 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan was thrown into political and constitutional
confusion Monday as its prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, appeared to
be close to death after suffering a sudden stroke over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a day of obfuscation, the acting prime minister,
Miko Aoki, finally admitted that Obuchi had fallen into a coma late
on Sunday and was being kept alive on a respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and the Japanese media were careful not to rule out
his chances of recovery, but it appears likely that the 62-year old
prime minister will never wake up, creating a sudden and unexpected
void in the leadership of the world's second richest country.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Obuchi's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) were
already discussing his successor last night, and the government was
quick to emphasize that his demise will have no effect on Japan's
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the tragedy has created a unique and constitutionally
baffling situation _ how to secure the resignation of a prime
minister who is not yet dead, but who may never speak or move
again.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary chain of events began on Saturday when, after
months of bickering and recrimination, the leaders of the minority
Liberal Party (LP) announced that they were abandoning his
three-party coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the negotiations appears to have taken it out of
Obuchi, who also had to deal with the eruption of a volcano in the
northern island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the prime minister's office initially claimed that
he spent much of Sunday working at home. In fact he had been
hospitalized at 1 a.m., 22 hours before an official announcement
was made late on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, in a peremptory press conference, Aoki, the
chief cabinet secretary, announced that Obuchi had suffered a
stroke and had asked him to take acting leadership. A few hours
later, he admitted that Obuchi was unconscious and breathing only
by artificial means.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 13 hours, from Sunday night to Monday morning,
Japan was without a conscious head of government.
</P>
<P>
   Constitutionally, a prime minister can be permanently replaced
after his resignation, but the laws give no guidance about how to
deal with an incumbent who is incapable of expressing his will.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it is difficult for the premier to make his own
decisions,'' a bemused Aoki observed. ``We will have to decide what
to do after considering his condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional experts speak of a scenario in which LDP leaders
``simulate'' Obuchi's decision to resign, before appointing a new
party head who will then be elected prime minister by the
government's parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably not be Aoki, a reserved party stalwart who has
never shown obvious ambitions to be prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the favorite appeared to be Yoshiro Mori, the
LDP's secretary-general, or the foreign minister, Yohei Kono, with
an outsider's chance for Kiichi Miyazawa, the octogenarian finance
minister, who served as premier in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis comes at a fraught time for Japan, which is showing
faltering signs of recovery from its worst recession in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP's tiny majority forced it to form a coalition with the
LP and the Buddhist New Komeito party, an awkward union which has
been the source of much bickering.
</P>
<P>
   There was more than a suggestion Monday that Obuchi's sudden
stroke was a consequence of stress and overwork. The LP leader,
Ichiro Ozawa, said that he regretted ``speaking so frankly'' during
his final discussions with the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he became prime minister in 1998, Obuchi was
considered something of a joke, and his stolid and uncharismatic
manner earned him the nickname ``cold pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing his relationship with two great former LDP prime
ministers, he referred to himself as a ``noodle shop between two
skyscrapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, though, his popularity ratings were at record
levels, although the bubble burst after his alliance with the JP
and New Komeito which was widely regarded as a cynical marriage of
convenience. &QL; 
