<HEADLINE>
POLICE DETAIN MOTHER OF STUDENT KILLED IN 1989 CRACKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: no byline; see also CHINA-SPY, CHINA-GERMAN-DEATHS,
CHINA-CLINTON) 
(HLW) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A mother of a student killed in the 1989 crackdown on
democracy demonstrators was detained by the police on Monday as she
tried to deliver gifts to a leading organizer of victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   The detained woman, Su Bingxian, was trying to deliver a book
and $1,000 in donations for families of people killed in the 1989
crackdown to Ding Zilin, a professor at People's University who
also lost a son when the army crushed the demonstrations in
Tiananmen Square and has organized aid efforts for bereaved
families.
</P>
<P>
   The book and money had been brought by Lois Wheeler Snow, the
79-year-old widow of the journalist Edgar Snow, who was lauded here
as a ``friend of China'' for his sympathetic writings. On Saturday,
Snow was prevented by the police from visiting Ding and giving her
the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   As Snow was blocked at the university gate on Saturday, Su
emerged to accept the gifts on Ding's behalf. But on Monday, when
she tried to deliver the book and money to Ding, she was detained,
Ding said in a letter faxed to foreign reporters. On Monday night,
Su's telephone went unanswered and it was unclear if she was still
being held.
</P>
</TEXT>
