<HEADER>
A5825 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-FALCONE-TEX     04-03 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MOB SERIES `FALCONE' TREADS LINE BETWEEN MORALITY PLAY AND GORE
FEST
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by FALCONE-PREDECESSORS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first scene of CBS' gutsy but wildly uneven ``Falcone''
shows a man gleefully bursting through the doors of a ballroom only
to find empty chairs and tables scattered about. Figuring
something's amiss, he turns to find a man blocking the doorway and
pointing a large shotgun at his face. We hear the boom and must
imagine the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' is a cops and mob series that takes its violence
seriously, if not cautiously. Vicious stabbings, terrible beatings
and cold-blooded murders carry viewers through the first episodes
of this highly anticipated drama, including a stylistically juicy
slow-motion ambush where three men are gunned down at point-blank
range in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a series that CBS has taken tremendous pains to
protect and nurture, first shelving its initial debut last year
when the Colorado shootings threatened to make the project a pubic
relations fiasco, and later making the decision to launch it during
midseason, when audiences are expected to be game for something _
anything _ fresh and new.
</P>
<P>
   What CBS and the show's creators don't want is for the violence,
however necessary it may be, to tell the story, to be its calling
card. Instead, the network's aspiration is a series that's more
morality play than shoot'em-up.
</P>
<P>
   To push home that point, CBS is taking the unusual step of
airing nine episodes over eight nights, beginning Tuesday with a
two-hour opener. This strategy is driven by a combination of fear
and hope. Fear that audiences might not return to such a dark and
dispiriting series after a week's time; hope that viewers tuning in
on consecutive nights will be hooked by the show's driving momentum
and compelling premise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' is loosely based on the 1997 film ``Donnie Brasco''
and the true story of Joe Pistone, an FBI undercover agent who, in
the mid-'70s, infiltrated the Mafia, getting closer to its inner
circle than had any previous law enforcer. Pistone, who serves as a
consultant on ``Falcone,'' spent 28 years with the FBI, six of them
infiltrating a mob family. Adopting the persona of a hard-nosed
jewel thief, he became part of the clan, proving his loyalty by
participating in crimes both petty and bloody.
</P>
<P>
   Portrayed by Jason Gedrick, whose stern-but-pretty face has led
to a number of mobster roles, Falcone is the ultimate method actor,
a man with many faces and even more lies. He shuttles between his
families, the one he works for and the one he tucks away in a
suburban house on a quiet street. Loyalty is the core issue in both
places, which is an added irony since Falcone, who's so good at
winning trust, is at once the most honest man and the ultimate
betrayer.
</P>
<P>
   The opening episode sets up this life of tightrope walking
pretty methodically. After the head don is rubbed out (remember the
shotgun to the head?), a fight for control ensues between ruthless
underbosses Santino ``Sonny Boy'' Napoli (Titus Welliver) and
Victor Mura (James Russo), who appear to hate one another with true
passion. Falcone must align himself with one of them; picking the
wrong one will not just push him out of position to collect enough
evidence to bring down the family, it will get him killed.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone reports to FBI field agent Jules, played by Robert John
Burke, who doesn't like Falcone's relentless risk-taking but takes
a better-him-than-me attitude. He appears to be more worried about
Falcone's family than Falcone, who has many other things to fret
about, including being constantly hounded by District Attorney
Francesca Gold, played by a growling Patti LuPone.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone's family scenes, filled with tense ambivalence, are what
give the series its most original energy. Amy Carlson plays Maggie
as a saintly, long-suffering spouse who understands his duty but
only to a point. His oldest daughter is sullen and untrusting of
Falcone; she knows something odd is occurring and that it hurts her
mother terribly. Her icy relationship with her father contrasts
with that between Falcone and his younger daughter, who is naive
enough to miss her father when he disappears for days and to love
him during his rare nights at home as a regular guy. (To keep the
mob off-balance, he keeps an apartment and has his phone forwarded
to a cellphone when at home.)
</P>
<P>
   As ``Falcone'' goes deeper into its story lines, the creators
are hoping audiences will get sucked up into the dramatic ambiguity
of it all _ whether, for instance, Falcone is so immersed in a
dangerous and confusing double life that his cause becomes less
clear to him. Is his loyalty only to the law? His wife and two
daughters? His Mafia clan?
</P>
<P>
   In one of the pivotal scenes, Falcone gets a call informing him
that Maggie's car has been blindsided and that she's been rushed to
the hospital. Needing to leave the bar hangout where the mobsters
spend much of their time, he invents a story about meeting a
business acquaintance in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone is questioned by one of Sonny's disapproving henchmen,
who demands that Falcone verify the Miami contact right then and
there.
</P>
<P>
   As they call Miami, and as sweat begins to dance across
Falcone's forehead, it's clear that it is this kind of threat of
exposure that the show's creators hope will keep audiences tuned in
once the series shifts to its weekly time slot.
</P>
<P>
   While the series does its best to tread new ground, it's hardly
new _ not only does it owe its story line to ``Donnie Brasco,'' it
also draws inspiration from ``Wiseguy,'' an '80s drama on ABC that
starred Ken Wahl as an undercover agent assigned to infiltrate and
bring down criminal conspiracies. That series was quite cerebral
for a cop show and was well-received by critics. But it also never
amassed sizable ratings, dying after four seasons and some
behind-the-scenes turmoil that resulted in Wahl's firing before the
final season.
</P>
<P>
   But neither ``Wiseguy'' nor ``Donnie Brasco'' is the ghost
``Falcone'' needs to worry about. Fairly or not, the new series
will be compared to ``The Sopranos,'' the mob show that has sent
orgasmic tremors through the press since its premiere last year,
and is now HBO's highest-rated original series. That's hardly
welcome news for ``Falcone,'' considering that the raw, R-rated
ferocity of the pay-channel series is the exact thing ``Falcone''
cannot offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the expectations of ``Sopranos''' fans aren't its only
problem. Even while executive producer Mark Johnson stresses that
the show is ``far more interested in an undercover FBI agent who
leads a life in which any small misstep will get him killed than in
laying out how a gangster society works,'' ``Falcone'' often falls
short in its attempts to at least capture the cultural and social
nuances of mob life.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, dialogue sometimes comes off sounding more like a
``Saturday Night Live'' skit than a grittily realistic drama. ``I'm
a tough guy, Sonny,'' says Raymond ``The Madman'' Ricci, played by
an overacting Eric Roberts. ``But my tough guyness is all soft
because my hands are tied behind my back.''
</P>
<P>
   And this, from Victor to Falcone when sides are being drawn.
``Either you get on the boat with me,'' he warns, ``or you drown
with the rest of the victims.'' (He delivers this exact line
moments later to another guy who gave him the wrong answer and was
stabbed repeatedly with what looked like an ice pick.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone's'' list of Mafia members and wiseguys is a long one,
but none of the criminal sidekicks stands out as an original
creation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not that changes remains to be seen. With the
real-life Pistone serving as consultant, ``Falcone'' plans to use
``Donnie Brasco'' as a starting point and then draw from many of
Pistone's other experiences that never made it into the film.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this matters if no one watches. It should be
noted that CBS was also the home of ``EZ Streets,'' another
multilayered series with mob overtones that also co-starred
Gedrick, as an ex-convict trying to go straight. That series was
adored by critics and ignored by viewers, who found its plot lines
convoluted and less than engaging. It died a rather quick death,
even after CBS, figuring it could prove its worth over time,
brought it back with a promotional push.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``EZ Streets,'' ``Falcone'' is the sort of show that needs
time to grow. It could become a rich, nuanced drama that finds a
committed audience _ or it could drown with the rest of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817)390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
