<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-RULING (Washington) _ U.S. District Court Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson announces he will rule at 5 p.m. today on whether
software giant Microsoft Corp. violated antitrust laws. The judge's
ruling follows the collapse Saturday of settlement talks between
Microsoft and the Justice Department. By MARK HELM. (Also will be
filed in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ The Supreme Court declines to consider
the constitutionality of a state law that makes it easier for
neighbors and school administrators to discover whether a convicted
sexual offender is within their midst. In addition, the justices
agreed to decide if the government can bar federally funded lawyers
for poor people from lobbying against strict welfare laws without
violating the attorneys' constitutional right to free speech. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-RESTRUCTURING (Washington) _ The Southeastern Legal
Foundation, a conservative law firm, urges the dismantling of the
U.S. Census Bureau, claiming it violates citizens' privacy. The
firm, which won a Supreme Court decision last year limiting use of
a Census sampling plan, proposes two new agencies to replace the
bureau. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLLUTION (Washington) _ Republican presidential hopeful
George W. Bush unveils a six-point plan for cleaning and
redeveloping polluted industrial sites. In a speech designed to
bolster his environmental credentials, Bush says states have
successfully begun cleaning and reusing so-called brownfields, so
the federal government should accelerate work on 450,000 remaining
sites. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY (Miami) _ Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the Cuban father of
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, seeks a visa to come to the United
States. Immigration officials, meanwhile, continue to hold talks
with relatives keeping the boy. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA and GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBUS-SHIPS (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ Several years ago the
city of Corpus Christi won the much-coveted replicas of Christopher
Columbus' fleet with plans to turn them into a tourist attraction.
Money was raised, facilities were built and tourists visited, but
the project quickly failed. The future is unclear with some wanting
the city to take over and others suggesting the ships go to another
port. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ The majority of the nation's high
school seniors find out this week if the colleges they want to
attend want them to enroll. It's also the time when they and their
parents are told just how much a higher education sojourn will cost
them. By SHANNON BUGGS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-OPENER (Pittsburgh) _ The Houston Astros begin their quest
for a fourth consecutive National League Central Division
championship when they open the 2000 baseball season against the
Pittsburgh Pirates. The game starts at 7:05 p.m. EDT. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN and BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA (Indianapolis) _ Full coverage of the NCAA Men's
Basketball Championship Game between Michigan State and Florida. By
JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN and BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Privacy is our constitutional right,
but it is not always a simple concept. People refusing to fill out
the Census forms may distort services based on that data. Critics
say New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani violated the privacy of a man
murdered by police. A judge has accused President Clinton of
illegally releasing friendly letters from a woman who claims he
groped her. And there's all that confusion about who gets to see
what in the world of e-commerce. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Judging from my e-mail, I
haven't been able to convince everyone of the need to improve
campaign finance laws. But we can all enjoy the spectacle of our
two major presidential candidates trying to carry the ``reform''
banner. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
