<SLUG> BC-BAD-GIRL-WHITNEY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS HAPPENING TO WHITNEY HOUSTON?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What is happening to Whitney Houston? Once the
ubiquitous, uncontested queen of soulful pop, these days she is
gaining quite a reputation instead for her clamorous absences.
</P>
<P>
   She dropped out of last month's Oscars ceremony at the last
minute, supposedly with a sore throat.
</P>
<P>
   She has cancelled a duet she was due to record with George
Michael for a new album, for reasons that are far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   She has not put out a new record since 1998, and stopped her
touring schedule last year to take what her publicists are calling
``a breather.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the rumors are swirling, none of them good. Early
last week, the New York Post challenged the official version of her
withdrawal from the Oscars, reporting that she had turned up to one
rehearsal ``totally out of it,'' and that she had missed cues and
sung the wrong song at a second.
</P>
<P>
   She did not pull out of the event herself, the Post alleged, but
was sent packing by musical director Burt Bacharach.
</P>
<P>
   According to two separate accounts heard by this newspaper, the
stylists and other assistants who showed up at Houston's hotel to
take her to the Oscars rehearsals found her in a state of some
distress with the windows of her rooms blacked out.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all. The May issue of Jane magazine reports that
Houston showed up four hours late for a photo shoot, claiming a
cracked tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was extremely unfocused, had trouble keeping her eyes
open, and kept singing and playing an imaginary piano on the
table,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   In her interview with the magazine, Houston remarked that
meeting the president and meeting a junkie are ``just the same.''
``The president gets off on the country. The junkie gets off on a
couple of hits,'' she is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unfortunate use of language for a woman stopped at a
Hawaii airport in January and accused of having half an ounce of
marijuana in her bags.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is well known for her imprecise sense of timing and her
eccentric behavior. She once turned up two hours late to a White
House dinner honoring Nelson Mandela, and has been known to order
hotel staff to hose down her room with mineral water.
</P>
<P>
   Her marriage to fellow singer Bobby Brown, who has a long record
of drunk-driving convictions and arrests for assault, has also
fuelled the celebrity rumor mill. But even her admirers are now
wondering if there isn't something badly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, such speculation is still being roundly squashed. A
publicist for the Oscars, Jane LaBonte, said last week: ``I was in
the rehearsal myself the whole time, and it was really obvious the
poor lady was having a problem with her throat.'' Poor lady,
indeed. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
