<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-OUTLOOK-JOHNSON-B     04-03 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OUTLOOK-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST NAME IN FIREBALLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Chapman had just heard, and only heard, two fastballs
whizzing by him on this overcast day, and he just plumb decided the
dugout would be a more commodious place than the batter's box, so
he placed the bat down and began walking to the Cleveland bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray!'' shouted plate umpire Billy Evans. ``You've got one
strike left!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind, Billy,'' said Chapman as he continued his little
stroll. ``I don't want it!''
</P>
<P>
   The man on the mound was Walter Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In the 73 years since Johnson hung 'em up, we have seen many
great pitchers, from Lefty Grove to Pedro Martinez, from Dizzy Dean
to Randy Johnson. But there is no evidence that we have seen a
better pitcher than Walter Johnson. The manager has never lived who
would not be very comfortable with Johnson on the mound in any
certified Big Game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, nicknamed ``The Big Train,'' pitched his entire career
(1907-27) for the Washington Senators. Often toiling for terrible
teams, he won 417 games (the precise total is the subject of debate
among diamond historians). He won 30 games twice and 20 games 12
times. He had a career earned run average of 2.17, 11 times having
an ERA in the 1s. He led the league in strikeouts 12 times, with a
high of 313 in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched three shutouts in four days in 1908. During the
teens, an average Johnson season was 29-15, 240 strikeouts, a 1.59
ERA, and 371 innings. In 1913, he was 36-7 with a 1.14 ERA. In 1924
and 1925, at which point he had already pitched 5,046 innings, he
submitted back-to-back 20-win campaigns. Oh, and in 1925 he also
batted .433 (42 for 97), giving new meaning to the term ``helping
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Ritter spoke to many of Johnson's contemporaries for
his epic 1966 book, ``The Glory of Their Times.'' It is clear that,
to them, Johnson was ``Half Man, Half Amazing,'' six decades before
Vince Carter was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' said Hall of Famer Wahoo Sam Crawford, ``the
greatest of them all was Walter Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   What struck Crawford, and just about everyone else, were two
things: 1. Johnson was almost exclusively a fastball pitcher. 2. He
threw with astonishing ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't have a curve,'' marveled Crawford. ``Just a fastball.
He didn't need a curve . . . He was the fastest I ever saw, by
far.''
</P>
<P>
   No curve, and no changeup of any kind, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter's idea of a changeup,'' Ty Cobb once said, ``was to
just throw harder.''
</P>
<P>
   This magnificent fastball was thrown by a man who looked as if
he were just having a catch on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever see one of those pitching machines they have?''
Crawford inquired. ``That's what Walter reminded me of, one of
those compressed-air pitching machines . . . You hardly saw the
ball at all. But you heard it. Swoosh, and it would smack into the
catcher's mitt . . . He threw so nice and easy _ then swoosh and it
was by you!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that guy could fire the ball!'' declared Davy Jones, an
outfielder of those times. ``He had those long arms, absolutely the
longest arms I ever saw. They were like whips; that's what they
were. He'd just whip the ball in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefty Grove was fast, and Sandy Koufax was, too,'' said Jimmy
Austin, another contemporary. ``But you should have seen Walter
Johnson. On a cloudy day you couldn't see the ball half the time,
it came in so fast. That's the honest-to-goodness truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Johnson was born in Humboldt, Kan., on Nov. 6, 1887,
hence a second nickname, ``The Kansas Cyclone.'' But he was
discovered pitching in the state of Idaho by Senators catcher Cliff
Blankenship, who was sent on a scouting mission by Washington owner
Clark Griffith while nursing a broken finger. Blankenship sent back
glowing accounts, as did an anonymous source whose words still
resonate some 93 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws so fast you can't see 'em,'' said the scout, ``and
he knows where he is throwing, because if he didn't there would be
dead bodies strewn all over Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   Major leaguers quickly learned that the best way to beat the
young rube was to bunt him silly. Batting against him was
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't long after he came to Washington that some of our
hitters, arriving in Walter's vicinity, were reporting to the sick
list,'' chuckled Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Echoed an early Cleveland newspaper account, ``Johnson's speed
was so terrific several Cleveland batters acted as though they had
no particular delight in being at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith leaned on Johnson for two decades. Said late Washington
Post legend Shirley Povich, ``Walter's drawing power and pitching
feats sustained Griffith and virtually kept big-league baseball in
Washington during the lean years. Griffith made the most of Johnson
as a gate attraction, carefully spacing the Big Train's
appearances, both home and road. Griffith would contact sports
editors the night before the game and plead over the telephone,
`Johnson's pitching tomorrow. Give me a headline.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the bunt thing worked only one time around. Cobb
reported that in his second game against the youngster he laid one
down and ``Walter bolted off the mound like a shot. It turned out
he had practiced for hours and hours.''
</P>
<P>
   His Washington teams weren't all bad. Yes, the Senators finished
last twice, seventh four times, and sixth three times during his
21-year career, but they contended strongly in 1912 and 1913 (you
think it had something to do with Walter going 69-19 those two
seasons?) and they finally won back-to-back pennants in 1924-25
(the 36- and 37-year old Walter going 43-14), and a world's
championship in 1924, Walter winning Game 7 in relief.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, it was as Bill James has said it
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his best years,'' wrote James, ``he had records as good as
anybody for teams that weren't as good as anybody's.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, therefore, that he became, along with Cobb, Babe
Ruth, Honus Wagner, and Christy Mathewson, a charter member of the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Johnson was not merely a great pitcher. He was a mythic
figure. Said Chief Meyers, who caught for the Giants in the teens,
``Everybody knew what was coming, but still couldn't hit him.
Walter's right arm was different than yours or mine. It was
special, like Caruso's lungs or Einstein's brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone out there interested in attempting to trump that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
