<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5854 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-STAIRS-FITNESS-AR     04-03 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STAIRS-FITNESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIGID REGIMEN FOR THOSE ON THE WAY UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) (DW) 
 By ALISON HENDRIE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The two-hour daily commute from Westport, Conn., to
Manhattan gives Maggie Kneip, a children's publishing executive for
Scholastic, plenty of time to catch up on work, but little chance
for exercise. Frustrated and energy-deprived, Kneip, 44, hoisted
her briefcase and raced the 10 flights of stairs to her office one
morning last year and has rarely hopped the elevator since.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past two years, my only workout was running for the
train,'' said Kneip. ``Sprinting the 10 floors is quick and
intense, although I'm so winded at the top, I have to assure my
co-workers I'm not going to faint.''
</P>
<P>
   Climbing to the top in the urban rat race is taking on new
meaning for many overworked professionals who, surrounded by
skyscrapers, are incorporating stair running into their busy
schedules as a convenient and effective workout.
</P>
<P>
   Every Tuesday afternoon, Jerry Silk, 30, a securities lawyer,
changes from business suit to sweats and meets one of the partners
of his midtown law firm in the stairwell of the Paine Webber
building. For the next half hour, the two race from their 33rd
floor office to the top, about 30 flights, and back down again to
lower and lower floors until they reach the point of exhaustion.
Silk estimates they run 80 flights on average and he still feels
the burn in his legs two days later. Workout complete, they shower
at the office and return to work.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the physical and psychological challenge is valuable
preparation for the corporate grind. Dino Bradlee, 41, a vice
president for the Trump Organization, views his 10-minute vertical
workout at his Manhattan apartment building each morning as an
advantage at the office. ``You need every edge you can get,''
Bradlee said. ``Climbing the stairs puts you physically and
mentally at the top of your game. And once you've done it, the rest
of the day is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The workout itself is not. Unlike using a step machine at the
health club, running a stairway pits gravity and the body's own
resistance against the runner, making for a grueling workout that
keeps the heart rate high and develops endurance, strength and
speed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Radu, a fitness trainer who uses the stairwell in
his gym on West 57th Street to incorporate stair running into his
program, a kind of chain reaction is triggered between the muscles,
from the legs through the lower back and even into the upper body
as arms pump and sometimes pull on the banisters. Because there are
often 10 clients at a time running the stairs in Radu's class, the
workouts become competitive. ``The group energy will lift you,
encouraging you to push yourself further,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Plemich, 43, a customer representative in Westchester,
Ill., for PeopleSoft, a business software company, is captain of
her company's seven-member stair running team. Year round, the
group trains together in its 10-story office building after work.
``It's obviously convenient and most of us are training for
marathons and triathlons anyway, so we work together,'' Plemich
said. The group recently competed in the Hustle Up the Hancock, an
annual race up the John Hancock building in Chicago to benefit the
American Lung Association.
</P>
<P>
   The routines vary. Bradlee sprints at full tilt for 10 minutes
and returns to his apartment in ``a heap.'' Linda Modico, a
37-year-old money manager in Manhattan, can spend 20 to 30 minutes
on a workout. It includes a single-step jog from the 33rd floor to
20th floor, then a return to the 33rd in the same pattern. Next,
she goes two steps at a time from 33 to 20 and back up at a skip.
Sometimes she'll jump with both legs or lunge-walk two or three
steps at a time, repeating these sequences up and down.
</P>
<P>
   Given the arduous nature of the sport, fitness experts caution
that the standard warnings given people starting a new exercise
program are especially important. As tempting as the skyscrapers
may be to potential climbers, most city buildings do not allow
general access to stairwells for safety and security reasons, other
than the occasional stair climbing races like the Hancock race and
the Empire State Building Run Up. But many of the smaller office
buildings and larger apartment buildings do allow access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stairway in our building is just begging to be used,''
says Kneip.
</P>
<P>
   For others like Modico, who races through the stairwell of her
downtown high-rise apartment nearly every morning, the exercise is
a little more private. ``I'm sure I'm the only one here doing
this,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
