<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SUBWAY-TABLOID-HNS &LR;      04-03 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBWAY-TABLOID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TABLOID MAKING HEADLINES IN PHILLY SEEKS OUTLET IN SAN
FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A free tabloid newspaper being distributed on
Philadelphia's buses and subways may make its next stop on the San
Francisco Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) system.
</P>
<P>
   A legal war is going on in Philadelphia over the Swedish-owned
Metro, which has started free, commuter-friendly newspapers in
Zurich, Prague, Helsinki, as well as Santiago, Chile. The first
North American version of the newspaper began two months ago in
Philadelphia, infuriating some in the mainstream journalism world.
</P>
<P>
   Most stories in the Metro are only three paragraphs long, but
Philadelphia's two daily newspapers object to the deal because they
say a government agency putting out a newspaper creates the
potential for a conflict of interest. Also, Metro is allowed to
distribute 150,000 newspapers on buses and in subway stations,
which is off-limits to the Inquirer and Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Metro International has been courting transit agencies in San
Francisco, Chicago, Boston and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Chicago and Boston have said no thanks. The Municipal
Railway in San Francisco said it had other priorities. But BART
officials say they may bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've expressed interest and we're interested in their
proposal,'' said BART spokesman Mike Healy. ``But I'm not aware of
anything concrete happening at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be because Metro International is locked in a legal
battle over distribution with the Philadelphia Inquirer and
Philadelphia Daily News, both owned by the Knight-Ridder newspaper
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's transit agency gets paid for the exclusive
distribution rights of the 24-page daily, which mostly runs brief
news, sports and entertainment stories.
</P>
<P>
   What troubles newspapers such as USA Today, the Philadelphia
dailies, the New York Times and Boston Globe, which are all suing,
is the dangerous precedent of government getting involved in the
world of publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last month rejected the
plaintiffs' request for an injunction to block distribution of the
Metro, but has not yet formally heard the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, known as
SEPTA, gets $30,000 per month in advertising revenue and one page
in each issue to write its own stories in exchange for distribution
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transit agency here is a government agency staffed by
political appointees. It just seems philosophically wrong for them
to be putting out a newspaper,'' said Zack Stalberg, editor of the
Philadelphia Daily News, a tabloid that gets most of its readers
through rack sales.
</P>
<P>
   He is especially galled because he said SEPTA has control in the
five-year contract over editorial content, even though the agency
filed a court affidavit saying it had no intent to interfere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they do or don't'' exercise control, Stalberg said,
``it seems like a bad precedent. The next thing you know the City
Council will be putting out its own paper and then the mayor.
They're pretending to be a newspaper when they're published by the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Stalberg also claims that the newspaper has conveniently ignored
several stories the mainstream newspapers have written about the
transit agency.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roberts, a former Daily News city editor and current boss
at Metro, said that while it is not stated in the contract that
SEPTA will keep hands off the content, they promised to essentially
do that in a court affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aggressively nonpartisan and independent,'' he said,
noting that the newspaper does not have an editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were a scandal at the agency, would his
publication report it? ``Absolutely,'' said Roberts, noting that
the newspaper ran a story on the agency's loss of a $50 million
lawsuit over a boy who lost his foot in a SEPTA accident.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts indicated he thinks the issue revolves more around
professional jealousy and newspapers that want to protect their
share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts also argued that the Daily News wanted the bus drivers
to sell the newspapers on board.
</P>
<P>
   Whether BART decides to distribute the publication is still
undecided, although the San Francisco area transit agency said a
deal with the Metro could mean revenue of $1 million per year.
Healy hinted that the agency probably would not want to get into an
agreement while a lawsuit is pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way,'' he said. ``I don't think we would
enter into anything that would give us exposure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
