<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Butterfly's Light Show
</P>
<P>
   All those Jumbotrons, Nasdaq-o-ramas and other giant TV screens
in Times Square have one thing in common. They use combinations of
just three colors _ blue, green and red, usually produced by
light-emitting diodes _ to create the infinite palette that humans
perceive.
</P>
<P>
   While it cannot display stock quotes, a male Indonesian
butterfly uses much the same principle to produce the spectacular
green color of its wings. It does not employ diodes, of course, but
there is no pigment to speak of either. The color is the result of
differing reflections of light.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Exeter in England, studying the
wing surface in detail, have found that it is covered in millions
of pits, each less than five microns wide, like some vast
microscopic muffin tin. The pits are made up of a multilayered
material that is iridescent; that is, it reflects light at
different colors depending upon the angle at which the light hits
it.
</P>
<P>
   Light hitting the flat bottoms of the pits is reflected back as
yellow. But light hitting the sloping sides is reflected as blue,
because it hits at a shallower angle. Ordinarily, this blue light
would not be reflected back to the observer.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the researchers report in the journal Nature,
the angles are such that the light bounces off one side to the
opposite side, where it is reflected back toward the source. These
reflections are so tiny that the human eye cannot distinguish them;
instead they mix to create green.
</P>
<P>
   Return to the Wild
</P>
<P>
   One of the original group of 27 California condors that were
captured in the mid-1980s as part of an effort to save the birds
from extinction will be released back to the wild Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The condor, the last female caught among the original group and
the first to be sent back, will be released in her native habitat,
the Sespe Condor Sanctuary in the Los Padres National Forest, about
30 miles east of Santa Barbara. She will be a ``mentor'' to two
10-month-old condors hatched in captivity and being released at the
same time. Among other things, she is expected to teach the younger
birds about where to find sites for roosting and foraging.
</P>
<P>
   The bird had been at the San Diego Zoo, part of the California
Condor Recovery Project, which was initiated in the mid-1970s and
has seen the condor population swell to 155, including 56 that have
been released into the wild. The bird, known as AC-8, had nine
offspring, but is now believed to be beyond breeding age.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the project expect that AC-8 will have little
trouble readjusting to the wild, even after 14 years. She has spent
the past several months in a flight pen at the Los Angeles Zoo,
preparing for her re-entry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
