<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDE EFFECTS: Of Pills, Pressure and Diabetes Risk
</P>
<P>
   A new study has found that one important class of high blood
pressure medication, thiazide diuretics, does not increase the risk
of diabetes, as had previously been suspected. In fact, patients
taking these drugs developed fewer cases of diabetes than people
not taking them.
</P>
<P>
   One other class of hypertension medications, beta blockers, was
found to increase diabetes risk by 28 percent. But the authors of
the study, published last week in The New England Journal of
Medicine, said that result by itself should not frighten patients
away from beta blockers, which for many people are the most
effective medicine with the fewest side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not suggesting that doctors stop prescribing beta
blockers, as they have proven benefits in lowering the risk of
cardiac events,'' said Dr. Frederick L. Brancati, a professor of
medicine and cardiology at Johns Hopkins University. ``But
physicians need to weigh the benefits against the diabetes risk and
monitor patients carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   The study drew its conclusions by comparing the results of
detailed physical examinations collected over six years on 12,550
middle-aged adults with heart disease or significant risk factors.
The study also found no increased risk of diabetes for patients
taking blood pressure medicines known as ACE inhibitors or calcium
channel blockers.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Boys' Heights Linked to Failing Grades
</P>
<P>
   Boys who are shorter are more likely to be held back in school,
a study from Australia suggests.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published March 29 in The Archives of Disease in
Childhood, researchers from the University of Melbourne compared
the heights of 2,848 students ages 5 to 12 from 24 schools.
</P>
<P>
   They found that at every grade, the oldest third of the students
were the shortest _ and that the difference was accounted for
almost entirely by the 133 children who had been held back a grade,
two-thirds of whom were boys.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggested that height as a sign of maturity or
lack of it might tip the balance in some decisions on whether to
hold back a struggling student. Some evidence suggests that adults
tend to treat children at a level appropriate to size, rather than
age, the article concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Melissa Wake, a pediatrician who was the study's lead
author, said that she often heard parents raise the issue of size
while wrestling with the difficult question of whether to hold
their child back a grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, `He's really big, he'll stand out from the
younger kids,' or `He's really little, he'll fit in,''' she said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main advice I would give parents is to focus on the
child's educational needs, but to be aware that height might be
playing a role in their or their school's decision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK: Surgery, Under the Influence of Herbs
</P>
<P>
   Half of the surgical patients surveyed in a University of
Colorado study used herbal or alternative medicines or vitamins in
the days before their operations, although many of these substances
could have interfered with their anesthetics, prolonged bleeding or
affected blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, published February in The American Association of
Nurse Anesthetists Journal, found that 51 percent of 500 patients
took one of these substances in the two weeks before surgery _ the
period of abstention recommended by the American Society of
Anesthesiologists. Twenty-four percent took more than one.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven percent took substances _ including garlic, ginko,
kava, vitamin E, fish oil and some Chinese herbs _ that could have
interfered with coagulation, the study found. Twelve percent
reported taking substances known to affect blood pressure, like
black cohosh and St. John's wort, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine percent took herbs, like kava or valerian, that could have
increased the sedating effect of anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   The study's author, Carol Norred, a nurse who is a doctoral
student at the University of Colorado Health Science Center's
Department of Anesthesiology in Denver, noted that earlier surveys
had found that 70 percent of people who took alternative medicines
never told their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can compromise a patient's safety if these medicines
aggravate a health condition or interact poorly with the drugs used
during surgery,'' Norred said.
</P>
<P>
   MUSCLE GROUPS: With Massage, Relief but No Renewal
</P>
<P>
   Massage may make tired athletes feel better, but it does not
appear to help &QC; the muscles recover from exertion any faster, a
study published last week in The British Journal of Sports Medicine
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Division of Sports Studies at the
University College Northampton enlisted eight amateur boxers to put
massage to the test.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-minute workout, in which an average of 400 punches
were thrown, half the boxers were given 20-minute massages and half
just rested for the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Before they got back in the ring for a second workout, blood
samples were taken and lactate levels were compared. Lactate,
produced as a byproduct of exertion, can hinder muscle function.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of massage suggest that it increases blood flow and
thereby speeds up the process of flushing lactate out of tired
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The tests, however, showed no difference in lactate levels, and
both groups saw their punching power fall by similar amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the boxers who got the massages did report feeling much
better than those who did not.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY: Thinking _ A Behind-the-Wheel Hazard
</P>
<P>
   Thinking while driving can be dangerous, but mental tasks that
involve spatial calculations seem to distract drivers more than
verbal problems, a new study from Spain concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Safety officials know that distraction is a serious hazard on
the road, but have little data so far about what kinds of mental
activity are more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In research conducted in and around Madrid, drivers were sent
out on highways and two-lane roads in a Citroen Bx-GTI equipped to
record their eye movements.
</P>
<P>
   As they drove, they were asked to &QC; repeat words starting with a
certain letter, or to visualize the letters of the alphabet,
categorizing them as ``open'' or ``closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Luis Nunes, a government psychologist who was a co-author of
the paper, said in an e-mail interview that most of the drivers
considered the spatial task easier than the verbal one, but that in
fact the visual work interfered with driving to a far greater
degree.
</P>
<P>
   During the spatial-imagery tasks, drivers fixed their eyes on
certain points longer and glanced less often at their mirrors or
dashboards, according to the study published last week in The
Journal of Experimental Psychology: Applied. ``It seems that during
the visual tasks, a person's eye freezes up,'' said Nunes'
co-author, Dr. Miguel Recarte, a psychologist at Complutense
University in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Nunes said in the e-mail message that they were not advocating
``extreme isolation'' of the driver. Some secondary activities,
like listening to music, have been found to enhance concentration,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you find yourself thinking about a problem that needs a
lot of attention,'' he advised, ``simply leave it for later _ or
you can have a more serious problem because of an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
