<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alcohol and Heat
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why does drinking alcohol give the illusion of warmth without
keeping you warm in cold weather?
</P>
<P>
   A. The assumptions of the question are not totally true, said
Dr. Samir Zakhari, a pharmacologist who is director of the division
of basic research at the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and
Alcoholism in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just drinking but where you drink and what kind of
clothes you have on'' that determine whether the body ends up
warmer or colder, Zakhari explained.
</P>
<P>
   What happens, he said, is that alcohol causes the blood vessels
in the skin to dilate, so that more blood passes through, and more
blood means more heat going through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you drink and are sitting in the living room with a
sweater on, that heat due to vasodilation will be retained, and you
will feel warm,'' Zakhari said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you go outside without enough clothing, all that heat
will dissipate, so that the body loses heat,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Such heat loss poses a serious risk of death from hypothermia
for people drinking outside in cold weather, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive drinking also impairs sensation and the judgment that
would ordinarily tell a person that it is time to come in from the
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
