<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MUSSELS-HUDSON-NY     04-03 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MUSSELS-HUDSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEBRA MUSSELS STAR IN HUDSON'S ECOLOGICAL MELODRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silently, mostly out of sight and unknown to all but a handful
of the millions of people who live along the Hudson River, a subtle
but elegant ecological drama is under way that may determine
whether the revivified, revitalized river can continue its hard-won
recovery from decades of pollution and degradation.
</P>
<P>
   The central player in the drama is the zebra mussel, a
coin-size, hard-shelled, black-and-white-striped mollusk from
Eurasia that hitchhiked to the Great Lakes aboard oceangoing ships
in the late 1980s and has since been on the march in waters of the
northeastern United States. The mussels first appeared in the
Hudson a decade ago; their fluctuating population there is
estimated at 500 billion to 600 billion in peak years.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, attention has focused on the mussel's ability to
disrupt water supplies by clogging intake pipes. But its ecological
impact is perhaps more spectacular; it has simply transformed the
chemistry of the freshwater portion of the Hudson, roughly above
West Point, and threatened the stability of that entire stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known for some time, for instance, that the
heaviest concentrations of mussels filter all the water in their
part of the river through their bodies every three days, as
compared, in their absence, with every 50 days for all other
aquatic organisms combined. In doing so, the mussels strain out and
consume microscopic plants, called phytoplankton, that are the
basis of the aquatic food chain.
</P>
<P>
   One result has been that numbers of tiny aquatic animals that
feed on the phytoplankton were cut about in half, sharply reducing
food supplies for creatures higher on the chain. Another is that
freshwater clams, which also consume phytoplankton, declined
drastically.
</P>
<P>
   Now experts have discovered another serious threat posed by the
mussels. They suck up so much oxygen from the water that in summer,
much of the ecosystem is approaching a danger point at which other
aquatic creatures begin to flee or die, according to a new study by
a team of ecologists at the Institute for Ecosystem Studies in
Millbrook, N.Y., who have been studying the Hudson ecosystem since
1987.
</P>
<P>
   The report of the discovery, by Dr. Nina F. Caraco and six
colleagues at the institute, appears in the April 1 issue of
Environmental Science and Technology, a publication of the American
Chemical Society. Their study was based on detailed measurements of
dissolved oxygen in the river and an analysis of differences in
oxygen concentrations before and after the mussels appeared.
</P>
<P>
   There is some irony in the discovery, since oxygenless dead
spots that once plagued the river as a result of an influx of raw
sewage have been eliminated over the last three decades at the cost
of several billion dollars' worth of sewage treatment systems.
Bacteria consume oxygen as they decompose sewage and other organic
matter.
</P>
<P>
   For the bacteria to match the mussels' depletion of oxygen,
Caraco said, ``you would have to increase present sewage in the
river threefold.'' The oxygen loss caused by the mussels would be
twice as bad as it is except for another aspect of their impact,
she said, and it is here that the ecological plot thickens.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, Caraco said, that the mussels also remove from the
river many small particles that cloud the water and reduce the
penetration of sunlight. With more sunlight flooding the clearer
water, slender, underwater native plants called water celery have
flourished. The plants give off oxygen as they convert sunlight to
energy through photosynthesis, and this extra oxygen has partly
offset the loss of it to mussels.
</P>
<P>
   But another actor now enters, altering the equation yet again.
It is a second exotic invader called the water chestnut, a floating
plant that produces spiny seed pods that can pierce a rubber sole
and grows so densely that some boats cannot go through it.
</P>
<P>
   Like all aquatic plants, Caraco said, the fast-spreading
chestnuts draw oxygen from the river as part of their metabolism;
but unlike the water celery, none of the oxygen they give off in
photosynthesis returns to the water; instead, it is vented to the
air. The result is that the water in many chestnut beds has no
oxygen at all in the summer _ when higher temperatures accelerate
organisms' activity _ and tidal mixing distributes some of this
water to other parts of the river.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Hudson has had a startling recovery since the
days in the 1960s when it was a foul stream polluted by the raw
sewage of cities and towns up and down its length. Some parts were
literally dead in the summer from lack of oxygen. Today, as a
result of deliberate cleanup efforts, industrial decline and the
recapture of onetime farmland by resurgent forests that reduce the
runoff of sediments, the river bursts with life. More than 200
species of fish live in or visit it, and the water is clean enough
in many places to swim in.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its resurgent vitality, though, the Hudson is in many
ways no longer natural but rather a human artifact. People control
and alter its shape, the flow of nutrients that sustain it, the
character of its habitats _ and the mixture of species that live in
it. At least scores and probably hundreds of species from other
lands and other parts of the continent inhabit the river and its
immediate environs. About 10 percent of these, according to earlier
research, have had an ecological impact, most of it negative.
</P>
<P>
   The zebra mussels are Exhibit A. At peak densities, they
outweigh all other organisms in their territory combined. The
territory stretches from the dam at Troy to the fringes of the New
York metropolitan area, where the water becomes too salty for them.
</P>
<P>
   They are especially concentrated in the upper stretches, where
the rocky bottom is to their liking and they cluster in densities
estimated at 10,000 to 20,000 individuals per square meter (about
10 square feet). Even in the lower, softer-bottomed stretches, they
may account for a third to a half of all organisms by weight, said
Dr. David L. Strayer of the Millbrook institute, one of Caraco's
co-authors.
</P>
<P>
   In a stroke of bad ecological luck, Strayer said, the highest
concentrations of mussels happen to be where the Hudson's
phytoplankton production is also concentrated. ``That's one of the
reasons the ecological impacts are so severe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While it seems likely that the mussels' drain on oxygen will
probably not get much worse than it already is, he said, the spread
of the water chestnut could combine with the mussels' oxygen use to
worsen it. Even if this never gets to the point where extensive
fish kills result, he said, it could well place a cap on further
efforts to enhance the river's health.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, areas dominated by the water chestnut are
already devoid of summertime oxygen, and this limits habitat for
native species, hobbling habitat restoration efforts and shrinking
rather than expanding the ranges of many aquatic creatures.
Expansion of the water chestnut could shrink the available habitat
even more.
</P>
<P>
   It is, Strayer said, as if the mussels and the chestnut are
limiting opportunities for further improvement of the Hudson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
