</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PROPHYLACTIC-MASTECTOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVING HEALTHY BREASTS FOUND EFFECTIVE IN HIGH CANCER-RISK
GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Minn., N.Y.)   (Science Times) 
(af) 
By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A desperate measure for reducing the risk of breast cancer,
removing both breasts while they are still healthy, has been proved
effective even for women who carry genetic defects that put them at
the very highest level of risk for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings come from the first long-term study to include
women with mutations in the genes BRCA1 and BRCA2, which cause 5
percent to 10 percent of all cases of breast cancer. Women with the
mutations have a 56 percent to 85 percent chance of developing the
disease. Removing the breasts reduces the risk by 90 percent for
those women, according to a study presented Monday in San Francisco
at a meeting of the American Association for Cancer Research.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted at the Mayo Clinic, included 214 women
considered high risk because breast cancer ran in their families.
All had their breasts removed as a preventive measure from 1960 to
1993. So far, of 148 who have been tested, 28 women had BRCA
defects, including 17 with defects specifically linked to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After a median of 15 years of follow-up, none of the 28 women
has developed cancer. There have been three cases of breast cancer
in the high-risk group despite the surgery, but none in women with
BRCA mutations. Overall, in a group of 214 high-risk women, 38
cases of breast would have been expected.
</P>
<P>
   The same researchers had already proved last year that breast
removal could protect women who had a strong family history of
breast cancer, and doctors had assumed that the findings would also
apply to women with BRCA defects. But they could not be sure,
because surgery had not been studied specifically in women known to
carry the mutations.
</P>
<P>
   The operation can never remove all breast tissue, and there was
always the possibility that enough mutant cells would evade the
scalpel to give rise to tumors later on.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings show that the surgery, prophylactic mastectomy,
does work. But not many women choose it, and it is controversial,
especially when treatments for women who already have breast cancer
are aimed at saving the breast whenever possible. In the study, the
number of cancer cases averted was small compared to the number of
women who had mutilating surgery and who might never have developed
cancer anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A patients' advocacy group, the National Breast Cancer
Coalition, said in a statement that very few women fall into the
high-risk category, and that although the surgery does appear to
help, it is drastic and ``should not be recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the operation provides the largest risk reduction
available. Another option is to take the drug tamoxifen, but it
reduces risk by only 45 percent, and can be taken for only 5 years.
It is not clear how long the protection lasts, and tamoxifen may
cause blood clots or uterine cancer in some women.
</P>
<P>
   Women at risk can also have frequent mammograms and breast
examinations in hopes of catching the disease early enough to cure
it, but it is not clear how well that approach works.
</P>
<P>
   The new information was presented by Dr. Lynn Hartmann, a
medical oncologist at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., and an
author of the 1999 article showing that the operation worked. The
214 women she reported on Monday were part of a group of 639 who
had their breasts removed and had a risk reduction of 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the original study, the researchers calculated the risk
reduction by comparing women who had the surgery to their sisters
who had not, and finding more breast cancer in the sisters who had
not had the operation.
</P>
<P>
   But at first, the researchers did not know whether any of the
women had BRCA mutations. They have since gone back and begun
performing genetic tests.
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann said she did not think her findings would change
doctors' or patients' minds about prophylactic mastectomy. ``I have
not seen waves of women coming forward to do this,'' she said,
estimating that the operation is done only 10 to 15 times a year at
the Mayo Clinic. ``For women who are interested, the data just help
them believe in the effectiveness of it. If a woman is not inclined
in this direction, this is not going to change her preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Payne, a psychologist at Memorial Sloan Kettering
Cancer Center in New York, said he counsels about one woman a month
who is considering the preventive surgery. Most go ahead with it,
and he said it was good news that the operation has proved
effective. But he also said that the data would not be used to push
women into having their breasts removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's elective surgery, with incredible ramifications for body
image,'' he said. ``Our job to some degree is to slow down the
process and make sure they're thinking through every part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
