<P>
   BKN-LAKERS-WEST _ Jerry West is an astute judge of basketball
talent who measures his words carefully. The Los Angeles Lakers
executive vice president is someone you take seriously, even when
he moves against the grain of conventional thinking. About a month
ago, as the Lakers were about to face Portland in the most
anticipated game of the NBA season, West said that, dominant
records notwithstanding, maybe they weren't the two best teams in
the league. You might recall West having said, ``The Spurs have to
be favored to win the title. Why? Because of the two big guys. They
may not excel in the backcourt or at small forward, but it's hard
to stop them when you've got to shoot over the top of Tim Duncan
and David Robinson.'' Some, Spurs' guard Steve Kerr among them,
thought West was merely deflecting pressure from his Lakers.
``Favorite'' was not a word Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich associated
with the defending champions. (Rosner, Austin American-Statesman).
23.
</P>
