<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-COST04-COX     04-03 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COST04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT LAWSUIT COST BOTH SIDES MILLIONS
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's decade-long antitrust battle
against Microsoft Corp. has cost taxpayers an estimated $15
million, and the tally could be millions more before the last
appeal is filed and the last court order signed.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sides in the case have been reluctant to disclose
exact costs, the Justice Department bowed to congressional pressure
last fall and provided an accounting for $13.3 million for several
legal actions against Microsoft dating back to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   That includes $7 million to finance the current lawsuit, which
was filed in May 1998, through last October. Since then, continuing
government work on the case has almost certainly pushed the total
up about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   That does not include expenses for 20 states that also have been
involved in the Microsoft suit and which have not disclosed how
much they are spending. Nor does it count what the company itself
has spent in its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mounting costs, pursuing Microsoft has cost less
than earlier titanic cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would hope that it wouldn't cost as much,'' said Joe Sims,
an antitrust lawyer who once served as the second-ranking Justice
Department official. He noted that the case that broke up the AT&AMP;T
telephone monopoly, estimated by published reports at $34 million
in current dollars, took eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The government spent 13 years on its unsuccessful attempt to
break up the computer giant IBM, Corp., and that case has been
estimated to cost $29 million in current dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The current Microsoft case has taken only two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said the expense to the Justice Department has been modest
enough so that ``you could argue about whether it make sense on
substantive grounds to file the case, but not according to the
expense.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Justice Department has enjoyed one break in the
Microsoft case. Its star prosecutor is private attorney David
Boies, who earlier beat back the government's attempts to break up
IBM. Boies has agreed to work for the government at an annual
salary of $104,000, which works out to about $50 an hour, a tenth
of his usual fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea what Microsoft has spent,'' Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Microsoft have said the company's spent $1 million
each week during the opening phase of trial in U.S. District Court
here, which took more than four months. In one symbol of the
spare-no-expense defense, an expert witness testified that he was
paid $250,000 by the company.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, company lawyers spent 3,000 hours on their
unsuccessful attempts to reach an out-of-court settlement,
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates told reporters last weekend in a
conference call. With lawyers, led by the Wall Street firm of
Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell, charging rates of $500 an hour, the failed
talks cost the company at least $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of the growing legal costs for Microsoft, the
company's most recent financial report says that it spent $506
million for ``general and administrative costs'' in the quarter
ending last December, an increase from $149 million the prior year.
The report cited ``increased legal fees'' as one reason.
</P>
<P>
   The expenses are not likely to break to the world's leading
software company, which also reported that as of last Dec. 31 it
had $17.8 billion in cash and short-term investments, plus $100
million in ``standby'' lines of credit.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft might need some of its cash if it chooses to fight the
Justice Department with appeals all the way to the Supreme Court, a
process some believe could take up to four more years.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
