<P>
   MICROSOFT RULING
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: All of these stories will move in the (f) Financial
category. Some, as noted, will also move in the (w) Washington
category.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is almost
certain to rule Microsoft violated federal antitrust law. The big
shoe to fall will be the penalty stage of the ruling that won't
come any earlier than this summer. Appeals could last years. A look
at what those penalities could be and what the tactics of both
sides, the government and Microsoft, are likely to be during this
period. It's predictable that Microsoft will try to put a PR spin
on the event and that'll be included too. (Glass, Cox News
Service). 50-60 _ With optional trim for papers wanting a shorter
story.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-HIGHLIGHTS _ WASHINGTON _ Highlights of the Microsoft
``Conclusions of Law.'' (Cox News Service). 6.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BUSINESS _ WASHINGTON _ What Microsoft's partners
(Dell, Compaq) and its competitors (Sun, Linux, AOL) say about the
ruling. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-COST _ WASHINGTON _ This has been an enormously
expensive trial, both for the government and for Microsoft. How
much did it cost Microsoft and the taxpayers. (Malone, Cox News
Service). 8.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REMEDIES _ WASHINGTON _ Here are seven possible
outcomes that could eventually result from Monday's ruling that
Microsoft violated antitrust laws. (Glass, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CLASS _ An avalanche of class action suits, based on
Jackson's probable ruling, are expected. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONSUMER _ Consumers shouldn't expect any real change
in how their computers work, what products are on the market, and
how much they pay. But long-term some of the penalties could change
personal computing. For instance, it's very possible that the Web
browser portion of Windows will be split off, creating more
competition. And prices could eventually fall. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-STOCK _ How will the market react? What does this mean
in the coming weeks for the market and Microsoft stock? (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH CHART.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-WEB _ We'll take the reader on a tour of the Web sites
_ including from Microsoft and the government _ that discuss the
ruling. And we'll show them where to go for the full text of the
ruling. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-WIRELESS _ One of the options open to Microsoft is to
explore new fields where it can dominate. One of those options is
to emphasis the use of wireless access to the Web. Katz visited
with Microsoft executives about that on a recent trip to the
Washington headquarters. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-COLUMN _ Haughtiness will make the world's largest
software maker, Microsoft, pay in the marketplace. Weighing in on
how the next few weeks will spin out for Ballmer, Gates &AMP; company.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUDGE _ WASHINGTON _ In the early days an earlier
stage of federal antitrust action against Microsoft Corp., when the
company insisted that the Windows 95 operating system wouldn't work
without its Internet browser, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson separated them himself with the help of a court technician.
Jackson's dive into the technical aspects of the case is indicative
of his approach to law. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
