<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, April 4, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will push off the Atlantic Seaboard
ahead of a cold front crossing the Appalachians on Tuesday. Very
mild, moist air along the East Coast will be replaced by cooler and
drier air from the west. However, a disturbance over the Tennessee
Valley will sponsor a chilly rain on the west slopes of the central
and southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms are likely near the Southeast coast.
Meanwhile, brisk winds from the northwest will combine with
residual clouds and sprinkles to produce a gray day in the Ohio
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, dry air over the South will yield to a brighter and warmer
afternoon. A surge of very warm air will cover the Rockies, but the
Northwest will become cooler with more clouds and scattered
showers. The Southwest will remain warm, though clouds will be
nestled along the Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: APRIL TORNADOES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the monthly tally of tornadoes, May is the most
active in the nation, with an average of more than 160 twisters.
But April holds the dubious distinction of spawning more killer
tornadoes. With the speedy jet stream continuing to derive energy
from large north-south temperature contrasts in April, robust
Pacific disturbances still come ashore and then forge slowly east
toward the Plains. Ahead of the system, humid air streams inland
from increasingly tepid waters of the Gulf of Mexico. When potent
disturbances meet high humidity, killer twisters can result.
</P>
</TEXT>
