<HEADER>
A5912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HANDGUNS-HNS &LR;      04-03 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDGUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GUN MAKER'S DEAL WITH CITES, STATES COULD BACKFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State and local governments have embraced a
former enemy, Smith &AMP; Wesson, since it broke ranks with fellow gun
manufacturers by agreeing to introduce a series of safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's decision, which allows it to settle lawsuits
with more than 30 cities and counties, has alienated loyal
customers, firearms distributors and retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides plan to use their economic clout to influence the
company: Many police agencies are vowing to buy only Smith &AMP; Wesson
firearms but distributors and retail stores are refusing to stock
the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith &AMP; Wesson has made some powerful new friends but its new
enemies have a lot more clout when it comes to selling guns,'' said
Tom Diaz, a senior analyst with the Violence Policy Center and
author of the 1999 book ``Making a Killing: The Business of Guns in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will see a coordinated effort to unravel this
deal. ... This is a very vindictive industry,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies account for 20 percent to 25 percent of
sales in the $1.5 billion-a-year gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the agreement, announced by President Clinton on
March 17, that allows Smith &AMP; Wesson to settle its lawsuits by
adopting a series of more than 100 measures, including mandatory
trigger locks and restrictions on distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, 65 cities and counties have agreed to try to use
their collective buying power to prod other gun makers to adopt a
similar code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capacity to squeeze manufacturers like a pincers
and hurt them in the marketplace,'' said New York Attorney General
Eliot L. Spitzer, a leader of the newly created Communities for
Safer Guns Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The gun industry and some consumers plan to squeeze back harder,
making Smith &AMP; Wesson a pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Clinton's announcement, Smith &AMP; Wesson was part of the
industrywide resistance to lawsuits and other anti-gun efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that no other major manufacturers will desert
this coordinated effort in favor of their own individual deal,''
said Robert Delfay, president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, the nation's largest firearms trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement contracts are eagerly sought by high-end gun
manufacturers, which often discount their handguns from the usual
retail price of about $500 each. Police contracts also give
companies bragging rights when marketing products to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson's main competitors in the police market _ Glock,
Beretta and Winchester _ have no plans to change their marketing
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Under its agreement, Smith &AMP; Wesson said it would quickly
install gun locks on all the weapons it sells, introduce ``smart
gun'' technology permitting weapons to be fired only by their
owners and bar sales of its weapons at gun shows without a
background check.
</P>
<P>
   The company also agreed to sell its products only to authorized
dealers, who in turn must agree to receive training and to abide by
the same code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But many dealers are angry about the restrictions it places on
them. Many gun-rights activists are vowing to boycott the company
for caving in to gun-control forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ill-conceived action on the part of one of the most
revered names in the American firearms industry,'' Delfay said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of Smith &AMP; Wesson's largest single distributors, the
RSR Group in Florida, said last week it will no longer stock the
company's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come to the difficult conclusion that we cannot
continue to do business with Smith &AMP; Wesson under the problematic
terms of their current agreement,'' the company said in a
statement. ``Although this agreement is being hailed by some as a
positive new development, it is our opinion as a wholesale
distributor in the shooting sports industry that its terms are
one-sided and fall short of offering any realistic solutions to the
problems concerning the criminal misuse of firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some critics of the gun industry doubt that the Smith &AMP;
Wesson deal can withstand the pressure from retailers, distributors
and gun-buying activists.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said the deal with Smith &AMP; Wesson ``is going to fall
apart'' because the brunt of the pain is felt by distributors and
dealers who can destroy the company in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sell a gun to every cop in America and that still is
not going to save Smith &AMP; Wesson,'' Diaz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOUISVILLE-THEATER-(1     04-03 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISVILLE-THEATER-(1500)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: WHEN THEATER SENDS UP ITSELF TO SAVE ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ ``I mean, this is driving me crazy!'' says the
actor planted in the audience, interrupting the play and causing
the actors onstage to confront the impertinent intruder directly.
``This is the whole problem with 20th-century theater. This is part
of the reason nobody wants to buy a ticket. We used to get stories;
now we get interpretations.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that so? The question _ the issue, really _ is at the heart
of ``Anton in Show Business,'' a mischievously self-skewering
comedy by the pseudonymous playwright Jane Martin being staged at
the Actors Theater of Louisville as part of the annual Humana
Festival of New American Plays. It is a play about a play about a
small theater company putting on a play (``The Three Sisters''),
and thus consciously an example of the problem it addresses, often
with aching hilarity _ that the world of the theater is growing
ever more estranged from the straightforward business of telling
stories.
</P>
<P>
   And except that it doesn't have a rape (or the threat of one) in
it, as four of the six full-length works staged here do, ``Anton''
made an apt spokesplay for the festival, which ends here this week.
Long on appropriating, analyzing, reconstructing and deconstructing
stories, the festival plays were a little short on making them up.
That's a characterization only, not an overall judgment; several of
the works presented here seem destined for future life. But in
addition to Martin's invocation of Chekhov, one play examined the
life of Orson Welles, one was a contemporary adaptation of a Greek
tragedy and one, ``No. 11 (Blue and White)'' by Alexandra
Cunningham, told the story of a privileged high school rapist that
was clearly drawn from the Alex Kelly case in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Like two other plays that have recently opened in New York,
``The Hologram Theory,'' about the murder of a New York City club
kid, and ``Down the Drain,'' about Susan Smith, the South
Carolinian who killed her children, ``No. 11'' was an attempt to
examine the cultural resonance of an already foraged-over crime. It
failed for the same reason; it unearthed only the already familiar.
Tied to these stories, the issues feel exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The general amalgamation in the entertainment universe (where
any story seems fair game for all media) seems particularly
threatening to the theater, which has long felt its relevance
slipping, its stories drowned out by the ever more clamorous din of
television and the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume of narrative to which we are exposed has made us
distance it,'' said Jon Jory, the producing director of the Actors
Theater, who founded the play festival 23 years ago. ``The
playwright lives in fear of hearing, `Oh, yes, that was a
television movie.' It objectifies narrative in a way that scares
us; we're all told we have to be tied into some larger
significance. I do sense, in young people, a fear that their
stories have become part of some Jungian pool and that they must
somehow find a way to tell the story of society. They feel an
intellectual pressure about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea saddened him, Jory said, sounding a lot like the spirit
of Jane Martin's play, which is pertinent because Jory is widely
thought to be Jane Martin (who is the nominal author of ``Talking
With'' and ``Keely and Du,'' among other plays) or at least the
chairman of a Jane Martin committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I can't tell you that,'' said 61-year-old Jory, when asked
directly if he is the playwright. But ``Anton in Show Business''
struck many at the festival this weekend as the valedictory
statement of a man who after this season is leaving the Actors
Theater, which he has led since 1969, to teach acting and directing
at the University of Washington in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Anton'' no element of the theatrical landscape escapes
satire. Self-involved actors, autocratic directors, romantic and
uninformed producers, complacent audiences, presumptuous critics,
cynical corporate sponsors all get their comeuppance here _ even
Actors' Equity, the union, one character says, that makes sure ``no
more than 80 percent of our membership is out of work on any given
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The barbs are insider-specific and most are affectionately
applied, and in the end the message is clear. The theatrical
enterprise has been so fouled by money problems, so twisted by a
culture of celebrity, so swaddled in intellectual pretension, that
the simple desire to put on a show, to tell a story onstage, has
been hopelessly _ almost hopelessly _ buried. What has risen in its
place is a hermetic theater world that talks to itself and whose
citizens are defensive and embarrassed about the fundamental joy
that drew them to the stage in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other highlights was ``Big Love,'' Charles L. Mee's
highly physical adaptation of the Aeschylus tragedy ``The Suppliant
Women,'' which turns the story of 50 sisters, who are promised in
marriage against their will and vow to murder their husbands on
their wedding night, into a modern-day war-of-the-sexes parable.
</P>
<P>
   It is a play staged on a wrestling mat because the actors are
called upon to hurl themselves about in remarkably vigorous
fashion; in twin set pieces, one with three women, one with three
men, the actors enact a fiercely violent ballet, with bruising
collisions and falls, conducted to screaming speechifying about the
irksome qualities of the opposite sex. Mee's script, an amalgam of
angry, essayistic monologues and jokey references to things like
hair products and Ken dolls, is also too often cornered into
preachy high-mindedness: ``Love trumps all,'' says the old woman
who is given the role of sage. ``Love is the highest law.'' Still,
the primordial, communal twitch of loins and heart has rarely been
so viscerally acted out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``War of the Worlds,'' conceived and directed by Anne Bogart and
written by Naomi Iizuka, is a deconstruction of the life of Orson
Welles. Even amid a rash of biography-based works, Welles has been
well scrutinized lately, the subject of a television movie, ``RKO
281,'' and a new play, ``Orson's Shadow'' by Austin Pendleton,
which had its premiere at Steppenwolf in Chicago this season and
will be remounted at the Williamstown Theater Festival this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart's production, which is to appear at the Next Wave
Festival at the Brooklyn Academy of Music in the fall, is visually
striking and very busy. Iizuka's script doesn't have the lyric
weapons to stand up to the staging pyrotechnics, but this is
nonetheless an intellectually engaging work, presenting Welles as a
self-defeating artist obsessed with capturing the truth of life
``within a frame'' and conducting a lifelong battle with the
standard he set for himself in his first movie, ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   The effective and clever narrative gimmick is that Welles' life
is presented as Welles presented the life of William Randolph
Hearst _ in flashback, with a reporter seeking the meaning of the
man's dying utterance. Kane said, ``Rosebud,'' of course; Welles,
we are told, said, ``Thorn.''
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a series of scenes that are refracted mirrorings
of the film's, suggestive not only of parallels between Welles and
Kane but also of differences between the stage and the screen, the
separate but equal potency of metaphorical imagery offered live and
realistic imagery framed and shaped by film. The climactic moment
has a narrator intoning a list of Welles' credits as Welles himself
(in a stylish mimicry, without caricature, by Stephen Webber) is
piling chairs with haphazard fury at center stage, recalling Kane's
reckless despair as he tears down Xanadu, the mansion he built as a
monument to himself.
</P>
<P>
   The two original full-length stories at the festival (there was,
as usual, a program of 10-minute plays and, as there was last year,
a series of dial-in ``telephone plays'') both concerned rape. One,
``Touch'' by Toni Press-Coffman, is an inexpressibly windy piece
about the anguish of a young astronomer when his wife is abducted
and murdered. The other, ``Tape'' by Stephen Belber, is a
well-constructed if not-quite-credible psychodrama about two men
and a woman in a three-way fencing match over a long-ago sexual act
that may or may not have constituted rape.
</P>
<P>
   Quality aside, the fact that so many of the plays here focused
on the primitively charged subject of sexual violence seems another
sign of a theater fearful of losing an audience; see four of them
in a weekend and you begin to think of crotch-grabbing stand-up
comics. Indeed, the lingering impression left by the festival is
that in a competition with television and the movies for
straightforward stories of human experience, theater's diminished
confidence in its relevance is probably justified. What will
restore it is not yet clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my question would be if plays, doing plays, doesn't
speak to the culture, then examining why or satirizing why is kind
of beating a dead horse,'' the audience member complains in ``Anton
in Show Business,'' adding, after a beat: ``From the inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
