<HEADER>
A5915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-LANE-COLUMN0404-COX-1     04-03 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0404-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST LEDE; resending for complete column
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Brewski bill a faint hope for beer snobs
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I'm no beer snob but ... Oh, why start off
with a lie? I am a beer snob and it's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Other kinds of snobbery give you social standing, opportunities
to bully lesser men, but beer snobbery? It gets you no further than
video-game snobbery. (''I won't buy Tomb Raider V. They ruined
Laura Croft's purity of line.'')
</P>
<P>
   This is not an easy vice to pursue. You suffer the effects of
pretentiousness without the advantages. At parties, you are
discovered systematically rifling the cooler until you find
something, anything, with a long neck, maybe a foil wrapper and
certainly without a twist-off cap.
</P>
<P>
   In stores, you scan the shelves for labels with 19th-century
style lettering and Victorian dingbats on the labels _ sure hints
the liquid within may be dark and heavy.
</P>
<P>
   You can't go to the corner convenience store for lottery tickets
and a six-pack of Ye Olde Oat and Crankshaft Extra-Heavy Cream
Stout. (''You know it's the real thing because there's stuff
floating in it.'') People make fun of you for trying to order it in
public. And even the Florida Legislature works against you.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the Legislature. It suppresses the sale of obscure
beers in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   How? Well, since 1965, Florida has required that beer be sold in
only four sizes of bottles or cans _ 8 ounces, 12 ounces, 16 ounces
or 32 ounces. That's it. Because the rest of the world uses the
metric system, this has the effect of banning foreign beers from
</P>
<P>
   Florida unless they are specially packaged for the Florida
market.
</P>
<P>
   Big brewers and wholesalers like this arrangement. It keeps
pesky, small brewers out of the state and restricts foreign beers
lest they corrupt the palates of Florida's beer drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Good, old-fashioned protectionism served cold.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's beer wholesalers won't come out and say they support
the law because it limits competition. That would be un-American.
Instead, they make their campaign donations and talk about the
pernicious effects if consumers were faced with too many choices.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Morroni (R-Clearwater), chairman of the House
Regulated Industries Committee, says he is leaning against a bill
that would finally end this nonsense and allow stores to stock any
size beer bottle under 32 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   He says feels this way because ``it would allow larger beer
sizes on college campuses.'' Another factor might be $1,000 in
donations he received last election from the Florida Beer
Wholesalers' ``good government'' fund.
</P>
<P>
   As serious as the problem of college alcohol abuse is, I don't
think small bottles are a deterrent. Many students have figured out
that if they can't get drunk on one bottle of beer, they can buy
more than one bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Those college kids can be very, very clever.
</P>
<P>
   Beer wholesaler lobbyists argue that more choices on the shelf
would ``confuse consumers'' and force stores to waste money
stocking a greater variety of beers in different sized bottles.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad car dealers don't think that way. Parking lots would
look pretty grim if the state required all cars to be black and
built only in four sizes. But anything else would confuse consumers
and create needless costs, wouldn't it?
</P>
<P>
   And bookstores that could sell only four kinds of books? That
would be really depressing _ but not at all confusing.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sadly silly law, but all efforts to fix it have died
quiet deaths, year after year. This would be a small thing, except
it vividly shows how selective our legislators are when they talk
about less government. They are willing to cut environmental
protections, scale back health and safety regulations and make it
harder to sue when manufacturers are negligent. But when it comes
to nonsensical government restrictions that exist solely to benefit
a few favored businesses that donate at election time, talk about
fighting government interference in the marketplace disappears
faster than a cold beer on a hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to be able to drink Plump Muskrat Cloudy Ale in
400 milliliter bottles. That you can't do so in Florida is another
demonstration of the veto power of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-state beer snobs, drink your next one for me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
