<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER04-COX     04-03 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Campaign keystone
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush is campaigning in the crucial rust belt state of
Pennsylvania this week. In tow is Gov. Tom Ridge, the Catholic
pro-choice GOP member being mentioned as the kind of running mate
who could help Bush win the upper Midwest states he'll need to beat
Al Gore. Cox Newspapers' Jena Health reports that Bush will stay
over at the governor's mansion Monday night and is expected to
continue touting education with an address on character education
today.
</P>
<P>
   CLEANING UP THE RUST BELT
</P>
<P>
   Monday in Pennsylvania, George W. Bush took on an issue that Al
Gore has promoted since 1993. Bush went to the site of a former
Jones and Laughlin steel plant in Aliquippa that was cleaned up,
and unveiled a plan to speed up redevelopment of polluted
industrial sites. ``Prosperity will mean little if we leave to
future generations a world of polluted air, toxic lakes and rivers
and banished forests,'' he said. J&AMP;L Steel had left steel deposits,
or slag, behind. US Gypsum cleaned up the 117-acre site and built a
$120 million plant that will open in May, making sheetrock with
synthetic and recycled materials and without discharge into the
Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACKS ON GIULIANI TEMPERED
</P>
<P>
   A subdued President Clinton took to the fund-raising trail
again, abandoning steaming criticism of his wife Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Republican Senate opponent, Rudy Giuliani, and casting
attacks on the GOP in general economic terms. Clinton headlined at
two events in Las Vegas that were expected to bring in $525,000 for
the Democratic National Committee. In Las Vegas, in contrast to a
fund-raiser in Washington the day before where he lambasted
Giuliani as a tool of the ``right-wing venom machine,'' Clinton
just talked about this fall's election hinging on what the parties
plan to do with the federal budget surplus. Later, he repeated the
message Monday in San Jose, Calif., at a $1 million fund-raiser for
the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   NOT AS EASY AS IT LOOKED FROM THE OTHER SIDE
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton said Monday that life on the Senate
campaign trail is harder than expected, especially for women. ``I'm
almost embarrassed to think back _ all the times that I would say
to my husband, `Well, you could have said this differently, or you
could have done that,''' she told about 100 people at a community
forum in Coxsackie, N.Y. ``Now, I would like to take all those
words back because it's very tough for both men and women,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH WON'T GIVE UP ON CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is taking pains to show he won't let history
repeat itself in California, eight years after his father ceded the
state early to Bill Clinton in a move that helped the Democrats win
back the White House. With symbolism and actions, Bush is seeking
to reassure jittery Republicans that he intends to fight for the
state and win _ just as his father did in 1988. One example: Even
though he's far behind Gore among Hispanics in the state, he's
going out of his way to seek their votes. But Gore is 10 points
ahead in the latest Field Poll, has a powerful ally in Gov. Gray
Davis, and the Clinton administration has had federal funds pouring
in recently.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER YEAR OF THE WOMAN?
</P>
<P>
   While 1992 was dubbed the ``Year of the Woman'' after four women
won Senate seats and 24 were elected to the House, 2000 is quietly
shaping up as the sequel. Women are seeking four of the 11 Senate
seats and six of the 18 House seats considered most competitive by
Congressional Quarterly. Women in top Senate races: Democratic Rep.
Debbie Stabenow challenging GOP Sen. Spencer Abraham in Michigan;
development executive Rebecca Yanisch against GOP Sen. Rod Grams in
Minnesota; Hillary Rodham Clinton facing Republican Rudy Giuliani
in New York; Democratic state Sen. Allyson Schwartz trying to
unseat GOP Sen. Rick Santorum in Pennsylvania; and in Washington
state, former Rep. Maria Cantwell and state Insurance Commissioner
Deborah Senn both are vying for the Democratic nomination to oppose
GOP Sen. Slade Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   PARENTAL GUIDANCE
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, President Clinton was far more popular among
women than among men as he sought a second term. Among women with
children at home, Clinton thoroughly dominated Republican Bob Dole:
Mothers preferred Clinton 60 percent to 37 percent. Today, in a
striking reversal for Democrats, mothers are solidly backing George
W. Bush. The gap is 11 points _ 52 percent to 41 percent _
according to independent pollster Andrew Kohut. Among fathers, Bush
is ahead of Al Gore by an even larger margin: 54 percent to 36
percent.
</P>
<P>
   READY TO TAKE THE MOUND FOR A SAVE IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   A Republican congressman who once had his eye on the New York
Senate race is shifting his gaze there again. Rep. Rick Lazio of
Long Island said his party is stumbling badly with Rudy Giuliani as
its Senate candidate against Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``We are in
the process of potentially blowing this race,'' he said. But Lazio
stopped short of saying Giuliani can't win. ``What I'm prepared to
say is we're less likely to win relative to myself or maybe even
another candidate who can bring the party together,'' he said.
Lazio said he could still replace Giuliani as the GOP candidate if
he gets the go-ahead from state GOP leaders, particularly Gov.
George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   TURNING OUT THE LIGHTS NO SIMPLE TRICK
</P>
<P>
   There's still activity at Bill Bradley headquarters in West
Orange, N.J., where a skeleton crew is manning the phones. Though
his campaign is gutted and shrinking by the day, campaign and
federal officials say it could take years before ``Bradley for
President'' officially goes dark. That is because, having accepted
federal matching funds for the primaries, Bradley's campaign must
now undergo a federal audit to determine how much of its remaining
funds must be returned to the Treasury. The campaign had $2,957,650
on hand Feb. 29, and that doesn't take into account the money
raised and spent in March ahead of the March 7 Super Tuesday
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   VERBAL DIFFICULTIES OFF THE CUFF
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reports that George W. Bush, ad-libbing his
way through an education speech several days ago, vowed to remove
the federal ``cuff link'' that stymies local control of schools.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERS TAKE STOCK OF BUSH
</P>
<P>
   According to the Washington Post, George W. Bush faces questions
about his ``demeanor and intellectual maturity _ or `gravitas,' as
columnist George F. Will has put it _ (that) continue to dog him
and threaten to become a central issue in a presidential race that
many believe will be decided as much on personality as issues.''
And the New York Times, exploring Bush's ability to broaden his
base, concluded that ``Bush must immediately and emphatically
establish himself as an unconventional Republican who is less bound
by an unyielding conservative ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   GOT THE HORSE RIGHT HERE, HIS NAME IS . . .
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Quarterly handicapped the Republican veep field,
giving Elizabeth Dole 9-2 odds, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge 6-1
odds, retired Gen. Colin Powell 7-1 odds, and Indiana Sen. Richard
Lugar and New York Gov. George Pataki 12-1 odds. Others range from
15-1 to 1,000-1 (Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura).
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM: WHY NOT ME
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham (D-Fla.), touting himself as a potential vice
presidential candidate, was quoted by ABC and the New York Times on
what he could bring to Al Gore on the ticket: ``I have had a long
association with some of the key issues in this campaign. ... I was
chairman of the education commission. ... I come from a large
state.''
</P>
<P>
   GREAT, IF HE'S RUNNING FOR BISHOP
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes is still running. He brought his message of
``restoring America's moral authority'' to Appleton, Wis., speaking
to about 500 people at Lawrence University's Memorial Chapel. Said
the Appleton Post-Crescent: ``The resemblance to a church service
didn't end there. Keyes' presentation is much in the style of a
tent show preacher, and so was his message. In fact, it wasn't
until the question-and-answer session at the end did he offer
specific policy proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   BILLIONAIRE COMES THROUGH
</P>
<P>
   Billionaire Eli Broad has given $1 million to the Democratic
National Convention's host committee in hopes of helping
fund-raisers meet their final goal. The donation is the first by
Broad to the organization he co-chairs, and it puts the
fund-raising total to date at $26.6 million of the $33.5 million
goal to cover convention costs. Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan,
who recently took control of the host committee, has been urging
potential donors to help make up the nearly $7 million difference.
The convention is set for Aug. 14-17 in downtown L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ELVIS LIVES ON AND IS RUNNING FOR MAYOR
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Presley is alive and stumping for enough votes in the
Wisconsin North Woods to remake The King into a mayor. Make no
mistake, Elvis Presley is his legal name. The 50-year-old Elvis
impersonator and tavern owner is running for mayor today in
Phillips, a town of about 1,700 people. He sports deep sideburns
and has had dental work to look more like the late singer. But he
has dropped about 40 pounds from the days he fit snugly into a
white sequin jump suit.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
