r l BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      04-03 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBSITE &AMP; MAGAZNIE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (RESENDING. MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L`` CATEGORIES) 
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Muller takes a quick look at some current magazine issues
and a website:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WEBSITE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; movie-list.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of watching those trailers while people are still finding
their seats and rattling their popcorn bags? Then Movie-List is for
you. The site features theatrical trailers for all the hot movies
coming out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers trailers and so-called teasers (shorter versions
of the trailer) in Quicktime. They are available in high-resolution
or low-resolution formats, depending on the speed of your
connection and how long you want to wait for a download.
</P>
<P>
   Recent additions to the site include trailers for ``The Hollow
Man,''which features Kevin Bacon as a not-so-nice invisible man,
``The Filth and the Fury,'' a documentary about the British punk
band the Sex Pistols, and ``Dinosaur,'' a Disney film about
prehistoric creatures.
</P>
<P>
   There also is ``Battlefield Earth,'' a new John Travolta flick
based on an L. Ron Hubbard book and ``Gone in Sixty Seconds,'' the
remake of the '70s movie of the same name, starring Nicolas Cage
and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   So, grab some popcorn and soda, and take a gander. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MAGAZINE REVIEWS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``BOY'S LIFE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Published by the Boy Scouts of America, this magazine is fun for
Scouts and non-Scouts alike, offering easy-to-read articles,
age-appropriate advice, cartoons and puzzles. My favorite how-to
this month is a primer on replacing a bike tire inner tube. Such
knowledge is especially useful in Arizona, land of the angry thorn.
There is also a Q-and-A on camping, which counsels Scouts to pack
out their garbage and avoid scratching their names on trees or
burning down the forest. Keep in mind that the magazine does have
some religious overtones. This issue includes a short story on
Scouts visiting churches, chapels and temples to learn more about
other religions. With baseball season starting, there also is a
reprint of the Thayer poem, ``Casey at the Bat,'' and a short story
on a light-hitting Little Leaguer who saves the day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ESQUIRE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Answers the burning question, ``What's on Heather Graham's
Mind?'' which, after reading the story, we have to conclude is
``not much.'' Still in all, it's an amusing if self-conscious story
about the winsome actress, whose appearance in ``Austin Powers 2:
The Spy Who Shagged Me'' has vaulted her to instant cult status,
especially among the denizens of the Internet. It's funny to learn
that she first appeared in film as a dead junkie in ``Drugstore
Cowboy.'' In that inexplicable ``Esquire''-think, the magazine
lists the 18 most important golf courses in America, and then tops
the list with the Old Course at St. Andrews, SCOTLAND. They're
trying to be cute here, but it just doesn't work. There is also a
piece on golfer John Daly, he of the thunderous swing and alcohol
problem. Again, we have to wade through all the self-serving pap
about the writer palling around with Daly until we get to the real
story: Daly is losing but happy. I wonder if that is his final
answer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``OUTSIDE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the camping issue, but hey, isn't every issue? Worth
picking up for story on the ``Surf Chimp,'' a long-armed surfer
dude named Jeff Hakman who dominated his sport, founded a
multimillion-dollar surfwear company and then lost it all to a
heroin addiction _ twice. Now he's competing on the surfing
equivalent of a senior's tour. Who knew? There also is an
interesting piece on those so-called adventure races where people
scale cliffs and navigate rapids so they break their arms and legs
and are shown weeping on the Discovery Channel. Article wonders
aloud if it's all just becoming too commercial. Surely not. Being
on TV has nothing to do with making money, does it? Also includes a
nicely done piece that suggests leaving behind all your techno
stuff _ phones, pagers, Iridium satellites _ when you head out to
the wilderness, so you can forget about civilization. What was that
again? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``REASON'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The libertarian magazine goes after _ surprise! _ Bill Clinton
this month, noting that he's survived scandals not because he's
innocent, but because he's an expert at managing the news and
handling internal crises. Interesting piece offers ``a five-step
program for surviving endless scandal,'' noting that Clinton
doesn't feed scandals and uses his office to distract the public,
mostly by having the military blow something up.
</P>
<P>
   There's another piece on agronomist extraordinaire Norman
Borlaug, the father of the so-called Green Revolution and a Nobel
Peace Prize winner, who is still teaching at Texas A&AMP;M at age 86.
Borlaug is widely credited with increasing wheat yields in the late
1960s and saving millions from starvation in Mexico, India and
Pakistan. There also is a good piece noting that this year's
presidential election will be less about issues than any election,
ever. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
