<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-FALCONE-NYT &LR;      04-03 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT, WISEGUY, ONE FALSE NOTE... 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love those Sopranos? Well, here come the countertenors, the
whining gangsters who strut through ``Falcone,'' the series that
begins Tuesday night on CBS. Like many of the journeymen crooks who
fleetingly pass through it, this earnest drama is trying to live by
the rules. And like those mobsters, it's being set up. It's gonna
get whacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' is bound to fall short in the inevitable comparisons
to ``The Sopranos,'' the groundbreaking HBO series, and to ``Donnie
Brasco,'' the 1997 film that shares its source material with
``Falcone.'' Nor is it well served by CBS' bombardment-style
introduction: two episodes Tuesday night and seven more over the
next eight nights (with Sunday off for good behavior).
</P>
<P>
   This is not ``Millionaire''-style soda pop for the millions to
guzzle night after night. It's a dark but strangely sanitized brew,
a decaf espresso, better sipped in small quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Gedrick stars as Joe Pistone, which is the real name of a
former FBI agent whose memoirs of infiltrating the Mafia inspired
first the film and now this series. When encountered Tuesday night,
the fictionalized Pistone, using the name Joe Falcone, has been
accepted by a mob family in New York. He's spending far too little
time with his real family: his wife, Maggie, and two daughters in
New Jersey. When he does slip away to visit them, the reunion can
be bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks!'' rails Maggie (Amy Carlson) in a scene meant to
establish the toll all this takes on her. ``Two weeks you been gone
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was workin', Maggs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I can't tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts might worry her. They'd certainly confuse her. And
maybe you, too. Joe is watching from the inside as a couple of
third-string capos vie for power. Joe had better side with the
right one, otherwise he'll get whacked. (This is the word heard
most in this show.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down t'choosin', I'll go wit' my instincts,''
Joe tells his FBI boss, Jules Weller (Robert John Burke). Joe does
choose correctly, and he becomes a trusted underling of the
triumphant Sonny Napoli (Titus Welliver). Thus Joe is given orders
by two glum middle managers, both of whom try to be as fair as
their inflexible codes allow. But like other promising elements in
the show, this one isn't explored.
</P>
<P>
   This series pulls its punches. Of course it must conform to the
requirements of broadcast television, so the language never
descends further than an occasional grade-school epithet. (Words
can still be offensive, however, as in the third episode, when a
black police detective looks down upon the body of a whacked
mobster and snarls an anti-Italian slur.)
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no sex here; in one scene set in a strip club,
the women writhing onstage display as much skin as your average
basketball player. Yes, plenty of whacking is depicted. Plenty. But
it's curiously bloodless. Besides deaths by shooting, stabbing and
strangling, Tuesday night's two hours offer a toe broken with
pliers and two scenes of faces shoved into hot food (pizza and chop
suey).
</P>
<P>
   Nobody cusses, nobody copulates, nobody sweats, and hardly
anybody bleeds. The only dramatic tension surrounds the question of
whether Joe's true identity will be discovered. But in that case,
he'd be whacked, and the show would be over.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves characterization to carry the day. Some of the
peripheral figures are winningly quirky. And Gedrick might be able
to charm the audience if given a chance. He gives great close-up.
In a moment that supplies one of the series' infrequent grace
notes, Joe gets home long enough to tell his girls a bedtime story,
his own version of the legend of Ulysses, another good guy who was
away from the house a lot. ``Tomorrow night,'' he tells them, ``the
suitors get whacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers from New Jersey, grumpy over the depiction of their
state on ``The Sopranos'' as a hotbed of crime (not to mention hot
beds), may take a grain of comfort from ``Falcone.'' Here the crime
is all on the New York side of the Hudson; when Joe crosses to the
west side of the river, he enters the oasis of normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those viewers may also catch an inside joke, an
appearance by Floyd Vivino, the clown prince of New Jersey cable.
He convincingly plays a character called Rocky TV, an apt
description of his eternal turn as Uncle Floyd. But any happiness
over the sight of Vivino without his oversize bow tie and
madras-plaid porkpie hat is quickly dashed: Rocky gets whacked.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `FALCONE'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Tuesday and 10 p.m. Wednesday through April 12, except
Sunday, on CBS (Channel 2 in New York).
</P>
<P>
   Robert Singer, Mark Johnson, John Lee Hancock, Bobby Moresco and
Ken Solarz, executive producers. Produced by Columbia Tri-Star
Television in association with CBS Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jason Gedrick (Joe Falcone/Pistone), Titus Welliver (Sonny
Napoli), Robert John Burke (Jules Weller), Amy Carlson (Maggie),
Sonny Marinelli (Jimmy Suits), Lillo Brancato Jr. (Lucky), Eric
Roberts (Ricci) and Floyd Vivino (Rocky TV).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
