<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5925 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-CURTIS-REVIE-AZR &LR;      04-03 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURTIS-REVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART IS RICH, BUT THE ESSAYS SUFFER FROM VERBOSITY  
 (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGH HAVE MISSED IT)
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 Review of: 
 
 ``AMERICAN DREAMER: THE ART OF PHILIP C. CURTIS'' 
 Hudson Hills Press ($45) 
 
 
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Considering the longevity of Philip Curtis' distinguished career
as a painter, it is surprising that only now has the first
full-length book of the artist's work been published.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``American Dreamer: The Art of Philip C. Curtis,'' the
book is a rich coffee-table compendium of the artist's work, filled
out with a series of essays by art critics and historians about the
Scottsdale resident.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly worth the price for the reproductions, which
cover Curtis' career from 1937 to the present, beginning with the
early New York social paintings and abstractions.
</P>
<P>
   The essays are less of a gift. They offer the occasional
insight, but mainly they pad the volume with endless jargon and
obscurantist palaver. It is a tough read and you come out the back
end without feeling a sense of either enlightenment or enjoyment.
This is not a book of graceful prose.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there is little to illuminate the life and
personality of Curtis, who is a wonderfully interesting man, with a
wry sense of wit that can cut through the BS like a scalpel. He
once told me, ``Yes, I'm happy, but not so happy that I'm an idiot
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been helpful to have at least one essay that would
serve as a biography or at least a snapshot of the man's
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, each essay dives headfirst into the list of ``isms''
and influences that make up an art historian's narrow worldview.
Several of the essays repeat the same information, almost word for
word, as if there had been no editor to keep track of the
redundancies and weed them out.
</P>
<P>
   And the verbiage reaches a climax in the essay by Susan Ehrlich,
``Invocations of Wonder Transfixed in Time,'' in which the author's
love of Roget outmans her and wrestles her to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis' work, she writes, ``bears filiations with the cryptic
illusions of Belgian Surrealists.''
</P>
<P>
   And she tells us ``suspense accrues from the enfilade of
sequestered rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   And a door ``leads to secluded recessions (that) can signify
psychological travel through shrouded corridors of the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   This stuff is thick.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on: ``Certainly Curtis over the years has juggled
antitheses, clothing complex issues in simple attire, treating
prosaic forms in a Surreal way, and imposing a rationcinative order
on ideation's fugitive wraiths.''
</P>
<P>
   The horror. The horror.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of these essays, we are given a tour of the alleged
influences on Curtis, and how you can spot Matisse here, or Helen
Lundeberg there, as if such observations meant anything.
</P>
<P>
   There is some relief in the longish final essay by Harry Rand.
It is not gracefully written, either, but it does offer some
insight into the sophistication of Curtis' mind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even Rand can lob out a line like: ``He was not alone in
eschewing a reductionist telos of Abstract Expressionism.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a one of them seems to understand Curtis with the clarity of
``Time'' magazine founder Henry Luce, who once wrote that
``Curtis's people are clearly all `waiting for Godot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He hits a simple truth of the art that all the righteous
scholarship of the art historians seems blind to in the verbal
blizzard of their glossolalia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at richard.nilsen(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8823. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
