<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    General Electric retains top spot on Forbes list
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General Electric tops the Forbes (April 17) list of
best-performing companies for the third straight year, with 1999
sales of $111.63 billion, a net profit of $10.7 billion and a
market value (share price times shares outstanding) of more than
$80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``By every yardstick, 1999 was a remarkable year of growth for
America's largest corporations,'' says Forbes. ``You'd have to go
back to 1994 to find a better year (for profits).''
</P>
<P>
   Total sales for companies on the magazine's 32nd annual Forbes
500 list rose 11 percent to $6.5 trillion. Profits rose 26 percent
to $440 billion, assets rose 13 percent to $16.8 trillion and
market value rose 25 percent to $14 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes ranks U.S. companies according to sales, profit, assets
and market value. That means its rankings are usually different
from the Fortune 500, which ranks companies by revenue. General
Motors, with 1999 sales of $189.1 billion, topped Fortune's list,
which was released over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Just behind General Electric on Forbes' list are Citigroup,
Exxon Mobil, Bank of America and IBM. The highest-ranking
Georgia-based company is BellSouth, at 30th place.
</P>
<P>
   A SALTY BEVERAGE COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   By dominating the salty-snack market, Pepsico has become leaner
and more profitable, Business Week (April 10) says in a cover
profile of Coca-Cola's biggest competitor. The credit goes to Roger
A. Enrico, a 29-year Pepsico veteran who became chief executive in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dramatic change at Pepsi is that soda and juice run a
distant second to the big engine that now drives Pepsico:
(Frito-Lay) snack foods, in which the company enjoys near-total
dominance,'' the magazine says. ``Pepsi-Cola is still second to
Coca-Cola, but last fall Pepsi's Mountain Dew edged out Diet Coke
for third place.''
</P>
<P>
   Enrico's challenge, says Business Week, is to do for Pepsi's
lagging stock what he has done for the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH MENTIONING ...
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet is here to stay, but many investors aren't sure
about some of the companies that inhabit it, says Kiplinger's
Personal Finance (April 11), which identifies companies and mutual
funds its analysts believe will grow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inc. (April), a small-business magazine, looks at ways
enterprising companies can raise money without automatically taking
a trip ``down the much-vaunted venture-capital/IPO route.'' Among
the alternatives are local banks and online investors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
