<HEADER>
A5930 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-03 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TRIED CAMPAIGN REFORM AND FAILED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Judging from my e-mail, I haven't been able to
convince everyone of the need to improve campaign finance laws. But
we can all enjoy the spectacle of our two major presidential
candidates trying to carry the ``reform'' banner.
</P>
<P>
   Any ``reform'' effort obviously will be difficult, and it will
be complicated by the superrich people who can afford to fund their
own campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature once tried to ``even the playing field'' _
as the cliche goes _ between wealthy and nonwealthy candidates. The
law didn't work, but the exercise is worth recounting because it
shows how laws can be ambushed.
</P>
<P>
   The effort stemmed from the 1990 gubernatorial race, in which
Democrat Ann Richards beat Republican Clayton Williams in a
hard-fought campaign. Williams, a West Texas businessman, spent
millions of his own dollars and may have won if he hadn't
repeatedly shot himself in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Among other gaffes, he told several reporters an insensitive
joke about rape, prompting much public outrage. And, further
endearing himself to taxpayers only a few days before the election,
he admitted publicly that he hadn't paid any federal income taxes a
few years earlier because of business losses.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 election occurred as the Legislature was getting a lot
of bad publicity about large lobby expenditures and large ethical
lapses. So there was a major effort in the 1991 legislative session
to enact an ``ethics reform'' law covering special interests'
influences on elections and the lawmaking process.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, who had battled Williams' wealth with some large
campaign contributions from supporters, urged lawmakers to limit
political donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think small,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't say how small, but presumably she meant something
smaller than the $350,000 in contributions and loans she had
received from her biggest money source _ Beaumont trial lawyer
Walter Umphrey and his law firm's political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   Richards also asked the Legislature to ``temper the influence of
personal wealth in campaigns'' by limiting the amount of political
contributions wealthy candidates could use to repay themselves for
their personal expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Bill Clements largely funded his own first successful
race for governor in 1978 but, after taking office, raised enough
money to repay himself from contributors eager to mend fences. Had
he won in 1990, Williams would have been able to do the same thing,
and Richards didn't think that was fair.
</P>
<P>
   Although wealth alone obviously isn't enough to win a
presidential race, as Steve Forbes and Ross Perot have recently
proved, it can be a significant factor in local and statewide
races. And the U.S. Supreme Court, while upholding limits on how
much money a candidate can raise from other people, has ruled that
lawmakers can't limit how much a candidate may spend to get
elected.
</P>
<P>
   So Richards proposed _ and the 1991 Legislature enacted _ an
indirect attack on a candidate's wealth. Lawmakers didn't limit
contributions from special interest groups and other sources, but
they restricted gubernatorial candidates' ability to repay
themselves from campaign donations to $500,000 per election. Other
statewide officeholders were given a $250,000 limit.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics law also imposed some additional lobby reporting
requirements, but, overall, it was pretty weak. It also created the
Texas Ethics Commission to advise state officials and candidates on
do's and don'ts and, occasionally, point out loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, answering a question from a judicial candidate,
the commission found a dandy loophole for the rich. It said the
payback limits didn't apply if a candidate, instead of spending his
own money outright, used his wealth to guarantee bank loans for his
campaign. The candidate could then raise as much money as necessary
to repay the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Millionaire David Dewhurst, who borrowed more than $3 million to
win the land commissioner's office in 1998, could use that
loophole. He hasn't repaid his loans yet, but maybe that's because
land commissioners can't raise money as fast as governors and
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   One legislator filed a bill last year to close the loophole, but
it went nowhere. That kind of ``reform'' apparently isn't in style
with most lawmakers anymore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison can receive email at clay.robison(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
