<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OLDER-WORKERS04-COX     04-03 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-WORKERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLDER WORKERS SHOULD BE ENCOURAGED TO REMAIN, PANEL TOLD
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government and businesses should assist senior
citizens who want to continue working beyond 65, a Senate panel was
told Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Skill training for older workers is not the norm, and senior
citizens in the work force remain under-represented in company
training programs, said Joseph Perkins, president of AARP.
</P>
<P>
   The best way employers could encourage older workers to remain
or re-enter the labor force is to provide appealing part-time
employment opportunities and ``phased retirement,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Phased retirement allows employees to gradually reduce their
work week as they approach retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``With unemployment at record lows and the need for highly
skilled and competent workers at record highs, employers will have
to re-think their attitudes about older workers as well as their
labor practices if they want to encourage good workers to stay on
the job longer or re-enter the marketplace,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens who can only work part-time should receive
pensions and private saving plans such as 401(k)'s, said Sen. Chuck
Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate Special Committee on
Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the labor pool shrinks, and as baby boomers age, we'll see
more creative ways to keep older employees then ever before,'' he
said. ``Customizing retirement arrangements and flexible scheduling
will be the norm. Congress has to respond in kind. We have to make
sure federal laws don't hurt older workers. Our economy depends on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans don't have enough money to retire and have to
work until they are older, the senator added. With that in mind,
Congress should pass laws that encourage retirement savings, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last week voted 422-0 to repeal the Social Security
earnings test, which reduces benefits for workers age 65 through
69. The Senior Citizen Freedom to Work Act is awaiting the
signature of President Clinton, who has promised to approve it. The
law will take effect retroactive to Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repealing the earnings limit was a good start. Next, we have
to help employers accommodate the needs of older workers,''
Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins noted that baby boomers are living longer, healthier
lives, are better educated than their parents, and are used to
having more options with regarding their work and leisure.
</P>
<P>
   A recent AARP study found that older workers continue to be
recognized and valued for having a good work ethic and providing
experience, knowledge and stability in the workplace, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the study's findings, many businesses try to
eliminate their older workers by offering lucrative retirement
packages when they are 62, or by imposing subtle forms of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
