A5933 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AAA-REPAIR-HNS &LR;      04-03 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AAA-REPAIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AAA AFFILIATE SEES BIG DEMAND FOR AUTO SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The concept may seem far-fetched: You're
drinking a mocha and surfing the Internet with your laptop, while
your kids play nearby and somebody changes the oil in your car.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the California State Automobile Association is
offering as it steps into the auto repair business with a chain of
shops catering to everyone from Gen X-ers to parents of young
children to anyone with a high-tech lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've gotten so much accomplished,'' said Barbara
Motton-Sims, who recently visited AAA Car Care Plus in Santa Clara.
``In one stop, I had lunch, had time to finish my Easter cards and
had my car checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   CSAA, the second largest AAA affiliate in the nation with 4
million members and membership revenue approaching $20 million, has
quietly ventured into the car repair business after surveys
indicated its members wanted more than diagnostic clinics and
referrals to AAA-approved garages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to get your car fixed is like going to the dentist,''
said Mark Woods, general manager for CSAA's auto repair line.
``It's not something that's pleasant, but we're trying to change
that here when people bring their cars in.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, CSAA has only the pilot location in Santa Clara. It
opened in February 1999 and serves people from San Jose and
surrounding areas. Another site is under construction in Sacramento
and will open this summer.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 more CSAA garages are being planned in the next four
years in the club's Northern California territory, which extends to
some parts of Nevada and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here for maps and tour books,'' said Pradeep Saraswat,
45, as he munched on a banana nut muffin in the clean,
air-conditioned cafe next to the repair garage. ``My car needed a
25,000-mile service.''
</P>
<P>
   After the facility opened, Saraswat visited the nearby AAA
membership offices and wondered what the new garage was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealers tend to talk you into getting things for your car that
you don't want,`` the Fremont resident said. ``I think AAA won't do
that. The services are also 15 to 20 percent cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Value and quality are what CSAA is aiming for, especially since
many people already trust the brand name, Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can still get evaluations on their vehicles' needs and
select from a menu of minor to major vehicle repairs, smog checks
and oil changes. They also can get their cars washed and detailed.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high demand for auto service, David Whitgob,
chief operating officer of the local affiliate's automotive
operation, doesn't think the new repair chain will affect business
at other repair shops.
</P>
<P>
   When the Santa Clara site opened, CSAA estimated it would
service 35 vehicles a day, but the number jumped to more than 50
with the average driver spending about $100 per visit, Whitgob
said.
</P>
<P>
   The repair shop is usually booked 4 1/2 weeks in advance,
leaving some drivers to look elsewhere. Those who can't be helped
at the site can be referred to AAA-approved garages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then, people will wait,'' Whitgob said. ``They trust the
AAA brand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1802EDT &QL; 
