<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FINANCING MAY BE NEGOTIABLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The majority of the nation's high school seniors find
out this week if the colleges they want to attend want them to
enroll.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the time when they and their parents are told just how
much a higher education sojourn will cost them.
</P>
<P>
   Average college tuition has more than doubled in the past two
decades, while median incomes for families with college-age
children has risen only 22 percent, according to The College Board,
which administers the SAT college entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   During the last school year, $64 billion in financial aid was
distributed nationally, with about 58 percent of it in student
loans.
</P>
<P>
   The increased availability of federal and state education loans
gives many more students the opportunity to attend college. But it
also saddles graduates with debt loads that are often difficult to
manage and pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Before accepting any admissions offers, students should
carefully consider the full financial ramifications of their
college choice.
</P>
<P>
   Students with aspirations of attending law, medical or business
school need to think twice about taking on a lot of debt in their
undergraduate years, because much of their graduate education will
be financed with loans.
</P>
<P>
   Those who plan to pursue fulfilling careers in low-paying
professions, such as education, social services or journalism, also
may have to worry about making enough to keep up with their loan
payments after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   So before you commit to a school, negotiate for the best
financial aid package you can get. Here are some tips on how to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Apply for aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person that I could tell you with absolute assurance
that is not eligible for financial aid is the person who does not
apply,'' says Robert Sheridan, director of scholarships and
financial aid at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   April 1 is the annual priority deadline for mailing in the Free
Application for Federal Student Aid that all colleges require
students seeking aid to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Those who missed it can still apply for financial aid, but the
chances of getting a federal grant to pay for school this year have
declined significantly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Calculate the costs.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost certain no two financial aid offers will look the
same. So, pay close attention to how much in grants and
scholarships the school is giving you vs. how much money you will
have to earn or borrow. The goal, of course, is to get as much free
money as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Also, find out if outside scholarships are used to reduce the
amount the student and family must contribute or if the money will
be used to lessen the school's grant amount.
</P>
<P>
   To help with your dollar and cents breakdown, use the calculator
at www.collegeboard.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a case in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Outline where the shortfalls are. For example, the estimated
transportation budget may not cover a roundtrip airline ticket home
for winter break or the true cost of filling your tank for the
daily commute to school.
</P>
<P>
   You may also want to include better offers from comparable
schools with a note stating your preference for the school you are
negotiating with and your concerns that you will not be able to
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Present all this information in person or by fax or e-mail and
follow up with phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think just saying you're not good at managing money is
enough to get a change made,'' says Ann Wright, vice president for
enrollment at Rice University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And complaining about sticker shock also won't get you more
money.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges consider making adjustments in aid package if something
has happened that significantly alters a family's finances.
Setbacks usually considered are illness, divorce and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges also realize that the federal financial aid form cannot
capture everything relevant to your family's finances. So, inform
your aid officer of any ongoing situations, like caring for an
elderly relative or paying off medical bills, that strain your
family's income.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask, don't demand.
</P>
<P>
   Financial aid maneuvering is not the same as hiring
negotiations. You are not in the position of power in this
situation _ the school is. So, don't make threats or demands.
Polite and diplomatic behavior will get you closer to what you
want.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, most public universities offer the best aid package
they can in the beginning and don't dicker. Many private schools
also have limits on what they will do. But it never hurts to ask.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
