r e BC-FAIRCHILD-PHILIP-SEYM     04-03 2150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-PHILIP-SEYMOUR-HOFFMAN-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF HOFFMAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JULIE L. BELCOVE  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When Philip Seymour Hoffman walks into the greasy spoon near his
West Village apartment, a hat with ear flaps is pulled down low on
his head, a blue muffler up high to his freezing nose, leaving
visible only a narrow strip of skin.
</P>
<P>
   It's the coldest day in New York in three years, and his
dark-framed glasses start to fog up within seconds. With the
sneakers and baggy work pants, he looks a little like the attendant
at your local gas station who always has a friendly wave and a
smile but is kind of scary anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He says hello to the waitress, who's waiting to lock up. Letting
her call it a day, Hoffman leads the way across Eighth Avenue to
another tiny cafe, where he greets the counter man with the same
familiarity he did the waitress. Both treat him like a regular, a
neighborhood guy who appreciates a good slice of apple pie. They
seem genuinely oblivious to the fact that their customer is one of
the fastest rising actors in the business.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Hoffman has made the difficult leap from
anonymous but respected character actor (``Oh yeah, that guy'' in
movies from ``Boogie Nights'' to ``Twister'') to leading man
(``Flawless,'' David Mamet's upcoming ``State and Main'').
</P>
<P>
   With two big movies (``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' and
``Magnolia'') now in theaters _ which together earned him the
National Board of Review's best supporting actor award _ Hoffman
has begun rehearsals for his Broadway debut, in a revival of Sam
Shepard's ``True West,'' which opened in March. This was Shepard's
first day sitting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was f---ing frightening,'' Hoffman admits with no hint of
pretense. The enigmatic playwright's presence isn't the only thing
giving Hoffman a case of the nerves. ``It wouldn't be scary if I
was one of the guys in the town in ``Our Town,'' you know what I
mean?'' he says with a laugh, then digs into that apple pie. ``Then
it would just be kind of fun _ like, I'm on Broadway, let's give it
a go.''
</P>
<P>
   This situation, he says, is more like ``Flawless,'' in which he
played a drag queen opposite Robert De Niro, ``picking the most
difficult situation to jump into new territory.'' He is referring
not just to the emotional intensity of ``True West,'' about two
brothers reunited in their mother's house, but to director Matthew
Warchus' decision to have Hoffman and his co-star, John C. Reilly,
swap parts every three or four performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not our idea,'' Hoffman says. ``In fact, that was one
of the reasons, when they came to me in the first place, I was not
interested. I was like, `I'm not going to do that. That's hokey.'''
</P>
<P>
   But then Reilly, who appeared with him in all three Paul Thomas
Anderson movies _ ``Hard Eight,'' ``Boogie Nights'' and
``Magnolia'' _ talked him into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil's probably the only person whose work I look at and go,
`Aw, man,''' Reilly says. ``It's like, where the hell did he come
up with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Both men agree that they wouldn't have wanted to do the play
with a total stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two actors really have to trust each other,'' Hoffman
says, ``because you're giving up your part to the other person
every few days, then taking it back. It's so intimate what these
actors are doing. It's like trading bodily fluids.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's shed his winter layers, by the way, Hoffman isn't
scary at all. Disheveled, yes, with blond hair sticking out in
every direction, and enough reddish growth on his face to indicate
he's giving his razor a lengthy vacation.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't really resemble any of his extraordinarily diverse
characters _ certainly not Allen, the overweight obscene
phone-caller in ``Happiness,'' or Scotty, the chubby, lovesick
production assistant in ``Boogie Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Hoffman isn't fat. A high-school jock before
discovering acting, he's a husky, powerfully built guy. But he's
also not vain, evidenced by his willingness to pork up to 230 for
slob-loser effect in ``Happiness.'' (Standing 5-feet-10-inches
tall, he says he was a trim 190 for ``State and Main'' but has
since put on 25 pounds because he quit smoking.)
</P>
<P>
   Some in the press, though, have been less than kind about his
physique, which has become a sore spot. Asked if there are any
characters he doesn't think he could play, Hoffman interprets the
question to be about his looks and brings up an unflattering review
of ``Flawless.'' (Overall, though the movie was panned, Hoffman's
reviews were superb.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy started commenting, `Phil's just not right for this
part. He's way too big for the dress he's in,''' he remembers. ``It
was something like that, but it was really kind of cruel and stupid
and just ignorant. You just wanted to find the guy and be like,
`Umm, I'm playing a guy who thinks he's a woman, jackass. That's
the whole f---ing point. What do you think, only skinny men are
these people? Only non-muscular men? Have you walked around Chelsea
lately?'''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that Hoffman is not entirely comfortable in a
profession that has always been _ and always will be _ heavily
based on looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get carried away with it,'' he says. ``Relax. Is the guy
acting well or not? Is she acting well or not? Are you caught up in
the story or not? Pay attention to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality is, Hoffman may not be the gorgeous guy you drool
over from afar, but he's the one you end up falling in love with.
Which may be why David Mamet cast him as the lead in ``State and
Main,'' due out in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really respect David for hiring me, because I don't think I
was the guy most people would think of to play the kind of Jimmy
Stewart role,'' he says, laughing. ``No one told me this, but I
have this feeling that there was somebody cast, and that didn't
work out. It was pretty close to shooting that I got hired _ like
three weeks before shooting _ and it was the lead of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which he describes as being about truth and the battle
not to sell out, stars Hoffman as a beleaguered screenwriter who
comes to a small town in Vermont to shoot his movie and falls in
love with a local woman, played by Mamet's wife, Rebecca Pidgeon.
</P>
<P>
   After some of the extreme characters he's portrayed, Hoffman
welcomed the chance to play an everyman _ and one who gets the
girl. But he insists the part was no less challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romantic leads are really more character roles than
anything,'' he explains. ``They're people falling in love, so just
how glamorous can that be? Think about it: Not knowing what to say,
feeling uncomfortable, feeling awkward _ or feeling completely not
awkward, so therefore you're saying stupid s--t all the time. It's
really kind of a bumbling thing, falling in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is so passionate about what he's saying that it's hard
to figure out where the character ends and he begins. He is cagey
about his personal life, at one point mentioning in passing that he
briefly moved to Los Angeles in his 20s ``for some woman,'' and
otherwise skirting the issue with, ``I take the Fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he returns to the subject on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time it's truly hard to be yourself is when you're
madly in love, obsessively in love,'' he says, ``because you're
really scared that you suck, that they're going to find out that
you suck. It's hard to be comfortable in your own skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the 32-year-old Hoffman is most comfortable is in the
theater. He had his start there in high school, outside of
Rochester, N.Y., after being sidelined with a sports injury. Then
he chose New York University to study drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no desire to do film at all,'' he says. ``I thought it
was silly _ not that film was silly, but that me acting in film was
silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie roles came early on anyway, in ``Scent of a Woman,''
``Nobody's Fool,'' ``The Big Lebowski'' and a couple dozen others,
and Hoffman found himself moving easily between stage and movie
set. He's on the board of the LAByrinth Theatre Co. and received
strong notices last summer for his first directorial effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``No money being made,'' he says of the company, ``and really,
purely, some great stuff being created.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Boogie Nights'' hit theaters in 1997, people had
begun to take notice of him, and then Hoffman auditioned for
``Happiness,'' director Todd Solondz' dark comedy about a group of
miserable New Jerseyites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never met Phil or heard of him,'' Solondz says, ``and was
terribly disappointed to discover that Paul Thomas Anderson had
already discovered him. I wanted to take credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Warchus, in turn, had recently seen ``Happiness'' when
he started looking for two ``chameleon-like actors'' who could do
``True West'' with the chance of transcending the typical
comparisons to the classic team of John Malkovich and Gary Sinise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first person I thought of was Phil,'' he remembers. ``He
is quite extreme without losing truth or plausibility. I think
that's a gift, not a skill.''
</P>
<P>
   John C. Reilly calls him ``a searcher'' and gushes, ``Phil can
make a meal out of the littlest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He points to the scene in ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' in which
Hoffman, playing Matt Damon's uppercrust tormenter, is listening to
records with Jude Law and cuts Damon down with just a withering
stare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could've been one of those light days. But you're just
like, `Goddamn, look at Phil Hoffman.' One scene with no dialog
establishes what the whole character's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman admits that the snobby Freddie Miles ``was exquisitely
fun to play'' _ and not just because it meant six weeks in Rome
with plenty of time for espresso, sightseeing with Cate Blanchett
and her husband and even some Italian lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddie's extraordinarily wealthy, floats around Europe and
hangs out with affluent, well-educated, literary people,'' Hoffman
says. ``I drank beer in the woods. That's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   His slight regional accent has led him to create a different
voice for virtually every character.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's writing parts for redheaded guys who grew up in
Fairport, N.Y.,'' he says. ``It's just not happening. I don't have
(the accent) as much, but my mouth is lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' ``I remember reading it and
just going --'' he breaks off, reshaping his mouth into Freddie's
smirk. ``They sound like they're from England, but they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman used his own voice as the tenderhearted nurse Phil in
``Magnolia,'' which he calls ``one of the best movies I've ever
been in. It's really ballsy stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed and more than a little irritated at the beating
it's taken from some critics (though his reviews have been
characteristically excellent), he adds, ``I really do think in 20
years people are going to talk about `Magnolia' as the movie that
was extraordinarily profound at the time it came out, saying
something about the numbness and cynicism of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he jumps out of his chair to help an elderly woman
and her pushcart into the cafe. When he returns to the table,
Hoffman has one last story to tell. It's about shooting the
surreal, climactic frog scene in ``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what his directors and colleagues have to say about his
talent, Hoffman insists acting comes naturally to no one, certainly
not him. But he's also not a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to act like there are thousands of frogs,'' he
remembers, ``and I have to start the scene crying. I was just fed
up, and I couldn't. I was freaking out.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crew waited at 4 a.m. to get the shot and go home to bed,
Hoffman struggled. Finally, out of pure frustration, he began to
cry. Paul Thomas Anderson called action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not a squirt-in-the-eye kind of guy,'' Hoffman
says. ``Morally, I feel like I'd burst into flames if I did
that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Julie L. Belcove is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
