<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marchers against Confederate flag meet opposition along S.C.
route
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONCKS CORNER, S.C. _ From the tailgate of a Chevy pickup truck,
Sharon Mims taunted Charleston Mayor Joseph Riley, walking briskly
amid 65 marchers protesting the Confederate flag atop the
Statehouse in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the second day of the Charleston-to-Columbia march
organized by Riley, and walkers met their first organized
opposition from flag wavers encamped at crossroads and in driveways
along U.S. 176.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riley, we appreciate you picking this road right in the heart
of the Lowcountry,'' Mims called over the honking of horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Confederate flag is our history,'' said Mims, 38, waving a
bandana of red, white and blue as she sat in the driveway of her
home. ``You do not fold it up and put it away.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a blaring message intended for legislators who today
resume the debate over moving the controversial banner from atop
the nation's last state capital to fly it. The state Legislature
raised the Confederate flag atop the Statehouse in 1962, and a vote
of the Legislature is required to move it.
</P>
<P>
   When the march ends Thursday at the Statehouse, Riley intends to
present to Gov. Jim Hodges, a fellow Democrat, the blue-and-white
state flag being carried by marchers. Flag supporters also plan a
rally in Columbia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, an estimated 300 flag supporters mobilized at
Carnes Crossroads, near Moncks Corner, to await marchers finishing
the first day of their 120-mile trek. But marchers stopped before
reaching the crossroads, setting up Monday's first encounter
between flag supporters and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a peaceful passing, interspersed with an
occasional exchange of remarks amid a heavy police escort for
marchers.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers on motorcycles instructed protesters not to cross
the white line at the edge of the highway, or to extend their
Confederate banners over the road.
</P>
<P>
   The flag supporters vowed to stage protests all the way to
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   As Riley walked, passing thickets of lavender wisteria littered
with beer cans and fast-food wrappers, he said he wouldn't respond
to protesters. ``The meanest thing we can do is to ignore them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day, plainclothes policemen flanked Charleston's
longtime mayor. He wore a bulletproof vest under his green shirt,
after receiving an anonymous handwritten death threat containing
racial slurs. Riley said he was ``confident it came from a
crackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
