<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CBS-MORNING-ART-NYT &LR;      04-03 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-MORNING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING EXPECTATIONS, CBS' `EARLY SHOW' DRAWS POOR RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, CBS invested more than $30 million in revamping its
morning news show. It brought in one of the pre-eminent stars of
morning television, Bryant Gumbel, as well as one of its most
experienced producers, Steve Friedman, and declared that after more
than four decades of futility it was finally making a serious bid
to be competitive in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Five months after Gumbel's highly publicized return to morning
television, accompanied with the fanfare of a glorious new setting
in a studio overlooking Central Park at 59th Street, the futility
has only deepened. Ratings for the new CBS News morning broadcast,
``The Early Show,'' have defied most expectations by decreasing
significantly from its far less costly, less promoted and virtually
unpublicized predecessor, ``CBS This Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter of the new year, which ended last week,
``The Early Show'' was down in every rating category, most
significantly having lost about 440,000 viewers a day from the
totals CBS was attracting in the corresponding period last year,
when Mark McEwen was the show's host.
</P>
<P>
   And this decline has taken place at the same time that both of
CBS' network competitors, NBC's ``Today'' show and ABC's ``Good
Morning America,'' have managed to buck the general trend of
network television by substantially increasing their audiences.
``Today,'' still the dominant show, added almost 400,000 viewers
over last year, while ``Good Morning America'' has added more than
600,000 viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, CBS executives had confidence that their $30
million investment was wisely spent. Andrew Heyward, the president
of CBS News, said at the time: ``I think we're going to do better;
the question is how much. We've got almost nothing but upside.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first-quarter numbers arrived, Heyward said he was
unconcerned. ``Of course we would have preferred to see growth
sooner, but this is a long, difficult process,'' he said. ``I'm in
no way disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   And Friedman, the show's senior executive producer, who twice
earlier in his career held the top producing job at ``Today,''
said, ``If we weren't doing a good show I'd be disappointed.'' He
also said that the decline in overall viewers may be a result of
the show's efforts to be, as he put it, ``younger and edgier.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman cited figures showing that CBS had managed to lower the
median age of its audience from 55.9 last year to 54.1 this year.
That means that most of the viewers the show has lost were older,
Friedman said. He pointed to the advance in the median age for both
the other shows, with ``Today'' moving from 51.2 to 51.5 and ``Good
Morning America'' going from 52.8 to 53.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Early Show'' replaced a hybrid morning show that CBS had
been using, with local stations in most cities producing the first
hour of a morning news show followed by a national program from CBS
News in the second hour. CBS executives said this shift had hurt
them in the ratings. Those local numbers did count nationally
because they contained national commercials. Many of those local
shows had strong followings in their cities, the CBS executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the faltering ratings may also mean that some of the cities
that still do not carry the first hour of ``The Early Show'' may be
more reluctant to do so in the future, Friedman acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   One factor CBS discounted as significant in the show's ratings
struggles is the publicity surrounding the bitter divorce
proceedings between Gumbel and his wife, June. That has been the
subject of much coverage in tabloid newspapers, and some industry
analysts have suggested that it could not help Gumbel, who has
scored poorly among women viewers in some research studies.
Friedman said that he hoped viewers could ``separate people's
private lives from their professional lives.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS had expected that at least ``Good Morning America'' might be
vulnerable, because its two anchors, Diane Sawyer and Charles
Gibson, had agreed to take over the show last January only
temporarily. But now ``Good Morning America'' has solidified its
position as the clear No. 2 show. It has been extremely competitive
with ``Today'' for many of the biggest news interviews, though not
always without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The series of interviews with Elian Gonzalez brought ``Good
Morning America'' both heavy publicity and heavy criticism last
week for the decision to allow a 6-year-old to be interviewed
without parental permission. Still, it now seems that Sawyer and
Gibson have settled in for a long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' has continued to expand what has been the biggest lead
ever in morning television. In the first quarter, the show scored
the widest margin of victory ever in the audience group most sought
by advertisers in the morning, women between the ages of 18 to 49.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman acknowledged that both his competitors had grown even
stronger. He cited Katie Couric's series on colon cancer as being
``amazingly good'' and ``Good Morning America's'' overall
improvement. ``The Early Show'' may have to ``wait until one of the
other guys stumbles'' before it makes significant ratings headway,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
