<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-PARKS-BOS &LR;      04-03 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PARKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE IN THE PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, the National Park Service sat on its hands while
letting the great national parks become noisy sandboxes for
visitors whose enjoyment includes use of internal-combustion
vehicles of one kind or another _ Jet Skis, snowmobiles,
all-terrain vehicles, and airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   A case can be made that these enthusiasts have a right to enjoy
the parks in their way. Apparently, not everyone thinks the
whistling of wind down through the Grand Canyon is music worth
protecting from the drone of sightseeing aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   But that attitude runs smack up against the 1916 act creating
the Park Service. The law says the parks should be run so as to
``leave them unimpaired for the enjoyment of future generations.''
Both present and future generations have their enjoyment impaired
by noisy, polluting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   So the Park Service is to be applauded for proposals announced
last week that would cut down on aircraft at the Grand Canyon and
other parks and ban snowmobiles at Yellowstone. Use of Jet Skis at
Cape Cod National Seashore (where they cannot be launched but can
land at many beaches) and other shore areas will undergo a two-year
review that we hope results in more limits or total bans.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service is also proposing to move against cars
themselves at two of its most popular parks, Yosemite and the Grand
Canyon. Most visitors would leave their cars outside the parks and
use electric buses or light rail. The automobile has been so much a
part of Americans' enjoyment of the parks that limiting its use
will be controversial. But as long as sufficient provision is made
for the elderly and handicapped it is hard to argue against steps
to keep those parks from looking like the Cape's congested Route 6
on a summer Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt points out that the national
parks are not really too crowded with people _ but too much
infrastructure is needed to handle all their cars. With a better
transportation system, more visitors could be absorbed with less
impact. He's right _ even hiking trails in the busy Grand Canyon
can provide magnificent solitude, especially if no airplanes buzz
overhead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
