<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-WEB04-COX     04-03 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-WEB04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web sites and chat rooms are abuzz with Microsoft talk
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Strong graphics and strong feelings for and against
Microsoft were the order of the day on a variety of Web sites and
Internet chat forums in the hours before Monday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judgment Day'' is the huge headline on the MSNBC home page,
where there is a graphic of a gavel coming down on the Windows
logo. MSNBC (www.msnbc.com), a joint venture of Microsoft and NBC,
offers what seems to be balanced coverage including favorable
analyses of the key players at the Justice Department as well as of
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson and of Richard Posner, the judge who
attempted to mediate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a video of Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates. In that
video, Gates says Microsoft ``went the extra mile'' during the four
months of heavy negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the ``picture is worth a thousand words'' category is
CNN Interactive (www.cnn.com). The lead graphic is a Microsoft logo
chopped neatly into even pieces. Before the ruling came out, CNN
wrote extensively and well about how investors were likely to fare
after the fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Time.com offered interesting analysis entitled ``Get Ready for a
Roller Coaster Ride.'' (www.cnn.com/2000/US
/04/03/microsoft43.a.tm/index.html)
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon Monday, CNN's Microsoft message boards were
filled with users arguing about a wide range of topics ranging from
the intricacies of the Microsoft operating system to the best way
to break up the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, when you already know you've been convicted, your
bargaining position is limited,'' one CNN user wrote. ``Microsoft
is in no position to decide whether a breakup is 'extreme' or not.
If it's good enough for Standard Oil, it's good enough for
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some users posting on ABCNews.com's Microsoft chat had
very different opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice to know there are other folks out there who think the
(U.S. Department of Justice) is messing around where they don't
belong _ trying to impede free trade and free markets,'' wrote one
ABCNews reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has done nothing wrong, and by imposing any of the
potential 'remedies' being discussed in the media, the court will
not only hamper the progress of one of America's greatest success
stories but will cause harm to our economy, our markets and our
ability to compete in international markets,'' the reader
commented.
</P>
<P>
   CNet News (www.cnet.com) has a special section, ``Microsoft on
the Ropes,'' complete with a graphic of Gates literally caught in
the wheels of justice. CNet readers in search of the full story can
click on a special CNet feature called ``The Big Picture,'' a
compilation of all the Microsoft stories relating to the case and
its participants. The news updates were focused on the company's
sliding stock price and the potential impact on investors.
</P>
<P>
   Declan McCullough, who moderates his own mailing list of
politics and technology called Politech, takes a look at why
Microsoft would rather fight in Wired magazine's online version.
(www.wired.com/news/print /0,1294,35368,00.html)
</P>
<P>
   The initial findings of the government's case against Microsoft
can be found on the Justice Department's Web site
(usvms.gpo.gov/findingsindex.html). Monday's ruling will be
available at usvms.gpo.gov. Copies of the ruling are also available
for purchase at $12 each and can be ordered online.
</P>
<P>
   The Court TV/Business Week online team
(www.courttv.com/trials/microsoft/primer.html) provide detailed
explanations of the legal precedents that surround the case as well
as the initial suit against Microsoft filed on May 18, 1998
(www.courttv.com/trials /microsoft/legaldocs/dojsuit.html).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
