</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, April 4 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft was found guilty
Monday of violating anti-trust laws much in the manner that the
coal, steel and oil behemoths did at the dawn of the century.
Monday's verdict by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson was the
government's second resounding victory over Microsoft. It had been
regarded as a virtual certainty since Jackson's findings of fact
last Nov. 5 that Microsoft had used its monopoly powers to strangle
competition and hurt consumers. The question now is what remedies
the judge will propose. They could include curbs on Microsoft's
business practices to a basic restructuring of the 25-year-old
company based in the Seattle area. No one expects a final decision
soon on the company's future. Microsoft has vigorously contested
the suit filed by the Justice Department's Anti-trust Division and
19 states all along, and lengthy appeals are likely, perhaps all
the way to the Supreme Court. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT23, and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TALKS (Undated) _ A look at the settlement
negotiations and how far the Justice Department was prepared to go.
By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LEGAL (Washington) _ A legal analysis of Judge
Jackson's decision, looking at any vulnerabilities on appeal. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-WARCRIMES (The Hague, Netherlands) _ U.N. prosecutors
rejoiced as the most senior war crimes suspect to date was arrested
Tuesday in Bosnia and brought for trial, galvanizing their crusade
to bring the architects of the Balkan ``ethnic cleansing''
campaigns to justice. Momcilo Krajisnik, a close ally of former
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, was arrested at his home in
Pale by French NATO troops who witnesses said forced open the door
of his home before dawn. Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency
said Krajisnik was led away in his pajamas and bare feet. (Summary
from wires) By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Japanese politics were thrown into
disarray Monday by the news that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was in
a coma after suffering a stroke on Sunday and was being kept alive
on a respirator. Japan learned of the gravity of Obuchi's condition
early Monday, nearly 36 hours after Obuchi, 62, was hospitalized
early Sunday with complaints of extreme fatigue. The news was
delivered by the prime minister's chief Cabinet secretary, Mikio
Aoki, who called a news conference and announced that he was
temporarily assuming control of the government on the prime
minister's behalf. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-EDUC (Atlanta) _ The states of the Southeast, desperate
for new ways to educate the nation's poorest and worst-performing
students, have begun to play a central role in experimenting with
education theories and school reform plans that are drawing
national attention. Almost every Southern governor is either
hunting for new school money, or trying a different combination of
familiar and occasionally untested ideas for improving student
achievement. Here in Georgia, which has taken the lead this year,
Gov. Roy E. Barnes has pushed through the state legislature a
sweeping overhaul of the education system mandating lower class
sizes, giving bonuses to teachers in good schools, ending all job
protection for teachers, and establishing a new education
bureaucracy to monitor annual testing. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
