<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-WIRELESS04-     04-03 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-WIRELESS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft's exit strategy focuses on wireless software, expert
says
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Microsoft sure hasn't been acting like a company
waiting for the axe of antitrust to fall on its head _ or has it?''
writes Dan Turner in the online magazine ``Feed''
(www.feedmag.com).
</P>
<P>
   Turner compiled a laundry list of deals the company has
announced in the past few weeks including plans to enter the video
game arena, and the spinoff of real estate Web site HomeAdvisor, as
well as the possibility of offering open source code _ the inner
workings of the software _ for Windows CE.
</P>
<P>
   Turner suggests that the combination of Microsoft offering even
some of its code combined with the spinoffs and new ventures
``suggest the company is thinking about _ and moving toward an exit
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of the Justice Department's ruling that Microsoft did
violate U.S. antitrust laws by bullying computer makers and
Internet services to use its browser software, Microsoft's
enthusiasm for new technologies is one way to shift its focus
toward the future and away from its past.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives, interviewed recently at the company's
headquarters in Redmond, Wash., were excited about bringing the
Microsoft Network off desktop computers and onto wireless devices
such as cell phones and Palm Pilots. This has nothing to do with
operating systems and browser wars and everything to do with the
success of Yahoo and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be able to access the Internet anywhere anytime
and from any device,'' said Yusuf Mehdi, director of marketing for
the Microsoft Network. ``We want to be a leader in cellular
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   MSN Mobile is already available on Nextel and Air Touch cellular
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's right up the alley of what Microsoft is all
about,'' said Mehdi.
</P>
<P>
   Medhi said that, after years of trial and error all the way back
to the ill-fated AOL competitor Microsoft tried to launch in 1995,
the company has learned that success depends developing what it
does best: software. In this case, that means building and
developing software for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft seems like a company that can't really
function if it doesn't have some type of competition in its sights.
The competition here is Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Mehdi pointed to Amazon's legendary one-click ordering system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fabulous, but it's only on Amazon.com,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the MSN team is to make the Web experience easier
than Amazon's one-click. It is possible that MSN will devise some
technology that eventually will out-Amazon Amazon. That could
revolutionize the industry _ or lead to another lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's commitment to the Web was underscored in a forceful
way when Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer moved his offices into the MSN
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge vote of confidence,'' Mehdi says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
