<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-COLUMBUS-SHIPS-HNS &LR;      04-03 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBUS-SHIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEP DEBT HAS GROUP FIGHTING TO KEEP REPLICAS OF COLUMBUS FLEET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over second n in Nina) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Tied to a bayfront pier with heavy
ropes, the 70-foot Nina rocks gently in a strong spring wind. Her
colorful Spanish flags snap from atop three stout masts, and the
squat wooden ship seems eager to hoist her sails and head for the
open sea.
</P>
<P>
   And while this 100-ton, oak-and-pine replica of one of the three
ships Christopher Columbus used to discover the New World is
certainly seaworthy, financial troubles have shackled her to the
pier.
</P>
<P>
   The ominous ``No Trespassing'' signs tacked to the Nina's hull
and the padlocked gangway, preventing a continuous stream of
curious visitors from exploring her, hint at her forlorn plight.
And her two sisters in the Columbus fleet, the Pinta and the Santa
Maria, are marooned in a concrete drydock a few blocks down the
waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Far from becoming a lucrative tourist draw, the fleet is mired
in debt, controversy and bitter finger-pointing about the millions
spent to keep the ships afloat. The fleet is closed to tourists
now, as the City Council considers handing the project over to a
new group, since the current operators are insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Spanish government is negotiating to relocate the
Nina, the Pinta and the Santa Maria to the successful Kemah
Waterfront near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   All this is the culmination of a series of problems that began
less than a year after the ships arrived here. A runaway barge
rammed into the Pinta and Santa Maria in April 1994, and the
repairs and relocation of the boats in drydock have had disastrous
results for the Columbus Fleet Association, the nonprofit operators
of the ships.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sending the ships out of state for repairs, the
association decided to build a $3 million drydock next to the
city's history museum and hired Spanish shipwrights to come here to
make the repairs. And while Lloyds of London paid $1.7 million to
cover repairs, the association's lawsuit against the barge owner
was unsuccessful in recovering several millions in revenue lost
during the nearly two years the ships were closed until drydock
construction and repairs were completed in late 1995.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``What happened is the ships were hit and damaged, and they
never recovered,'' said Rick Stryker, director of the Corpus
Christi Museum of Science and History who has served as president
of the fleet association. ``This plaza was built so the ships could
be fixed and to keep the ships alive. And now people are
questioning it out the wazoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say it was a bad business decision. I'd say it was
bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's people who come by here all the time, all the time,
wanting to tour the boat ... You should see the traffic,'' laments
Richard Ingram, a maintenance worker who sweeps up around the pier
on the Corpus Christi bayfront where the Nina is moored. ``But
there never is anybody down here to present it to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Spanish government is working on a deal with
Houston-based Landry's Seafood Restaurants to move the ships to
Kemah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in serious discussions with Landry's about a possible
arrangement for a first-class facility for the display of the
ships,'' said James Goold, a Washington attorney who represents
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   For Corpus Christi, it is a disappointing counterpoint to the
heady expectations expressed by jubilant city leaders in 1992,
after the Spanish government was persuaded to lease the three ships
_ for $1 million with additional payments to come _ to the
nonprofit Columbus Fleet Association as a visitors attraction and
historical exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Corpus Christi was doing an enviable job of
developing its waterfront with top-line tourist attractions linked
to the sea. In 1990, the Texas State Aquarium opened its doors, and
soon after the city won the competition to bring the retired U.S.
Navy aircraft carrier USS Lexington to town as a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Corpus Christi to enter the home port
competition was helped by the tremendous interest shown during the
fleet's 1992 visit to the Americas, part of the international
celebration of the 500th anniversary of Columbus' expedition to the
New World. During a short stay in Corpus Christi, the ships
attracted 108,000 visitors, the largest crowd of any of the stops
at 18 U.S. port cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were first here there was a lot of excitement, but
we somehow lost it,'' said Ray Hernandez, a volunteer on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the lengthy litigation after the barge accident
and other problems, the ships have not lived up to the city's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Columbus ships are really an interesting attraction, and
for whatever reason, they just have not been, so far, the most
actively attended draw we have here,'' observed Tom Utter, Corpus
Christi assistant city manager.
</P>
<P>
   Last week city officials stepped in after the fleet association
declared itself insolvent and laid off its last two workers. And
the City Council voted to give another chance to a newly created
nonprofit group, backed by a group of local business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The new organization, called Grupo Las Carabeles, was given six
months to demonstrate that the ships can pay their own way without
financial help from the city. But the deal requires approval of the
Spanish government _ an action that doesn't seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Durrill, a local beer distributor whose charitable
foundation has donated $1.3 million toward the purchase of the
ships and other expenses, wants to seek a grant to build a marina
next to the city museum at the entrance to the ship channel.
</P>
<P>
   All three ships would be docked there, and the Nina and Pinta,
which are shallow-draft vessels, would sail in Corpus Christi Bay.
The larger Santa Maria would likely be a static display because it
is too large to sail there.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Columbus Fleet Association say the lease
agreement with Spain called for the ships to be sailed. They
complain that the boats were beginning to deteriorate in the museum
drydock, which had become a permanent museum exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan would get the ships in the water where they were
originally intended to be.
</P>
<P>
   All factions agree that the Columbus fleet must be part of an
educational exhibit if the ships are to draw enough tourist revenue
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The city-owned museum already has artifacts and exhibits of
three Spanish treasure ships, which sank off the Texas coast, as
well as artifacts from the French explorer LaSalle's newly
excavated ship, La Belle. More important, the museum has on
permanent loan the 10,000-square-foot ``Seeds of Change'' exhibit
assembled for the Columbus 500th anniversary by the Smithsonian
Institution's Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials, while acknowledging the credentials of
leaders of the nonprofit Grupo Las Carabelas, insist taxpayers will
not bail them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we would love to be able to help a local group, but
the council has made it very clear the city is not willing to
expend taxpayer funds on the ships,'' said Utter, the assistant
city manager.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's council meeting, it also became evident that some
city officials were unclear about financing and other details of
the new group's rescue plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the ninth inning, and I don't know who's on first,''
complained Councilman Mark Scott, as he heard the group outline its
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   On the bayfront, not far from council chambers in City Hall,
tourists eager to tour the Nina say city leaders should find a way
to keep the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corpus is a heck of a seaport,'' said Wyoming retiree Dave
Pomerinke as he photographed the Nina. ``They (the ships) just seem
to fit the town.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
