u e BC-EGYPT-ARCHITECT-ART-2     04-03 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-ARCHITECT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORING A VISIONARY EGYPTIAN IF NOT HIS VISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Greece, Egypt, N.M.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)(DW) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW GOURNA, Egypt _ A half-century ago a quixotic architect
built this village from scratch, or rather from bricks made of
sun-dried mud and straw. That architect, Hassan Fathy, created
vaulted roofs punctured by small openings to direct and cool the
prevailing winds, courtyards to give each owner a ``private piece
of sky,'' crooked streets to emphasize the intimacy of houses,
communal wells to invite neighborly chats.
</P>
<P>
   It was Fathy's grand experiment, the realization of his evolving
philosophy of creating cheap housing for the poor using native
materials, indigenous designs and input from the people who would
live in his buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped that Gourna might just hint at a way to begin a
revived tradition of building, that others might later take up the
experiment, extend it and eventually establish a cultural barricade
to stop the slide into false and meaningless architecture that was
gathering speed in Egypt,'' Fathy wrote in his 1969 memoir of the
project, ``Architecture for the Poor.''
</P>
<P>
   New Gourna today is a sorry epitaph for Fathy, who died in 1989
at 89, an eccentric but at last cherished prophet in his native
Egypt. The village is inhabited by the peasants he at once
romanticized and vainly hoped to transform. But like many of the
modern architects who were influenced by his philosophy, they have
remade his vision on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have plugged up the wind catches, drastically
increasing the indoor temperature in summer and lowering it in
winter. They have covered the courtyards, blocking out the sky.
They have crammed concrete into the windows. Whenever one of the
signature Fathy domes collapses _ as they tend to do from natural
wear and a little help from the villagers _ the residents rebuild
in reinforced concrete, mimicking the anonymous urban housing
blocks Fathy so detested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has changed,'' said Abdel Badawi Mohammed Omar, the
proud owner of a boxy concrete house that he built on the ruins of
an original Fathy structure. ``We wanted something modern, with a
modern look.''
</P>
<P>
   Egypt is now celebrating the 100th anniversary of the birth of
Fathy, its most famous architect, who received the international
Aga Khan Award for Architecture in 1980 in recognition of his
influence on postmodern design but was dismissed in his own country
for most of his career as the architect of mud.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the celebration is at the American University
in Cairo, which received Fathy's voluminous personal archives in
1994. On March 23 the university opened an exhibition in its Rare
Books Library of his architectural drawings, design notes,
furniture, gouaches in the style of Persian miniatures, and
sometimes acerbic accounts of his battles with Egyptian
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   If few of Fathy's altruistic building projects remain, his ideas
have made an indelible impact internationally. They provided an
essential source in the development of vernacular design programs
at institutions like the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Fathy defined the source for creating architecture
that had been untapped before him,'' said Abdelhalim I. Abdelhalim,
a leading Cairo architect who described Fathy as his inspiration
and the reason he returned home to Egypt from Berkeley 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The centennial exhibition, while limited in scope, provides
snapshots of Fathy's life: his formal training in the Beaux-Arts
style, his experiments with building materials like reeds and mud,
his attraction to the simple practicality of Nubian design, and the
domed homes he designed for wealthy clients in Egypt and the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Fathy was born a landowner's son in Alexandria and grew up on
his mother's idealized stories of her youth in the countryside. As
a young man, he once wrote, he dreamed that if he had all the money
in the world, he would do one of two things. He would buy a yacht,
hire an orchestra and sail around the world with friends listening
to Bach, Schumann and Brahms. Or he would build a village where the
fellaheen, or Egyptian peasants, ``would follow the way of life
that I would like them to.''
</P>
<P>
   That fascination with the possibilities of social engineering
through architecture was to define Fathy's career. But he was also
passionate about low-cost housing for the poor, and he realized
early on that he would be fighting a lonely battle against
short-sighted government clerks, politically powerful contractors
and the peasants themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to build a village came in 1945, when the
Egyptian antiquities authorities hired him to create New Gourna
near Luxor in Upper Egypt. The idea was to relocate the settlement
of Gourna, which sat squarely on a network of pharaonic tombs, and
to get Gourna's tomb robbers out of the way of temptation.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than compensating the villagers directly, the authorities
gave the money to Fathy, ensuring that the residents would see him
as little more than an agent of the government bent on forcibly
evicting them from their traditional homes. Instead of
participating in the design of their new homes as Fathy had
envisioned, most of the prospective residents of New Gourna refused
even to talk to him. They sabotaged a system of dikes at the new
site, flooding the unfinished village and damaging the foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the project gave Fathy the chance to test theories that
ran counter to all that was fashionable in architecture at the
time. Instead of the machine as metaphor and the industrial age as
idiom, he sought an integration with nature.
</P>
<P>
   He was fascinated, for instance, by the Nubian custom in Upper
Egypt of orienting rooms according to the position of the sun in
different seasons, so that they would be cool in summer and warm in
winter. In New Gourna he also studied the prevailing winds and
built his houses with funnels that drew air inside and cooled it
over wet charcoal.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted, too, on a village where people would live
according to his personal vision. He built a space to exhibit
crafts, thinking that the relocated peasants would rediscover
long-lost artisanship. Eschewing the idea of running water directly
to each house as too expensive and unsuited to village customs, he
installed neighborhood wells and rhapsodized about the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine a village in Egypt without its
black-robed women,'' he wrote, ``erect as queens, each with her
water jar carried nonchalantly on her head, and it will be a pity
to lose the sight.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end the people of old Gourna could not be persuaded to
move to Fathy's village. (The government to this day is trying with
limited success to bulldoze Gourna out of existence.) The project
was simply abandoned in the upheaval after the 1952 Egyptian
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years squatters took over neglected buildings,
demolished the school to farm the land under it and filled the
crafts hall with trash. With the opening of the Aswan High Dam, the
water table rose, eroding the earthen foundations. The people who
live in New Gourna now say that Fathy's houses do not meet their
needs. They see no charm in communal wells and prefer running
water. Instead of courtyards, they want as many enclosed rooms as
possible to house their extended families. The mud bricks crack in
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few families make do in the original houses. ``We are
poor,'' explained one homeowner, Latafat Omar Ibrahim, ``so we kept
it like Hassan Fathy built it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Fathy understood the utopian nature of his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most poor people envy the rich and try to copy the possessions
of the rich,'' he wrote. ``Therefore when a peasant gets enough
money to build a house, he often builds a copy _ cheaper and
nastier in every way _ of the houses of the local rich, which in
their turn are copied from the villas of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The relentless paving over of farmland and suburban gardens
around Cairo in recent decades stands as further proof of Fathy's
assessment. Unable to build on his New Gourna experience, he left
Egypt in 1957 to work with the Athens firm of Constantine Doxiades,
which was trying to meld aesthetics and environment.
</P>
<P>
   He returned home six years later but was considered a pariah in
a profession that was tied at the time to didactic schools of
modernist thought that identified progress with all that was new,
Western and industrial.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition of Fathy's archives makes his iconoclastic
position clear. It includes his souvenir program from a visit to
Notre Dame du Haut at Ronchamps, France, the masterwork of the
modernist Le Corbusier. On the program is a quotation from Le
Corbusier, ``I wanted to create a place of silence, of peace, of
interior joy.'' Next to the word ``silence'' Fathy had added his
own comment, ``which shouts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the end of the 1960s that Fathy's ideas about
humanizing the housing for the poor began to gain currency
internationally. His book, originally written in the '50s, was
published in English, and his work was showcased at the U.N.
Habitat conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is really most influential for is his attempt to find
a reconciliation of the ideals of modern architecture and the
conditions of the developing world, in particular those of the very
poor,'' said William J. Mitchell, dean of the school of
architecture and planning at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Fathy's only venture in the United States was the 1981
construction of Dar al-Islam, a mosque and housing complex in
Abiquiu, N.M., where he studied native materials and designs for
the domed adobe structures. In his final years he watched as the
superficial elements of his style _ the vaults, the inward-facing
compounds, the domes, the Nubian friezes _ became the leitmotif of
new air-conditioned tourist resorts in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   For a man who valued the authentic above all other artistic
values, it must have been a strange anticlimax. ``He never bought
the aesthetic of the machine or extreme materialism or
functionalism,'' said Abdelhalim. ``He was a man who did not betray
his eyes, what his eyes saw in the truth and power of local
cultures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
