<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAMING-BELL-GTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BELL ATLANTIC AND GTE MERGE, THEY WILL EMERGE AS VERIZON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trying to trade their somewhat musty images for that
of a young technology dynamo, Bell Atlantic and GTE said Monday
that they would call their combined company Verizon after their
merger deal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would create the No. 1 local telephone carrier in the
nation. Executives from both companies said the old names carried
too much baggage from the days of slow-moving communications
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that we need to separate ourselves on a
going-forward basis from the tradition and the limited perspective
that a Bell name assigns to us,'' said Bruce S. Gordon, the Bell
Atlantic executive who is set to become president of the combined
company's retail unit. ``We set out to find a global image and a
high-tech image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be dynamic, cutting-edge, fast, customer-focused,
entrepreneurial, youthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon would not say how much Bell Atlantic was spending to
develop and promote the new brand.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic emerged from the breakup of the old American
Telephone and Telegraph Co. in 1984 as the local phone monopoly for
much of the mid-Atlantic region. Shortly after passage of the
deregulatory Telecommunications Act of 1996, Bell Atlantic agreed
to acquire the Nynex Corp., which served many areas from New York
to Maine. After that deal was completed, the Nynex brand
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The GTE brand has its genesis in 1935, with the organization of
the General Telephone Corp. After that company merged with Sylvania
in 1955, the company became known as General Telephone and
Electric. Not until the 1970s did the company call itself GTE.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of their history, brands like Bell Atlantic and GTE
may seem a bit quaint, especially in the face of companies with
futuristic-sounding names like Cisco and Lucent. After agreeing to
acquire IXC Communications Inc. last year, Cincinnati Bell decided
to rename itself Broadwing.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and GTE said Monday that Verizon was derived from
the word horizon and the Latin word for truth, veritas.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and GTE expect to complete the merger, which was
announced in 1998, by the end of June. The companies announced the
Verizon name Tuesday as Bell Atlantic completed a deal to fold its
United States wireless communications unit into a joint venture
with Vodafone Airtouch PLC of Britain. That venture is to be called
Verizon Wireless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDIES04-     04-03 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDIES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT COULD HAPPEN NEXT TO MICROSOFT?
 &HT;    Eds: Repeating a story first moved for release Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    With COX-MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are seven possible outcomes that could
eventually result from Monday's ruling that Microsoft violated
antitrust laws:
</P>
<P>
   1. Microsoft is split into two or more separate companies. One
of them would market Windows, the firm's flagship product, while
another would sell its suite of applications, such as Word. Yet a
third company might be formed to offer Internet-based content and
services.
</P>
<P>
   2. Microsoft is split into several equal-sized entities,
popularly known as ``Baby Bills'' after chairman Bill Gates.
Initially, at least, each of the newly formed rivals would sell the
same software and products while competing against each other on
price and quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   3. Microsoft is broken up into several firms that target
different market segments. Under this plan, one such successor
company could tailor its products to consumers while another might
focus on large business customers. To ensure uniformity, a separate
company also could be formed to guarantee that divergent flavors of
Windows can still run the same basic applications.
</P>
<P>
   4. Microsoft is required to license Windows to its rivals. These
companies would then be free to market enhanced Windows clones that
would compete against Microsoft's ``classic'' version.
</P>
<P>
   5. Microsoft is required to provide detailed programming
``hooks'' into Windows to help its rivals compete. By opening up
the ``source code,'' they would become free to extend the Windows
operating system into such new areas as ``smart'' browsers, voice
or touch-screen commands, and next-generation audio and video
services.
</P>
<P>
   6. Microsoft is forced to ship a version of Windows that strips
away its built-in Internet browser. It could also be obliged to
offer other Windows versions that feature competing browsers.
</P>
<P>
   7. Microsoft is made to change its business practices. One
possibility: It would be barred from striking exclusive licensing
deals or required to publish a price list for its software and
services that would offer all comers the same deal, calling a halt
to current preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
