<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDIES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT COULD HAPPEN NEXT TO MICROSOFT?
 &HT;    Eds: Repeating a story first moved for release Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    With COX-MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are seven possible outcomes that could
eventually result from Monday's ruling that Microsoft violated
antitrust laws:
</P>
<P>
   1. Microsoft is split into two or more separate companies. One
of them would market Windows, the firm's flagship product, while
another would sell its suite of applications, such as Word. Yet a
third company might be formed to offer Internet-based content and
services.
</P>
<P>
   2. Microsoft is split into several equal-sized entities,
popularly known as ``Baby Bills'' after chairman Bill Gates.
Initially, at least, each of the newly formed rivals would sell the
same software and products while competing against each other on
price and quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   3. Microsoft is broken up into several firms that target
different market segments. Under this plan, one such successor
company could tailor its products to consumers while another might
focus on large business customers. To ensure uniformity, a separate
company also could be formed to guarantee that divergent flavors of
Windows can still run the same basic applications.
</P>
<P>
   4. Microsoft is required to license Windows to its rivals. These
companies would then be free to market enhanced Windows clones that
would compete against Microsoft's ``classic'' version.
</P>
