<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEXICO-TELECOMS-NYT &LR;      04-03 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TELECOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TELECOM GIANT STIFLES U.S. COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ If any company represents the marriage of Mexico
and modern business, it is Telefonos de Mexico, the
telecommunications giant that towers over its industry at home and
is the Mexican stock that Wall Street investors love to own.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was sold by the government a decade ago to a private
sector consortium headed by Carlos Slim Helu, now Latin America's
wealthiest man, Telmex more than any other enterprise has
symbolized Mexico's passage from an inward-looking state-controlled
economy to a thriving globalized free market. And since Telmex,
once a monopoly, was forced to face competition in both long
distance and recently in local service, the government has touted
the opening as an example of its commitment to free trade and
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   But American companies that took Mexico at its word and tried to
challenge Telmex in long distance say they have hit a wall raised
by a powerful conglomerate that presses many lingering monopoly
advantages and subdues the regulators who are supposed to impose
discipline. The clash has forged an improbable alliance between two
of the biggest telephone players in the United States, AT&AMP;T and
MCIWorldcom, which find themselves underdogs in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released on Friday, the U.S. trade representative,
Charlene Barshefsky, said she was ``seriously concerned'' about
what she called regulatory failures in Mexico. She also said Telmex
is inhibiting the creation of competition in the telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Because Telmex is the flagship of Mexico's privatizations, its
apparent reluctance to play on a level field, and the soft-spoken
approach of Mexican regulators to the problem, have cast a shadow
on President Ernesto Zedillo's often stated pledge to honor
open-border economics.
</P>
<P>
   Telmex also has provided a close view of Slim's style of
business. As a financier he is an acknowledged master of bargain
spotting and management turnaround, recently demonstrated by his
purchase of Prodigy, a foundering American Internet service
provider that he transformed in two years into a booming Latin
American Web channel. But his competitors say that in Telmex, the
heart of his empire, Slim has proven to be a hardball tactician who
exploits the edge afforded by the company's holdover monopoly
status.
</P>
<P>
   Telmex officials reject suggestions that the company does not
play fair. They attribute their long-distance competitors'
hardships to inexpert management and inexperience with the Mexican
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made concession after concession to create a healthy
market,'' said Arturo Elias Ayub, a senior Telmex official who is
the company spokesman. ``But they are never happy. They always want
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Telmex and top regulators argue that Mexico has opened up
to telecommunications competition at record speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the progress of regulation and the penetration of the
competitors, our opening compares very favorably with other
countries,'' said Jorge Nicolin, director of the Federal
Telecommunications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a dispute between a leading Mexican company and
foreign interlopers, although it often appears that way in the
Mexican press. While Slim and a small group of Mexican investors
control 51 percent of Telmex, the remainder is evenly divided
between SBC Internationa, a subsidiary of SBC Communications, and
France Telecom. Avantel, MCI Worldcom's long-distance company in
Mexico, is 55 percent-owned by Grupo Financiero Banacci, a large
Mexican bank. AT&AMP;T holds 49 percent its Mexican affiliate Alestra,
while 51 percent is split between Grupo Alfa, a Mexican
manufacturing conglomerate, and Bancomer, another large Mexican
bank.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation is, however, between an alliance of newcomers
to Mexico's telecommunications industry and Slim, an established
figure with a broad hold on Mexican business. Slim's properties now
account for more than half of Mexico's stock market.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of competition, Telmex still has about 75
percent of the $4.4 billion long-distance market while eight
competitors share the rest. Avantel and Alestra each have about 10
percent. Between them, they have invested more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The core dispute is over the cost of linking calls from Telmex's
local lines to the competitors' long-distance networks. The cost of
these connections has continued to rise while the rates companies
charge have slid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught us in a pincer action,'' said Francisco Gil Diaz,
the chief operating officer of Avantel. Both Avantel and Alestra
said they pay about 60 percent of their revenue directly to Telmex.
</P>
<P>
   Connection costs keep rising because they are pegged by
regulation to inflation. In addition, the smaller companies argue
that the rates they pay to Telmex were set at artificially high
levels by regulators. Mexico pledged, when it first set the rules
for long-distance competition, to promptly bring those rates down,
close to the cost of providing the service. That has not happened.
</P>
<P>
   The competitors contend that Telmex has pushed down rates to its
own customers by subsidizing its long-distance service with the
generous cash flow from its local business and with discounts
written into big commercial contracts.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that Telmex has subjected its competitors to
crippling failures of service. Both Avantel and Alestra rely on
Telmex to provide special high-traffic lines that carry Internet
and corporate data. For nine months after July 1999, Telmex stopped
providing these lines, on the grounds that the competitors had
failed to pay back bills. The Mexican regulator took no effective
action. In January, the Federal Communications Commission levied a
$100,000 fine on Telmex based on the damage to customers in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Gil Diaz said, Telmex disconnected 40 of his best
business customers to force Avantel to pay disputed bills. Two
years ago Avantel tried to introduce a service allowing Mexicans to
make long-distance calls from public phones using prepaid cards.
Telmex refused to give Avantel a free number for the calls to go
through.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolin, the regulator, agreed that the competitors' costs are
too high. But he said that his agency had been restrained from
acting by legal challenges from Telmex.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at least a year after he was expected to act, Nicolin
issued special rules governing Telmex, intended to bring down costs
and improve service.
</P>
<P>
   Elias, the spokesman, said Telmex will ``fight very hard'' in
the courts against the regulator's new rules, which were designed
``to tie Telmex's hands and feet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectation when we made our investment was that the
regulator would enforce the regulations,'' said Frank Voytek,
AT&AMP;T's representative on Alestra's board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
