<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-NYT     04-03 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STUMPS FOR CHINESE TRADE PACT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ President Clinton took his lobbying campaign
for a decisive Chinese trade agreement to Silicon Valley on Monday
and rallied the support of high-tech executives as he made the case
that China cannot resist the liberalizing influences of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question China has been trying to crack down on the
Internet,'' Clinton said. ``Good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the Chinese leadership clearly understands how
the Internet age may ``threaten the old order,'' and this is
``proof that we should keep going in this direction, not that we
should hold back.''
</P>
<P>
   As he tries to sway reluctant House members in both parties to
clear the way for China to enter the World Trade Organization,
Clinton received Monday what his aides have been seeking for weeks:
a congressional commitment to hold a vote on a bill granting China
permanent normal trade relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader, said Monday that
the House would take up the legislation by May 29, when the House
breaks for a weeklong recess for Memorial Day. The bill faces
easier prospects of passage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also praised the support of the governors of 40 of the
50 states, plus Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands and American Somoa.
From the high-tech industry, he released a letter from nearly 200
chief executive officers who are backing the trade agreement,
including those at Microsoft, Compaq, Lucent Technologies and
Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   These executives said in a letter to lawmakers that giving China
upgraded trade status is ``the most critical vote you will make in
support of our high technology industries this year.'' The United
States promised to work to grant China permanent trading rights as
part of a sweeping trade accord it negotiated as part of China's
effort to join the trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   White House vote counters say the outcome could still go either
way in the House, depending on the decisions of scores of
uncommitted lawmakers in both parties. To sway them, Clinton is
focusing on Democrats in safe seats who are close to the high-tech
industry and can resist the entreaties of labor unions, many of
which have sharply criticized the trade measure as detrimental to
the interests of American workers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has also sought to generate support among
members of Congress who represent districts with heavy agricultural
interests because the trade accord frees up trade in many farm
products.
</P>
<P>
   A vote in May, backers say, would allow the issue to be decided
before the arguments become bogged down in the national political
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Monday at the Tech Museum of Innovation, Clinton said:
``This vote by Congress is on an agreement that lowers no American
trade barriers, lowers no American tariffs, grants no greater
access to China to any part of the American economy _ nothing, zip,
zilch, nada, zero. On the other hand, Chinese tariffs will fall by
more than half over five years in every sector _ from
telecommunications to automobiles to agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the deal received an import new convert Monday: Rep.
Zoe Lofgren, of San Jose, a leader in the House Democrats' outreach
effort to the burgeoning high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free markets cannot prosper in authoritarian regimes, and in a
global world authoritarian regimes cannot waltz by the impact of
freedom and free markets,'' said Lofgren, who had been undecided on
the issue and was being pressured by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised her statement of support as ``a brave
announcement'' and urged other lawmakers to follow her lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do this, 20 years from now we will wonder why we ever
had a serious debate about it,'' Clinton said. ``If we don't do it,
20 years from now we'll still be kicking ourselves for being so
dumb. And there is no point in my being delicate about this. I
think this is a big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
