<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CENSUS-RESTRUCTURING-     04-03 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RESTRUCTURING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONSERVATIVE GROUP URGES DISMANTLING OF CENSUS BUREAU 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A conservative legal organization urged Congress
Monday to dismantle the U.S. Census Bureau, claiming that the 2000
survey violates people's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the Southeastern Legal Foundation, which won a
Supreme Court decision last year limiting the Census Bureau's use
of statistical sampling, proposed that lawmakers create two
agencies to replace the bureau in order to make the head count
simpler and less invasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government [is] trying to extort very personal information
out of private individuals under the threat of prosecution,''
foundation president Matthew Glavin said at a news conference here.
``We've made the process too complex.''
</P>
<P>
   His group said one new agency would send a postcard to every
household asking only how many people live in that residence. A
second agency would collect more in-depth population data similar
to that in the current 53-question census long form.
</P>
<P>
   Both agencies would report to Congress and neither could
threaten people who fail to respond with prosecution. Currently
those who don't reply face a fine up to $100.
</P>
<P>
   Glavin contended that the single-question postcard census would
accomplish the constitutionally required decennial head count more
accurately and would boost the number of mailed responses.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, 55 percent of Americans had responded to the
census. The bureau has set a minimum goal of 61 percent and a
maximum target of 70 percent before Census officials begin making
house calls to non-respondents on April 22.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 vote early last year, the Supreme Court agreed with the
foundation and ruled against President Clinton's plan to use
statistical sampling to supplement the mailed-response data in
order to reduce the number of citizens undercounted by the Census.
The 1990 census had undercounted 8.4 million people and overcounted
4.4 million others.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sampling to complete the head count, the high court
said, the Census Bureau must count every citizen individually, as
mandated by the Constitution, in apportioning congressional seats
among the states.
</P>
<P>
   However, it also said the statistical method may be used for
other purposes such as allocating billions of federal dollars for
various programs among the states.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based, tax-exempt Southeastern Legal Foundation,
which calls itself a public interest law firm that advocates
limited government, is funded privately by individuals, charitable
foundations and corporations. It has also filed a complaint with
the Arkansas Supreme Court seeking to have Clinton disbarred.
</P>
<P>
   A Census Bureau official, asked for comment on the foundation's
proposals, said all questions on the census form are there for
valid legal reasons and are important in allocating federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Walker, communications director for the House Subcommittee
on the Census, encouraged people to answer every question. He said
the subcommittee will hold hearings in the next couple of months
and may eliminate the long form. But he said the debate over it now
may serve only to diminish mail-in response.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks several Republican leaders have objected to
census questions that some of their constituents had complained
about, particularly those on the long form, which was mailed to one
in six American households.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, said last week he might not answer all of the
questions on the long form if it were mailed to him. And Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., encouraged people to leave
blank any questions they felt invaded their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Glavin said Monday he would fill out only his address and the
number of people living in his home on a census form although he
urged others to answer every question. He explained in an interview
that while he disapproves of the Census Bureau's methods, he
recognizes ``the value of these questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavin blamed Congress for the current privacy controversy,
noting that the lawmakers were given the census questions in 1998
and were asked to list any objections. He noted that Congress
accepted the questionnaire as submitted.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
