u i BC-SAFRICA-RACISM-BOS &LR;      04-03 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-RACISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOVES COME OFF IN DISCUSSION OVER RACISM IN THE MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Six years after the demise of apartheid, South
Africa has begun a long-deferred conversation about race, the issue
that has defined this country for 350 years.
</P>
<P>
   The gloves are off.
</P>
<P>
   Propelling an increasingly rancorous public debate are hearings
on racism in the media that resumed Monday before the South African
Human Rights Commission after a three-week break. On the surface,
the inquiry seems to be an aggressive encroachment on press
freedoms. At one point, editors were threatened with jail time if
they refused to answer questions about what they published, and
some of those who have testified have faced rigorous cross
examination.
</P>
<P>
   But at a deeper level, the hearings reveal the confusion of a
society emerging from a brutal, bigoted past. In the arena of
democracy, where the rules of conduct are no longer color-coded by
the state, relations among black and white South Africans are
becoming muddier and angrier. Once the term for a clearly defined
social illness, ``racism'' now serves as a catch-all invective, a
ready retort in any dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The media hearings are ``symptomatic of the way race operates in
this society: as an object of denial by whites and a bludgeon by
black politicians and interest groups,'' said Steven Friedman,
director of the Center for Policy Studies: ``Whites tend to say,
unless they are pushed, that there is no issue here. Apartheid is
gone, the problem is solved. On the black side, race becomes a way
of achieving other objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's first black president, Nelson Mandela, sought
racial healing in the early years after apartheid. Differences were
played down in an attempt to build a new, national identity based
on a love of land rather than color of skin. But old imbalances
remain: Most blacks live in poverty, while whites still wield
significant influence over business, the civil service, and the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thabo Mbeki, Mandela's successor, ``transformation'' has
replaced ``reconciliation'' as the watchword of government. Blacks
are clamoring for more control across the socioeconomic spectrum,
while whites struggle to retain rank and privilege. This
increasingly charged environment has exacerbated unresolved racial
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Race dominates radio talks shows. It is the focus of a new play
by the Afrikaans poet Antjie Krog that pits a black woman against a
white woman in a bitter dialogue that _ perhaps ominously _ reaches
no conclusion. Affirmative action is altering the workforce and
professional sport. Parliament has held debates on racism. Mbeki
called for a national summit on the issue to be held this year.
</P>
<P>
   With the media hearings, race has become a singular national
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of dissatisfaction about race on all
sides,'' said Njonjo Mue, an advocate of press freedoms at Article
19, an international media watchdog organization in Johannesburg.
``Now everyone gets a chance to talk about it. The media just
reflect what a society is all about, and these are issues that need
to be debated.''
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry into racism in the media started when a black lawyer
took issue in late 1998 with newspaper reports accusing her client
of corruption. She rallied her black colleagues, who lodged a
collective complaint with the Human Rights Commission. The panel
ordered a sweeping investigation of all media and found widespread
evidence supporting the lawyers' claim.
</P>
<P>
   In February, subpoenas were served on more than 30 editors
around the country. The summonses were repealed following an
international outcry, and the panel then ``invited'' editors to
make submissions in public hearings starting last month.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the panel wanted to find out whether and how
journalists, either wittingly or otherwise, perpetuated negative
racial stereotypes. One question prevailed: Do press freedoms
collide with South Africa's constitutional right to human dignity?
</P>
<P>
   Many blacks at the hearings argued that newspapers promote
racism in their depictions of blacks as victims of AIDS, natural
disasters, political violence, and driving accidents. They said the
media reported more corruption stories about blacks than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip van Niekerk, a respected white editor whose weekly
newspaper, the Mail and Guardian, was heavily criticized for its
investigative reports on black politicians, rejected such findings.
``Misuse of `racism' is increasingly dangerous, given that there
are those who define ours as a black government and then use the
emotionality of the term to prevent its critics from speaking
back,'' he told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of the inquiry, the focus has shifted away
from the content of stories to power in newsrooms. Most black
editors, such as Khulu Sibiya of City Press, told the commission,
``the media is predominantly in the hands of whites. This imbalance
must be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   One consensus has emerged: In a society torn apart by race for
centuries, no institution in South Africa is free of racism, and
the media should be more self-critical. As a journalist, the whole
inquiry makes John Battersby, editor of the Sunday Independent,
uncomfortable. But as a South African, he embraces the arrival of a
broader debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace at which we South Africans will be able to
consolidate our new-found democracy will depend to a large degree
on the pace at which we are able to vanquish racism as a
determining factor in our society,'' he said Monday. ``The debate
has highlighted the importance both of eradicating racism and of
the principle of freedom of expression . . . two sides of the same
coin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
