<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA TO SELL ONLINE GAMES ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not wanting to be upstaged by recent
announcements from its bigger rivals, Sega says it will start
selling Internet access this fall for the fast-growing number of
young consumers who play video games online.
</P>
<P>
   The service, at $21.95 a month, is unusual for Sega, which is
primarily a video game company. It will pit Sega against
well-established Internet service providers such as America Online
and Earthlink.
</P>
<P>
   Sega executives say they intend to compete with these
juggernauts by promising fast access and minimal delays in ferrying
signals across the Internet. Both are crucial considerations when
players are reacting to split-second moves by opponents who are
miles away, said Greg Chiemingo, vice president of marketing for
Sega.com, a new division focused solely on the exploding online
game market.
</P>
<P>
   Sega's news comes weeks after its much larger rival, Sony Corp.,
introduced the fast-selling PlayStation2 in Japan, and on the heels
of an announcement Microsoft will enter the market in 2001 with its
X-Box machine.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Sega has struggled in the shadow of Sony, which has
consistently claimed 40 percent or more of the video game market.
By the late 1990s, it looked as if Sega had lost the battle. But
with the introduction of its Dreamcast console last year, Sega grew
its market share from a paltry 0.5 percent to 15 percent, according
to International Data Corp. Sega is looking to preserve that
hard-won market share with its move toward playing games online.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from sales of online games is expected to grow from just
2 percent of the game market today to 24 percent in 2002, according
to Forrester Research. Sega isn't alone: Virtually all game
companies are positioning themselves by developing online games and
building modems into their consoles.
</P>
<P>
   But Sega's unusual tactic _ diving into Internet access _ may
prove risky, said analyst Schelley Olhava, of IDC: ``There are so
many reasons why consumers would choose to go with another service
provider. It's a pretty tough business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
