u v BC-MICROSOFT-ADVISORY-NY     04-03 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the decision in the Microsoft antitrust case. This does
not include any text.
</P>
<P>
   The text of Jackson's ruling is available on the Web site of the
federal court for the District of Columbia: www.dcd.uscourts.gov.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft was found guilty
Monday of violating anti-trust laws much in the manner that the
coal, steel and oil behemoths did at the dawn of the century.
Monday's verdict by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson was the
government's second resounding victory over Microsoft. It had been
regarded as a virtual certainty since Jackson's findings of fact
last Nov. 5 that Microsoft had used its monopoly powers to strangle
competition and hurt consumers. The question now is what remedies
the judge will propose. They could include curbs on Microsoft's
business practices to a basic restructuring of the 25-year-old
company based in the Seattle area. No one expects a final decision
soon on the company's future. Microsoft has vigorously contested
the suit filed by the Justice Department's Anti-trust Division and
19 states all along, and lengthy appeals are likely, perhaps all
the way to the Supreme Court. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT23,29, and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TALKS (Undated) _ A look at the settlement
negotiations and why Microsoft took the positions it did. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LEGAL (Washington) _ A legal analysis of Judge
Jackson's decision, looking at any vulnerabilities on appeal. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACT (San Francisco) _ Industry reaction to the
judge's ruling. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REDMOND (Redmond, Wash.) _ Reaction from Microsoft's
home. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUSTICE (Washington) _ Justice Department's reaction
to the decision. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-NEXT (Undated) _ Now that the verdict is in, the
Microsoft trial shifts to a new phase during which the penalty, or
remedy, will be decided. Judge Jackson has told the litigants that
he wants to hold a separate hearing as part of his deliberations
over a remedy. He hasn't said how it will be structured or when it
will begin. (175 words)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TECH-STOCKS (New York) _ The Nasdaq stock market, the
source of much of the new wealth created during the 1990s, lost a
big chunk of its market capitalization Monday, recording its
fifth-biggest decline ever. Led by Microsoft, which plunged on news
that efforts to resolve the government's antitrust case against the
company had failed, the Nasdaq composite index plummeted 349.15, or
7.6 percent, and closed at 4223.68. The money flooding out of
Internet and technology stocks did not flee the stock market
completely. Instead, it was redirected into high-quality blue chip
stocks, which a number of analysts have said were undervalued. By
Kenneth N. Gilpin. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, this story replaces MARKET.)
</P>
