<HEADER>
A6013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-XCHANGE-STREAM-BOS &LR;      04-03 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XCHANGE-STREAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAME CHANGE, ACQUISITION MARK DAY FOR SOFTWARE MARKETER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rather than place help-wanted ads or hire recruiters,
one software marketing company has decided to expand its work force
by simply buying another firm with related expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Exchange Applications said it is changing its name to
Xchange Inc.; for $52 million in stock, Xchange said, it has also
acquired Knowledge Stream Partners, a private Boston
database-mining company with about $4 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In today's tight job market, Xchange's challenge has been to
find tech-savvy workers who can help it keep pace with its growth.
Last year, sales jumped 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Knowledge Stream was a way to get top talent and added
depth in the company's marketing discipline, said Xchange's chief
executive and founder, Andrew Frawley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a perfect match,'' said Knowledge Stream's
CEO and founder, Robert van der Hooning.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition adds 20 skilled professionals to Xchange's work
force of 300 people, Frawley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relative bargain in the Internet supermarket,'' a
Forrester Research senior analyst, Bob Chatham, said of the
acquisition price. ``They get world-class talent.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when many Nasdaq companies lost heavily, Xchange shares
fell $9.6093 to close at $43.3125, well below a 52-week high of
$74.75 it had reached last week.
</P>
<P>
   Many big corporations collect data about their customers from a
variety of sources, including telemarketing calls, sales purchases,
loyalty programs, and visits to company Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Xchange software lets such clients as Bell Atlantic,
DaimlerChrysler, and Staples Inc. coordinate all this information
and use it to create marketing aimed at individual customers _
based on their expressed preferences and their histories with the
client.
</P>
<P>
   These personalized communications can take the form of e-mail,
direct mail, or telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We generated 400 million e-mails last year,'' Frawley said.
``And we generated 2 billion pieces of direct mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose a consumer buys a printer from Staples, and six months
later a search of the Staples database shows that the customer
hasn't bought any toner or paper.
</P>
<P>
   Xchange's software would assume the customer is buying such
products elsewhere and might send e-mail with a $10 discount on
toner, Frawley said.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose the same customer visits the Staples.com Web site;
Xchange software might instantly recognize the customer, and the
coupon for toner might appear as a banner ad on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Many firms offer similar features, but only Xchange has a full
menu of services that let clients do personalized marketing _ both
online and offline _ and track results, Frawley said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge Stream's specialty is using statistical models to make
real-time predictions about a consumer's buying patterns, based on
past dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with such software and expertise, Xchange clients can
``avoid the spam syndrome'' that results when customers are
bombarded with unwanted e-mail, Chatham said. Xchange enables
clients to ``send the right e-mail to the right person with the
right offer at the right time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1994, Frawley's company went public in late 1998. It
earned $1.1 million last year, on revenue of $43.3 million. If not
for a 1999 acquisition, profits would have equalled 7 percent of
revenue, Frawley said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Xchange announced an alliance with Engage
Technologies Inc., a CMGI Inc. company in Andover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
