<SLUG> BC-HERALD-TRIB-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNATIUS NAMED EXECUTIVE EDITOR OF INTERNATIONAL HERALD TRIBUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Ignatius, a columnist and editor at The Washington Post,
was named Monday as the executive editor of The International
Herald Tribune. He will succeed Michael Getler in September, when
Getler's term expires, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Editing a global newspaper in the age of globalization is the
ultimate challenge,'' said Ignatius, 49, who has worked at the Post
since 1986, overseeing business coverage as well as serving as
foreign editor and editor of the Sunday opinion section.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing The International Herald Tribune ``is a
combination of preserving the editorial excellence and changing
enough so we're changing with the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, which is based in Paris, is owned jointly by The
New York Times and The Washington Post and is printed in 19 cities.
</P>
<P>
   While the newspaper, which was founded in 1887, has long served
as a mainstay for Americans staying or living abroad, it faces keen
competition from The Wall Street Journal and The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   The International Herald Tribune, which uses stories from its
two owners as well as staff reports, has the advantage of having a
wider focus than its competitors, which are primarily business
publications, Ignatius said. ``We're in a position to see the world
whole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ignatius said he planned to work closely with Peter C. Goldmark
Jr., the newspaper's chairman and chief executive, to examine
Internet projects and other business ventures the company might be
able to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   At The Washington Post, Ignatius is an associate editor and
op-ed columnist, writing mostly about business and technology twice
a week. He said he hoped to continue to write a column in his new
position.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming a columnist last year, Ignatius served as the
Post's assistant managing editor in charge of business news for six
years. He was the foreign editor from 1990-92, and edited the
Outlook section, covering politics, economics, foreign policy and
intellectual trends from 1986-90.
</P>
<P>
   Ignatius also spent 10 years as a reporter for The Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
