<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-PILOTS-STORMS-BOS &LR;      04-03 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOTS-STORMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORMS DON'T DETER PILOTS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commercial pilots are far more likely to fly into severe
thunderstorms than aviation officials previously thought _ and the
closer the jet is to the airport, the less likely the pilot is to
change course, an MIT study has found.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms are breeding grounds for wind shear, a sudden and
dangerous burst of wind. Wind shear has been blamed for many
aviation accidents, including the crash-landings of US Air Flight
1016 in Charlotte, N.C., in 1994, killing 37 people, and Delta Air
Lines Flight 191 at Dallas-Fort Worth on Aug. 2, 1985, killing 137.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised to find that pilots were penetrating Level
3, Level 4, and Level 5 storms,'' coauthor Dale A. Rhoda said
Monday. In a Level 3 storm, rainfall is between 1.1 inches and 2.2
inches per hour; in a Level 5 storm, between 4.5 and 7.1 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda authored the report, done at MIT's Lincoln Laboratory,
with Margot Pawlak. It examined weather in the Dallas-Fort Worth
and Love Field approach areas and found that in 60 hours of stormy
weather in spring and summer 1997, there were 2,000 approaches to
the airports. In two-thirds of them, the pilots chose to fly
through the severe weather. And the closer to the airport the
planes flew, the less likley the pilots were to alter course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data show very little variation in pilots' behavior near
the destination airport; nearly all of the encounters within 20-30
kilometers of the airport resulted in penetrations,'' the report
states.
</P>
<P>
   But the closer a plane is to an airport, the lower its altitude
is _ and the more vulnerable it is to wind shear.
</P>
<P>
   In each case studied, though, the plane landed safely without
injuries or other incidents.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the study found, pilots are a bit like sheep:
If one plane flies through a thunderstorm instead of around it, the
plane behind it is likely to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Rhoda said, is that pilots on approach and air
traffic controllers are all on the same radio frequency. ``The
report from the preceding pilot, who has the same concerns and
sensitivities as you, is an additional piece of valuable
information,'' Rhoda said. ``It is very current, one of the most
current pieces of information they have. The only trouble is that
weather can change in the two or three minutes between consecutive
aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both the Delta and US Air flights that crashed were
following planes that had taken off or landed safely.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that pilots were less likley to change
course at night or if they had spent more time flying to the
destination than had been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Air Line Pilots Association were
unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6043 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-TERM-LIMITS-ART-2TAKE     04-03 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERM-LIMITS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERM-LIMITED LAWMAKERS SCRAMBLE FOR RACES TO RUN IN
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Calif., Ohio, Mo., Del., Colo., Mont.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT33 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Fla. _ For nearly two decades, Elaine Bloom has been
a fixture in the Florida House of Representatives, an outspoken
Democrat who has served at various times as deputy majority leader,
speaker pro tem, and chairwoman of the health and tourism
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 62, she is running an uphill campaign for Congress
against a popular 10-term Republican incumbent, E. Clay Shaw Jr.,
in what promises to be one of the most expensive House races in the
country this year. Why would she relinquish a position of stature
she loves in Tallahassee for a long shot at a seat on a back bench
in Washington, a thousand miles from her home and family?
</P>
<P>
   Two words: term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Like 17 other states, Florida placed a limit in the early 1990s
on the number of years that legislators and many other state
officials could serve.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in dozens of places from coast to coast, politicians
like Bloom who are prohibited from running for re-election are
campaigning instead for higher office against prominent incumbents.
It is a consequence that few of the advocates foresaw when the
term-limit measures were enacted. And it has created many more
compelling races for Congress than might otherwise have been
expected.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for instance, a state senator knocked off an
incumbent congressman in the Democratic primary last month, and
several other state legislators are competing in congressional
races. In Ohio, two of the leading members of the Legislature
competed against each other in the Republican primary for a
congressional seat in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom typifies the situation. ``I have been an insider,'' she
said as she drove from a lunch at a synagogue in North Miami Beach
to the police station here in Hollywood, just north of Fort
Lauderdale, where she spoke to the officers. ``I love the
Legislature. If it were not for term limits, I probably would
continue where I am. It would be the easiest thing to do. But
that's not possible now.''
</P>
<P>
   In some states, like California and Colorado, the first impact
of term-limit laws was felt in 1998. In others like Florida and
Ohio, eight-year limits were enacted in 1992, and the first effect
is being felt this year.
</P>
<P>
   In California this month, state Sen. Hilda L. Solis soundly
defeated Rep. Matthew G. Martinez, who was running for his 10th
term, in the Democratic primary for a safe Democratic seat in an
eastern suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that what motivated her was term limits,''
said Allan E. Hoffenblum, publisher of the nonpartisan California
Target Book, which handicaps political races in the state. ``She
was looking for a long-term career.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, there are only 40 state senators and 80 seats in
the Assembly, compared with 52 congressional seats from California
out of a total of 435 in the House of Representatives. That means
state senators represent more people and generally have
considerably more influence than all but the most senior members of
Congress. And in the Assembly, positions of authority are reached
much more quickly than they are in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in his right gourd would leave Sacramento and run for
Congress if not for term limits,'' Hoffenblum said. ``It's 3,000
miles away, and it's awfully hard for a member of Congress to have
any visibility in California.''
</P>
<P>
   But with term limits in place, another Democratic state senator,
Adam Schiff, is challenging Rep. James E. Rogan, a Republican, in
the district that includes Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, a term-limited Democratic assemblywoman, Susan
Davis, is running against Rep. Brian P. Bilbray, and in a district
west of San Jose, a term-limited Republican assemblyman, Jim
Cunneen, is running for an open seat in the House.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, there are no term limits on the state level, but
New York City officials can serve no more than eight years. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who cannot run for a third term, is running for
the U.S. Senate. Also, several City Council members are running for
higher office.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, two legislators about to lose their seats to the
eight-year limit _ Pat Tiberi, majority leader of the Ohio House,
and state Sen. Eugene Watts _ competed this month in a rousing
Republican primary to replace Rep. John R. Kasich, who is retiring
from Congress. Tiberi (pronounced TEE-berry) won.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich himself is something of a victim of term limits. The
Supreme Court ruled in 1995 that states could not apply limits to
the terms of members of Congress. But the Republican Party in the
House decreed that its members could sit no more than six years as
committee chairmen. Kasich's term as chairman of the Budget
Committee is up after this year, clearly a reason he is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, another state where term limits are having an effect
for the first time this year, three friends and colleagues who are
unable to run for re-election _ Attorney General Joseph R. Mazurek,
Auditor Mark O'Keefe and Secretary of State Mike Cooney _ are
campaigning against one another for the Democratic nomination for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Two Democratic governors who cannot run for re-election are
challenging Republican senators, setting up a couple of tight
Senate races.In Delaware, Gov. Thomas R. Carper is running against
Sen. William V. Roth Jr., and in Missouri, Gov. Mel Carnahan is
challenging Sen. John Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There may be more good races for Congress here in Florida as a
result of term limits than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bloom, state Sen. Patsy Kurth, a Democrat, is
running against a three-term Republican representative, Dave
Weldon, in an East Coast district that includes Melbourne and Vero
Beach. In Orlando, Linda Chapin, a Democrat who has completed the
eight years she is allowed to serve as chairwoman of the Orange
County Commission, a powerful position equivalent to mayor of a
large city, is running for the open seat now held by Rep. Bill
McCollum, a Republican who is running for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are favored to hold all three of these seats. But
politicians in both parties give each of the Democratic women a
strong chance to pull an upset.
</P>
<P>
   None more so than Elaine Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that is because the voters in the 22nd congressional
district _a sliver 90 miles long and rarely more than a couple
miles wide along the Atlantic Ocean from Miami Beach to north of
West Palm Beach _ vote solidly Democratic except for their support
for Shaw, who has rarely had a consequential opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton carried the district handily in 1992 and 1996. In
1998, Buddy MacKay, the Democratic candidate for governor, won 54
percent of the vote in the district when he lost statewide to Jeb
Bush, 55 percent to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important is Bloom's ability to raise a prodigious sum
of money in one of the most expensive districts in the country to
run in.
</P>
<P>
   So far, records show, she has raised $1 million, and she says
she intends to raise another $1 million before Election Day. These
sums may be necessary because just to run a television advertising
campaign the last three weeks before the November election will
cost more than $850,000, Bloom's campaign manager, Jeffrey Garcia,
said.
</P>
<P>
   She raised more than $250,000 for her campaign chest at a
fund-raiser last month that Clinton attended. It has been his only
appearance so far to raise money for a Democratic challenger for
Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   The president was repaying a political debt. In 1991, Bloom was
one of the first elected officials in the country to endorse his
presidential candidacy. At the fund-raiser here, the president
said, ``Elaine was there for me when only my mother thought I could
be elected.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shaw, moderate in temperament and skilled as a lawmaker, is
a formidable opponent. He has held the seat easily for 20 years.
There is a possibility that if he wins re-election, he will become
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee. And he will doubtless
match Bloom dollar for dollar.
</P>
<P>
   He was chief sponsor in 1996 of the law that ended the old
welfare system. And he is a main sponsor this year of the measure
to allow Social Security recipients 65 and older to earn as much
money as they want without losing benefits. That legislation is
especially popular here, where one-third of the residents are over
65, the highest proportion of any district in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good,'' Shaw, 60, said in an interview. ``Our
polls are strong, and we are definitely ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, shortly after Republicans won control of the
House, Shaw voted in favor of a constitutional amendment imposing
term limits on members of Congress _ a proposal that fell well
short of the two-thirds majority needed for approval. Now, he said,
after watching what has happened in Tallahassee, he has changed his
mind on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the next Florida Legislature is going to miss a lot of
experienced legislators,'' he said. ``A lot of us may look back and
think it's not a very good idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
