<HEADER>
A6049 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FREEDOM-SALE-BOS &LR;      04-03 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM SECURITIES SEEKS $25-A-SHARE OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Freedom Securities Corp. would sell itself if a buyer
came forward with $25 a share, people close to the brokerage and
investment firm say.
</P>
<P>
   Three years since Freedom's management-led buyout from John
Hancock Financial Services, insiders are tired of waiting for their
big payoff, former employees say. Freedom's shares, even after
surging nearly 40 percent since Jan. 1, are at $15.625 _ 22 percent
below their IPO price of two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston Financial Corp. is said to have offered as much as
$19 a share for Freedom, sources say, but those talks appear not to
have moved far.
</P>
<P>
   For Fleet, such a purchase would mean adding high-end brokers to
its current Quick &AMP; Reilly discount brokerage arm and its
Suretrade.com online trading site. Brokers could help sell Fleet's
mutual funds. It's less clear how Tucker Cleary's (formerly Tucker
Anthony Inc.) investment banking and research capabilities would
fit with the larger Robertson Stephens, which Fleet gained in its
BankBoston buyout.
</P>
<P>
   John Goldsmith, Freedom's chief executive, said no FleetBoston
offer was presented to him. As for whether the brokerage and
investment firm, which owns Tucker, of Boston, would sell for a $10
premium over its current share price, Goldsmith said, ``It's like
asking what would you do if someone put a gun to your head. You
don't know until it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence of stress at the company. In the Freedom
Capital division, which manages money for pension funds and for
individuals, a $100 million fund-of-funds has been quietly shut
down. The company had tried to sell the funds, which are run by
several portfolio managers, but when the sale fell apart, it simply
decided to fold the operation, people close to the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   At least six employees have left Freedom as a result of the fund
closure, and the assets are to be returned to the investors.
Brokers who sold the fund say they have been left in the lurch.
Goldsmith deferred questions about the fund to the unit's chief,
Dexter Dodge, who could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   There have been talks about changing Freedom's name to Tucker
Cleary, after its best-known unit and biggest revenue producer.
Freedom's stock is not widely followed on Wall Street, and a string
of small acquisitions has not raised its profile.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom's revenue rose 26 percent last year, to $553.3 million.
Net income rose 16 percent to $29.1 million, or $1.39 per share.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Freedom's stock has lagged in part due to unlucky
timing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a growing business, investors have shunned most
financial stocks for the past year, as high-tech stocks grabbed the
spotlight. And Freedom missed the window of opportunity in 1997 and
1998 when banks were scooping up regional brokers for big prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hottest candidates have been acquired,'' observed Dennis
Gallant, a consultant with Cerulli Associates, a Boston firm that
researches financial firms. And the rise of online brokerage hasn't
helped regional firms like Freedom, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith countered that Freedom has online trading
capabilities, but its wealthy clientele prefer to deal with
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's ever going to be a big part of our
business,'' Goldsmith said. ``We are very focused on the high- end,
touchy-feely, end of the business, people who want to talk to
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goldsmith and his high-profile backers at the Boston buyout
firm of Thomas H. Lee Co. didn't get into the brokerage business to
see their stakes grow so modestly. There is a clear willingness to
sell the company if an attractive offer comes along, according to
people close to the upper ranks at Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Top brass and Lee are not underwater: Their shares were valued
at about $5.50 each before the April 1998 IPO, sources said. But
employees and outsiders who invested when the shares went public
have reaped no profits yet.
</P>
<P>
   Lee owns 22.5 percent of Freedom's shares. Other top holders
include Wellington Management of Boston, with a 4.2 percent stake,
and Dimensional Fund Advisors of Santa Monica, Calif., with a 3.3
percent stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
