<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6050 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-CHINA-NAT     04-03 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHINA-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  MASS. COMPANIES RALLY FOR CHINA TRADE BILL
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Canizares
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 3 - Arguing that China's one billion-member
market represents an untapped gold mine for New England high-tech
companies, Massachusetts businesses are joining a push to open
permanent free trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that if a trade agreement is passed and China joins
the (World Trade Organization), Chinese purchases of Massachusetts
high-tech equipment will skyrocket,'' said Jim Klocke, director of
government affairs for the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber of commerce is one of three hundred other industry
leaders gathering in Washington today to rally support for
legislation that would allow U.S. companies to tap China's massive
market and, supporters say, help improve the country's business and
labor standards after China's expected entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. businesses claim if Congress fails to pass the legislation,
China's entry to the WTO -- expected to be approved by the
international organization as early as this summer -- would open
the market to countries besides the United States.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made the trade agreement a top priority
and is aggressively lobbying members of Congress to vote on the
bill by Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Democratic Leadership Council in San Jose,
Calif., yesterday, Clinton unveiled a letter endorsed by CEOs of
nearly 200 high-tech companies supporting the legislation, pending
for a vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The letter also includes signatures from 40 governors, including
Gov. Paul Cellucci, who returned yesterday from a two-week trade
mission to China.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Massachusetts exported $366 million in goods to
China, up 15.4 percent from 1998, according to the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's chamber of commerce maintains that if China joins the
WTO and the U.S. passes permanent trade relations, high-tech
companies and financial institutions would be the most immediate
beneficiaries, Klocke said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' exports to mainland China of scientific
instruments, electronic hardware and other high-tech goods - which
totaled $114 million in 1997 -- could grow by a factor of eight in
coming years, Klocke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally it's a concern that if we don't do it, we stand to
lose,'' said Savage Deirdre W. Savage, vice president and general
counsel of the New England Council, which represents businesses,
academic, health and financial institutions in the region and is
attending today's event. ``We believe that by having American
companies in place (in China) it can only lead to liberalization of
the whole society.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies also maintain that China's entry to the WTO would
force the country to drop non-tariff trade barriers that deter
foreign companies from entering the market.
</P>
<P>
   China currently places strict restrictions on sales of
telecommunications services. Another rule bars foreign banks from
opening branches outside of a handful of major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Haemonetics Corp., a manufacturer of automated blood processing
equipment in Braintree that is attending the rally, hopes China's
WTO membership and U.S. businesses' presence in China's market
would nudge the country to comply with business practices and
international laws, such as rules to protect intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   This would make business planning more reliable for Haemonetics,
which conducts one-third of its sales overseas, and projects its
sales to China will grow to $30 million, said Lisa Lopez, the
firm's vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Lopez said, the lack of transparency in China
makes its trade and licensing restrictions seem like ``state
secrets'' to U.S. and other foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton's bill faces an uphill battle in Congress,
especially among Democrats, who are under strong pressure from
labor unions to vote it down on the grounds that it limits the
United States from being able to influence China's human rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts lawmakers are either opposed to, or undecided on,
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is giving China free reign with no checks or
balances,'' said Massachusetts AFL-CIO Secretary Treasurer Kathleen
Casavant. ``If we do grant them permanent trade status, it's
basically letting them do what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an annual review, Congress has granted China normal trade
status every year since 1980, and conducts over $14 billion in
trade each year. Such a review would be made unnecessary under the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts AFL-CIO is waging its own lobbying campaign in
Washington, and will send between 400 to 500 labor leaders from the
state to join what they hope will be 10,000 unionists from around
country on April 12 to fight against the China bill and
international trade organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really up in arms on this,'' Casavant said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
