<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MARKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ LOSES 350 POINTS IN MICROSOFT AFTERMATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite index plummeted nearly 350 points Monday,
the biggest point decline in its 29-year history, as Microsoft
Corp.'s failed settlement talks in the federal antitrust case
accelerated a sell-off that began last week and has clobbered most
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors fleeing tech stocks did not leave the stock market
entirely. Instead, they sent a deluge of money into retail,
financial, and other stocks that comprise the Dow Jones industrial
average, which climbed 300.01 points. The Dow's sharp rise
continued to lift an index that has gained 15 percent from its
recent low just over a month ago. The Dow index closed at
11,221.93.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's descent started as the market opened, in reaction
to news over the weekend that the federal government and Microsoft
had reached an impasse. Anticipation of a harsh court ruling
against the world's biggest software company in the government's
antitrust case sent its stock down $15.375 a share, to $90.875.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq losses amounted to a 7.63 percent decline, the
index's fifth worst ever, in percentage terms _ and its toughest
day since Russia's financial crisis sent tremors through the world
markets in the roiling summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's decline compounded a correction last week. The
index _ which leaped through the 5000 ceiling earlier this year _
came to rest at 4223.77.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got killed,'' Mark Minervini, chief investment strategist
for Quantech Research Group in Connecticut. ``The Nasdaq right now
is a dangerous place to be, and I'd be very cautious in that area
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq's 349.06-point drop exceeded the second-worst day on
record _ Jan. 4 _ by 120 points. The precipitous drop concentrated
its biggest losses to small technology companies more vulnerable to
a Nasdaq decline. By contrast, many computer giants withstood the
index's drop _ Hewlett-Package Co. and Hopkinton-based EMC Corp.
were unchanged _ and IBM Corp. actually rose $3.625 a share, to
$122.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has the power to pull down the Nasdaq, because it is
one of the biggest issues in an index that gives more weight to
member companies with the largest market capitalization. Cisco
Systems Inc. recently passed Microsoft as the company with the
largest market value on the Nasdaq Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, though a Nasdaq-listed company, is also one of the
companies that make up the Dow average of 30 industrials. But, a
runup in a host of old-line companies enabled the Dow to counteract
the downdraft from technology. American Express rose $6.5625 a
share, to $155.50. Wal-Mart Stores Inc. gained $4.6875, closing at
$61.1875 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's decline, said Marshall Acuff of Salomon Smith
Barney, was a catalyst for closing the gap between the overpriced
Nasdaq and the slower-moving Dow. The Dow so far this year is down
2.4 percent; the Nasdaq is up 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you got today are growth investors who said we'd better
put money in health care, consumer staples, and financials,'' Acuff
said. He predicted Microsoft investors may continue to sell their
shares.
</P>
<P>
   But, Microsoft, which sells the Windows operating system seen on
most company and home desktop computers, ultimately may recover
from yet another punch in its lengthy legal match with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Irrevocable damage has already been done to hundreds of smaller
companies that may be forced to scrap plans to raise capital in the
stock market to finance their growth, investment experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology IPO window, which was wide enough to drive two
semitrucks through a week ago, is now closed _ and closed until
further notice,'' said James Weiss, head of equities for State
Street Research &AMP; Management Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Investors stampeded out of small companies, many of which have
been fair game for speculative buying that has sent stocks to
dizzying heights.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of high-flying Akamai Technologies Inc. lost more than
a third of its value, falling $41.81 a share, to $119. Sycamore
Networks Inc. slid $27.9375 a share, to $101.0625, and Navisite
Inc. lost $26 a share, closing at $95.75.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation over the fallout of Microsoft's antitrust battle
with the government has added to the Nasdaq's volatility, which has
experienced wider and wider swings in recent months and is
especially troubling for small tech companies. Portfolio managers
said the index is expected to be choppy for days, even weeks, and
it may fall further Tuesday as details of the ruling are pored over
by analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The wording of Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's finding was
harsh, saying that Microsoft unlawfully ``maintained its monopoly
power by anticompetitive means and attempted to monopolize the Web
browser market'' in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   Some investment experts argued the decision had very little
impact on the Nasdaq, which was destined to continue a decline from
highs that a growing contingent on Wall Street believes is
unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nasdaq would've gone down without the Microsoft'' events, said
Lawrence Horwitz, an economist with Primark Decision Economics in
Boston. ``There's still a shift going on toward so-called value
stocks that are not nearly as expensive and where there are actual
earnings,'' Horwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft only added to the bad environment, he said. ``People
are quite worried whatever decision comes down today, and in future
months, that Microsoft's value will be eroded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
