<HEADLINE>
FOLLOW THESE SIMPLE STEPS TO FIX OSCARS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Maybe I shouldn't complain about the length and the
ponderous pacing of the Oscars telecast. After all, I got paid to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from some readers' comments _ ``awful,''
``absolutely the worst,'' ``a rerun of ``The X-Files'' was far
better viewing'' _ maybe I should. (And these people watched for
free.)
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, I have a few suggestions for next year's show,
humbly submitted.
</P>
<P>
   First, rehire Billy Crystal. His musical tribute to the Best
Picture nominees always goes on too long and his hero worship of
Jack Nicholson is a pain, but when they drop him into films, it's
always entertaining, and his jokes usually hit the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Next, eliminate more minor awards from the telecast.
Sound-effects editing is crucial to a picture, but frankly, who
cares who does it best?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, try this: Lose the filler, complete the show in two
hours and immediately broadcast the Best Picture winner.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone would watch, and even with a long movie, we'd still be
done in time for the news.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what do I know? Oscar ratings were up over last
year, and it was the most-watched show of the week. A lot of
gluttons for punishment out there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If this is the end for ``Sports Night,'' it's going out in
style.
</P>
<P>
   Inconsistency has been a theme this season, whether in the
quality of the writing (creator Aaron Sorkin's attention has been
divided by his other excellent show, ``The West Win''g) or simply
its hide-and-seek spot on the schedule (ABC routinely yanked it
during sweeps ratings periods).
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night's show was a return to ``Sports Night'''s
goulash-of-a-plot form, a brilliant episode dealing with budget
cuts, possible layoffs, romantic headaches and _ improbably but
absolutely winningly _ Passover. Hints at the show's presumably
impending demise popped up everywhere, yet were so perfectly
inserted that the effect was more heartbreaking than obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It comes down to this: ``Action'' is dead. ``Freaks and Geeks''
sleeps with the Nielsen fishes. Can't ABC leave viewers with one
show that prizes quality over quantity and makes a viewer feel cool
for liking it to boot? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Discovery has commissioned a sequel to its ``Raising the
Mammoth,'' the highest-rated cable documentary ever.
</P>
<P>
   What is it going to do? Bury it again? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, shut my mouth. After complaining that ``WWF Smackdown!''
is all UPN cares about, word arrives of a pilot called ``I Spike,''
a show about female FBI agents who go undercover as, ahem,
volleyball players. Another show in the works is called ``Hip-Hop
Bounty Hunters,'' about ... well, guess.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Let's add one more Oscar-show suggestion: Let UPN broadcast
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
