<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HURRICANE HUGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ One of the newest government office
buildings in Caracas is the marbled-sided Ministry of Finance.
Walking through the lobby there the other day I noticed that the
huge clock overlooking the reception desk was either (a) broken or
(b) 20 minutes slow. I didn't stay long enough to see which. But I
did stay in Venezuela long enough to realize that many people were
asking the same thing about President Hugo Chavez's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Is it broken? Or is it just a little late in blooming? Is he
leading Venezuela in a transition, the exact direction of which
will emerge after the May 28 presidential elections, or is he
leading Venezuela into a dead end?
</P>
<P>
   Who is Hugo Chavez? You hear that a lot here, and not just from
the corrupt politicians who ruled Venezuela for four decades before
the populist Chavez ousted them in a vote last year that amounted
to an electoral revolution. With unemployment here at 20 percent,
and with the economy having shrunk by 7.2 percent last year, even
some of the poor have turned against Chavez with graffiti: ``He
feeds us rhetoric to fill our minds, but our stomachs are empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best description of Chavez was from a diplomat here
who said: ``Hugo Chavez is a work in progress _ and a piece of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hugo Chavez who is a piece of work is the Chavez who ordered
U.S. military ships steaming to Venezuela _ on an emergency aid
mission to rebuild the vital coastal highway destroyed by mudslides
_ to go away. Chavez, a former army colonel and pal of Fidel
Castro, didn't want to look too dependent on the U.S. He recently
described Castro's medical-welfare system as a ``sea of happiness''
_ ignoring how many Cubans were risking their lives to swim away
from that sea.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hugo Chavez who is a work in progress is equally
interesting. Venezuela's political system needed a radical
overhaul, and Chavez is doing that. But so far his biggest reform
has been to rewrite the Constitution to widen his powers and
lengthen his potential time in office.
</P>
<P>
   If Chavez is re-elected in May _ he is being challenged by
Francisco Arias Cardenas, a former comrade who has charged Chavez
with incompetence _ the big question is, what will he build on his
new foundation, and with whom? Frankly, his team has a certain
Keystone Kops, not-ready-for-prime-time quality to it.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is obvious. Venezuela is a country that has been
cursed with oil. The reigning assumption in this nation, which sits
atop some of the world's richest fields, has been that Venezuela is
naturally rich and if it is getting poorer it is because someone in
power is stealing. So politics has tended to be about whom to
lynch, not what to build. The truth is, though, that with 85
percent of its foreign currency coming from oil sales, Venezuela is
a country that has forgotten how to create wealth. It only knows
how to distribute it. First the oligarchs distributed it to their
cronies. Now Chavez wants to give more to the underclass.
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't enough oil money anymore, and Chavez has not
detailed any credible plan for creating new wealth _ by attracting
non-energy-related foreign investment and building globally
competitive companies _ so that one-fifth of the country doesn't
have to work for the government. Today, the biggest export of
Venezuela's private sector is itself; the managers and scientists
who have global skills are leaving, frightened by the rising crime
wave and the Chavez populism that suggests that anyone here who has
money must have stolen it.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Chavez ran for office as Robin Hood in a country that needs
Bill Gates _ someone who not only redistributes wealth but knows
how to create it. Chavez came into office with a deep suspicion of
globalization. But on his recent trip to Beijing it was the Chinese
who told him to pay more attention to developing a globally
competitive private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez deserves a chance to prove himself as something more than
Robin Hood. If he can use his credibility with Venezuela's
underclass to lead them to a more modern economy, he will become
one of the most important figures in Latin America. If he doesn't,
Venezuela, which is America's largest supplier of oil, is going to
witness some really explosive and destabilizing politics.
</P>
<P>
   Time is short, and, somewhere at least, a clock is ticking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-03 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEAVE US ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Privacy is our constitutional right, by golly, and
we are serious about it. The national refrain is: Leave us alone!
Despite her legend, Greta Garbo didn't invent this demand.
</P>
<P>
   But the noble business of keeping the government, commercial
enterprises, competitors and snoopy neighbors out of our personal
lives is not as simple as it sounds. We have buttressed the
Constitution with laws and court rulings. Yet still we find
ourselves enmeshed in profound and constantly expanding conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Today there is great confusion about who gets to see what
records about whom in the Internet world of e-commerce, which is
still virtually unregulated. Congress is trying to grapple with the
issue but thus far not doing a reassuring job.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is afoot that our elected geniuses, or at least many
of those over 40, do not know what they are talking about on this
subject. They'd rather rag Vice President Al Gore, who does
understand the World Wide Web, about his claim to have invented the
Internet than master the subject themselves. That's what they hire
young staffers to do.
</P>
<P>
   Many individuals are refusing to fill out some of the questions
on the long form of the new Census Bureau survey because they feel
they are too intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the census is an important governing tool, the official
measurement of our national socioeconomic status that influences
how federal and state grants are allocated. Individual reports are
supposed to remain secret. The survey is after aggregate numbers
only.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., have encouraged reluctant participants not to answer all
the questions. Democrats charge they are less concerned about
privacy than about skewing the numbers to deny poorer regions the
government aid that they might otherwise be eligible for.
</P>
<P>
   Two other test cases over privacy issues have popped up
recently. Both New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and President
Clinton are accused of violating the privacy of individuals who
have embarrassed them. They released supposedly legally protected
records that make those individuals look bad.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, Clinton is on stronger legal ground than
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth ruled that the president
committed a crime by releasing letters to him from White House
volunteer worker Kathleen Willey, in which she seemed friendly and
affectionate despite her public charges that earlier Clinton had
offensively groped her. The judge regarded the letters as part of
the official White House record and therefore protected by the 1974
Privacy Act.
</P>
<P>
   But the letters represented a private correspondence between two
individuals. Willey sent her letters to the White House because
that is Clinton's mailing address. They are not official documents
that are normally subject to the Privacy Act. The Justice
Department and the president's lawyers, citing previous judicial
rulings, said such personal exchanges are in a separate category,
controlled by individual judgment, not by a law that is meant to
protect official, federally gathered information.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lamberth, however, has taken a provocative position that
is legally unsupportable. He had previously ruled that the Privacy
Act applied to every piece of paper or computer disc in the White
House, an extraordinary, single-handed attempt to undermine a
president's ability to function. In Lamberth's view, Clinton's lips
must be sealed against any attacks on him. Others may use knowledge
about him, but he may not counter with his knowledge about them
even though it was acquired from information other than
government-obtained documents. Sensibly, Clinton will appeal
Lamberth's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's political and legal bind is different. He released
official documents tracking the background of an unarmed black man
killed by police outside a local bar. To suggest the cops had
reason to fear Patrick Dorismond, Giuliani publicized details of
the victim's police and medical records, including juvenile charges
that had been dismissed and sealed by a court and a toxicology
report of marijuana in his body.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City charter requires that confidentiality laws be
obeyed _ by the mayor as well as everyone else. The mayor counters
that privacy laws end at death. But the Supreme Court recently
rejected a similar argument when Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
tried unsuccessfully to force White House aide Vincent Foster's
lawyer to tattle on the conversations they held shortly before
Foster committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani case, too, is going to court. The mayor complains
that ``politically correct prejudice'' is behind the angry backlash
he is enduring. Technically, as with Clinton, the issue is about
maybe breaking the law. Realistically, both cases involve
incumbents fending off others who are dumping on them. And nobody
is doing it in private.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-HNS &LR;      04-03 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE RULES MICROSOFT VIOLATED ANTI-TRUST LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. violated the nation's anti-trust
laws by illegally using its dominant position in the computer
software industry to stifle competition and hurt consumers in an
attempt to ``monopolize'' the Internet browser market, a federal
judged ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft placed an oppressive thumb on the scales of market
fortune,'' U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said
in his 50-page ruling of law, delivering a resounding but not
unexpected defeat to the company that has been a cornerstone in the
heated technology economy.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the software giant violated the anti-trust laws
laid out in the 1890 Sherman Act by maintaining its monopoly power
through ``anti-competitive means'' and ``attempting to monopolize''
the Web browser market. Internet browsers allow users access to the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jackson has handed down his verdict, the case moves
into the remedy phase. Among the possible remedies that Jackson
will consider are imposing fines on Microsoft, restricting its
conduct in the marketplace, and in the most extreme case, breaking
up the corporation. This decision could come later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also said that Microsoft violated anti-trust rules by
``unlawfully tying its Web browser to its (Windows) operating
system.'' A computer's operating system is the core program that
allows other programs, such as word processing, to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft trammeled the competitive process through which the
software industry normally innovates and hurt consumers through its
actions,'' said Jackson, who added that the company could be sued
under state anti-competition laws.
</P>
<P>
   Because Windows runs 95 percent of all computers, Jackson said,
Microsoft's bundling, or tying together, of its operating system
and its Internet browser meant that browser competitors _ such as
the Netscape Communications Corp., now part of America Online _
were at a severe disadvantage when it comes to selling their own
products. This Microsoft practice led to less competition and less
innovation, which hurt consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference in Redmond, Wash., Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates promised to appeal Jackson's decision, arguing that his
company's browser is not a separate product but an integrated
feature of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we did everything we could to settle this case, we
believe we have a strong case on appeal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals could last two years.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gates said his company was still open to talks with the
Justice Department and the 19 states and District of Columbia that
brought the suit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At a Washington news conference, Joel I. Klein, who brought the
case for the government as chief of the Justice Department's
antitrust division, praised the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Jackson's ruling will open the door to competition,
innovation and choice in the software industry,'' he said. ``It
will lay the ground rules for the information age.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said: ``Microsoft has been held
accountable for its illegal conduct by a court of law. Thanks to
this ruling, consumers who have been harmed can now look forward to
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge accepted 23 of 26 arguments brought forth by the
states that joined the federal government in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling had been expected to go against Microsoft
based on harsh assessments he outlined in November in his findings
of fact. In that document, Jackson found that Microsoft repeatedly
engaged in anti-competitive behavior by taking advantage of its
monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson delayed issuing his ruling until after U.S.
stock markets had closed for the day, his anticipated harsh verdict
sent Microsoft stock down 15 3/8 to 90 7/8 on the Nasdaq exchange,
slicing $78 billion from the company's total capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft plunge triggered a record selloff in Nasdaq
stocks, sending the index down 349.15, or 7.6 percent, to close at
4,223.68. It was easily the Nasdaq's worst point drop in history,
surpassing a 229-point plunge on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling followed the collapse of settlement talks
between Microsoft and the Justice Department on Saturday. Chicago
appellate court Judge Richard Posner, whom Jackson appointed as a
mediator in November, said in a statement that the differences were
``too deep-seated'' to forge an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the failed talks, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that negotiations in Chicago collapsed after the
company insisted on its own proposal to settle the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became obvious that Microsoft was rejecting the
government's proposal and demanding their own approach,'' one
government source said. ``But their plan was filled with loopholes
and wouldn't have been effective or even workable.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a Saturday news conference, Gates blamed the failure of
the talks on the Department of Justice and the states, which he
said were not working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between them, they appeared to be demanding either a breakup
of our company or other extreme concessions,'' said Gates, who did
not provide details of the company's offer to settle the case.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Monday's Wall Street Journal, Gates also said
that regardless of Jackson's ruling, his company would continue to
integrate the company's Internet browser into its Windows software,
even though that linkage is at the core of the Justice Department
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling is just a step in the legal process. It doesn't
change any situation relative to what we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal rejected Gates'
claim that the settlement talks failed because of a gulf between
the Justice Department and 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences between the states and the Department of
Justice are minimal when compared to the divergence between our
side and Microsoft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson now will begin designing a remedy to the violations he
cited in his ruling. According to antitrust specialists familiar
with case, the judge likely will pick among one of three possible
settlements:
</P>
<P>
   _ Creating separate companies for operating systems,
applications software and the Internet. Gates would be allowed to
run only one of these companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T, separate Bell telephone companies
were created to provide local service, while AT&AMP;T remained a
long-distance provider. The irony of this is that, if the AT&AMP;T
precedent prevails, the separate parts could eventually be worth
more than the whole, so Gates, a billionaire many times over, could
end up with even more wealth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keeping Microsoft intact but allow other companies to produce
their own versions of Windows, either by having Microsoft auction
off the rights to produce the software or by publishing Windows'
secret application program interfaces, or APIs, which run the
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Requiring Microsoft to publish these interfaces and explain how
they work would help quell much of the criticism logged against the
company from its competitors. APIs are the software hooks that
enable other companies' programs, from word processors to games, to
run on Windows computers.
</P>
<P>
   Some software developers contend that Microsoft has ``hidden
APIs'' in Windows that give a leg up to its own applications and
favored partners. Microsoft says that is untrue. Other software
developers alleged that the real problem is that the API
documentation from Microsoft is often misleading or erroneous.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leaving Microsoft and its monopoly status intact but imposing
specific rules on its behavior toward customers and competitors,
although this type of arrangement might require a huge Justice
Department enforcement effort.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said the government ``will seek a remedy that prevents
Microsoft from using its monopoly in the future to stifle
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The states and the Justice Department will have to iron out any
differences in their approaches to a remedy. The states reportedly
are seeking to break up the company, while the Justice Department
is willing to accept less harsh terms.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of private litigation was seen as a major incentive
for Microsoft to settle. Several private antitrust lawsuits have
been filed against the company in anticipation of a guilty verdict.
With Jackson's finding that Microsoft violated the law, private
plaintiffs need only to prove that the software giant harmed them
through its actions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
