<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are highlights of the ``conclusions of law''
issued Monday in the Microsoft antitrust case by U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   He ruled that Microsoft:
</P>
<P>
   _ Violated federal antitrust laws by maintaining ``monopoly
power by anti-competitive means.'' As a result, the company
``trammeled the competitive process through which the computer
software industry generally stimulates innovations'' that best
serve the public.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tried to monopolize the Web browser market by unlawfully tying
its Internet Explorer software to its Windows operating system in
order to exclude a rival product by Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   _ Entered into illegal ``exclusionary'' agreements to thwart its
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Did not illegally prevent Netscape, which has since become
part of America Online Inc., from distributing its Navigator
browser software.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
