<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB ARRESTED, CHARGED IN `ETHNIC CLEANSING' CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ In a daring pre-dawn raid, French
commandos blew down the door Monday of a Bosnian Serb linked to the
murder of thousands of Muslims and Croats, making him the highest
ranking official to be arrested on war crimes charges involving
``ethnic cleansing'' in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Momcilo Krajisnik, 55, a former leader of of the Bosnian Serbs,
was dragged from his bed to an armored personnel carrier and then
flown to a cell in The Hague to await arraignment on charges of
genocide and crimes against humanity later this week, said
prosecutors at the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia. They called the arrest in the Bosnian Serb stronghold
of Pale the most important of the 18 war crimes arrests made to
date by NATO forces in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a secret indictment, French soldiers used explosives
to breach the door to the home of Krajisnik's elderly father at 3
a.m., the prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The bold action may also have blown away insinuations that
French soldiers have been unduly sympathetic to the Serbs and
turned a blind eye to those indicted for war crimes in the sector
of Bosnia they control. It marked only the second time French
troops had arrested a suspected war criminal in Bosnia. British
troops have made the bulk of arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest was especially risky because Krajisnik was usually
surrounded by heavily armed bodyguards, but the French troops
pulled it off without any reported casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik stands accused of orchestrating the deaths of
thousands of Muslim and Croat men, women, and children and the
torture and forced deportation of hundreds of thousands more in
1991 and 1992. The indictment charged him with planning the
massacre of civilians in about 20 villages and towns, establishing
at least a dozen concentration camps, and conducting forced marches
to those camps in which victims were summarily pulled from the
ranks and shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik is a close associate of former Bosnian Serb president
Radovan Karadzic, who is also under indictment for war crimes and
remains the tribunal's most wanted man. Krajisnik was Karadzic's
deputy leader in the Serbian section of Bosnia, and he replaced
Karadzic as the leading Bosnian Serb politician after the charges
against Karadzic forced him to go underground.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in The Hague were jubilant because of the importance
of their catch, and because it was French troops who corralled him.
</P>
<P>
   They were also encouraged because it was the quickest arrest yet
in the tribunal's seven-year history. Krajisnik's secret indictment
and arrest warrant were handed up on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most significant arrest in the history of the
tribunal,'' said Paul Risley, a spokesman for Carla Del Ponte, the
chief prosecutor of the war crimes tribunal created by the United
Nations Security Council in 1993. ``This shows that NATO has the
will and the ability to go into any area and carry out the arrests
of individuals under indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the US ambassador to the UN and former US
special envoy to the Balkans, hailed Krajisnik's arrest as one of
the most significant advances in the region in the last five years
and praised the French soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is by far the most important indicted war criminal who was
picked up,'' Holbrooke told reporters at the United Nations.
``Because it is a secret indictment, it should warn people they may
not be as invulnerable as they think.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who brokered the 1995 Dayton Agreement that ended the
Bosnian war, described Krajisnik as an ``out and out separatist and
a complete racist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the biggest break in our favor in a long time, because
it is a major blow to the separatists, racists, and murderers who
have been trying to thwart the single national concept that is at
the heart of Dayton,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, Krajisnik was the Serb representative on
the shared three-member presidency that rules Bosnia under the
Dayton Agreement. He is now a businessman whom western diplomats
have accused more recently of collaborating with the reputed
gangsters who run much of the Republika Srbska, the Serb section of
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said they hoped that Krajisnik's arrest had
tightened the noose that is slowly closing around their most
coveted targets, Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, the former head of the
Bosnian Serb army who carried out Karadzic's orders to rid Bosnia
of Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Karadzic, I wouldn't be sleeping too well tonight,''
said Risley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
