<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-CANDIDATES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES AND COMEDY: WHO'S WINNER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - With politicians clamoring to appear on late-night
talk shows _ the road to New York's U.S. Senate seat runs through
his studio, David Letterman boasts _ it's fair to ask the question:
How do the presidential hopefuls stack up as entertainers?
</P>
<P>
   And who better to answer than the guys at Comedy Central's
Indecision 2000 political team, who've enjoyed a front-row seat
during the presidential-primary season _ the best place from which
to lob the occasional journalistic cream pie?
</P>
<P>
   Like when a correspondent, playing off the Confederate flag flap
in South Carolina, asked John McCain whether the Dukes of Hazzard
should remove the flag from their car, the General Lee. Or would
that fall under the jurisdiction of the show's sheriff?
</P>
<P>
   ``He started waxing nostalgic about lessons he's learned from
Rosco P. Coltrane,'' says Stuart Bailey, a senior producer for
``The Daily'' ``Show With Jon Stewart'' (on which Indecision 2000
appears), of McCain. ``He doesn't miss a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   If you thought the national media loved McCain _ and they did _
the Indecision 2000 team practically worshiped the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after he dropped out, the flag at Comedy Central flew
at half-mast,'' correspondent Mo Rocca says. ``We liked him for the
same reason the `real' press kissed his ass for the last six
months: He was accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, despite a generally well-received guest spot on ``The
Tonight ``Show,'' McCain is now a roadside carcass on the
presidential highway, joined by other leading entertainment lights
who aspired to the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw Gary Bauer come back to the hotel as a beaten, wee
man, it was the end of an era,'' Bailey says. Bauer made primary
sound-bite history by falling off a stage while attempting to flip
pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad for him as a candidate,'' Bailey says, ``but
professionally, I had to think, `All is right with the world.' That
was just a sheer delight, to see that. As if things couldn't go bad
enough for the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we're left with George W. Bush and Al Gore _ able
politicians, obviously, but not exactly Laurel and Hardy when it
comes to entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like it's going to be high comedy,'' Rocca
says. ``I hope we don't have to rely on banana peels.''
</P>
<P>
   All this a mere eight years after then-candidate Bill Clinton
was slammed for playing the saxophone on ``The Arsenio Hall Show.''
Demeaned the office, people complained. Now Bush, Gore and McCain
all have appeared on the late-night circuit, and no one debated
whether they should have. We debated whether they were funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first glance, even I would have to say, yeah, somehow maybe
it does demean the whole process,''
</P>
<P>
   Indecision 2000 correspondent Vance DeGeneres says ``that we're
electing not the new Johnny Carson but the most powerful man in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the other hand, somehow it makes me feel better that
there is a human side to the guy. It makes me feel a little safer.
I would worry about a guy who has no sense of humor about anything,
including himself.'''
</P>
<P>
   And with Steve Forbes out of the race, he won't have to.
</P>
<P>
   DeGeneres' prediction probably won't come true _ that the
Letterman and Leno shows will replace the caucuses and primaries _
but there is no denying that politics and entertainment have become
as intertwined as Pamela Anderson and Tommy Lee (when they're not
broken up).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's become more important because of the rise of
entertainment in general,'' Bailey says. ``People, for some strange
reason, know the box-office receipts of the weekend's movies. All
of a sudden, our entertainment knowledge, the base of it, has grown
so fast it's natural politics got sucked in as well.''
</P>
<P>
   If neither Bush nor Gore is a laugh riot, all hope is not lost
at Comedy Central. Bush's train-wreck appearance on Letterman (a
later Leno appearance went better) proves that anything can happen,
Bailey says. And Gore's contentious debate exchanges with Bill
Bradley sharpened his entertainment skills. Still, it won't be like
the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't phone it in anymore,'' Bailey says. ``When you have
interns in the White House, you just sit back and let the jokes
write themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't forget the potential bonanza that's known as the
Reform Party,'' Rocca says. ``You've got a gorgeous mosaic of
crackpots. It's the most delicious buffet of craziness. And what
better ringleader of this crazy circus than Pat Buchanan?''
</P>
<P>
   It may not replace ``ER,'' but at least it's something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
