<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-03 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DOWN FOR THE COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many of you out there have strong reservations about the
U.S. Census? May I see a show of hands?
</P>
<P>
   I thought so. Everybody's cool. Once again, the radio talk-show
circuit has plunged us into a violent debate about an issue that
stirs the passions of average Americans slightly less than the
cancellation of ``Beverly Hills 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   You have no doubt received a census form, probably the short one
that takes just a few minutes to fill out. The long form, which
goes to about one-sixth of all American households, contains 53
questions, including whether your toilets flush and your relatives
are all in their right minds. The answers are going to remain
confidential for the next 72 years; at that point a Ph.D. candidate
may grant you immortality by writing a dissertation on your indoor
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Census opponents appear to be mainly opponents of government,
period. (James Bovard, the author of ``Freedom in Chains,'' called
the census ``a scheme for generating grist for the expansion of the
welfare state.'') But they've created some nervous roiling in
Congress. Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska is working on legislation to
remove the $100 penalty for failure to answer the questions, even
though the fine hasn't been imposed in decades. He's being assisted
by Sen. Charles Robb of Virginia, a Democrat up for re-election
who's determined to leave no group unpandered to.
</P>
<P>
   The census is actually a noble public enterprise. It represents
the founding fathers' breakthrough concept that people should have
power not because of their property or titles, but simply because
they're there. If we cannot expect election-fevered politicians to
be reasonable about, say, Elian Gonzalez, it does seem they could
muster up the grit to tell folks that they should regard filling
out census forms like voting, and pretend to appreciate the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But George W. Bush regards the issue as too hot for rationality.
First he announced that ``all of us need to encourage people to
fill out the census,'' then instantly added that he could
understand why some ``don't want to give all that information to
the government. And if I had the long form I'm not sure I'd want
to, either.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush said the governor had received the short
form, this year's equivalent of announcing you got a high draft
number.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said recently
that Lott was telling people to just skip over any question they
felt was intrusive. Now, the senator's constituents in Mississippi
make out like bandits when it comes to federal aid, receiving an
average of about $2,000 per person more than they pay in federal
taxes. On behalf of all the states that pay more than they get
back, let me say: Go to it, Mississippians. Skip the long forms,
and the short forms too. We'll give the money to some less
conflicted state, perhaps one that hasn't just received a contract
to build a monster aircraft carrier the Pentagon doesn't even want.
</P>
<P>
   We interrupt this harangue to report that Lott's office now says
the senator wants everybody to fill out the forms, and tells people
to skip questions only if they threaten to toss their forms into
the river unless their objections are met. When it comes to
penalties for non-compliance, his spokesman added, ``the senator is
completely agnostic.''
</P>
<P>
   This is possibly the first time in history that Lott's name has
been used in the same sentence with the word ``agnostic.''
</P>
<P>
   For every politician who's trying to distance himself from the
census, there are four others desperately trying to get their
constituents to fill out the forms, and raise their chances of
getting more federal aid. The governor of Georgia has gone on
television with an ad urging his state to cooperate ``or our
Georgia money will be educating New York children for another 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm a little wounded by that. Certainly we New Yorkers
disagree with Georgians about some minor matters, such as the
relative charms of John Rocker. But our elected officials _
appalling as they may be _ don't try to scare us into doing what
they want by threatening to give our tax dollars to kids in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Go yell at the Mississippians for a while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FALCONE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      04-03 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALSETTO `SOPRANOS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; ``tonight'' refers to Tues., Apr. 4) 
Our rating: 2{ stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' proves why the networks could never have made ``The
Sopranos.'' First, check out the cast of thugs and cops _ all are
blandly attractive and coolly vicious to the point of seeming
completely interchangeable, not like the colorful and distinctive
bunch on the acclaimed HBO series. Next, check out the tricky moral
quandaries _ or rather, the lack of same: You got your cops, you
got your gangsters, and they're all talking the same brand of
tough, and basically just circling one another endlessly, no one
apparently in charge, like sharks in a vortex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' (based on the feature film ``Donnie Brasco,'' itself
based on a true story) centers on Joe Falcone (Jason Gedrick), a
low-level soldier in the Volonte family mob by day and Joe Pistone,
family man, at night. Falcone has to walk the tricky minefield of
undercover agent in a deadly business filled with paranoia and
hair-trigger tempers; he's been at it for two years, which sort of
begs the question: Just how much extortion, robbery and murder does
he have to witness before the government has a case against these
guys, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   CBS is presenting nine episodes of ``Falcone'' over eight
nights, like a pseudo-miniseries, which is probably a good idea
because there's a lot of complicated duplicity and interconnected
plotting. The fact that everyone sort of looks and dresses the same
doesn't help alleviate the confusion. (Here's the easiest way to
tell this is a CBS series: The women in a strip club are more
covered than those in the average UPN series.)
</P>
<P>
   The main points are: Volonte's iced, and there's a scramble to
replace him (a whacked-out character in a prison psycho ward,
(over)played _ naturally _ by Eric Roberts gets the improbable
nod), forcing Falcone to choose his alliances carefully. Another,
sloppier, undercover agent is brought in when Falcone's captain,
Sonny (Titus Welliver), plans a major contracting scam with the
school board, imperiling both Pistone and his family. Other scams
and crimes (involving a purloined prize pooch and phony birth
certificates) keep the action burbling along. ``The Sopranos''
could make subplots like the contracting scam amusing; the stories
here are humorless (except for the fizzled dognapping yarn, which
falls flat) and, dramatically, register mere shrugs. When a goofy,
wanna-be mobster is introduced, you know immediately he's
ultimately going to be played for poignancy. Scenes with Pistone's
in-the-dark and not-quite-understanding family offer the weakest
material here _ on ``Sopranos,'' those scenes are often the best.
</P>
<P>
   And plotting at times seems iffy _ these crack federal
investigators can't seem to loosen some much-needed chump change to
make an undercover agent appear to be a serious player, but they
can clean out an entire house and relocate the family in it in an
hour's time.
</P>
<P>
   Gedrick's a little blank for the role _ he doesn't show us
Falcone's/Pistone's internal gears spinning when he needs to come
up with a quick-witted response when his cover's about to get
blown. Welliver is good at playing a cool facade with a short fuse,
and everyone else around him seems to be aping him. ``Falcone'' is
like ``The Fugitive'' in reverse, a cat-and-mouse game that both
shows promise and seems to come with a built-in short shelf life:
The deeper things get, the more difficult it will be to sustain
Pistone's alias and, of course, the guy's got to start making
arrests at some point.
</P>
<P>
   If viewers don't go for this hefty serving of ``Falcone''
quickly, however, it may be a moot point. It has its intriguing
moments, but if the network whacks the show, viewers will no doubt
respond with the sort of cold-eyed resignation virtually every
character here demonstrates.________ &QL; 
The show: ``Falcone.'' &QL; 
What: Miniseries of one-hour episodes about a fed undercover in the
mob. &QL; 
The stars: Jason Gedrick, Titus Welliver, Eric Roberts. &QL; 
Where: KCBS (Channel 2). &QL; 
When: 9 tonight, 10 p.m. Wednesday through Saturday and Monday
through April 12. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
