<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     04-03 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO MAKES THE DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fortified by the addition of Peter Schourek (anagram
for RUTH KEEP SCORE), shaken by the sudden disgruntlement of
veteran Tim Wakefield, picked to win the World Series by Sports
Illustrated and Larry King, the Red Sox Tuesday night will be the
last American League team to take the field for the start of the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Pedro will be in the House. Always, things go better
when Pedro is in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The House could be Fenway Park, Safeco Field (where he'll start
against the Mariners Tuesday night), the Jimmy Fund Clinic, or the
Boston Sheraton grand ballroom for the annual Baseball Writers
dinner. Doesn't matter. When Pedro is in the House, it's an event.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's event is the first game of the second century of
Red Sox baseball. Pedro Martinez, winner of just about every award
(ESPN Magazine gave him an Oscar for being the ``Latin American
Beauty''), puts the Sox in position for a fast start.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Pedro is The Man. At home. On the road. At any
function. Fans line up four hours early if he's making a scheduled
autograph appearance. They bring baseballs for him to sign, babies
for him to kiss. A random Pedro sighting in a movie theater or
restaurant results in urgent phone calls that guarantee a crowd
will be waiting when he exits.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro is coming off the single greatest season of power and
precision pitching in the last 100 years (23-4, 2.07, 313
strikeouts, 37 walks), and life has changed for the diminutive
Dominican. He's still the Sox' clubhouse cutup, but it's getting
harder to live the everyday life he loves. Every stranger in the
street makes demands. Every charity wants him for its worthy cause.
Every reporter needs just one more quote. Most recently, SI put him
on its cover next to a headline that says the Red Sox will win the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not anything unusual,'' said the 28-year-old righty. ``I
was prepared for this. I was ready. I don't like it, but I have to
take it. To me, it's not anything that's going to take me by
surprise. I know what I'm doing. I know what I'm in and I know what
it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   He already has warned the world that it's not fair to expect a
repeat of his 1999 performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People, they can't expect more than 100 percent,'' he said.
``That's all I'm gonna give.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, 100 percent has done the job for the fandom. Pedro
has been a member of the Red Sox for only two seasons, but his
popularity already has outstripped that of Roger Clemens in his
prime. Luis Tiant, Fred Lynn, Carlton Fisk, and Nomar Garciaparra
have enjoyed the adulation of Red Sox Nation, but not since Carl
Yastrzemski (circa 1967) has any Sox player enjoyed the godlike
status that engulfs Pedro today.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's ready for the season. The Sox were a
worst-in-the-majors 11-19 in Florida and Arizona, but Pedro got his
work in, pitching 15 2/3 innings in five games, allowing eight runs
and 17 hits while fanning 20 and walking only two.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this time of year, I'm where I want to be,'' he said.
``I'm healthy and that's all I need. All the rest is just a matter
of time and playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he made his Boston debut, striking out 11 in
seven innings of a shutout victory over the Oakland A's. Last year
he took the opening act to Kansas City and again fanned 11 in
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But there was never the spotlight and expectation like now. ESPN
altered the American League schedule in order to televise Pedro's
2000 debut. Pedro games are certified hardball events. His next
start is Sunday in Anaheim (the master's gifts are wasted on Orange
County casuals) and we don't yet know whether his Fenway debut will
be next Friday or Saturday. It matters if you're sharing a
season-ticket package with your brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about all the attention,'' he said. ``I'll be
me no matter how much they ask for me, how much they do, or what
they do. I can't change. I can only be me and that's the only one I
know how to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still having fun. I wouldn't say as much fun as ever, but
it's a lot of fun. It's just busy. It's busier now than it was
before. But that's what they pay you for.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he'll be careful not to let his celebrity intefere with
his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing everybody's gotta be clear: when I gotta work, when
I have to do my job, I don't care how much you clap, how loud you
are, I have a job to do,'' he said. ``That's pretty much it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the 2000 Sox. Is this really the year?
</P>
<P>
   ``What they say is one thing and what we do on the field is
another thing,'' said Pedro. ``We're a big league team and better
on paper than we were last year. We're the only ones that beat the
Yankees in the playoffs. What else do we have to do? Just play.
Come ask us in November. See where we finish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 162 to play,'' said manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night is Game No. 1. It's the start. And the Red Sox go
to battle with the best starter in all of baseball. Tune in at
8:05. Pedro will be in the House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
