<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, April 4. If you
have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCCAIN (Phoenix) - Deferring to what she called the need for
``party unity,'' Arizona Gov. Jane Hull has given up her
prerogative to lead the Arizona delegation to the Republican
National Convention. Hull announced her decision Monday in a letter
that was released one day after Sen. John McCain, in an appearance
Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' dismissively rejected the idea
of Hull leading the Arizona delegation.
</P>
<P>
   By KRIS MAYES. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SYMINGTON (Phoenix) - Former Gov. Fife Symington testified Monday
that the fact that he personally guaranteed $178 million in
construction loans should have been a ``red flag'' to pension funds
that lent him money in 1990, as the Valley's commercial real-estate
market began to collapse. Symington's testimony was intended to
buttress his attorneys' arguments that the six pension funds that
lent him $10 million to finance the failed downtown Mercado retail
and office project did not analyze his financial statements. By
JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) - If his father had died at sea and Elian
Gonzalez's mother was waiting for him back in Cuba, we'd have
fished the 6-year-old out of the ocean and shipped him back to
Havana before his pants dried. We can stop pretending the case of
young Elian is an argument over the differences between Cuba and
the United States. It's not. It begins and ends with the age-old
belief that a child's mother is more important to him than his
father By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
