<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-SUITS-BOS &LR;      04-03 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING COULD ENCOURAGE SUITS AGAINST SOFTWARE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp., absorbing a harsh blow in its
antitrust battle with the government, now faces another big legal
problem: Monday's ruling gives a boost to scores of private
antitrust cases against the company.
</P>
<P>
   At least 120 companies and individuals have filed their own
actions against Microsoft. Most charge that the software giant
abused its monopoly power to keep software prices high and to
stifle rival products, which might have been cheaper and more
innovative than Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers bringing these cases are organized. More than 50 of
them met in Washington in January to swap strategy and coordinate
requests for documents and depositions from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Their effort got fresh fuel as Federal District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson concluded that Microsoft broke antitrust laws in
trying to protect its Windows monopoly and in attempting to
dominate the market for Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   All of the private antitrust plaintiffs must prove that
Microsoft is a monopoly, or their claims will be rejected. But now
that Jackson has called Microsoft a monopoly, and is certain to
repeat that conclusion in his final judgment expected later this
year, lawyers in the private cases can merely point to Jackson's
ruling to prove that part of their argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a third or half of the work, establishing that a
company has monopoly power,'' said Rich Gray, a Menlo Park, Calif.,
antitrust lawyer who is following the Microsoft case closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see a lot of other cases climbing out of the
woodwork against Microsoft,'' said Charles Haworth, a former law
professor now with Owens, Clary &AMP; Aiken in Dallas. ``I think their
problems are just beginning. It's a nightmare for the company, no
doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Chesley, a Cincinatti lawyer leading the drive to
organize plantiffs attorneys against Microsoft, said Jackson's
ruling was ``very helpful'' to the private cases. ``We're going to
be able to utilize that. These private persons have rights, and we
have every intention of pursuing all of our remedies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the lawyers bringing suits against Microsoft have
experience in taking on the tobacco, breast implant and vitaman
supplement industries.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the private cases could become a major problem for
Microsoft is that most seek to be certified as class actions
representing thousands of plaintiffs. And under federal law, a
defendent found guilty of antitrust violations must pay triple the
actual damages to each plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   One Massachusetts case, filed by Michael Germano of Wilmington,
seeks to represent all Massachusetts residents who bought or
licensed Microsoft's Windows operating system or its Internet
browser, called Internet Explorer, for use but not for resale.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says that because of Microsoft's illegal behavior,
consumers were not able to buy computer operating systems or Web
browsers ``at prices determined by free and open competition,'' and
that they paid more for Windows and Internet Explorer than they
would have in a competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cullinan, a spokesman for Microsoft, rejected that argument
and the company's liability in the other private lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The class action litigations are about overcharging,
basically, and there's nothing in the record of the DOJ (Department
of Justice) trial that addressed such a thing,'' Cullinan said.
``Microsoft's whole business model is high volume and low prices,
so we severely doubt that even a finding of monopoly power by the
court will help in the overcharging issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that complaints about overcharging for Windows ``are
completely without merit, and are an effort by plaintiffs'
attorneys just to go after a successful company.''
</P>
<P>
   In their suit, the US Justice Department and state prosecutors
did not seek damages on behalf of consumers, even though they had
the right to, Attorney General Tom Miller of Iowa said. The
government's suit was massive even without making that effort, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's recent experience as an antitrust defendant has been
mixed. In January, it paid an estimated $275 million to settle
charges brought by Caldera Inc., a small Salt Lake City company
that claimed Microsoft competed unfairly in the market for MS-DOS
operating system software. The settlement forced Microsoft to take
a charge of 3 cents per share in the quarter ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, however, Microsoft won a federal jury trial in which
a small Connecticut company, Bristol Technology Inc. of Danbury,
said the software giant improperly withheld software code that
Bristol needed for its survival.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ``findings of law'' followed his Nov. 5 ``findings of
fact.'' Barring a last-minute settlement between Microsoft and the
government, Jackson will issue a final judgment that incorporates
those two sets of findings.
</P>
<P>
   Private plaintiffs will likely want to cite the final judgment,
rather than Jackson's earlier findings, in their own cases. Because
Jackson's rulings so far have been harsh in their assessment of
Microsoft, the final judgment is expected to hit the company hard
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aiding the private cases is a set of legal principles that say a
party, once it has had the chance to fully litigate an issue,
should not be given the chance to debate it all over again in a
different court. ``These plaintiffs will argue that Microsoft,
having had a full and fair opportunity to litigate the issues that
led to the judge's conclusions, should not be able to relitigate
those issues in another forum,'' Haworth said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the judicial system has already settled the
question of whether Microsoft is a monopoly. Other aspects of
Jackson's rulings may be useful to private plaintiffs, as well.
However, each plaintiff will still have to prove it suffered harm
because Microsoft illegally used its monopoly power.
</P>
<P>
   When facing the private suits, Microsoft can draw little comfort
from the fact that Jackson rejected some of the government's
charges, as private plaintiffs are free to raise those claims
again, Haworth said. To bar them from doing so would deprive
plaintiffs of due process rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal suits against Microsoft, the discovery process _
the process of requesting documents and depositions from parties in
a case _ will likely be consolidated before a single federal court.
</P>
<P>
   After discovery, the federal suits would be tried in the courts
in which they were filed. More than 60 of the suits filed so far
have been brought in federal court, and about 50 in state courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
