<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v BC-MICROSOFT-COMPETITORS     04-03 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COMPETITORS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT RULING COULD COME BACK TO HAUNT COPORATE FOES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft's antitrust trial ultimately may bite the
software industry that bore and fed it, or harm the consumers whose
dollars have built the industry into the powerhouse it has become.
</P>
<P>
   It was competitors' complaints about Microsoft's monopoly in
Intel-based PC operating systems that led to Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson's ruling Monday that the company had violated the Sherman
Antitrust Act, as the Justice Department and 19 states had claimed
in their 1998 lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp. led the parade, and Sun
Microsystems, Intel, Compaq, RealNetworks, IBM, Apple Computer and
others testified at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Microsoft has been judged a monopolist that has
harmed consumers, and the time has arrived to consider how to
punish it, the companies are pulling back.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's Scott McNealy has urged that Microsoft not be dismembered,
as some states and the Department of Justice are said to be
advocating. McNealy says he opposes such a so-called ``structural
remedy'' only because the pieces would each continue to offend, not
because the company doesn't deserve to be punished.
</P>
<P>
   Even Microsoft's competitors warn, though, that any punishment
eventually decided upon by the court musn't interfere with
Microsoft's productivity. The entire computer industry realizes
that Microsoft's success is essential to its own. For example, on
May 1, 1998, executives of 26 of the nation's largest technology
companies urged the Justice Department not to block release of
Windows 98, out of concern about how that might affect them and the
industry as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Changing some of Microsoft's conduct, like insisting it separate
Internet Explorer from Windows, probably wouldn't pose a problem to
the industry. But other provisions the government wants, like
sharing the source code for Windows with partners or the public,
present their own set of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may find, for example, that the ease with which they
can read a document or spreadsheet created by a friend or colleague
may diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Assume for example that Microsoft is forced (or agrees) to share
the source code, or blueprints, for current and future versions of
its Windows operating system. That may lead to the release of
multiple versions of Windows as companies or individuals
``improve'' it. The Linux community, where open source code has
been most successful, calls that process forking. Over time, some
forked versions will gain features other lack. That means files
created on one machine might not be fully usable, or usable at all,
on another.
</P>
<P>
   People who have used computers since before Windows achieved its
97 percent market share may recall the not-so-good-old days in the
early 1990s when Apple, DOS, OS/2 and Windows were battling for
market share. No developer wanted to waste time and money writing
word-processing, spreadsheet, database, and myriad other
applications for operating systems that weren't likely to capture a
big share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   So they invariably chose one or maybe two to develop for. As a
result, people often couldn't read files created by colleagues or
friends. As Windows gained market share, more applications were
written for it, which, in a classic chicken-and-egg situation,
helped it gain yet more market share.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, of course, likes this argument _ it suggests that its
monopoly evolved naturally as a result of consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   From a software developer's view, too, the lack of a single
operating system made developing new products more expensive and
time consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Now we may begin reliving those days.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   If government regulators take a lesson from the Linux community,
economic and social pressures, and possibly licensing requirements,
could help prevent Windows splitting the operating system into too
many and too varied versions or ``forks.''
</P>
<P>
   Socially, ``anyone who forks gets really punished, because the
culture frowns on it'' as unfair, said Tim Bird, the chief
technology officer for embedded-Linux vendor Lineo. In terms of
economics, it doesn't make sense, Bird said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
