<SLUG> BC-MA-GUN-RULES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AG SAYS BAY STATE WANTS TO LEAD NATION IN GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the announcement that he will start enforcing
tough consumer protection laws against the gun industry, Attorney
General Thomas Reilly declared an ambitious goal Monday: not just
to change Massachusetts, but to lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts will be the first state, Reilly said, to use its
consumer protection regulations to prohibit the sale of guns
without tamper-resistant serial numbers, child-protection features,
trigger locks, and other safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   And even as gun industry advocates questioned his motives, and
some lawmakers took steps to challenge his authority, Reilly said
his tactics ought to set a new example. In triumphant tones, he
pledged to guide other state attorneys general, and declared
Massachusetts ``a national model...as to how we can stand up
against the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   And John Rosenthal, chairman of the Newton-based group Stop
Handgun Violence, declared Massachusetts ``the gun control capital
of America.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same banner Chicago and New Orleans waved in 1998, when
they led a succession of cities that filed lawsuits to hold the gun
industry liable for the medical and social costs of gun violence.
Some of those suits have since been dismissed, and some are now
pending in court.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the prospect of a wave of Reilly followers worries Bob
Delfey, president of the National Shooting Sports Foundation, the
nation's largest gun manufacturers' trade association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very possible other attorneys general will do this,''
Delfey said, predicting that each new state will attempt even
tougher regulations, in order to stay on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to want to go one up,'' Delfey said. ``They're
going to want the headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   In both the courts and the political arena, the fight over gun
control has increasingly become a game of brinksmanship. And the
scene in Massachusetts Monday was no different, as each side used
high-flying rhetoric and duelling statistics, and each challenged
the other side's motives.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and his supporters said Massachusetts' strict gun safety
regulations, passed in 1997 and upheld by state courts last month,
are common-sense provisions that should not impede the lawful use
of guns. The gun industry's ongoing resistance, he said, is ``based
upon their decision to put profits ahead of safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But Delfey said gun accidents are actually on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firearms are incredibly safe, reliable instruments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Yacino, executive director of the state Gun Owners'
Action League, said Massachusetts' rules won't solve the problem of
gun violence, and could harm law-abiding citizens who need their
guns in emergencies, when they ``don't have time to dig for your
little key.''
</P>
<P>
   Yacino questioned whether Reilly was trying to lay the
foundations for a gubernatorial bid. And Delfey said the timing of
Reilly's announcement was suspect. It came just days after U.S.
Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo and New York
Attorney General Elliot Spitzer gained national headlines with a
gun announcement of their own: that manufacturer Smith &AMP; Wesson
Corp. would sign a code of conduct, agreeing to install safety
locks and ``smart gun'' technology.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson may now emerge as one of the few manufacturers
whose models can be sold in Massachusetts, Reilly said, since he
plans to enforce the state's rules immediately.
</P>
<P>
   And though Reilly insisted that ``it's not our intent to put gun
dealers out of business,'' some predicted that his actions could
effectively shut down gun sales in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether these gun manufacturers are going to be
able to meet all the standards that are in here...they'll stop
shipping firearms into the state,'' said Rep. George Peterson, a
Grafton Republican. ``My sense is, he's trying to shut dealers down
through the regulatory process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
