<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIKE THAT TAKES OVER WHEN YOU'RE TIRED 
EDWARD WESTON AND MODERNISM IN BOSTON 
ATHENS EXPANDS METRO, UNEARTHING ANTIQUITIES 
LUXURY RIVERBOAT TO PLY LOCHS AND HIGHLANDS 
`SILENT SERVICE' MARKS ITS CENTENNIAL
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: England, Boston, Greece, Scotland, D.C.)  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new electric-bicycle company in the Lake District of England
could be the solution for visitors who would like to explore the
countryside by bike but aren't fit enough to tackle the hilly
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Easyriders, offers bicycles with small electric
motors and sensors that monitor the speed and pedal force provided
by the rider and calculate when to supply extra power, thus taking
the effort out of uphill cycling, long distances and head winds.
Depending on road conditions and other factors like weather, the
range of these electric bikes, powered by small nickel metal
hydrogen batteries, is over 25 miles. If the battery runs out, the
bicycle reverts to pedal power only.
</P>
<P>
   Bikes can be rented at the Coniston Boating Center, Lake Road,
Coniston, (44-15394) 41366, or at Waterhead, Windermere Lake,
(44-1539) 431245, for $28 a day or $20 a half day. The price
includes helmets, locks and route maps. Child seats are available
and renters must be at least 14 years old. On the Web:
easy-riders.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Weston and Modernism in Boston
</P>
<P>
   Edward Weston's images _ the elegant seashell, the voluptuous
pepper, nudes melding into the landscape, landscapes sinuous as
nudes _ are so familiar that it is easy to forget his pioneering
role in American modern art. ``Edward Weston: Photography and
Modernism,'' on view at the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, through
May 29, presents 140 of his vintage prints alongside nearly 60
works by modernist masters, including Georgia O'Keeffe, Diego
Rivera, Brancusi and Picasso as well as the photographers Alfred
Stieglitz and Imogen Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Through photographs drawn from the Lane Collection, on long-term
loan to the museum, the exhibition traces the purity of form,
fascination with patterns and interest in mundane objects that
marked Weston's work throughout his 30-year career. It illuminates
his contribution to the art movements of his time, from Cubism to
Surrealism.
</P>
<P>
   Some pairings are obvious: an abstract nude from his
breakthrough years in Mexico beside a Rivera drawing, a clean-lined
Brancusi sculpture near those sexy vegetables. Others are more
surprising: a painting by Jackson Pollock above three photographs
of objects in nature that anticipate Abstract Expressionism. The
artistic ferment of the era is captured in small-format portraits
of friends and contemporaries. Igor Stravinsky stares into the
camera; E.E. Cummings looks away; nobody smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's darkroom from Carmel, Calif., has been reconstructed
with the help of his son Cole, and a timeline provides context: in
1926, for example, Weston returned from Mexico, Monet died and the
pop-up toaster was invented.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are Monday and Tuesday, 10 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.; Wednesday
through Friday, 10 a.m. to 9:30 p.m.; and weekends, 10 a.m. to 5:30
p.m. Admission is $12, seniors and college students $10, age 7 to
17 $5 during school hours and free other times. Call (617)
267-9300, or check www.mfa.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Nan Levinson
</P>
<P>
   Athens Expands Metro, Unearthing Antiquities
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of its role as host of the 2004 Olympics, Athens
is expanding its metro system. The $2.5 billion project includes
two new lines, adding more than 12 miles and 21 stations. Expanded
service began in January with the opening of 13 new stations. The
fare is now 70 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership is expected to increase to 780,000 passengers each day
from 330,000. Ramps, escalators and elevators have been installed
to help passengers with disabilities, and 168 cars have been added
to the system.
</P>
<P>
   Line 1, the green line, has run from Piraeus to Kifissia, a
northern suburb, since 1957. Stations on this line are being
refurbished and made wheelchair-accessible. Line 2, the red line,
will connect the southwestern suburb of Dafni with the northeastern
reaches of the city; it currently runs between Syntagma and
Sepolia. Line 3, the blue line, runs east to west, connecting
Syntagma to Ethniki Amyna. Stations at Omonia, Syntagma,
Monastiraki and Attiki serve as transfer points between lines.
</P>
<P>
   Five additional stations on the red line are expected to be
ready at the end of October. Plans include extending the blue line
to the new international airport in Spata in time for the Olympic
Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the new stations lie within the borders of ancient
Athens. Initial excavations uncovered remains dating as far back as
12,000 years ago, including bathhouses, aqueducts, a sarcophagus
and a room filled with oil lamps. Tunneling rather than surface
excavation was used at stations near archaeological sites.
Photographs and replicas of some interesting finds will decorate
stations in the area of the excavations.
</P>
<P>
   For information, contact the Greek National Tourist
Organization, 645 Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10022; (212)
421-5777.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury Riverboat to Ply Lochs and Highlands
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish Highlands will become more accessible when the
refurbished 50-passenger 150-foot riverboat Lord of the Glens goes
into service between Inverness on the east and Oban on the west of
Scotland in September. Short enough to negotiate the locks of the
60-mile Caledonian Canal, the vessel will be the first luxury
passenger boat to carry overnight passengers the 200 or so miles of
what is called the Great Glen, including crossing Loch Ness.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel has been outfitted with mahogany paneling and brass
fittings and has a dining room with picture windows, a topside
lounge with panoramic view, a library and a gift shop. Cabins
feature twin beds, a desk, color TV and bathrobes.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-night package, including seven nights aboard the boat, two
nights at the Balmoral Hotel in Edinburgh and a night at the
Cameron House Hotel on Loch Lomond, is offered by Thomas P. Gohagan
&AMP; Co. of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   After touring Edinburgh Castle and Holyrood House in Edinburgh,
passengers cross the Highlands by bus to Inverness to board the
Lord of the Glens. During the cruise, they will stop at the
Culloden Battlefield and Cawdor Castle and at Fort Augustus, from
which they will travel by bus and ferry to the Isle of Skye.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $4,595, plus $125 tax, to $6,195, plus tax,
depending on hotel accommodations and departure date, and include
round-trip air fare from New York. Information: (800) 922-3088.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `Silent Service' Marks its Centennial
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history, the Navy's fleet of submarines has been
known as ``the silent service.'' During the Cold War especially,
when American submarines lurked beneath the world's oceans in
pursuit of Soviet warships and secrets, the fleet's operations _
its disasters and successes _ were known only to a few.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the fleet celebrates its 100th anniversary, the Navy has
lifted the cloak of secrecy a bit. As part of its ``Submarine
Centennial,'' the Navy is sponsoring a yearlong series of
ceremonies, open houses and exhibitions around the country to honor
the fleet _ and not incidentally, in a time of declining defense
budgets, to make a case for its future.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece is an exhibition at the National Museum of
American History in Washington. Called ``Fast Attacks and Boomers:
Submarines in the Cold War,'' the exhibition examines the history
and lore of the submarine fleet from 1945 to 1991 _ a time of
superpower tensions, intrigue and occasional derring-do.
</P>
<P>
   On display are objects from five submarines, including four
fast-attack submarines, whose mission was to locate and track the
enemy, and one boomer, the larger class of submarines that carry
nuclear ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has declassified some artifacts especially for the
exhibition, like control panels and a model of a propeller from the
1960s-era Sturgeon class of submarines. Some of the displays will
try to recreate the extraordinarily claustrophobic quarters of even
the largest submarines.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition opens with a private ceremony on Tuesday, 100
years to the day that the Navy established its submarine force with
the purchase of a gasoline-powered submarine built by John P.
Holland. It opens to the public a day later and will run through
April 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, part of the Smithsonian Institution, is on the Mall
at 14th Street and Constitution Avenue. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy is also sponsoring smaller exhibitions at submarine
museums across the nation _ from the Growler, which is docked at
the Intrepid Sea Air and Space Museum in New York, to the Maritime
Museum in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In June there will be an international flotilla of submarines
visiting Norfolk, Va., followed by another in Pearl Harbor the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has posted a full list of events at www.navy.mil.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Steven Lee Myers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
