<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWSUIT SAYS CAMPAIGN DONATIONS TO JUDGES ARE
UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A group of lawyers and consumer advocates filed
a federal lawsuit here Monday claiming Texas' system of electing
judges _ viewed by some as the most notorious in the nation _ is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of lawyers and parties with cases pending before
the court making political donations to sitting judges, while legal
under state law, violates the constitutional guarantee of a fair
trial, lawyers bringing the case said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because judges must raise money both to obtain their seats and
hold onto them, no judge can break free of the appearance of being
beholden to the contributors,'' said Tom ``Smitty'' Smith, head of
the state chapter of the Public Citizen interest group.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Supreme Court rulings have prohibited even the appearance
of a bias. Smith and the other plaintiffs have asked the court to
stop all judicial elections starting in 2001, a move that would
force Texas lawmakers to devise a new method of choosing judges.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Browne, a spokeswoman for the Texas attorney general,
said she had no comment until the office had a chance to review the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Thomas Phillips of the Texas Supreme Court issued
a statement that read: ``It's a bad system that impairs public
confidence in the courts. But in a democratic society, repair of it
should be by the Legislature and the people and not by federal
court order.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three elections, Supreme Court justices raised a
combined $11 million, according to Cristen Feldman, staff attorney
for Texas for Public Justice, a judicial watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   These donations have worn away the public's and the legal
community's confidence, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 survey by the State Bar of Texas and Texas Supreme
Court, only 1 percent of Texas attorneys said they believed
campaign contributions had no influence on judicial decisions,
while 79 percent said donations had either a very significant or
fairly significant influence.
</P>
<P>
   That contributions are legal is somewhat preposterous, Smith
said, especially considering the restrictions placed on attorney
contact with jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a grounds for mistrial if a attorney were to hand
a cup of coffee or a tissue to a juror, but, ironically, it is not
for a judge to receive a significant campaign contributions from
one of the parties to the case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State law limits the size of contributions to Supreme Court
justices, lower appellate and trial judges in large counties.
Individuals can give no more than $5,000 and law firms no more than
$30,000, and political action committees are capped at $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are 14 states that elect either local, appellate or
supreme court judges, said Allison Zieve, a Public Citizen attorney
in Washington, who will be a co-counsel on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rightly or wrongly, Texas has become the poster child for this
sort of system of financing elections,'' she said. ``For various
reasons, Texas has become the most notorious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
