<HEADER>
A6087 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CANDYBAR-CRIME-HNS &LR;      04-03 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDYBAR-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOCOLATE CRAVING LANDS THIEF 16-YEAR SENTENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Tyler, Texas, thief, whose first crime was stealing Oreo
cookies as a teen-ager, has been sentenced to 16 years in prison
for stealing a Snickers candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Dude Payne III's tough sentence for a chocolate craving
that normally would have meant a shoplifting charge is the result
of a life of crime, albeit mostly nonviolent crimes, prosecutors
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's kind of goofy when people look at it,'' said Smith
County prosecutor Jodi Brown. ``It wasn't about stealing a Snickers
bar, it was about a lifestyle essentially. ... It was a lifestyle
that he chose and has been choosing since he was 16 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentence for the December theft at a Tyler mom-and-pop store
was handed down last month under the state's habitual offender law.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest, Payne also possessed a bag with less
than 2 ounces of marijuana, a charge that got him a 180-day jail
sentence after he pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Payne had no money when he was arrested, and Brown said he told
police he took the candy bar because he ``knew if (he) went up to
the owner and asked him to give it to (him), he'd say no.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he went to trial last month, Brown asked the jurors to
sentence Payne as a habitual criminal for a minimum of 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old man's criminal history dates to 1987 when he was
16 and was first arrested for stealing the cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Then he moved up to tools, another misdemeanor crime that earned
him jail time, and a misdemeanor assault, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way he also did state prison time, earning a four-year
sentence for felony criminal mischief shortly after the cookie
theft, another four-year stint for a 1988 credit-card theft and a
10-year sentence for a 1993 credit-card theft. He was released on
mandatory supervision, a type of parole, in December 1998 after
serving about 4 1/2 years on the 10-year sentence, said prisons
spokesman Glen Castlebury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pain in the butt to have in your neighborhood, but he's
not dangerous,'' Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she had been concerned the jury might feel sorry for
Payne and buy his attorney's argument that it was only a candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's lawyer, Linda Altier of Tyler, did not immediately
return a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he needed to be taught a lesson,'' Brown said. ``I
think that the community needs to see that regardless of what you
go in and steal, if you engage in that type of lifestyle then
that's what you're risking.''
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said Payne will not be eligible for parole for at
least four years.
</P>
<P>
