<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-HENNESSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN HENNESSY, COMPUTER ARCHITECT, NAMED PRESIDENT OF STANFORD
UNIVERSITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Underscoring Stanford University's deep
relationship with Silicon Valley, John Hennessy, the provost and a
professor of electrical engineering and computer science who
founded a semiconductor company, was named president of the
institution on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A well-known computer architect who has taught at Stanford for
22 years, Hennessy, who is 47, was appointed provost last July.
</P>
<P>
   Within months he had secured a $150 million donation to the
university, the largest since its founding, from James H. Clark, a
former colleague in the computer science department who went on to
found the Netscape Communications Corp. The money is being used to
develop Hennessy's pet project, an interdisciplinary program in
biomedical engineering and sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy, who founded MIPS Technologies, a semiconductor
company, also co-wrote with David Patterson, a professor at the
University of California at Berkeley, a seminal textbook on
designing computers, Computer Architecture: A Quantitative Approach
(Morgan Kaufmann Publishers, 1990).
</P>
<P>
   Despite Stanford's connections to the very start of Silicon
Valley _ when former Stanford students William Hewlett and David
Packard began an electronics company in a garage in Palo Alto _
Hennessy is the university's first president with an engineering
background.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming provost, he was the popular dean of the school
of engineering, where he developed the school's first online degree
program _ a master's in electrical engineering _ and increasingly
offered online classes. His appointment as president was expected;
Stanford has a long history of appointing leaders from within.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy will succeed Gerhard Caspar, a constitutional law
scholar who announced his retirement in September after eight years
leading the university. Caspar, who said he plans to take a
sabbatical then return to teaching, transformed Stanford into one
of the most effective fund-raising universities in the world,
stabilizing a university that had been accused of bilking the
federal government for research. Caspar directed Stanford's most
comprehensive cost-cutting efforts in 30 years, remade the
undergraduate curriculum and oversaw a $1 billion construction,
preservation and restoration program.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday afternoon, an ebullient Hennessy said he
planned to continue to ``build on the foundation'' that Caspar
created.
</P>
<P>
   One issue Hennessy faces as a Silicon Valley president is
assuaging concerns that Stanford is becoming a ``techie'' paradise
at the expense of its humanities and social science departments. An
editorial in Monday's Stanford Daily urged him to make a special
commitment to the humanities.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy said that he intends to devote attention to the fields,
including using his connections in Silicon Valley to help the
humanities and social science departments secure more support for
their programs. ``I think there are a lot of entrepreneurs who come
from these backgrounds and appreciate their importance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge, Hennessy said, is keeping and recruiting
faculty to the most expensive housing market in the country. The
university must also keep students from being seduced by the
high-paying lures of Silicon Valley companies before earning their
degrees, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The university is finishing a housing study he commissioned as
provost, he said, to address ways to develop housing that faculty
could afford. As for retaining staff and students, he said: ``We're
in the heat of the gold rush. After a little while it will calm
down a little bit. There will still be a lot of students interested
in entrepreneurship and the new economy. But they'll want to get
their graduate studies done first. I fully believe that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
