<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., April 9)  
(jt) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biking in Wales
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm planning a biking trip to Wales and would like some
information on the route between Cardiff and Holyhead, as well as
suggestions on camping. _ MarySue Wyndom, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A. The 288-mile stretch of the Welsh National Cycle Route
between Cardiff in South Wales and Holyhead in North Wales is part
of a 9,000-mile network of bicycle and hiking routes being
constructed across Britain. The entire trail system is scheduled to
be completed by 2005; the section between Cardiff and Holyhead was
finished in the late '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the route follows unused railway tracks, quiet backroads
and trails. It also goes through the centers of historic towns and
cities like Cardiff and Hay-on-Wye, and past historic sites like
the 13th century Caernarfon Castle, overlooking the Menai Strait.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the terrain is gentle, there are also more
challenging sections like those that run through Brecon Beacons
National Park, the Cambrian Mountains, Snowdonia National Park and
along Wales' rugged coastline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sustrans, the civil engineering company that is building the
trail system, can provide you with maps and a brochure for $9.50,
plus $6.35 postage (at a rate of 63 pence to the dollar). They can
be ordered by calling (44-117) 929-0888, or through the Web,
www.sustrans.org.uk. You can also request another free booklet,
published by the Wales Tourist Board but available from Sustrans,
called ``Cycling Wales.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the camping sites along the Cardiff-to-Holyhead route are
the following:
</P>
<P>
   In North Wales, Bryn Cynan Fawr Farm, Caernarfon, is a small
family campground on a 40-acre farm on the A499 road. It is open
from June 30 to Sept. 30. Sites range from $8 to $16. Information:
(44-1286) 830320.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In central Wales, Ynysymaengwyn Camp Site, The Lodge,
Ynysymaengwyn, Tywyn, is set on the wooded grounds of an old manor
house on the A493 between Tywyn and Dolgellau. It is open April 1
to Oct. 31. The sites are $9.50 for two people. Information:
(44-1654) 710684.
</P>
<P>
   In South Wales, there is Brynich Caravan Park at Brecon on the
A470 near the A40 junction. It has 60 sites, costing $13.50 to $15
a night. Information: (44-1874) 623325.
</P>
<P>
   New Baltic Ferry
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you know anything about a new fast ferry between Helsinki
and Tallinn? _ Jonathan P. Duvale, Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   A. Silja Line, a Finnish shipping company, is introducing ferry
service between Helsinki and Tallinn, the capital of Estonia,
cutting the crossing time in half. Starting April 17, the
Italian-made SuperSeaCat IV, traveling at about 42 miles an hour,
will make three round trips daily. The one-way crossing will take
an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The 328-foot monohull ferry is equipped with a T-foil, an
under-water wing that works as a stabilizer. It seats 752
passengers on 2 decks, and can carry 164 cars and 4 buses.
Facilities include a bar and cafeteria, a duty-free shop and
observation area overlooking the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry will depart Helsinki at 7:30 a.m., 1 p.m. and 5:30
p.m. Return trips depart Tallinn at 8:45 a.m., 2 p.m. and 6:30
p.m., local time.
</P>
<P>
   From June 16 to Aug. 14, an additional trip will depart Helsinki
at 9:30 p.m. and Tallinn at 10:30 p.m. The fare is $24 one way, $12
ages 6 to 17. Cars are an additional $18.
</P>
<P>
   For information: contact Silja's U.S. representative, Norwegian
Coastal Voyage/Bergen Line Services, (800) 323-7436.
</P>
<P>
   Avignon for Children
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I, along with our two boys, ages 5 and 7, will
be spending two weeks this summer near Avignon, France. Do you know
of any activities or attractions that might be suitable for our
children? _ Lynne Clarence, Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. You're not going to find any big theme parks in the vicinity
(something that may come as a relief), but your children are likely
to have a grand time exploring the lovely town of Avignon and the
surrounding Provencal countryside.
</P>
<P>
   In Avignon itself, there is the Papal Palace, on the Place du
Palais des Papes, the seat of Christianity and home to nine popes
in the 14th century. The sprawling Gothic structure, with its 10
crenelated towers and massive walls, was built as a citadel during
an age of strife, and bears more resemblance to a fortress than a
religious structure. Built atop the Rocher des Doms, it soars above
the city and is certain to capture any child's imagination. At 6.9
francs to the dollar, admission is $6.50, $5.20 for children 7 and
over. Information: (33-4) 90.27.50.74.
</P>
<P>
   Avignon's white-and-gold tourist train leaves from the square in
front of the Papal Palace. A half-hour ride through the city costs
$5; a 15-minute trip up to the gardens surrounding the Rocher des
Doms costs $1.45. Information: (33-4) 90.82.64.44.
</P>
<P>
   While exhaustive museum visits may not be suitable for small
children, the permanent collection at the Natural History Museum,
67, rue Joseph Vernet in Avignon, with displays on local geology
and fauna, may hold more immediate appeal. Admission is free.
Information (33-4) 90.82.43.51.
</P>
<P>
   Grands Bateaux de Provence offers boat trips along the Rhone.
The excursions range from short jaunts around Avignon to lunch and
dinner cruises and daylong excursions to Arles. Prices are from $6
to $40 a person. Information: (33-4) 90.85.62.25.
</P>
<P>
   Biking is a popular activity during the summer months. Although
the countryside is quite hilly to the north of Avignon, the city is
surrounded by gentle terrain, and there are plenty of small local
roads that see little traffic. Bicycle rentals for adults and
children are available at the Cycles Peugeot Aymard shop, 80, rue
Guillaume Puy, in Avignon. Day rates are $8.75 during the week,
$12.50 on weekends. Information: (33-4) 50.86.32.49.
</P>
<P>
   Near the town of Roquemaure, about seven miles north of Avignon,
there is a small amusement park with rides and games, called
Amazonia. It is open on weekends from late March through October.
The admission fee is $10. For information, call (33-4)
66.82.53.92. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're there in July, you may want to check out Avignon's
international theater festival, which includes outdoor performances
near the Papal Palace. For a schedule and general information,
contact the Avignon Tourist Office, 41, cours Jean Jaures,
telephone (33-4) 32.74.32.74.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
