r l BC-MEN-HEALTH-WEB-COX     04-03 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-HEALTH-WEB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To learn more about men's health
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  healthcentral.com features such self-help items as a life
expectancy calculator.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  menshealth.com features excerpts from Men's Health magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  drkoop.com/family/mens features a search engine by topic, as
well as articles on everything from stress and anxiety to diet and
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``How Men Can Live as Long as Women'' (Kenneth Goldberg,
Summit Publishing Group, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Manly Weight Loss: For Men Who Hate Aerobic Dance and Carrot
Stick Diets'' (Charles Poliquin, Dayton Publications, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKLETS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ``Men's Maintenance Manual,'' a 33-page guide to men's
health, sponsored by the American Academy of Family Physicians as
part of National Men's Health Week, June 14-20; call
1-800-955-2002.
</P>
<P>
   AND FOR WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   This month's issue of ``Men's Health'' magazine recommends women
conduct a physical on their men. Three tips:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sleep apnea: Instead of elbowing him, listen to how your mate
is snoring. If there are periods of silence, followed by gasps or
snorts, he may have sleep apnea.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heart murmur: Listen to your man's heart between the sternum
and left nipple. You should hear a distinct lub-dub; if you hear a
shhhh or a whoosh, similar to the sound made when softly blowing
out a candle, a valve may not be sealing properly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Skin cancer: Carefully examine his skin for dark moles or
pearl-colored bumps. Use your fingertips to feel for lumps or
crusty patches of skin.
</P>
