<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT04-COX     04-03 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE FINDS MICROSOFT BROKE ANTITRUST LAW
 &HT;    950&AMP;add. With MICROSOFT-BUSINESS, MICROSOFT-COST,
MICROSOFT-REMEDIES, MICROSOFT-HIGHLIGHTS and MICROSOFT-JUDGE.
Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. broke the nation's antitrust laws
by placing ``an oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive
fortune'' to target rival firms that threatened its software
monopoly, a federal judge ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By finding that Microsoft has used illegal means to dominate one
most dynamic sectors of the U.S. economy, U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson opened a new stage of the trial that would
set ``remedies'' _ including possibly the breakup of the world's
most valued software company.
</P>
<P>
   Although a negotiated settlement is still possible, Microsoft
pledged to appeal the ruling, potentially prolonging the legal
struggle for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The historic ruling flowed from Jackson's blistering ``findings
of fact,'' issued last November, in which he branded Microsoft as a
predatory monopolist that for years had run roughshod over
competitors, strong-armed clients, harmed consumers and throttled
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   In equally scathing terms, Jackson's ``conclusions of law''
Monday spelled out how Microsoft had violated both sections of the
110-year-old Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft mounted a deliberate assault upon entrepreneurial
efforts that, left to rise or fall on their own merits, could well
have enabled the introduction of competition into the market for
Intel-compatible PC operating systems,'' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the evidence does not prove that they would have
succeeded absent Microsoft's actions, it does reveal that Microsoft
placed an oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive fortune,
thereby effectively guaranteeing its continued dominance in the
relevant market.
</P>
<P>
   ``More broadly, Microsoft's anticompetitive actions trammeled
the competitive process through which the computer software
industry generally stimulates innovation and conduces to the
optimum benefit of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 43-page ruling, Jackson concurred with three of the
government's four key contentions over how Microsoft had violated
the law.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that the company had unlawfully maintained its Windows
operating system monopoly, unlawfully tied its Internet Explorer
Web browser to the operating system and entered into numerous
unlawful exclusionary agreements to the detriment of its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not find Microsoft guilty of seeking to monopolize
the Internet browser market at the expense of Navigator, the rival
product of Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court concludes that Microsoft's multiple agreements with
distributors did not ultimately deprive Netscape of the ability to
have access to every PC user worldwide to offer an opportunity to
install Navigator,'' Jackson found.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Jackson's long-awaited decision, lawyers for
both sides will gather again in the judge's chambers, probably
Tuesday, to map the schedule for the next stage of what is by now
nearly a two-year-long legal process.
</P>
<P>
   At any stage of this process, the litigants could decide to try
once more to settle the case, this time likely through direct
negotiations. Barring such a settlement, the U.S. Supreme Court
might be forced to rule in what is likely to be its most important
antitrust decision since the breakup of the Standard Oil trust in
1911.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials and some state attorneys general
raised the prospect that they make seek to impose interim sanctions
against the software giant while the appeals process moves forward.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, at a press conference on Microsoft's Redmond, Wash.,
campus, chairman Bill Gates said the company may seek an expedited
appeal, perhaps ahead of Jackson's remedy rulings in the wake of
Monday's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gates on a day in which his personal fortune fell by some
$11.5 billion as Microsoft stock tumbled by 15.5 per cent: ``While
we will continue to look for new opportunities to resolve it, we
believe we have a strong case on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   A half hour earlier on the other end of the continent, Attorney
General Janet Reno said: ``We are pleased that the court agreed
with the department that Microsoft abused its monopoly power, that
it violated the antitrust laws, and that it harmed consumers.
Microsoft has been held accountable for its illegal conduct by a
court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's antitrust chief, Joel Klein, who has personally steered
the case through the courts, said: ``This landmark opinion ... will
also set the ground rules for enforcement in the Information Age.
It demonstrates once again that no company, no matter how powerful
or how successful, can refuse to play by the rules, and thwart
competition for America's consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's verdict came two days after extensive efforts to reach
an out-of-court settlement collapsed. Hoping the litigants could
strike a deal, Jackson had delayed issuing his ruling while Richard
Posner, chief judge of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Chicago, sought in vain to hammer out an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the aborted negotiations as ``very complex,'' Iowa
Attorney General Thomas Miller, a frequent courtroom visitor, said
many factors led to the breakdown, but ``the position of the states
was not the cause of the failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, immediately available on the Internet, was issued
an hour after the major financial markets closed in a session that
saw Microsoft stock battered. At close of trading, it had lost 14.5
percent of its value on the day, or $15.37 a share, to fall to
$91.88 on volume of 125 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat toppled Microsoft from the top, leaving it as the
world's third most valued company, at $474 billion, behind General
Electric and Cisco Systems and contributing to the largest biggest
one day loss ever on the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ruling serves as an important milestone in a historic
action brought nearly two years ago by the Justice Department at 19
state attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing 76 days of testimony from the bench and reviewing
scores of post-trial briefs, Jackson essentially upheld the
government's original contention that Microsoft had illegally
leveraged its Windows monopoly to to try to crush its rivals and
bully its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's verdict enhances the standing of some 115 class-action
lawsuits that have already been filed by on behalf of Microsoft
customers and potentially opens to the door to many more. The
guilty verdict hands plaintiffs valuable legal ammunition to pursue
these civil suits over Windows pricing and related issues. If
successful, they could result in the award of triple damages.
</P>
<P>
   But William Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel, said, ``it's
not so clear to us that a judicial decision ... translates into a
decision in these class-action suits.'' He suggested the lawsuits
may be put on hold while Microsoft pursues its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's settlement proposal, rejected out of
hand by Microsoft last week, could still be revived by Jackson in
the remedial phase of the trial, which is likely to yield one more
courtroom drama to hear oral arguments.
</P>
<P>
   In its proposed consent decree, the government called for strict
and enforceable rules on what products could be bundled with
Microsoft's flagship Windows software. Other demands were aimed at
preventing Microsoft from retaliating against personal computer
manufacturers that used something other than Windows in their
computer offerings or supported competing technology.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had made three key concessions during negotiations,
which proved insufficient but which nevertheless are likely to be
revived by the company in the next stage of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   It offered to sell Windows at a standard price to all comers,
thereby eliminating the discounts which some less favored computer
maker viewed as biased. It also offered to open up the secret
Windows program source code to its rivals and to sell a version of
Windows separate from the Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft now faces months of uncertainty before the remedies
are imposed and years more in pursuing the appeal process, which is
likely to reach the Supreme Court even as if continues to contest
the swarm of the civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   Like the nation's cigarette and gun industries in America,
Microsoft must wage a struggle to preserve its markets even as it
fights a potentially crippling battle in the legal arena. But
unlike tobacco and firearms, which are relatively static
commodities, the software business continues charge constantly,
putting an added burden on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens from here on in the courts, Microsoft can
expect to see a phenomenal flow of income from Windows for some
time to come,'' said William Janeway, a senior managing director of
Warburg Pincus Equity Partners, a venture capital firm with large
investments in the high technology field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the key problem that Microsoft faces has little to do with
the courtroom,'' Janeway added. ``It is that the industry is
quickly moving into a new space the features Internet servers and
mobile devices. And in this space, Microsoft is just another player
and not such a strong player at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
