<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND04-COX     04-03 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just call Harvey a child of the '60s
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Atlanta citymag ($3.95) says in its profile of one of
Atlanta's most controversial attorneys, most criminals would kill
to have Bruce Harvey on their side. And most of them have. Writer
Alice Welsh Doyle goes behind the ever-present ponytail to reveal
more about the lawyer who thrives on high-profile, unpopular cases.
(He defended convicted mail bomber Walter Leroy Moody and is
currently representing Teri Lynn Peterson, who is accused of
killing her 5-year-old nephew Terrell Peterson.) Moody says he's
simply a product of the '60s. ``I had the hair and tattoos before I
became a lawyer,'' he says. And the flamboyance Harvey exhibits in
the courtroom is all part of the show, says Gwinnett County
District Attorney Danny Porter. ``All trial lawyers put on shows.
...You have to make the jury believe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jaws, revisited: Twenty-five years after Peter Benchley chased
everybody out of the water with his novel about a great white
shark, the writer has had a change of heart. ``I couldn't possibly
write `Jaws' today ... not in good conscience anyway,'' he writes
in the April 2000 issue of National Geographic ($3). When he wrote
``Jaws,'' Benchley says, it was accepted as fact that great whites
ate people by choice. ``Now we know that almost every attack on a
human is an accident,'' he says. Benchley and underwater
photographer David Doubilet will provide a close-up view of sharks
Sunday at 8 p.m. on National Geographic's Explorer on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roberts rules: No, Julia Roberts' picture didn't make the
cover of Rolling Stone ($3), but she has appeared on the front of
nearly every other magazine lately. The actress does get ample
coverage inside with a lengthy conversation with Chris Heath, who
culls questions and answers from Roberts' grueling three days of
press interviews to promote her movie, ``Erin Brockovich.'' After
fielding the usual questions about cleavage and her boyfriend
Benjamin Bratt, Roberts opens up about everything from her
relationship with her late father to how she felt when she was in
school in Georgia. ``I was considered completely common and
average...''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diamond darlings: GQ ($3) correspondent Peter Richmond
profiles three of baseball's biggest superstars in a cover story on
shortstops Derek Jeter, Alex Rodriguez and Nomar Garciaparra. The
one thing they have in common besides class, Richmond writes, is
``a love of the game the way it was meant to be played, free of
frills.'' And, in ``Duh and Dumber,'' Alex Richman analyzes the
country's obsession with ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and
decries the lowering of our standards from tough questions in an
isolation booth to multiple choices with help lines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The final frontiers: Time and Newsweek (each $3.50) tackle big
science topics this week. Newsweek's cover story reports on the
Human Genome Project, the race to determine the exact chemical
sequence that constitutes the DNA in every cell of the human body.
The completion of that task, expected in June, promises to
revolutionize medicine and biotechnology. And in the latest of five
special reports on ``Visions for the 21st Century,'' Time ponders
whether humans will ever live on Mars, travel to the stars, meet
alien intelligences, learn how to time-travel, clone dinosaurs and
other fascinating science-fictional questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
