A6097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH04-COX     04-03 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush aims to clear environmental record with new proposal; Penn.
governor good VP match, some say
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush swung through tactically
critical Pennsylvania on Monday touting his alliance with its
popular governor and a new environmental initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe Bush may have found an ideal running mate in
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, a pro-abortion rights Catholic and
Vietnam veteran who is in a good position to deliver this state's
23 electoral votes in November.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, using a former steel plant as a backdrop, Bush
laid out a plan aimed at bolstering his environmental image, which
critics say is murky at best.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed a six-point plan that would speed up redevelopment
of polluted industrial sites and abandoned factories called
brownfields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosperity will mean little if we leave to future generations
a world of polluted air, toxic lakes and rivers and banished
forests,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal to redevelop abandoned industrial sites while
maintaining greenspace could help blunt criticism of his
environmental stewardship in Texas, where air pollution in Houston
recently surpassed that of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   By addressing an issue that Vice President Al Gore has
championed since 1993, Bush continued his effort to coax support
from the type of Democrat and independent voters who liked former
candidate Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bush and Gore in a statistical dead heat and Bush has
said that he intends to fight hard in Pennsylvania, with the
59-year-old Ridge at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pennsylvania is a big, somewhat complex state and (Ridge) is
highly regarded,'' said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the
Annenberg School of Communication at the University of
Pennsylvania. ``He has worked well with the Legislature. He has
been a very successful governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Credentials such as Ridge's could help Bush capture swing votes
while muting questions about Bush's own military experience, which
included a stint in the Texas Air National Guard when many of his
peers, like Ridge, were in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush campaigned in New Jersey and Wisconsin with two
other frequently named possible V.P. contenders _ Gov. Christine
Todd Whitman and Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   States such as Wisconsin and Pennsylvania, both of which hold
primaries today, are critical because Gore and Bush already have
divided the rest of the country. Gore is strong in the Northeast
and in California _ a delegate powerhouse _ and Bush dominates the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania also has rabbit's foot appeal. Since 1960, all but
one presidential contender who has won the state has also seized
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a competitive, two-party state ...,'' said Terry
Madonna, director of the Center for Politics &AMP; Public Affairs at
Millersville University. ``If Gore appears too liberal, then Bush
will win the blue collar, working class Catholics in the mining and
mill towns of southwestern Pennsylvania. If Gore can make Bush
appear right wing, way out on the limb, then (Bush) loses the
suburban voters in the Philadelphia suburbs. The balance hangs on
being the centrist and making the other candidate appear to be out
of the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush called on the Environmental Protection Agency to develop
clean-up standards that are more flexible than those under the
Superfund program and to protect developers who meet the new
standards from future federal litigation. Bush also wants to
permanently extend a brownfield clean-up tax incentive set to
expire Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Superfund program, created two decades ago to clean
up polluted industrial sites, has had limited impact. A General
Accounting Office study found that 595 of the nation's 1,231
Superfund sites have been cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign Monday attacked Bush's support for allowing
plants to voluntarily reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of whitewashing can cover up Bush's record,'' Gore
spokesman Doug Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
