<SLUG> BC-VIDEOS-STARWARS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will `The Phantom Menace' be a Force in video?
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's back _ again. ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' last year's No. 1 box office hit, which amassed $922.6
million in ticket sales worldwide, arrives in video stores today.
But even some of the most die-hard ``Star Wars'' fans are starting
to say the ``Phantom'' party's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little burned out,'' says Carl Cunningham, 28, of
Acworth, an IBM staffer in Marietta and longtime ``Star Wars''
collector. ``When you have a wedding, you plan a party and end up
with a hangover and a headache. This was like a party we had for 16
years _ and the hangover lasts longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Cunningham will still buy a ``Phantom'' video for his
daughter Taylor for her sixth birthday Saturday. ``The cheap
pan-and-scan version. She won't know the difference.'' Plus, he'll
try to snag one of the life-size Yoda figures that Blockbuster will
give away at each of its stores in metro Atlanta at drawings to be
held Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I was heavily into it, there was no way to collect
all the fast-food toys,'' Cunningham says. ``It was like last
mid-August when I started to feel like `Stop, stop bombarding me
with this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham says he saw ``Phantom'' at the theater 16 times. ``It
was the 16th time that I decided I was disappointed in the film
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some video store managers have a sense that the public would
rather ``see dead people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think `Phantom Menace' is going to be as big as `The
Sixth Sense,''' says Chuck Tintle of Dunwoody Versatile Video.
``The Sixth Sense,'' the Oscar-nominated movie with its own
life-size Yoda _ Haley Joel Osment _ was released on video last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Tintle's store has 48 copies of ``Phantom'' and 66 of ``The
Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   On Internet site reel.com, ``Phantom'' is selling for $16.99 in
standard VHS format and $33.99 for a wide-screen collectors'
edition that includes a behind-the-scenes documentary and
commemorative 35mm film strip. The movie is not yet available on
DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
