<HEADER>
A6098 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-TURKS-CARIBBEA     04-03 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TURKS-CARIBBEAN-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELAXING LIKE A CELEBRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., April 9)  
(jt) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frankly, I was seduced by the brochure. After all, I had never
been to Parrot Cay, the new Caribbean resort in the Turks and
Caicos Islands, nor did I have friends who had visited. But my
husband, Tim, and I were both exhausted and, this January,
desperately wanted to indulge ourselves with a world-class rest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I worried. Parrot Cay, with 56 rooms and 2 restaurants,
was the only thing on the 1,000-acre island: no shops, no night
life. How much could we read and how much could we swim? If we
didn't like the other guests, how could we avoid them? The price
was high, and the food, the amenities and the service were
unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   So I had an alternative plan: use our itinerary through Miami to
the Turks and Caicos as an escape hatch. I told myself we could
always retreat to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But our spirits lifted enormously when Bandele Neutelings, the
charming wife of the general manager of the resort, picked us up at
the airport on Providenciales, the busiest of the country's roughly
40 islands, for the drive to the harbor and the boat ride to Parrot
Cay. Her enthusiasm for the islands and the hotel was palpable.
</P>
<P>
   And when we stepped off the resort's cabin cruiser onto the
Parrot Cay dock, I immediately scrapped my backup plan. As a golf
cart whisked us up to the main house atop a 55-foot hill _ the
highest in the islands _ we felt ourselves entering a deliciously
exotic South Seas atmosphere. And we stayed enveloped in it until
the day we left. In fact, my phone calls to friends, advising them
to try it as soon as possible, were the biggest additional charges
on our bill, with the possible exception of pina coladas.
</P>
<P>
   The brochure had shown a room with a four-poster bed draped in
white mosquito netting. There was a view through a bedroom door
framed by white curtains wafting onto a balcony that looked out to
a chartreuse, lime and slate-blue sea: the vast, mirror-still
infinity swimming pool seemed to touch the edge of a horizontal
belt of white sand.
</P>
<P>
   There were no guests in the photos, only a housekeeper fluffing
pillows and a smiling waitress bearing drinks. The illusion was
that Parrot Cay would be our own private island paradise. The
reality came close to that illusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the white stucco main house, which is the center of the
hotel's public space, light poured through floor-to-ceiling windows
over the earth-tone tile floors and the low, simple Balinese style
furniture. From the front desk, there was a sweeping view in one
direction out to the thin line of white breakers crossing the coral
reef. Behind was the almost deserted island of North Caicos _
separated from Parrot Cay by just a few hundred yards of quiet
water so shallow you can walk across at low tide.
</P>
<P>
   In the adjoining octagonal room was a large, round bar,
surrounded by deeply upholstered white sofas. A wide flight of
stairs led down to the dining room, where guests could dine either
indoors or on the broad patio.
</P>
<P>
   With only a handful of cars, no jets overhead and few
speedboats, Parrot Cay seemed strangely silent. There were no signs
announcing dinner hours, events or trips. Few guests wandered by.
It was several days before I learned that we were not the only ones
who had been seduced by the vision of Parrot Cay's desolate beaches
and the promise of sailing, snorkeling and being pampered in a spa
offering six types of massages, as well as body wraps and yoga with
a private instructor.
</P>
<P>
   There were celebrities all over the place. They just were rarely
visible. Paul McCartney and his daughter Stella were there, halfway
through a three-week stay. One afternoon, I saw Raquel Welch
lounging on a white chaise by the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Then I caught a honeymooning Jerry Seinfeld and Jessica Sklar
deep in conversation over lunch. The actor Judge Reinhold and Amy
Miller, also on their honeymoon, checked in shortly after we did,
and Liam Neeson, his wife, Natasha Richardson, and Aidan Quinn
arrived toward the end of our stay.
</P>
<P>
   Even Welch, who was on the boat with us when we left, marveled
at the roster of celebrities. ``I have never seen so many in one
place,'' she said. ``They all come for the privacy, and the
beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   For these people, the lure of a private island away from prying
paparazzi surely was a large part of its appeal. Yet while the
hotel may be remote, it offers elegance without formality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I designed it for people who were past the point of needing to
wear two watches and Cartier jewelry by the pool,'' said Keith
Hobbs, the resort's interior designer, in a telephone call from
London after our stay. ``These people want to go back to shorts and
relax, which is why it has attracted a number of superstars. They
don't have to change three times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   My husband put on a blazer just once during our stay, and then
only because the evening was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Parrot Cay was created in 1988 by a wealthy Kuwaiti, who built
the main house and the series of long, white two-story stucco
buildings with barrel tile roofs and Saltillo tile floors. The
buildings tumble down the hillside to the sea and house about 40
guest rooms. But the Gulf War came, the Kuwaiti's finances went,
and the hotel stood empty.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a Singapore couple, B.S. and Christina Ong, bought the
island, redid the main hotel and added six bungalows along the
beach, where the celebrities hid out. They opened the resort in
December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Ongs have kept the 48 guest rooms simple. In eight two-story
buildings, the rooms are spacious, with high peaked ceilings and
gently whirring fans. There are no upholstered armchairs, oversize
armoires or television sets (unless you request one). Indonesian
teak furniture is set on terra-cotta tile floors, and bright white
linens and shuttered windows add a Caribbean flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the simplicity masks an awareness of how to pamper spoiled
guests _ skills learned well by the Ongs, who also own the
Metropolitan and the Halkin hotels in London and four Four Seasons
properties, in Singapore, the Maldives and Bali.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
