<HEADER>
A6099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-CLASS04-COX     04-03 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CLASS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruling could trigger new suits vs. company
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling Monday against
Microsoft will strengthen lawsuits now pending against the company
and spawn even more, antitrust lawyers predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling will have a significant impact in terms of
creating a road map of liability against Microsoft in other
cases,'' said Kevin Grady, an antitrust lawyer for the Atlanta firm
Alston &AMP; Bird. ``And, certainly, a strongly worded order will
probably bring a lot of other cases out of the woodwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of lawsuits have already been filed against the company.
These include class-action cases filed by Microsoft's wholesalers
and distributors, suits filed by competitors of the software
company and a number of consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling from Judge Jackson is going to make it a lot easier
because it will be admissible in cases like ours,'' said San
Francisco lawyer Terry Gross. He filed suit against Microsoft on
behalf of consumers and companies, contending they paid too much
for the Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers in the California case will try to introduce
Jackson's ruling into evidence under the legal doctrine of
``collateral estoppel.'' This doctrine allows a ruling in another
case _ such as the federal antitrust case in Washington before
Jackson _ to be admitted in a similar case in another jurisdiction.
Because the issue before Jackson already has been litigated by
Microsoft, it should not be contested again, plaintiffs' lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The force of Jackson's ruling in these other cases, however,
will have limited effect until Microsoft's appeals run the gamut.
Only if Jackson's ruling is upheld can it be used persuasively in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the plaintiffs' lawyers are expecting the judge's ruling
will improve their position on liability against Microsoft or on
damages, or both,'' said Atlanta lawyer Martin Chitwood, who
specializes in class-action cases.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates has called these types of
class-action cases ``piling on.'' He has predicted his company will
prevail on appeal and contended that Microsoft has charged the
lowest price possible for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But Gross countered that the class-action complaints are being
filed because of the violations exposed in the federal antitrust
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These lawsuits are not being filed because we're piling on,''
the San Francisco attorney said. ``It's because the federal
antitrust action has turned over the rock under which Microsoft was
hiding evidence of its illegal monopolistic actions.''
</P>
<P>
   California is one of only 17 states that allow state court
antitrust lawsuits by consumers and companies that have not bought
their products directly from the company.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Supreme Court decision in 1977 barred federal lawsuits by
so-called indirect purchasers. For example, a consumer who bought
Microsoft software from a retailer cannot sue Microsoft on
antitrust grounds in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, Microsoft's competitors are sure to be poring
over Jackson's findings.
</P>
<P>
   When deciding valid antitrust claims, the courts first determine
the total amount of commerce generated by the company found to have
violated the law. The courts then calculate what percentage of
business it cost the company that suffered the harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If upheld, this ruling could be very valuable to Microsoft's
rivals,'' Atlanta lawyer W. Pitts Carr said. ``In a case like this,
looking at it from a damages standpoint, you're talking about
enormous, enormous numbers, potentially billions and billions of
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-TURKS-CARIBBEA     04-03 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TURKS-CARIBBEAN-2NDTAKE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and Bali.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each room had not only the requisite terry cloth robes, but also
flip-flops and oversize straw bags that were so attractive we saw
two of them on the plane going home with guests who'd bought them.
The TV we requested (which was free) had 20 channels via satellite
and a built-in VCR for movies from the hotel's ample library _ no
sign outs, no rush returns. Music CD's were similarly abundant and
accessible for the CD players that were also available on request.
</P>
<P>
   Our private, covered second-floor balcony had an ocean view and
was painted a clean white and equipped with a coffeepot, cups, a
refrigerator and full minibar. So when we woke early, we made our
coffee outdoors, curled up on the oversize rattan chaise longue and
watched the sun creeping up over the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Parrot Cay has two tennis courts, lighted for night play. There
are also bicycles, extra tennis rackets, nimble little 16-foot
catamaran sailboats, kayaks, and equipment and experts for scuba
diving and snorkeling. But the lapping waves, the pale blue sky and
white sand beach mostly inspired us and the few other guests we saw
to sit under canvas umbrellas napping, reading or just staring at
the sea. After several days, when I passed the exercise pavilion
and saw people working out, I was mystified at their ability to
expend such energy.
</P>
<P>
   We took an hour here and there to skim along the beach a few
hundred yards offshore on one of the hotel's three little
sailboats. We went snorkeling, too, along the inner edge of the
coral reef line that runs parallel to the the shore nearly a mile
out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   There, in perhaps 20 feet of water, iridescent red, blue, yellow
and green tropical fish meandered cautiously near the dark safety
of coral nooks and caverns, just out of reach of the few solitary
silver barracudas cruising silently by. Nyoman, the Balinese who
took us to the reef, assured us that snorkeling in Bali was even
more beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   But my favorite pastime was walking up and down our milelong
beach (there are two others on the island) and standing there alone
at the end of the day watching the sun go orange and sink into the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   There was no rush to lunch or dinner. The two restaurants _ one
poolside, just back from the beach, and the other in the main house
_ were never crowded. We alternated between always promptly
delivered breakfasts on our balcony and a breakfast buffet on the
main-house terrace with its Florida keystone balustrade.
</P>
<P>
   The chef, Rajah Pillay, who has worked at several Four Seasons
hotels, told us he prided himself on homemade croissants and pain
au chocolat. But the health-minded could choose from a buffet with
cereals, yogurt, fruit juices and omelets.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch was served at the open-air pavilion by the pool, where the
menu included Caesar salad, penne and club sandwiches. Every day,
there was grilled fresh local lobster or other local fish; only the
tuna and salmon were imported.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner alternated between the main house and the open-air dining
room. One evening, as torches illuminated the sky and reggae music
played softly, we feasted on pan-fried crab cakes and roasted
Chinese duck breast.
</P>
<P>
   Though many guests dined in their bungalows, those who stopped
at the bar in an old stone building by the sea often got into
conversation, but evenings ended early. The single night we agreed
to have dinner with another couple, even setting a time to meet
seemed vaguely pressured.
</P>
<P>
   Such languorous and luxurious living came at a high price. The
five-day package, for instance, included an oceanfront room, three
meals, transportation costs between Providenciales and the island,
an excursion and a bottle of champagne, and cost $4,100 for two.
</P>
<P>
   Like most hotels, Parrot Cay has different packages. Generally,
however, with a modified American plan (breakfast and dinner),
nightly rates range from $620 for a garden room to $850 for an
ocean view. Bungalows are more. There was no charge for our
bicycles, tennis or sailing (or for many of the resort's other
activities).
</P>
<P>
   But the competition for indulgences was intense. Booking a
massage that week had to be done early _ I booked two days ahead. I
opted for a no-frills Swedish massage ($100) made especially
wonderful because my masseuse, Kate, who had left her job in London
to work at Parrot Cay, came to our room. But at dinner, a couple
raved about the Balinese massages.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered a secret place on the island, too: the spa. It
consists of two small wood bungalows, one with a number of
treatment rooms and the other a single large room that can be
reserved for private yoga classes. From its own small infinity
pool, there was a view across the narrow strait to North Caicos.
The hotel's architect, Rolf Rothermel, an Englishman who lives on
Providenciales, told me that the stillness of the water and the
rarity of boats on the channel made the view his favorite on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Parrot Cay has its glitches. The hotel has yet to heat the
swimming pool, which can be quite chilly on a breezy day. Some
guests complained of insect bites. Though I had some, they were a
minor annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that if you can fly five hours to a place that feels
like your own South Seas island retreat, then the not
inconsiderable cost is worth every penny. In fact, the only
negative emotion I experienced all week was regret at the thought
of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   From Miami, American Airlines, (800) 433-7300, www.aa.com, flies
jets twice daily to Providenciales. The Parrot Cay resort arranges
for guests to be driven to the harbor for the half-hour boat ride
to Parrot Cay.
</P>
<P>
   THE RESORT
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a single private home, the
Caribbean-Indonesia style Parrot Cay is the only residence on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   There are 48 rooms and 3 bungalows that each have two
one-bedroom suites; a pair of two-bedroom beach houses have private
pools. There are two restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel offers sailing, tennis, snorkeling, fishing and
excursions to nearby islands, included in the rates. Golfers can
take the resort's boat to Providenciales, where there is an 18-hole
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Oceanfront rooms are $850 a day and garden view rooms $620,
including breakfast, dinner and airport transfers. Dinners are
about $70 a la carte, with wine.
</P>
<P>
   The Romantic Getaway package costs $4,100 and includes five
nights in an oceanview room, all meals, a bottle of champagne,
travel to and from the airport and an excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Parrot Cay, Box 143, Providenciales, Turks and Caicos Islands,
British West Indies; (877) 754-0726 or (649) 946-7788, fax (649)
946-7789; www.provo.net/parrotcay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
