<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-03 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: PROTESTING MUGABE
</P>
<P>
   An opposition group vowed to begin 100 days of prayer meetings
and peaceful demonstrations to protest the policies of President
Robert Mugabe, and his governing party. The decision by the
National Constitutional Assembly came after thugs attacked its
peaceful march over the weekend, injuring several people. The
group, which blamed the police for failing to prevent the violence,
has criticized official corruption, the unraveling economy and
Mugabe's support of black squatters on white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO QUIZZED
</P>
<P>
   A five-member team from the attorney general's office questioned
former President Suharto at his home about corruption during his
32-year rule. The session ended after 90 minutes when Suharto said
he was tired. He has defied summonses to appear at the attorney
general's office for questioning, saying he is too ill.
</P>
<P>
   LAOS: BLAST TIED TO TERRORISTS
</P>
<P>
   Authorities blamed unspecified terrorists for an explosion at
the Thank You Very Much Restaurant in the capital, Vientiane, that
it said wounded six Western tourists and two Laotians. Such acts
are rare in the capital but bandits and the remnants of
anti-Communist Hmong insurgents do operate in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: CURRENCY WEAKENED
</P>
<P>
   Reported drought damage to opium crops has further battered
Afghanistan's weak currency and driven money-changers in Kabul to
try to dump the local currency in favor of hard currencies. A
bumper harvest last year established Afghanistan as the world's
leading source of opium, the U.N. estimates. Afghanistan relies on
opium, the raw ingredient for heroin, as its primary export.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: HOLOCAUST TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss man who denies Hitler's gas chambers existed has gone on
trial on charges he violated Switzerland's anti-racism law.
Gaston-Armand Amaudruz, 79, is being tried in Lausanne for writing
that there was no evidence of the Holocaust's gas chambers. A 1995
Swiss law makes it illegal to deny or justify genocide. If
convicted, Amaudruz, a spokesman for a far-right group, faces up to
three years in jail and a $25,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: EX-PREMIER PAYING BACK TAXES
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Charlie Haughey, 74, will sell off family
properties to pay more than $1.2 million in back taxes, including
interest, on gifts received from a supermarket executive while in
office. Haughey's fall from grace reached a low last year when he
was booed by spectators at the funeral of a previous Fianna Fail
party leader. He is currently on trial for obstructing a 1997
tribunal looking into payments to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: RIGHTIST DATA
</P>
<P>
   The number of neo-Nazi and right-wing extremists declined from
about 54,000 in 1998 to around 51,000 in 1999, the Federal Agency
for the Protection of the Constitution said in an official report.
The number of rightists deemed likely to commit acts of violence,
however, grew by about 10 percent to 9,000, the agency said, adding
that recorded violent attacks by far rightists reached 746, up from
708 in 1998. Germany's seven million foreigners are considered
particular targets of those attacks.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SPYING ON KOHL
</P>
<P>
   The former head of East Germany's foreign espionage service,
Markus Wolf, said in an interview with Reuters that his agents had
known for a long time about the illegal slush fund set up by the
Christian Democrats under former Chancellor Helmut Kohl. But he
said he made little use of the information because he considered
all capitalists to be corrupt.
</P>
</TEXT>
