<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS' CREDIBILITY QUESTIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Beyond any harsh scoreboard reality is the threat
of the Clippers losing a credibility they probably never had.
</P>
<P>
   The pointing finger can be found in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the Biggest Apple, one NBA columnist has deduced that the
healing of Maurice Taylor's ankle and Lamar Odom's calf muscle
could have an intentional link to the team's future in the May 21
NBA Draft lottery. Two recent unexpected and unexplained Chicago
victories have the Clips poised to finish the season with the
league's fewest triumphs and the most Ping-Pong ball combinations
needed to grab the top pick.
</P>
<P>
   One fly in the ointment of such nasty ink is the anticipated
list of available talent. With no Tim Duncan-type suspects on the
horizon, the top candidate for No. 1 selection has been Cincinnati
power forward Kenyon Martin. Martin, projected by scouts to be a
defensive monster with limited offensive chops, must recover from a
broken leg in time to maintain his No.1 status. But he's no
franchise messiah.
</P>
<P>
   A second problem with the theory of intentional Clipper defeat
was underscored by Taylor, who has promised to scram via free
agency at the stroke of Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I help 'em?'' said Taylor about taking one for the
team he plans to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, by the way, practiced at full speed Monday and plans to
play in tonight's game with Utah at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel cool,'' said Taylor, who has missed five game with the
bad left wheel. ``I feel better than I thought I was going to feel.
You have to give it (ankle) a chance to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom might have seconded that motion in regard to his left calf,
if he had attended the Monday morning workout. He didn't, but was
expected to receive therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fined,'' said interim coach Jim Todd, who indicated
that the rookie probably didn't realize he was expected to report
for inactive duty. ``He'll be at shoot-around; it's possible he can
play tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom has missed three consecutive games with the injury and like
his teammates had Saturday and Sunday off. So did center Michael
Olowokandi, who arrived about an hour late Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
