<HEADLINE>
$1.3 MILLION FOR NONPROFIT GROUP; THREE NEW POLLS; ANTI-ASBESTOS
ADS; EXPENSIVE STATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   $1.3 MILLION FOR NONPROFIT GROUP
</P>
<P>
   A nonprofit group allied with the House majority whip, Rep. Tom
DeLay of Texas, raised $1.3 million in 1998 from five donors,
including one that contributed $1 million, according to tax records
reviewed and reported on Monday by Roll Call, a Capitol Hill
newspaper. The group, U.S. Family Network, run by Robert Mills, a
former campaign manager for DeLay, was created under section
501(c)4 of the tax code, which means the names of donors do not
need to be publicly disclosed, though their contributions are not
tax-deductible. The group's largest known supporter is the National
Republican Congressional Committee, which contributed $500,000 in
1999. U.S. Family's records for 1999 will not be filed until
November. Public records show that the group has lobbied Congress
for four years on issues like prayer in public schools, although
Roll Call reported that U.S. Family Network officials did not
formally register as lobbyists until February.
</P>
<P>
   THREE NEW POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas holds an 18-point lead over Vice
President Al Gore in the latest poll on the presidential race taken
in Indiana and a 4-point lead in the latest Pennsylvania poll. But
a poll from Wisconsin has the two men in a dead heat. In the
Indiana poll, in which The Indianapolis Star surveyed 825 voters on
March 26-29 (margin of error plus or minus 3.5 percentage points),
Bush led 54 percent to 36 percent, with Pat Buchanan getting 4
percent and 5 percent undecided. In the Pennsylvania poll, in which
The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette surveyed 855 voters March 28-30 (margin
of error plus or minus 5 points), Bush led Gore 44 percent to 40
percent, with Buchanan getting 5 percent and 11 percent undecided.
In the Wisconsin poll, in which The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel
surveyed 574 voters March 9-23 (margin of error plus or minus 4
points), Bush and Gore were tied at 46 percent each, with 8 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-ASBESTOS ADS
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos legislation in Congress is the latest subject to find
its way into issue advertising in this year's campaigns. In
Minnesota, a coalition of labor, environmental and consumer groups,
along with trial lawyers, is behind a television advertisement
against Sen. Rod Grams. Grams, a Republican seeking a second term,
is a co-sponsor of the bill that would set up a system to screen
asbestos victims and essentially allow only the seriously injured
to be compensated. The advertisement flashes a 1964 photo of
Minneapolis plant workers, a dozen of whom have since died from
asbestos-related disease, and accuses Grams of ``pushing
legislation to let the asbestos companies off the hook.'' Gram's
campaign manager, Pat Fiske, would not comment on the
advertisement. Its producers say similar commercials may be used in
the districts of as many as 20 House and Senate co-sponsors, many
of whom face tough re-election battles. One commercial was
broadcast in January in Montana against Conrad Burns. Burns and
Rep. Rick Hill, both Montana Republicans, later withdrew their
support for the asbestos bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXPENSIVE STATE RACE
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive state Senate race in Texas history is
developing east of Houston in Senate district 13. At stake is the
Republicans' razor-thin 16-15 majority in the Texas Senate and the
ability to select Lt. Gov. Rick Perry's successor if Gov. George W.
Bush should become president. Perry, who could also lose control of
the Senate if a Democrat won the seat, said in a fund-raising
letter on behalf of the Republican candidate, ``This contest is
personally important to me.'' State Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, head
of the Senate Democratic Campaign Committee, told The Dallas
Morning News that the race would determine which party ``has the
political power in Texas.'' State Rep. Todd Staples, the
Republican, and the Democrat, David Fisher, a lawyer, spent heavily
to win their respective primaries for the vacant seat, and experts
say strong statewide interest in the race could push expenditures
for the campaigns to between $4 million and $8 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
