<P>
   MICROSOFT-RULING (Washington) _ A federal judge rules that the
Microsoft Corp. violated the nation's anti-trust laws by illegally
using its dominant position in the computer software industry to
stifle competition and hurt consumers in an attempt to
``monopolize'' the Internet browser market. By MARK HELM. (Also
filed in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ The Supreme Court declines to consider
the constitutionality of a state law that makes it easier for
neighbors and school administrators to discover whether a convicted
sexual offender is within their midst. In addition, the justices
agreed to decide if the government can bar federally funded lawyers
for poor people from lobbying against strict welfare laws without
violating the attorneys' constitutional right to free speech. By
STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-RESTRUCTURING (Washington) _ The Southeastern Legal
Foundation, a conservative law firm, urges the dismantling of the
U.S. Census Bureau, claiming it violates citizens' privacy. The
firm, which won a Supreme Court decision last year limiting use of
a Census sampling plan, proposes two new agencies to replace the
bureau. By AUSTIN ZALKIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
