<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-WEST04-COX     04-03 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WEST04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs `quietly confident' against L.A.
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Not long ago, Jerry West said he considered the
San Antonio Spurs favorites to win the NBA championship _ missed
jump shots, minor defensive warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   West, the Los Angeles Lakers' executive vice president, figures
Tim Duncan and David Robinson are that imposing, adept enough to
compensate for other deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   West is an astute basketball man who carefully measures his
words. You take him seriously. And yet, too many times you've
watched the Spurs plod along on offense. When the University of
Wisconsin dragged basketball back into the 1950s last week, the
Spurs were already there waiting with a tray of milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why ``favorite'' is not a word Spurs Coach Gregg
Popovich associates with his team. ``Discombobulated'' and
``clueless'' were commonly used by Popovich only a few weeks ago.
After all, Duncan and Malik Rose were injured, and Sean Elliott was
still trying to again approval for his return after a kidney
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Another championship? Popovich worried that he was about to
watch his team slide all the way to seventh place in the West, a
skid greased by inefficient offense and defense more generous than
statistics would indicate. The Spurs couldn't make the necessary
plays at either end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   With two weeks left in the regular season, we're still not sure
if West overestimated the Spurs or if Popovich's worst fears have
merit. His team now alternates between fourth and fifth place in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the uncommon circumstances under which Elliott
works, the Spurs can only be viewed as an interesting and inspiring
story.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they look downright spry, at least as much as can be
expected from a team old enough to get into the movies for half
price. They won five straight games, including victories in Seattle
and Portland on consecutive nights last week, before losing at
Miami on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, San Antonio ranks 21st in the NBA in scoring,
thanks mostly to perimeter players less reliable than your old
Pinto.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Spurs advance in spite of that. As expected, when they
make any forward movement, Duncan and Robinson have provided the
push. Duncan no longer is working through an injury-induced
decrease in production: 16.8 points and 8.0 rebounds during eight
games after he returned from a strained lower abdominal muscle. In
his last seven games, Duncan averaged 25.6 points and 14.4
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has been forceful since January, dismissing any notion
that damaged knees and a sore back might finally torpedo the
Admiral's career. The Spurs center averaged 13.4 points during his
first 27 games. He has improved to 19.9 points during the last 43
games, relying more on a running hook shot in the lane and the
innate quickness available when he is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, the Spurs should be watched with a mix of
anticipation and skepticism during the final nine games of the
regular season. Elliott, just 10 games into his comeback, is still
the Spurs' best defender on the perimeter, a role he must play
against the Lakers' Kobe Bryant, Portland's Scottie Pippen and
several others. Elliott hopes next to rediscover his offensive
skills, a goal he moved toward with three three-point baskets at
Miami on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs also need help from backup guard Terry Porter, who
returned Sunday after missing 13 games with a knee injury. When
healthy, Fourth-Quarter Porter gives the Spurs a reliable shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have two games left with West's Lakers, winners of 28
of their last 29 games _ Saturday in L.A. and April 19 in the
Alamodome. They split their first two games, with the Lakers
winning by six at home and the Spurs by 24 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs might match up better with L.A. than does any other
team. Shaquille O'Neal is the clear choice for MVP, but he can
guard either Duncan or Robinson, not both. O'Neal incurred foul
trouble trying to stop Duncan during the game in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is why some Spurs have at least a partial view from
West's vantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a great chance, I really do,'' Elliott said.
``A lot of guys on the team are quietly confident we can throw
something together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
