<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6114 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-CONSUMER04-     04-03 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CONSUMER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At consumer PC level, changes will be subtle
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the earth shifted for Microsoft as a company
with Monday's ruling, consumers should not expect immediate changes
in how Windows _ Microsoft's most visible and important product _
works.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will a walk down the aisles of the computer store be any
different tomorrow. Any drastic changes in the marketplace would
come after the penalty stage of the antitrust case, which will
come, at the earliest, this summer. Even then, a lengthy appeal
process is likely and could further delay things.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, too, that no one knows just what changes the
courts might force Microsoft to make. That would be part of the
penalty stage. But there are some likely scenarios that affect the
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key issues of the antitrust case was the fact that
Microsoft included its Web browser _ Explorer _ as a built-in part
of Windows. Microsoft said that was a necessary technological
improvement. Some competitors and the government charged that
Microsoft was taking unfair advantage of Windows' dominance.
Windows has about 85 percent of the market as an operating system,
the software that teaches your computer to be a computer.
</P>
<P>
   If it was Microsoft's intent to hitch its browser to Windows'
star, it worked. In 1996, Explorer had just 18 percent of the
market, and the Netscape Navigator browser had almost all the rest.
In 1998, when the antitrust suit was filed, Explorer had 50
percent. It has more than 60 percent of the market today.
</P>
<P>
   It's probable that the courts will force Microsoft to separate
Explorer and Windows. It's possible Microsoft might be required to
include _ right on the disc that Windows comes on _ copies of
competing Web browsers. With that help from the courts to create a
level field for competing browsers, there may be more innovation.
</P>
<P>
   However, something a lot less pleasant for consumers could also
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Explorer and Navigator are available free for the
downloading on the Internet. Ironically, competition could change
that.
</P>
<P>
   Some competing browsers, such as one called Opera from Oslo,
Norway-based Opera Software, already are distributed through
commercial channels. Opera costs $35. If the emphasis in the
marketplace shifts from getting as much free distribution as
possible to using expensive resources and manpower to create the
best commercial product, users could end up being forced to pay for
any browser that they choose _ including Explorer and Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   The next possible remedy from the courts would be to require
that Microsoft make the inner workings of its Windows software
available to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   That's important, since Microsoft also sells the leading word
processor, Word, and the leading spreadsheet program, Excel.
Competing word processors and spreadsheets for PCs have to be
designed to operate using Windows, and that creates a real
advantage for Microsoft. It knows just how future versions of
Windows will work and can get a head start creating the programs
that work with it.
</P>
<P>
   But the courts could require that Microsoft keep competitors in
the loop, making the code _ the program language itself _ freely
available.
</P>
<P>
   Before the dominance of Windows, the marketplace was crowded
with word processors and spreadsheets. Help from the courts to
competing companies almost certainly would mean a shift in the
marketplace balance back to the days of more competition, more
products.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is one thing to keep in mind while forecasting
the future of technology: The drive has always been for a standard.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when there were competing versions of VCRs _ VHS
and Beta _ the marketplace eventually settled on one standard, VHS.
Standards are needed because businesses and home users want
products that work seamlessly with the software that they power. In
the case of VCRs, that was movies. In the case of computers, it's
programs.
</P>
<P>
   So it is unlikely that the dominance of Windows will go away.
While there are challengers, the most notable being Apple's
Macintosh operating software and the increasingly popular Linux
operating system, the odds are that Windows _ because of the head
start it now has _ will remain a familiar sight on most computer
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
