<HEADLINE>
PROSPECT OF ISRAELI PULLOUT INCREASES ANXIETY ON ISRAELI-LEBANESE
BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note) (ART ADV:  Photo NYT34  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FATMA PASSAGE, Israeli-Lebanese Border _ Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Monday that he did not expect a military confrontation
after Israeli troops withdraw from southern Lebanon this summer,
and that he foresaw no need for a significantly larger
multinational peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   But here on the border, the commander of Israel's southern
Lebanese allies radiated anxiety about the consequences of the
planned withdrawal for the residents of a region that has been a
proxy battleground for Middle Eastern adversaries. The commander,
Gen. Antoine Lahad, wearing soft white leather loafers and a
worried expression, said defiantly that his forces would not
disband and flee but stay put and ``defend their land unto the
death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to stay in their homes,'' he said of his people.
``They want to die in their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   As Barak moves steadily closer to his July deadline for ending
the Israeli occupation of southern Lebanon, his hopes for doing so
in the context of an Israeli-Syrian peace agreement are fading
fast. Speaking sanguinely in Jerusalem Monday, he addressed a
rising concern that a unilateral troop withdrawal could produce
violent chaos in the border region or even provoke a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that there is an immediate danger of a
flare-up of any kind,'' he said, expressing determined confidence
that Israel's military strength, combined with international
support for its withdrawal, would discourage any attempt to
escalate the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The military forces in this border region have moved into full
preparation for a complete shake-up of the decades-long balance of
power in the nine-mile-deep buffer zone. Locked in their war rooms,
the Israeli army, the South Lebanese militia, the U.N. forces and
the Hezbollah, or Party of God, guerrillas are all devising battle
plans, and end-of-battle plans.
</P>
<P>
   At the physical heart of the security zone conflict is the
Israeli-backed South Lebanese Army commanded by Lahad, who strongly
opposes a unilateral pullout by Israel. ``If it is Israel's
decision to leave without security or peace established, well, then
it is Israel's decision,'' he said at a briefing sponsored by the
Israeli army. But he also said Monday, for the first time since the
Israeli Cabinet voted to withdraw the troops, that he and his
fighters had decided not to abandon their struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Lahad said he had changed his mind about seeking asylum abroad
now that the possibility of Israeli-Syrian and Israeli-Lebanese
agreements are dimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm responsible not only for the South Lebanese Army, but for
the 70,000 to 80,000 people in the area,'' said the general, who
was widely believed to be contemplating a new life in France, where
his family lives. ``I would be viewed by them as a traitor if I
left now.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace agreements would presumably have spelled out the future
for the population of the security zone and for the 2,500 fighters
of the South Lebanese Army, many of whom have been convicted of
treason by the Lebanese military courts and sentenced in absentia
to punishments including death.
</P>
<P>
   Without such agreements, Lahad said his soldiers would defy
Lebanese forces seeking to regain control of the area unless they
were granted amnesty for their convictions in absentia. Using a
very strong analogy, he mentioned the ``Masada precedent,''
referring to the ancient Jews who committed suicide on a hilltop
above the Dead Sea rather than be taken captive by Romans.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli journalist, Yoram Hamizrahi, who used to be a
commander in southern Lebanon, said on the Israeli radio Monday
that Lahad's extreme statements ``should not be taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Lebanon, they say, ``There is no tax on words,''' he said.
``Antoine Lahad is not going to kill himself. There is not going to
be any Masada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who believes that the SLA, which is supported by the
Israeli army, can suddenly turn into an army of heroes that can
fight on its own against Hezbollah _ anyone who believes that is an
utter fool,'' Hamizrahi said. ``Yet Antoine Lahad's statements
today are dangerous because they hint that the fence will not be
closed, they hint that southern Lebanon will remain under Israeli
patronage.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat out of sync with Lahad's thinking, a senior Israeli
military official made an unequivocal pledge Monday on behalf of
Israel to take care of the southern Lebanese. Standing by the side
of his South Lebanese Army counterpart, Brig. Gen. Beni Ganz said
Israel would be ready to absorb the entire population of the
southern Lebanon security zone if it sought refuge in Israel. Ganz
quickly said that it was more a statement of principle than a
concrete plan, because most of the Lebanese have no desire to
become refugees in Israel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the Israeli army is believed to be scouting locations for
the resettlement of South Lebanese Army soldiers _ in the northern
towns of Nahariya and Metulla, for instance _ and to be negotiating
with third countries to relocate some high-ranking officers.
</P>
<P>
   In Metulla, eight Israeli employers have banded together to seek
government permission to sponsor the relocation of their 100
southern Lebanese workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to tell you how terrified they all are,''
said Miriam Hod, 49, who owns the Bet Shalom Motel. ``They're sure
they're going to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can barely function, they're so worried. I think that the
state of Israel has a moral obligation towards these people. There
is going to be a massacre there. I am the daughter of Holocaust
survivors, and I know we have to do something to save them.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to such anxiety, Ganz said he believed that the
withdrawal would take place in the context of some kind of
``arrangement,'' if not a peace agreement. He presumably referred
to an arrangement with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   And Barak said his confidence that violent chaos would be
averted was partly inspired by his ``memory of how effective the
Lebanese were in disarming other militias and pacifying other parts
of Lebanon.'' He said he believed that the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon, which comprises 4,500 troops, would be able to handle the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure that there will be a need for any extra
forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen, who stood by Barak's
side Monday, added that he did not believe that U.S. troops would
get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Barak continued: ``If there is a will, there is a way to solve
this issue. But we are not going to lead it. We will pull out to
the border out of our own interests, and we will defend Israel and
its interests from our borders. We don't have a claim on a single
square mile of Lebanese territory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
