<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If breakup occurs, company, consumers benefit
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What we learned through most of the last century was
that virtually all attempts to destroy the monopolistic hold of big
companies had several outcomes, all good for the economy, and in
reasonably short order.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup of the Rockefeller empire 90 years ago unleashed
huge growth in oil and enriched the holders of securities as each
of the individual parts of Standard Oil prospered on its own.
</P>
<P>
   As we have recalled frequently, the breakup of American
Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. into regional parts, and separating the
equipment and product development businesses, enriched
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T shareholders enormously.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases smart, smaller companies burst forth with growth
when the canopy of the big company was removed. The breakup of the
Rockefeller oil colossus gave us a wealth of new refined oil
products and services, and ultimately cheaper energy.
</P>
<P>
   The dissolution of the rigid old motherly phone company gave way
to younger, smarter managers and allowed the regional phone
companies to grow with the fast-stepping service area, then branch
into global enterprises like wireless communication.
</P>
<P>
   In all cases the consumer came out ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Why should the ``breakup'' of the Microsoft grip on computing
and telecommunications be an exception?
</P>
<P>
   That's the theory of Jagdish Sheth, the deep thinker about
marketing at business strategy at Emory's Goizueta Business School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that regardless of the details, if the government
succeeds in breaking up the Microsoft monopoly, the company wins,''
Sheth said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Charles Brown, chairman of AT&AMP;T, complained bitterly
about government intervention in his company's affairs during the
years leading to that breakup, only to see the whole Bell family
enriched, bitterly critical Bill Gates will come out richer and
probably happier, Sheth said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because all shareholders will likely come out well, and
Gates is the biggest shareholder of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: While we all know Microsoft as the software mogul
that created the Windows operating system and dominates that field,
Microsoft has, in fact, been changing. The company has been
changing into a service company, not just a maker of software to
run computers.
</P>
<P>
   The company has become a major player in the Internet portal
business, powering MSN into a site behind only America Online and
Yahoo. It has helped to produce other sites and to address urban
markets, even one offered in conjunction with BET to address
African-American interests.
</P>
<P>
   It has invested in cable services, with a strong leaning toward
wireless and satellite applications.
</P>
<P>
   As Sheth sees it, Microsoft will fight like a tiger to protect
its Windows franchise, possibly stretching the combat out for
years. It's enormously profitable _ why not?
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the company will likely be ceaseless in
probing service ideas in the area of wireless communication,
delivering high-speed communication as well as video by way of
television. All of these services need software, Microsoft's strong
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, as portal developer, is already a competitor with
AOL. It is possible, many analysts believe, that the company could
evolve, as AOL has, into a pipeline company that devises numerous
ways to deliver to homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In time it could become a merger partner, too, as AOL has with
Time Warner, and be ready for a content provider to help fill not
just pipelines but the air _ with wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   As it probes the markets, looking for innovative ways to grow,
Microsoft becomes more exciting, more of a live wire in the vast
new merged business of telecommunications, video and wireless
communication. It becomes a company more enticing to the best minds
in digital technology and the marketing of services.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk to the Goizueta Business School recently, Gary
Hamel, the Harvard futurist, talked about the differences between
old-line companies, wedded to theories of slow, incremental growth,
and the nimble small companies devoted to innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably Microsoft, threatened with becoming an incremental
company, weaving its annual upgrades of Windows, has turned a
corner and is now becoming more the innovator, thinking outside its
old box, under the guidance of the new Bill Gates, chief of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   So the reality is, we don't have to wait years for the outcome
of a federal lawsuit to glimpse the new Microsoft. It is at hand,
and we have only to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
