<HEADLINE>
USA TODAY REDESIGN TONES DOWN IMAGE AND CUTS PAPER COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost two decades after the splashy birth of USA Today, with
its vivid colors and snappy graphics, Monday's issue introduced a
makeover with pages and sections designed to present a more sober
image.
</P>
<P>
   The redesign of USA Today, which was six months in the planning,
also includes a reduction in the web size of the paper _ the width
of a paper roll from which four pages are produced _ from 54 inches
to 50. This change will save USA Today's owner, the Gannett Co., 7
percent on the newspaper's paper costs, said its publisher, Tom
Curley.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we're trying to do is come up with a cleaner
look,'' he said of the redesign, which was done by Richard Curtis,
who also created the original design in 1982. ``We didn't want to
shout at readers as much as we had in the past. There's a conscious
effort to tone it down. In a white-hot media market, where all the
media are shouting, we really want to tone it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The new web configuration means the width of each page will be
reduced by about an inch and expanded in length by a half-inch,
Curley said. USA Today has also shifted to a taller and narrower
typeface. These combined changes, Curley said, will mean eight
inches more of text on each page, while preserving legibililty.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today is following other large newspapers in reducing the
size of pages to save on the cost of paper and ink. In 1998, The
Washington Post narrowed the size of its pages, and more recently
The Boston Globe started to make the shift.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe, which is owned by The New York Times Co., is
converting its presses to produce smaller newspaper pages from a
54-inch web size to 50. Some of its readers are already getting the
new versions, though The Globe is not expected to complete the
conversion until September, when the makeover will be introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reduction to a 50-inch size seems to be something that a
lot of newspapers are doing, prompted by the savings that occur,''
said Richard Gulla, a spokesman for The Globe. ``Our thinking was
that while we were going to this size, a new graphic design will be
more friendly.'' He said the paper has a redesign almost 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times also considered reducing the size of its page
width but decided to continue printing the newspaper on a 54-inch
web size, said Nancy Nielsen, a spokesman for the company.
``Maintaining our size supports the needs of our advertisers and
readers who look to The Times as a distinctive national
newspaper,'' she said. ``The extra space gives them a broader
canvas for ads and content.''
</P>
<P>
   Before it shifted to a narrower size, USA Today held focus
groups among readers to gauge reaction of a new look. Curley said
readers were willing to expect some change, though not if it meant
shifting features to different places. He said the basic section
features would remain in the same places.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has really been a two-pronged effort,'' Curley said,
calling newsprint USA Today's biggest single expense. ``Saving 7
percent is large and needs to be considered,'' he said. ``Secondly,
we had not done much in redesign in the 18 years since it was
started. So we were at a point to make some changes there as
well.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
