<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLLUTION-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CALLS FOR MAKING CLEANUP OF CONTAMINATED SITES EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa.)  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ Unveiling his first set of detailed
environmental proposals since he began his presidential campaign,
Gov. George W. Bush announced a plan Monday to spur the cleanup of
contaminated, abandoned industrial sites by easing certain federal
regulations, protecting redevelopers from federal liability and
giving states broader discretion over the use of federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The sites, known as brownfields, are especially prevalent in and
near cities, and Bush said that excessive federal interference had
created a disincentive for companies to rehabilitate these
properties and instead encouraged them to seek out undeveloped
sites for their factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old system of mandate, regulate and litigate only sends
potential developers off in search of greener pastures _
literally,'' the Texas governor said in a speech at a manufacturing
plant in Aliquippa, outside Pittsburgh, that was built on newly
purified ground. ``Brownfields get passed over, while greenfields
get paved over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that he and other Republican governors had launched
successful initiatives to stem that trend, but had done so almost
in spite of the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't wait for Al Gore to wave his magic wand to clean up
our environment,'' Bush told reporters at a news conference
immediately following his speech. ``We cleaned it up ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks and proposals represented his first serious foray
as a presidential candidate into an area of policy that many
political analysts view as a potential liability for him. By
several environmental measures, Texas ranks as one of the most
polluted states in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor has been using the early weeks of his general
election campaign to stake out issues, like education, that often
receive more attention from Democrats and are often used as wedges
against Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And he did not seem the least bit daunted by the fact that the
vice president claims his expertise on the environment as one of
his greatest strengths. Gore even wrote a best-selling book,
``Earth in the Balance,'' on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that Gore was too wedded to bureaucratic federal
solutions and cast himself as someone who better understands the
need to foster business growth while still maintaining a respect
for the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every environmental issue confronts us with a duty to be good
stewards,'' Bush said. ``As we use nature's gifts, we must do so
wisely. Prosperity will mean little if we leave future generations
a world of polluted air, toxic lakes and rivers and vanished
forests.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore said that Bush's actions in office belied those
words, and they immediately dismissed his plan, which they
acknowledged they had not yet digested, as an attempt to divert
attention from his environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of whitewashing can cover up Bush's bad record on
the environment,'' said Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway added that on an array of environmental problems,
including brownfields, ``you can bet that more progress would be
made with a trusted, long-term environmentalist at the helm rather
than someone who's tied so closely to the oil companies and
polluting industries in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Weiss, the political director for the Sierra Club, an
environmental advocacy group, said that he feared that Bush's call
for federal cleanup standards with more flexibility translated into
a desire to relax those regulations in ways that might endanger
public health.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton administration officials said that they had already
put into effect several aspects of Bush's plan, including tailoring
cleanup standards for brownfields to the intended use of the
property. A site slated for a manufacturing plant, for example,
would have to meet less rigid criteria than a site slated for a
school.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental officials estimate that there are about 450,000
brownfields nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that his plan would allow flexibility in
rehabilitating those properties only after establishing high
standards for any and all cleanup projects. His goal, he said, was
to allow and encourage state and local governments to devise
innovative solutions to the problem, rather than miring them in red
tape.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said that he also wanted to enact legislation to
grant developers who met national standards while rehabilitating
properties protection from federal liability if the site is later
deemed to be contaminated and the contamination was not the
developers' fault. Such liability, he said, scares developers away.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush proposed that existing federal funds for the
rehabilitation of brownfields be focused more intensely on the
development of new cleanup technologies; that federal loan programs
for such cleanup projects be transformed into block grants for
states, to be administered according to states' more flexible
regulations; and that a current tax incentive for such projects be
extended permanently. That incentive is due to expire at the end of
2001.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The governor squarely challenged the notion that Gore would be a
better protector of the environment by criticizing aspects of the
Clinton administration's environmental record and extolling
elements of his own.
</P>
<P>
   He said that many industrial sites and parks owned by the
federal government violate environmental standards with impunity
and that he, as president, would order them to comply with the
environmental laws that apply to privately owned land.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he cited a program he began in 1995 that he said
has led to the rehabilitation of brownfields in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These successful state programs show that America needs a
different vision where what counts is what you do, not what you
promise,'' Bush said. ``The old vision distrusts markets. It
distrusts local government. It distrusts solutions that do not
originate in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his case in a largely industrial state that promises
to be one of the fiercest battlegrounds in the general election.
Partly because Pennsylvania is considered to be up for grabs, its
Republican governor, Tom Ridge, is one of the names that political
analysts mention most frequently as a possible running mate for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge was snug at Bush's side almost from the minute Bush
arrived in Pittsburgh around midday to when the two traveled to
Harrisburg, the state capital, early Monday night. Bush made
repeated references to their close friendship. Ridge smiled broadly
every time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
