<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET JOURNAL ADDS A TOP EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Wall Street Journal named Stephen Adler as a
deputy managing editor on Monday, bringing to three the number of
editors in that rank and expanding the cadre of top newsroom
managers responsible for finding new outlets for the newspaper's
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Adler, like his fellow deputy managing editors Daniel Hertzberg
and Byron E. Calame, will report to the managing editor, Paul E.
Steiger. Steiger said in an interview that he ``needs to be more
involved'' in the newspaper's efforts to ``find ways to extend our
journalism outside the bounds of the paper,'' into electronic
products, books, and other media.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal, which is published by Dow Jones &AMP; Co., has an
average daily circulation of 1,753,000. It is the second-largest
circulation newspaper in the country, after USA Today, which is
owned by Gannett Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Adler's responsibilities will include coordination with The
Interactive Journal, whose Web site, wsj.com, has a
subscription-based readership of about 400,000. Adler will also
retain responsibility for The Journal's investigative reporting
team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
