A6121 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-WILSON-COLUMN-LAD     04-03 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WILSON-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA ANITA DERBY HORSES DESERVE TRIPLE CROWN RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif._ No matter what happens in Saturday's $1 million
Santa Anita Derby, recent history tells us we'd better respect any
horse that comes out of the Grade I event and runs in the Triple
Crown races.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   -- Charismatic finished fourth in last year's Santa Anita Derby,
beaten 8 1/4 lengths by General Challenge, and went on to win both
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Real Quiet lost to stablemate Indian Charlie in 1998, then
won the first two legs of the Triple Crown before losing to Victory
Gallop in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   -- Silver Charm parlayed a second-place finish to rival Free
House in the '97 Santa Anita Derby into victories in the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   -- In 1995, Wayne Lukas' Timber Country ran fourth at Arcadia
and won the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tabasco Cat was second-best to Brocco in the 1994 Santa Anita
Derby, but won the final two legs of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more. Lots more.
</P>
<P>
   -- A.P. Indy won the 1992 Santa Anita Derby and later captured
the Belmont after missing both the Kentucky Derby and Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   -- Winning Colors (1988) and Sunday Silence ('89) followed
victories in the Santa Anita Derby with Kentucky Derby wins.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 14 horses that ran in the Santa Anita Derby went on to
post Kentucky Derby victories. Eight of those horses won here on
Derby Day before heading to Churchill Downs, the most recent being
Sunday Silence in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) I still don't like Lukas' filly, Surfside, in
Saturday's race, which will be run at 1 1/8 miles over the main
track -- an eighth of a mile shorter than the Kentucky Derby
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Surfside has won four consecutive graded stakes and seven
of nine races overall. She's well-seasoned and conditioned by a
trainer who's won three of the past five Kentucky Derbies and four
overall.
</P>
<P>
   The horse is a daughter of Triple Crown champion Seattle Slew
and Lukas has already won the Kentucky Derby with a filly (see
Winning Colors, 1988).
</P>
<P>
   So why don't I like her?
</P>
<P>
   Simple. She's beaten an ordinary crop of fillies, and in less
than scintillating fashion to boot. She's going to have to take a
major step forward to beat this talented field Saturday, and I just
don't see it.
</P>
<P>
   Either jockey Pat Day and Lukas are the best sandbaggers in
recent memory, or the Surfside camp's plans to run against the boys
again on the first Saturday in May will be scrapped soon after the
Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Undeterred by Worldy Manner's seventh-place finish in
last year's Kentucky Derby, sheiks Maktoum al Maktoum and Mohammed
al Maktoum are ready to try again.
</P>
<P>
   Word from Saudi Arabia is that Godolphin Stable's China Visit is
being pointed toward this year's Run for the Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin racing manager Simon Crisford told The Associated
Press that the Makhtoum family is hoping that Chief Seattle, second
to Anees in last November's Breeders' Cup Juvenile, will also make
the race.
</P>
<P>
   China Visit won the first United Arab Emirates Derby at Dubai on
March 25 in only his second career start, beating Bachir by 4 1/4
lengths in the one-mile race on dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Seattle has not raced this year, but according to Crisford
he may run in a Dubai trial race to prepare for the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   One question comes to mind -- if, as Crisford maintains, the
sheiks are so eager to win the Derby, why don't they bring their
horses to the U.S. a little sooner and give them some real prep
races?
</P>
<P>
   Did they ever hear of the Wood Memorial or Blue Grass Stakes?
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) According to the Japanese newspaper Sports Nippon,
30-year-old jockey Yutaka Take will leave Japan and ride in the
U.S. for a year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Take will relocate to the West Coast in
June and begin riding at Hollywood Park, Del Mar and Santa Anita.
While in the U.S., he will also occasionally ride in Japan and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Take (pronounced TAH-kay) has been Japan's leading rider since
1987 when he became a teen idol. The jockey has won every major
race in the country, and last November captured Japan's most
important international race when he rode Special Week to victory
in the Grade I Japan Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
