<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TIMELINE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A history of the feds vs. Microsoft
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Milestones in Microsoft's antitrust dealings with the federal
government:
</P>
<P>
   1990, May 30 _ The Federal Trade Commission staff opens an
antitrust probe of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   1993, Feb. 5 _ On a 2-2 vote, the FTC deadlocks on taking action
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 20 _ The FTC decides to drop its Microsoft probe. The
Justice Department says it will take over the case.
</P>
<P>
   1994, July 16 _ Microsoft and the Justice Department
trustbrusters reach a settlement requiring company to change a
variety of business practices.
</P>
<P>
   1995, Feb. 14 _ U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin rejects the
proposed settlement.
</P>
<P>
   April 27 _ The Justice Department sues to block Microsoft's
acquisition of Intuit, maker of the popular Quicken personal
finance program. Microsoft abandons takeover.
</P>
<P>
   June 16 _ A federal appeals court upholds the 1994 settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 21 _ U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson approves
the 1994 settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   1996, Sept. 19 _Microsoft reveals that the Justice Department is
probing the bundling of its Internet Explorer browser with Windows
95.
</P>
<P>
   1997, Oct. 20 _ The Justice Department sues Microsoft, accusing
the company of having violated the 1994 court-approved settlement
by requiring computer makers to install Internet Explorer to
license Windows.
</P>
<P>
   1998, May 14 _ Microsoft and the Justice Department reveal they
are conducting settlement talks aimed at heading off a wide-ranging
antitrust action.
</P>
<P>
   May 18 _ After the settlement negotiations fail, the Justice
Department and 19 states file a broad antitrust suit against
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 19 _ The federal antitrust trial opens in Washington, with
videotaped testimony from Microsoft co-founder Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   1999, Jan. 13 _ The government rests its case after calling 12
witnesses. The prosecution repeatedly seeks to portray Microsoft as
a bullying monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 26 _ The defense rests its case after also calling 12
witnesses. Microsoft denies all accusations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 5 _ Jackson calls Microsoft a monopoly and says it used its
great wealth and monopolistic power to stifle competition, which
harmed consumers.
</P>
<P>
   2000, Jan. 10 _ Computer software maker Caldera settles an
antitrust suit against Microsoft for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 12 _ USA Today reports government lawyers have come up with
a plan that would split the software giant into at least two
companies, possibly three.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 13 _ Gates announces the promotion of his longtime friend
and company president, Steve Ballmer, to chief executive officer of
the software giant. Gates, the only chief executive officer
Microsoft has ever had, remains chairman.
</P>
<P>
   March 24 _ Microsoft puts a last-minute settlement offer on the
table, apparently spurred by a federal judge's warning that he
plans to issue a verdict unless there is movement toward full
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   April 3 _ Jackson issues a ruling on the Microsoft antitrust
trial. The decision describes the ``findings of law'' on the case,
outlining the extent to which he believes Microsoft's behavior
violated the law. These findings could foreshadow exactly how tough
a final remedy of Microsoft's behavior could be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
