u f BC-MICROSOFT-CHARACTERS0     04-03 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CHARACTERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key players in the Microsoft antitrust case
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Penfield Jackson, U.S. district judge
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 63, found last November that Microsoft dominates the
market for personal computer operating systems and uses its
monopolistic power to squash competition and stifle innovation. On
Monday, the judge declared the company broke the law. Jackson was
appointed in 1982 by President Reagan. During the trial, he
occasionally lost his temper toward witnesses and lawyers and
openly laughed at videotape of Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates'
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Posner, mediator
</P>
<P>
   Posner, 60, was asked late last year to help Microsoft and the
Justice Department reach an out-of-court settlement. The
Chicago-based federal judge graduated with a degree in English from
Yale University in 1959 and finished first in his class at Harvard
Law School in 1962. After teaching law for a year at Stanford
University, he came to the University of Chicago, where he taught
at the law school until being named to the bench in 1981 by Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates, Microsoft chairman
</P>
<P>
   Gates, 44, is the world's richest person, worth an estimated
$71.5 billion. He co-founded Microsoft in 1975 after dropping out
of Harvard. By 1991, the vast majority of world's personal
computers relied on Microsoft's operating system. He chose not to
appear in person as a witness in the antitrust trial, though he has
testified in other courtroom proceedings. In his videotaped
deposition for the current trial, he jousted with government
lawyers over almost every question, appearing evasive when he said
he forgot about key events and e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Steven A. Ballmer, Microsoft chief executive officer
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, 43, a classmate of Gates' at Harvard University, is
ranked by Forbes magazine as the fourth-richest American, on the
strength of his 5 percent stake in Microsoft. Ballmer joined the
company in 1980. He was made president in 1998 and succeeded Gates
as chief executive in January. Ballmer has been adamant in speaking
out against any settlement of the antitrust case that would result
in the company's breakup.
</P>
<P>
   David Boies, Justice Department lawyer
</P>
<P>
   Boies, 58, wore the same blue tie nearly every day of the trial.
He came into the case without a great grasp of computer technology
but later competently questioned witnesses about technically arcane
subjects like Java programming language. He appeared to favor
asking Microsoft witnesses seemingly innocent questions, then
confronting them with e-mails or other documents _ often written by
themselves _ that appear to contradict their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Joel I. Klein, assistant attorney general, Antitrust Division
</P>
<P>
   When Klein, 53, was nominated by President Clinton as the
Justice Department's antitrust chief, some senators considered him
too soft. So it's somewhat ironic that Klein is now widely viewed
as an aggressive, even zealous, champion of antitrust enforcement,
a reputation cemented by his challenge to Microsoft. Klein was
appointed assistant attorney general for the antitrust division in
October 1996
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0510 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ADROVER-FASHION-ART-N     04-03 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADROVER-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKERS LINE THE DOCK AS A SHIP COMES IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT30-32 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds., spelling Jennefer, 4th graf, is CQ) 
(jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is 34, six months behind on the rent and last week
had to borrow $200 from his father, a farmer in Spain. Conventional
wisdom would suggest that Miguel Adrover get a job, but to the
cockeyed fashion world, which can forgive anything except a
mediocre talent, Adrover's creative gifts are apparently as good as
money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday afternoon, the fledgling designer, who was hailed a
star after only his second show, in February, at the New York fall
collections, was in his apartment on East Third Street. Like his
clothes _ which are made largely from donated fabrics and things he
can buy cheaply on the street, like baseball caps and sweat shirts,
and which he stays up nights rubbing with sandpaper until they look
old _ the apartment shows just how far a person can go on nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The place consists of two small rooms in the basement, although
that probably makes it sound like a cozy garden apartment.
Actually, to get to Adrover's apartment, one must go down a long
grimy passageway that reeks of every imaginable New York smell. One
can only hope that Adrover's door is open, throwing out a weak
yellow shaft of light, because, on top of everything else, it is
too dark to see.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Adrover has a couch, a couple of old chairs and a table
stacked with magazines and press clippings about himself. He has a
phone in there, and when it rang, about every 15 minutes, Jennefer
Hoffman, an artist who has been helping Adrover, picked it up and
said brightly, ``Studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was funny, since nothing about the place _ not the weak
yellow light, not the lumpy brown sofa, not the stuffed deer head
lying over in one corner _ said studio.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Adrover has a curious effect on people, which is, they want
to give him money. Jeffrey Kalinsky, who has Jeffrey boutiques on
14th Street and in Atlanta, said last week that he would be willing
to give Adrover $25,000 to help get his fall collection
manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done that in my life with a designer,'' Kalinsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   This past January, Linda Dresner, who has stores with her name
on Park Avenue and in Birmingham, Mich., visited Adrover in his
apartment with Catherine Dietlein, an independent scout for
retailers. There were five people crammed in there working on the
fall collection. ``And smoke!'' Dresner recalled. ``I said, `Open
the door, dear.''' Adrover was hanging the finished samples over
his bed and sleeping under them at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole scene was so sincere,'' Dresner continued. ``I mean,
I wrote a check _ that's how I felt. He has something to say with
his clothes that nobody else is saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Gilhart, a vice president for women's fashion at Barneys
New York, isn't in a position to write a check, but she said
flatly, ``If Miguel just wants to make some clothes for us, we'll
take them.'' She has called him every few days for the past month,
``just to see what's up,'' she said, and added: ``He's what they
call in Texas a wildcatter. He's larger than life, and just
brimming with ideas and energy.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Adrover's days of living on sandwiches and
selling a sample here and there to get by (he recently sold one
from his spring 2000 collection to Sarah Jessica Parker for $300)
may be numbered. Although he couldn't give specifics because of
confidentiality agreements, he is close to working out a production
deal with the recently formed Pegasus Apparel Group.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Ruzow, a former Donna Karan executive who was named
chairman and chief executive of the group just last Friday,
confirmed that talks were under way with Adrover, but also declined
to elaborate. Pegasus Apparel Group is an interesting story in
itself. Formed as a holding company less than a month ago, it is
one of two $800 million private equity funds controlled by its
principals. The group, which has plans to invest broadly in
so-called lifestyle categories like fashion and cosmetics, has
already announced a financing deal with the designer Pamela Dennis.
Similar agreements are said to be in the works with Daryl Kerrigan
and Cynthia Rowley.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the group was officially formed, intermediaries were
making contact with Adrover less than 48 hours after his February
show. As Ruzow said, ``there's a great deal of commercially viable
product there.'' Presuming Adrover gets financing, it's still
uncertain whether his fall collection can be delivered to stores in
time. Barneys, Linda Dresner, Neiman Marcus, Jeffrey and others
have all expressed interest in the line.
</P>
<P>
   Although Adrover, who grew up on his family's almond farm on
Majorca, is untrained and has operated on a shoestring, he is
nothing if not resourceful. For several years he and a friend,
Douglas Hobbes, ran a small downtown boutique called Horn that
attracted a word-of-mouth following. Then last September, as if via
the same East Village underground, word got out that Adrover was
staging his first show, and that Alexander McQueen would be there.
That show, which included a much-photographed miniskirt salvaged
from an old Louis Vuitton bag and dresses cleverly patched with
newspaper (a foreshadowing of John Galliano's Dior show?), cost
about $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   By February, Adrover had become the most talked-about newcomer
since _well, since nobody can recall. Not even the buzz around
Isaac Mizrahi in the late 1980s is comparable, because, unlike
Mizrahi, who had ties to the fashion establishment, Adrover seemed
to come out of nowhere. What's more, his fall collection showed a
substantial leap forward (helped by Mei Zou, a seamstress who
worked for Adrover during her off hours, and Sebastian Pons, a
childhood friend, who has been an assistant to McQueen, along with
others). Not only were the clothes sophisticated, with tailored
suits and ladylike blouses, there were also witty takes on luxury
labels like Hermes and Burberry.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Adrover has been waiting for the rest of his life to
begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all these magazines stacked around here,'' he said
last week in his basement rooms. ``I'm everywhere, in pages and
pages. I'm invited to parties. And I think, `This is me, living
here.''' He shook his head and grinned as he said, ``It's really
weird.''
</P>
<P>
   If Adrover senses the paradox of his situation, he is not
unmindful of the stakes, or risks, involved with being a hot new
property. He said he had no interest in trying to build his
business slowly on his own, the way designers used to, or in
accepting a one-shot infusion of cash. ``I need to pay the people
around me salaries,'' he said, ``and I don't want to struggle from
one day to the next to eat. It's really sad, because in this
business if you don't have the infrastructure, you can never make
it. No matter how good you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion is an essentially optimistic undertaking. Why else would
anyone go into a business whose motto could read: ``Whatever
happened to ...?'' As Ruzzo said, ``It's survival of the fittest.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Adrover seems to have an instinct for survival. It's
almost as if he doesn't know what he can do because he's never
bothered to ask what he  &UR; can't &LR;  do. Make a ravishing mulberry coat
with a cheeky back of Vuitton vinyl? Why not? Pump up the shoulders
of a sweatshirt by fitting them with baseball caps? Of course!
</P>
<P>
   Adrover has so many ideas that when he was told that a prominent
magazine editor had said his fall show needed more editing, he
looked nonplused.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's editing?'' he asked Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's when you make things more focused,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Adrover frowned: ``Focused on what?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman smiled indulgently as if talking to a child. ``Just keep
thinking that way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
