<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH UNVEILS PLAN TO MAKE CLEANUP OF POLLUTED SITES EASIER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALIQUIPPA, Pa. _ Presidential hopeful George W. Bush defended
his environmental record as Texas governor Monday and unveiled a
plan to spur cleanup of the nation's polluted industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our state, like Pennsylvania, didn't wait for Al Gore to wave
his magic wand and clean up our environment. We cleaned it up
ourselves, and our states are better off for it,'' said Bush, who
signaled he would go after his Democratic opponent on an issue
considered one of Gore's strong suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to say, 'I'm an environmentalist,''' he said.
``It's another to point to a record.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential nominee, said he is
looking forward to debating Gore on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush toured a US Gypsum wallboard factory under construction on
the grounds of the former J&AMP;L Steel Mill, a site that is among more
than 600 so-called ``brownfields'' Pennsylvania has cleaned up and
reclaimed. The new factory, set to open this summer, will employ
more than 150 people in this depressed steel town near Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, accompanied by Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, told
construction workers at the site that if elected president, he'll
bring ``common-sense reform'' to brownfields cleanups.
</P>
<P>
   He announced a six-point plan in which he would direct the
Environmental Protection Agency to set cleanup standards with more
flexibility than the current Superfund standards, protect companies
from federal liability if they clean the sites properly, and focus
the efforts of the federal government on developing new cleanup
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   His plan would provide block grants to states through a
brownfield cleanup loan fund, and would make permanent the current
tax incentives for cleaning up the sites. He also would hold the
federal government, which he called the country's worst polluter,
accountable for cleaning up its own messes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What counts is what you do,'' he told the workers, ``not what
you promise.``
</P>
<P>
   A Gore spokesman responded to Bush's proposal by questioning the
Texas governor's sincerity, saying Bush surrendered environmental
protection in Texas to the wishes of his campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of whitewashing can cover up Bush's record,'' Gore
spokesman Doug Hattaway said. ``He allowed his special interest
friends to help weaken environmental laws and on his watch Texas is
now the most polluted state in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said state Superfund spending,(the longtime national
toxic site cleanup program) was cut from $44 million to $22 million
in Texas for fiscal years 1997-98. He also criticized a Bush
program, written with input by industry, that allows some
grandfathered air polluting plants to voluntarily come into
compliance with the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush became governor in 1995, Texas has cleaned up 451
brownfield sites and is working on more than 500. Bush said that
was possible because of legislation he pushed through to allow
local governments to give property tax incentives for the cleanups.
The new laws also protect future owners and developers from
liability for past contamination if they meet reasonable standards
for cleaning up the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said 450,000 brownfields across the country have been
abandoned by polluters and shunned by other companies that fear
being sued for the environmental harm caused by former owners.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the federal government's rigid environmental
regulations, especially under the Superfund cleanup program, for
the lack of progress in cleaning up the sites, and for the sprawl
created when companies use up the land and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old system of mandate, regulate and litigate only sends
potential developers off in search of greener pastures,
literally,'' he said. ``Brownfields get passed over, while
greenfields get paved over.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he intends to combat Gore's expertise on the
environment, and his endorsements by national environmental
organizations, Bush poked fun at the Democratic candidate's book,
``Earth in the Balance,'' and said Gore might have to explain some
of his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he has written on the subject,'' he said. ``I think
that's the book that said we would get rid of automobile engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between rhetoric and reality. I happen to
believe that job growth can coexist with good environmental
policy,'' he said, ``and I know that the command and control policy
of Washington won't work.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore's approach, and the approach of the Superfund cleanup
program he helped create, is based on the philosophy that ``we can
sue our way to clean air,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sue our way to clean air. In fact the threat of
lawsuits makes it more difficult to meet reasonable standards when
it comes to cleaning up industrial sites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that when Superfund was established in 1980, the plan
was to clean up some of the country's worst toxic sites in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years later, the job isn't done,'' he said. ``Less than
half of the Superfund sites have been cleaned up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also defended himself against the Gore campaign's
contention that his allegiance to big business in Texas has led to
the state's status among the worst air and water polluters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may say that, but this is a man who will say anything to
get elected. Remember who I'm running against,'' he said.
``Industrial pollution is down in my state since I've been
governor. I've got a good record.``
</P>
<P>
