<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYOS-DIVORCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REFUSES TO LET WOMAN IMPLANT FROZEN EMBRYOS OVER HUSBAND'S
OBJECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The highest court in Massachusetts, ruling in a case
that pitted a woman who wanted to implant frozen embryos in her
womb versus her ex-husband who wanted no more children with her,
has come down firmly on the ex-husband's side, saying that no one
should be forced to become a parent.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion, issued Friday, is expected to influence court
decisions around the country in a nascent area of the law: how to
treat high-tech baby-making, and in particular, how to decide the
fates of frozen embryos when the couples who have made them in the
course of fertility treatments later separate or divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Such cases have reached three state supreme courts, are pending
in a half-dozen other states and are likely to become more common
as the numbers of frozen embryos, now estimated at about 150,000,
increase.
</P>
<P>
   In the Massachusetts case, a woman identified in court papers
only as B.Z., wanted to try one last time, at age 44, to become
pregnant using the four frozen embryos left from her years of
fertility treatments. Her ex-husband, identified as A.Z., objected,
even though his ex-wife had seven consent forms he had signed over
the years saying that if the couple separated, the embryos would
revert to her for implantation.
</P>
<P>
   A family court had ruled in favor of the ex-husband, saying, in
part, that because the couple had had twins and divorced since the
agreement, circumstances had changed too much for him to be held to
it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Judicial Court, in a ruling it made in February
but only now backed up with a detailed opinion, has taken a big
step further. The consent forms, it said, had some problems, but
``Even had the husband and wife entered into an unambiguous
agreement between themselves regarding the disposition of the
frozen pre-embryos, we would not enforce an agreement that would
compel one donor to become a parent against his or her will. As a
matter of public policy, we conclude that forced procreation is not
an area amenable to judicial enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The opinion by Justice Judith Cowin said that ``respect for
liberty and privacy requires that individuals be accorded the
freedom to decide whether to enter into a family relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   In similar cases, state courts have tended to rule that whenever
possible, the agreement a couple had signed with a fertility clinic
about what to do with their embryos in the event of a divorce or
death should be considered a contract. A few legislatures have
considered or passed laws requiring such agreements. But the
Massachusetts ruling, experts say, indicates that such a contract
is far from iron-clad.
</P>
<P>
   Couples ``cannot assume that one or the other can use the frozen
embryos in the event of a divorce in Massachusetts or any court
jurisdiction that follows Massachusetts,'' said Susan L. Crockin, a
lawyer here specializing in reproductive technology. ``This court
has made it absolutely clear that there is no agreement, no matter
how clearly understood and entered into, that is going to bind a
subsequently objecting partner, and programs need to make that
clear to patients now starting the process, as well as to patients
who have embryos frozen. The prior agreements are out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Van Ness, the lawyer for B.Z., said that she has not
decided whether to appeal the ruling. Previous courts, she said,
had seemed to lean toward the ``vetoer,'' the partner who did not
want the embryos brought to term. But if ever a case seemed to
support favoring the partner who wanted children, she added, this
one did, because the woman had relied on her husband's promises and
found time running out when he objected to her use of the embryos.
The woman's clinic would implant embryos in women only until age
45.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court says, `We're not going to force procreation on
someone,' but by making that decision, they've forced my client not
to procreate,'' Van Ness said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using the power of the state to prevent my client from
using the embryos that she suffered and almost died to create,''
she said, referring to ectopic pregnancies and other complications
B.Z. suffered.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, Van Ness noted, the husband had participated voluntarily
in fertility treatments for years, demonstrating more intent to
procreate than simply having sex, and the courts have consistently
held men responsible for children they produce through sex. Yet
because the embryos exist outside her client's body, she said,
``the court has set up a different rule.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Crockin said the fact that an embryo is in a freezer vial rather
than in a womb makes a great difference. ``The court is not
balancing the constitutional rights of a pregnant woman against a
partner,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Paula H. Noe, a lawyer who represented the husband in family
court, said: ``What I think the court is saying is that absent a
pregnancy, which weighs things differently, we have individual
rights called privacy rights, that must be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a man and a woman who are potential parents,'' Noe
said, ``and no one has the upper hand; their privacy rights are
equal, and I think that's right on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
