<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-STOCK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Caution boils up in tech sector
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bargain-hunting usually follows a steep plunge in
stock prices. But many analysts warn against early shopping among
technology stocks despite the Microsoft-led damage in that sector
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which includes Microsoft and most
other high-tech stocks, fell 349.15 points, or 7.6 percent. The
percentage loss was the biggest since a tumble of 8.6 percent on
Aug. 31, 1998, in the midst of the Asian currency crisis. The point
drop, however, easily exceeded the earlier record of 229.46 points,
set Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities strategist Larry Wachtel said today's
market ``will likely see the extension of the tech decline.''
</P>
<P>
   At Robinson-Humphrey in Atlanta, senior strategist Robert S.
Robbins, who had lowered his technology allocation recommendation
to 43 percent from 48 percent Friday, lowered it again Monday to 38
percent of total stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   A further decline today would push the Nasdaq composite close to
a bear market level for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   At 4,223.68, the Nasdaq is just over 16 percent below its
all-time high of 5,048.62, set March 10. Wall Street generally
regards a 10 percent decline in an index as a correction, while a
drop of 20 percent is a bear market. The Nasdaq fell almost 31
percent in the last bear market during the summer of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the best-performing stocks of the first three months of
2000 suffered miserable losses Monday. They included Applied Micro
Circuits, Juniper Networks and Rambus, the best-performing stock in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As new economy stocks sank, old economy blue chips continued to
rise as investors were drawn to values in beaten-down shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 300.01 points, or 2.8
percent, to 11,221.93, and would have gone higher except for the
decline of Microsoft, a Dow stock.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dow gainers included Wal-Mart Stores, J.P. Morgan, Merck,
Philip Morris, DuPont and Caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the caution expressed by some analysts, Brian Goodstadt
at Standard &AMP; Poor's reiterated a ``buy'' rating on Microsoft
because he said the ``worse case scenario'' is already factored in
the share price.
</P>
<P>
   Goodstadt argued that the most damaging aspect of the federal
court's ruling Monday is that it opens the door to more civil
lawsuits against Microsoft. Other analysts think the company will
appeal the ruling. That process could take years, with Microsoft
continuing to make money throughout.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Microsoft stock, which fell $15.37 1/2 to $90.87 1/2 in
regular-hours trading, was reported trading higher in the
after-hours session.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft was blamed as the trigger for Monday's Nasdaq
sell-off, analysts said it was not the only reason, since the stock
accounts for only about 8.5 percent of the index's value.
Robinson-Humphrey's Robbins noted that the Morgan Stanley
technology index had advanced more than 96 percent in the six
months that ended with the Nasdaq's recent high, creating a
situation where ``profit taking is very easy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the market's attention focused on the technology slide
Monday, most traders overlooked the usually important manufacturing
report from the National Association of Purchasing Management.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's March index dipped to 55.8 percent from 56.9
percent in February, but it was still well above the reading of 50
percent that indicates growth.
</P>
<P>
   The price component jumped to 79.8 percent from 74.1 percent,
the highest level since February 1995. In a normal session, that
probably would have been treated as another inflation threat
leading to higher interest rates by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
