<SLUG> BC-GORE-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DENOUNCES DISPARITIES IN MINORITY ACCESS TO COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Speaking at the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s alma
mater on the eve of the anniversary of his death, Vice President Al
Gore called Monday for programs to narrow the ``digital divide''
that has left minorities with unequal access to computers and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, referred
repeatedly to the famous final speech that King delivered 32 years
ago Monday night, when the civil rights leader declared that he had
been to the mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take this mountaintop moment,'' he told about 500
students at Morehouse College, ``and squander the resources that we
call the surplus on a tax cut for the wealthy, on a risk that is
designed not to lift up those that are in need, but to give more to
those who have much, what will happen to those that are waiting for
the help that ought to be extended to them?''
</P>
<P>
   The want ads, Gore continued, are filled with high-paying jobs
that cannot be filled because of inadequate training. ``And
simultaneously,'' he said, ``we have hundreds of thousands and
millions who have the ability, the curiosity, the desire to learn
and to succeed but have not had the opportunity and the access.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, Gore said, will come from government financing to
place computers with Internet access in every classroom and
library, to train teachers in new technologies, to integrate
computers into the full scholastic curriculum, to build computer
learning centers in needy communities and to bring Internet access
to every household. He said the country should set a national goal
of making every student computer literate by the eighth grade. He
did not disclose a price for his recommendations, many of which
have already been proposed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In maintaining his campaign's focus on education, Gore has
spoken on this topic several times. But by doing so at Morehouse,
one of the country's elite black private colleges, he again
underscored the importance of black voters to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although polls show that Bush is a solid favorite across the
South, the Gore campaign believes it can break the Bush
stranglehold in selected states with the help of a heavy turnout of
loyal black Democrats. One of those states is Georgia, which the
Democratic ticket won narrowly in 1992 and lost narrowly in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapel named for King, Gore shared the stage Monday with
one of King's top lieutenants, Andrew Young, former mayor of
Atlanta, and with King's eldest son, Martin Luther King 3rd, now
the president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. Gore
also made a point of introducing his campaign manager, Donna
Brazille, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Gore echoed government officials who fear that
the computer divide may soon exacerbate existing racial disparities
in education, employment and income. A variety of recent studies
have shown that while Internet access is expanding rapidly,
persistent gaps remain in access based on income, race, education
level and region.
</P>
<P>
   A Commerce Department study released last summer found that
households with incomes of $75,000 and higher were 20 times more
likely to have access to the Internet than those at the lowest
income levels, and more than nine times as likely to own a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Though disparities have narrowed in recent years among high
earners, the study found racial gaps that could not be explained by
differences in income alone. Among households with earnings from
$15,000 to $35,000, for instance, more than 32 percent of white
families owned computers, compared to only 19 percent of black and
Hispanic families. Seventeen percent of white households had home
Internet access, compared to 8 percent of black and Hispanic
households.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the gap threatens to further the perception that
minorities are politically disenfranchised. ``This new technology
of the Internet and computer communication can close that digital
divide,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore also was the headline attraction at a expensive fund-raiser
here Monday night for the Democratic National Committee. With a
price tag of $50,000 a person, the event was expected to raise more
than $1.5 million for the committee, said Jenny Backus, the DNC's
press secretary. The committee can use the money to promote
Democratic themes and candidates, including Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The list of contributors included Anne Cox Chambers, the
chairwoman of Atlanta Newspapers Inc., which publishes The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, and Michael Coles, the Georgia cookie magnate
who has run unsuccessfully for Congress. Other contributors
included prominent Atlanta companies like Coca-Cola, United Parcel
Service and Bell South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
