<SLUG> BC-FAKE-ARTIFACTS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phony antiques prompt damages
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A jury has awarded an Atlanta man nearly $1 million in
damages in connection with his purchase of hundreds of alleged
pre-Columbian artifacts, which an antiquities expert later
identified as elaborate fakes.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of more than a year, the buyer, Robert B.
Watson of Atlanta, purchased hundreds of Central American artifacts
_ including jade masks, pendants, carved statuettes, and stone ax
heads _ from Atlanta collector W. Edward Vaught Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Vaught and Enrique Vargas, a Costa Rican artifact dealer, have
in the past sold thousands of pre-Columbian artifacts to Atlanta
area collectors, including some pieces that are now owned by the
Michael C. Carlos Museum at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos museum officials have said they have no reason to doubt
the authenticity of pieces on display at the museum. But the
verdict clearly shows that despite international agreements
designed to halt the flow of illicit antiquities from Latin
America, active trade in such items is continuing. It also
underscores the fact that, in the antiquities market, forgery is
all but impossible for casual collectors to detect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a week of testimony before Fulton County Superior Court
Judge Joel Fryer, it was not clear whether Vaught himself knew the
pieces were modern forgeries of ancient craftsmanship when he sold
them to Watson _ or whether he himself had been duped.
</P>
<P>
   The jury decided it didn't make any difference. The verdict
awarded on Thursday to Watson, the buyer, covered the $178,000 that
he had previously paid for artifacts _ and $750,000 in punitive
damages. Watson, meanwhile, must return the fakes.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the authenticity of the artifacts did not become
an issue until Watson wrote $59,000 in bad checks in 1997 for his
final shipment. Vaught sued to collect his money, and Watson
countersued _ armed with reports from an artifact expert, who said
hundreds of the purchases had been ``fabricated by methods and
using devices common today.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gramly, an archaeologist with the Great Lakes Artifact
Repository in New York, told the jury that the supposed
2,000-year-old artifacts he examined actually had been made in
modern times ``with obvious intent to deceive'' unsuspecting
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Latin American countries forbid the export and
sale of pre-Columbian artifacts, market prices are so high that
many countries now have thriving cottage industries that turn out
replicas that often are buried or weathered for a brief time to
give them the appearance of great age.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
