<HEADER>
A6139 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-PRACTICAL-TRAV     04-03 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPING FROM THE CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on Sunday, April 9) 
(ms) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although travel with children is climbing steadily _ an increase
of 68 percent was reported by the Travel Industry Association
between 1988 and 1998 _ some people would rather not.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those are parents themselves. This is confirmed by
Calvert Roberts, general manager of Curtain Bluff in Antigua, where
children under 12 are not welcomed from Jan. 10 to March 10. ``We
get people who work hard _ doctors, lawyers, people from Wall
Street,'' Roberts said. ``They are coming for vacation then and
they want to get away from the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Other travelers just want to be someplace quiet, where shouts
are confined to the tennis match and outdoor tranquillity is not
disturbed by a child pursuing a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Hostility, while probably not publicly endorsed, also exists:
Watching an adult airline passenger whose seatback is being kicked
by an unrestrained child shows how this emotion is fostered.
Oblivious or arrogant parents who haul children who are too young
into adult settings like trendy restaurants or the theater augment
this part of the population.
</P>
<P>
   So, while ski resorts, individual entrepreneurs and unlikely
places like Las Vegas are looking at the demographic charts and
offering environments that accommodate families, others are
creating niches or, like Curtain Bluff, setting aside time periods
when adults can expect to be with other adults only. Avoiding
children depends to a large degree on how controlled the entry to
the environment is: On a plane, train or bus, it is likely to be
impossible. Cruise ships, however, present a controllable
situation. After complaints about the behavior, particularly
drunkenness, of teen-agers, some ship lines took steps. In 1997,
Carnival Cruise Lines instituted a policy of not accepting
reservations for passengers under 21 unless accompanied in their
cabins by someone 25 or older. Other lines have variations on this
approach. Three expensive lines, Seabourn, Silversea and Windstar,
share a policy: ``children under 12 not encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Cruises does not book passengers under 18. When the
first of its five vessels went into service in August 1998, said
Brad Ball, a spokesman, passengers could take their children. ``But
there was basically nothing for them to do, and I guess we had a
couple of unruly ones,'' Ball said, so about a year ago the line,
following passengers' suggestions, became adults-only.
</P>
<P>
   Adults can generally read the signals. Motels with promotions
featuring cartoon characters probably have pools where cannonballs
are the dive du jour. Inns furnished with antiques probably
discourage children. On the road, the designation ``family
restaurant'' tells its own tale, although often the sign indicates
that liquor is not served.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Zagat issues some separate nightlife guides,
and often includes ``romantic'' categories in general guides.
Although it's a clumsy way to decide, price may help; even
well-to-do parents may have enough sense to avoid spending a lot of
money on a child who wants only the roll and butter.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lawler of Lawrence, Kan., who admits to a child of her
own, recently wrote ``Child-Free Travel'' (Pilot Books, Greenport,
N.Y.), but cautiously subtitled it ``The Curmudgeon's Guide.''
Lawler has adopted a humorously cranky tone _ for example,
providing a list of ``resorts to approach with caution,'' because
children might be around. Her joke wears thin, but she compiled
some lists of places and activities that might provide leads to
those seeking tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   Club Med, marking its 50th anniversary, has gone with the flow
on the issue of children in its long life. When it came to the
Western Hemisphere in 1968, it was a progenitor of the childless
resort. The picture of bikini-suited beautiful people, wearing the
beads that in those days bought drinks, became the slightly racy
image of Club Med vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, boys and girls met, settled down and had
children. Club Med followed, adding children's activities to some
villages; it opened the first Mini Club in Guadeloupe in 1974. In
the 70s, according to Edwina Arnold, a longtime spokeswoman for the
company, only 15 percent of bookings were for families, the rest
for couples or singles. By 1997, 40 percent were families, 30
percent couples and 30 singles. Today's singles scene has changed,
and Club Med focuses on single travelers in their 30s for whom
frenetic activity is unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   Right now on this side of the Atlantic, the organization has
three places reserved for adults over 18: Turkoise in the Turks and
Caicos Islands and Cancun and Playa Blanca, Mexico. Eight family
villages in the Western Hemisphere have kids' programs that allow
parents to enjoy themselves separately for part of each day, and at
seven others, children are welcomed but parents must care for them.
A fourth adults-only village will be created next winter at Club
Med's Copper Mountain ski area in Colorado; the former Marriott at
Crested Butte, which the Club just bought, will cater to families.
Partying On
</P>
<P>
   The old Club Med aura abides in some resorts, however. The
announcement of the opening last fall of Hedonism III, an
adults-only resort in Runaway Bay, Jamaica, said an earlier
Hedonism property ``has stuck successfully to its party-hearty
adults-only concept through the wave of politically correct virtue
which swept the 80s and 90s.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Hedonism II, opened in 1976 in Negril, Jamaica,
was buffeted by a wave of virtue in the go-go 80s and the dot-com
90s falls oddly on ears that have heard mutterings from adults who
resented having children even in the airport boarding line.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still plenty of rational people who want
environments where there are no children, places with an ambience
more lively than a Henry James villa while not necessarily equipped
with Hedonism's see-through Jacuzzis.
</P>
<P>
   Sandals is an adult-only (in fact couples-only) resort, but the
message is somewhat modulated. Gordon Stewart, the proprietor who
calls himself Butch, speaks of couples who have lost track of each
other through years of marriage and family. ``We have tried to
create an environment to allow people to focus on each other,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that his 10 Sandals resorts, which accept no one
under 18, were designed with nooks where people can get away from
others, in addition to diverse restaurants offering varied cuisines
to guests who don't want to leave the resort. He is ebullient about
the results. In a telephone interview from Providenciales, Turks
and Caicos, he said, ``I have so many letters from people whose
marriages we've saved!''
</P>
<P>
   Hedonism? Well, SuperClubs, the owner, has opened Boscobel Beach
near Ocho Rios in Jamaica, which it calls the Caribbean's only
``Super-inclusive resort for families.'' There are SuperNannies and
Kiddy Cocktail parties, but there is also a West Wing for those 18
and older.
</P>
<P>
   And Roberts at Curtain Bluff says that for 10 months of the
year, his resort welcomes children. ``We have to build our
clientele,'' he said. ``We are going to want those children when
they are adults.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
