<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6141 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SOUTH-EDUC-ART-1150(2     04-03 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-EDUC-ART-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAGGING IN EDUCATION, THE SOUTH EXPERIMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The states of the South, long home to the nation's
poorest and worst-performing students, have desperately begun to
experiment with education theories and school reform plans in ways
that are drawing national attention.
</P>
<P>
   While experimentation is going on in a few states in other
regions, almost every Southern governor, Republican or Democrat, is
either hunting for new school money or trying combinations of
familiar and occasionally untested ideas for improving student
achievement. Some of the plans mix new spending for large state
education agencies and teacher salaries with conservative proposals
like vouchers and an end to teacher job protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southern states have really been pushing the envelope,''
said Kathy Christie, who runs the information clearinghouse at the
Education Commission of the States, a nonprofit policy group based
in Denver. ``They may be low in achievement, on average, but they
have a number of high-quality proposals out there that may start to
change that in the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul E. Patton of Kentucky seemed to be speaking for the
entire South earlier this year when he informed state lawmakers of
his top four priorities: ``Education, education, education and
education.'' Not all his colleagues have been quite so wry about
it, but in virtually every statehouse in the South, the priorities
are essentially the same.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is about to become the first state in the country to
wipe out all job protection for teachers, a measure Gov. Roy Barnes
pushed through the state Legislature over the objections of teacher
organizations as a message that the world had changed. The end of
tenure is the most attention-getting element of Barnes' sweeping
education overhaul, approved last month, which mandates smaller
class sizes, bonuses for teachers in good schools and a new
education bureaucracy to monitor annual testing.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has been spending more than $70 million a year to
raise teacher salaries above the regional average and provide
scholarships for future teachers, and it has established a new
training institute for principals.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas approach begun in the early 1990s and enhanced by Gov.
George W. Bush has put a strong emphasis on testing, breaking new
ground in the close monitoring of low-income and minority students.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina _ hailed along with Texas in a 1998 study by the
National Education Goals Panel as having made among the largest
gains in reading and math scores in the first part of the 1990s _
is tightening the licensing of both new and experienced teachers.
At the same time, it is offering substantial bonuses for teachers
in high-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has pioneered a program to provide private-school
vouchers for students in poorly performing public schools. The
program was recently ruled unconstitutional by a state judge, but
the state is appealing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   As the region with the lowest per-capita income, the South has
always lagged the rest of the country in educational achievement,
burdened by its former reliance on low-skill jobs and the residue
of segregated school systems. Forty percent of Americans without
high school diplomas are in the South, twice the percentage of any
other region, according to the Southern Regional Education Board, a
cooperative compact to improve the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The South was slower than the rest of the country to begin its
school reform, and for all the recent years of innovation,
performance has just barely begun to move up. The Southeast is
still the lowest-ranking of the nation's four regions on the
federal government's National Assessment of Education Progress
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 states that belong to the regional board, only six
meet the national average for proficiency in fourth-grade reading
(although others have shown some improvement), and only three do so
in eighth-grade reading. In the Deep South, only North Carolina
meets the national proficiency averages for both grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lagged behind the rest of the country for so long that
there is a much greater receptivity to experimentation,'' said John
Dornan, executive director of the Public School Forum, a nonprofit
public policy group based in Raleigh, N.C. ``The states are trying
a lot of high-stakes programs, but we're just now starting to fight
our way up to average.''
</P>
<P>
   As in most states, the effort to improve public schools began in
the South with the dire warnings published 17 years ago in ``A
Nation at Risk,'' a federal commission's report attacking the
quality of American education, and was prodded by business leaders
who said the regional economy was at stake. But the South had much
further to go than the rest of the country. It spent less on
education than any other region, and had by far the largest number
of dropouts and failing students. Nowhere was the connection
between student poverty and school performance more evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't put importance in the state of public education
until the last few years,'' Barnes, of Georgia, said in an
interview last week, riffling through bulging folders of education
statistics. ``Because in the South you didn't have to. You had
manufacturing concerns _ kids could drop out in high school and go
to work at a mill. Well, the mills are no longer there; the mills
are in Mexico or Asia. The economy has changed, and we've got to
improve our standards or we won't have the smart people to fill
those jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Governors of the New South like Lamar Alexander in Tennessee and
Richard Riley in South Carolina first began talking like this in
the 1980s, trying to repair their states' reputations with the
first wave of school reforms like testing and improving teacher
quality. James B. Hunt Jr. of North Carolina, one of the earliest
and most successful education advocates among the governors, was
the founding chairman of the national standards board that
certifies teachers in their fields, and his state now leads the
nation in board-certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Other states, particularly in the Deep South, moved more slowly,
but now it is no longer possible to be a Southern governor without
a similar agenda. In Mississippi, which has the nation's
lowest-performing schools, Gov. Ronnie Musgrove promised in his
inaugural address in January to find $286 million to raise teacher
salaries to the regional average over the next five years (although
he has not yet persuaded legislators).
</P>
<P>
   Next door, in Alabama, Gov. Donald Siegelman has also proposed
substantial raises for teachers, in exchange for making it easier
to dismiss them without a lengthy procedure. But after his plan for
a state lottery to support education failed last year, he said the
money would have to come out of the same pot used for higher
education, and now university administrators have come out against
the proposal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it is the South's wealthier states, like Georgia,
Florida and the Carolinas, that are setting the pace for
innovation. Georgia's plan, centering on school accountability, is
typical of what other Southern states are approving or considering,
and Barnes frankly admits that much of it was borrowed from North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia plan, passed overwhelmingly in the state Legislature
last month and set to be signed into law in a few weeks, is based
on annual tests in Grades one through 12 in reading, writing,
mathematics, science and social studies. If students meet the goals
set by a new state Office of Education Accountability, the teachers
in their school will get bonus pay. If students in a school fail
repeatedly, they will be allowed to move to a different school, and
teachers and administrators can be disciplined or dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, class sizes will be limited to 21 students in
first through third grade, down from the current maximum of 33; in
later grades, class sizes can grow to 28. School councils of
parents, teachers and business leaders will be set up to work with
principals.
</P>
<P>
   Any teacher dismissed will be given a written reason but will
not have the right to a hearing. Although a few other states have
shortened the hearing process, none of them have eliminated it
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The larger of two state teachers organizations, the Professional
Association of Georgia Educators, eventually dropped its opposition
when Barnes agreed that the dismissal rule would be applied only to
teachers hired from now on, not to existing faculty. But a smaller
teachers group, the Georgia Association of Educators, remains
opposed; its executive director, Drew Albritton, said the provision
would drive away good teachers by permitting arbitrary dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, a Democrat who ran the risk of alienating a crucial
constituency of his party with the measure, acknowledged that there
was no statistical link between teacher tenure rights and student
achievement. But he said the move sent a message to educators that
change would be pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tenure is an outdated concept,'' he said, ``born of a time
when we treasured process over performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's consensus is not always easy to come by, however,
especially in states that passed the first reform measures some
time ago and are now coming to realize that the costs only go up.
In Kentucky, which has seen steady improvement since passing a
school reform bill in 1990, legislators have been unable to agree
on Gov. Patton's proposal to pay for enhanced teacher training
programs. Gov. Mike Foster of Louisiana has not been able to find
the $220 million he wants to raise teacher salaries to the
Southeastern average, and the state's teachers groups are murmuring
about an autumn strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've actually made a lot of progress, considering where we
were,'' said Mark Musick, president of the Southern Regional
Education Board. ``But we had a lot of room to make progress. The
next steps are going to be even harder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6143 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-BOSNIA-WARCRIMES-650&AMP;     04-03 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-WARCRIMES-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO TROOPS SEIZE A TOP SERB FACING WAR CRIME CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ After years of criticism for not
bringing top war criminals to justice, NATO troops Monday arrested
Momcilo Krajisnik, one of the most important Serb leaders in the
Bosnian war, on charges of war crimes, including genocide.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said in announcing the arrest that Krajisnik, a
close ally of the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, was the
most senior of 39 war crime suspects now in custody. Diplomats have
described Krajisnik as a fanatic politician who sometimes equaled
Karadzic in power, and through his business deals helped finance
the ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign in the 1992-95 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik was immediately flown to The Hague where he will stand
trial before the International Tribunal, which charged him with
every war crime in its statute for his role as a principal
strategist behind hundreds of civilian massacres. Conviction would
mean a maximum life sentence for Krajisnik, 55, who is expected to
enter a plea this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although his impending indictment was reported in the Serbian
press three months before it was handed up secretly in February, it
was not clear why French troops with the SFOR peacekeeping force
decided to arrest him now.
</P>
<P>
   But given the long-running failure of NATO forces to bring war
criminals to trial, Krajisnik clearly was not expecting his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said Krajisnik was at his elderly parents' home
in Pale when French troops knocked down the door shortly after 3
a.m. Monday. They locked his parents in a closet, hogtied his two
sons and hustled Krajisnik, still in his pajamas, onto a plane.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. representative at the
United Nations, said in an interview, ``This is possibly the most
important day since the Dayton agreement on Bosnia,'' adding that
``Krajisnik was a very important person after all. He was the
former co-president of Bosnia, he was the head of the Bosnia Serb
delegation at Dayton.'' Holbrooke was the author of the Dayton
peace accord on the Bosnian war in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The removal of Krajisnik from the country, which is long
overdue but couldn't happen until he was indicted, removes from
Bosnia the leading public opponent of the Dayton agreement. The
other opponent, Karadzic, has been in hiding for four years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor for the tribunal, Carla Del Ponte, said Monday
that Karadzic ``should stand trial jointly'' with Krajisnik. The
tribunal is clearly pressing NATO to make that trial a reality by
finally arresting Karadzic, indicted in 1995 on charges of
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's indictment against Krajisnik cataloged dozens of
destroyed villages and hundreds of massacres. It also listed 11
prison camps where non-Serbs were detained and tortured, executed
or deported under orders from Krajisnik and other top leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the war he was second only to Karadzic and shared command
over Bosnian military and police,'' said Paul Risley, the spokesman
for Del Ponte. ``The decisions he participated in, resulted in the
deaths of thousands of Bosnians and in the deportations and ethnic
cleansing of hundred of thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on NATO to arrest key figures accused of genocide
in the Balkans has been growing since last spring, after Louise
Arbour, then the international tribunal's prosecutor, began
complaining publicly about the lack of cooperation she had received
from Western governments.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Arbour began to receive the help she sought from
British, German and U.S. military intelligence agencies, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that ``this puts pressure on everyone else, is a
strong warning, and a strong assertion of renewed determination by
NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte, who succeeded Arbour, said the tribunals'
investigators have stepped up their work in turn, and expect to
bring as many as 50 more indictments of senior officials
responsible for crimes of genocide, murder and ``ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Del Ponte has intensified the demand on the nations of NATO for
intelligence support and military action against suspected war
criminals in the Balkans. She called Monday for those nations ``to
insist on the apprehension and surrender of all other indicted''
war criminals, and in particular Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' demands helped stiffen NATO's spine, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik, an executive of Yugoslavia's biggest power company
before the nation war, has long been Karadzic's political tool.
Dealing in arms and business rackets during the Balkans war, he
also played a shrewd enough hand to emerge as the titular political
leader of Bosnia's Serbs in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Out of office since 1998, he still wielded political control in
concert with Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krajisnik is a big fish,'' the State Department spokesman,
James Rubin, said in an interview Monday. ``And we expect his
arrest to rattle Karadzic's cage.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans to arrest Karadzic have existed on paper since 1997. There
they have remained. U.S. officials say they were scuttled by U.S.
commanders who feared a bloody operation would inflame Serbs and
Americans alike.
</P>
<P>
   French officers also were reluctant to act against prominent
Serbs in and around Pale, the zone French forces command under
NATO's banner; in the past three years they have arrested one minor
suspect and killed another.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was the French forces taking the lead in Monday's
arrest, prompting the Secretary of State, Madeleine Albright, to
call France's foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine, to offer her
congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French have been stung by criticism and were tired of
getting targeted'' for the fact that indicted war criminals like
Karadzic and Krajisnik seemed to live and work without fear in the
French zone, a senior U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, 70 suspects are known to be under indictment by the
tribunal; other sealed indictments may also exist. Of those
suspects, 39 are now in custody, including Krajisnik, with 20 of
them having been arrested by NATO forces, according to the
Coalition for International Justice, a Washington group working
with the war crime tribunals in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krajisnik is by far the most senior person they've arrested,''
said Kathy Ward, a senior fellow at the coalition. ``This is by far
the strongest indication of a commitment by NATO to go after not
just the little fish but the most senior leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
