u f BC-MICROSOFT-REDMOND-NYT     04-03 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REDMOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEATTLE, A $35 BILLION PAPER LOSS BUT SUPPORT FOR MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST; see also MICROSOFT-ADVISORY) 
(ms) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ When Microsoft got its legal thrashing from a
federal judge Monday, the Seattle area's roaring economy got a bit
of a jolt too. With about 40 percent of the company's stock in the
hands of people who live in the region, roughly $35 billion, on
paper anyway, vanished here between the time Bill Gates and Steve
Ballmer rose Monday morning and the time the company's two top
leaders stepped to a podium here to respond to the judge's finding.
</P>
<P>
   But sounding no less self-assured than they have throughout
their antitrust battle with the government, both men calmly
defended the company's actions, predicted vindication in both the
marketplace and the legal arena, and reiterated a
through-the-looking-glass depiction of how government prosecutors
have misunderstood the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling turns on its head the reality that consumers know
_ that our software has helped make PCs more accessible and more
affordable to millions,'' said Gates, Microsoft's co-founder and
chairman. ``Innovation will continue to be the No. 1 priority at
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson concluded that the
company had violated antitrust laws and kept ``an oppressive
thumb'' on the competition, Ballmer insisted that Microsoft's legal
and image problems stemmed from the fact that it had never been
able to shed its little-guy mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent the past 25 years thinking of ourselves as a
small, aggressive company playing catch-up to industry giants even
though at some point along the way we became a large company,''
said Ballmer, the chief executive. ``Our intense focus on moving
forward has at times been seen as threatening and our passion for
being the best has been misinterpreted. We can do better. But that
doesn't mean innovating any less or delivering any less value to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   If such a view may inspire derision from competitors in Silicon
Valley, it still has considerable resonance in the Seattle area,
where Monday's news did not seem to generate any large sense of
panic. In fact, it prompted many people in the street to express
anger that _ as more than one person put it _ their taxpayer
dollars were being spent to ``harangue'' the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the government typed up the indictment, what did they use
to type it up with?'' said Selah Houdin, a student at Seattle
Central Community College. ``They used Microsoft. They had the
option to use other programs to type it up. They chose Microsoft
because it's best.''
</P>
<P>
   Money managers who are heavily invested in Microsoft stock were
clearly not happy, but most said they considered the company's
long-term prospects excellent and were not inclined to sell off
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think the outlook is much different than it was
Friday,'' said Bill Whitlow, manager of the Safeco Northwest Fund,
a mutual fund with roughly 6 percent of its $152 million in
holdings in Microsoft stock. Like many other analysts here, he said
the stock had actually enjoyed a run-up recently, built in part on
unrealistic expectations that a settlement was at hand. And several
noted that even if the company is broken up, a prospect they still
considered unlikely, the sum of its parts might well be worth more
than its current whole, as was famously the case with John D.
Rockefeller's Standard Oil trust.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Pascall, a senior fellow at the Institute for Public
Policy at the University of Washington, who has studied the
company's impact on the local economy, said many people here viewed
Monday's ruling as an ``interim legal event'' in a long-running
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not sure you're going to see a lot of gnashing of
teeth in response to this,'' said Pascall, who is also a columnist
in the local Puget Sound Business Journal. Asked to characterize
the fallout from Monday's ruling, he said: ``I would say that a
small number of people with large holdings of Microsoft stock
suffered a large one-day paper loss because of an overreaction to
the end of an unrealistic expectation of an early resolution. The
market has totally discounted the fact that Microsoft would have
had to make significant concessions to resolve the process through
negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   If such sanguine reactions were typical here, they may
themselves wind up being overly optimistic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
