u i BC-HAITI-KILLING-NYT &LR;      04-03 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMINENT RADIO JOURNALIST IS SHOT TO DEATH IN HAITI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jean Dominique, Haiti's most prominent radio journalist and a
passionate voice for democracy through decades of dictatorships and
political turmoil in his impoverished homeland, was shot to death
along with a security guard Monday by two gunmen outside his
station in Port-au-Prince, Haiti's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique, 69, was the founder of Radio Haiti Inter, whose news
and commentary in Creole and French were heard six days a week by
300,000 Haitian-Americans in the New York area in recent years and
by many of Haiti's 8 million people since the 1960s. He was shot as
he stepped from his car at 6:15 a.m., local time, the station said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen fled and there were no immediate arrests. Wounded
several times in the head and neck, Dominique and his guard,
Jean-Claude Louissaint, who was shot in the neck, were rushed to a
hospital in suburban Petionville, where both were pronounced dead.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing was unknown. But Haitian-Americans in
New York _ including Ricot Dupuy, the manager of Radio Soleil, the
Brooklyn station that carried Dominique's broadcasts _ and
Jean-Claude Bajeux, a former minister of culture and a human rights
advocate in Haiti, called it an assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was killed to silence his voice,'' said Dupuy. He noted
that Dominique, in recent broadcasts, had defended President Rene
Preval's decision to delay legislative elections until later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   News of Dominique's death _ solemnly broadcast by a substitute
announcer on ``Inter-Actualities,'' the 7 a.m. program on which the
victim and his wife, the journalist Michele Montas were to have
been the anchors _ was met with dismay, sorrow and anger in Haiti
and in the Haitian community in New York. He is also survived by
three daughters, Gigi, Dolores and Nadine.
</P>
<P>
   Preval, for whom Dominique was a special assistant; Prime
Minister Jacques-Edouard Alexis; and the former president
Jean-Bertrand Aristide went to the hospital but issued no
statements.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy in Port-au-Prince expressed ``great concern''
over ``the brutal slaying.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique was born in Port-au-Prince to a well-to-do family and
attended private schools in Haiti and France, studying agronomy,
said Jonathan Demme, the filmmaker, who did a documentary on
Dominique.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, when virtually all of Haiti's news media
were owned and used as propaganda outlets by the government,
Dominique founded Radio Haiti Inter as a voice of the people. It
was the first outlet to broadcast in Creole, the language of most
Haitians, 75 percent of whom are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two decades, as Haiti was brutalized and
systematically looted by Francois Duvalier and his son,
Jean-Claude, Dominique was among the few pleading for human rights.
Friends said his life was threatened often by the Tontons Macoute,
the secret police. He was severely beaten, his brother was killed
and members of his family and staff were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Dominique's station was shut down and he was driven
into exile in New York. But in 1986, when a popular uprising
toppled Jean-Claude Duvalier, Dominique returned to rebuild his
station, and 50,000 people met him at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   He became a supporter of Aristide, who was elected president in
1990 in the first democratic elections in 33 years. But a year
later, Aristide was ousted by the army, thugs attacked and again
wrecked Radio Haiti and Dominique again went into exile, this time
with Aristide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after United States intervention, Aristide and
Dominique returned to Haiti. But while the radio station was
restored to life, democracy has remained elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique had defended the government's decision to delay the
elections, though opponents said it would help Aristide's allies,
because he believed that opponents were trying to rig them, Dupuy
of Radio Soleil said. ``He wanted to make sure the elections were
fair and democratic,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
