<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN-BROTHER04-COX     04-03 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN-BROTHER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin's brother denounces `frenzy'
 &HT;    By Mae W. Gentry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Acting with ``the frenzy of a lynch mob,'' police
officials and the media have made it difficult for Jamil Abdullah
Al-Amin to get a fair trial, his brother said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Brown expressed outrage at ``irresponsible'' news coverage of
the case against his brother, the former H. Rap Brown, who is
accused of shooting two Fulton County sheriff's deputies, one
fatally, on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   He singled out Fulton County Sheriff Jackie Barrett for creating
a ``poisoned'' atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost from the beginning, she loaded the dice,'' he said.
``She came out with this charge that they were ambushed.'' That, he
said, implies premeditation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the first time on behalf of Al-Amin's family,
Brown, who lives in southwest Atlanta, said they have ``tried to
take the high road, quietly putting together a defense team that
can prove him innocent.'' But, he said, he felt compelled to
balance the ``innuendo, rumor and unsubstantiated charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he and his siblings were reared ``with a strong sense
of right and wrong, morality and decency.'' They were taught, ``You
had a responsibility to make things better for the next
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 58, is the eldest of three children born in Baton Rouge,
La., to Thelma Warren Brown and Eddie C. Brown Sr. She worked as a
schoolteacher, domestic and dietitian; he was a pipefitter for Esso
Standard Oil. Both are deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's sister, Patricia, 57, is a retired music teacher who
lives in Washington. Al-Amin, 56, was born Hubert but changed his
name after converting to Islam in prison in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's activism _ as a member of the Student Non-Violent
Coordinating Committee and as a Muslim leader _ was ``to help
people,'' said Brown, who is marketing manager for an engineering
firm and who has an even longer history of involvement of the
student-led movement to desegregate public accommodations
throughout the South. In 1960, he was expelled from Southern
University for political reasons, he said. His sister and brother
later attended Southern and were active in the student movement.
</P>
<P>
   Brown moved to Washington, enrolled in Howard University and
joined SNCC. Al-Amin followed him to D.C. and into the
organization, developing a reputation for militance that put him
under FBI scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has continued to promote the electoral process. He became
executive director of the Voter Education Project, an agency whose
staffers conducted voter registration workshops and
get-out-the-vote campaigns. When it disbanded in 1992, Brown turned
his efforts to emerging democracies. He observed elections and
conducted voter education and registration in post-apartheid South
Africa, among other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's spiritual journey led him down a different path. For
more than two decades he has been leader of a mosque in Atlanta's
West End neighborhood, site of the killing of the deputies,
Aldranon English and Ricky Kinchen. Kinchen died in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   People in West End have been generally supportive of Al-Amin,
crediting him with ridding the neighborhood of drugs and
prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said his brother tried to build an Islamic community.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's plans were taking shape in White Hall, Ala. An
architect had been hired, and a model built for a community that
would offer housing, a specialty supermarket, and other goods and
services for Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Alabama that Al-Amin participated in voter
registration drives and became a friend of John Jackson, now mayor
of White Hall, where Al-Amin was captured four days after the
deputies were shot.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Al-Amin's claim that his arrest was a ``government
conspiracy'' may not be farfetched. Many black leaders have been
targets of the government, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time when he was arrested in Cambridge (Md.), we have
assumed he was under surveillance,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown calls a report in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution that
Al-Amin was under investigation in 14 unsolved killings
``irresponsible to the highest degree. It has no bearing on what
he's being charged with, and there was no evidence,'' Brown said.
Al-Amin was never charged in those homicides.
</P>
<P>
   A national defense fund is being organized in Atlanta, and a Web
site is under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility to withhold judgment extends to media and to
Sheriff Barrett, Brown said. ``I understand her sense of grief and
the sense of grief of those families, but we still have an
obligation to ensure that an accused person gets a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
