<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MAMBO-SALON-ART-2TAKE     04-03 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMBO-SALON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SUNDAYS, AN EAST VILLAGE HAIR STYLIST OPENS HIS SALON FOR MAMBO
MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT 36-37, have been sent to New York Times photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By Sunday afternoon, the ringlets of cut hair and
traces of ponytails are swept up at the Ene Hair Salon in
Manhattan's East Village. The swivel chairs and the bubble hair
dryer are tucked in a corner. But jars of aqua-blue Barbicide,
hairspray and pomade still line the counters as men and women sway
forward and back across the wine-red plywood floor.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, many go to the salon for trims, highlights,
conditioning treatments, maybe an upper body massage. But come
Sunday afternoon, they are infected by mambo madness when the
basement-level salon on East Ninth Street turns into a dance
palace.
</P>
<P>
   Their hips are rotating. Their arms coil upward as they twirl.
Some count out the beat for the syncopated steps under their breath
as they plunge into a dip, then a spin.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the salon proprietor's Pekingese poodle terrier,
Virginia (nicknamed Peekapoo), weaves between the legs of the mambo
dancers, barking at the Afro-Cuban melodies.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to become indifferent to the oddities of the East
Village, a neighborhood where pierced noses and spiky dyed hair are
common and boutiques with names like Religious Sex sell leather
corsets. This is New York, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is something particularly off-kilter, like a campy
John Waters film, to the mambo scene at Ene on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Even as chorus lines of more than a dozen people heat up the
floor, elbow to elbow, a few frazzled people amble in, eager to
make appointments for haircuts and colorings. On a recent Sunday,
an aggressive salesman blustered through the door, insisting on
giving his sales pitch for an electronics product to the salon
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you see we're dancing, man,'' said the annoyed
proprietor, Nelson Barreto, who was trying to maneuver a mambo
turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came a long way,'' huffed the indignant salesman, glaring
over his shoulder on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, though, passers-by stop in their tracks on
the sidewalk, peering inside the bay window of the Ene salon. The
place is hard to miss. It has a lavender-painted facade and in the
window is a two-foot-high statue of a praying angel, with a
container of hair gel between its wings. (The salon gets its name,
Ene, from the Spanish pronunciation of the letter n (EN-eh), the
initial of the owner's first name.)
</P>
<P>
   The mambo tradition, if it can be called one yet, began about
two months ago when Barreto, the owner, agreed to let the boyfriend
of one of his hairstylists hold dance classes there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do something else that we hadn't done before,''
said Barreto, a 35-year-old native of Puerto Rico. He lives in a
fifth-floor walk-up next door. ``We're given a license to make you
feel beautiful and music is an addition to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Classes began with a few clients on the salon's mailing list,
but the mambo sessions have grown exponentially as clients have
told their friends. Like the homey salon, the $15-dollar classes
draw a multicultural crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It is not quite the Palladium in midtown Manhattan, the
legendary Latin ballroom that was ground zero for the mambo in the
1950. But the salon has created its own special comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel like they know us,'' Barreto said. ``It's less
threatening than going to a club or a huge class, where people know
how to dance. Some don't want people to know they have two left
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nuss-Caneda, a 37-year-old public school teacher from
Brooklyn, has her long reddish-brown hair colored at the salon. But
on Sundays, she is accompanied by her Mexican-born husband, Rene, a
Spanish-language tutor. She appreciates the diversity of the salon
as much as learning the mambo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to work hard to find communities that are
different,'' she said. ``This is a way that we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Sunday, it was getting steamy inside the salon so the
door was left open. The customers were learning a beginner's step,
the right foot crossing over the left foot as hips twist and swivel
on three beats. The instructor, Frankie Martinez, calls it the
``Suzy-Q,'' because the step feels the way it sounds as the hips
twist, twist, twist.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, a trimly built 24-year-old with a goatee, learned the
mambo from his mentor, Eddie Torres, a leading New York mambo
teacher who has a professional dance troupe. Martinez is a member.
The mambo is the original version of the popular dance called the
salsa, but it is danced on a different time structure. Torres has a
repertory of more than 350 mambo steps.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who also holds a black belt in karate, started dancing
only about two years ago. He has taught mambo for one year.
</P>
<P>
   It is evident that some customers will never advance to what
might be called mambo's black belt, an intricate pattern of quick
steps that is sort of like skating with feet. Torres calls it the
``syncopated jelly jam, a little dab will do you.''
</P>
<P>
   The instructor, who was dressed the other day in a billowy white
shirt, cream-colored pants and black and white dance shoes,
remained consistently upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mambo divas, you,'' Martinez called out, his dimples
deepening as the dancers laughed. They snapped their fingers to
find the driving beat when the instructor turned on the tape
player. As the two-hour session progressed, they stopped glancing
at their feet so much, undulating quickly, confidently.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Hernandez, already an experienced salsa dancer, heard
about the class through a friend and has not missed a Sunday. It
relaxes her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I know salsa, the steps in mambo are shorter and
faster than salsa steps,'' said Hernandez, 43, a home-care
supervisor in Brooklyn. ``It's like learning something totally
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Gieringer, a 47-year-old artist in cargo pants and
sneakers, was taking a break under a bubble hair dryer as her
husband, Polar Levine, and the other men were practicing turns. Her
husband, a musician whose head is bald except for a single
dreadlock at the nape of his neck, said he gets inspiration from
Martinez's instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get brain lock when I'm taught stuff, but he's real good and
when I unlock my brain, I'm killer,'' said Levine, leaning into a
turn.
</P>
<P>
   Among the salon's most loyal customers is Toni Castillo, a
petite 51-year-old, who on Sundays brings her grim-faced boyfriend,
Carlos Flores. He was stuck the other day on a move called the
``drop-catch.'' Turning with his back facing Castillo, Flores had
to drop his partner's hand down his back and lightly catch it with
the opposite hand.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, wearing jeans and black stiletto heels, giggled that
her 45-year-old boyfriend told her that she should get a leg
transplant to improve her moves. She does not mind that he pokes
fun at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come in every single Sunday,'' she said merrily. ``It's
been beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As dusk fell on a recent Sunday, the mambo instructor's
girlfriend, Aisha Koswara, sat quietly next to a row of sinks.
</P>
<P>
   She was listening to a woman who had wandered in off the street.
The woman, Ann Schwanke, owns a lingerie import business and spoke
to Koswara about feeling a bit psychic. Not even five minutes
before, she said she was thinking about Latin dance lessons _ then
there was the mambo class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw something going on in the hair salon that was not
hair,'' said Schwanke, who began displaying silken lingerie from a
bag to Koswara in hopes of collaborating on a lingerie mambo party.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, Koswara, a svelte 22-year-old with a pierced
diamond stud in her nose, joins her boyfriend, Martinez, on the
floor to give a dazzling demonstration of a tricky step. The class
watches the couple's liquid moves in silence before bursting into
applause.
</P>
<P>
   It was the hairstylist's idea to have mambo classes at the
salon. She saw nothing unusual in it. She noted how her mother, a
Puerto Rican, met her father, newly arrived in New York from
Indonesia, in an underground gambling den in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything happens in the Village,'' she said with a shrug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
