<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI seeks Al-Amin Alabama helpers
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The FBI is investigating about 10 people in the tiny
town of White Hall, Ala., who may have helped Jamil Abdullah
Al-Amin after he fled there last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Imfeld, special agent in charge of the FBI's investigation
of Al-Amin in Alabama, said Mayor John Jackson, a longtime friend
of the former black militant turned Islamic spiritual leader, is
among the people under investigation. Al-Amin's black Mercedes-Benz
was found last week on property owned by Jackson's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not ruling anyone out _ including Mayor Jackson ... in
the harboring case,'' Imfeld said Friday. ``We are also looking at
four of Al-Amin's friends stopped in a black Cadillac and some
other people in the town.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will be cleared from suspicion, Imfeld said, until
evidence collected from Al-Amin's black Mercedes-Benz is tested and
returned to the FBI and Atlanta police.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has vehemently denied harboring Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Al-Amin's friends, detained the same night the suspect
was captured in a patch of woods, also have denied they saw Al-Amin
after he arrived in the town.
</P>
<P>
   The four are acquainted with Al-Amin and also are members of
White Hall's small Islamic community. They were released from jail
after police determined there was not enough evidence linking them
to the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   A day before Al-Amin's Mercedes was found, the car's Georgia
license plate was discovered behind the Bismillah Cafe, a small
restaurant once operated by Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
