<HEADER>
A6154 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-MASTERS-AMATEUR-T     04-03 2372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-AMATEUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET HAAS MAKING LOUDEST NOISES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Champagne flowed in the tiny motel room, where family members
waited for the conquering hero to wash away the residue from a long
afternoon on the golf course and join in the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   As toasts were raised to Hunter Haas' victory at the 1999 U.S.
Public Links Championship, which clinched his spot in the 2000
Masters, the mood was altered by the strains of pounding on the
shower door.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hunter, the quietest of seven siblings in the Haas
household, doing something most uncharacteristic. He was releasing
emotion. Soon, the pounding begat shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen Corner! Amen Corner!'' Haas hollered between thumps. ``I
can't believe I just won a USGA event!''
</P>
<P>
   Hans Haas, one of Hunter's older brothers and soon-to-be Masters
caddie, smiled as he recalled the culmination of their weeklong
stay in Alton, Ill. With Hunter's 4 and 3 victory against Michael
Kirk in the final match of the U.S. Golf Association event, the
graduate of Southwest High School in Fort Worth, Texas, completed a
circuitous journey from Sycamore Creek Golf Course to Augusta
National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the 23-year-old will become the first amateur golfer
from Fort Worth to compete in the Masters since Lindy Miller
finished 16th in 1978 and John Grace in 1975-76, who missed the cut
both years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of the Masters stuff really hit him until he
was in there,'' Hans Haas said of a shower scene that, from his
perspective, ranks with anything produced by Alfred Hitchcock in
terms of lasting impact. ``It was never mentioned the whole time we
were rooming together.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Hunter said, the ramifications of his match against
Kirk _ winner to Augusta, loser reduced to watching on television _
dominated his thoughts that morning on the way to Spencer T. Olin
Community Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided whoever dropped that from his mind first and shut
that out of his head would have the best chance,'' Hunter said.
``It didn't cross my mind again until afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Such focus is rare, said Roland Harper, the former Colonial
Country Club head golf professional who has tutored Haas since
childhood. But it is something Harper began noticing shortly after
Haas recorded his first ace, as an 8-year-old, on Colonial's 13th
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the junior golfers I've had, he's the one I thought
would be special,'' said Harper, 72. ``There's something about his
attitude that's different from the rest. Hunter is unusually calm.
If he shows any emotion on the course, it's a spark and then it's
gone. He stays in control of what he's doing, and he's done that
since he was 12. That was the thing that always made me feel like
he'd be special.'' A QUIET LONER
</P>
<P>
   Even among seven siblings with enviable golf resumes, Hunter
stands out. He was the first of Jim and Karen Haas' children to be
born at home, rather than in a hospital, after the couple decided
four offspring had provided them enough insight to eliminate
doctors from the birthing process. He's the only loner among an
otherwise outgoing group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys think he's a jerk because he doesn't say much,''
said Heidi Haas, 21, the sibling closest in age to Hunter. ``But
he's not. He's introverted and the rest of us are extroverted. Out
of seven kids, somebody had to be the quiet one.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's his name. Hunter is the only Haas child with five
names on his birth certificate: Hunter Jefferson Huck Finn Haas. An
avid Mark Twain fan, Jim convinced Karen to include the name of a
favorite literary character in his youngest son's official handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter used to be a little bit shy about it, but not any
more,'' Jim Haas said. ``It's distinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter has embraced his uniqueness to the point that, in the
golf bag he carries, one headcover is emblazoned with ``Huck,''
another ``Finn.'' He also has made peace with the fact he's a
perpetual sufferer from ``Little Brother Syndrome,'' which drove
him, at age four, to enter his first Fort Worth city junior golf
tournament. Holly, his oldest sister, followed Hunter around
Sycamore Creek to help him count strokes and fill out his
scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Holly became the first of five Haas children to win
a city, state or high school district golf championship. Hunter
watched as trophies began filling the family home. The ones that
most caught his eye belonged to Hans, who was five years older but
the brother closest to his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever my brother did, I set a goal to do better,'' Hunter
Haas said. ``I wanted to start beating him, whatever it took.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't easy. Hans won three state high school titles, two
city championships and a state amateur title. He landed a golf
scholarship at Arkansas, then transferred to Oklahoma. Hunter
eventually made his mark for the Sooners as well, winning the 1998
Big 12 individual championship.
</P>
<P>
   But such accomplishments seemed far off in the days when Hans,
28, and Hud, 30, used their little brother as a tackling dummy in
games of backyard football. The older brothers would be the
quarterbacks and defenders on respective two-man teams, with Hunter
the permanent receiver who shifted between squads and absorbed all
the punishment after catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just hammer him the whole game,'' said Hud, now the
superintendent of greens at The Academy at WaterChase. ``I think
that toughened him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, it sharpened his hunger for success. Jim Haas
recalled settling many a dispute between Hans and Hunter when the
competitive juices overflowed, from who shot the lowest golf score
to who grabbed the largest chicken drumstick at the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think those two would cut each other's throat for a
dime. It brought my wife to tears over the intensity of it,'' Jim
Haas said. ``But it was instrumental in developing Hunter's
mystique on the golf course.'' BREAKTHROUGH
</P>
<P>
   It took years, but Hunter finally had his breakthrough moment.
On a makeshift green in the back yard, he made up for mountains of
lost baseball cards by beating Hans in a chipping contest. He can't
recall the year, Hunter said, but he was in high school and Hans
was home from college.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big boost for me. If I could beat him, I could beat
anybody,'' said Hunter, who soon thereafter posted a lower score
than his brother for the first time in an actual round.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence gained from succeeding as an underdog against Hans
eventually propelled Hunter to bigger things, like back-to-back
Texas State Boys Junior Championships (1994, 1995) and four
consecutive district titles at Southwest. Of 24 high-profile titles
won by members of the Haas family as junior golfers, Hunter added
eight to the family collection, including two Fort Worth city
junior championships.
</P>
<P>
   After completing his eligibility at Oklahoma, Haas' career took
its biggest upsurge last summer, when he won two of the nation's
most prestigious amateur events _ the Public Links and the Porter
Cup _ and reached the semifinals of the U.S. Amateur. By the time
he'd posted a 3-1 record for the U.S. team in the 1999 Walker Cup,
amateur golf's version of the Ryder Cup, Haas found himself headed
to Augusta as the nation's top-ranked amateur.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrives, he'll have no bigger ally on the grounds than
Hans, the lifelong adversary who will carry his bag. Through their
battles growing up, Hunter said the two formed a friendship to go
with their rivalry. At Hans' wedding on Feb. 26, Hunter and Hud
shared best man duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter knows I can push his buttons, for the good or the
bad,'' Hans Haas said. ``My goal going down there is to keep Hunter
in check and not let his emotions get the best of him. He has the
game to compete with the best in the world. I'm not saying that
because he's my brother. I see it. Hunter would beat me like a
drum, up and down, if we played every day.''
</P>
<P>
   How well Haas will fare against the Masters field is open for
debate. Harper predicted Haas would make the cut. Jim Haas said his
son ``thinks he can win.'' Hunter Haas, who finished second in the
Azalea Amateur on March 26 in his final pre-Masters tuneup, said he
has no definitive goal beyond making ``as many pars and birdies as
I can'' and playing four rounds, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   Haas spent the weekend of March 10-12 practicing at the course
and said he felt ``a lot more comfortable'' on the layout than he
expected. He'll play practice rounds this week with Tom Lehman and
Arnold Palmer, among others, in quest of additional insight.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, a four-time Masters champ, was the first player Haas
approached about a practice round. They plan to play Tuesday, along
with David Gossett, the U.S. Amateur champ from the University of
Texas. Haas said Palmer, 70, provided a logical source of Masters
insight because ``if you think about who's been most successful
there and still plays, it's probably him.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have not met, but Haas saved the letter Palmer wrote
him, confirming plans for Tuesday's practice round. At Augusta,
Haas said his greatest strength _ a stellar short game _ should
come into play more than at most major-championship venues because
of the short rough and undulating terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can scramble from anywhere,'' Haas said. ``I can hit it
average and still score well because my short game will take care
of the rest.'' MASTERY OF SHORT GAME
</P>
<P>
   Part of that attitude was instilled from sessions with Harper,
who stresses one recurring theme to students: All else pales when
weighed against the ability to get the ball in the hole within two
shots from inside 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter is one of the few who took me to heart on that,''
Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he took lessons at Colonial, Haas rarely played the
course while growing up. A self-employed painter, Jim Haas
relinquished the family membership at the club because of financial
concerns before Hunter's 10th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   That meant Hunter and Heidi, the youngest members of the Haas
clan to play college golf, honed their skills primarily at
municipal courses. On summer days, Hunter often would complete a
round at Pecan Valley Golf Course, then stay for six hours rolling
putts on the practice green. In July and August, said Heidi, the
grass on that green was essentially threadbare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd hit across divot holes and he was still making putts,''
she said. ``That's why he has such a great short game. He learned
off nothing, under the crappiest conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's the final member of a golf-crazed family still
competing regularly in tournaments. He'll have all of his siblings,
plus their spouses, following him in Augusta. In many ways, the
Masters will serve as a reunion for a group that could be
considered the First Family of amateur golf in Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect Jim Haas to see it that way. Unlike Dallas
resident Ernie Kuehne, who welcomed being labeled as the patriarch
of ``America's First Family of Amateur Golf'' after daughter Kelli
and son Hank won U.S. Amateur championships, Jim Haas said he
considers such labels ``embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be awfully vain to say that, even with all the
stuff they've done,'' he said. ``Our kids have had a lot of fun
playing golf and they've gotten a lot of attention from it. But
history takes care of itself with those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never saw Byron Nelson pumping himself up like that. Or
Ben Hogan. In some ways, Hunter's a lot like Hogan ... kind of a
nice fellow who keeps to himself. I don't think he'll change. If
Hunter ever gets to flitting around in a limo, acting \Rspoiled\S
like one of the Cowboys, I can about guarantee one of his brothers
will knock his head between his shoulders real low and get him back
where he should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although comparisons with the Kuehnes are inevitable, and the
two families maintain an amicable relationship, Jim Haas said a
clear line of demarcation exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the blue collars and Hank's people are the Highland Park
group,'' he said. ``I'm friendly with Ernie, but he's a different
personality type.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is Hunter. Quiet and intense, he's prone to action, not
words. That is why Harper said he became emotional when Haas showed
him the ring he earned for winning the 1998 Big 12 championship.
Inscribed on the side are the initials ``RH,'' for Roland Harper.
Also ``PIP,'' which stands for ``Play in the Present,'' a Harper
buzz phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ``You teach all your life and something like that makes it worth
all the work and time and heartache,'' said Harper, who retired in
1992. ``When I saw that, that made me feel really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas considered it a fitting tribute to the guy who got him
started on what he hopes will be a career in professional golf.
Haas plans to turn professional after the Masters, but might wait
until May, to enhance his opportunity of landing an amateur's
exemption into the MasterCard Colonial (May 18-21). STUBBORN AND
CONFIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Asked to identify his greatest strength as a golfer, Haas cited
``stubbornness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to convince me I can't do something,'' he said,
sounding every bit the driven little brother. ``I've got a lot of
confidence and I'm going to do it my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas' way has taken him to Augusta. Among his closest
confidants, the only one missing this week will be Harper. The
former Colonial club pro is battling skin cancer and will be
undergoing chemotherapy sessions until Thursday at a local
hospital. By Friday morning, Harper said he plans to be home in
Granbury, in front of a television, getting updates on Haas'
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Hud Haas, meanwhile, eagerly awaits his first journey down
Magnolia Lane, from the front gate to the Augusta clubhouse. While
a student at Mississippi State studying golf-course agronomy, he
stood at that gate and displayed his superintendent's card, seeking
an audience with the man in charge of manicuring the Masters
layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every question I asked, the guard said, `No,' '' he recalled.
``Things didn't pan out, to say the least. Now, the superintendent
wants to meet me. Who would have figured my little brother would be
the one to change that?'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
