<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-FAMILY-     04-03 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-FAMILY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S TOP CATCHER ALSO AN ALL-STAR FAMILY MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American League Most Valuable Player hits .300 every year,
wins Gold Gloves and plays in the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez is also good at playing Monkey in the Middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have two people on each side and someone in the middle,''
his daughter Amanda, 4, explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two people throw it to each other,'' continued Dereck, 7,
the oldest of Rodriguez's three children. ``The person in the
middle tries to catch it. If he does, the person who threw it is
It.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand?
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez does because he plays the game often. He also wrestles
with Dereck, takes Amanda swimming and sits on the sofa and watches
television for hours on end with his wife, Maribel. There were also
nights during spring training in Port Charlotte of Putt-Putt Golf,
Go-Kart Racing and dinner at Sarasota's swanky St. Armand's Circle,
just like any tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy is a good daddy because he always plays with me,''
Amanda said.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the best catcher in baseball's efforts to be
the best father possible. While growing up in Puerto Rico in a
house usually filled with relatives, friends and neighbors,
Rodriguez came to the conclusion that family is and always should
be important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be alone,'' said Rodriguez, whose second
daughter, Ivanna, was born on Jan. 12. ``When I grew up, there were
always people in the house. When I go on the road, when I'm in a
room by myself, I get lonely. I need somebody to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was up to me, my family would go everywhere with me.
They can't because of school, but I enjoy having my family around
me.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Dereck is around often enough, just reaching the age
where he can go to the ballpark with his dad without needing mom to
supervise. Tall and skinny for his age _ he doesn't look like
another Pudge _ with a snappy crewcut, Dereck was all over the
Rangers' compound this spring, on the field and in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a sight seeing Rodriguez stroll into the Rangers'
clubhouse with Dereck tagging along right behind him holding a
small pouch and his dad's cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   It was his dad's phone wasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have him along because it keeps him out of
trouble,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   That is until Dereck goes tearing through the clubhouse bouncing
a basketball, swinging a bat or indulging in his favorite pastime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being in the clubhouse because I get to take stuff out
of guys lockers and hide it,'' Dereck said.
</P>
<P>
   He also doesn't mind taking a few hitting lessons from batting
coach Rudy Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the blood,'' Rodriguez says proudly. ``He could be a
player, but I don't want to push him. I want him to be a baseball
player if he likes. But if he wants to be something else, I'll help
him do what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually those plans change on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day he wants to do something different,'' Maribel said.
``We took him to the Air Show with the Blue Angels and he wanted to
be a pilot. Then, as we were leaving, he talked to some guy who's
in the Army. Now he wants to be in the Army.''
</P>
<P>
   His dad always wanted to be a baseball player. Dereck's mother
never quite knew what to make of that.
</P>
<P>
   Maribel Rivera was born in Puerto Rico but grew up in Brooklyn.
She was 15 when she moved back to Puerto Rico and was introduced to
Rodriguez a couple months later. He had just signed his first
contract with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't into sports,'' she said. ``I really didn't know who
he was. His brother introduced us. I just liked being around him
and the way he was. He was funny. He still is.''
</P>
<P>
   Maribel spent most of the spring in Florida with the family, but
only went to a couple of games. She spent most of her time at their
rental house with the two daughters while Dereck was wrestling with
Rafael Palmeiro or hiding his equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like watching Pudge play,'' she said. ``But when I know he's
not going to play, I don't go to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   They dated while Rodriguez was in the minor leagues. They were
supposed to get married on June 20, 1991, but that was the day
Rodriguez was called up to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to get married that day,'' Rodriguez said. ``But
(Tulsa manager) Bobby Jones called me in into his office and told
me I had to be in Chicago the next day. I had to tell her we
couldn't get married.''
</P>
<P>
   The story goes that Rodriguez got married that morning, then
went to Chicago and right into the Rangers' lineup. But that's not
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows it, but we didn't get married,'' Rodriguez said
with a smile. ``We got married down here (the following spring). We
drove over to Punta Gorda and got married.''
</P>
<P>
   Maribel admitted she had a tough time getting used to being the
wife of a major league star and sharing him with the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been overwhelming and in such little time,'' she said.
``So many things have happened. People wanted him to do so many
things. I'd plan something together as a family and then we'd have
to cancel it. I think only in the last 21/2 years have I started
getting used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things she hasn't become comfortable with, like people
asking not only for her husband's autograph, but hers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that,'' she said. ``That's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The autograph craze can be bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone to Wet N' Wild, we're in the pool, and people ask
for his autograph,'' she said. ``People come up to him with
baseballs and baseball cards at Wet N' Wild. They're in their
bathing suits. I'm wondering where they got the baseballs from. I
still don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for privacy and time alone with family has led the
Rodriguez family to seek their own private sanctuary. They have a
house in Colleyville where Dereck and Amanda attend a Montessori
school, and they still have a home in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   But they also have an apartment in Miami and are seriously
considering building a home there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Miami,'' Rodriguez said. ``Miami is like Puerto Rico. I
love water and I love the ocean. I like to be in a boat, I enjoy
going out on the ocean in a boat. I want to build a house on a
canal so I can put a boat in my backyard. So when I want to go out
on the water, I can just go in my backyard and get in my own
boat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus Miami just is an hour and fifty minutes away from Puerto
Rico by plane and just two hours from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason Rodriguez likes Miami over Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Puerto Rico,'' Rodriguez said. ``Puerto Rico is
beautiful. It's my country. But the schools in Puerto Rico aren't
as good as here in the states. Dereck went to school there and had
a bad experience. That was it. The work he did over here is totally
different.''
</P>
<P>
   For the American League's Most Valuable Player, it remains all
about the family coming first. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
