<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON WARNED OF NEW COMPUTER VIRUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A computer virus that erases hard drives, then makes bogus calls
to 911 emergency service providers has been detected in the Houston
area, the FBI's National Infrastructure Protection Center warned
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at the FBI/NIPC office in Washington said the virus
targets computers set up for file and print sharing, scanning
thousands of computers through four internet service providers _
America On-Line, AT&AMP;T, MCI and Netzero.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few computers have been affected by the virus,
however, the spokesman said. He declined to say when the virus
first struck, nor specifically how many computers may have been
affected. The first warning in the case was issued Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sonya Lopez, spokeswoman for the Greater Harris County 911
Network, said 911 centers in Harris and Fort Bend counties were
warned of the virus Monday morning. Only one bogus call has been
received in Harris County, she said. A second call was made to the
Anderson County Sheriff's Department in Palestine, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparently few cases, Matt Yarbrough, a former
computer crimes prosecutor with the U.S. attorney's office in
Dallas, described the virus as ``pretty darn scary.''
</P>
<P>
   He likened the 911 virus attack to earlier efforts to flood
Amazon.com, Yazoo and other Web sites with transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stores itself in your autoload file, then when you come
back to work, turn on your computer, it loads itself up and dials
911,'' said Yarbrough, now a special Internet counsel with Vinson &AMP;
Elkins' Dallas office. ``If you have hundreds or thousands of
users, you've got hundreds or thousands of calls going to 911. It's
flooded. It has the potential to shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can probably wait for an ambulance when you have a
heart attack, right? This is pretty malicious stuff. It's pretty
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Such hacking is in violation of federal and state laws. If
convicted of intentionally interfering with computers, an offender
could be sentenced to as much as five years in prison and fined
$250,000 for each affected computer.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of the virus should immediately report the episode to
the FBI/NIPC at 202-323-3204.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
