u f BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-BOS &LR;      04-03 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: MICROSOFT VIOLATED ANTITRUST LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. violated federal antitrust laws by scheming to
monopolize one of the Internet age's crucial consumer markets, a
federal judge ruled Monday, in a verdict that wiped out billions of
dollars in Microsoft stock value.
</P>
<P>
   In a 43-page judgment that accused the software empire founded
by Bill Gates of ``a deliberate assault upon entrepreneurial
efforts'' by technology rivals, US District Court Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson found Microsoft's efforts to corner the market for
Web browsers repeatedly violated the Sherman antitrust act and
antitrust laws of 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the ruling, released shortly after 5 p.m., Wall
Street pounded Microsoft shares down $15.375, or 14.47 percent, to
$90.875 before trading was briefly halted. The implosion drove a
nearly 8 percent drop in the technology-heavy Nasdaq market index,
its worst one-day slide in point terms.
</P>
<P>
   The worst selloff in Microsoft since the 1987 market crash
temporarily wiped out $12.1 billion of Gates' personal wealth,
dropping the value of his Microsoft holdings from $83.6 billion to
$71.5 billion, although company stock began to rebound in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ruling had been expected in light of his harsh
``findings of fact'' in November that called Microsoft a
monopolistic bully. But the judgment did not address what
punishment the Redmond, Wash., company might face.
</P>
<P>
   It could take months of further hearings and deliberations
before Judge Jackson decides on sanctions. And both the ruling
finding Microsoft guilty of antitrust violations and whatever
remedies Jackson orders appear certain to be appealed by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Both Microsoft and government lawyers said they remain open to a
settlement. But the most recent negotiations collapsed in failure
Saturday, amid reported squabbling between federal prosecutors and
state attorneys general over how far to go in punishing Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson's ruling survives the expected appeals to the US
Supreme Court, Microsoft could face billions in fines, wide-ranging
restrictions on how it does business, a demand it reveal the secret
contents of its Windows computer operating code, or even an
AT&AMP;T-style breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, whose department pressed the case
against Microsoft, said the judge's ruling showed that ``consumers
have been harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel I. Klein, the top antitrust enforcer for the US Justice
Department, said Jackson's ``landmark opinion'' will ``set the
ground rules for enforcement in the Information Age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It demonstrates once again that no company, no matter how
powerful or how successful, can refuse to play by the rules and
thwart competition for America's consumers,'' Klein said. He said
antitrust prosecutors will insist on ``a remedy that we think will
have an enduring impact going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an evening press conference, an unrepentant Gates said,
``There are several steps ahead in this case... . We believe we
have a strong case on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Microsoft remains open to settling the case before
Jackson rules on what punishment it should face, Steve Ballmer, the
company's chief executive officer, said, ``We'd love to continue
discussions in an appropriate way.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ballmer also said, ``Until the appeal is over, nothing is
settled.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling opens the door for a spate of civil antitrust suits
against Microsoft by technology companies, large and small, that
can claim its conduct cost them revenues and profits. Among them
are companies Jackson cited as victims, including IBM,
Hewlett-Packard, Intel, Netscape, and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McNealy, chief executive of Sun, whose Java operating
software was cited by Jackson as a target of Microsoft's
anticompetitive efforts, urged the judge to ``act decisively to
ensure that Microsoft's illegal activity _ and the harm that it has
done to the industry and to consumers _ is brought to an end
forcefully and permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   McNealy said the only way to protect consumers and industry
competitors is to break up Microsoft. He said the company ``must be
prohibited from using its ill-gotten gains to buy its way into new
markets and lock in new customers'' by buying up stakes in
technology startups with its ``massive cash hoard.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were divided on what the ruling means for Microsoft,
with some speculating the company would be well served by delaying
a settlement or punishment for as long as possible in hopes of a
presidential victory by Texas Governor George W. Bush, who opposes
a breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   For every month Microsoft can stall the antitrust case with
appeals, others noted, it can cement its position in emerging
markets for software that drives wireless Internet access systems
and other next-generation technologies, cushioning any impact on
its core computer operating system and office software market.
</P>
<P>
   While his November findings of fact described a wide-ranging
pattern of Microsoft punishing competitors and threatening
companies to use its products and shut out rivals', Jackson's
verdict turned on its conduct in the market for Web browsers, the
software Internet surfers use to find and display Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Having initally underestimated how quickly the Net would take
off as a crucial part of Americans' work, shopping and leisure,
Gates pushed Microsoft in 1995 and 1996 to catch up in the market
for Net browsers, then dominated by Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to build a market for its Internet Explorer, however,
Microsoft illegally exploited its monopoly position in computer
operating systems, Jackson ruled. More than 90 percent of the
world's computers use Windows operating systems, by many estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The judge upheld 23 of 26 monopoly misconduct arguments brought
by the states that joined the federal government in bringing the
case 22 months ago, although Jackson found the company not guilty
of ``unlawful exclusive dealing'' in marketing arrangements for
Windows with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ruled that Microsoft's efforts to push sales of Internet
explorer and force Windows users to buy the browser amounted to a
clear violation of the 1890 Sherman Act, the same antitrust law
that led to the breakup of the Standard Oil trust 90 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft mounted a deliberate assault upon entrepreneurial
efforts that, left to rise or fall on their own merits, could well
have enabled the introduction of competition into the market'' for
personal computer operating systems that run on Intel-compatible
chips, the judge said in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only when the separate categories of conduct are viewed, as
they should be, as a single, well-coordinated course of action does
the full extent of the violence that Microsoft has done to the
competitive process reveal itself,'' the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ruled that Microsoft's insistence on selling a version
of its Windows operating system that bundled in its Internet
Explorer _ and discouraged consumers from installing Netscape or
other Web browser programs _ ``was the result of a deliberate and
purposeful choice to quell incipient competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, Microsoft's share of the Internet browser market has
jumped from about 25 percent to over 60 percent, almost all at the
expense of rival Netscape, which was purchased by America Online
last May in a bid by AOL to hold off a monopoly in browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Top Microsoft executives repeated their mantra that Microsoft
wants to be free to continue to develop innovative products.
</P>
<P>
   Gates asserted that ``this ruling turns on its head the reality
that consumers know: that our software has helped make PCs
accessible and more affordable to millions of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer, named the company's CEO last year when Gates took a new
post as chief software architect, said, ``Our intense focus on
moving forward has at times been seen as threatening and our
passion for being the best has been misinterpreted. We can do
better. But that doesn't mean innovating any less or delivering any
less value to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides erasing billions in Microsoft wealth, the stock market
selloff dropped the company from No. 1 last week to No. 3 in total
stock market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   At $472.5 billion at the market close, Microsoft lagged General
Electric, worth $530.5 billion, and Silicon Valley networking giant
Cisco Systems Inc., worth about $506 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
