<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0535 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-AHEAD-BOS &LR;      04-03 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-AHEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT PRESIDENT VOWS TO CONTINUE THE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Ballmer is a famously tough businessman, and he's known
for months that federal judge Thomas Penfield Jackson would issue a
harsh verdict in the Microsoft antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ballmer, the president of Microsoft, is also a man who wears
his feelings on his sleeve. So at a press conference Monday, there
was no mistaking his emotions _ sadness, dismay and a steely
determination to keep fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intense focus on moving forward has at times been seen as
threatening and our passion for being the best has been
misinterpreted. We can do better,'' Ballmer admitted. For a moment,
he sounded chastened, slightly remorseful. Then he quickly added,
``But that doesn't mean innovating any less or delivering any less
value to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The right to innovate on behalf of customers, no matter how
badly it hurts Microsoft's competitors, has been the company's
battle cry throughout this antitrust case. Monday, Microsoft made
it clear it will continue to make that argument all the way to the
US Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And some industry experts say that the company's chances aren't
as bleak as they might at first appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a big setback for Microsoft, but the truth
is the game is far from over,'' said Michael Gartenberg, analyst
for the Gartner Group in Stamford, Conn. ``Microsoft has had a very
successful track record in fighting negative court rulings in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-known example occurred earlier in the legal wars over
Microsoft's Internet browsing software. In 1998, a federal appeals
court overturned an earlier injunction issued by Jackson in an
attempt to stop Microsoft from including an Internet browser in its
Windows 98 operating system. Even if Microsoft's actions harmed
rival browser maker Netscape Communications Corp., the court said
Microsoft had a right to take such actions if they also benefited
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Jackson specifically rejected the appeals court's
ruling. Yet that same court will hear Microsoft's next appeal.
Jackson ``has decided to buck the court he reports to,'' said
Charles Rule, former antitrust chief in the Justice Department and
sometime legal consultant to Microsoft. ``I think there's a real
question whether legally that's a sustainable position.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Microsoft's adversaries see the matter very
differently. ``I don't even understand their argument. You cannot
change the facts,'' said Mike Pettit, executive director of
ProComp, an organization that supports the federal antitrust suit
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Pettit noted that Monday's conclusions of law were based on the
findings of fact issued last year. At almost every point, the
findings agreed with the Justice Department's view that Microsoft
sought to ruthlessly crush rival companies.
</P>
<P>
   These findings of fact were not available to the appeals court
in 1998, when it ruled in favor of Microsoft. Now the court must
take the findings into account when reconsidering the matter, and
findings of fact are rarely overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In Pettit's view, the facts about Microsoft's behavior are so
damning that the appeals court will reverse itself and agree with
Jackson's ruling. ``I don't think they have a leg to stand on, on
appeal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal won't be coming for a while yet. First, Jackson
must decide on appropriate penalties. That could require several
more months, said Lars Liebeler, an antitrust attorney for the
Computing Technology Industry Association, a group that supports
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states and Justice will want to proceed as quickly as
possible to a remedies stage,'' said Liebeler. But he suggested
Microsoft improves its ultimate chances by delaying the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case itself has demonstrated that the technology sector
can change rapidly,'' said Liebeler. ``The marketplace doesn't look
anything like it looked two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft can drag the case through the courts for a couple
more years, it may be rendered moot, he said. So in that view, the
company has every reason to wait out the penalty phase, then take
its case first to the federal appeals court and perhaps eventually
to the US Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   To Liebeler, it's all a colossal waste of time. He pointed out
that a key witness for the Justice Department, MIT economist
Franklin Fisher, testified that he knew of no evidence that
Microsoft's business practices had harmed the public. ``To me,''
said Liebeler, ``that ended the case.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how it looks to Connecticut Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal, who sees Jackson's ruling as vindication of his
view that Microsoft has hurt consumers. ``All of the findings point
to the conclusion, and I think it'll be strong on appeal, that
Microsoft engaged in classic anticompetitive behavior,'' Blumenthal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even some stern Microsoft critics think the company may
survive the process intact. Bob Lande, board member of the American
Antitrust Institute, says the wording of Jackson's ruling gives him
hope that Microsoft will be broken up. ``Strong language gives rise
to a strong remedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lande still doubts that Jackson will go that far. ``Judges
rarely break up companies,'' he said. ``Rarely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
