u a BC-UGA-WRECK04-COX     04-03 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-WRECK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hazing suspected in fatal wreck
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ A University of Georgia student killed in a auto
wreck last week may have been handcuffed and blindfolded as part of
what Oconee County Sheriff Scott Berry suspects is a fraternity
hazing event.
</P>
<P>
   University officials could not say Monday whether hazing had
been part of the accident Thursday that killed Benjamin Folsom
Grantham III, 20, ``because the investigation isn't complete,''
said UGA communications director Tom Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But UGA President Michael Adams said the school would take
appropriate disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out that's what happened, there'll be some serious
consequences for those involved,'' Jackson added. ``We don't want
to get ahead of the investigation and we want to have all the facts
before we say too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Grantham, who was buried on St. Simons Island on Monday, was
apparently thrown from the cargo hold of a sport utility vehicle
after it struck a tree south of Watkinsville. He was a member of
Alpha Tau Omega _ not a pledge, a fraternity official said.
</P>
<P>
   Before authorities arrived at the scene of the wreck, someone
removed handcuffs from Grantham's wrists, Berry said. But
``handcuffs leave a very distinct mark,'' he said. ``From
information we've received from talking to various people, we
believe it was some kind of hazing incident.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of handcuffs were found at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragic event for us and the members of this
fraternity,'' said Wynn Smiley, executive director of the
Indianapolis-based national ATO organization, who came to the UGA
campus Monday. Smiley was in town to comfort the fraternity
brothers, but also to investigate the circumstances of the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will talk with the officers of (ATO), university officials
and possibly the police,'' he said. ``Certainly our prayers go out
to the families.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley said ATO members told him there was no organized event
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   He said members described Grantham, a transfer student, as ``an
enthusiastic, well-liked member of the fraternity. He seemed an
all-around good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   An Infiniti QX4 SUV and two other cars carrying Alpha Tau Omega
members were traveling west in south Oconee County around 11:45
p.m. when the accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The two cars allegedly left the accident scene before
authorities arrived, Berry said, and so did the driver of the
Infiniti.
</P>
<P>
   After it leaves Ga. 15, Elder Mill Road changes from pavement to
gravel, and the accident occurred at that transition, Berry said.
The driver of the Infiniti apparently lost control and hit a
sweetgum tree.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia State Patrol is reconstructing the crash, accounting
for time and movement, Berry said. He said the car apparently
flipped over and was so damaged it was difficult to determine
exactly what happened, other than ``it was a dramatic impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of alcohol was found in the SUV and at the scene, Berry
said. Blood alcohol tests on occupants of the SUV were sent to the
State Crime Lab for evaluation. Results were not back Monday, said
Allison Hodge of the Georgia State Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Although Berry said he didn't know how fast the SUV was going
when it wrecked, he was certain it was traveling along the
woods-lined road much faster than the posted speed limit of 25 mph.
The sheriff got to the scene about 20 minutes after the accident
and helped carry Grantham out of the ditch where he was lying, with
injuries to his head and chest. Grantham was transported to St.
Mary's Hospital in Athens, and died early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Dailey, 18, of Dalton, also had been ejected and was taken
to St. Mary's, where he remained in serious condition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the vehicle, Walter David Penn, 20, of Marietta,
wasn't at the scene but went to St. Mary's with injuries, Berry
said. Penn was listed in fair condition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said he saw two other passengers walking around,
apparently uninjured. He declined to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mullendore, UGA vice president for student affairs, said
the university's first priority is to work with the families of the
injured students and Grantham. He said there is much grieving on
campus, since five other students have died of various causes this
semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``We join the Grantham family and Ben's many friends in mourning
his loss,'' Adams said in a written statement. ``If we learn
anything in such a dark moment, it is that pranks and fun and
foolishness are not always harmless. From the perspective of the
university's student and organizational conduct codes, if there is
responsibility to be assigned and disciplinary action to be taken,
it will be done in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   ATO is ``your average, run-of-the-mill fraternity, no different
from many others,'' said UGA Assistant Police Chief Jimmy
Williamson. Its last run-in with the UGA Student Judiciary was in
the spring of 1995, when it was placed on social probation for a
quarter, after a female guest fell into a hole that had been dug
for a mud volleyball event.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Plott Brice
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
