<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-COMPUTE-NYT     04-03 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COMPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS RENEW CALLS TO BREAKUP MICROSOFT
</HEADLINE>
   (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF and MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Reinvigorated by Monday's ruling in the
Microsoft antitrust case, Microsoft Corp.'s competitors in Silicon
Valley on Monday renewed their calls for harsh ``structural''
sanctions that would lead to the break-up of the nation's largest
independent software company.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in the debate away from so-called conduct remedies,
which would have regulated or restricted Microsoft's market power
but would have left the company intact, came after negotiations
between the Justice Department, states attorneys general and
Microsoft fell apart on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to several people today, and others are feeling
this way,'' said James Barksdale, the former chief executive of
Netscape Communications Corp., who testified against Microsoft
during the antitrust trial last year. ``I testified for a
structural resolution at the trial, and I think the judge would be
disposed to it. In many ways it is the simplest solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling that more extreme remedies might now be likely was
mirrored Monday at Enterprise 2000, an Internet business conference
in Monterey, Calif., attended by several hundred Silicon Valley
venture capitalists and business executives.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to vote electronically on what remedies would be most
appropriate, 46 percent voted that Microsoft should be broken up,
while only 30 percent voted that the company should be fined $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our discussions we realized the conduct remedies are like
Swiss cheese,'' said Ed Black, president of the Computer &AMP;
Communication Industry Association. ``The uncertainty is off the
table, and the government has to put forth a credible remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of the Valley's leading executives and venture
capitalists led by Sun Microsystems Chairman Scott McNealy and
Oracle Corp. Chairman Larry Ellison are quietly orchestrating a
movement to develop a new set of structural remedies that would
break up Microsoft or simply spin off part of the company.
</P>
<P>
   McNealy, a public and bitter opponent of Microsoft, suggested
over the weekend that his company's legal battle with Microsoft
over the Java language might expand after Monday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in the seat of the CEO of Sun Microsystems,''
McNealy said. ``Every time we sign a deal, they go in behind us and
make an investment. It's beyond blatant. Cash is the most fungible
tool in a monopolist's arsenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Silicon Valley entrepreneurs and executives argue that
anything short of structural remedies would enable Microsoft to
forestall or litigate its way out of a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without structural remedies, it's hard to imagine Microsoft
isn't going to find a way to keep dodging the bullet,'' said Tim
O'Reilly, chief executive of O'Reilly &AMP; Associates, a publisher of
computer books.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, O'Reilly said he believed that the decision
comes when Microsoft is in a ``weaker position than they've ever
been'' because it faces real competition from Web-based businesses
that are providing consumers Internet-based alternatives to the
Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Other Microsoft rivals from the Valley said they were not
committed to any particular type of remedy but felt that the
company's competitive abuses must be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This establishes what everyone already knew,'' said Jerry
Fidler, chairman and co-founder of Wind River Systems Inc., a maker
of operating systems based in Alameda, Calif. ``Now we have an
opportunity to fix the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts have said that the language of the decision
could encourage potential litigants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just opens the door to a multitude of private lawsuits,''
said Jack Russo, an intellectual property lawyer in Palo Alto,
Calif. ``This litigation could end up looking a lot like the
tobacco industry, with a lot of lawyer time and a big legal process
for Microsoft to manage.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequently overlooked, however, among the strong anti-Microsoft
sentiments, is is that the software publisher still has many
friends and allies in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the I-hate-Bill club gets the government to do their heavy
lifting for them, they will come to regret it in the form of new
and objectionable regulations,'' said Alan Cooper, president of
Cooper Interaction Design, a software design firm based in Palo
Alto. ``Our federal government and our justice department doesn't
have an understanding of the digital universe and is
miscomprehending it. There actions will backfire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
