<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE04-COX     04-03 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore vows to close high-tech gap
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore talked in Atlanta on Monday
about getting technology into the hands of those who can't afford
it, then turned to fund-raising among those who can afford the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers and an Internet hookup are as vital to education in
this century as a blackboard and chalk were in the last
generation,'' Gore said to students and civil rights group members
at Morehouse College.
</P>
<P>
   For about 30 minutes in the King Chapel, the vice president
outlined plans to bring about ``truly revolutionary'' changes in
education. Most of his ideas involved high-tech changes. Gore said
the government has to lead the way in closing the so-called digital
divide _ the difference between the computer and technology access
of the haves and the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive Democratic nominee for president outlined his
plans for getting more computers into American homes and schools
and providing better training in future technology, especially
among low-income groups that are behind the technological wave.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed making the Internet accessible in every school and
library by the end of his first term to create technology centers
for students and adults in poor rural and urban communities.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed creating classes to ensure that all students
are computer-proficient by eighth grade, putting 75,000 new
teachers into schools nationwide, and starting a program for
tax-free college savings.
</P>
<P>
   But it was definitely the ``haves'' who spent the latter part of
the evening with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After the hourlong forum, Gore was the highlight of a Democratic
National Committee fund-raiser at an Atlanta home, where the going
rate for entry was $100,000 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   The event, at the home of oncologist Larry Cooper, was expected
to raise just under $2 million for the DNC, with about 7.5 percent
of that going to the Georgia Democratic Party to aid in local and
state level races. By contrast, a DNC fund-raiser featuring
President Clinton last fall was just $5,000 per couple.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's quick fly-in _ Gore departed later in the evening for
Philadelphia _ was his first visit since the vice president swept
Georgia's March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of most of Georgia's Democratic leaders, Gore
carried 84 percent of the state vote against an almost nonexistent
campaign by former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials hailed the visit as an indication
that Georgia, overshadowed amid 15 other primaries and caucuses in
March, will play a more important roll in the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a lot more visits between now and
November,'' said David Worley, Georgia Democratic Party chairman.
``We have every expectation that Georgia will be a targeted state
in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
