<HEADER>
A6167 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-PIRATES-BOY-HNS &LR;      04-03 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRATES-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN SHOT BY PIRATES RECOVERING IN DALLAS HOSPITAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It is a story that seems out of place in the
Information age: A Dutch family sailing the globe is attacked by
pirates off the coast of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is because of technology that all members of the van
Tuijl family were able to share the details of their harrowing
ordeal at a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The family spoke at the Children's Medical Center in Dallas
where 13-year-old Willem van Tuijl is recovering from a gunshot
wound that left him paralyzed from the waist down.
</P>
<P>
   The van Tuijls were saved by ham radio operators who put them in
touch with a Miami doctor who talked them through the medical care
of their son. The amateur operators also steered the family to
Children's Medical Center, which sent a Lear jet to Honduras to
pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had not been for them, he probably would have died,''
Jannie van Tuijl said.
</P>
<P>
   The saga began more than a week ago when the van Tuijls, who
have been sailing around the world since 1995, anchored their
steel, 44-foot sailboat near Half Moon Reef in the Atlantic Ocean
about 50 miles from Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Jacco van Trujl and his son launched an inflatable dinghy to
visit another sailboat anchored nearby and to fish the reef a few
hundred yards from their yacht.
</P>
<P>
   While they were gone, Jannie van Tuijl said an open wooden boat
similar to the kind used by Honduran fishermen pulled alongside
their yacht. Four men pulled out AK-47 assault rifles and boarded.
</P>
<P>
   They demanded nothing but ``papers,'' she said. She pretended
not to understand Spanish. Recognizing that something was wrong,
Jacco van Tuijl turned the dinghy toward the yacht.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started screaming, `Please go back, go back,' '' she said.
``He turned the boat and they were already shooting.``
</P>
<P>
   At first, she said, the men fired into the air. Then she saw her
son lurch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Willem collapse in slow motion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet entered his right side, ripped through a kidney,
intestines and spine and exited through his left kidney,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The same bullet punctured and deflated the dinghy, tossing
father and son into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel my legs anymore,'' the boy told his father.
</P>
<P>
   While Willem clung to him, Jacco van Tuijl swam to the yacht,
where his wife had already sent out a distress call.
</P>
<P>
   For five hours, the mother pressed her hand against her son's
wounds in an attempt to stop the bleeding. He was remarkably calm,
she said. He never cried and kept assuring her that ``everything
will be all right.``
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Willem said, ``I'm so happy that they shot me,
Mom.``
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you say that?'' she asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if they had shot one of you, I would have died from
sadness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly 20 hours for help to arrive and take the boy to a
hospital in Honduras. During that time, the parents were in
constant contact with Dr. Jim Hirschman, a Miami doctor and ham
radio operator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid he was going to die any minute,'' Hirschman told
The Associated Press. ``It grieved me that we had so many hours to
go and no way to relieve the boys suffering.``
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a wheelchair in his hospital room Monday, Willem said
the pain was not great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just BOOM and my legs were feeling like they're not
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The van Tuijls said they have had no communication with Honduran
authorities and have know idea who the assailants were or what
motivated the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might have wanted to steal the boat for drug transport
but not kill us yet,'' Jacco van Tuijl speculated. ``They would
have needed us to get the boat where they wanted it. That's just a
theory. What they exactly wanted, we don't know.``
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the family has logged more than 40,000 miles at sea,
van Tuijl said, and had planned to make the boat their permanent
home. Now, they may return to the Netherlands and settle on land.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that he will never walk again, Willem said, ``I would like
to have as close as possible to an ordinary life ... have fun ...
be with my family.``
</P>
<P>
   He was listed in fair condition, but a hospital spokeswoman said
he will be at Children's for an indefinite stay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
