<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-UMPIRES04-COX     04-03 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner Field looks at `AL' strike zone
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Monday delivered him to a new dressing room in a new
park in a new league, and yet when the new guy took the field, who
knew?
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the major leagues was the game's new umpiring
arrangement more evident than at Turner Field, where 17-year
American League umpire John Hirschbeck, president of the new World
Umpires Association, worked the plate in his first NL game. And
before anyone takes issue with the eight called strikeouts between
two of the freer-swinging teams in the game, the ump has a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' he said, ``it gives you something to write about.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually not. Atlanta's first experience with the game's new
interleague umpiring crews passed without major incident.
Hirschbeck and AL rookie ump Jim Reynolds joined NL veterans
Charlie Williams and Mark Wegner for the Braves' opening series,
just as mixed crews worked every park.
</P>
<P>
   Of 17 crews, nine this season are split 2-2 between AL and NL
umpires while the other eight have one league-crosser. They wore
generic MLB patches on their caps and right sleeves (the official
new uniforms debut in a few months), and if the strike zone did not
seem as generic, Hirschbeck has this thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys have a tighter strike zone, but if the ball is over
the plate at the right height, that's a strike no matter who you
are,'' he said. ``You're talking about a half-inch outside, a half
on the inside. Up and down, the same thing. Some guys are a little
tighter. They want that ball, in their minds, to be right on the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other guys say that if it nicks the corner, that's good enough
for me. That's the only difference in the strike zone. It's really
not an American- National League thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with Javy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be good,'' the Braves catcher said. ``I like
it because people complain too much about our pitchers' location.
The American League umpires, that doesn't bother them.''
</P>
<P>
   The new union is working under a one-year agreement reached 11
days ago after it was determined a more comprehensive agreement
couldn't be completed in time. In theory, there are still AL and NL
umpires, but the distinction will vanish once the new contract is
settled.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under one umbrella is good, but the way the game is played is
different,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``I've been
in both leagues; it's a different style of game. I don't think they
have to make all the umpires the same.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not, or not officially. Unlike last year, clubs will not
evaluate plate umpiring nightly for an MLB survery. While Sandy
Alderson, MLB's director of operations, says the high strike could
be called more regularly, the commissioner's office issued no
strike zone directive this spring, as it did in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mixing of crews, after the growing pains take
place, will be a benefit,'' Braves GM John Schuerholz said. ``They
will be able to reduce the travel. It just makes a lot more sense
for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I also believe that whatever the disparity about the
differences in the two leagues with regards to the strike zone
especially, either from a reality standpoint or from an imagination
standpoint, will be diminished and then eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
