<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GRAD-STUDENTS-UNION-N     04-03 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAD-STUDENTS-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NLRB ALLOWS GRADUATE STUDENTS AT NYU TO UNIONIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a ruling that some say could alter the
relationship between graduate students and their professors at
private colleges and universities across the United States, a
regional director for the National Labor Relations Board ruled
Monday that graduate students who work as teaching and research
assistants at New York University may organize a union.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, by Daniel Silverman, the board's regional director
for the New York region, is the first to allow graduate student
employees at a private university to unionize. Public universities
are subject to state labor laws, and graduate students at many
campuses _ including the State University of New York, the City
University of New York and the University of California _ already
belong to unions.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision, which covers 1,700 of NYU's 17,000 graduate
students, clears the way for them to vote on whether to join the
United Auto Workers. If a union is approved, the students will be
able to negotiate wages, benefits and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But NYU, which, like most universities, relies significantly on
graduate student labor, could appeal the decision to the labor
board in Washington. University officials said Monday that they
were ``disappointed'' by the decision and would discuss whether to
appeal with the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling may raise real problems for the way in which
graduate education can proceed,'' said Robert Berne, the vice
president for academic development. ``To me, it is a chilling
message that faculty members may not be able to talk to their
graduate assistants about their assistanceships without going
through a union representative,'' he added. ``If that is the case,
it can't help but detract from the significant relationship that
faculty members develop with their graduate assistants.''
</P>
<P>
   Graduate students and union officials, however, called such
comments scare tactics and applauded the decision. ``It is very
clear to me that what we do here is work, and like any other
workers, we should be able to take an active role in setting our
working conditions,'' said Kimberly Johnson, a fifth-year graduate
student in American Studies who helped organize the union campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has helped teach introductory courses in
metropolitan studies and in women's studies, said that her
responsibilities varied greatly from semester to semester, and
included everything from teaching and grading papers to writing a
newsletter, buying books and photocopying materials.
</P>
<P>
   And Lisa Jessup, the UAW organizer who ran the campaign, said
she believes that the decision ``really opens the door for graduate
employees at all private universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the graduate students still must vote, Jessup and
Johnson both expressed confidence that they would win. If the
university appeals, Silverman, the NLRB regional director, said
that the labor relations board could postpone the election until it
rules or let the election proceed, then either count the ballots or
temporarily impound them.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges and universities rely extensively on graduate
students to carry a significant share of undergraduate teaching;
typically, graduate students lead discussion sessions in large
lecture courses, grade papers and tests, and sometimes run actual
courses. They also help conduct research and assist in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, the terms governing their work, like most
other matters within academia, were largely determined by
university officials. Those terms vary from campus to campus, but
often involve a tuition subsidy additional stipend that account for
a large part of graduate student financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   In decisions more than 20 years ago, the NLRB said that although
graduate students earned money by teaching and conducting research,
those activities represented a small portion of their role as
graduate students. Unionization would intrude on the academic
process, the board said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the ruling Monday, Silverman wrote that while NYU said
the graduate teaching program was run for the benefit of the
graduate students, it was clear that the teaching assistants ``play
a large role in the undergraduate experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,700 graduate students employed as teaching, research or
other assistants, about half are in the Faculty of Arts and
Sciences. The Stern School of Business, the School of Education and
the Tisch School of the Arts also employ large numbers. Some
departments require service as a teaching assistant for all of
their doctoral students.
</P>
<P>
   While graduate students talk about higher wages and health care
benefits, university officials say they are most concerned about
the bargaining impinging on academic considerations, like class
sizes or what to teach. ``It is almost impossible to draw the line
between what we consider academic issues and what they consider
work issues,'' Berne said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Yale University, where graduate students have
attempted to organize for several years, also voiced dismay about
the decision. ``If left standing,'' said Richard C. Levin, Yale's
president, in a statement, ``it could bring national labor policy
into conflict with a national educational policy that has for
decades promoted the international leadership of America's graduate
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But John J. Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, called the
decision part of a national trend ``among student employees seeking
respect and dignity on the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
