A6177 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-QUOTE-OF-THE-DAY-NYT     04-03 0063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUOTE-OF-THE-DAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUOTATION OF THE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This quotation refers to BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT, which
moved in ``f'' news file.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The court concludes that Microsoft maintained its monopoly
power by anticompetitive means and attempted to monopolize the Web
browser market.''
</P>
<P>
   _JUDGE THOMAS PENFIELD JACKSON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0549 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6179 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-LEGAL-2NDTA     04-03 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-LEGAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: 20th century.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The judge concluded, for instance, that Microsoft maintained its
monopoly power over operating software through anti-competitive
means, ruthlessly striving over a four-year period to crush any
potential threat to its domination over operating system software.
He also found that the company tried to monopolize the market for
Internet browsers in violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, Microsoft mounted a deliberate assault upon
entrepreneurial efforts that, left to rise or fall on their own
merits, could well have enabled the introduction of competition
into the market for Intel-compatible PC operating systems,'' the
judge wrote. ``While the evidence does not prove that they would
have succeeded absent Microsoft's actions, it does reveal that
Microsoft placed an oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive
fortune, thereby effectively guaranteeing its continued dominance
in the relevant market. More broadly, Microsoft's anti-competitive
actions trammeled the competitive process through which the
computer software industry generally stimulates innovation and
conduces to the optimum benefit of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Handing a small bone to Microsoft, Jackson dismissed the
government's claims that the company's marketing arrangements with
other companies like Compaq and Apple Computer had violated Section
1 of the Act.
</P>
<P>
   But on a fourth major issue, one on which an appeals court had
previously reversed him and ruled in Microsoft's favor, the judge
was unyielding even to his superiors. Instead, he took the highly
unusual position for a lower court judge of both criticizing and
dismissing the appellate court decision.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals decision, issued a month after the current case was
filed, is one of Microsoft's strongest legal defenses. When it was
handed down, it forced the government to broadly expand the case.
The appeals judges lifted an injunction imposed by Jackson after
they found that Microsoft had not violated the Sherman Act by
bundling its Windows operating system with its Internet Explorer
software.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also set a high standard for the government to
make a successful case under Section 1 of the Sherman Act. It said
that Microsoft should be free to blend its Web browser into Windows
as long as it could make a ``plausible claim'' of business
efficiency or consumer benefit from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson Monday called the appeals opinion ``inconsistent
with the pertinent Supreme Court precedents'' and ``not formally
binding.'' Using one of the law's cruelest Latin cuts, he called
the appeals court's reasoning ``obiter dicta,'' or surplus language
peripheral to a decision and therefore of no legal consequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read literally, the D.C. Circuit's opinion appears to immunize
any product design (or, at least, software product design) from
antitrust scrutiny, irrespective of its effect upon competition, if
the software developer can postulate any `plausible claim' of
advantage to its arrangement of code,'' Jackson wrote. ``This
undemanding test appears to this court to be inconsistent with the
pertinent Supreme Court precedents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
