<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES04-     04-03 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Cat's back, back, back
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Using Opening Day as his stage, Andres Galarraga took
all of three at-bats to give Braves fans an idea of how his return
from a yearlong bout with lymphoma was going.
</P>
<P>
   As in going, going gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Comeback Cat hit a home run off Pedro Astacio in the seventh
inning and made the defensive play that was the difference,
smothering an Astacio shot up the line to save at least two runs
and carry the Braves to a 2-0 victory against the Colorado Rockies
in front of 42,255 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   That and Greg Maddux made the Braves winners on Opening Day for
the seventh time in the past nine years. Maddux, who handed the
shutout over to Mike Remlinger two outs into the eighth inning, was
happy to concede the day to the ``Big Cat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was cool,'' Maddux said. ``You want to stand up and start
clapping, too. The road he had to go through to get back, and to do
that? The game-winning RBI, save two, three runs with his glove.
Plus he's one of the guys you root for. It's great to see, it
really was.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga ended a defensive standoff in which outstanding plays
were swapped. Diving catch by Andruw Jones. Running catch by
Colorado's Tom Goodwin. Bare-handed play on an infield chop by Jeff
Cirillo. Over-the-shoulder catch by the Braves' Reggie Sanders.
Then Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   He rescued Maddux from a bases-loaded jam with his stellar grab
to take a hit away from Astacio, who'd driven a Maddux pitch down
the line with two out in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the bat back in his hands in the bottom of the seventh,
Galarraga, who'd been hit by a pitch and struck out, sent a 1-0 low
fastball from Astacio high into an orbit that ended in the
left-center-field seats for his first home run since Sept. 23,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   He also gave Andruw Jones some ideas. Jones took an Astacio
pitch over the left-field fence two pitches later to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of things happen to me great in my career, but
today is something special,'' Galarraga said. ``It's like a movie.
Believe me, I don't have the words to say how happy I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga had been getting the Braves' attention since his first
day of camp, but even those who saw him hit .347 with three home
runs this spring were overwhelmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable how things work out, almost like magic,''
manager Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   The day was magical all around for the Braves. They got the game
in despite threatening weather. They eased some bullpen worries
while John Rocker is unavailable by sending out Remlinger, who got
four outs for the save.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was that one. One Galarraga home run and
counting.
</P>
<P>
   As shortstop Walt Weiss put it, ``The story just keeps getting
better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
