<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIACCHETTO-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY ADVISER TO THE STARS FACES CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As recently as a year ago, Dana C. Giacchetto was an
investment adviser to the stars, counting actors, rock bands and
artists among his clients. He moved in a world of high-powered
entertainment deals, and his boyish face stared from the pages of
national magazines.
</P>
<P>
   But his small investment company began losing a string of
clients during the winter, and in March federal agents searched his
home and office. Monday, federal prosecutors in Manhattan charged
that Giacchetto, 37, looted more than $6 million from clients and
lied to securities investigators about financial problems at his
company, the Cassandra Group.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors would not identify which clients lost
money, Giacchetto, who was charged with stock fraud, has listed
Matt Damon, Ben Stiller and the rock group Phish among his
clientele, according to records filed in court. Giacchetto's
company managed more than $100 million for 305 clients in 1999,
according to records filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Monday, a federal judge granted a request by securities
officials to freeze his company's assets.
</P>
<P>
   SEC lawyers said Giacchetto billed himself as a safe and
conservative money manager to appeal to artists and entertainers
who had considerable wealth but lacked financial sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   The company's brochures said the Cassandra Group never had
direct custody of its clients' money, and therefore ``assures the
client security of his or her account.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company deposited the money with a separate
company.
</P>
<P>
   Giacchetto was allowed to make stock trades with the money, but
he was never supposed to take custody of the money.
</P>
<P>
   But Giacchetto did not abide by the terms of the bargain,
federal prosecutors from the Southern District of New York said.
</P>
<P>
   They said from 1997 until March 20, 2000, Giacchetto improperly
transferred $20 million from his clients' bank accounts into his
company's accounts. Once it was there, prosecutors charged,
Giacchetto took about $6 million in various ways. He used some of
the money to pay Cassandra's business expenses, and other money to
pay his bills, including travel, dining and rent at his Manhattan
loft, the prosecutors said. Other money was used to repay clients
whose money had previously been taken, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Giacchetto, who did not appear in court, was out of the country
Monday and was expected to return Tuesday, his lawyer, Andrew J.
Levander, said.
</P>
<P>
   Levander would not comment on the criminal case, saying he has
not had a chance to speak with his client or fully read the
documents. If convicted on all charges, Giacchetto would face up to
10 years in federal prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0552 </DOCNO>
