<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-COURSE04-     04-03 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-COURSE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evolution: Augusta adapts to high-tech game
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Augusta National has undergone several face-lifts
during its history, but recent changes have some of the top players
grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tiger Woods' runaway victory in 1997, officials have
lengthened several holes, planted, replanted and moved trees,
enlarged and changed the contours of the greens and added rough.
</P>
<P>
   Hootie Johnson, chairman of the Masters tournament, explained
that change always has been a constant at Augusta National. But the
purists complain that officials are beginning to distance
themselves from the philosophy of course co-creators Bobby Jones
and Alister Mackenzie that simplicity can offer a stern test in
golf.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jack Nicklaus, a six-time Masters champion, said he thinks
officials crossed the line in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like what they've done to the golf course at all,''
said Nicklaus, who missed last year's tournament while recovering
from hip replacement surgery. ``They've taken a golf course that
played for years a certain way and now they've eliminated that. I
was in favor of them putting in light rough, but I didn't realize
they did what they did. It looks like somebody who doesn't play
golf or understand the game did it. And I've never said that about
Augusta before.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe Woods' runaway victory in '97 _ and the fact that
he was hitting short irons into par-5s _ led to the changes. Others
blame golf's new technology, which continues to allow pro golfers
to get greater distance, thus threatening to make older and shorter
courses obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new equipment has something to do with them changing the
course,'' John Huston said. ``There are all kinds of clubs that add
length off the tee and clubs that get greater flight and all kinds
of stuff. They're changing with the equipment, so you don't know
when it might stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III understands the dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Augusta ... they have maximized their length almost as much
as they can,'' he said. ``If the greens are fairly soft, if they
get a little bit of rain, guys are going to shoot it up, and they
have to do everything they can to keep that from happening. The
15th green gets higher every year and and 13 gets longer. They do
whatever they can to keep scores low.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nos. 10 and 16 greens have been rebuilt for agronomic reasons
and to reduce the encroachment of Bermuda grass. At the 10th green,
new pin positions were established by expanding the green left
front and right rear.
</P>
<P>
   _ On No. 16, the right front and right rear of the green has
been softened and the left front has been expanded. The changes
open the way for possible new pin positions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nos. 12 and 13 greens have been re-grassed, and the lost edges
were recovered by encroachment, making new pin placements.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the right side of the 14th fairway, as part of a
reforestation program, four trees have been planted. The addition
puts a premium on accuracy off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   _ On No. 17, two trees were removed on the right fairway, at
approximately 175 and 255 yards. Three trees were added between
Nos. 15 and 17 on the fairway beyond the Eisenhower Tree. The tee
has been moved up 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``After careful consideration and after consulting several
players and our golf course architect, we made additional
modifications to No. 17,'' Johnson said. ``The changes at No. 17
will continue to place a premium on accuracy off the tee. Overall,
we were satisfied with the hole last year, but we think this will
be a further improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jury is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised at all the changes, just because of the history
there,'' David Toms said. ``All the people who have gone around
that golf course ... being able to compare them to what's going on
now with the current players can't really be done. So, it's
unfortunate. The rough they've added makes a difference. They're
trying to make it harder to play. But it's still a great
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price has no problem with the changes. He thinks Augusta
National needs to keep pace with enhanced technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy they are doing that,'' Price said. ``There are
changes that needed to be done there over the years. It's nice to
see them do that, to make the course play longer and harder. The
players today, with the way equipment has advanced, can hit the
ball a long way. In the end, as talented as the players are, it
sounds as if they prefer more of a challenge than not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the course) needed some sort of defense as the game
has progressed, but I think they have gone about it the right
way,'' Lee Westwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer joked that the continued growth of the course
prompted him to reach out to Augusta officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have written a note to the powers at Augusta and said that
since I am now a member, I'd like to play the members tees,''
Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, but his point was well-taken.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
