<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBILITY OF DISRUPTION BY SMALL GROUP OF CUBAN EXILES GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Cuban-Boy-Opposition; a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Elian Gonzalez's father, kept from his young son for
more than four months, received approval from the US government
Monday to come to the United States and take at least temporary
custody of the boy, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But details over when and where relatives who have been caring
for the boy will hand him over must still be worked out. The issue
is an incendiary one. With hundreds, perhaps thousands, of Cuban
exiles vowing to stop the child from being returned to his
homeland, federal authorities want to avoid a confrontation at the
home of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, in Miami's Little
Havan, where Elian has been staying.
</P>
<P>
   Miami residents from all walks of life worry that might be
impossible, regardless of where the exchange takes place. As word
filtered back that visas had been granted to a delegation from Cuba
and arrangements for Elian's care had been made, the crowd of
ardent anti-Castro exiles who gather daily outside the modest gray
house promptly linked arms and began practicing civil disobedience
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get what we want accomplished; we have to,' said Marta
Valdez, a retiree who emigrated from Cuba 30 years ago and was at
the house of Elian's great uncle for the first time Monday. ``We
have to help this boy. We'll figure out some way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, many of the demonstrators have vowed to avoid
violence and, instead, disrupt the city with sit-ins and marches.
Their numbers, in fact, are relatively small _ 5,000 or so hardcore
exiles who can be counted on to demonstrate whenever a Cuban band
performs in Miami or confront politicians who do not speak to their
liking, according to local observers.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pittance a city with some 800,000 Cuban or
Cuban-American residents. But it's a loud constituency that is
unaccustomed to losing, and some Miamians, Cubans among them, fear
that ugliness is inevitable if federal officials try to return
Elian to his father in Cuba, as the US Immigration and
Naturalization Service has ordered. A federal judge upheld that
order, a ruling that Elian's Miami relatives are now appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a situation that's going to be resolved easily or
maybe even peacefully,'' said James Kane, chief pollster for the
Florida Voter Poll, which has found that most people in the state
support the government's position. ``All of us are saying, 'What if
federal marshals have to go in and take the boy?' The Cuban
community is going to lose whatever composure it has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about a little boy,'' he added. ``This is about a
man, (Cuban leader Fidel) Castro, and our relationship with Cuba.
Elian is just a symbol.''
</P>
<P>
   As a symbol or as a sad little boy who was found alone clinging
to an inner tube on Thanksgiving Day after his mother drowned with
others en route to Florida and freedom, Elian has won the hearts of
almost everyone here.
</P>
<P>
   But while a Miami Herald poll showed that only 5 percent of
Cubans say Elian should be sent home, questions concerning his
future have gripped only a tiny segment of the Cuban exile
population, with many, expecially younger Cubans or Cuban-Americans
born in the United States, more concerned with their careers or
mortgage payments than protesting his plight. Immigrants from other
Caribbean countries sound almost fed up with the attention being
paid the boy and the possibility of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because they're not getting their way doesn't mean they
can break the law or stop traffic or other stuff,'' said Edgar
Perdomo, a half-Puerto Rican, half-Dominican hotel maintenance
worker. ``It's not right. It's unfair, really unfair, that no other
group gets the same breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Martha Compos, a Nicaraguan restaurant hostess who has
been waiting 13 years for permanent residency, ``Oh yeah, big time
they're used to getting what they want. It should be the same for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cubans get what they want like that,'' she added, snapping her
fingers and noting that she does not know why her paperwork has yet
to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
apparently imminent, negotiations between lawyers for the relatives
and the federal government are scheduled to resume Tuesday. The
marathon session Monday resulted in several developments, among
them the ``temporary care'' arrangement placing Elian with his
father in exchange for a promise by Gonzalez to remain in Miami
during the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Six visas were granted, to Gonzalez, his second wife, their baby
son, a young cousin of Elian's, one of his kindergarten teachers
and a pediatrician -- just six of the more than 28 visas sought by
Cubans in Havana. Elian's father and his family would stay at the
home of Cuba's chief diplomat in Washington, Fernando Remirez, who
lives in an upscale suburban Maryland neighborhood. Remirez, his
wife and two children will vacate the house to make room for the
visitors from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The other visas are for Elian's classmates and for National
Assembly President Rafael Alarcon, a top aide to Cuban President
Fidel Castro; those applications are still being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting the number of visas granted could help soothe tempers
in the middle-class neighborhood where Elian has been living with
his relatives, specialists in Cuban-American politics said,
particularly if his father is the one to take Elian from the house.
Still, the scenario that everyone agrees would be easiest and
safest would be a transfer at a neutral location, one away from the
knots of people now stationed outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is not going to burn down,'' said Max Castro, a
political science professor at the University of Miami. ``There
aren't going to be more than a few dozen arrests at most. Maybe the
port or airport will be closed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the strategy of the family has been very disturbing,'' he
added. ``They've been saying they won't do anything to facilitate
the transfer but you're going to have to come through this crowd.
It's a very cynical position.''
</P>
<P>
   But outside the great uncle's house, where a woman handed out
turquoise-blue plastic rosaries and an early afternoon crowd of
perhaps 50 people prayed for the boy whose arrival some have
compared to the birth of the baby Jesus, mortgage banker Henry
Someillan insisted Elian should stay in the United States and that
his father should instead move to Miami. His own father, he said,
went to prison fighting for a democratic future for Cuba. A lot of
fathers did. And their sons, raised without them, turned into fine
men, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Someillan said he was willing to go only so far to fight
for his own beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuban society has never demonstrated violence in this
country,'' he said. ``We'll form human chains. We'll make things
difficult. I'll go as far as I'm allowed to go so that I don't get
hurt and no one else gets hurt. ``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
