<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A LEFT-HANDED COMPLEMENT AT DH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Who said the Yankees didn't have a left-handed
designated hitter? As long as Bernie Williams' throwing shoulder
hurts, they've got the best one they've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dull ache, but it doesn't hurt when I swing,'' Williams said
in a clubhouse charged with the anticipation of a new season,
another one promising to last well into October, no matter what
those Grapefruit League standings said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Yankees survived another Darryl Strawberry walk on
the wild side, and Ed Yarnall's lack of control and a few Florida
afternoons when George Steinbrenner was about to burst. That's what
spring training is for, working out the kinks, weeding out the
kooks and getting your serious lineup together and intentions in
order just in time for opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of serious and well-intentioned, here's Williams on the
eve of the Yankees' 2000 debut Monday night _ on American soil but
past everyone's bedtime back East, and how come Mark McGwire
doesn't sound off about that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we want to win more than anybody else,'' said
Williams, before Orlando Hernandez, who starts everything now for
the Yankees, took the ball against the Angels at Edison Field.
``It's what we're playing for, the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds hokey in the context of the standard sports
cynicism, then go explain the amazing century not long ago
concluded with the Yankees' third World Series title in four years,
the last two in four-game sweeps, for a 20th- century grand total
of 25, or the most glorious .250 batting average there will ever
be.
</P>
<P>
   Explain Bernie Williams entering a 10th season in a Yankee
uniform and a 15th year at work for one organization, which is so
much against the odds of modern sports economics that Williams'
face must be on a dartboard somewhere in Marvin Miller's basement.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's an old story how Williams was so close to signing with
the Red Sox in November 1999 that he could smell the Fenway Park
sausage. The point is, he didn't, because Steinbrenner coughed up
$87.5 million (over seven years), and Williams weighed a few extra
Boston millions against center field in Yankee Stadium and all that
interlocking history stitched into his cap and shirt.
</P>
<P>
   New York being New York, Williams heard that although he was a
wonderful guy and that old softie Steinbrenner had made the
sentimental decision, maybe Albert Belle would have been a better
idea, given Williams' annual visits to the disabled list and his
tendencies to drift in and out of a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   Then the verdict came in, and the contemporary notion that
long-term security is the death of motivation, especially for a
player like laid-back Bernie, had been debunked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the fact that I played 158 games, despite the
fact that my left shoulder was killing me in the second half of the
season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He more than played; he produced. Career highs in hits (202) and
runs batted in (115) and runs scored (116). Yes, there were times
in the early months last season when Williams seemed to be on
cruise control, but, as Manager Joe Torre said, ``He's one of those
guys who's struggling, and you look up and he's hitting .330.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Williams hit .342, another career-best. And if
there was one moment last season when the Yankees were getting the
look of just another common contender, it was in September, in
Toronto, until Williams' grand slam snapped them from a state of
hypnosis, with orders to finish the century the way champion
Yankees should.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our superstar on a team that supposedly doesn't have
superstars,'' David Cone said. ``Derek Jeter is the de facto
captain, the guy we look to as a leader. But Bernie is the guy who
can really carry us, with those power numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Williams not only played down Cone's assertion that
he is the difference between very good and great, but almost looked
baffled by it, before deferring to his elders, like Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 37 and he's got 6 percent body fat,'' Williams said.
``Being around guys like Paul motivates me.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it was easy for people to take their cue from
Williams and dwell on other vital issues in Florida. The DH. The
fifth starter. The backup infielder. But spring training ended,
mercifully, and the Yankees did have a better record than the Red
Sox, so how bad was it?
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza will cover the No. 5 spot until Steinbrenner's
baseball people figure out a permanent solution. And as for the DH,
that's where Williams started Sunday night _ with Ricky Ledee
starting in center field _ and is likely to remain for a while.
</P>
<P>
   What would he do with the extra time between at-bats? Hit off
the tee, he said. Watch video. Soft toss. Cheerlead. All those
exciting pastimes that come so naturally for a star who hides in
the clubhouse, strumming his guitar. And then you look up, and he's
hitting .342. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
