<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BIZ-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE A STRICKEN LEADER, JAPAN MAINTAINS ITS COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The reaction to news that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
was in the hospital was testament to the Japanese determination to
maintain the ``wa,'' the social harmony that this country so
greatly prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Obuchi lay in the hospital in serious condition,
various economic developments caused the stock market to roar ahead
to its highest level in three years. The benchmark Nikkei 225 stock
index rose 1.9 percent to close on Monday at 20,726.99, and
companies continued to churn out news releases outlining their
plans for alliances, investments and new products.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was no panic when the market opened Tuesday, as
investors seemed ready to continue their recent strategy of
shifting money out of stocks tied to the ``new economy'' and into
some of the lumbering giants that, by some measures, are
undervalued. At midmorning, the Nikkei had given up almost half of
Monday's gains, but that was attributed to the fall in the Nasdaq
market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That was in stark contrast to the gyrations that roiled the
stock market in America when there was even a remote possibility
that President Clinton might be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general view of the business world is that if the
political vacuum is short, the influence on the economy will be
limited,'' said Yotaro Kobayashi, chairman of the Fuji Xerox Corp.
and leader of the Japan Association of Corporate Executives, one of
the four large business lobbies here.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the government was careful to keep news that Obuchi
was hooked up to a respirator to itself until well after trading
stopped on Monday, making sure that investors focused on the good
news emanating from the currency market and from a survey of
business confidence released on Monday rather than on the prime
minister's illness.
</P>
<P>
   He had not designated a successor before his stroke, which
occurred in the wee hours of Sunday morning, and that lapse also
contributed to the delay in announcing the severity of his medical
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a very cautious calculation made by the
party bosses in the Liberal Democratic Party not to disclose
everything at once,'' said Shigenori Okazaki, an analyst at Warburg
Dillon Read in Tokyo, referring to the governing party. ``Instead,
they released the news gradually, and the shock was mitigated.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no sign of panic in the markets Tuesday morning,
either. The party already seems to be lining up Yoshiro Mori as
Obuchi's successor. A colorless party loyalist, Mori is unlikely to
change the policies Obuchi pursued. Japan changes its prime
ministers almost as often as Italy does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common wisdom among Japanese and foreign investors I
talked to yesterday was that his replacement is unlikely to hammer
out a different policy course,'' said Kathy Matsui, chief
strategist at Goldman, Sachs (Japan) Ltd. ``The post tends to
change hands rather often here without any serious consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The normal ebb and flow of funds has also helped to cushion the
market. Many companies and banks, which typically have an
investment portfolio, tend to have hoarded cash prior to the close
of the fiscal year on March 31, in an effort to improve the look of
their balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   They traditionally open the fiscal year by redeploying that cash
in the stock and bond markets. The quarterly survey of business
confidence, or Tankan, which was released Monday, showed business
confidence rising for the fifth consecutive quarter, another sign
that corporate investment is picking up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope both the ruling party and the opposition parties will
work to make the political situation stable so we can quickly take
measures to compile a domestic and foreign agenda for the country
as quickly as possible,'' said Hiroshi Okuda, chairman of the
Toyota Motor Corp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
