<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6194 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-WAKEFIELD-     04-03 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WAKEFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY WAKEFIELD MAY SEEK TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Red Sox pitcher Tim Wakefield, angered at being sent
to the bullpen, plans to meet Friday in Anaheim, Calif., with his
agents, Bill Moore and Dick Moss, and is expected to ask the Sox to
be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Sox signed lefthander Pete Schourek over the weekend,
Wakefield was scheduled to pitch Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't told me this yet, but at some point, if this doesn't
change, he'll probably ask to be traded,'' Moore said from his
office in Arizona Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While Nomar Garciaparra was standing on one side of the Red Sox
clubhouse Monday, commenting on the absence of a spring controversy
for the first time since he joined the club, Wakefield was seething
on the other side, furious at being told he was going back to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing personal against Pete,'' Wakefield said, ``but why is
it always me that's the sacrificial lamb?''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield emerged from a meeting with manager Jimy Williams and
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, walked to his locker and immediately
turned to face reporters, anxious to say his piece publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of last season I wasn't on the playoff roster,''
said Wakefield, alluding to being dropped before the ALCS. ``I came
to spring training, and I was slated to be the No. 4 starter. I
felt I was needed and wanted, and now this happens. They're hot and
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who said he volunteered to pitch in relief last June
when Tom Gordon went on the disabled list for the second time, has
more reason than usual to be anxious about how he is used. The
33-year-old knuckleballer is in the last year of a three-year
contract paying him $4.5 million this season, and after approaching
him last summer about picking up the $5 million option they hold on
him for next season, the Sox broke off talks.
</P>
<P>
   The sides met again in spring training about three weeks ago,
but talks broke off again last week, just a few days before
Wakefield was informed he was going back to the bullpen. General
manager Dan Duquette told Wakefield's representatives that they
would talk again after the season, when Wakefield is eligible to be
a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield hesitated when asked if he would request a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, as he did Sunday, insisted Wakefield was needed in the
bullpen because of injuries to Juan Pena (out for the year after
tearing the ulnar collateral ligament in his elbow) and Rod Beck
(on the DL with an irritated nerve root in his neck).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my versatility is being abused but that's my
opinion,'' Wakefield said. ``I've had teammates come to me and say
they feel like I'm being screwed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we're better with me as a starter. I'm averaging 13
wins as a starter, and I eat up a lot of innings. It's hard to
swallow right now, but I won't disrespect any of my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield's bargaining position for a new contract next season
is greatly weakened, of course, if he's not in the rotation. He was
not effective in spring training, going 1-1 with a 10.80 ERA, but
he claimed that he had better command of his knuckler than he did
last season, and publicly, both Williams and Kerrigan pronounced
themselves satisfied with his effort.
</P>
<P>
   It's still quite conceivable that when Beck returns, Wakefield
will be restored to the rotation and Schourek will displace
Fassero. Fassero, scheduled to pitch the third game of the series
against the Mariners here, was 0-1 with a 7.48 ERA in six
appearances this spring. In light of his 5-14 record and 7.20 ERA
last season, his spring numbers don't allay concerns that he is a
weak link in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect him to be (upset),'' Williams said of
Wakefield. ``That's good from my standpoint. It's good that he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make the decision. This is the best decision for our
team to start the season. We haven't played a game yet. We have to
start somewhere. Maybe there's a reason the decision had to be
made. We don't have a lot of options in Triple A.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams hinted that, given time, Wakefield may feel differently
about the decision. Williams brought up 1997 and his first
controversy as Sox manager, when he moved incumbent shortstop John
Valentin to make room for a rookie named Garciaparra. Valentin
walked out of a camp for a couple of days, but ultimately went
along with the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a cooling-off period then,'' Williams said. ``Here,
two days before the season, I have to tell a starter he's not going
to start. We don't have a lot of time. I understand that. If it
were me, I'd probably feel the same way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
