<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6195 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-GALARRAGA0     04-03 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GALARRAGA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga hasn't lost a step
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter your vantage point Monday at the Turner
Field of Dreams, Andres Galarraga was the man in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   If Hollywood wasn't watching, it should get the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Cat returned to baseball with a bang _ or a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Just check the seventh-inning tears of wife, Eneyda, and
daughters, Andria, Katherine and Andrianna, for proof.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months after being diagnosed with non-Hodgkins lymphoma _
cancer _ in his back, and wondering if he'd ever play again,
Galarraga didn't just put on a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   How about two fine defensive plays in the top of the inning,
including a diving stop to end a bases-loaded threat, and the
game-winning home run in the bottom half?
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is something special,'' Galarraga said. ``It's like a
movie. Believe me, I don't have the words to say how happy I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Braves and Rockies took the field, Eneyda closed her
eyes. She crossed herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed a lot for this moment,'' she said. ``I prayed before
for me, but after Andres' problems, I pray for everybody, the
children, my family, friends. We're very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Galarraga's homer, John Borum, 36, said, ``It's a
testament to the fact tough times don't last, but tough people
do.''
</P>
<P>
   TBS announcer Skip Caray said, ``It's amazing to think that a
year ago today, he wasn't sure he'd be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga was deathly scared when diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   There was no fear Monday, just appreciation for a man who
averaged 41 homers and 129 RBIs from '95-'98, and enchanted people
with his smile.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder 9-year-old Bryan Johnson was dancing in the stands in
his Galarraga jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my favorite because he just seems like a nice person and
he's good,'' said Johnson's mother, Debbie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has moral ideas that are good for a 9-year-old,'' she said.
``If there's a player you want your child to emulate, it's him, not
just for his stance and style, but for his outlook on life.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Stan Belinda struck out Galarraga in the bottom of
the eighth. Afterward, he wasn't gloating. He was relating.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen months ago, while with the Reds, Belinda was diagnosed
with multiple sclerosis. He knows of Galarraga's path.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go through something like that is a tremendous achievement,
not just in baseball, but in life,'' Belinda said. ``That's where
you separate hard-willed people from people who feel sorry for
themselves. It shows you what kind of heart he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
