<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carmakers' Post Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Strong March Sales Five leading automakers posted record
sales for the month of March, topping off a quarter that was the
best ever for the American automobile industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, DaimlerChrysler, Toyota, Honda and Mitsubishi all reported
record sales for the month while GM, which had had a special
promotion in February, was up only slightly and continued to lose
market share. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS Morning Show Is Struggling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS spent $30 million to revamp its morning program, brought in
one of its pre-eminent stars, Bryant Gumbel, and one of its most
experienced producers, Steve Friedman, to make a push to become a
serious competitor on the morning television lineup. But in the
months that have followed, the program's ratings have been
falling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biotech Companies Plan Promotion &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a backlash against genetically engineered crops,
some of the world's biggest biotechnology companies are planning a
five-year, $250 million campaign to convince consumers that the
products are safe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Data Show Economic Growth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A monthly report from the National Association of Purchasing
Management said manufacturing expanded for a 14th consecutive month
in March, while the Commerce Department said construction spending
rose 1.5 percent in February, to a record annual rate of $758.7
billion. The two reports added to the evidence that the nation's
economy has not slowed down despite the Federal Reserve's interest
rate increases over the last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mattel to Sell the Learning Co. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mattel said that it would seek a buyer for the Learning Co., the
educational software unit that it bought in May for $3.6 billion
and which has been in a slump ever since, leading to $300 million
in losses and the resignation of its chief executive. Analysts
think Mattel will get only a fraction of the price that it paid for
the company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic-GTE Picks a New Name &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to trade their somewhat stodgy images for that of a young
technology dynamo, Bell Atlantic and GTE said that they would call
their combined company Verizon after their merger deal is
completed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aurora Foods Restates Its Profit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aurora Foods, owner of well-known brands like Duncan Hines and
Log Cabin, named a new chief executive and restated its earnings
for 1998 and 1999. The moves come in response to an investigation
by the company into how it accounted for promotional spending and
follows the resignation in February of four of its top executives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telephone Competition in Mexico &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telephone companies struggling to make inroads in the Mexican
long-distance market say Telefonos de Mexico still benefits from
monopoly advantages and friendly regulators, but the Mexican
company says inexperience with the Mexican market is partly to
blame. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   USA Today Gets a Makeover &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost two decades after the splashy birth of USA Today, with
its vivid colors and snappy graphics, Monday's issue introduced a
makeover with pages and sections designed to present a more sober
image. Among other changes, the newspaper reduced the width of its
pages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adviser to Celebrities Is Charged &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have charged Dana C. Giacchetto, an
investment counselor to actors, rock bands and other artists, with
stealing $6 million from his clients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
