<HEADLINE>
GATORS' MILLER MAY JOIN 3 SPARTANS IN GOING PRO  
 ANOTHER FLINT ATHLETE  
 MEET YOUR COUSIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves, Morris Peterson
and perhaps A.J. Granger should be off to professional training
camps next fall. But they may have company.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the season, Florida's sophomore forward Mike Miller
indicated that he was ready to enter the National Basketball
Association draft. As the Gators kept winning in the national
tournament, the native of South Dakota did his best to push those
thoughts away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is definitely on a roller-coaster ride right now,''
Miller said before Monday night's national championship game. ``If
I think about going to the NBA and leaving this team, I might fall
off. And if I fall off, I might pull the rest of the team with me.
When the season's over, of course, I will think about it. But to
think about it right now would be hurtful to myself and my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Final Four began, Miller admitted he had at least 45
contacts with the New York-based agent Andy Miller, who was not
registered as an agent in Florida and did not follow the state's
guidelines, which are the strictest in the country. Andy Miller is
under investigation in Florida for violating the law, which is a
felony. Mike Miller has said only that he did not violate NCAA
regulations. But he conceded that his plans and the flap over his
status, have been a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER FLINT ATHLETE
</P>
<P>
   The Florida media guide lists Teddy Dupay's hometown as Fort
Myers, Fla. But the sophomore guard was born in Kansas City, Mo.,
and has lived in other places. Dupay seems amused that the news
media is intrigued by Michigan State's ``Flintstones'' _ Mateen
Cleaves, Charlie Bell and Morris Peterson _ who are all from Flint,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make a big deal out of those guys from Flint,'' Dupay
said. ``I lived in Flint for six years, up until the third grade.
Welch Boulevard. Ask them. They'll know where that is. My point is:
It doesn't matter where you come from or how old you are. The game
is played between the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to the Flint Police Department confirmed that there is,
indeed, a street by that name. ``Go Spartans!'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The hometowns of the players do provide an interesting contrast
between the two teams. Eight of the 15 players on Michigan State's
roster are from the state of Michigan. Six others are from states
or a Canadian province that shares a border with Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   On the 13-man Florida roster, eight come from the Sunshine State
and three are from nearby states like Georgia, West Virginia and
North Carolina. But Mike Miller is from South Dakota and Matt
Bonner from New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   MEET YOUR COUSIN
</P>
<P>
   Florida Coach Billy Donovan planned to rotate as many as four
players at center against Michigan State and that two of them
happened to be cousins.
</P>
<P>
   The starter Udonis Haslem and his first backup, Donnell Harvey,
are cousins, and Haslem found that out during the season. Haslem's
mother told him, and Harvey said he already knew but kept it a
secret because, ``I didn't know if I should say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Haslem is a 6-foot-7-inch sophomore and Harvey is a 6-8 freshman
who was the national high school player of the year from Shellman,
Ga. Haslem weighs 260 pounds and is the more physical player, and
Harvey weighs 216 pounds and is quicker and more athletic. The pair
give Donovan a special blend of muscle and quickness at center.
``They battle each other in practice and make each other better
players,'' Donovan said. ``People think we're a team that just
comes down and jacks up 3-pointers, but I feel very comfortable
with us feeding the ball into the post.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
