<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-UCONN-VOLS-FOLO04     04-03 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-VOLS-FOLO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Champion UConn appears blessed for future
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Connecticut coach Geno Auriemma's mother
sprinkled some holy water on the players Sunday in the moments
before their NCAA title game with Tennessee. But the Huskies
already were in a state of grace.
</P>
<P>
   Their 71-52 demolition of the Lady Volunteers had been billed as
a heavyweight battle between the sport's biggest rivals. Instead,
it was a crowning moment for a 36-1 UConn team ranked No. 1 all
season.
</P>
<P>
   The frightening prospect for the rest of women's basketball is
that the Huskies, who return their top nine players, will be
complemented by the best recruiting class in the country. But
unlike the Lady Vols, who boasted after their 39-0 championship
season in 1998 that they would be ``better than ever'' _ then got
bounced out in the Elite Eight the next season _ UConn won't make
any bold declarations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early right now for us to be looking at next year,''
said UConn guard Shea Ralph, the Final Four MVP with 15 points,
seven assists and six steals. ``We're just going to enjoy
everything about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph personified the Huskies. Even though she has had to
overcome two knee injuries, Ralph thinks nothing of flinging
herself to the floor to dive for loose balls. Center Kelly
Schumacher, from the hockey hotbed of rural Quebec, blocked nine
shots. Point guard Sue Bird, bothered by a jammed finger most of
the game, adeptly led the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach said it ... `There were no MVPs,''' Ralph said. ``This
was a team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, denied its seventh title, will have all of its
firepower coming back. But the Lady Vols, vulnerable in the
backcourt at times during the season, don't have any immediate
solutions for enhancing a guard contingent that is not quick or
particularly adept at perimeter shooting. Their top signee is a
post player.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game doesn't mean that your program's falling apart or
that you can't be competitive at this level,'' Tennessee coach Pat
Summitt said. ``We haven't won six titles thinking that way.''
</P>
<P>
   As in their 27-point loss to Georgia in January, however, the
Vols were susceptible to a team with depth, pressure defense and
prowess in transition.
</P>
<P>
   They never picked up UConn running countless back-door plays or
flashing cutters across the lane. ``They only ran two offenses the
whole night, but when they ran them, they scored,'' Tennessee
forward Tamika Catchings said. Catchings had 16 points but
struggled against double-team defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee reeled off three NCAA titles in a row after losing
to UConn in the 1995 championship game. For the moment, the only
other team with a reasonable chance to challenge UConn's supremacy
is Georgia, which has eight of its top nine players returning and
three high school All-Americans on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this 26 years, and I've never experienced
anything like this,'' Summitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
