<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-MATTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Analysts Approve of Move to Sell Money-Losing Learning Co.  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Mattel, the world's largest toymaker, announced yesterday plans to
sell its money-losing software business.
<P>
   Analysts predict that the El Segundo (Los Angeles County)
company will recoup less than a third of what it paid last year for
the Learning Co., which makes most of Mattel's software.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Mattel's software titles, the most well known of
which are Myst, the Carmen Sandiego series, and Barbie titles such
as Barbie Fashion Designer, is unclear, although the company said
in a statement that it intends to retain control of all traditional
Mattel brands.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman declined to comment on who would produce
software based on popular Mattel brands such as Barbie, Hot Wheels
and Fisher-Price once the sale is complete.
</P>
<P>
   The software business will be treated as a discontinued
operation in Mattel's financial statements effective March 31,
according to the company's statement.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Mattel paid $3.6 billion in stock to acquire the
Learning Co., a Cambridge, Mass., educational softwaremaker with
offices in Novato and Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sale, the Learning Co. has weighed down Mattel's
profitability and stock performance. The Learning Co. lost $206
million in 1999 and has seen its stock lose two-thirds of its value
since the sale, falling from a high of $29 on April 16, 1999, to a
low of $9.50 on March 7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's chief executive Jill Barad resigned February 3 after
Mattel reported losing $18.4 million in its fourth quarter ending
December 31. Barad was widely criticized for paying too much for
the Learning Co., Company,  &LR; and the educational softwaremaker's
software maker's  &LR; continuous problems were a factor in her
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Also on February 3, Mattel announced a restructuring plan that
led to the layoff of about 500 workers at the Learning Co.,
including several hundred in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel has engaged Credit Suisse First Boston to sell the
software business. Analysts predicted the selling price will range
from $200 million to $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The toy company may license to an outside softwaremaker the
rights to produce games based on its name brands, much like it has
licensed the Barbie and Hot Wheels names to Patriot Computers to
create children's personal computers based on those brands, said
Jim Silver, publisher of the Toy Book, a monthly trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Possible buyers for the Learning Co. include Havas Interactive,
a division of the French company Vivendi SA; Knowledge Universe;
Microsoft; and Infogrames Entertainment, analysts said. But Jill
Krutick, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, questioned whether the
money-losing Learning Co. would be much in demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that a sale of (the Learning Co.) could be
difficult for Mattel,'' Krutick wrote in a report released
yesterday. Krutick predicted that the Learning Co. would lose $150
million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's stock closed at $10.93 yesterday, up slightly from
$10.50 the day before. Analysts viewed the sale as a step that
might put Mattel on the path to recovery and almost inevitable in
the light of the Learning Co.'s dismal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were solid, competent management in place, I could
see them trying to turn (the software business) around,'' said Sean
McGowan, director of research for Gerard Klauer Mattison. But since
Barad's resignation, McGowan charged, Mattel's acting CEO Ronald M.
Loeband has only given Mattel part-time attention. ``You have a
rudderless, leaderless company now.''
</P>
<P>
   Krutick, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, said the sale of
the Learning Co. may help Mattel attract a permanent CEO.
</P>
<P>
   While the entire CD-ROM industry has faced difficulties in
recent years, McGowan was critical of the Learning Co. acquisition
even though getting into the software industry was not an unwise
choice for Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are spending less time and attention and money on
traditional toys. Software seemed to be a logical choice, and it
continues to be a logical choice, but educational software is less
interesting to kids than fun software,'' McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   While Hasbro, Mattel's main rival, has been more successful with
its software division, it, too, has faced speed bumps on the road
to bringing its business into the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Hasbro closed Alameda's Microprose, a software
company it had purchased just 16 months earlier. But while Barbie
is Mattel's only truly high-selling software title, Hasbro has been
able to build success on a variety of successful games in its
stables, including classics such as Frogger, and Hasbro board games
such as Scrabble and Monopoly, Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View company Purple Moon, purchased by Mattellast
March, will also be included in the sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
