<SLUG> BC-PENDER-PENDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH/KATHLEEN PENDER 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Market's Bulls Still Hot for Microsoft's Battered Stock 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Microsoft stock tumbled 14.5 percent yesterday, bringing it all the
way back to where it was a month ago.
<P>
   That's right. Despite the severe beating, which sparked a
bloodbath in tech stocks, Microsoft's stock closed a few cents
above its price on March 6, before it started running up on rumors
of an impending settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, who have been mostly bullish on the stock
since last fall, were slow to change their opinions yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Of 27 analysts tracked by First Call, nine reiterated a ``strong
buy'' rating, six reiterated a ``buy'' and only one downgraded the
stock. Of course, that could change today as analysts have more
time to digest the news, said Chuck Hill, director of research at
Boston's First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Lone bear Melissa Eisenstat of CIBC World Markets lowered her
recommendation on Microsoft yesterday from a buy to a hold.
</P>
<P>
   Her previous rating ``was based on a hope that the suit would be
settled, over, boom, finished, no more black cloud, and that even
if it hit the operating model, people would say, `We can move
on.'''
</P>
<P>
   With yesterday's decision, ``unfortunately the black cloud is
just bigger. If you take the long-term view, it's still a great
company. But there's enough uncertainty that I'm just unwilling to
say, `Back up the truck and start buying here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstat also believes that Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
issuing of the conclusion of law opens Microsoft to a flood of
civil lawsuits. ``Microsoft has roughly $18 billion in cash with
which to defend itself, yet we believe that there is significant
risk in moving from a technological innovator to a defendant on
many fronts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the close on Friday, Microsoft was trading at 55 times
expected earnings, more than twice its 25 percent earnings growth
rate. ``When a high-flier gets crushed, you sometimes see the
multiples contract to something like one times the growth rate,''
Eisenstat said. ``This suggests that a 50 percent correction in the
share price is possible, but not probable.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstat believes the antitrust case will affect Microsoft's
operations over the longer term, but she didn't change her earnings
estimate because she doesn't have enough ``clarity on the relief
and its impact on Microsoft's future earnings power.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, First Call's Hill doesn't think any analysts will be
changing their estimates, because Jackson's ruling ``won't have any
impact for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the reason why so many brokerage houses upheld
their outlooks yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does (yesterday's decision) change the way Microsoft does
business? The answer is zero,'' said Brown Brothers Harriman
analyst Sanjiv Hingorani, who reiterated his buy recommendation.
``It's not going to be put into effect for a long time, if ever.
The business fundamentals of the company will take hold once
investors internalize the fact that there isn't going to be a quick
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He think's Microsoft's stock will perk up when the company
reports earnings on April 20. He expects they will be higher than
the current consensus estimate.
</P>
<P>
   George Godfrey of ING Barings reiterated his strong buy rating
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I liked it at 106 on Friday, I have to love it at 91,'' he
said. ``Even if the courts take the most aggressive approach, a
breakup, I actually think, from a pure investment perspective, that
shareholders will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Mary Meeker of Morgan Stanely Dean Witter , &LR; maintained
her ``outperform'' rating on Microsoft. ``We believe, on average
over the next few years, MSFT shares will outperform the S&AMP;P 500
owing to above average revenue and operating income growth,'' she
wrote in a report. ``That said, we think this DOJ investigation
continues to be a negative not only because it's a serious cloud
that creates uncertainty, but also because it is a serious morale
hitter for Microsoft employees.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. I called several analysts who were quoted here last week
saying Microsoft is a great buy. None returned my call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VANGUARD DROPS FEES &QL; 
Vanguard Group is removing those annoying transaction fees on five
of its index funds and lowering the fees on three others.
</P>
<P>
   The Small-Cap, European, Pacific and Total International index
funds are eliminating their 0.5 percent transaction fees, and the
Extended Market fund is killing its 0.25 percent fee.
</P>
<P>
   The Emerging Markets Fund is lowering its fee to 0.5 percent
from 1 percent. The Tax-Managed International Fund is reducing its
fee to 0.25 percent from 0.75 percent. And the Tax-Managed
Small-Cap Fund is cutting the fee to 0.5 percent from 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Transaction fees apply to all new purchases, but unlike loads
that are paid out to brokers, they go back into the fund to cover
the cost of buying stocks. Vanguard said it could cut the fees
because the cost of trading has declined.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is good news for most Vanguard customers, ``If if
 &LR; you're already in the fund and are not making new purchases, the
change is a slight negative,'' said Scott Cooley, a senior analyst
with fund-rater Morningstar. That's because investors who are
buying new shares will be paying less or nothing to subsidize the
cost of their purchases.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cooley said that drawback will be far outweighed by
eliminating the nuisance factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had all kinds of complaints from people about the
transaction fees. A lot of people see these are no-load funds and
don't realize the fees are there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It especially irritates smaller investors because on top of
the transaction fee, you get a $2.50 per quarter account
maintenance fee if you have less than $10,000 in a fund. Some
people feel like they're getting nickel-and-dimed.''
</P>
<P>
   The change does not affect the annual fees paid by all
shareholders to cover management and operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
