<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-SEGA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Sega Site to Give Video Gamers World-Class Competition  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Video-game-consolemaker Sega will venture into uncharted territory
today with the launch of a company that for the first time will let
console users battle each other over the Internet.
<P>
   At its annual summit today in Las Vegas, San Francisco's Sega of
America will spin off Sega.com Inc., an independent firm that
includes a gaming portal and Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, which will go live in May, will act as the gateway
to Sega games on the Web for users of its flagship Dreamcast
console. SegaNet, the ISP, will be operated by a yet-to-named
 &LR; yet-to-be-named company, and is scheduled to premiere debut  &LR; in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Sega.com, also to be based in San Francisco, has $100 million in
backing from Sega Enterprises Ltd, Sega of America's Japanese
parent, and about 150 employees, many of whom are from the
now-defunct SegaSoft division.
</P>
<P>
   For Sega, the venture represents a revamped Internet strategy
and an attempt to ride the momentum from having sold more than 2
million Dreamcast console units. Sega and its larger competitors
are rushing to go after the exploding online game market.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm, expects the
number of gamers online to grow from about 38 million last year to
68 million by 2003. Revenues from advertising on gaming sites and
subscriptions for online games is expected to shoot from $106
million in 1999 to $769 million by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a unique position in that we're the only company that
owns the delivery system, the proprietary hardware and proprietary
software,'' said Greg Chiemingo, Sega.com's vice president of
marketing. ``That's something no other company can match.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega hopes its Internet online game strategy will lure game
enthusiasts, who want the network's tournaments, chat rooms,
rankings and cheat codes, and folks who don't have a computer but
want to be able to cruise the Internet, get e-mail and play games.
</P>
<P>
   But Schelley Olhava, analyst at research firm IDC, is skeptical
about Sega's latest venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting into the ISP business is really risky,'' she said.
``It's going to be an upward battle getting people to go SegaNet
because a lot of consumers already have established service with
AOL or EarthLink, and it's hard to get people to do things like
change their e-mail email  &LR; addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   To offset some of those concerns, Sega is offering a powerful
financial incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who sign a two-year contract with SegaNet will get a
free keyboard and a check for $200, which covers the cost of the
$199 Dreamcast. Sega says it will make money through ISP
subscriptions _ $21.95 a month _ as well as advertising, fees from
e-commerce transactions and licensing.
</P>
<P>
   The Net venture will be unprecedented. While PC gamers have been
able to go head to head online for years with players of Quake, an
action title from Id Software, console owners of all types
including Dreamcast, PlayStation or Nintendo64 have been limited to
playing the person sitting beside them on the living room couch.
</P>
<P>
   Though there has been much hype to the contrary, no console
company has capitalized on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Sega unveiled its 56K modem-equipped Dreamcast in
September, there were almost no online titles for it, though users
could send e-mail and surf the Web on the minimal Dreamcast
Network.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has remedied that by lining up more than a
dozen online games, including Quake 3 and NFL 2K1 for the SegaNet
and Sega.com launches this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, analysts say Sega's main advantage is a word
rarely hyped in today's lexicon: narrowband.
</P>
<P>
   The X-Box, Microsoft's first console, and Sony's pending
PlayStation 2 support only broadband such as DSL and other
high-speed connections. By contrast, narrowband refers to 56K or
slower Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sega will offer a broadband adapter later this year, it
will initially fashion its Sega.com games with the Dreamcast's 56K
modem in mind.
</P>
<P>
   By capitalizing on narrowband now rather than when broadband
reaches a critical mass, Sega gains a major foothold in the online
gaming industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sega is acknowledging that there are many paths to the
Internet, and that includes narrowband as well as broadband,'' said
Bruce Leichtman, analyst at the Yankee Group, a Boston research
firm. ``Broadband is emerging, but there are still many, many more
people with narrowband. If you're only focusing on broadband,
you're only going to get a very, very small piece of the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2 million people have broadband connections now, versus
about 40 million with 56K or slower, Leichtman said. By 2004,
broadband users will swell to almost 17 million. But narrowband
will still remain dominant _ with about 50 million users.
</P>
<P>
   Narrowband may give Sega a lead _ but it will a finite one,
industry watchers predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to have games the competition won't have,
they're just going to have them first,'' said Joe Funk, editor of
Electronic Gaming Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the X-Box isn't due out until 2001, as is Nintendo's
Dolphin.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's PlayStation 2 _ the industry's 800-pound gorilla _ is set
to hit U.S. stores this fall, but so far, the company hasn't
announced any online titles. Also, the company on Saturday began
recalling 1.6 million PlayStation 2 units because they played
unauthorized DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these missteps from its competitors, Sega's online
foray won't be a cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   After the debacle surrounding its failed Genesis console in the
mid-1990s, the company slipped to a distant third in the gaming
hardware market (behind No. 1 Sony and then Nintendo) and was
written off by many in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamcast has helped the company regain a 15 percent slice of
the console market, up from 0.5 percent just before its launch. But
it's still far from the 50 percent Sega once commanded.
</P>
<P>
   And as more entertainment, Internet and software companies turn
an eye toward the lucrative and growing game industry, Sega will
continue to face stiff competition.
</P>
<P>
   The latest juggernaut on the horizon is a recent partnership
between American Online and Electronic Arts. The companies late
last year formed an alliance in which Redwood City's Electronic
Arts, the No. 1 video-game-maker in the United States, will create
games and other entertainment content for AOL, the world's No. 1
online services provider.
</P>
<P>
   Still, game insiders give the company kudos for being the first
console to truly support online games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a milestone in the game industry because
it's so different from playing online with a PC,'' said Crispin
Boyer, editor at Electronic Gaming Monthly. ``This is going to be
playing games on the Internet with people from around the world
with a console _ something that costs thousands less than a PC.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at kzito(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
