u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-DAYNE04-COX     04-03 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-DAYNE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weight concerns dog Dayne
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wisconsin running back Ron Dayne and Georgia Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton were two of college football's best
players last year. They finished 1-2 in voting for the Heisman
Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eyes of many NFL scouts, Dayne is too large and
Hamilton too small.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the players in this year's draft, the pair might inspire
the least consensus. Because of his height, Hamilton probably won't
be chosen until the second day of the draft, possibly no earlier
than the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, the NCAA's career rushing leader with 6,397 yards, will
go in the first round. But concerns about his weight seem likely to
prevent him from being the first running back selected. At
February's draft combine, Dayne tipped the scales at 259 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, he's always going to have problems with his
weight,'' said Reed Johnson, the Falcons' director of college
scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams have Dayne rated the fourth-best running back, behind
Virginia's Thomas Jones, Alabama's Shaun Alexander and Tennessee's
Jamal Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, who has been compared with the Steelers' Jerome Bettis
and former Redskins star John Riggins, seemed to temper some
concerns about his waistline after a workout last month in Madison,
Wis. He ran the 40-yard dash under 4.6 seconds, much faster than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Ron Dayne,'' Chiefs general manager Carl Peterson said.
``He fits well into our offense. That's what we do. We run the
ball. We hammer you and hammer you and hammer you, and, hopefully,
in the fourth quarter you break.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs, who have the 21st pick of the draft, are one of
several teams expected to draft a running back in the first round.
The Ravens (fifth and 15th picks), Cardinals (seventh), Giants
(11th) and Seahawks (19th and 22nd) also need running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me,'' Dayne said. ``I don't get caught up
into No. 1, No. 2, whatever. As long as I get picked and get to
play, I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some scouts also were concerned about Dayne's stamina, because
he didn't play in the fourth quarter of many games. But Dayne says
he wasn't in the game because the Badgers blew out most of their
opponents the past two seasons. Others say he carried the ball too
much in his four seasons at Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably one of the bigger concerns with him is, if you're of
the belief that a back has only so much mileage, he's carried the
ball an awful lot over four years,'' said Phil Savage, the Ravens'
director of college scouting.
</P>
<P>
   With less than two weeks before the April 15-16 draft, the Great
Dayne continues to take everything in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got everything a smaller running back has, but better,''
he said. ``I don't seen any running backs like me. That's the
reason why people criticize me. They don't know where to put me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
