<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-STOCKGIFT-STOCKGIFT_S     04-03 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKGIFT-STOCKGIFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 
 Stockgift.com lets people give securities for any occasion 
 &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
When business student Gino Heilizer and photo editor Christina
Shutes of Washington, D.C., became engaged a couple of years ago,
they followed the age-old custom of signing up with the bridal
registry at a local department store.
<P>
   But as they debated which items to request from their relatives
and friends, it dawned on them that they didn't really need any of
the traditional wedding gifts. Already in their late 20s, they had
long since stocked up on silverware, dishes, linens and the like.
</P>
<P>
   What they actually wanted, they agreed, was money to buy stock
so they could ride the powerful bull market to wedded prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to start saving for our financial welfare, for kids,
for their college,'' Heilizer says. ``We have the mundane stuff of
life, so we wanted to start building our portfolio. We have a lot
of friends in the same boat.''
</P>
<P>
   But tradition says that you aren't supposed to ask your wedding
guests for hard cash _ it's too tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   Heilizer and Shutes decided that it doesn't have to be, so six
weeks ago, they launched Stockgift.com, an online registry where
engaged couples _ or anyone else, for that matter _ can discreetly
ask for money to buy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Stockgift.com does the buying for them. It is licensed
as a securities broker, and it makes money off the venture by
charging $19.95 for each trade it transacts.
</P>
<P>
   Stockgift.com maintains a Web site at www.stockgift.com and
assigns the prospective gift recipients their own, separate Web
pages. To get installed on the site, they must fill out the forms
normally required to open a brokerage account.
</P>
<P>
   Stockgift.com recipients typically choose the stocks they would
like to own and include a little write-up explaining how they
decided on their choices.
</P>
<P>
   The gift givers can transfer actual shares of stock if they
happen to own stakes in companies the recipients like. But most
givers simply contribute cash, either by check or credit card. (If
they use a credit card, Stockgift.com charges them a 2.95 percent
processing fee.)
</P>
<P>
   As the money accumulates, Stockgift.com spreads it evenly among
the stocks the recipients requested.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it is up to the recipients to decide whether and
when they want to sell the stocks in their accounts. They can use
the account as they would any other brokerage account _ for
example, to buy more stocks with their own money.
</P>
<P>
   If they are audacious enough, the recipients might personally &LR; 
 &LR; buttonhole potential givers and tell them to check out the
Stockgift.com Web site. If they are too shy to make their own
pitch, Stockgift.com will do it for them by sending out e-mail
notices.
</P>
<P>
   Stockgift.com isn't only for weddings. The more than 100
registrations now currently  &LR; on the Web site also include births,
birthdays, confirmations, bar mitzvahs, graduations, college funds,
you name it.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the recipient is a minor, an adult must set up
and administer the brokerage account as custodian.
</P>
<P>
   Some Web pages celebrate no occasion in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Jones, 31, chief technical officer of a Santa Clara firm
that helps other companies develop their Web sites, recently
registered his little goddaughter, Isabella Sells, with
Stockgift.com after hearing an announcement about the service on
the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't defined an event yet,'' he says. But he is asking
Isabella's family and family friends to take a look at her Web
page.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, considering his profession, Jones chose three
big, Internet-related stocks _ Cisco Systems, Microsoft and 3Com _
for Isabella's portfolio. But he also tossed in General Electric.
``Every portfolio should have a blue chip,'' he explains
apologetically.
</P>
<P>
   David Schiffman, 31, a salesman in Highland Park, Ill., set up a
page for his daughter, Alexis, on the Stockgift.com Web site. The
occasion is her first birthday, which won't arrive until October.
</P>
<P>
   Schiffman says he heard about Stockgift.com from a friend who
works for the company.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Microsoft and America Online for his daughter's
portfolio because, as he explains on the Web site, they promise
``solid growth and performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiffman confesses: ``I don't know if I have a really good
reason for picking those stocks. I play the market shorter term
myself, but I figure for her _ regardless of what Microsoft and AOL
might do in the short term _ they seem good for the longer term.''
</P>
<P>
   Heilizer says he can't estimate how many more people will sign
up with Stockgift.com, but he notes that his Web site is getting
1,000 hits per day. He is convinced that he is riding the wave of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Meltzer, director of marketing for Los Angeles'
WeddingChannel.com, a leading online bridal registry that features
traditional gift giving, concedes that ``there is some validity''
to Heilizer's business plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that it is important to accommodate a variety of
preferences, and we will look to expand our own registry offerings
down the road,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But she contends that traditional registries are ``here to
stay.'' WeddingChannel.com, she points out, is growing and
flourishing in its present form, with 350,000 listings from engaged
couples seeking gifts from such stores as Bloomingdale's, Macy's
and Burdine's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even couples who are marrying later and own some of the
household basics are viewing their wedding as an opportunity to
acquire higher-quality items,'' Meltzer explains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
