<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORZINE REPORTS A THREAT TO EXPOSE MORE ETHNIC SLURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Extending his stroll through the minefield of
ethnic politics just when the issue seemed behind him, Jon S.
Corzine Monday accused a spurned would-be campaign worker of trying
to blackmail him by threatening to go public with more ``dirt''
about supposed slurs against Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, who appeared alongside
Corzine, used the occasion to make it perfectly clear that he
supports Corzine over former Gov. Jim Florio in the Democratic
primary for the seat being vacated by Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who apologized repeatedly last week for making
offensive remarks _ most recently, for joking about cement shoes to
an Italian-American contractor _ said he had been threatened twice
on Friday, first in a telephone message left at the Corzine
campaign headquarters that morning and then in a late-night phone
call to Corzine's wife, Joanne, at their home in Summit.
</P>
<P>
   He identified the caller as Michael Cino, a co-chairman of an
Italian-American Democratic club called the Columbus Coalition, who
had sought a job with the Corzine campaign for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cino's game is up, and that effort is in the open,'' Corzine
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Cino, 36, of Demarest, who on Saturday faxed to reporters and
posted on the Internet a rambling statement asserting a ``pattern
of ethnic slurs on the part of Jon Corzine,'' did not return
repeated messages left by telephone at his home and by e-mail
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Corzine's lawyer, Stanley Arkin, played
a copy of a voice-mail message apparently left by Cino at 9:49 a.m.
on Friday, in which he demanded that a ``peace conference'' with
Corzine be held Monday _ or else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have more material, so I think it's in everybody's
best interest and the interest of the Democratic Party to have that
meeting on Monday, OK?'' the caller says on the voice-mail
extension of Karen Goldman, a Corzine campaign worker. ``This is
your last chance, Karen.''
</P>
<P>
   That night at 11:17, according to Joanne Corzine, Cino called
the Corzine home and again demanded to meet Corzine on Monday,
warning, ``We have so much dirt on him we can't decide which to
throw out first.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said the caller, his voice growing louder as the
15-minute call went on, added: ``If Jon would just meet with us
Monday, this would all go away. Your staff promised we would be
taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said he believed the matter of Corzine's statements
was now put to rest. ``I hope this is the last irrelevancy of the
2000 campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, the chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, said he had tried to maintain a ``studied neutrality''
in primary contests among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But a moment later, asked his opinion of Florio's character,
Torricelli responded after a long pause, ``I am somewhat less
neutral in some races than others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
