A6206 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     04-03 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Be Prepared To Explain Your Loss 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I used to own a small business, but seven years ago I retired
and discontinued it. While I was in business, I purchased some
surplus for it for commercial use. I was unable to obtain financing
and finally abandoned the project. This equipment is still in
storage and eventually will be scrapped or sold at a fraction of
the cost. Is there any way I can deduct my loss from my current tax
liability?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: You appear to be in luck.
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says that if you
didn't depreciate the cost on earlier income-tax forms and didn't
write off the cost when you shut down your business, you are
entitled to claim a business loss.
</P>
<P>
   If you get nothing for the equipment, then the loss is equal to
the amount you paid. If someone pays for it, then the loss would
amount to the cost minus the payment you receive.
</P>
<P>
   Report the details on IRS Schedule C, ``Profit or Loss from
Business.''
</P>
<P>
   Weller warns that because you may not have filed a Schedule C in
recent years _ and because the one you are going to file will
include no revenues, only an inventory loss _ there is a strong
chance that the IRS will ask you some follow-up questions.
</P>
<P>
   He advises you to attach an explanatory statement to your
return. You also should assemble any receipts and other documents
related to the purchase of the equipment, and you should dig out
your past returns and other business records in case you are asked
to confirm that you didn't write off the loss previously.
</P>
<P>
   I'm assuming that you still have all that stuff. Probably most
taxpayers have tossed out financial records going back seven years
and more. But that's unwise, especially when there are still some
loose ends, as in your case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
High Return or Low Risk?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have about $10,000 that I need to invest in mutual funds or
something else that is not too risky, yet still has a high rate of
return. I plan to withdraw the money after about five years. What
do you advise?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: There isn't any satisfactory solution.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds and stocks have the potential for high rates of
return, but they are riskier than you seem to think. While there is
a strong chance that an investment in a diversified stock portfolio
will be worth more five years from now than it is today, there
certainly is no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Treasury issues or bank certificates of deposit are
virtually risk-free, but their returns _ in the neighborhood of 5
or 6 percent per year _ are not considered high.
</P>
<P>
   Those returns do, however, exceed the current rate of inflation.
So, if inflation remains low, your buying power would increase with
these investments.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that you will have to decide which is most
important to you: high return or low risk. It may be that you will
decide on a compromise, mixing stocks or mutual funds with
fixed-income investments in whatever proportion makes you
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Toward Zero Capital Gain
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am in the 28 percent federal tax bracket. Suppose I report
$1,000 in short-term capital gains and $1,000 in long-term capital
losses for 1999. Will my net capital gain be zero ($1,000 minus
$1,000) or $80 ($1,000 times 0.28 minus $1,000 times 0.2)?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: Your question may mystify some readers, so I'll expand on
it.
</P>
<P>
   For someone in the 28 percent tax bracket, short-term capital
gains are taxed at 28 percent, but long-term capital gains _
involving assets held more than one year _ are taxed at only 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to answer your question: No such distinction is made for
capital losses. Any capital loss _ long-term or short-term _ can be
fully offset against any capital gain.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you have $1,000 in short-term gains and $1,000 in
short-term losses, there is no net gain or loss and therefore no
capital-gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag(At)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
