A6208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DRKOOP-STOCK04-COX     04-03 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRKOOP-STOCK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drkoop.com studying prescription for recovery
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Drkoop.com Inc., the company named after the
famous former surgeon general, urged the public Monday not to pull
the plug on it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in the Austin-based online health company dropped 41
percent Friday after its independent auditor cast doubt on its
ability to continue operating because of dwindling cash reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares sank an additional 19 percent Monday,
falling 72 cents to close at $2.97.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, drkoop.com said that it was still alive
and looking for ways out of its financial predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to distinguish between a `going concern'
opinion, which ... is basically the result of a calculation
involving cash burn and cash reserves, from an opinion as to a
company's viability,'' the company stated. ``It is not a prediction
that a company is about to fold. We continue to explore a host of
strategic financing options that we will announce as soon as is
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Auditors are required to file ``going concern'' letters when a
company has less than 12 months' worth of cash with which to
operate.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for drkoop.com _ who said the company is in a
quiet period until it files its next quarterly report on April 25 _
refused to elaborate on what financing options were being
considered. Analysts have said the company could solicit a private
investment or put itself up for sale but would have difficulty
raising money by selling more stock or issuing bonds because of its
poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors' letter, reported in drkoop.com's annual report
March 30, stated that there was ``substantial doubt'' about the
company's future because it did not have enough cash reserves to
cover its expenses through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
