u i BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-1STLD-WR     04-03 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH JAPAN'S PREMIER IN A COMA, SUCCESSION MOVES GET UNDER WAY
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: UPDATES throughout with more on succession fight, criticism
of how Aoki released information, quotes, political background; now
in 2 takes; no pickup; subs overline.) 
(js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese politics were thrown into disarray Monday by
the news that Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was in a coma after
suffering a stroke early Sunday, and was being kept alive on a
respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese did not learn of the gravity of Obuchi's condition
until early Monday, nearly 36 hours after he was hospitalized early
Sunday with complaints of extreme fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   By late Monday afternoon, televised reports said that Obuchi,
62, was breathing only with the assistance of a respirator, and
that he had been given drugs to reverse a catastrophic drop in
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently he is in a coma,'' said Mikio Aoki, the prime
minister's chief cabinet secretary, who assumed temporary control
of the government. In a formula usually reserved in Japan for
people near death, Aoki said that Obuchi's condition was ``beyond
prediction.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's illness set the political community into high gear.
Leaders of the long-governing Liberal Democratic Party planned to
meet, and there were indications that they would choose Yoshiro
Mori, secretary-general of the party, to act as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders mentioned were Foreign Minister Yohei Kono and
two former prime ministers, Kiichi Miyazawa, Obuchi's finance
minister, and Ryutaro Hashimoto, Obuchi's immediate predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders moved to prepare campaigns to unseat the
Liberal Democratic Party _ a conservative party despite its name _
in the coming general election.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts concluded Monday that the country would
almost certainly hold elections before July, when Japan plays host
to the Group of Eight summit meeting of economic powers.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Obuchi became ill, politicians had begun
behind-the-scenes jockeying knowing that elections had to be called
by October. And for several months now, the government's popularity
has dwindled because of scandals involving public officials as well
as high unemployment and a faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although he quietly worked toward the prime minister's job for
much of his political life, Obuchi was widely written off as a
merely a transitional figure when his party selected him for the
job in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a top aide to the longtime party kingmaker, and former prime
minister, Noboru Takeshita, Obuchi thrived not by staking out
positions of his own, but by doggedly serving his masters, by
patience and by projecting a sense of selflessness and loyalty to
the party.
</P>
<P>
   As prime minister, Obuchi used many of those qualities to win
over a skeptical public. During his first year in office his most
winning attribute was his striking modesty. In a country where many
political leaders conduct themselves with a haughty arrogance,
Obuchi proclaimed that he had no ideas of his own, but would rely
on his ability to listen to others to guide his decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi pushed through a $400 billion plan for outlays to
stimulate the economy and to recapitalize banks to try to get the
economy growing, measures that were popular with the public. But
they indebted the government, and critics say that other tough
reforms, involving health care and corporate tax reform, were
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   His humble style won him strong public support, and soon, for
the first time in his political career, Obuchi began to show
glimmers of personal ambition. One of his goals was to serve a long
time as prime minister. He was also eager to welcome the summit
meeting of leading industrial nations, to take place in Okinawa in
July.
</P>
<P>
   But Obuchi's fixation on the summit meeting, which he counted on
to give him a boost in the elections, seemed to distract him from
other important matters that were working to undo his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months a string of high-level scandals affecting
everything from featherbedding by bank regulators to cover-ups of
police misdoings hurt his popularity. Obuchi was severely
criticized in the press for his handling of the scandals.
</P>
<P>
   When a police inspector was found to have gone to a spa to drink
and play mah-jongg with a local police commissioner rather than
inspect the troubled commissariat he was sent to examine, for
example, Obuchi remarked to Parliament that the inspector had been
``unlucky'' to have been caught.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, thickset and gravel-voiced, has quickly emerged as the
favorite within the Liberal Democratic Party to succeed Obuchi. He
heads the third-largest faction in the party and has close
relations with the party's main coalition partner, the
Buddhist-backed New Komeito party. He also has had a flawless
record of loyalty to Obuchi throughout his term in office.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, if selected, will probably need to call new elections
quickly so that Japan will not be in the position of serving as
host to the economic summit meeting under interim leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A likely opponent might be Yukio Hatoyama, a wealthy heir of an
old political family who heads the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few people expect Aoki to serve as anything other than an
interim leader. Already in his 24 hours at the helm, he has faced
mounting criticism of his exercise of authority, particularly the
way he broke the news. The public was spoon-fed information about
the crisis, with no news until 21 hours after Obuchi's
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   For many the situation seemed to highlight the creaky nature of
Japan's rules of succession and to underscore the ingrained
attitude among those in power that the public's right to know
counts for little in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One deception widely criticized Monday was that the prime
minister's office had told the press corps early Sunday that Obuchi
had risen at 6 a.m. and was spending the day at his official
residence. It was learned later that the prime minister had checked
into Juntendo University Hospital at 1 a.m. on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like the wartime government announcements, deceiving
the people,'' said Atsuo Nakamura, an independent member of
Parliament. ``Even 50 years later, the administration is following
the same pattern, hiding problems and putting off announcements.
All the while, they are having discussions on how to advance their
own interests arising from the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Aoki, who has announced most of the public information about
Obuchi's condition, first told the nation of a problem shortly
after 11 p.m. on Sunday. Even then, he strove to minimize the
problem, saying in a four-minute statement that the prime minister
had remained conscious and had been driven to the hospital in a
private car rather than by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   But by Monday afternoon Aoki was giving a different account.
Looking grim as he spoke to the press, Aoki said Obuchi had been
placed on a respirator by 9:50 p.m. on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by the press corps, Aoki acknowledged that this meant
that the prime minister had already lost consciousness well before
the acting prime minister's first vague statements to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper editorials speculated that Aoki had extended the
information vacuum as long as possible to favor the kind of
back-room discussions over a new leader that define Japanese
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics have focused on the barely scripted mechanism by
which Aoki assumed authority: He said he had been asked to do so in
a conversation with Obuchi that apparently had no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Constitution is vague about what should happen when a
leader suddenly vacates power. Aoki relied on the so-called cabinet
law, which allows a prime minister to designate his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Isao Sato, an emeritus professor of law at Sophia University,
said: ``In the earlier times, when the cabinet was formed the prime
minister would designate an acting prime minister just in case
something happened to him. They were informally called deputy prime
ministers, making it clear who was to take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sato said the practice had fallen into disuse because the heads
of various Liberal Democratic Party factions resented the selection
of an official who would have a leg up in the next succession
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, with the prospect of an emergency succession looming for
the first time in 20 years, many politicians criticized the law's
vagueness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not based on the Constitution, and it is a big problem
that two people can decide the supreme authority of the state all
by themselves, at their own discretion,'' said Naoto Kan, the
policy director of the Democratic Party, Japan's leading opposition
group. ``This has all occurred without witnesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
