<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-FALCONE-REVIEW-SFC     04-03 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN UP! IT'S TIME FOR MOBSPEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS has provided us jackass critics with a glossary of Mafia
terms to help us understand ``Falcone.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you know, for example, that ``whacked'' (or ``wacked,'' as
CBS spells it) means ``being killed off''?
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``racket'' (or ``raquet,'' as CBS spells it) means ``a
fraudulent or dishonest business.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, CBS!
</P>
<P>
   I'm not so sure about CBS' spelling on racket/raquet/racquet,
but I know that ``Falcone'' is an incredibly whacky, if not wacky,
TV show.
</P>
<P>
   One indecisive ``wiseguy'' (``a member of the crew who is not an
official member of the mob'') is minced with an ice pick by someone
who apparently is an official member of the mob.
</P>
<P>
   Two others are garroted, quicker than they can say ``salud''
(``the Italian tern for `hello,' which has many translations in the
mob world'').
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, I don't know what an ``Italian tern'' is, but I
hope there isn't a hunting season.
</P>
<P>
   A ``stoolie'' (``a person functioning as a decoy, an informer'')
is spiked on one of those sharp things that used to be used for
discarded paper. Several others are merely gunned down, practically
an act of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   All of this ``wacking'' is terribly violent by network
prime-time standards, but it proves to be as addictive as ever for
those of us outside the wiseguy ``raquet.''
</P>
<P>
   It can also be quite suspenseful, especially when undercover FBI
agent Joe Pistone (series star Jason Gedrick) could get whacked at
any moment.
</P>
<P>
   The show is based on the real Pistone's exploits, and on the
movie (``Donnie Brasco'') inspired by Pistone.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is ``millionairizing'' (running a show in highly
concentrated form, in hopes of building an audience) its new Mafia
drama. It has ordered nine hours of ``Falcone,'' and will air it
Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, next Monday, next
Tuesday and on April 12.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``ratings'' (official statistical indications of public
acceptance) allow, ``Falcone'' will find a place on the fall
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise it will be ``canceled'' (a network term for whacked)
after its maiden nine hours.
</P>
<P>
   Pistone is two years into his dangerous gig, using the name Joe
Falcone, when the show opens.
</P>
<P>
   He has penetrated the Volonte crime family in Brooklyn, where
Victor ``The Pick'' Mura (James Russo) and Santino ``Sonny Boy''
Napoli (Titus Welliver) are set to square off after family boss
Carlo Volonte meets an earlier demise than he'd anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Volonte's successor, Raymond ``Madman'' Ricci (Eric ``Curled
Lip'' Roberts), wants his squabbling captains Mura and Napoli to
make peace. But Ricci is confined to a mental hospital, so there's
not much he can do.
</P>
<P>
   Pistone/Falcone has to thread through the delicate maze of mob
loyalties and align himself with the right guy, or his FBI
assignment will end fruitlessly.
</P>
<P>
   He also has the equally delicate task of squeezing quality time,
here and there, for his wife, Maggie (Amy Carlson), and their two
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Along its route, ``Falcone'' picks up reliable supporting help
such as Patti LuPone in the role of an assistant district attorney
with her own agenda; the recognizable Mike Starr as a school board
member with a gambling weakness; and Robert John Burke as Falcone's
FBI handler.
</P>
<P>
   But the dramatic crux of the series is the relationship between
Falcone and Sonny Napoli (Sonny Napoli! ``Sunny Naples''?).
</P>
<P>
   Falcone seems to have won the genuine affection of the volatile
mobster, who has a sort of soft side when he's not being a
homicidal maniac. One slipup, though, and Falcone will be fried
Sonny side up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' keeps putting the possibility out there. For one
thing, there's a henchman named Jimmy Suits (Sonny Marinelli), who
doesn't trust Falcone.
</P>
<P>
   Start with it from the top, and you might find ``Falcone''
addictive. The writing is certainly above average, the black
leather-coated mobsters make for lively viewing and the doe-eyed
Gedrick, in the title role, has always projected the vulnerable air
of a man on thin ice.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if it weren't for HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' ``Falcone''
might earn raves. But ``The Sopranos'' has raised the bar; its
startling success is based on a knack for making its Jersey
mobsters refreshingly life-size, and for splashing sardonic humor
into its own take on life in the mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' lacks that sense of humor and gives the Mafia more
of a conventional Hollywood slant. But within those confines, it's
a highly watchable trip through mob mayhem and undercover jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Call this one ``The Mezzo-Sopranos,'' which CBS might define as
``an opry tern for a voice with a lower register than a Tony
Soprano.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
