<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WILLIAMS-INJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARM INJURY SIDELINES YANKEES' WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Bernie Williams might not be able to play
center field for the first few games of the Yankees' season because
of a strained triceps in his right arm. But Williams says the
injury only hurts when he is throwing, so he figures to be in the
lineup as the designated hitter until he gets better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it'll be only a few days,'' said Williams, who
cannot recall when he got hurt. ``Probably making a throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee will start in center field and Shane Spencer _ who
will usually be the DH this year _ will start in left. Ledee, who
hit .351 with a team-high seven home runs in spring training, was
to hit sixth in Monday night's lineup, an indication of Manager Joe
Torre's growing confidence in the young outfielder. Tino Martinez,
a left-handed hitter, will bat fifth and Ledee, also a left-handed
hitter, will hit sixth, all but inviting the opposing manager to
bring in left-handed in the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than insert the switch-hitting Jorge Posada between
Martinez and Ledee, however, Torre will use them back to back, to
get Ledee higher in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   In the days to come, the Yankees could turn to the newly
acquired Lance Johnson to play center field. Johnson joined the
team Monday, arriving with his signature goatee shaved off _ the
first time since he was a rookie, he figures, that he has no facial
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Torre met with Johnson and told him, as Johnson knew, that he
would be used as an occasional pinch-hitter. ``Or I might get into
the game in the late innings to steal bases,'' Johnson said. ``I'm
just glad the Yankees called.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Pompoms?
</P>
<P>
   There is a cheerleading convention at the hotel where the
Yankees are staying, and Monday, Derek Jeter poked his head out of
his room to put down a room service tray _ and was spotted by one
of the cheerleaders. After that, a group of cheerleaders from
Clifton, N.J., stood outside his door and did cheers for the
Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
