familiar street message. (Corina Lecca/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- ADROVER-FASHION-1 -- Though
he's six months behind in the rent, Miguel Adrover's creative gifts
are apparently as good as money in the bank. Like his clothes,
which are made largely from donated fabrics and things he can buy
cheaply on the street, like baseball caps and sweatshirts, and
which he stays up nights rubbing with sandpaper until they look
old, Adrover's cluttered basement apartment is proof of just how
far a person can go on nothing. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- April 3, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2 --
The mood was celebratory in the elevator carrying Justice
Department officials and lawyers to their offices following a news
conference where they commented on the federal judge's ruling
Monday which found Microsoft had violated anti-trust laws. David
Boies, with turtleneck, lead attorney for Justice Department in the
Microsoft anti-trust case, with Iowa Attorney General Tom Miller,
second from left; trial attorney Phil Malone, center (with beard);
and Joel Klein, third from right, assistant attorney general,
Anti-Trust Division. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- BBN-METS-PADRES-2 -- In his
first game for New York at Shea Stadium, Derek Bell provided the
Mets one to start their 2000 home season, hitting a tiebreaking
home run in the eighth inning for a 2-1 win Monday over the San
Diego Padres. Bell gave a well-rested Al Leiter (1-0) the win when
he hit the first pitch he saw from Donne Wall (0-1) over the fence
in left-center to break a 1-1 tie with two outs in the eighth.
(Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- BBN-METS-PADRES-1 -- In his
