<P>
   (NYT26) STORRS, Conn. -- April 3, 2000 -- BKW-HUSKIES-HOMECOMING
-- About 5,000 fans turned out for a mid-afternoon rally Monday at
Gampel Pavilion to help the Connecticut Huskies celebrate their
second NCAA championship in five years. The crowd was treated to
the highlights of Sunday night's 71-52 rout of perennial powerhouse
Tennessee. Their frenzy peaked as the team made their way onto the
floor, the scene of so many other victories in the past few years.
(Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- PUENTE-PROFILE-2 -- This
Thursday at Yale, five-time Grammie-winner Tito Puente will be
awarded a Chubb Fellowship honoring him, according to Robert Farris
Thompson, the professor who directs the Chubb, as ``the foremost
exponent of that world-class music, mambo.'' ``I'm a really
creative person,'' said Puente, 77, who likes to use his hands when
he talks. ``I always try to stay up to date. The most difficult
thing is to maintain.'' (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- PUENTE-PROFILE --
Percussionist and band leader Tito Puente, 77, who has won five
Grammies so far in his career, during an interview in a Manhattan
restaurant. This Thursday Puente will be awarded a Chubb Fellowship
for being ``the foremost exponent of that world-class music,
mambo,'' according to Robert Farris Thompson, the professor who
directs the Chubb. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- April 3, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST --
Thomas Penfield Jackson, left, the federal judge overseeing the
Microsoft antitrust trial, and Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft.
Penfield Jackson ruled Monday that Microsoft was guilty of
violating the nation's antitrust laws on every count in the
government's exhaustive suit against the company, a verdict that
was surprising for its sweep. (Susana Raab, left, Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW GOURNA, Egypt -- April 3, 2000 -- EGYPT-ARCHITECT-2
-- New Gourna as the architect Hassan Fathy envisioned it a
half-century ago - before its residents transformed it. Fathy
created vaulted roofs punctured by small openings to direct and
cool the prevailing winds, courtyards to give each owner a
``private piece of sky,'' crooked streets to emphasize the intimacy
of houses, and communal wells to invite neighborly chats. (Aga Khan
Trust for Culture/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- April 3, 2000 -- EGYPT-ARCHITECT-1 -- The
architect Hassan Fathy's original gouache depiction of his romantic
designs for New Gourna, Egypt. A half-century ago the quixotic
architect built New Gourna from scratch, or rather from bricks made
of sun-dried mud and straw. (Aga Khan Trust for Culture/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-SEA-FLOOR-MAPS-3 -- A
new set of maps, which depict the earth as seen from space with no
covering clouds, provide shaded, three-dimensional views of the
geophysical variations that give the planet its unique look. In
addition to the new images, many more topographical maps, like this
one of Lake Erie, can be seen on the National Geophysical Data
Center's Web site. (NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-SEA-FLOOR-MAPS-2 --
Coming to a Web site near you: A new set of color,
computer-generated relief maps depicting the textured surface and
seabeds of the earth on a scale not previously available. The most
significant data relates to the seas, where even the
earthquake-producing fault lines are depicted. The black lines show
fractures in the shifting sea floor. (NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-SEA-FLOOR-MAPS-1 --
Computer-generated maps reveal the heights and depths of the
geophysical earth with more great detail. Dark blues depict the
greatest depths; the reds show the higher elevations. (NASA/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-STAIRS-FITNESS --
Climbing to the top in the urban rat race is taking on new meaning
for many overworked professionals who, surrounded by skyscrapers,
are incorporating stair running into their busy schedules as a
convenient and effective workout. Maggie Kneip, a publishing
executive, thought she had little time for exercise, until she
began sprinting up 10 flights to her office in SoHo. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-PRIVATE-4-COX -- Dr.
Barbara Garces laughs with Juan Andres Stuart near her home in Old
Havana. Stuart fixes and refills cigarette lighters and earns about
three times what Garces makes as a physician. Cuban officials
express confidence that the social changes brewing in their country
and the influence of foreign tourists won't undermine their
socialist ideals. (David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-ECONOMY-5-COX -- Cubans
jump into Havana harbor for a swim near Morro Castle. Ten years
after experts predicted the collapse of the Soviet Union would send
Fidel Castro's communist Cuba to the graveyard of broken socialist
dreams, Havana is bustling with workers, visitors and a tourist
invasion that poses stiff competition for its Caribbean neighbors.
(David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-ECONOMY-4-COX -- Cuban
women in native costumes at Plaza de San Francisco, a cobble stoned
square featuring some of Havana's oldest buildings. The women
charge $1 to pose with tourists. (David Tulis/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-ECONOMY-3-COX -- The
Cuban flag is lowered as the sun sets outside the Hotel Nacional, a
favorite of European tourists. Hopes that the embargo will fall
burn brightly in Havana, from government officials to people on the
streets eager for a flood of American dollars. (David Tulis/The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-ECONOMY-2-COX -- The
sound of jackhammers echoes along the famous seaside walk called
the Malecon as construction crews transform priceless but crumbling
16th-Century buildings into pricey five-star hotels. Ten years
after experts predicted the collapse of the Soviet Union would send
Fidel Castro's communist Cuba to the graveyard of broken socialist
dreams, Havana is bustling with workers, visitors and a tourist
invasion that poses stiff competition for its Caribbean neighbors.
(David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-ECONOMY-1-COX -- Onellia
Rojas Villa, left, and Margarita Perez Rodriguez, behind the
counter in their stall where they sell jewelry to locals for three
to six pesos apiece. Since the collapse of the Soviet Union and the
end of its billions in annual aid to Cuba, the government has
allowed limited private industry and the legalization of U.S.
dollars. But owning one's own business is pricey. The government
charges Rojas Villa and Perez Rodriguez 25 pesos per day for their
stall and 200 pesos per month for a license to sell privately.
(David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-PRIVATE-3-COX -- Since
the collapse of the Soviet Union and the end of its billions in
annual aid to Cuba, day-to-day life for many Cubans has been a
ceaseless grind. Trips to the state-run store to pick up monthly
rations sometimes yield empty shelves, leaving people scrambling to
earn American dollars so they can purchase life's necessities in
markets like these that sell produce at market rates. (David
Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-PRIVATE-2-COX -- Dr.
Barbara Garces laughs with Juan Andres Stuart near her home in Old
Havana. Stuart fixes and refills cigarette lighters and earns about
three times what Garces makes as a physician. Cuban officials
express confidence that the social changes brewing in their country
and the influence of foreign tourists won't undermine their
socialist ideals. (David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HAVANA -- April 3, 2000 -- CUBA-PRIVATE-1-COX -- Felix
Garces, 54, gave up his job as a translator to buy a three-wheeled
bicycle that he converted into a rickshaw-like taxi ferrying
tourists and locals to make about $5 a day. Garces wife, a
physician, makes about $16 a month from the Cuban government.
(David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- April 3, 2000 -- OBIT-PATTON-B&AMP;W -- Frances
Gray Patton, a writer whose short stories appeared in The New
Yorker through four decades and whose works included the popular
1954 novel ``Good Morning, Miss Dove,'' died Tuesday at Duke
University Medical Center in Durham, N.C. She was 94 and lived in
Durham. Patton is seen in a 1954 file photo. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BALTIMORE -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-BIOPSY-ACCURACY --
Biopsies are sometimes wrong, and second opinions are often proper
when cancer is diagnosed. And determining if cancer is present in a
sample of tissue which could be the size of a pinhead is not always
clear cut. The experience and specialty of the pathologist is often
crucial an accurate finding. Dr. Jonathan Epstein, a pathologist at
the Johns Hopkins Hospital, studied biopsy results for people
suspected of having cancer and found seriously flawed diagnoses in
two to three percent of cases. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-FLATOW-NPR -- Ira
Flatow, one of the most influential communicators of science,
during his show on National Public Radio, ``Science Friday.'' The
show is a weekly dialogue with scientists and members of Flatow's
audience of two and a half million listeners who phone in their
questions, ideas and opinions. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- VITAL-SIGNS -- Massages may
make tired athletes feel better, but it does not appear to help
muscles recover from exertion any faster, a study published last
week in the British Journal of Sports Medicine concludes. (Philip
Greenberg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PRINCETON, N.J. -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-PHYSICS-STRINGS
-- In the last few months, new ideas emerging from theoretical
workshops offer some hope of connecting the airy speculations of
superstring theory to reality. Physicists are proposing a revised
view in which at least one of the six extra dimensions expounded in
the theory is vastly larger, large enough perhaps to be indirectly
probed with existing accelerators. Dr. Rayman Symdrum, right,
discusses particle physics at Princeton University with Dr. Lisa
Randall. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-BRODY-HEALTH -- New
warnings have issued on the dangers of piercings. In a recent issue
of Emergency Medicine, a medical magazine, Dr. Charles Stewart of
Colorado Springs and the Dakota Heartland Hospital in Fargo said
various complications that have been known to result from body
piercing include allergic reactions,infections and scarring.
Meredith Lee, manager of Gauntlet, Inc., shows off jewelry used in
body piercing. (Larry Davis/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 3, 2000 -- SCI-DOGS-EVOLVE -- Roger
Spear, a chauffeur with Doggie Style Limousine Service, checks in
on his client Guineviere. After splitting genetically from wolves
around 135,000 years ago, dogs have followed humans through every
step in their cultural and social development. So closely entwined
are the lives of dogs and their owners that a number of
evolutionary biologists argue that dogs and humans have co-evolved.
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
