<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-COLUMN-GRIFFEY04-COX     04-03 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-GRIFFEY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans wished upon a star _ and got one
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Around here, where the Reds became baseball's first
professional team exactly 132 seasons ago, Opening Day is a
religion. Schools unofficially close and so do workplaces. There
are marching bands from the center of town to the ballpark, along
with banners everywhere and a mighty dose of magic.
</P>
<P>
   So this Ken Griffey Jr. thing was almost too much to take for
those already Reds hot. When he trotted into view Monday at Cinergy
Field during pregame introductions, the place exploded with cameras
flashing and voices screaming.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the star from a local high school was back after
an 11-year pitstop with the Mariners, and the ovation wouldn't
stop. According to Jack McKeon, the Reds manager who has seen
slightly more than everything during his 50 years in the game, ``It
gave me chills.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was Ken Griffey Sr., the stoic father, who played on
Cincinnati's Big Red Machine during the 1970s. As a bench coach for
the Reds these days, he leaned against the front railing of the
home dugout while the 55,596 spectators hugged his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little tear in my eye,'' Griffey Sr., said, before his
wife, Alberta, shook her head nearby. She said she had no reaction
to the moment. That's because the stadium's elevator operator was
late in getting her to her section in the stands. Alberta laughed,
before saying, ``I did get to see his first at-bat with the Reds,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Alberta could have missed. It was rather forgettable. So
was Griffey's only other at-bat, before a steady rain ended the
Reds' game against the Brewers in a 3-3 tie after five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, most among the crowd stood in the first inning, when
the Brewers' Steve Woodard induced Griffey Jr. to swing weakly at
two change-ups around a couple of balls. Then, the man of the
moment popped out to third baseman Jose Hernandez with Barry Larkin
at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I nervous?'' Griffey said, who grounded to shortstop in
his other at bat. ``Yeah, I was nervous. If you weren't nervous in
that situation, you'd be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's Griffey Jr.'s situation: Designated Savior for the Reds,
that's all.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the other stuff involving the Reds' resurgence after
nearly a decade of stagnation. They won 96 games last year by
having the manager of the year, the NL Rookie of the Year, and the
executive of the year. And even before Griffey signed for anywhere
between $40 million and $80 million less to play for the Reds
instead of the Mariners, Cincinnati's Opening Day was sold out in 3
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you add Griffey into the mix, you have what former Reds
Hall of Famer Joe Morgan said is the player ``who is doing more for
this franchise in a short time than Johnny Bench and the rest of us
didn't do for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all overwhelming for Griffey Jr., 30, who is only two home
runs shy of 400 along his way to catching Hank Aaron's 755.
</P>
<P>
   Still, although Griffey fields with the grace of Mays and hits
with the flair of Mantle, he doesn't have the power of Mother
Nature. Not yet, anyway. So it rained on Griffey Jr.'s parade, but
all of those soggy screamers couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
