<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-SANDOMIR-TVSPORTS     04-03 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SANDOMIR-TVSPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SELLING OUT HAS NO LIMITS WHEN IT COMES TO BAD
TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The outstanding image of opening day was not Ken Griffey Jr.'s
first at-bat as a Cincinnati Red, Griffey's first putout in center
field for the Reds or the reactions of Ken Griffey Sr. to his son's
first at-bat and putout as a Red.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was Monty Stratton's right prosthetic leg, bent and
shelved inside a display case at Christie's, which plans to auction
the late Chicago White Sox pitcher's wooden limb (along with a
tuxedo, signed ball and minor league uniform) Wednesday as part of
an auction that features Joe DiMaggio memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton's right leg was amputated after an accident he had
while hunting rabbits in 1938. His inspiring struggle to return to
play with the prosthesis after World War II was portrayed in a
popular 1948 film starring Jimmy Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   So, a man posts a 36-23 major league record, valiantly returns
to play minor league baseball on a hinged wooden leg, dies of
cancer in 1982 and his wooden leg (and accompanying ephemera) is
put up for sale for $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tacky mercantilism like this _ and who knows how much even
ickier memorabilia is being sold on eBay _ is not new. Recently,
the late White Sox owner Bill Veeck's wooden leg, a most renowned
prosthesis, sold for $10,000 at a Chicago auction, and Ty Cobb's
dentures sold for $7,500 at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   The DiMaggio items include what is reputed to be the last home
jersey he wore before his retirement (projected to sell for a
minimum of $130,000), one of his last pairs of pinstriped pants, a
driver's license, passport, MasterCard and Screen Actors Guild
card. No Mr. Coffees. If you have $30,000 to spare, how about
buying the Yankee Clipper's gas-powered golf cart?
</P>
<P>
   None of DiMaggio's items were as personal as some of those
removed from a 1997 Mickey Mantle memorabilia auction. Although his
prescription vials, socks and eyeglasses were taken off the block,
a lock of his hair was not.
</P>
<P>
   When Griffey Jr. is old or gone, one can only speculate about
what will be auctioned off from his world. The pen with which he
signed his Reds contract? The socks he wore to the signing? His
first video-game joystick? The cap that, when worn backward,
enraged Buck Showalter when he managed the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, of course, was the star of ESPN's early opening day
coverage. He did not dominate ESPN2's new ``Baseball 2Day'' studio
show, but his presence hovered over the show and the subsequent
rain-delayed Reds-Brewers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Griffey makes no pretense of being Neville Chamberlain,''
Peter Gammons of ``Baseball 2Day'' said. One would hope not. The
former British prime minister appeased Adolf Hitler in 1938 and
played a weak center field.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN showed the standing ovation Griffey received when he was
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Griffey Sr. was seen trying not to beam.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:20 p.m. Eastern time came Junior's first at-bat. At 1:23,
he popped out.
</P>
<P>
   With shock in his voice, ESPN's Jon Miller said during the game
that Barry Larkin's failed attempt to stretch a single to a double
``has taken the bat out of Griffey's hand.'' How disrespectful of
Larkin, on Junior's great day!
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, where ESPN carried the Cubs-Cardinals game, Chris
Berman felt the strange compulsion to apologize when it was
announced minutes before the first pitch that Mark McGwire would
not be playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't something we drummed up,'' Berman said. Berman
seemed to be down on himself for not having divined McGwire's
malady during a pregame chat.
</P>
<P>
   Berman could have simply said: ``McGwire's back hurts. He's out
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury gave Craig Paquette a chance to substitute for
McGwire and prompted Berman to say, ``So it's that famous
Sosa-Paquette home run duel we've anticipated all winter.'' Then
Paquette homered in his first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Long periods of time with Berman require listening to his
onslaught of nicknames, some of them amusing, some of them forced.
The Cubs reliever Andrew ``Quiche'' Lorraine? Todd ``Good
Housekeeping'' Zeile? You decide.
</P>
<P>
   What can be decided is the relief at hearing Ralph Kiner in the
booth for the Padres-Mets game.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment at seeing Shea Stadium on the tube
for the first time this season was spotting the name and logo of
ESuperstars.com, an online company, plastered all over the wall of
the Mets' dugout. No spot in a ballpark is free of advertiser and
sponsor messages.
</P>
<P>
   Had the game been in San Diego, fans would have witnessed how
the Padres made the Sycuan Casino, which is run by Native
Americans, a ``presenting sponsor'' of the team's entire season.
You can hardly go anywhere at Qualcomm Stadium (or on the team's
Web site) without bumping into Sycuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
