<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-DRUGS-OFFICER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COLONEL IS ACCUSED OF DELAY IN REPORTING CRIMES BY HIS WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A U.S. Army colonel who once led the government's
anti-drug campaign in Colombia was linked Monday for the first time
to an international drug-smuggling case in which his wife has
pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The colonel, James C. Hiett, is expected to plead guilty on
April 17 to charges accusing him of failing to advise government
officials as soon as possible that his wife, Laurie Anne Hiett, was
engaged in money laundering, according to court papers filed by an
assistant U.S. attorney, Lee G. Dunst.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation by the U.S. Customs Service, Mrs. Hiett,
36, admitted in January that she had conspired to smuggle more than
$700,000 worth of heroin out of Bogota last year and had flown to
New York at least twice to pick up payments for the drugs. She said
she had hidden the scheme from her husband, who led all U.S.
military activity in the country from July 1998 until August 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told him what I was doing,'' she said in court.
</P>
<P>
   A three-month inquiry conducted last year by the Army Criminal
Investigation Division cleared Hiett, saying he had no prior
knowledge of his wife's crimes. Harvey Perritt, an Army spokesman,
refused to comment Monday on the colonel's case other than to say
that he is still serving as a training officer at Fort Monroe in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Dunst also refused to comment on Hiett's expected guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her plea in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, Mrs.
Hiett said she had shipped six brown paper packages of what she
thought was cocaine from Bogota to New York City. The shipments, in
fact, contained heroin, according to chemical tests.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hiett also told the court that she had flown twice to
Queens to pick up payments for the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Col. Hiett carry a maximum penalty of three
years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
