<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SCENE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S NEIGHBORS APPREHENSIVE ABOUT RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY E. NEVALA  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ As news of the antitrust decision filtered off
the Redmond Microsoft campus Monday, neighboring business people
voiced apprehension about the company's possible dismantling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bum ruling,'' said Dot Chase, a membership
representative at Bellevue Place Club, an exercise facility popular
with Microsoft employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with it. I'm a big supporter of Microsoft.
They've taken the time to do the research, recruit the best people
and develop the best product,'' Chase said. ``I don't think they
should be punished for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good for them if they appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg's Bellevue Cycle manager Anthony Devita said he dreaded
possible changes in software compatibility that may arise if the
company splits as a result of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like things the way they are. I like the standardization,''
said Devita, who uses Microsoft software on his work and home
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared about a break up. I'm afraid we're going to have
the same problems as we did with the phone companies back in the
'80s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer management consultants sipping pints of amber ale
inside Chadfield's Sports Pub in Bellevue were sympathetic to
Microsoft founder Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who worked hard and now a lot of competitors are
trying to bring him down,'' said Mike Riley, a consultant from
Leeds, England, visiting Bellevue on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chopping up the company would be a mistake,'' added David
Jastrebski, a Seattle computer consultant joining Riley for a brew.
``I think this is a good exercise for the U.S. judicial system to
go through but I think divesting is wrong. Microsoft as an entity
has done good things for America. It's given me a job. It's given
lots of people jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up the company will hurt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Microsoft campus in Redmond, employees _ some outside
smoking cigarettes, others jogging across campus _ were
tight-lipped following the announcement, deferring questions to
corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   For others, the news was still too fresh for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a decision? What was it?'' said one employee as he
jogged to his car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
