<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS' KOHN GETS TWO SCARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Winger Ladislav Kohn isn't taking any more chances --
not after what happened to him Saturday and Sunday. Kohn barely
escaped a devastating injury against the Kings when he was hit
between the eyes by the side of Luc Robitaille's skate as the Los
Angeles star was falling down.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to get Kohn talking about learning to play with
a visor over the summer. But that process was speeded up Sunday
when he was hit in the left eye by deflected shot in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that is a sign that I better wear one,'' said Kohn, who
played with a visor on Monday versus Nashville. ``The skate was the
first warning, the puck the second, and I don't want a third
strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohn, who played with a visor in juniors, compares playing with
a visor to wearing glasses, but he said ``it's worth it to save
your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohn's eye was almost completely shut within a half hour of the
accident and he spent the rest of the day icing it and draining the
blood that had accumlated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a very fun day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg insisted that Ducks were not
going to have one eye on the scoreboard Monday, looking for the
Edmonton-San Jose result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not during a game,'' he said of scoreboard watching. ``Our
entire focus has to be on ourselves. If we focus on anything else
it's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Ducks second line of Matt Cullen, Kip Miller and Ted
Donato, which had provided some much needed support for the team's
No. 1 line since Miller was picked up from Pittsburg on Jan. 29,
came into Monday's game having only one Cullen assist to show for
its efforts in the previous four games since the trio combined for
three goals and five points in Anaheim's 5-2 win over the Kings on
March 21. Cullen came into the Nashville game in the midst of a
14-game goal-scoring drought.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nothing comes easy for the Ducks. Heading into Monday's game,
Anaheim had outshot Phoenix and the Kings 57-25 in a stretch of 105
minutes, but the Ducks had to rally from two goals down to beat
Phoenix 4-3 in overtime and lost to the Kings 2-1 despite holding
them without a shot for nearly 24 1/2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks did set a new club record when they held the Kings
without a shot. Anaheim's previous low was two shots allowed.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Ducks signed Colgate University Center Andy McDonald to a
two-year contract. McDonald (5-10, 185) scored 25 goals and 58
points in 34 games in his senior season. He recently was named a
Hobey Baker Award finalist awarded to the top U.S. collegiate
player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
