<HEADER>
A6246 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-LAD     04-03 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT SUSPENDED FOR A GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Regrets? Sure, Kobe Bryant has a few after getting
fined and suspended for his Sunday-afternoon altercation with Chris
Childs of the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But reacting to Childs' head-butt and ``featherweight'' punches
by striking back is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you have to stand up for yourself,'' the Lakers'
dynamic playmaker said Monday. ``I don't think there's anything
wrong with that.I'm not pro-fighting by any means. But if it comes
to that point, you have to do what you gotta do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first fight of Bryant's pro career, and the NBA
responded with a $5,000 fine and a one-game suspension, which will
cost him another $109,756 in missed pay. He'll be home tonight when
the Lakers play the Suns in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA dealt Childs a two-game suspension and $15,000 fine for
starting the fight, which happened at the end of the third quarter
in the Lakers' 106-82 victory at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is sorry he'll miss a game when the Lakers are close to
clinching the best record in the NBA, sorry that backcourt-mate Ron
Harper won't get his planned rest on the injured list and sorry
that rookie guard John Celestand won't get a chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as anything -- since he's being punished anyway --
Bryant regrets not landing his return punch, which missed when
Childs backed up. Bryant was quickly restrained by officials and
was furious as he was escorted away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like to fight that much, you know what I mean?
But if you do get to that point where you want to fight, (begin
ital)fight(end ital). Don't throw a punch and run. That was
frustrating,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant would rather have earned the suspension and fine by
actually connecting -- ``absolutely,'' he said. ``That's just human
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Already one of the NBA's brightest young stars, the 21-year-old
has also been one of its best citizens. He had just one technical
foul on his four-year resume until Sunday and couldn't recall ever
losing his temper in a game, even in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally try to keep a cool head,'' he said, ``but
sometimes things like that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs threw punches after Bryant elbowed him in the head while
running around a pick. Though Childs said Bryant gets away with
such moves often, Bryant said it was unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops,'' said Bryant, who called the elbow ``just part of the
game. It pretty much happens every play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like an intentional thing, to hit him in the face,''
he said. ``It was more like, you make a cut going through when
somebody's holding, you want to get them off of you. The fact that
I hit him in the face was an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bryant's stature around the league has grown, so has the
clutching and grabbing from defenders, teammates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of respect. They have to respect his game,''
Harper said. ``They have to try to get to him and slow him down and
try to take him out of his basketball game. So you're going to see
guys holding, doing all those things now. So it's up to him to
maintain his head and go out and do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Childs just trying to disrupt Bryant's game? ``I don't think
so,''Bryant said. ``I don't think he's that smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates supported Bryant's retaliation, and Shaquille O'Neal
said the NBA shouldn't punish players for defending themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Commissioner) David Stern needs to change the rules,'' said
O'Neal, who was suspended in November for fighting Houston's
Charles Barkley. ``I don't know what you expect him to do when a
person takes two cheap shots to the face. ... They should (allow)
like a two-punch retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant will rejoin the team Wednesday in Oakland, and knows how
he'll spend his day off: ``Sleep. Relax. That's all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while he accepts that his clean-cut image has acquired a
scuff or two (one teammate jokingly dubbed him ``Muhammed Kobe''),
Bryant acknowledged that players have to show they won't be pushed
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has really ever seen that side of me,
except for some of the players in closed practices,'' he said,
``but if somebody's going to push you, you've got to let them know
what the limit is.''
</P>
<P>
   The punishment, Bryant accepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's justified, because violence is not the way,'' he
said. ``We have to somewhat set an example for people who are
watching, for children who are watching, to kind of turn the other
cheek, as hard as it may be. And understand that if you don't do
that, there are going to be consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. PHOENIX
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 7:30 p.m., America West Arena
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KCAL-Channel 9, TNT; KLAC-AM (570) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (62-12) update: The Lakers are going for their 10th
straight win and another historic achievement - they can become the
third team in NBA history to have three double-digit winning
streaks in one season. The 1970-71 Milwaukee Bucks and 1980-81
Philadelphia 76ers are the others.
</P>
<P>
   Suns (48-25) update: They've won nine of their last 11 games,
and showing no dropoff after Jason Kidd's injury, have won their
last three in a row. Kevin Johnson, 34, lured out of retirement,
played for the first time in two years Sunday and logged 18 minutes
in a win at Minnesota. Tonight will be his home debut.
</P>
<P>
   - Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
