<HEADER>
A6375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-OPENER04-COX     04-03 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-OPENER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Griffey reception 'awesome'
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Dave Findlow traveled from Denver to attend Ken
Griffey Jr.'s debut as a Cincinnati Red on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He paid a broker $100 for an Opening Day ticket that the team
sells for $6.
</P>
<P>
   So when rain forced the umpires to suspend play with the
Milwaukee Brewers and Reds tied 3-3 in the fifth inning, Findlow
was not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely mad,'' said Findlow, a Cincinnati native, who
played baseball against Griffey in high school. ``I flew 1,200
miles to see this game. And I have to go home tomorrow morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain spoiled what was supposed to be one of the greatest Opening
Days in Reds' history. A record regular-season crowd of 55,596 _
including Ohio Gov. Bob Taft and U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine _ welcomed
Griffey home with a standing ovation. Reporters from 63 newspapers
and 36 television stations, including ESPN, which broadcast the
game, were on hand to record Griffey's every move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' Griffey said of the reception, ``something I
wasn't expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   But a steady downpour cut Junior's official homecoming short.
Umpires suspended play for good at 6 p.m., three hours after the
grounds crew pulled the tarp over the infield and the players
retreated to the clubhouse. It was the first time in Reds' history
Opening Day was a washout.
</P>
<P>
   Because the game ended in a tie, the Reds and Brewers will play
a complete game today beginning at 7:05 p.m. Fans with ticket stubs
from Monday's game will be admitted for free. No additional tickets
will be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans left Cinergy Field by 4 p.m. Monday, weary of the rain
and convinced play would not resume. They had seen Griffey bat
twice, but he never reached base. He popped out in the first inning
and grounded out in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't doing so hot,'' said Jacob Lindhurst, 12, of
Florence, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't seem to bother Lindhurst or anyone else at
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were expecting too much of him,'' said Pat Courts, a
travel agent from Mason. ``Let him settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey acknowledged he was nervous his first time up and
``swung at bad pitches.'' But he pointed out he has 162 more
regular-season games to go.
</P>
<P>
   With no game to watch and no Griffey home run balls to scramble
for, the several hundred fans who stuck around attempted to amuse
themselves. One young man ran onto the field and did two belly-flop
slides on the puddle-filled John Deere tarp before he was promptly
handcuffed and escorted away by police.
</P>
<P>
   Another attempted the same feat but managed little more than a
stumble and flop before police hauled him away. An hour or so
later, a third man dashed across right field and crawled through
the black tube that is used to roll up the tarp. He, too, was
cuffed and taken away.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of other fans sat in the green seats below the overhang
and shared personal stories about their connection with the famed
Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Ruberg, 10, of Alexandria, Ky., said his father, Dave,
used to baby-sit for Griffey Jr. and occasionally had a tough time
settling the superstar down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once (Ken) was being mean to his younger brother, Craig; he
kept tackling him, so my dad locked him in the garage,'' Curtis
said. (Curtis' uncle and Dave's older brother, Ken Ruberg,
confirmed the story, adding, ``Griffey Jr. was kind of a wild
one.'')
</P>
<P>
   Findlow of Denver recalled the time, as a senior at McNicholas
High School, he hit a shot into right center field against
Griffey's Moeller Crusaders. Griffey, of course, caught it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stole a double from me,'' Findlow said. ``That's my claim
to fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Findlow enjoys watching Griffey more in the
outfield than at the plate. The fact that Griffey didn't smack a
home run or even get a base hit Monday didn't bother Findlow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only one game,'' he said. ``The kid has so much pressure
on him. You just can't expect him to hit a home run (right away).
He's going to be beautiful, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
