<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6380 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR &LR;      04-03 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOTHER OF ALL DOUBLE STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If his father had died at sea and Elian Gonzalez's mother were
waiting for him back in Cuba, we'd have fished the 6-year-old out
of the Atlantic and shipped him back to Havana before his pants
dried.
</P>
<P>
   That finally became clear over the weekend, when lawyers for
Elian's Florida relatives attacked the boy's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, claiming he may be an unfit parent.
</P>
<P>
   After more than four months, we now can stop pretending the case
of young Elian is an argument over the differences between Cuba and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about the virtues of freedom vs. the evils of
communism, or the oppression of Castro vs. the opportunities of
America.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   It begins and ends with the age-old belief that a child's mother
is more important to him than his father, even if the mother is
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe (the father) Juan Miguel is completely under the
gun of the Castro regime,'' said an attorney for Elian's relatives.
``We think they are putting him up to psychological warfare and
tactics against his own son.''
</P>
<P>
   Warfare against his own son? For saying he loves him and wants
him back?
</P>
<P>
   That was over the weekend. Last week, this same lawyer said,
``We fear them (the Immigration and Naturalization Service)
revoking Elian's parole, tearing him from his family and returning
him to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   As if a boy's father is not his family. As if Elian would not be
returning to family, but only to Cuba. To the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine such things being said if we were discussing the
boy's mother?
</P>
<P>
   Would her affection be doubted as much? Would her motives be
questioned as harshly?
</P>
<P>
   Would Cuban activists in Miami be practicing resistance
techniques to keep a child from his mother? Would they be promising
to link arms outside the boy's Florida home to keep Elian from the
woman who gave birth to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not let Elian's civil rights be violated,'' said a
spokesman for the anti-Castro Democracy Movement in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Would the activists be so quick to cite civil rights and ignore
parental rights if Elian's mother were asking that he be returned
to her?
</P>
<P>
   And what about the American media? ABC aired an interview with
Elian without asking permission from the boy's father. An official
at the network said, ``What we put on the air was very tasteful,
very appropriate, very low-key, non-intrusive to Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked why Juan Miguel Gonzalez wasn't consulted
before his son was interviewed, an ABC spokesman said, ``It was a
supervised visit. We did have permission of his custodial guardian
and his attorney, which is what we thought was necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Elian's mother have been so easily dismissed?
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, we assume she did what she thought was best for
herself and for her son when she boarded a rickety boat bound for
the United States last November.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't Elian's father, right or wrong, deserve the same
assumption in wanting his boy back?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cuban President Fidel Castro said that airing a
television interview with Elian without the father's permission was
``monstrous and sickening.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro said the same thing about the way Elian's case has been
handled and about the amount of time a boy has been kept from his
father.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Americans should find even more monstrous, even
more sickening, is that the old dictator is right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0606 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
