<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-TALKS-1STLD     04-03 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE'S DECISION CAME AFTER 4 MONTHS OF UNSUCCESSFUL SETTLEMENT
TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add 500 words, bgng `The Justice Department proposal tried
to address...')  
(With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the four months of settlement talks, Microsoft and the
Justice Department prepared 19 proposals and counterproposals
dealing with fine points of software in the technical parlance of
``source code'' and ``application program interfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives say they were finishing a reply to the
Justice Department's latest offer when the federal judge acting as
mediator halted the talks on Saturday. At that point, the two sides
had moved toward agreement on some elements but were still apart on
others, according to people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department proposal on the table, people familiar
with the discussions said, would have modified a range of
Microsoft's business activities, from its contract deals to sharing
information about its technology more openly with personal computer
makers and software makers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the proposal not only left Microsoft intact but, it seemed,
would not fundamentally alter the way the company does business.
Several of the 19 states joining in the suit protested to the
Justice Department and to the mediator, Judge Richard A. Posner,
that the proposal left Microsoft too many loopholes and lacked
sufficient enforcement mechanisms. And industry executives who were
read a summary said it was too weak to loosen Microsoft's grip on
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said that the states were overreacting and
that the industry executives were not shown all the provisions. But
one person close to the talks characterized the Justice Department
proposal as a ``65 percent solution'' and one that could be
``fairly criticized as not serious enough.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did Microsoft resist it? One key reason is apparently
that Microsoft viewed contract restrictions in the proposal as
limiting its freedom to add new technology freely to its
industry-standard Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives did not discuss precise details of the
confidential settlement talks. But in interviews over the weekend,
Bill Gates, the Microsoft chairman, and William Neukom, the
company's general counsel, repeatedly alluded to that point.
</P>
<P>
   In the antitrust case, the government alleged _ and Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson agreed in his ruling Monday _ that Microsoft
illegally bundled its software for browsing the Internet to its
monopoly product, Windows, to stifle competition from Internet
software. Microsoft denied the charge, saying that it has the sole
discretion to determine what technology is included in its
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental issue in this case was whether we could
support Internet access in Windows,'' Neukom said.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft points to a 1998 federal appeals court decision in
a related case that found that the company could bundle browsing
software into Windows as long as it could make some ``plausible''
claim of consumer benefit or business efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday, Gates noted that ruling and applauded
its sentiment in detailing the stand of principle he insists that
Microsoft is making in continuing to fight the antitrust case in
court. ``We want to be free to put new things into Windows,'' he
said. ``The judiciary should never be involved in designing
software.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates pointed to speech-recognition software as the kind of new
technology that might reasonably be bundled into future generations
of Windows. At present, speech recognition software is an
application product, sold separately, made by companies including
Dragon Systems and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Before Microsoft bundled its browsing software into Windows, the
browser pioneer, Netscape Communications Corp., had a sizable
business in the browser market. But after Microsoft put browsing
into Windows and gave it away free, the separate market for
browsing software withered.
</P>
<P>
   Speech recognition software, say industry analysts and antitrust
experts, may be the next test for Microsoft's bundling strategy.
``The policy goal for the government in a settlement or through
court-ordered remedies is to try to insure that what happened to
Netscape will not happen in another major new product area,'' said
Mark Popofsky, a former Justice Department attorney who worked on
the Microsoft case, and who is now a partner at Kaye Scholer
Fierman Hays &AMP; Handler.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department proposal tried to address that issue in
two ways. First, it sought to encourage consumer choice by allowing
personal computer makers to choose what new features they wanted to
include in Windows by allowing them to take things, like the
browser, off or add new things, like a desktop ``shell'' tailored
for the PC maker's preferred software or Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   But if the PC maker made such changes, it would be responsible
for the costs of technical support of the modified version of
Windows. Microsoft has long maintained that its contracts with PC
makers insisted on a consistent ``look and feel'' to Windows, so as
not to drive up its own costs of giving technical help to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The second provision the Justice Department included in its
proposal to try to free PC makers to choose competing software was
to prohibit Microsoft from writing contracts that forced the
manufacturers to accept an additional Microsoft product as a
condition of receiving Windows, according to people close to the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Again, a key assertion in the antitrust case was that
Microsoft's Windows contracts with PC makers forced such bundling
of the Internet browser and Windows. In short, the Justice
Department proposal told Microsoft that it could add new technology
to Windows, but it could not force PC makers to accept it as a
condition of licensing Windows, which runs the basic operations of
nearly 90 percent of PCs sold today.
</P>
<P>
   Yet apparently, Microsoft regarded that restriction as too
severe. To the company, according to people close to the talks,
that provision in the Justice Department proposal amounted to
getting the government or courts involved in deciding what is and
what is not in a computer operating system. To the government, the
provision was a way of ensuring competition and consumer choice,
its goals in bringing the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the government seeks to increase competition
through restraints on Microsoft's contracts and conduct _ as
opposed to breaking it up _ you are going to get yourself involved
in a line-drawing exercise about what's in the operating system,''
said Robert Litan, a former Justice Department official who is now
at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement talks were limited to so-called conduct remedies
because Microsoft refused to voluntarily discuss breakup proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, of course, is betting that on appeal it can whittle
down Jackson's ruling, so that the final outcome will not support a
breakup or even the kinds of restrictions the Justice Department
was proposing last week. ``We are long-term players in the legal
process,'' Neukom said. ``And we are confident in our legal
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet computer experts had advised Microsoft to settle. A month
ago, Microsoft asked Michael Cusumano, a professor at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Sloan School of Management,
for his advice. ``I just told them to settle and agree to almost
any conduct remedies the government requested, because it wouldn't
change that much in the industry,'' he recalled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0608 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-UCONN-ART-NYT &LR;      04-03 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT WOMEN ARE THE CHAMPIONS BY DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT26 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ By dismantling a once-mighty but obliging
Tennessee team to capture the women's basketball national
championship, the Connecticut Huskies did everything they had done
so well during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, they did it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told these kids all year long that every pass we make in
practice, every cut, every rebound, pretend like it's the one
that's going to win the national championship,'' UConn coach Geno
Auriemma said after his team celebrated its 71-52 victory against
Tennessee in Sunday night's NCAA title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have practiced like this all year long, and the
night that they had to do it, they did it better than any other
time in the season,'' he said. ``And the fact that we did it
against a team as good as Tennessee makes this an accomplishment
all the more worthwhile because I know how hard it is to beat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (36-1) made a shocking spectacle out of the
anticipated rubber match, capping a near-perfect season with a
flawless performance. They avenged their only loss of the season,
which came at home against Tennessee, by sticking to their
steamrolling mentality while adopting the Lady Vols' trademark
defense as their own.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening minutes, UConn executed the fast break like a
practice drill and spun the Lady Vols silly on backdoor cuts. And
with Tennessee's shooting guard, Kristen Clement, sidelined with a
severely sprained ankle, the Huskies took advantage of the
situation. They were able to trap the Lady Vols' young guards into
26 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut also frustrated Tamika Catchings, the nation's best
collegiate player, in limiting her to six shots. While the rest of
the Lady Vols missed easy baskets, Connecticut missed nothing, or
at least it seemed that way. The Huskies shot 50.8 percent from the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   And as they have done all season, the Huskies overwhelmed their
opponent with a deep arsenal of talent from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Such an imbalance made for bad theater, but that might have been
the only failing on a night when the Huskies could do no wrong.
They started the season at No. 1 and ended it in the same lofty
place.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and Tennessee (33-4) split the home-and-home series
in the regular season, with Tennessee taking the most recent game
in Storrs, Conn., when the Huskies relinquished a 14-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   They were not giving away anything Sunday night; Shea Ralph
would not let them. Connecticut's redshirt junior willed her team
to the title, flashing an ``out of my way'' glare. Ralph was
determined to make those excruciating six-hour sessions of
rehabilitating her knees mean something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked so hard over these past two or three years and I
haven't wanted anything as badly as I wanted it tonight,'' Ralph
said after leading the Huskies with 15 points, six steals and seven
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph's all-American teammate, Svetlana Abrosimova, contributed
14 points, while the 6-foot-5-inch center Kelly Schumacher had nine
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   All three players are juniors. Point guard Sue Bird, the magical
ingredient in UConn's chemistry this season, is a sophomore. So are
the post players Swin Cash, Asjha Jones and Tamika Williams. The
senior forwards Stacy Hansmeyer and Paige Sauer will graduate this
year, but the Huskies will hardly notice. What is more, UConn will
bring in four of the nation's top freshmen next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think next year it's going to be even better because we know
that we won a national championship, so we just have to repeat
that,'' Abrosimova said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut won its first title since the 1995 team went 35-0
and also beat Tennessee for the crown. That year the Huskies used
seven players; this year, they went with 10 and they will only get
deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee returns all of its starters as well, including
Catchings and Clement. Without Clement, who averaged 5.6 points a
game, the Lady Vols lacked experience and emotion in the title game
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would that have changed the outcome of this game?'' Tennessee
coach Pat Summitt said. ``I can't say that that would have
happened. She's been our best defender on the perimeter. When we
started I thought it really affected our press offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, Summitt bore a resigned look on the
sideline. Her team was self-destructing, much as it did in a
blowout loss to Georgia earlier this season, and she could not stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   Catchings did not score the first of her 16 points until there
were four minutes left in the first half. By then the game was
already over. Semeka Randall hit only one of her 11 shots. No one
played defense.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Summitt, upset with her team's embarrassing
performance, privately apologized to people who had followed the
team all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game doesn't mean your program is falling apart or that
you can't be competitive at this level,'' she said. ``We are not
going away. I'm certainly not on my way out and we'll be back here,
hopefully, again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and Connecticut will renew their rivalry _ UConn leads
it by 6-5 _ with another home-and-home series next season.
</P>
<P>
   The championship was hyped as a potential groundbreaking event,
pitting the top two teams in the country. But the final had no
cosmic significance. It was simply a game won by a team far better
than any other right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the people at ESPN would have much preferred a
double-overtime game won on a 3-pointer at the buzzer, and I
apologize for that,'' Auriemma said, half-seriously. ``The game
itself does need more great rivalries. Connecticut-Tennessee is
one. It needs more.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the second-best team in the nation cannot contest
Connecticut, then perhaps parity in the women's game will take
longer to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the beginning of anything and this isn't the end of
anything,'' Auriemma said. ``I'd like to look at this as the
continuation of the growth of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-03-00 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000403.0609 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-DUVAL-MASTERS-TEX     04-03 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-MASTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL SAYS HE'S FIT FOR A MAJOR BREAKTHROUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Outsiders examine David Duval's new look _
chiseled upper body, tapered waist, collarless shirts _ and see a
player in transition, grasping at another straw in an effort to
close the gap on Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   They peruse Duval's playing record, which shows a full calendar
year between PGA Tour victories, and sense a slump for the No. 2
player in the world golf rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Both observations are based on fact. But Duval said the
conclusions are faulty.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares for Thursday's opening round of the Masters
Tournament, Duval said he feels just as confident about winning as
he did a year ago. Maybe more so, Duval added, because he is not
worn down from off-course scrutiny that seemed to short-circuit his
game shortly after surpassing Woods _ for a brief stretch in 1999 _
as the game's top-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have some very big things ahead of me the next few
weeks,'' Duval said. ``I don't know how you quantify it. But
physically and mentally, I am right there. I feel very good about
myself and my golf. I just need a good break here or there. Maybe
that one last putt falling for me that really turns it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, 28, had all the momentum on his side heading into the
1999 Masters. He had won two consecutive tournaments and captured
11 titles in 34 starts before finishing a distant sixth at Augusta.
A year later, Duval is riding an 0-for-22 stretch into Masters
week. In some ways, he surmised, that might be more blessing than
curse.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after finishing five strokes behind winner Jose Maria
Olazabal at the 1999 Masters, Duval began withdrawing from events _
including the MasterCard Colonial _ because he felt ``burned out.''
Contrast that to last month, when he was a surprise, last-minute
entry in the 2000 Doral-Ryder Open despite making a cross-country
flight during tournament week. Duval said a rigorous conditioning
program, coupled with a fat-free diet and a self-imposed ban on
chewing tobacco, has given him a fresh outlook and greater energy
in his ongoing Tiger chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see how fit I could get,'' said Duval (6-foot, 180
pounds), whose body fat-ratio has dropped into single digits since
November. ``I figured it would help my golf to get stronger, but
this is about so much more than golf. It's about self-discipline. I
told myself, `If I can do something like this, I can do a lot of
other things.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He might not have a victory this season, but Duval ranks seventh
on the money list ($1,006,205). He is tied for second with Woods
among tour players in greens in regulation (73.8 percent) and is
third behind Woods and Hal Sutton on the charts in ball-striking, a
new statistic that blends distance and accuracy variables. The
biggest thing keeping Duval out of the winner's circle has been a
balky putter. He ranks tied for 56th among peers in putting (1.765
average per green in regulation), as opposed to first at this
juncture last season (1.677).
</P>
<P>
   But the putting, he said, has rounded into shape in recent weeks
and all systems point toward liftoff at Augusta. Despite the
victory drought, Woods said Duval is ``far from slumping ... He's
just not getting any breaks to fall his way right now. We all go
through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval said he has made peace with negative feedback he received
from fans and U.S. captain Ben Crenshaw for adopting a pay-for-play
stance before the 1999 Ryder Cup. Eventually, a compromise was
reached and PGA of America officials, organizers of the Ryder Cup,
agreed to donate $200,000 to charities of each participant's
choosing.
</P>
<P>
   In part to repair his image from the Ryder Cup flap, Duval made
a series of humorous commercials for AT&AMP;T and Charles Schwab that
play off his dry wit. He counseled with a media consultant. He
changed his look. But inside, Duval said he's still the same guy
who believes honesty is the only policy when dealing with other
people. Given another opportunity to tackle the pay-for-play issue
in advance of the Ryder Cup, Duval said, he wouldn't change
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you ask my opinion, I give it to you. I am not going to
tell you something I don't think,'' Duval said. ``I don't have a
problem with people who differ with my opinion. That is what life
is all about, learning from people with varying points of view ...
To be lambasted for having a different opinion than the majority, I
find that kind of strange. That has hurt me, but I don't hold
grudges.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believed he had won back the majority of golf fans,
Duval shrugged and made a sweeping motion with his hand toward
reporters in the interview room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that everybody in this room probably likes me.
But you're not ever going to get in a room where everybody likes
you, unless it's at your own birthday party,'' Duval said. ``I
think all my relationships, with the fans included, are going to
continue to change and grow and evolve.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true with his chest measurement, waistline and
clothing choices. The benefits of his new physique, Duval conceded,
might be lost on outsiders who focus only on the fact that Woods
has won 10 times at PGA Tour events since the 1999 Masters, while
he has remained winless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much of a rivalry right now, is there?,'' Duval
said, laughing. ``There's no question in anyone's mind that Tiger
is the best player in the world right now. But it's not like he's
on another, unreachable level. I'm not that far behind him. And, in
golf, things have a way of changing in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 2000 season, change has been par for the course for
David Duval. During Masters week, he'd like to change his status as
the top-ranked player in world golf rankings without a major
championship.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
