<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW, OLD MAKES FOR POTENT RANGERS OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Can I change my MVP vote now?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, c'mon, I really meant to say that Pudge Rodriguez would
repeat as American League MVP. That Manny Ramirez thing, that must
have been a typo.
</P>
<P>
   OK, if not Pudge, how about putting me down for Gabe ``The
Babe'' Kapler? You'll at least let me get away with that much,
won't you?
</P>
<P>
   And Cy Young? Somehow Kenny Rogers didn't strike out a single
batter Monday and still managed to look unbeatable. Forget about
Pedro Martinez and Roger Clemens. ``The Gambler's'' back and he's
bad.
</P>
<P>
   It was Opening Day at The Ballpark in Arlington on Monday, which
is kind of like Christmas and New Year's Eve and Halloween all
rolled into one, and the Texas Rangers gleefully took the wraps off
a team that had six new faces in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   There was something old (Rogers), something new (Kapler) and
something blue (Rodriguez) for the White Sox as the Rangers treated
a record-shattering crowd of 49,322 to a rousing 10-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler and Rodriguez each homered twice and Rogers had the
frustrated White Sox pounding the ball into the ground for eight
solid innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was everything I wanted and more,'' said Rogers, back in
a Rangers uniform for the first time since leaving as a free agent
after the 1995 season. ``This was everything we needed as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense was explosive and just kept pouring it on, too.
That's a sign of a good offense. We got up 4-1 or whatever but the
guys didn't let up. They kept swinging the bats good and driving in
runs. As a pitcher, you love that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers did his part with a sinker that had more bite than a
rattlesnake. He notched 17 groundball outs as a strong infield
defense, led by shortstop Royce Clayton and third baseman Tom
Evans, turned four double plays behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Kenny was in command,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``When he needed the double play he got it.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he needed runs, he got those, too, thanks mostly to
Kapler and Rodriguez, who took turns battering White Sox starter
Mike Sirotka.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler introduced himself to Rangers' fans with a solo home run
in the second. Rodriguez snapped a 1-1 tie in the third with a
three-run homer off the left-field foul pole on a pitch that broke
Sirotka's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was thigh-high cut fastball,'' Sirotka said, shaking his
head. ``I make my living with that pitch against righties, and not
many can do what he did with that pitch, hit it hard and keep it
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler drilled a second homer to left in the fourth and
Rodriguez belted another, a two-run shot, in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   If this was Rodriguez's opening salvo in defense of his American
League MVP crown, it was an auspicious beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just seems to add something to his game every year,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always telling myself every year, I want to do better
numbers,'' said Rodriguez, whose .332 average, 35 homers and 113
runs batted in earned him his first MVP award in 1999. ``That's the
attitude I have this year again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who thought Rodriguez had simply had a career year last
year might have to think again. The best, hitting coach Rudy
Jaramillo predicted, is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's had his best season yet,'' Jaramillo said.
``He's got such great hand-eye coordination, plus he's so strong in
his hands, wrists and forearms and he's got great legs. His
conditioning has taken him to where he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has the type of year he had last year, it's great, but
he and I are shooting for a better year. He wants to hit 40 home
runs without going out there trying to hit 40 home runs. He's going
to hit over .300 and we want his RBI production to go up, his runs
scored to go up. He still has potential for his whole game to go up
and that's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is, but Rodriguez was among those in the Rangers'
clubhouse lining up to say that Monday's victory wasn't about
individual accomplishments. It was a team thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with (what he did in Monday's) game,''
Rodriguez said, ``but it's more important that we go home with a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, that theme echoed from the interview room to the
Rangers' clubhouse. From Rodriguez, to Kapler, to Rogers to Oates.
What we're seeing is a team coming together just as the starting
gun fires. The timing couldn't be more perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it all spring, don't sell these guys short, they may
be a little better than what a lot of people are expecting,'' Oates
said. ``It was fun watching them get after it today. We're going to
be a fun team to watch and that's not just one win talking. I've
been saying that all spring.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about it: The fun has just begun; 161 more to go.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
