<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: THOSE VOLATILE TECHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change 14.8 to 16.3 in 7th graf; INSERTS new 11th graf,
bgng `It used to be...'; CHANGES $506 billion to $527 billion in
12th graf.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't just Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index endured one of its worst days ever
Monday, as technology stocks broadly sold off. The decline, of 7.6
percent, was the worst daily performance for the index since the
summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which is just one of the 4,827 stocks in the Nasdaq
composite but makes up 8.5 percent of the value of the index, was
responsible for only about one-sixth of the record 349.15-point
decline. Its shares fell $15.375, to $90.875 _ shaving $80 billion
off the company's market value _ as investors waited for the ruling
that the company had violated antitrust laws, a ruling made after
the end of regular trading.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nasdaq wipeout was far broader than Microsoft. Of the
100 stocks in the Nasdaq 100 _ generally the largest companies in
the Nasdaq composite index _86 fell in value. They included some of
the highest fliers heretofore, like Cisco Systems, which for a time
last month was the most valuable company in the country, and
Qualcomm, the mobile phone technology company that is now down
nearly 30 percent from the peak it reached in the first trading day
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it was the fifth-worst day ever for the index, measured
by percentages, trailing just the 8.6 percent fall of Aug. 31,
1998, and three days during the 1987 stock market crash. The 1998
fall came amid worry that the world's financial system was
crumbling, and the 1987 falls came as the entire American stock
market seemed to be collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Monday's move came on a day when many stocks were
doing quite well, thank you. The Dow Jones industrial average
leaped 2.7 percent Monday _ and would have been up 3.7 percent had
it not been weighed down by the changes Dow Jones made last
November, when it added Microsoft and Intel to the list.
</P>
<P>
   Just what the Nasdaq plunge means _ or whether it means much of
anything at all _ is not easy to analyze because volatility in the
Nasdaq market has been running at record levels this year, and big
falls have often been followed by equally large rebounds. The
Nasdaq composite is down 16.3 percent from the peak it reached
March 10. But it is still up 3.8 percent since the end of last
year. The Dow, by contrast, is up 13 percent since March 10, but is
down 2.4 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of opposite movement for the Dow and the Nasdaq is far
from common. The Nasdaq index, which dates back to 1971, has seen
41 daily declines of at least 3 percent prior to this year. The Dow
had declined on 40 of those days, the only exception being on Oct.
20, 1987, the day after the worst day of the 1987 crash. That
exception reflected not so much investor sentiment about the
relative weakness of the Nasdaq issues but a quirk of the previous
day. The decline in Nasdaq the day before had been smaller than the
Dow's because many of the brokers that made Nasdaq markets chose
not to answer their phones, and thus kept reported prices
artificially high.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Nasdaq has gyrated wildly this year, the Dow has
often moved to a different drummer. Of the 11 days in 2000 on which
the Nasdaq has fallen at least 3 percent, four of them have seen
the Dow go up.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, it appears that the new-economy stocks that
zoomed last year and early this year are falling. Meanwhile, the
old-economy stocks that did not rise much if at all last year and
early in 2000 are gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that when panic struck equity investors they
bailed out of stocks in general, putting money into cash. But these
days it appears that they are more likely to buy other stocks
instead. The belief in technology stocks is being challenged, but
not the faith overall in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, which rose $5.375 to $161 Monday, is again the
most valuable company in the land, with a market value of $530.5
billion, compared with $527 billion for Cisco and $473 billion for
Microsoft, according to Bloomberg Financial Markets. A week ago, GE
was in third place.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is among the most widely held stocks in the country,
both in individual portfolios and in mutual funds. But the extent
to which holders were hurt Monday depended largely on what else was
held. Diversified funds with many large stocks were not badly
damaged, while funds concentrated in technology stocks were. The
Fidelity Magellan Fund, for which Microsoft was the largest holding
at last report, was off just 0.3 percent Monday, in part because
General Electric was the fund's second-largest holding. But the
Fidelity OTC Portfolio and the Fidelity Select Technology Fund, for
which Microsoft was also the largest holding, fell 7.8 and 9.2
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The easy-come, easy-go nature of this market is illustrated by
the PBHG Technology and Communications Fund, which fell 13.6
percent Monday. At its peak on March 9, the fund was up 71.5
percent from the end of 1999. Now its gain for the year has been
cut to 7.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
