<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' ROGERS DELIGHTS IN MORE HOME COOKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Kenny Rogers was 19-6 with a 3.34 earned-run
average at The Ballpark in Arlington before this year, including a
perfect game in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   So it's only natural that, after a four-year hiatus, he was
happy to don a Texas Rangers home uniform again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be back here,'' Rogers said. ``I was comfortable
in this park before, and knew I would be again.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Rogers is comfortable in just about any park he calls
home.
</P>
<P>
   By holding the Chicago White Sox to one run on six hits in eight
innings of the Rangers' 10-4 Opening Day victory Monday, he won his
19th consecutive game in his home park, tying him with Frank Viola
for the third-longest home winning streak in major-league history,
one behind Lefty Grove and four behind Ray Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're comfortable at home, that makes a difference,''
Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   The streak started on Sept. 7, 1997, four seasons and three
teams ago, when he pitched for the New York Yankees and defeated
Baltimore. He was traded to the Oakland Athletics in the
off-season, and won all 11 decisions at Network Associates Coliseum
over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Oakland the first year, it wasn't a coincidence,'' he
said. ``I pitched well just about every time out, and could have
won more games.''
</P>
<P>
   It continued last season, when he won four home starts for the
A's and then, after an August trade to the New York Mets, earned
victories in his two decisions at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a little bit of a fluke,'' Rogers said. ``I had
a couple of games I should have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad outings came in no-decisions. In the 19 victories, his
ERA is 1.56. He hasn't always dominated in the streak; he has only
struck out more than five batters four times. But he has been
efficient, just as he was against the White Sox on Monday when he
got four double-play grounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some pitches on the corner, kept the breaking balls
and changeups down, moved the fastball in and out,'' Rangers
catcher Ivan Rodriguez said. ``He kept the ball down, and made them
hit it on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the streak continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's there, but I don't focus on that at all,'' Rogers
said. ``I know some day that streak will come to an end, but
hopefully not for a long time.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
