<HEADLINE>
LACK OF PATIENCE COSTS WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-PATIENCE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The message written in black Sharpie and
pinned to the bulletin board in the visitors' clubhouse went
largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The pregame schedule for the Chicago White Sox offered sound
advice for opposing Texas Rangers left-hander Kenny Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be patient,'' it read. ``He doesn't like to get deep in
count.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what happened on Opening Day?
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox took ``some very young swings'' in the estimation
of manager Jerry Manuel, and Rogers required only 88 pitches to
complete eight innings during the Rangers' 10-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers failed to throw a first-pitch strike to 11 of the first
14 batters, and the White Sox squandered multiple hitters' counts.
Only four of the first 14 batters reached safely, and Rogers erased
three from the basepaths by inducing double-play ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox's failures during their first three at-bats
established a pattern for the remainder of the afternoon. The
swings by second baseman Ray Durham and shortstop Jose Valentin on
2-1 pitches resulted in ground-ball outs, and first baseman Frank
Thomas also grounded out on a 3-0 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a fastball away there,'' Thomas said. ``He
sunk one down and in on me, and I had already committed. That's a
veteran for you. He doesn't get bothered on 3-and-0 and 3-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox designated hitter Paul Konerko grounded into a
second-inning double play on a 1-0 pitch after right fielder
Magglio Ordonez reached on a five-pitch walk. Durham hit a weak fly
ball to left field on a 3-2 pitch during his third-inning at-bat
after working the count to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we helped him out wouldn't be giving him the credit he
deserves,'' said Konerko, who also hit a routine fly ball on a 2-0
pitch during his fifth-inning at-bat. ``I think we were a little
overanxious all day, but he made some good pitches, too. He's a
smart pitcher, and I think he took advantage of us being
overanxious on Opening Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 27 of Rogers' 54 pitches were strikes through four innings,
but the White Sox produced only one run _ and it scored on a
double-play ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Rogers pitched a good game,'' Thomas said. ``He really
changed speeds well, worked in and out and kept us off balance. It
was the seventh inning before we knew it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
