<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-RADIOACTIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT COLUMBIA, QUESTIONS LINGER OVER A RADIOACTIVE STAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mystery writer might call it ``The Pillow Case.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months after officials from Columbia University began
investigating a stain of radioactive material that a graduate
biology student said she found on her pink pillow, questions
persist about how and why the contamination occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The university says that evidence shows the student, Yao Cheng,
intentionally tainted her pillow with the material, phosphorus-32,
as part of a convoluted plan to shift from graduate studies in
biology to the business school. Cheng was expelled last month. The
city Health Department concurred with the technical findings,
although it did not venture a motive.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng says she is innocent and has complained about the
university's disciplinary procedures that led to her expulsion. She
has appealed her expulsion, but if that fails _ a ruling is
expected in the next few days _ she may lose her student visa and
be forced to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   No one was harmed, but city health officials said it was the
first time they could recall that radioactive material left a
restricted laboratory in the city and, potentially, exposed the
public to contamination. Given the small amount of phosphorus-32
involved _ a few drops _ only someone who slept on the bed
repeatedly would have been at risk, radiation experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Cheng took a Geiger counter home to her apartment
and, she has said, found the material on the pillow. Cheng and her
husband told university officials they had no idea how the stain
had gotten there.
</P>
<P>
   An intensive investigation began and the university's radiation
safety officers quickly concluded that the stain was too
concentrated to have been an accidental smear. They said that it
had to have been put on the pillow intentionally, and that there
was no suspect other than Cheng.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Lei Liu, a doctoral candidate in computer science,
was also investigated, but he was exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Both students are from China and met while studying at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng and her husband said that she had no opportunity, under
the university's disciplinary system, to challenge the
investigators' assertions, offer evidence or be present to question
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week in the couple's apartment, Liu said he
and his wife were shocked at how the hearings had been handled.
``In this country, we thought you have a chance to see witnesses,
to ask questions,'' Liu said. ``That may be true in court, but not
at this school.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several dozen Columbia students, mostly from China,
demonstrated outside the school's administrative offices in the Low
Memorial Library, saying that the case has been handled unfairly
and that Cheng was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia officials declined Monday to comment on the case,
saying only that the appeal was still being considered.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal officials who track radiation incidents,
the case is one of only a handful in recent years in which
phosphorus-32 has left a licensed laboratory and potentially
exposed someone to radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident, Columbia has installed locks on the
refrigerators and freezers in which phosphorus-32 and other
radioactive research materials are stored. Until this year, the
university, like most other institutions using isotopes, had
required licensed personnel to monitor the use of the substances,
but had not tightly restricted access to them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The report filed by the investigative committee asserts that
interviews conducted with Cheng indicated that she was unhappy in
the biology program. It speculated that she might have thought that
if she became contaminated with radioactivity, she would not be
able to do further work in the science labs, because federal
regulations set an annual limit for allowable exposure.
</P>
<P>
   In the interviews, according to the report, Cheng suggested that
it might be necessary to transfer to a different degree program.
</P>
<P>
   George Hamawy, the university's radiation safety officer, wrote
in the report: ``I asked her what would she do if we find out that
she received a large exposure dose. Her answer came fast, that she
would change her major. I inquired further about that. She revealed
that if we find out that she received a large dose, she would not
stay in the Biology Department, with a potential of further
exposure, but she would change her major to a school such as the
Business School.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges were filed, even though the removal of the
dangerous substance from the laboratory violated state licensing
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Levy, a lawyer who is representing the couple, said
the university's case against Cheng was largely circumstantial. He
said Cheng's predicament was made more difficult by the
university's disciplinary rules, under which a student can base an
appeal only on the mishandling of an investigation _ not on the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that dean's office at Columbia is giving this an
objective look,'' he said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
