<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-SPI &LR;      04-03 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES MICROSOFT VIOLATED ANTITRUST LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN,  
 DAN RICHMAN and KATHY MULADY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The decision in round two, like round one of what
could be a very long and bruising Microsoft Corp. antitrust bout,
on Monday went to the federal and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of almost no one, U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson ruled that Microsoft violated the Sherman
Antitrust Act as well as the laws of 19 states that also sued the
Redmond, Wash., software maker.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the ruling at the end of trading Monday, investors
hammered Microsoft's stock all day long, slicing $80 billion off
the market value of the company. The stock fell $15.38, to close at
$90.88. Trading more than 132 million shares, the battering helped
drag the Nasdaq composite index to its biggest point loss ever; the
7.6 percent plunge was the fifth-worst one-day drop.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's losses also trimmed about $35 billion from the hands of
people in the Seattle area, where roughly 40 percent of the
company's stock is held. Even so, reaction ranged from concern that
one of the nation's most successful companies was being reined in,
to hope that a vicious predator's hurtful business practices would
be curbed.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that happens is to be determined in a ruling _ now
expected sometime this summer _ on remedies and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, still protesting the strength of its legal case, on
Monday promised to appeal the ruling, stressing a 1998 U.S. Court
of Appeals decision that affirmed its right to support the Internet
in its Windows operating system. The appeal, though, would have to
come after any ruling on remedies by Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   William Neukom, Microsoft's executive vice president for law and
corporate affairs, said Microsoft expects an expedited review of
its appeal could produce a decision within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom said the ``broad-based'' appeal will contest the
procedure of the case as well as the application of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the middle innings of this lawsuit,'' Neukom said.
``We like our prospects very much in the later innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the game may not be over, the decision immediately
subjects the software maker to increased exposure from private
lawsuits which can base their arguments of harm to consumers and
competitors on Jackson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had been expected to rule against the company since his
findings last November concluded, after an 11-month trial, that
Microsoft was a monopoly and had harmed consumers. His description
of the company Monday was harsh.
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft placed ``an oppressive thumb on the scale of
competitive fortune. ... Microsoft's anticompetitive actions
trammeled the competitive process through which the computer
software industry generally stimulates innovation and conduces to
the optimum benefit of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a conclusion of law. The next step is to decide
what penalties and remedies he might assess against Microsoft.
Those could include at least seven options from radically
restructuring or breaking up the company to assessing fines and
placing limitations on Microsoft's business practices and the
products it sells.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came after four months of settlement talks, from
which emerged 19 proposals and counterproposals. By Saturday,
though, agreement had been reached on some points, but not others,
when the talks were halted.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling quickly followed, as he had threatened
throughout the talks. Microsoft had violated the 110-year-old
federal antitrust law, which prohibits efforts to restrain trade or
attempting to monopolize markets, as well as state antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys general who have pushed the case hailed the ruling
as a victory for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we've been vindicated,'' said Iowa Attorney General
Tom Miller. ``Consumers were harmed in terms of choice, innovations
they would have had and perhaps in price.''
</P>
<P>
   The states declined to get into specifics about what they will
recommend to Jackson. Miller said a settlement is still a
possibility, although he added that any agreement ``has to be
substantial and it has to address competition.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Microsoft officials said the company still is open
to a settlement, but they have steadfastly opposed any effort to
split up the company.
</P>
<P>
   That's the only solution, according to Ralph Nader, a prominent
critic of Microsoft, who said Monday that leaving Microsoft intact
would require ``an army of law enforcement officials to monitor
this global economy.'' His sentiments were echoed by some in the
software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Barksdale, former chief executive of archrival Netscape
Communications Corp., said the ``most effective way to restore
competition is through a structural remedy or a breakup of
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said the breadth and
thoughtfulness of Jackson's research ``puts Microsoft in a bind''
and leaves little room for success on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ruling ``definitely keeps a shadow on the stock,'' he
said. ``I don't think it keeps the stock from performing. It just
slows it down.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Jackson said that Microsoft broke the law by
unlawfully tying its browser, Internet Explorer, to its Windows
operating system by maintaining its monopoly position in operating
systems through anticompetitive means, and attempting to monopolize
the Web browser market.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did decline to find Microsoft in violation of antitrust
laws on a third issue: exclusive arrangements with computer makers
calling for placement of Internet Explorer and shutting out
Netscape Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson ruled that Microsoft went out of its way to discourage
computer manufacturers from including Netscape Navigator on their
machines and to keep Internet access providers from generating
browser usage for its rival's browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft was truly inspired by a genuine concern for
maximizing consumer satisfaction, as well as preserving its
substantial investment in a worthy product, then it would have
relied more on the power of the very competitive PC market, and
less on its own market power, to prevent (computer makers) from
making modifications that consumers did not want,'' Jackson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also said he is concerned that not only has Microsoft
maintained a monopoly position in one market, for operating
systems, it has used predatory tactics to attain monopoly power in
a second market for Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives took sharp exception to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-technology industry that Microsoft has helped create
has unleashed a wave of competition and innovation that has led to
new, more powerful products for consumers, at lower prices than
before,'' said Chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ballmer, Microsoft's chief executive officer, said the
company's ``intense focus on moving forward has sometimes been seen
as threatening.'' But he added, ``We're supposed to work hard on
new innovations. The industry would not be better if we didn't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Neukom also mentioned an issue that Microsoft has raised before
and on which some in the software industry are equally uneasy about
_ the government dictating what features should be in software.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the appeals court already has ruled, it is a mistake for
government regulators or the courts to try to design
high-technology products,'' he said. ``Government regulation of
software product design would surely slow innovation and harm
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did note in his ruling that he has been overruled once
before on the issue of combining a browser with an operating
system. But he said Microsoft's bundling of Windows and Internet
Explorer was done not from technical necessity or efficiency but in
an attempt to quash competition, and he believes his ruling is
consistent with Supreme Court opinions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another issue looming over the entire case is whether
changes in technology and the market will render any decision moot
by the time it's final. Microsoft raised that point during the
case, citing the acquisition of Netscape by America Online. Iowa's
Miller, asked if a protracted fight might play to Microsoft's
advantage, said that was one reason for considering a settlement,
but he also said not all of Jackson's proposed remedies might be
stayed while an appeal is heard.
</P>
<P>
   The case has already dragged on for 10 years in judicial and
administrative proceedings that began with a 1990 Federal Trade
Commission probe into whether the company monopolized the operating
systems market.
</P>
<P>
   The initial probe ended three years later with the commission
unable to reach a conclusion, but was re-ignited by the Justice
Department the same year in a separate investigation pushed by many
of Microsoft's competitors including Sun Microsystems and Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, seemed to end in 1994 when Microsoft agreed not to
tie one product to another but kept the right to ``integrate''
products.
</P>
<P>
   It was that integration of the Microsoft browser that led to the
current case.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of those investigations and lawsuits,
Microsoft's value has risen nearly a hundredfold at its peak in
late December. And the impact of this latest ruling for investors
is likely to be only temporary, one analyst said Monday
</P>
<P>
   Scott McAdams, president of Seattle investment firm McAdams
Wright Ragen Inc., said Microsoft stock is likely to remain
``beleaguered'' for a few weeks until investor attention shifts
from the court case to earnings and new product introduction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
