<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT ASKS COURT TO STRIKE DOWN TEXAS' SYSTEM OF ELECTING JUDGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two public interest groups Monday asked a
federal court to strike down the money-riddled system of electing
state judges, contending that it violates Texans' right to fair and
impartial courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The suit doesn't propose an alternative way to pick judges, but,
if successful, it would force the Legislature to impose a new
system before the 2002 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has become notorious across the country as a state where
`justice is for sale,''' said Tom ``Smitty'' Smith of Public
Citizen Inc., one of the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The millions of dollars given to judges and judicial candidates
by lawyers and other special interests violates due process by
undermining the appearance of neutrality among judges, according to
the petition.
</P>
<P>
   It was filed in U.S. district court by Public Citizen, the Gray
Panthers and five individual Texas lawyers. Public Citizen is a
nonprofit corporation founded by consumer advocate Ralph Nader. The
Gray Panthers is concerned primarily with issues affecting senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges must not only be impartial, but appear so, in order to
engender respect for and obedience to the law,'' said Fred Lewis,
an attorney for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The suit notes that Texas judges aren't even required to step
down from cases involving political contributors. As a result, it
points out, a survey found that 83 percent of Texans _ including
many judges _ believe that campaign contributions have a
significant effect on judicial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other states have partisan elections for judges, but Texas
is the only state with partisan elections in which a judge is
permitted to solicit donations from lawyers and clients, including
those with cases before the judge, the plaintiffs said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas courts, particularly the Texas Supreme Court, for years
have been at the center of a partisan and philosophical war fueled
by campaign contributions. Consumers and plaintiffs' lawyers, on
one side, have been pitted against doctors, businesses and
insurance companies on the other.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes`` has done two shows _ the most recent in
1998 _ questioning whether justice in Texas is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But several legislative efforts to scrap the current system have
failed amid sharp differences over key issues, including whether
judges should be elected or appointed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush favors electing judges. However, several
members of the Texas Supreme Court have advocated a system under
which judges would be appointed by the governor and subject to
election to keep their seats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Chief Justice Tom Phillips, an early supporter of
efforts to junk the current system, called it a ``bad system that
impairs public confidence in the courts.'' But he said changes
should be made by the Legislature, not by a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Smith of Public Citizen said the Legislature ``has clearly had
the opportunity and failed to remedy this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first lawsuit challenging Texas' judicial selection
system since 1989, when minority plaintiffs, in a voting rights
case, won a federal court ruling that countywide elections for
district judges discriminated against minorities in the state's
largest counties. That decision was overturned, however, by the
U.S. Supreme Court in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
