<HEADLINE>
KARROS: HUNDLEY HOLDS THE KEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL -- Todd Hundley's first throw of the season sent the
ball in to center field. The catcher's first swing sent the ball
into the last row of the right-center field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Be it prophetic or coincidence, it doesn't matter. But a few
hours before the Dodgers opened their season in Montreal, first
baseman Eric Karros said Hundley's season would have the largest
bearing on how the Dodgers fared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest key is Hundley,'' Karros said. ``That's out
biggest key, without question. It's not even close. He has the
biggest impact of anybody on our team, both offensively and
defensively. There is not another players on this team that impacts
the offense and defense as much as he does. Nobody. Not even close.
Who?''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Hundley can give punch and protection to the middle
of the lineup. If he's hitting well, pitchers will hesitate to
pitch around the meat of the lineup to get to him. He was 3 for 5
in the opener, including a hit right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we had it last year, we had a good team,''
Hundley said.``We've just got to be consistent and play good
defense and have strong pitching. Offensively, we can score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the impact is even greater. The first two times
Jose Vidro reached base, he ran. The first resulted in an errant
throw that allowed Vidro to go to third and eventually score. The
second time it put him in scoring position with less than two outs.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the effect of what a strong defensive showing would
do for the pitchers, who won't have to worry as much about walks or
singles turning into doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year is last year,'' said Hundley, who gunned down only
23 of 129 runners and made a career-high 16 errors last season.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for offense: The major reason the Dodgers went with
Kevin Elster at shortstop is offense. Manager Davey Johnson
believes Elster can provide it, and didn't think Alex Cora was
ready to do so.
</P>
<P>
   However, Elster's found the going rough since winning the job.
He ended spring training with 1 hit in 18 at-bats, and saw his
average drop to .174 in 46 at-bats, and he was 0 for 3 in the
opener. Cora's average was .176 in 34 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But the 35-year-old Elster, who last played a full season in
1996, brings patience to the offense. Despite his dismal spring
average, he had a .321 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Daly dose: In the movie business, Bob Daly would know after the
first night of a release whether his $100 million production was a
hit or a flop.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such time table for a $90 million baseball team.
Daly, admittedly anxious while in the clubhouse before the game,
said the feeling heading into this season was very different from
the last 50-plus seasons he's been a Dodgers fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference going to see a movie that somebody
makes for $80 million than making a movie for $80 million,'' said
Daly, Dodgers managing partner and CEO. ``When you make a movie for
$80 million and you sit for your first screening and the lights
come up the first time out, you pretty much know whether your movie
is going to work or not. ...If I had a failure, there was nothing
you can do. You can't change (the players), or make a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: It's subject to change at any moment, but manager
Davey Johnson tentatively set up how he wants to use the
right-handed set-up contingent in the bullpen. It will be Mike
Fetters, Terry Adams, Alan Mills and Gregg Olson. ...Cindy Lloyd,
the wife of Expos pitcher Graeme Lloyd, on the disabled list with a
shoulder problem, died Monday morning due to complications
resulting from a 14-year battle with Crohn's disease....L.A.'s Gary
Sheffield's fifth inning triple was his first since June 19, 1998,
at Colorado. ...Montreal's Vladimir Guerrero, who had two homers
and four RBI in the game, is 11 for 20 (.550) lifetime against
Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS vs. MONTREAL
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4:05 p.m., at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Fox Sports Net 2; 1150-AM, KWKW-AM (1330 Spanish).
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: After a spring of struggling, Dodgers RH Chan Ho Park
(13-11, 5.23 ERA) tries to flip the switch and start pitching well.
And as the No. 2 starter, his success is paramount to the Dodgers'
success. Park had an 8.31 ERA in his last three springs starts and
battled tightness in his arm, but he said he feels fine and relaxed
for his 2000 debut. But the dome hasn't treated Park well. He's 1-2
with a 5.81 ERA in six career games. Montreal RH Hideki Irabu
(11-7, 4.84) makes his Expos debut. He was acquired in an offseason
trade with the Yankees and should bolster a young pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   - Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
