<HEADLINE>
U.S. GRANTS VISAS TO ELIAN'S FATHER, OTHER KIN &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department on Monday approved visa
requests for the immediate family of Elian Gonzalez, and the father
of the 6-year-old Cuban boy whose battle over his custody has
created a storm of controversy could arrive in the United States on
Tuesday to claim his son.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of the visas came as immigration officials said
they will transfer the custody of the boy from his great-uncle to
his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, upon his arrival from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions will resume Tuesday between the Miami family's
attorneys and INS officials, but those talks will center on the
transfer of the boy to his father. The federal government had set a
deadline for Tuesday morning for Elian's Miami relatives to provide
written assurances that the boy would be surrendered to INS
authorities once all appeals are exhausted. Failure to do so would
have meant revocation of Elian's temporary stay in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   However, Robert A. Wallis, INS district director in Miami, said
Monday that ``revocation of Elian's parole has been superseded by
the expected arrival of Juan Miguel Gonzalez in the United States.
The Miami relatives have long said that they wanted the father to
come here. The father has indicated that he wants to be here with
his son. Once Mr. Gonzalez arrives, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service will begin transferring parole care from
(great-uncle) Lazaro Gonzalez to the boy's father.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials are hoping to reach an agreement that will
allow the transfer to take place without incident by giving the
Miami relatives sufficient time to prepare the boy for his reunion
with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transfer of parole care does not mean that the child will
be immediately removed from the home. Instead, it is our hope to
begin a smooth and orderly process that will create as little
disruption as possible for Elian. We wish to add no further trauma
to that which this innocent child has already endured,'' Wallis
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said the visas for Juan
Miguel Gonzalez and his immediate family ``could be issued as early
as (today).''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement cleared the way for Gonzalez to leave Havana on
Tuesday if he chooses. In addition, Rubin said that visas had also
been granted for Gonzalez's second wife, his infant son, a cousin,
a teacher and a doctor to make the trip as well.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin said it may take longer to decide whether to allow a
Cuban government official and other nonfamily visa applicants who
have an interest in the case into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presumption is that those visas for immediate family
members is something we will process favorably and quickly,'' Rubin
said. ``Beyond that, we're going to have to review each of the
individual requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez and 27 others submitted visa applications
Monday in Havana. In addition to family members, the applicants
include Ricardo Alarcon, president of Cuba's national assembly,
some of the boy's former schoolmates, a teacher, a doctor and a
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Fidel Castro has requested that nonfamily
members be allowed to accompany Gonzalez in order to smooth the
boy's transition back into Cuban life, should his father be given
custody of his son when he arrives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said a final decision on whether nonfamily members will be
granted visas will be decided by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in consultation with the Justice Department and
immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been in the temporary custody of relatives in Miami
since he was rescued at sea four months ago while trying to cross
from Cuba to Florida on a boat with other Cuban refugees, including
his mother. His mother and 10 others apparently drowned when their
boat sank.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez will likely travel to the nation's capital, where he
will stay at the home of Fernando Remirez, Cuba's chief U.S.
diplomat here. Gonzalez has requested that he be given immediate
custody of his son, and Justice Department and immigration
officials indicated Monday that Elian would likely be brought to
Washington or some other location as soon as possible to be
reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   An immigration official said the Miami relatives have been told
that if they comply, the boy and his father will remain in the
United States ``until the appeals process has run its course.''
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations resume between attorneys for the Miami family
and immigration officials, concerns were raised that the removal of
the boy from his Little Havana home could spur demonstrations that
may turn violent. In January, anti-Castro groups took to the
streets in Miami's Cuban exile community, clogging streets and
threatening to close Miami International Airport. Group leaders
have pledged to resume demonstrations if the boy is forcibly
removed from his great-uncle's home.
</P>
<P>
   About 5:30 p.m. Monday, Lazaro Gonzalez, his brother, Delfin,
and spokesman Armando Gutierrez returned to the Federal Justice
Building to rejoin talks. About an hour later, after a full day of
talks, the Gonzalez brothers emerged from the federal building with
their attorneys for a brief announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be first and foremost concerned about the
mental, psychological well-being of this young 6-year-old,'' said
Manny Diaz, one of the boy's attorneys. ``To that extent we have
spent a lot of time today talking about numerous issues and will be
back tomorrow to continue our conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
