<HEADLINE>
WELLS WASTES NO TIME ON HIS WAY TO MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WELLS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Chicago White Sox planned to put Kip
Wells on the fast track to the majors when they drafted him out of
Baylor with the 16th overall pick in the June 1998 draft, but this
is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Wells traveled almost as fast as the NASCAR drivers flew around
Texas Motor Speedway last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At this time two seasons ago, Wells was preparing to pitch in a
Big 12 Conference game for the Bears. Tuesday, he starts for the
White Sox against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to be in an organization that needed help quickly,''
Wells said. ``I was in the right place at the right time, and got
drafted by the right team.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he was drafted by an organization that needed pitching
help at the big-league level. But it takes more than opportunity to
make it to the majors. It also takes talent, and the 22-year-old
right-hander with the low-90 mph fastball, outstanding curveball
and good changeup is in the majors because he has plenty of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to be one of the good young pitchers in the
American League,'' White Sox manager Jerry Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' professional career actually got off to a slow start.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox drafted him after he went 13-4 with a 3.71
earned-run average his junior year at Baylor, but he didn't sign
until December.
</P>
<P>
   Once he made his professional debut last spring, he moved up
quickly. He was 13-8 with a 3.29 ERA in 25 starts for Class-A
Winston-Salem and Double-A Birmingham, then was promoted to the big
leagues to make a start for the injured Jim Parque on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a spot start,'' Wells said. ``I didn't know if I would
be there for the rest of the season or just one day.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be for the rest of the season. He beat the
Detroit Tigers by allowing one run on six hits in 51/3 innings to
earn a spot in the rotation, and went 4-1 with a 4.04 ERA in seven
starts. He had one bad outing, when he allowed eight runs in 32/3
innings against the Indians. Throw out that start, and his ERA was
2.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stuff and the velocity of your pitches gets you drafted,''
he said. ``Then it's a matter of getting guys out on a regular
basis and making adjustments from pitch to pitch. Luckily, I was
able to do that early in my career as opposed to taking three or
four years to find that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
