A6414 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITESOX-     04-03 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GUYS, OLD PUDGE LIFT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Kenny Rogers was masterful. The defense
turned four double plays. The American League's Most Valuable
Player was just that. The right fielder was every bit as good as
his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Even former President George Bush was on his game, throwing out
the ceremonial first pitch without bouncing it up to home plate or
injuring catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers couldn't ask for anything more for an
announced crowd of 49,332 fans at The Ballpark in Arlington, the
largest regular-season crowd in club history. Everything seemed to
fall into place for the Rangers as they trounced the Chicago White
Sox, 10-4, on Monday in the season-opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special day,'' first baseman David Segui said.
</P>
<P>
   That it was, especially for right fielder Gabe Kapler.
Redefining the meaning of sudden impact, Kapler smashed two home
runs in his first two at-bats with the Rangers and added a
run-scoring single in the fifth. By that time he was getting
standing ovations just for adjusting his socks properly and putting
his glove on the correct hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy for Gabe,'' Rogers said. ``That's a great day
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler had help. Rodriguez also smacked two home runs as the
Rangers showed they may still score a few runs even though Juan
Gonzalez and Todd Zeile are no longer in their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything seemed to just click with just about everybody,''
Kapler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some question marks about our offense, but we proved
we certainly score some runs,'' left fielder Rusty Greer said.
``Being consistent at that will be important; you can't score 10
runs one night and one run the next. But I think you're going to
see us put some runs on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, taking advantage of the offense and four double plays,
kept the White Sox under control for eight innings, allowing just
one run on six hits. He walked two and didn't strike out a batter,
but the defense behind him made every play.
</P>
<P>
   The victory allowed him to extend his home winning streak to 19
consecutive games, tying him for the third-longest streak in
major-league history. Rogers hasn't lost a game in his home park
since June 28, 1997, while pitching with the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have drawn up a better scenario,'' Rogers said.
``Everything went well. Good pitching, great offense, great
defense. That can win you a lot of ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler got the Rangers going with a second-pitch home run off
White Sox starter and loser Mike Sirotka in the second inning. The
White Sox picked up a run in the third with a couple of hits and
Mark Johnson's double-play grounder. But Rodriguez smashed a
three-run homer in the bottom of the inning to give the Rangers a
4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the fifth, Kapler and Rodriguez had gone deep
again, the Rangers were in complete command with a 9-1 lead, and
White Sox manager Jerry Manuel was probably wondering if President
Bush still had something left on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those days when everything went right for us,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``It was fun to watch the way we
got after it today.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``it's-only-one-game'' theory was evident throughout the
clubhouse, but shortstop Royce Clayton said, ``It's very important
to see what we're capable of. Not only offensive, but Kenny pitched
a great game and we did what we're supposed to do on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that we did a lot of little things was positive,
like hitting the cutoff man and keeping runners from advancing. We
didn't always do those things last year, but you have to if you're
going to be a good ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling tickled inside today to see what this ballclub
is capable of doing.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
