<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-KAPLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER AN INSTANT SMASH WITH RANGERS, FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ ``Juan Who?'' they asked. ``Juan Who?''
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler answered with two home runs and one wink.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers' new right fielder needed only one pitch to
make an already good impression even better to the fans at The
Ballpark in Arlington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love him,'' Vernon Gray, 26, of Cleburne said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler _ the other right fielder involved in the Juan Gonzalez
trade to Detroit in the off-season _ hit two bases-empty homers,
added a run-scoring single and showed off his arm with an
on-the-money throw to third base during the Rangers' 10-4 victory
against the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to love from his first impression before the home
fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to be a real nice young man,'' Chuck McCoy of
Arlington said.
</P>
<P>
   And a real nice ballplayer to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real game-day player,'' George Atkins, 53, of Bedford
said.
</P>
<P>
   And a real nice-looking ballplayer to still others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' said Lindsey Hall, 18, of Fort Worth. ``I'll be
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ballpark employees couldn't escape Kapler's charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely adds to the view from right field,'' usher
Joanie Vasko said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler returned to his position in the field amid cheers after
every inning _ the ovations only grew louder after the two home
runs _ and when he finally couldn't ignore the ``Juan Who? Juan
Who?'' chants anymore, he gave a half-turn of the head, smiled and
sent a wink to the fans in the lower Home Run Porch.
</P>
<P>
   They went wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not three home runs?'' yelled Atkins, who said Kapler
signed a ball for his 10-year-old son, Harrison, before the game.
``I think he's already been accepted. Look around. If you're out in
right field today, you're having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   The glowing spring-training reports about Kapler's attitude and
hustle did wonders for his popularity even before he played a home
game. Debbie Winter of Roanoke, a season-ticket holder for the past
five seasons, said she witnessed Kapler's enthusiasm first-hand
during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was real accessible, and when he told you he was excited to
be here, you could tell he was thrilled,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To some fans, that marks a change from Gonzalez, who gave the
impression of aloofness, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciated his ability,'' said Alan Gonzales, 28, who made
the drive from Austin for Monday's game. ``I don't think we'll
forget him, but I think it will be a lot easier to forget him if
they beat the Yankees (in the playoffs) this year with Kapler.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Kapler's lone mistake was met with forgiveness. He ran
through a stop sign from third-base coach Jerry Narron and should
have been thrown out, but scored when the ball popped loose from
the catcher's glove. The fans credited him for hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's aggressive,'' fans said to each other as they reviewed
the play. ``As long as he stays consistent, we don't need two home
runs a game from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler said he'll keep trying to impress his right-field support
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get those guys on your side,'' he said. ``A
lot of them sit out there every day, and you don't want them to
think you're not out there to win it all. I want them to know we
are there to win it all so they'll keep coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Who?'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
